<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC DEFEAT KNICKS, 81-72 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing rubbed his eyes and let out a sigh as
he stared into the distance long after the questions stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The more frustrated he sounded, the harder he pounded a lotion
bottle into the palm of his hand. Usually, Ewing is the nonchalant
one, the one unruffled by defeats.
</P>
<P>
   This one got to him. The Knicks blew an 11-point, third-quarter
lead under a barrage of turnovers and a stretch of panicked play
against a Magic team that seemed to toy with the Knicks before
putting them away, 81-72, on Tuesday night at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks fell to 0-5 against the two teams above them in the
Atlantic Division, Orlando and Miami. They collapsed under 22
turnovers and another horrendous effort in the fourth quarter. This
time, the Knicks (18-16), who fell out of playoff position, made
just 6 of 24 shots down the stretch. When the Magic (26-10) felt
like it, it turned on a 21-5 run and gulped up the Knicks' 11-point
edge in the first five minutes of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mad at myself,'' said Latrell Sprewell, who missed all
five shots he took in the second half and turned the ball over five
times on the night. ``I didn't give the team what they needed. We
had them in the first half. We played well. But we seemed to get
big-headed about it. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disturbed, really upset. We're running out of time. So,
yeah, this is as upset as I've been.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Anfernee Hardaway's 30 points, the bulk of which were
scored around the lethargic defense of Allan Houston, the Magic
took control in the second half. The Knicks did all of their damage
in the first half. Ewing had 16 of his 28 points, while Houston
scored 10 of his 14. When it counted, everyone vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am at a loss for words,'' Chris Childs said. ``I guess we
are a one-half team. We are not a good team. We don't play with
urgency. We don't play with the kind of emotion we need for a whole
game. When we get down, we don't play with any emotion
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy had no sense for what kind of effort he was
going to get from his team against the Magic. There was motivation.
The Knicks had lost to the Magic twice already this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more than feeling good about ourselves, we have to
know what it takes to win,'' Van Gundy said before the game. ``I
think sometimes, and I always read about teams having fun, but
that's all bull. You have fun when you win, and when you play
right. You shouldn't be having a whole lot of fun if you're not
doing the right thing. You feel good when you're winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were giddy in the first half because they were
playing the right way. They were soothing Van Gundy's anxiety of
their perimeter defense by holding the Magic to 0 for 7 from
3-point range and just 27.7 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Knicks were shooting a stirring 53.8 percent to
take a 44-33 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The look of glee on the Knicks' faces faded in the third
quarter. The Magic tuned up its defensive energy and forced four
turnovers in the first seven minutes of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Each mental collapse by the Knicks was topped by another. During
the Magic's 21-5 run to pass the malfunctioning Knicks, Hardaway
was shaking Houston for 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Magic was ahead, 54-49, with five minutes left in
the third, a startling turn of events. The Knicks regrouped and
used a 3-pointer and a layin by Ewing to regain the lead and take a
shaky 57-56 lead into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was closer than anyone imagined based on the Knicks'
first-half performance. Playing with efficiency, the Knicks'
attention to detail on both ends of the floor led them to a
12-point lead in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They had the strength of Ewing's 16 first-half points, and they
remained unusually composed when they rode out a brief run by the
Magic, which was able to cut the Knicks' lead to 3 points. One
energetic spurt later, and the Knicks held an 11-point lead at the
break.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the Knicks were playing in sync. Often, Houston and
Sprewell have operated like independent parts.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was no different, but with Larry Johnson healthy
enough to get back in the starting lineup, Sprewell came off the
bench for the first time in two games. Before he came in late in
the first quarter, Houston looked comfortable in his familiar role
next to Ewing and made three of his first six shots.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell entered the game, and Houston stepped into the
background. This has been a disturbing trend since the Sprewell
trade was made on the premise that he could play next to Houston.
It didn't matter, though, because Sprewell was on a roll himself.
Sprewell was 3 for 4 and scored 10 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever path the Knicks took in the first half, it worked. The
same could not be said for the rest of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
