<SLUG> BC-TEEN-SMOKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKING BY TEENS LINKED TO DNA HARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A new study shows that teen-age smokers, even if
they quit later, cause themselves long-term genetic damage that
increases the risk of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published today in the Journal of the National Cancer
Institute, shows that early smoking hinders the body's ability to
repair smoking-related damage later in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another reason for kids to really think hard about
smoking,'' said the lead author, John K. Wiencke, director of the
Laboratory for Molecular Epidemiology at the University of
California, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they can quit and later on there will be no harm
done. That may not be true.''
</P>
<P>
   But several San Fernando Valley teen-agers seem no more
concerned about this study than others that have shown the dangers
of smoking young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studies are studies. People are going to do it anyway,'' said
Carlos Cardenas, an 18-year-old senior at suburban Van Nuys High
School, puffing on a chocolate-flavored Black &AMP; Mild cigarillo
Tuesday. ``It's not an addiction, it's more of a habit. We'll grow
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like a handicap,'' Wiencke said. ``You may not be
able to go back exactly to the way you should've been.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers who surveyed 143 lung-cancer patients did not set
out to study teen smoking, Wiencke said, but found it to be a
common thread. He said the patients with the most genetic damage
started smoking when they were young -- one at age 7.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year study was funded by federal grants from the
National Cancer Institute and the National Institute of
Environmental Health Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with those who picked up the habit later, participants
who began smoking in their teens had many more adducts, compounds
that latch onto the DNA and are thought to promote lung cancer. And
they had levels 3{ times higher than nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would make sense. The body is more vulnerable at that
point,'' said Judy Sopenski, executive director of Stop Teen-age
Addiction to Tobacco, based at Northeastern University in Boston.
``When a young person is developing, a whole lot is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Rosen, director of the Free For Life stop-smoking program
in suburban Canoga Park, started smoking when he was 13 and quit 14
years ago when he was 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we start as kids, we feel it's innocuous, but pretty soon
it's the center of our lives,'' he said. ``It's the forbidden
fruit. I had a sense of invulnerability and a sense of fatalism at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said he started puffing ``to be hip, to be cool, to be
sophisticated, to be a bad boy, to be a rebel, and it's no
different today.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, the Van Nuys High School senior, said he smokes to
relax. ``It cools you down when you're stressed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good,'' admitted his friend Felipe Villalobos, 18, of
North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what is?'' Cardenas cut in.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking with a half-dozen friends in front of a Jack-in-the-Box,
Camilo Novoa, an 11th-grader at Taft High School in suburban
Woodland Hills, dismissed the smoking study.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's been smoking since he was 17, and he's healthy as a
horse,'' said Novoa, 17 himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's a lot of people who don't smoke who get lung
cancer,'' chimed in Alex, a 16-year-old 10th-grader who declined to
give his last name.
</P>
<P>
   The study should not be used as an excuse to continue smoking,
Wiencke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fatalism, and you say what's the use,'' he said.
``That's not what the science says. That's just wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Anytime someone quits smoking, that person's risk of lung cancer
decreases, but repairs take longer for someone who started smoking
young, Wiencke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a reason to not stop smoking,'' he said. ``It's a
reason to do it sooner than later.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
