<HEADLINE>
RADIO STATION BILLBOARD SPARKS ANGRY CALLS IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A billboard leasing company will remove dozens of
cryptic radio promotions that read ``Is your son's coach gay?''
after receiving at least 80 angry -- and some threatening --
telephone calls, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The billboards were part of a Southern California promotion
launched Monday by radio station KFI-AM (640), which also drew
attention in 1995 for controversial O.J. Simpson billboards.
</P>
<P>
   The latest billboards have ``severely disrupted business'' so
much at Outdoor Systems Billboard Leasing that they will be removed
when the weather allows, a company employee said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two billboards were placed in the suburban San Fernando
Valley northwest of downtown, in Van Nuys and North Hollywood, as
part of what KFI calls a ``teaser campaign,'' designed to spark
community discussion about controversial issues, station marketing
director Stuart Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to ask questions that get people's blood boiling or
make them laugh, and get them talking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently it worked too well.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy threatened to come down here,'' said Steve, an Outdoor
Systems employee who declined to give his last name. ``I've
received about 70 or 80 calls in the last two days and they are
coming down no matter how KFI feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to worry about the safety of the people coming in
and out of the building,'' Steve said.
</P>
<P>
   KFI marketing consultant Bill Louis said he understands the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a business to run, and they are responsible to their
land holders,'' Louis said. ``When there have been problems with
our campaigns in the past, we've had no problem changing or
removing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles gay and lesbian advocates said the question on the
billboard wasn't offensive in and of itself, but they were
concerned the campaign could be followed by an answer that might be
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those billboards usually change within a week or two, and we
weren't sure if they would say `So what?' or `Get rid of the
coach,' '' said Corri Planck, a spokesperson for the Gay and
Lesbian Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was some lapse in judgment at KFI, but we're
happy they are coming down.''
</P>
<P>
   The KFI campaign included about 100 different questions, such as
``Why do you cheat on your wife?'' and ``Who is reading your
e-mail?'' But the gay coach question sparked a barrage of concerns,
Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Morgan was outraged by a billboard in Van Nuys near the
intersection of Victory Boulevard and Fulton Avenue which he saw
while on an errand for light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It borders on hate crime,'' said Morgan, 70. ``It's a strange,
stupid ad.''
</P>
<P>
   David Morales of North Hollywood saw the sign while washing
three loads of clothes at a Victory Boulevard Laundromat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not too smart because you can take it a few
different ways,'' said Morales, 31. ``If they mean it to keep an
eye on your kids, it's OK. But if they want you to beat up the
coach, that's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
