<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIGHTROPE-WALK-AZR &LR;      04-07 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGHTROPE-WALK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 and JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both are world-famous daredev ils. Both have risked life and
limb in spectacular public stunts at some of the most famous
locations on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, both motorcyclist Robbie Knievel and high-wire walker Phil
lipe Petit are coming to Arizona to pit their nerves and their
skill against a legend _ the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Knievel, son of motorcyclist Evel Knievel, has received
permission from the Hualapai Tribe for an April 29 jump over a
portion of the Canyon, a feat not even his famed father attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Petit has been given the go-ahead by Navajo Nation officials to
try a 400-yard tightwire walk across the 1,600-foot-deep Lower
Colorado River Gorge on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the sudden shows of testosterone at the Canyon?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the idea occurred to Petit before. Ten years ago, he
had a cable strung across the gorge for a walk, but he opted to try
the Eiffel Tower instead. And Evel Knievel talked years ago about
jumping the Grand Canyon but could never get National Park
officials to agree.
</P>
<P>
   This time, his son has targeted an area on the Hualapai
reservation west of Grand Canyon National Park, a jump that could
break his world record of 223 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The jump, to be broadcast nation ally on Fox, will be east to
west over an area where the Colorado River bends, said Jeff
Androsky, supervising producer for Tri-Crown Productions.
</P>
<P>
   But it gets better: He'll be traveling at least 100 mph and will
have to maneuver his machine around cactuses before his leap into
the canyon, which is between 1,200 and 2,500 feet deep in that
area. The exact distance he will cover is uncertain, although it
will be at least 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   And despite his mother's plead ing, Knievel, 36, won't be
wearing a parachute, in part because one foiled his father's
attempt to jump the Snake River Canyon in 1974 when it deployed
early, and also because he wouldn't have time to pull the cord
anyway at that speed, according to Androsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Noetzel, a photographer for Fox affiliate KSAZ-TV (Channel
10), was at a promo shoot last week, and he came away in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what what could possess him to do this,'' Noetzel
said. ``I think really, that he knows he can make it, but there's
just something about jumping the Can yon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had rappeled about 50 feet down and was shooting up as they
pushed some (donated) motorcycles over the the edge . . . and when
they hit the bottom, you don't want to know what happened to them.
It was intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews are building ramps and removing as many obstacles as they
can, Androsky said Tuesday. He said cactuses, shrubs, snakes and
other wildlife are being moved for the jump but will have to be
returned to their exact locations as part of an agreement with the
Hualapais.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Wilder, assistant planner for the Hualapai Tribe, said
Knievel visited in late March, and the tribe gave him the needed
permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that's left to do is for him to jump,'' Wilder said.
</P>
<P>
   Knievel gained notoriety in April 1989 when he jumped the
fountains at Caesars Palace, a jump that nearly killed his father,
Evel Kni evel, 21 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Knievel's most re cent publicized jump was from one
hotel tower to another at the Jockey Club on the Las Vegas Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Androsky said if Evel Knievel had thought about asking the Huala
pai Tribe for permission to jump the Canyon, he might have made the
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Petit has done his high-wire act between the towers of the World
Trade Center, the spires of the Notre Dame cathedral and on a cable
connected to the top of the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   But the French thrill seeker is saving his most challenging
tight rope walk for Arizona's Grand Canyon country.
</P>
<P>
   It's 300 feet higher than any of the 70 tightrope walks he has
done all over the world, the highest of which has been New York's
World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   The winds also are exceedingly tricky, which had given him pause
the first time around. The high-wire act could be delayed for a
day, if the winds are high on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at an apartment in New York City, Petit refused to
comment on the specifics of his walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a signed contract and it will go off as scheduled,''
Petit said.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in this month's New Yorker magazine, Petit said in
a written statement that the Canyon walk is the ``greatest show of
my life, the most arduous crossing, the most fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lee, spokeswoman for the Navajos' Bodaway Chapter, where
Petit hopes to complete his tightrope walk, said an agreement was
reached after intense negotia tions last month. Lee said Petit will
pay an undisclosed sum to both Bodaway and the Cameron Chapter for
use of their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's (Petit) been out studying the Canyon and the winds for 10
years,'' Lee said. ``It's been a lot of research. We wish him the
best.'' &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com via e-mail. Jim Gintonio can be reached at
(602) 444-8380 or at jim.gintonio &LR; pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
