<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST FOR OPENERS, VELARDE PLEASED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Randy Velarde vowed to play the first game of the
season as if it were his last.
</P>
<P>
   But three hours before it started on a cloudy Tuesday night at
Edison Field, the Angels' second baseman sat deep in an armchair in
front of a clubhouse TV set, the periwinkle sleeves of his team
jacket wrapped tight around his broad chest. Hardly the picture of
a gung-ho warrior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to stay warm,'' Velarde said.
</P>
<P>
   If one guessed that in addition to feeling the weather, the
36-year-old was experiencing a case of opening-night jitters, it
would be no insult.
</P>
<P>
   After fearing his career was over as he recovered from Tommy
John elbow surgery for most of the 1997 and '98 seasons _ wondering
if he had already played his last major-league game _ Velarde would
be entitled to more opening-night emotion than most of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely wish I could bottle this kind of intensity and use
it the rest of the season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his fellow Angels starters should have felt the same
way:
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Greene, the designated hitter after missing two-thirds of
last season following shoulder surgery that threatens his
once-soaring catching career.
</P>
<P>
   _Andy Sheets, the utility infielder who arrived from San Diego
in a late-March trade and landed his first opening-night start when
shortstop Gary DiSarcina broke his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   _And Troy Glaus, the 22-year-old third baseman who played his
'98 opener at Double-AA Midland and his '97 opener at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   But each of them wore a stony mask Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scheme of things, it's just one of 162 (games),''
Greene said in his corner of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to take advantage of an opportunity,'' Sheets
said in front of the other big-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was getting my professional career started. This
year I'm getting my major-league career started,'' Glaus said as he
hurried from the indoor batting cage to a pregame players' meeting.
``It's all the same.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the stoic, one-foot-in-front-of-the-other
approach that defines a baseball life.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers players trotted out that preposterous cliche _ ``It's
just one of 162'' _ after their come-from-behind, 11-inning victory
over the Arizona Diamondbacks in Monday's opener. A few of them
might actually have believed it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have to have gone through Velarde's past two seasons
to know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening day to me is nerves, frustration, anticipation,
fear... all bottled into one,'' said Velarde, who grew up in
Midland, Texas, and is one of those guys who never saw a big-league
stadium until he played in one. ``It's all those emotions racing
through you. It's truly a once-a-year excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending parts of nine seasons with the New York Yankees
as a utility man, starting each season on the bench or in the
minors, Velarde made an opening-night start at second base in '96,
his first year with the Angels. He hit .285 and set career highs
for runs (82), RBI (54) and homers (14).
</P>
<P>
   But three weeks before the '97 opener, Velarde felt a stabbing
pain in his throwing elbow as he warmed up for a Cactus League
start in left field. Surgery soon followed. He made his only
appearance that season came as a pinch-runner in a September game.
</P>
<P>
   In '98, on and off the disabled list, he finally put the injury
behind him by playing 51 games at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, opening day wasn't a celebration for me,'' said
Velarde, who was with the team in Anaheim. ``I couldn't tell you
the first thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was there?'' Velarde said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels beat the Yankees 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played the Yankees?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to opening-night action Tuesday with a new
appreciation for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``As ballplayers, we think we're indestructible, but we're
fooling ourselves,'' Velarde said. ``A lot of guys think, `I'll
take today off. I'm not feeling that good. I'll get 'em tomorrow.'
I always assumed there would be a next day. This (an injury)
gut-checks you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play every game as if it might be your last. You
never know how long your body will hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Velarde's first swing of 1999 produced the Angels' first
hit of the season, a clean single up the middle off Cleveland
Indians right-hander Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   A good start. You'd have to go back to '96 to find his last one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask me about this (opener) next year,'' he had said before
the game, knowing it would be one to remember, ``and I'll tell you
everything about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
