<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8567 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-GUNS-KAN &LR;      04-07 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-GUNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI VOTERS REJECT CONCEALED-FIREARMS PROPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Missouri voters turned out in record numbers Tuesday and
rejected Proposition B, the nation's first statewide test of public
support for concealed handguns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A huge anti-gun vote in St. Louis County offset strong support
in rural areas for the measure, which would have legalized
concealed firearms in Missouri for the first time since 1875. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Groups supporting the measure conceded the battle late Tuesday,
after having led briefly in early returns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you fight against the governor, the first lady, the
Justice Department and the barrels of ink of the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch and The Kansas City Star?'' said Fred Myers, campaign
manager for Missourians Against Crime, which spearheaded the
pro-gun campaign. ``To say I'm disappointed is an understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure lost by a ratio of 2-1 in St. Louis County. But the
race was closer than expected in Jackson County, where the
proposition lost by fewer than 4,000 votes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Support was strong in southwest Missouri and overwhelming in the
southeast part of the state, where advocates had counted on a
strong endorsement of gun rights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 97 percent of the vote counted, Proposition B was losing by
about 50,000 votes, or 52 percent to 48 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; votetab1:The vote with 97% of precincts reporting:
 &LR; votetab2:Yes 605,749 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No 653,732 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After an often-bitter campaign, the vote was as close as
expected. The biggest surprise was in the northwestern counties,
where the proposition was losing by a small margin. Overall, state
voter turnout reached about 36 percent, translating into the
highest number of voters ever for an April election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Auditor Claire McCaskill, an outspoken opponent of
concealed weapons, was elated by the outcome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Money can't overcome common sense,'' she said. ``Voters,
particularly in urban areas, understand guns are not the answer for
safety.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Myers said he had been encouraged by early returns because so
many came from St. Louis County. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the out-state vote is where our people are,'' Myers
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Wayne Crump, a Potosi Democrat who sponsored the
concealed-firearms bill last year, said he was disappointed that
the proposition was routed so badly in St. Louis County. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think in the near future it will be resubmitted to
voters,'' Crump said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the proposal lost 52 percent to 48 percent. In
Platte County, 56 percent opposed the measure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In southeast Missouri, the proposition was receiving support
from 68 percent of voters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association set the tone for the campaign,
spending $3.75 million in support of Proposition B through Sunday.
That represented a bit more than an entire year's membership dues
from the group's 103,000 Missouri members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, who had hoped to raise $2 million, reported raising
$828,359. The difference in spending was evident in the frequency
of the television ads, the slickness of the brochures and the
variety of ways the campaigns reached out to voters.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The effort by Missourians Against Crime, which spearheaded the
Yes-on-B campaign, had all the features of a modern campaign: phone
banks, polling, direct mail, and workers blanketing public
gatherings with literature.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Safe Schools, which led the No-on-B effort, spent most of its
money in the final weeks on a widespread television ad campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the group could not match supporters' presence in other
venues. So it relied on local officials and opponents in education,
health care, religion and the black community to reach out to the
public.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missourians Against Crime also benefited from an impassioned
core of supporters who saw concealed weapons as a constitutional
right. Safe Schools never generated that kind of fervor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B would have allowed people to obtain a permit to
carry a concealed firearm if they were at least 21 and had never
been convicted of a felony. They could not have had a misdemeanor
conviction involving a gun or a bomb. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They could not have been a known drunk, must never have been
committed to a mental institution, and must not have made threats
or been violent for the previous five years. They also would have
been required to complete 12 hours of training. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The issue divided many traditional allies. Many police officers,
especially in rural areas, supported the measure. Most law
enforcement supervisors and many street cops in urban areas opposed
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was marked by distortions and exaggerations on both
sides. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents criticized the proposal because it would have forced
sheriffs to issue gun permits to people with convictions on
relatively serious misdemeanor charges such as receiving stolen
property. They argued that people guilty of stalking and assault
could have gotten weapons as long as the incidents had occurred
more than five years before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also warned that firearms would have been allowed near
schools, at sporting events and at shopping centers. And more guns
on the street, they argued, would lead to accidental shootings and
vigilante actions and would cause minor incidents to escalate into
gunplay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters argued that criminals already have guns; it's
law-abiding people whom the prohibition hurts. Most supporters said
concealed weapons deter crime because criminals never know who
might shoot back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many supporters said they doubted that guns deter crime. But
they said the issue came down to a question of choice, and the
advertising campaign reflected that: Even if you don't want to
carry a gun, the ads said, don't take that right away from me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You may think that a concealed weapon won't deter an
attacker,'' said Steve McGhee, president of Missourians for
Personal Safety, a grass-roots group that supported Proposition B.
``But it certainly will make a difference in whether you can fight
back.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gun proponents scoffed at opponents' concerns. They said
criminals would not be willing to be fingerprinted and go through
12 hours of firearms training to get a permit. And they responded
to the argument about accidents and frequent gunplay by pointing to
30 states that have reported few problems after adopting
concealed-carry laws. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
