<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-SLAYINGS-KAN &LR;      04-07 1794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-SLAYINGS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Telephoned threat leads police to murder suspect  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL AND JOE STEPHENS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As police closed in Tuesday on the leading suspect in the
murders of five men, Jim Maupin answered a phone belonging to one
victim's brother. The voice growling over the line was the very man
at the center of the manhunt: 56-year-old limousine driver Gary
Beach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell that (expletive) nephew of mine he is next,'' Beach
reportedly said, referring to the victim's brother, Dennis Gulley.
``Tell him I am going to get him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maupin, a friend of Gulley's, was shaken. But the next phone
call was even more chilling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gulley's mother was on the line, frantic. She said Beach had
just called her, claiming he was in his car at that very moment,
stalking her son. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, however, police acted on a tip forwarded by
Maupin and descended on the suspect at a Westport-area hotel.
Police arrested Beach on charges of first-degree murder and armed
criminal action in the death of one of the five men. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors may file more charges in the other deaths in what
has become Kansas City's biggest murder case in a decade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police officers found the decomposing bodies of all five victims
in a midtown home Monday, and the home's renter, Beach, became the
chief suspect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from the death of Kenneth Gulley, who was
shot in the face. Beach was being held in jail Tuesday night
without bond and will be arraigned on those charges this morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Robert Beaird said there are no other
suspects in the four other homicides. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beach knew all of the victims, authorities said. They are: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Gulley, 45 of Independence. He was the stepson of Beach's
brother. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Mark Nelson, 28. He lived with Beach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Michael L. Davis, 32. He was Beach's stepson, lived with
Beach and drove a limousine for a living. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- Christopher Conrad, 27, of Overland Park. He knew Beach
through Nelson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials were awaiting fingerprint analysis before identifying
the fifth victim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Authorities declined to divulge a motive for the killings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, a man claiming to be Beach called /{The Kansas City
Star/} at 9:18 a.m. Tuesday and left a voice-mail message for a
reporter, talking about some of the victims. Two persons, a
relative and a longtime neighbor of Beach, identified the voice on
the message as Beach's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is what the caller said in reference to a Tuesday story
about the killings: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're on the wrong track. You kept emphasizing about
men, men, men. It was all a crazy crack situation, where crack
suppliers wouldn't leave certain people alone, and I finally got
fed up with it. And two of the boys there, Mark Nelson and Mike
Davis, I just didn't want them to live with the shame on their
conscience of what they were.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A man claiming to be Beach also called the Kansas City Police
homicide unit and the TIPS Hotline, authorities said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; brk:The arrest &QL; 
 &LR; tx:Police said they had reason to hone in on Beach as a suspect
after Gulley's relatives broke into to Beach's home at 4275
Jefferson St. and found a body. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gulley was last seen March 31, with Beach. Over the weekend,
Beach told others that they had gone to a bar on the Country Club
Plaza and several bars in North Kansas City. Beach told his
relatives Gulley left a North Kansas City bar with a woman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police also connected Beach to Gulley's death through a
handwritten note in Beach's home listing the five victims' names
and the location of their bodies inside the home. An expert
determined handwriting on the note matched Beach's message and
signature on a greeting card, prosecutors said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next break in the case came Tuesday morning when Beach's
series of telephone calls alerted police to his whereabouts.
Fugitive apprehension detectives directed all available patrol cars
to saturate the midtown area, especially hotels. Police believed
Beach was staying at a hotel since he moved out of his house over
the weekend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A rookie and his field training officer who were first at
Beach's house after the relatives discovered the bodies Monday were
the officers who found Beach on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officer Marty Lyons said he and Paul Myers, who graduated from
the academy three weeks ago, decided to check the parking lot of
Embassy Suites, 220 W. 43rd St., a few blocks from Beach's house. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they drove into the parking lot, a Lincoln Town Car pulled
out of the underground parking garage in front of them, Lyons said.
The car drove behind the hotel and the driver glanced in his
rearview mirror, police said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When he saw we were behind him, he pulled up behind a
Dumpster, stopped his car and got out,'' Lyons said. ``He said,
`You got me. You got me. No resistance. I have a gun in the front
seat and it's unloaded.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lyons pointed his handgun at Beach while Myers handcuffed him.
It was 9:47 a.m. Two homicide detectives took Beach to police
headquarters, where they questioned him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police declined to say what Beach said during the interview. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow crime scene tape was taken down around the Beach's home
about 3 p.m. Tuesday. Police said they had collected about 300 bags
of evidence, including two interior doors that were splattered with
blood. Police also found 9mm shell casings and other small-caliber
shell casings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the killings were horrifying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen this many people killed in one place since a
1989 arson fire that killed six people,'' said Capt. Jerry
Gallagher. ``It doesn't get much worse than this.'' &QL; 
 &LR; brk:`A midlife crisis' &QL; 
 &LR; tx:To Beach's longtime friends, the events of the weekend don't
fit his profile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They depict him as the hard-working driver of an airport
limousine, a large, gentle man who wore pressed black suits and
loved to trade jokes with other chauffeurs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friends said he was unusually close to Davis, his stepson from a
marriage that failed more than 20 years ago. Beach ate meals and
vacationed with Davis, who was among the victims found at Beach's
home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They were gentlemen,'' August Dubbert said of Beach and
Davis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Dubbert had rented Beach the white
single-story house. Months passed without Beach bothering to call
his landlord. He paid his $400 a month rent in cash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Waitresses and managers at Nichols Lunch, a 24-hour restaurant
just a few blocks from his house, knew Beach well. He ate there
almost every day, often for more than one meal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Beach accidentally backed his Town Car over a
cat, according to limousine driver Carol Fitzpatrick, who had known
Beach for years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary cried and cried and cried,'' Fitzpatrick said. ``He took
the cat to the vet himself.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Underwood, who inspects limousine services for Kansas
City, remembered Beach's humor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a nice person, a friendly sort of fellow,''
Underwood said. ``He was a jolly kind of guy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beach was a familiar face to many veteran drivers at Kansas City
International Airport. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Stark often traded work with Beach, filling in when Beach
or Davis couldn't make an appointment. Stark said Beach worked at
the airport for 20 years while Davis had worked there at least 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete surprise to everybody,'' Stark said. ``Among
their peers out here they had a really good reputation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But early this year, many friends said, Beach underwent a sudden
change in demeanor and lifestyle. Beach fell behind on his rent and
into debt with some of his fellow limousine drivers. He began to
stay out late and took on new friends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly complained that his friends and in-laws depended
on him to bail them out of trouble and pay their bills. And he told
Fitzpatrick he recently realized he would not be able to retire at
age 56, as he had planned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I accused him of going through a midlife crisis,'' Fitzpatrick
said. ``He hadn't worked much since January. He just went
downhill.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friends said they were surprised to learn from a reporter that
Beach had a criminal record. On an application for a taxi permit,
Beach listed four criminal convictions, all dating to the late
1970s. He listed both felony and misdemeanor convictions for what
he described as ``returned check charges.'' He also listed a 1976
misdemeanor conviction for ``solicitation &AMP; immoral'' conduct. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His taxi-permit photo shows him with a receding hairline above a
chubby, smiling face. He wore a white shirt and dark tie. The
document lists him as 5 feet, 11 inches tall, 190 pounds with brown
hair and blue eyes. He listed his birthplace as West Plains, Mo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked to itemize his recent traffic convictions, he used large
capital letters to scrawl: ``NONE!'' &QL; 
 &LR; brk:`Hard to fathom' &QL; 
 &LR; tx:By Friday evening, police believe Kenneth Gulley had been shot
to death in Beach's home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Beach unexpectedly visited the Pleasant Hill home
of his brother _ who is also Gulley's stepfather, according to
police reports and friends. Beach's brother is married to Gulley's
mother. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beach attended church that evening with the victim's mother and
brother, Dennis. Beach also ate Easter dinner with the family the
next day, Maupin said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They said you wouldn't have known anything was wrong,'' Maupin
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Maupin said, Dennis Gulley drove to Beach's house and
used a cinder block to bash in the back door. He found a body
inside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Gulley, who also operates a limousine service, planned to
spend Tuesday making funeral arrangements. He gave his car phone to
Maupin, and asked him to pick up any clients who telephoned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three times on Monday morning, Maupin said, the phone rang but
the caller hung up when he heard Maupin's voice. Maupin's intuition
told him the caller was the murder suspect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maupin prayed for God to tell him what to say. On the fourth
call, Maupin blurted out: ``Gary?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The voice, he said, grunted affirmation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you?'' Maupin asked quickly, before the caller could
think. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Plaza.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The caller, Maupin said, then issued his warning: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell that (expletive) nephew of mine (Dennis Gulley), he is
next. I was down there all weekend at his church. I aimed to get
them this weekend. Tell him, I'm going to get him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maupin called Gulley to warn him, and passed along the tip on
the caller's location. Gulley believed he was threatened because he
discovered the bodies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Gulley's mother called to report she had
spoken to Beach, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to fathom this whole thing and put it together,''
Maupin said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
