<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8571 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEATING-AZR &LR;      04-07 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEATING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES KEATING PLEADS GUILTY AS PART OF PLEA DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER   
 and MARTIN DOLAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Charles H Keating Jr., a central figure in the
savings and loan scandal of the late 1980s, has ended nearly a
decade of battles with federal prosecutors by admitting to
financial crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But with a plea agreement approved Tuesday in U.S. District
Court, Keating avoided a retrial and the possibility of more prison
time. And he admitted none of the charges of concocting phony land
deals and bilking elderly investors, charges that provoked national
outrage against Keating and politicians who supported him.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, who bragged of buying influence and was fond of calling
prosecutors and bank regulators ``scum,'' pleaded guilty Tuesday
afternoon to four federal counts of fraud for siphoning $975,000
from American Continental Corp. just days before the company
declared bankruptcy in April 1989.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Mariana R. Pfaelzer accepted Keating's plea
agreement and sentenced him to the 50 months he served after he and
his son, Charles H Keating III, were convicted of fraud in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   She also waived imposing restitution against Keating and
dismissed all charges against his son, 43, who was an officer in
Phoenix-based American Continental and its California-based thrift,
Lincoln Savings and Loan.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Keating, 75, could have gotten 20 years in prison and
a $1 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 10 years, Charles Keating has fought us, denied
any guilt and refused to accept responsibility for his illegal
conduct,'' said Alejandro N. Mayorkas, U.S. attorney for
California's Central District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, that fight is over. Through the extraordinary diligence
of law enforcement agents and prosecutors, Charles Keating has been
forced to admit his fraud and deceit.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating, who has claimed he was being pilloried by a ``vicious
and vindictive group of bureaucrats and sinister politicians hoping
to cover their perfidy and ignorance,'' was matter-of-fact when
Pfaelzer asked him whether he had done the things he pleaded guilty
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, your honor,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plea deal, Keating submitted a sworn financial
statement to the judge. Pfaelzer, in consideration of a $3 billion
civil judgment Keating faces, ratified a stipulation in the
agreement that says Keating has no ability to pay restitution in
the criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the court, Keating _ suntanned and craggy in a pale blue
suit _ stood mute as his attorney, Steven Neal, spoke to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want him to talk until everything is finally resolved,
until all these matters are behind him,'' Neal said, referring to a
fraud case that's pending in California state court.
</P>
<P>
   Neal emphasized that the counts to which Keating pleaded guilty
had nothing to do with the core of the government's case _ that he
and American Continental officials conducted sham land deals that
allowed him to create an illusion of prosperity as he drove Lincoln
into the ground, and that he kept peddling American Continental
junk bonds to unsuspecting buyers with bogus assurances that the
company was thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there was a risk involved'' in going to trial,
particularly a lengthy trial, Neal said. ``You weigh all that
against the offer that was made to us and it was irresistible.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal said Keating's financial statement shows a ``negative net
worth,'' and an exhaustive search for hidden overseas assets turned
up nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Neal also took a jab at bank regulators, saying that if Keating
and his companies had been left alone, ``the investors would have
done very well.'' The assets of Lincoln, seized when the government
took over the thrift in 1989, have performed ``spectacularly'' over
the past decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Sharon McCaslin, who was not the trial prosecutor,
said the deal was cut ``in the interests of justice.'' She noted
the difficulty of pressing a complex case that's 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line, prosecutors say, is that Keating has
finally admitted he broke the law.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, Karen Keating, wife of Charles Keating III, said her
husband was a good man ``who did not deserve the last 12 years of
suspicion and scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him, his kids love him and we are glad this is finally
behind him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several of those who lost money in the collapse of American
Continental and Lincoln were thankful the long fight had finally
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of ironic, because we're getting our last little bit
of money out of the lawsuit,'' said Don Maxfield, who lost $21,000
invested in American Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Don and Judy Maxfield, who lived in Lakewood, Calif., when they
invested in 1979, sued along with thousands of other bondholders.
They have recovered about 65 percent of the money they lost, not
including interest.
</P>
<P>
   The Maxfields considered themselves lucky because, unlike many
elderly bondholders, they were young enough to recover from the
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   James Catena, a retired Army veteran in Hemet, Calif., said time
has healed the wounds he suffered at Keating's hands. He's ready to
let bygones be bygones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 84 years old, and I don't have that much time left,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Catena almost had a nervous breakdown when he lost $100,000
he'd invested in American Continental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm a little forgiving,'' he said. ``I just wonder if
he's had enough. I have mixed feelings about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Catena has recouped about 80 percent of his investment through
lawsuits and special funds set aside by the courts over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much more to get from him,'' Catena said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Michael Manning was less forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't dodge a bullet, he dodged a howitzer,'' said
Manning, who worked for the federal agency in charge of handling
Lincoln's losses.
</P>
<P>
   Manning described Keating as a man who left ``a
multibillion-dollar black hole for the taxpayers to fill up.''
Lincoln's losses were set at $3.4 billion, the costliest failure in
the national S&AMP;L debacle.
</P>
<P>
   But the human suffering Keating inflicted on his victims was
even harsher, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were careers ruined, people lost their law licenses,
lost their accounting licenses, there were suicides . . . a number
of broken marriages,'' Manning recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much has been written about the financial wake of this man's
greed and larceny, but there's much more that's wrong about Charles
Keating than just the financial loss. And it's too bad that he
won't spend more of his life starting the repayment of that debt.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1993, a federal jury convicted Keating of 73 counts
of wire and bankruptcy fraud in the collapse of American
Continental and Lincoln. His son was convicted on 64 counts.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaelzer called the evidence against the elder Keating
overwhelming and sentenced him to 12 years and 7 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the conviction was reversed after it was discovered that
jurors knew of Keating's previous conviction in a California state
court and had discussed it during his federal trial. The state
conviction, on charges that Keating had swindled bond investors in
American Continental, was itself thrown out because of a flawed
instruction to the jury by the judge. An appeal by prosecutors, who
want the conviction restored, is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Neal jokingly turned aside a question from a reporter who wanted
to know how he was being paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one question I should let you ask Mr. Keating, but not
today,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Neal, Keating and several Keating family members
climbed into a chauffeured Lincoln Town Car and drove off. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 0130EDT &QL; 
