<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-BETTING-KAN &LR;      04-07 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-BETTING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFSHORE INTERNET SPORTS BOOK IS NOW TAKING BETS ON THE DOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the stock market isn't crazy enough already, an offshore
Internet sports book is now taking bets on the daily ups and downs
of the Dow Jones industrial average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Professional tennis matches and national election returns might
be next. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inversiones Ibarburu, based in Costa Rica, began accepting bets
on the Dow's close in late March on its Web site at
www.bestbetsports.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company tested the wagering waters a few weeks earlier when
it accepted bets on who would win the Oscars, customer service
manager Tony Price said in a telephone interview. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We got pretty good play on the Academy Awards,'' Price said.
``We're looking at areas to expand to give people what they
want.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's one potential problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's illegal,'' said John Russell, a spokesman for the U.S.
Justice Department in Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not so, according to Internet operators who contend that their
offshore casino and sports book sites operate legally in those
countries and thus are beyond the reach of federal and state laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the cyberbookies may be right, at least for the time being. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors acknowledge that they have been stymied for
years in enforcing a federal anti-gambling law that predates the
Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Justice Department hasn't tested its jurisdiction
over gambling in cyberspace, and only a handful of states,
including Missouri, have attempted prosecutions under state law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our players are Americans,'' Price acknowledged.
``What we do is perfectly legal in Costa Rica.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering a bill that would outlaw any Internet
gambling that is not regulated in the United States. An earlier
version of the measure failed to advance last year, in part because
of a disputed provision that also criminalized the actions of
at-home gamblers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schneider of St. Charles, Mo., who is chairwoman of the
Canadian-based Interactive Gaming Council, said there were now more
than 300 gambling sites on the Internet, with more being added
every month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be stopped,'' Schneider said of cybergambling in an
article last week in her online magazine at {www.igamingnews.com}. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although experts' estimates vary widely, all would agree that,
left unchecked, online gambling revenue will soon be measured in
billions of dollars, if they aren't already. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers have Wall Street watching very closely. But
because of the legal uncertainties, investors so far are not
enamored with the many publicly traded Internet gambling firms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very flaky,'' Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. analyst Jason Ader
said recently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his recent newsletter, Prudential Securities analyst Joseph
V. Coccomiglio doesn't forecast a bonanza, even under the best of
legal scenarios. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Online casinos cannot compete with real casinos,'' he
declared. But given a legal fighting chance, he said, online
gambling would certainly carve a lucrative niche for itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coccomiglio and others note that some leading U.S. casino firms
and others have begun to cautiously position themselves in
cyberspace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most casinos already are online with customer service and
information Web sites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month Playboy Enterprises Inc. announced it was developing
a casino site at {www.playboy.com} called Play 4 Fun that would
offer slot machines, video poker and other games without the risk
of losing money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year several states in Australia became the first in any
large country to legalize and license Internet gambling. Canada
considered national legislation last year, and Hong Kong is
exploring ways to sanction and regulate Internet gambling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While several U.S. states are considering laws to outlaw the
activity, the Nevada Legislature two years ago embraced intrastate
Internet gambling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legal or not, Schneider said, there will be no consumer
breakthrough for the industry until at-home players trust that the
games they play are honest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a handful of sites where there have been
problems,'' Schneider said. ``But those sites are pretty much
known. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Players communicate with each other. New players need to do
their homework.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Schneider's council later this month will begin
issuing what it calls seals of compliance to gambling Web site
applicants that pledge to adhere to the council's code of conduct
and dispute-resolution process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Better Business Bureau,'' she said of the group's
current list of 55 Internet industry members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Costa Rica, the Dow wagering proposition is similar to the
standard ``over-under'' bet on total points scored in an athletic
contest. Market watchers bet whether the Dow will close higher or
lower on the day after they place their wager. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Up or down, the odds are locked at -110, which means a bettor
must risk $110 to win $100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like most gambling Web sites, financial transactions occur
through players' credit cards or bank wire transfers, Price said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 a Greene County, Mo., grand jury returned a one-count
indictment against offshore-based Interactive Gaming &AMP;
Communications Corp. for operating an unlicensed Internet gambling
operation accessible to Missourians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case ended last fall in the nation's first prosecution of an
Internet bookie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a plea bargain, Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon accepted
misdemeanor guilty pleas of promoting gambling from the Web site's
publicly traded corporate parent, based in Pennsylvania, and its
chief executive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The defendants, who reported handling more than $30 million in
bets during 1997 and part of 1998, paid fines totaling $7,500. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
