u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-1STLD     04-07 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)  
 MEXICAN OFFICIALS ISSUE ARREST WARRANT FOR GOVERNOR IN
HIDING  (sw) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican authorities on Tuesday issued an arrest
warrant for the maverick governor of a Caribbean state that became
a cocaine smuggling center during his six-year tenure, which ended
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general, Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, said he had been
unable until now to seek the politician's arrest because as
governor he had enjoyed constitutional immunity from criminal
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But the ex-governor, Mario Villanueva Madrid, who abandoned his
duties last month and fled into hiding after he became the target
of a federal drug and racketeering investigation, said in a letter
from underground faxed to Mexican newspapers that the accusations
against him have been invented as part of a political vendetta.
Villanueva said that he would continue to elude arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva was the governor of the state of Quintana Roo in the
Yucatan peninsula. The warrant issued on Tuesday for his arrest
caps a lengthy investigation by Mexican and U.S. authorities that
is one of the most ambitious attempts to prosecute any senior
Mexican politician on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy statement issued on Tuesday night, the attorney
general denied that the investigation was politically motivated,
and requested international help in locating Villanueva.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter Villanueva faxed to newspapers late on Monday, he
offered for the first time his own explanation for his
extraordinary decision to go into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hounded by an investigation designed to incriminate me at all
costs, I had to take an extremely difficult personal decision:
abandon my native soil to avoid imprisonment,'' Villanueva said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a criminal,'' he said. ``They're persecuting me for
strictly political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not explain his whereabouts, which remain a mystery. On
March 26, Villanueva disappeared, leaving his state Government in
chaos after delivering a final speech to supporters in Chetumal,
the Quintana Roo capital at the south end of the Yucatan peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The letter confirmed what until recent days had seemed almost
unthinkable: that one of Mexico's 31 state governors and a leader
of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, has
fled into hiding to avoid arrest and begun to publicly attack the
Mexican justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't wait ingenuously for an injustice to be orchestrated
by federal prosecutors,'' Villanueva said in his letter. ``I'll
plan my defense, but not at the risk of prison or at the expense of
my ability to act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They accuse me of being a cocaine addict, but I'm not, and I
can prove that objectively and scientifically,'' he said. ``They
want to destroy me physically, psychologically and morally.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenure of Villanueva, 53, coincided with a surge in the
smuggling of Colombian cocaine through Quintana Roo, and Mexican
and U.S. officials have for a year been accusing the governor of
protecting traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his complaint that his prosecution is partisan will ring
true for many here because he has quarreled publicly with powerful
PRI officials and because many Mexicans believe that other senior
PRI politicians as well as military and police officials have
profited from the drug trade without facing prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
