<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8580 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     04-07 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN HURT AS ANGELS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ If it were a movie script, one would think it was
written by Stephen King, not the Walt Disney Co. After all, nowhere
in a Disney movie does the star attraction get hurt so soon after
the curtain opens.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened to first baseman Mo Vaughn only minutes
into his first game as an Angel. Vaughn, who signed a six-year, $80
million contract last November, roamed to the visitors' dugout on
the first base side in an attempt to catch a pop foul hit by the
Cleveland Indians' Omar Vizquel, the second batter of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn reached the edge of the top dugout step, then went one
step too far, falling into the dugout and spraining his left ankle.
He remained in the game and played five innings of the Angels' 6-5
victory, going 0 for 2.
</P>
<P>
   In typical Disney fashion, the game had a happy ending for the
home team. Troy Glaus' two-out double scored Garret Anderson from
first base in the eighth to give the Angels the 6-5 lead. And Troy
Percival, after strong performances by fellow relievers Mark
Petkovsek and Mike Holtz, closed it out with a 1-2-3 ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who was due to lead off the bottom of the sixth, was
replaced by Jeff Huson to start the top of the sixth so Vaughn
could go for precautionary X-rays, which were negative.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn limped noticeably while he was in the game, and fell at
the plate after hitting a fly ball to left field in his first
at-bat. But Angels medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum said after
Vaughn was taped up ``he felt comfortable enough to continue.
</P>
<P>
   At least for a little while.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another Angels' free agent acquisition struggled in
his debut. Tim Belcher, who signed a two-year, $10.2 million
contract, lasted just 41/3 innings, giving up five runs and six
hits while making 92 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back homers by Tim Salmon and Garret Anderson in the
fourth off Indians' starter Jaret Wright gave Belcher and the
Angels a 3-2 lead, but Belcher surrendered the lead in the fifth
when the Indians scored three runs on four hits.
</P>
<P>
   With Petkovsek providing three scoreless innings of middle
relief, the Angels rallied from their 5-3 deficit with two runs in
the seventh. Shortstop Andy Sheets drove in the first run with his
second hit of the night, and Darin Erstad's sacrifice fly scored
Matt Walbeck (2 for 4) to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was a little wild early, walking two in the first inning
and one in the second. But he didn't allow a hit until third inning
when Kenny Lofton led off with a triple and scored on Vizquel's
two-run homer. Vizquel, who had only two homers all of last season,
has just 30 career homers in 1,321 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got on the scoreboard against Wright in the bottom of
the third after Walbeck singled, went to third on Sheets' single
and scored on Erstad's groundout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
