<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WRITETHR     04-07 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE TO SUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For a more humane approach to this season of
water-drip torture, the Clippers have decided to abandon pretenses
and drown the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   In front Tuesday's captive audience of 6,450 at the Sports
Arena, the not-so-good guys began their NBA Draft lottery stretch
drive in an 88-83 loss to the ripe Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their little gimmick defense,'' said Clipper coach Chris Ford
of a half-court trap trotted out by the Suns (16-18) in the fourth
quarter, ``got us out of what we were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Clippers (3-30) were doing - while low-flying pigs
orbited the venue -- was controlling the game. Before committing
multiple acts of treason, they held scoreboard for the first 38
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just broke down on offense,'' point guard Sherman Douglas
said. ``We backed down; we lost the momentum and couldn't get it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, before the Clippers' signature fourth-quarter retreat,
this adventure started much like a Republican paradise: everything
was going right.
</P>
<P>
   One example of favorable mojo was the absence of Tom Gugliotta
(wounded knee), the Phoenix power forward who averaged 22 points
and 13 rebounds in two Suns victories over the Clippers this
season. Suns shooting guard Rex Chapman was on the injured list,
just another NBA veteran struck down by turf toe.
</P>
<P>
   Suns coach Danny Ainge did enough crabbing to attract stereo
technical fouls and watch the fourth quarter on a TV inside the
visitors' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected Clipper bonus was the play of dynamo Suns
point guard Jason Kidd, whose early performance - relative to his
all-star standards - was uglier than a bridesmaid dress. Through
three quarters, Kidd had seven points (on 3-of-10 shooting), four
assists and a season-high nine turnovers. But he finished with the
anticipated panache, scoring 15 points and handing out two assists
in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason got into his zone,'' Ford said. ``He just took over the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before what smelled like the inevitable, Eric Piatkowski - who
tied a career high with 29 points -- may not have taken the Suns to
school, but he dropped them off within walking distance. The
Clipper shooting guard pulled the trigger for 14 first-half points,
and the Suns trailed, 50-40, at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Piatkowski added seven in round three, but the Clippers' lead
was sliced to 65-62 entering round four. ``Pike'' scored eight more
before it was over, while the Phoenix trap had his teammates
inviting copyright lawsuits from relatives of the Keystone Kops.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Kidd had the Clipper defense chasing him like
overmatched babysitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you let him get off,'' Douglas said, ``you're in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you're in trouble, there's a good chance you also are in
the Sports Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
