<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ATHLETICS-N     04-07 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ATHLETICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT A'S, 7-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ David Cone has a respectable reputation as a
prognosticator. Before last year's playoffs, he thought that Scott
Brosius would star, that he had ``a glint in his eye.'' Brosius was
named the most valuable player of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, it should be noted, recently pointed to the adjacent
locker of Orlando Hernandez and said, ``I think he's going to have
a big year,'' emphasizing the word big. Big as in exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez took his first step toward realizing Cone's
expectations on Tuesday night, limiting Oakland to three hits in
seven and one-third innings in the Yankees' 7-4 victory _ their
first of the 1999 season and the first under the interim manager
Don Zimmer. Derek Jeter hit a triple and two singles in five
at-bats. He finished strongly in spring training, batting .378
during the exhibition season, and already has six hits in eight
at-bats in the regular season, with a 1.375 slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics rallied for three runs in the eighth off
Hernandez, Mike Stanton and Mariano Rivera, who got the save, to
pull within a run, 5-4. But Paul O'Neill's two-run triple in the
top of the ninth gave the Yankees a three-run cushion.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won 125 games in 1998 and it was Hernandez who
pitched and won in the only true must-win situation, Game 4 of the
American League Championship Series, which the Yankees entered
trailing 2 games to 1. The Yankees certainly did not need to win
Tuesday night's game in the same way; this was the second game of a
162-game schedule, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But in beating the Athletics, Hernandez applied some salve to a
team growing more tense by the day: The Yankees played poorly at
the end of the exhibition season, they didn't hit and lost the
season opener Monday, and it has been four days now since the
principal owner George Steinbrenner has spoken to his interim
manager. ``But I know I'm in his thoughts,'' Zimmer noted, before
sprouting a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Hernandez has supplanted Zimmer for a day in
Steinbrenner's mind, for he was brilliant on Tuesday night. Some
American League teams exploited Hernandez last year by stacking
their lineups with left-handed hitters. But Hernandez, El Duque,
has adapted to this, using a sharp curveball early in the count to
get ahead, then interchanging his fastball and changeup to finish
them off. The first seven hitters in Oakland's batting order were
either left-handed or switch-hitters, and combined to go 1 for 13
the first two times through the order.
</P>
<P>
   Before Manager Joe Torre left the Yankees, he shared thoughts
similar to those of Cone. The league cannot necessarily adjust to
Hernandez in this, his second year in the league, Torre said,
because there is nothing to adjust to, no pattern to discern.
Hernandez has such a wide-ranging variety of pitches and speeds and
throws from so many different angles _ high and low, from over the
top to down by his belt buckle _ that even after seeing him a
second or third time, they still don't know what to expect from
pitch to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, too, is adept at giving himself a chance to win. Last
year, he had quality starts (three runs or less in six or more
innings) in 14 of his 21 starts, the highest ratio of any Yankees
starter.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed just two hits and a run in the first five innings on
Tuesday night, and by then the Yankees already had a four-run lead
after jumping early on the Oakland knuckleball pitcher Tom
Candiotti. Chuck Knoblauch slapped a single over shortstop, Jeter
hammered a line drive to the wall in right-center for a triple, and
O'Neill flied out deep enough to center for Jeter to tag up and
score. Six pitches into the game, the Yankees led, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   They continued to beat on Candiotti in the second, using a
disciplined approach to hitting the right-hander's knuckler _
rather than take their normal step forward as they swung, some of
the Yankees waited patiently for the knuckler. Chad Curtis waited
and slammed a knuckler over the wall in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis singled leading off the fourth inning and Jorge
Posada walked, and the Oakland infielders moved in, suspecting that
Brosius would bunt with two on and no out. Instead, Zimmer ordered
a double steal, with the 39-year-old Davis as the lead man, and the
ploy worked. Davis scored when Brosius flied out to left, and
Posada eventually completed his trip around the bases on a wild
pitch and Curtis's sacrifice fly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
