<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-07 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN FORCED TO LEAVE ANGELS DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Whoops.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Angels are cursed.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn's California career got off to a shaky start Tuesday
night when he sprained his left ankle chasing Omar Vizquel's
first-inning popup in the Angels' season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans weren't yet in their seats (this is California, folks)
when Vizquel, the second batter of the game, hit a foul pop toward
the first base dugout. Mo, clearly unfamiliar with the terrain,
raced over and fell off the stage, dropping 4 feet down into the
Cleveland dugout. None of the Indians attempted to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the first, Anaheim fans gave him a standing
ovation when he came to the plate. Vaughn fell down in the batter's
box after he lofted a routine fly to left. He was late getting back
on the field for the top of the second. Presumably, the Angel
medical staff was taping his ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn flied to left again in the third. As the game wore on, it
became painful to watch him jog on and off the field between
innings. He didn't come out for the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Angels physician Lewis Yocum determined that Vaughn had sprained
the ankle, and the big first baseman was taken from the ballpark
for X-rays. The tests were negative, and Mo was on crutches in the
locker room following Anaheim's 6-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a high sky out there (Tuesday night),'' said Vaughn.
``I didn't really know where I was, and no one yelled anything. But
it's my job to protect myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearances, Vaughn isn't ready to rule himself out.
``I'll come back out to the park (Wednesday),'' he said. ``I'm a
quick healer, you never know. I'm just glad it wasn't broken.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Angels' curse? ``No curse,'' he replied. ``I've
already been through that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from Boston to Anaheim, and perhaps only the
late Stanley Kubrick could have properly chronicled the events that
led to Mo's departure from Fenway Park. He was a member of the Red
Sox organization for 10 years, bolting on the eve of last
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in front of his locker before his Angel debut, Mo talked
about what he misses in the Hub:
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss my friends. I miss Jimy Williams and the coaches over
there. I miss the fans. I'm gonna always miss the fans and things
like that, but I think it was a situation that we knew was gonna
happen. So I'll always look back and figure that Boston put me on
the map, but I also knew I had to make this change and I'm happy
where I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy taught me to play both sides of the ball. He taught me
how to play defense. He's a great teacher and a good man. He gives
it to you straight and tells you how it is. He's a baseball person.
He was good to me. They'll make him the fall guy if things go bad
there, but I'll always remember him _ and Rico (Petrocelli) and
Wendell (Kim) and (Jim) Rice and Grady (Little). Those are my
boys.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention Red Sox CEO John Harrington and general
manager Dan Duquette, the Eliot and Barry of Boston sports. Vaughn
last year called them ``the joint chiefs of staff.'' (``Did I
really say that?,'' he asked Tuesday night.) It was never really
clear which man wanted Mo gone, but the Sox carried out their plan
and now Boston's centerpiece player is an Angel.
</P>
<P>
   Mo joins the ever-expanding club of ex-Sox stars who travel the
big league circuit spreading the gospel of Boston's front office
buffoonery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got tired of all the garbage,'' Vaughn said. ``I felt
my job was to show up and play, and I did that. I played hard and I
played well. But it's hard when you don't have people that should
be behind you behind you. Now I'm in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is so tough because they haven't won and when things go
poorly, you need someone to step up and relieve the pressure. But I
have no hard feelings from where I have come from and what
happened. I was lucky that Roger (Clemens) had gone through it
before so I was kind of prepared for it. Boston was positive for me
and I enjoyed myself there, but I just knew that upstairs they
couldn't do it, and we had to make a move.''
</P>
<P>
   He claims to be happy in his new surroundings. He hit .271 in
spring training with only one homer and 14 RBIs. He said there's no
extra pressure riding shotgun with his $80 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it,'' he said. ``I just come out here and
play my game. If you prepare and work hard and put your time in,
it's gonna come to you. How it starts is not how it's gonna end.
When I'm out there playing, I'm not thinking about my contract.
I've always loved to just play this game. Period. And the
situations and the pressures is what you live on. You can't play in
more of a pressure situation than the one I played _ playing on a
one-year deal was the toughest thing. I just go out and play to my
capabilities and play hard. It's the thing I've always done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adjustment has been fine. It's been a good situation, a
smooth transition. The guys in the clubhouse and the organization
are all very nice. The game hasn't changed and I have the same
intensity I always had. I'm a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy and Shirley Vaughn have moved to this land of swimming
pools and movie stars. Mo said he'll keep his home in Easton, Mass.
He also said he'll keep sending first baseman's mitts to Mike
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's teammates say nice things about him. (Reliever
Shigetoshi Hasegawa says Mo has fine taste in Japanese jewelry.)
He's already made pledges to contribute to local charities. And
Mo's the go-to guy for that carnivorous California media. There
were no less than 20 reporters around his locker two hours before
the Angels took the field for their season opener.
</P>
<P>
   I took a chance and asked him the question that is on the lips
of every Sox fan I know. I asked him if he'd found any suitable
replacement for the Foxy Lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better cut it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I'll take that as a yes.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
