<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     04-07 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD'S HOMER WINS IT 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget brewing, the rivalry between the Arizona
Diamondbacks and Dodgers is brewed and ready to explode.
</P>
<P>
   A memorable opening day was followed by more drama, not to
mention some bad blood, and ended on left fielder Gary Sheffield's
one-out solo homer in the bottom of the 10th as the Dodgers beat
the Diamondbacks 3-2 Tuesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sheffield's first homer, and came on the first pitch he
saw from Diamondbacks reliever Brian Anderson. ``I remember Devon
(White) was telling me all game, `Gary, you're swinging
tentatively,''' Sheffield said. ``I just let it go. He gave me a
changeup, up, and I connected. I was being tentative. Before that,
I wanted to make sure I got a strike to swing at.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers' second straight extra-inning win doesn't appear
to be a culmination, but rather a beginning, to a feud.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks took umbrage with a pitch Dodgers right-hander
Chan Ho Park threw behind Matt Williams in the sixth inning. It
came one pitch after Williams, who hit his 300th career homer in
the fourth inning, missed another homer by a few feet before the
ball hooked foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't intentional,'' Park said. ``It wasn't on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, and Williams, thought otherwise. Williams
began shouting toward Park, and in a split second the benches and
bullpens of both teams emptied. Plenty of pushing and jawing took
place, but no punches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona manager Buck Showalter said both benches were given
warnings by the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they were throwing at Matt,'' Showalter said. ``The
warning after the fact... basically, they gain an advantage by what
they're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   During the episode, Diamondbacks starting pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre was animated. He didn't retaliate, but the battle may
not be over. It should also be noted that Bernard Gilkey, who hit a
pair of homers off Kevin Brown on Monday, was hit with a Park pitch
in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (Stottlemyre) was frustrated he couldn't do something
for our side,'' Showalter said. ``It makes it frustrating. A 2-2
ballgame makes it tough. But there will be other days.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said: ``It's a little
overreaction. You have to pitch batters inside.''
</P>
<P>
   With a hangover _ not to mention chill _ in the air from the
Dodgers' 8-6 opening-day win, it took a near-altercation and more
late heroics to shake things out. The teams were a combined 0 for
18 with runners in scoring position. The Diamondbacks' runs came on
solo homers by Steve Finley and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre's two-run homer in the second inning
gave the Dodgers a 2-0 lead. Still, the Dodgers were hitless in
their 11 at-bats with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it,'' Johnson said. ``The beauty was we
kept putting pressure on them. Every inning you could see it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was especially evident following the Park-Williams
excitement. But with two runners on and none out in the sixth, Eric
Karros grounded into a double play and Mark Grudzielanek flied out.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Karros had another opportunity with runners
on second and third and one out, but he popped out to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won,'' Karros said. ``I don't think anyone (cares) how, but
we won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had their chances, too, but also faltered.
</P>
<P>
   With Dante Powell on second and one out in the ninth, Dodgers
reliever Alan Mills (1-0) got Gilkey to pop to second and Tony
Batista to pop to catcher Todd Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   One inning later, Mills again pitched out of a jam, this time
with David Dellucci on third and one out. After Finley fouled off
six pitches, the right-handed Mills struck out the left-hander for
the second out. Jay Bell grounded to third to end the inning,
setting up Sheffield's blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense will come, and (Tuesday) it was Sheff,'' Hundley
said. ``But you have to keep the defense consistent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
