<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MODEL-SFCHRON &LR;      04-07 2095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MODEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 KOSOVO CRISIS SERVES AS MODEL OF WARS TO COME  &HT;     By FRANK VIVIANO 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  PARIS _ Two things stand out in the memory of anyone who has
traveled through Kosovo in the past decade: The poverty and the
madness.
<P>
   They are the defining context of the NATO bombing raids on
Serbia and its ethnic Albanian province, and the inevitable frame
for what is to come next. Like the Pentagon's high-tech weapons,
they also define the new face of war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the appearance of impromptu intervention, the United
States and its allies have actively prepared for this crisis. That
it will almost certainly lead to ground intervention _ to the
Western occupation of Kosovo _ has been quietly part of NATO's
policy assumptions since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that such assumptions will forge the template of
conflicts to come, a 21st century of Kosovos, Rwandas and
Kurdistans, in which the anxious decades of the Cold War will come
to be viewed as a carefree Pax Russo-Americana.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that there is little or no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what's happening in the world now,'' said Major Greg
Gerovac, a senior task force analyst for the U.S. Army in Europe.
``It's only prudent that we be ready to go into places like
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1994, Gerovac was part of a task force that began
training American infantry battalions, along with their
counterparts from six other NATO countries, for service in a
mythical nation torn by violent nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   The site chosen for the training was Hohenfels, a former Nazi
Wehrmacht base that covers 44,000 fenced-in acres of countryside
near Regensburg in southern Germany. Mock villages were constructed
in the base's rolling hills, with a distinctly Balkan architecture.
Bands of heavily armed ``ethnic militias'' were formed, manned by
GIs wearing guerrilla fatigues and carrying Soviet-manufactured
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Burned cars were scattered around the village streets. Tunnels
were dug under houses to hide terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The base became ``Vilslakia,'' an impoverished breakaway
province of a multiethnic federation known as ``Danubia.'' It was
provided with all of the now-familiar elements of the Balkan
nightmare _ artillery-shattered churches and mosques, a long
history of communal violence, political leaders for Danubia's
hostile factions, a U.S. State Department Area Report on the
crisis, troublesome journalists on the front lines and military
public relations officers to monitor them.
</P>
<P>
   The trainees were backed up with the full panoply of NATO arms
and equipment deployed in a ground campaign, notably including
Warlord battlefield computers for directing infantry assaults and
the same Apache AH-64A helicopters, outfitted with Hellfire
antitank missiles, that were shipped into Albania on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the NATO soldiers at ``Vilslakia'' were taught to cope
with overwhelming numbers of terrified refugees and with an
``enemy'' driven by blind, irrational sectarian hatred. ``In
evolving military terminology, a lot of what we're training for
here is `operations other than war,' '' said Gerovac, a principal
author of the scenario employed at Hohenfels.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario designed by Gerovac and his colleagues might have
stood for many of the former East Bloc states that crumbled into
violent disarray after 1990. But from the beginning, U.S. Army
Third Infantry officers understood that it was most closely
intended for a very specific contingency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't stuff we dream up. It's taken from newspapers and
intelligence reports,'' said Lieutenant Colonel John Angell, an
early graduate of the Hohenfels exercises and chief operations
officer for the U.S. mission in Macedonia in 1995. ``There's no
mystery about the model.''
</P>
<P>
   The model was Yugoslavia, and specifically Kosovo. The new face
of war, the cauldron of poverty and madness.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty is a cliche in Third World reporting. But the poverty of
Kosovo _ which lies within a normal day's drive of jet-set
Mediterranean resorts, and less than an hour's flight from Rome and
Munich _ nearly defies words. A single image from the mid-1990s,
sketched into a reporter's notebook in the village of Babus,
halfway between the Macedonian border and the provincial capital of
Pristina, will suffice:
</P>
<P>
   Barefoot children walk to school on an unpaved lane in the dead
of winter, with the thermometer at 15 degrees. No romanticism about
tough peasant constitutions here; these kids are visibly in pain,
hobbling along as fast as they can, thinking only of the kerosene
stove that awaits them in the school.
</P>
<P>
   Except for evening cooking fires, the houses of Babus were
unheated. Long before the bombs and shells began to fall on them,
they were already half-ruined, with tar paper stuck over gaps in
their mud walls. There were no indoor toilets or water pipes, which
would have been frozen in any case. The road was studded with sharp
rocks, as were the fields that surrounded the village. The fields,
planted in a feeble strain of maize, were the main source of
nutrition in Babus.
</P>
<P>
   When Yugoslavia was still whole in 1990, Kosovo's per capita
income was barely one-tenth that of Slovenia, at the opposite end
of the Yugoslav federation, which was itself less than one-half the
per capita income of Western Europe. In short, conditions for the
Kosovars, at home before the war, were only marginally better than
they now are in the swarming refugee camps of Albania and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Those conditions have worsened geometrically since the afternoon
in June 1989, when Slobodan Milosevic delivered his celebrated
speech in Kosovo calling for Serbian rights _ igniting the most
virulent nationalist firestorm to sweep Europe in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   The flames burned their way through Croatia and Bosnia, before
they returned to the countryside where they were lit by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty was the visible surface of Kosovo, and mostly, but
not entirely, Albanian. The madness was in the shadows, and at that
point _ before the Kosovo Liberation Army began adding its own
tinder to the flames _ it was mostly, but not entirely, Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   Its emblematic figure was Bozidar Pavnovic, a 45-year-old man
who lived with his wife and two daughters next to an abandoned
Serbian cemetery in the town of Vucitrn, about 12 miles north of
Pristina. He had answered Milosevic's call in 1989 and led his
family there on foot from their previous home 90 miles away in
eastern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Pavnovic has appeared in The Chronicle before, shortly after the
war swept into Bosnia in 1992. But it's instructive to listen to
him again, to know what NATO is up against if _ or when _ it sends
ground troops in after the bombs and missiles. The Vucitrn cemetery
was holy ground, Pavnovic explained, when asked why he had settled
among the tombstones. ``This is Serbia,'' he said in pidgin German.
``We fought and died on this ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were no Serbs other than the Pavnovics in the area at
the time, now,  &LR; and he was the cemetery's self-appointed guardian.
His daughters, who wore Serbian monarchist T-shirts, served tea as
he wrote a lengthy essay in the notebook.
</P>
<P>
   An English-speaking friend in Belgrade translated: ``The man
writes that he has come on behalf of all Serbs, the dead and the
living, to bear witness to the truth. He vows that he and his
family will not leave until Vucitrn is once again Serbian and the
Battle of Kosovo is avenged.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle, in which the Turks defeated the Serbs and drove them
out of Kosovo, which was resettled by Albanians, took place in 1389
on the plain where Milosevic gave his speech 500 &LR;   &LR; 600 years later.
</P>
<P>
   An ethnic Albanian schoolteacher in Vucitrn who read the essay
had refused to translate it and spat onto the pages where Pavnovic
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgrade friend, a talented writer in his mid-thirties, saw
nothing wrong with it. `I suppose that makes me a Fascist,` he
said, `but I really don't give a s_.`
</P>
<P>
   The writer's mother is a Jew, a survivor of World War Two
concentration camps. The new face of war is not entirely new.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first principle to be mastered in understanding why
the Kosovo war must be fought yet makes no sense: On a battlefield
of little strategic significance, and no economic value whatsoever,
the crisis is reduced to madness _ to a choice between confronting
it, at dangerously uncertain cost, or allowing it to fester at
greater cost.
</P>
<P>
   The normal policy questions _ what is to be gained, what
rationale can be applied _ are virtually irrelevant, which accounts
for the dazed confusion that seems to hang over the Alliance
partners even as the NATO assault mounts.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Rome, Bonn, London and other Western capitals, as in
Washington, the sense is that there are no right answers in the
Kosovar quagmire, only less wrong ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there rests any hope of obtaining by political
means the resolution of a conflict, the recourse to arms is not
legitimate,'' said Archbishop Jacques Delaporte, president of
France's Commission for Justice and Peace, who has worked since
1992 as a mediator on the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today, it seems to me, it is hard to deny that we find
ourselves in one of those situations where _ according to the most
steadfast doctrines of the Church _ the use of arms is legitimate,
as the `last resort,' to avoid an even greater evil,'' he agonized
on Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morality, in Kosovo, was not on the side of nonintervention,''
said agrees  &LR; Helmut Lippelt, co-founder of Germany's Green Party
and one of Europe's most outspoken pacifists.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, according to unconfirmed reports out of Kosovo,
Vucitrn was leveled by Serbian shells, which is partly why Bozidar
Pavnovic came to mind.
</P>
<P>
   This is the NATO account. In a rival account from Serbian
sources, the town was destroyed by NATO bombs. There is no word on
the fate of the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   All news out of Kosovo is unconfirmed. With the borders
effectively sealed _ apart from the outward tide of tens of
thousands of ethnic Albanians daily, expelled from the province by
Serbian militia _ rumor has largely replaced fact, in a Balkan
universe where genuine facts are hard to come even under the best
of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The last western journalist in Pristina, an Italian radio
reporter, vanished without a trace on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded by the West's military public
relations machine, which honed its ``news management'' skills in
the Gulf War and is diligently applying the lessons as it bombs
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press has a right to cover the story, and we have an
obligation to tell our side of it,'' Lieutenant Colonel Angell said
at the Hohenfels NATO base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how the media are handled, the story that goes
into print will either be ours, or someone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, the world's most respected newspapers and broadcast
companies reported that key ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo had
been summarily executed. NATO was the source of the report, and
also of the retraction two days later when the dead men
inconveniently appeared on Yugoslav television.
</P>
<P>
   The media war, too, betrays a kind of madness, played out
against the struggle for a land so poor that its value lies only in
historic symbols. It is as though Bozidar Pavnovic had taken charge
of events.
</P>
<P>
   This is the murk in which a host of critical conclusions must be
reached _ the policy conclusions of President Clinton and his
fellow NATO presidents and prime ministers, the public opinion
conclusions of their voters _ and there is no sign that the fog
will soon lift.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the outlook is starkly clear. Despite the
reassuring rhetoric across the Atlantic Alliance, despite the
promises that no ground troops will be deployed, NATO soldiers will
almost surely march into Kosovo _ to assume responsibility, to
confront the madness. To change the political equation by force.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message in the Hohenfels training, in the arrival of
Apache helicopters in Albania, in the steady buildup of Allied
troops in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the conflict continues, the more that the idea of
Kosovo remaining part of Yugoslavia will become unacceptable,'`
said Jacques Rupnik, director of research for France's National
Foundation of Political Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Americans finally come, we will have our own
republic. I am certain of that,'' a Kosovo Albanian leader told The
Chronicle last year.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that his name be used then. Today, it would be an
act of madness to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 0334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
