<HEADER>
A8639 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-SILICONVALLEY-SF     04-07 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SILICONVALLEY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE COURTS HIGH-TECH CALIFORNIA  &HT;     By ROBERT B. GUNNISON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Jose, Calif. _ In his 55th visit to California as vice
president, Al Gore put on an impressive display of presidential
campaigning Tuesday, but he got a good taste of how strongly
Republicans plan to challenge him for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day that included a visit to the Tech Museum in San
Jose and concluded with fund-raisers in the leafy wealth of
Woodside, a San Francisco suburb. Through it all, Gore used his
post as vice president to project himself as the only logical
candidate to succeed President Clinton next year.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he collected more than $330,000 for his campaign
from Silicon Valley executives who are also being wooed by
Republicans, especially Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the crowd of about 150 executives that he ``fought
every year'' for research and development tax credits and
``revolutionary changes in public education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of our nation is here in California,'' said the
vice president, a former senator from Tennessee. ``Every time I
come here, there's a bunch of things that weren't here yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gore's political future is here. California, with 54
electoral votes, is the election's richest prize next year. Clinton
and Gore have won the state twice, breaking 28 years of Republican
domination in presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's latest visit, his first as a candidate, prompted the GOP
to flex its muscles enough to show him that California cannot be
had without a fight. Indeed, a Field Poll in March showed Gore
basically tied with Bush and Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing weakness, Republicans greeted Gore with television ads
that poked fun of his recent claim that he played a vital role in
creating the Internet. The ads, paid for by the Republican
Leadership Council, are running 50 times a day on the four major
networks in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   In a newspaper advertisement on Monday, 55 high-tech executives
urged Bush to run for president, citing his views on education,
litigation and regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need visionary leaders who understand the New Economy,''
wrote the executives, some of whom have supported Republicans like
former Gov. Pete Wilson in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Bush backers are Jim Barksdale, president and CEO of
Netscape Communications; Bob Herbold, chief operating officer of
Microsoft Corp.; Jeff Henley, chief financial officer of Oracle
Corp; and Steve Behm, a vice president of Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   They praised Bush for ``creating an environment that stresses
personal responsibility over government intervention, and
innovation over regulation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican strategists said that despite the display,
Clinton and Gore have dominated the political support of high-tech
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton and Gore have worked Silicon Valley better than any
politicians in America,'' said Dan Schnur, former Republican
political director for Technet, a bipartisan lobbying organization.
``Republicans have forfeited it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans hope that as Gore emerges as his own political
personality, separate from Clinton, voter disenchantment will grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot we have to learn about Al Gore,'' said Leslie
Goodman, a Sacramento GOP strategist and friend of Bush. ``He does
not have the personality traits that served the president so
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But the stereotype of Gore as stiff and wooden seemed a bit of a
stretch Tuesday, as he easily mixed with children at the Tech
Museum and watched his wife, Tipper, play drums with a band that
included former Grateful Dead members Mickey Hart and Bob Weir at
the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   In shirtsleeves despite a chilly wind, Gore mixed with the crowd
in the yard of Janina Pawlowski, founder of E-Loan, an Internet
banking service, while the Flying Others Brothers Band played Dead
tunes.
</P>
<P>
   While the crowd drank wine and mineral water and munched on
shrimp and sushi, a smiling Gore listened to the band play ``Queen
Jane Approximately'' and watched his wife play the congas. ``She's
a pretty good drummer,'' he remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore arrived Monday in California, and he and Gov. Gray Davis
paid a visit to a largely Hispanic high school on the west side of
Los Angeles to announce $129 million in federal funds to help the
state's public high schools reduce the size of math and language
arts classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key changes we can make is to reduce the number of
students in each classroom,'' Gore said. ``I grow a little
impatient with these characters who talk about eliminating the
Department of Education.''
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to a Hollywood fund-raiser, Gore appeared on a
Spanish-language television station, where he chatted in Spanish
with an interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning at Merced Community College, Gore led a
roundtable discussion on improving access to higher education
before heading to San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
