 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 427 - April 7, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 427 -- April 7, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. KEATON CARRIES ON The ever-elusive Diane Keaton has survived
Woody, Warren and the Hollywood shuffle. This Garbo-esque recluse
and Oscar winner discusses her latest movie project, in which she
stars and directs and ponders what it means to be the unofficial
Queen of ``quirky.'' By Merle Ginsberg. From W magazine. 1,000
words + photos. 2. 'PHANTOM' OF THE ORCHESTRA ``John Williams
communicates so beautifully,'' says George Lucas, ``that I can make
a silent movie.'' ``The Phantom Menace,'' the eagerly awaited first
film in Lucas' new prequel trilogy to ``Star Wars,'' isn't a silent
movie. But neither were films of the ``silent'' era, which depended
on musical accompaniment to make their full effect. No-one can
think of the ``Star Wars'' movies without hearing John Williams'
music. The success of the film, and of the music, helped restore
the romantic symphonic movie score to popularity. Williams has now
recorded the music for ``Phantom.'' By Richard Dyer. From The
Boston Globe. 3,000 words + photo. 3. CREATING 'THE MATRIX' The
Brothers Wachowski hardly look like guys capable of revolutionizing
action movies. They dress like overgrown schoolboys, with baggy
hip-hop clothes and backwards baseball caps. But the Illinois
natives, in their early 30s, have just directed their second film,
``The Matrix,'' -- it's a new breed of techno-thriller. By Joshua
Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo. 4. MELISSA JOAN HART : A WIZ OF A
WITCH Forget about black cats, bats and bubbling cauldrons.
``Sabrina, The Teenage Witch,'' is the sunniest show about the
black arts ever, thanks to Melissa Joan Hart, 22, the high-spirited
young actress who provides a dependably upbeat tone to the show's
supernatural events. By David Kronke. From TV Guide Canada. 1,300
words + photo. 5. THE GRANDSON ALSO RISES : TONY GOLDWYN STEPS
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND THE CAMERA Tony Goldwyn knows more about Hollywood
history - he is the son of movie producer Samuel Goldwyn Jr. and
grandson of the late, legendary Hollywood impresario Sam Goldwyn -
than about Jewish-American history. But that hasn't stopped the
actor (best known as Patrick Swayze's lethally conniving friend in
the 1990 film ``Ghost,'') from producing and directing ``A Walk on
the Moon,'' a drama about the coming of age of the very Jewish
Kantrowitz family in 1969. ``The Jewish experience was really not a
part of my upbringing, yet I completely identified with this world
when I read the script.'' The emotional fireworks take place
against a backdrop of Woodstock and the Vietnam War, with the first
moon landing looming in the background. By Ian Spelling. 1,300
words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
THINK SYNC : BEHIND THE SCENES WITH A TEEN SENSATION The
phenomenally popular band ``N Sync'' has sold millions of albums
and the band members are continually mobbed by teenage girl fans.
The challenge, the band knows, will be to maintain this level of
fame in a sector of the music business known more for quick - and
temporary - success stories than for long-term careers. By Gary
Graff. 1,300 words + photo. 7. CHRIS O'DONNELL ISN'T ROBIN ANY MORE
``I'm not sure those tights from my superhero days would fit any
more,'' laughs Chris O'Donnell. He can joke about ``Batman and
Robin'' (1997,) the film flop that, it is rumoured, almost cost him
his career. Actually, he says, his two-year hiatus from the screen
was intentional. It gave him time to get married and adjust to life
as half of a couple, but it also involved getting away from
Hollywood for a time. Now he's back, with a full slate of projects
and a debut as a producer. Teenage girls are still flinging
themselves at this reluctant sex symbol. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300
words + photo. 8. CLAIRE DANES REVISITS 'THE MOD SQUAD' Clare
Danes, known for serious work on-screen, is finally getting her
chance to play cops and robbers as the delinquent-turned-cop Julie
Barnes in a big-screen version of the hip ``Mod Squad'' television
series. To try to make it more accessible to her generation,
director/co-writer Scott Silver has updated the story, while
retaining elements of the 1968-1972 series. The action now unfolds
in present-day Los Angeles, though there is plenty of 1970's style
on view. ``What made it appealing and exciting to me is that you
have a bunch of groovy, swanky, rebellious kids fighting the
system,'' Danes says. ``That will always be seductive. It's a
common process that kids have to work through.'' By Ian Spelling.
1,300 words + photo. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or
