<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-TAKE     04-07 1761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw TV commercials for Boston Market, but I
thought it had gone bankrupt. If that's the case, why is the chain
still running commercials?
</P>
<P>
   A: Boston Chicken Inc., owner and operator of Boston Market
stores, filed Chapter 11 bankruptcy in October. Chapter 11 allows a
company to continue operating, including advertising, under
scrutiny by the court while it tries to reorganize its finances to
stay in business.The Boston Market chain was built mainly by
franchisees who borrowed funds from Boston Chicken to open food
shops with sit-in eating. However, a substantial number of the
shops did not prosper and the franchisees were unable to pay back
their loans to Boston Chicken, a major reason for its bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand there are several states with no state income
tax. Which ones are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nine states have no income tax on earnings: Alaska, Florida,
Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington
and Wyoming. Tennessee, however, does tax interest and divident
income. The taxing method among the states varies greatly, with
some taxing all income at a flat rate and others taxing only higher
incomes. A few states assess a percentage of the taxpayer's federal
income taxes. New Hampshire and Alaska also have no general sales
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the seating configuration in economy class for
Delta's new Boeing 777? A recent article discussed business class
seating, but not the ``last class,'' and there's no information on
Delta's web site, either.
</P>
<P>
   A: Coach configuration is 2-5-2, said Delta spokesman Bill
Berry, which means two seats, an aisle, five seats in the middle,
another aisle, and two more seats.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We hear a lot about the Geneva Convention, but I'm confused
on one point. Did the United States ever sign it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first Geneva Convention (or treaty), providing for the
humane treatment of civilians, prisoners and wounded people in
wartime, was signed in 1864 and accepted by the United States, all
European countries, and some countries in Asia and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements in 1906, 1929, 1949 and 1977 added new provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States never ratified the 1977 Geneva Convention
protocols, intended to improve treatment of combatants and civilian
war victims and specifically outlaw hostage-taking and beating of
prisoners. One protocol dealt with international armed conflicts
and the second with domestic or civil warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States ratified the Geneva Conventions in
1956, the two modernizing protocols fell victim to cold war
politics. In l987, President Ronald Reagan sent the protocol
dealing with domestic conflicts to the Senate and recommended
ratification, but withheld the protocol on international conflicts,
arguing that it provided ``recognition and protection'' to
terrorists and anti-Western guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee, then under Democratic
control, disagreed with the Reagan administration, and refused to
even hold hearings on the second protocol while Reagan blocked the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia signed the 1977 protocols, as have more than 100
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Christiane Amanpour, CNN's international correspondent, is
married to James Rubin, the State Department spokesman. Is she a
U.S. citizen? When did she begin her TV career?
</P>
<P>
   A: She's a British citizen, according to CNN. Although she was
born in Britain, Amanpour spent many years in the United States,
and holds a bachelor's degree in journalism from the University of
Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining CNN in 1983 as an assistant to the network's
international assignment desk in Atlanta, Amanpour worked at
WJAR-TV in Providence, R.I., as an electronic graphics designer. In
1981-82, she worked as a reporter, anchor and producer for
WRBU-Radio, also in Providence. Her CNN career has included stints
as a writer and producer in its New York bureau. In 1990, she was
named CNN's correspondent in Frankfurt, Germany. After the Persian
Gulf War she joined CNN's Paris bureau, and in 1994 was named CNN's
chief international correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Two all-time baseball greats died recently, Cal Ripken Sr.
and ``Birdie'' Tebbetts. Ripken got a lot of well-deserved press,
but almost nothing was reported locally about Tebbetts. Can you
recap his career?
</P>
<P>
   A: George Tebbetts, 86, died March 24 at Sunrise Rehabilitation
Center in Bradenton, Fla., of congestive heart failure. He played
for the Detroit Tigers (1936-47, except for his three years in the
Army); the Boston Red Sox (1947-50); and the Cleveland Indians
(1951-52). In 1,162 games, the right-handed batter hit .270 and
made four All-Star teams. He also was manager of the Cincinnati
Reds (1954-58), the Milwaukee Braves (1961-62) and the Cleveland
Indians (1963-66). A heart attack in 1965 hastened the end of his
managing career, and from 1968 to 1994 he scouted for several Major
League teams.
</P>
<P>
   About the nickname: He was born George Robert Tebbetts on Nov.
10, 1912, in Burlington, Vt. When he was a boy, an aunt said of his
high-pitched voice: ``He chirps like a bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article about troublesome computer dates other than
Jan. 1, 2000, reported that Feb. 29, 2000, is a leap year and
computers may miss the added day. I always thought leap years
occurred every fourth year except in those years divisible by 400,
like the year 2000. Is my memory of my college astronomy classes
failing me?
</P>
<P>
   A: World Book Encyclopedia expains that a leap year (with 366
days) occurs in every year that can be divided evenly by four,
except the years that mark the even hundreds, such as 1500. The
only century years that are leap years are those than can be
divided evenly by 400, such as 1600 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Q: President Clinton's job approval rating was reported often in
the media during the Monica Lewsinsky scandal. What is it now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Still up there. The Gallup Organization of Princeton, N.J.,
takes polls constantly. The fastest way to monitor them is online _
www.gallup.com _ by clicking first on Gallup Poll (near the top of
the page), then Poll Trends on the next page, and then Clinton
Presidential Ratings-Job Approval on the page after that.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent job approval poll, taken March 19-21, showed
that 64 percent approved, 33 percent disapproved, and 3 percent had
no opinion. In a one-night poll taken March 25, asking about
Clinton's handling of the Kosovo situation, the numbers showed 58
percent approval, 32 percent disapproval, and 10 percent no
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's average approval rating for the last quarter of 1998
was 66 percent in the Gallup poll. Even during Clinton's Senate
impeachment trial, his job approval numbers remained high, even as
his ratings on honesty and moral character dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the movie ``Mr. Holland's Opus,'' a beautiful young
actress sang ``Someone to Watch Over Me.'' I thought she was
wonderful, but I haven't seen her since. Who is she, and what can
you tell me about her career?
</P>
<P>
   A: She's Jean Louisa Kelly. The 26-year-old started singing
lessons as a tot, and by age 10 was crooning her grandparents'
favorite George Gershwin and Cole Porter tunes while other kids
were more interested in Duran Duran. She began her professional
career at the age of 11, starring in a community theater production
of ``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first film was ``Uncle Buck'' (1989), after which she
appeared in the TV movies ``American Shaolin'' (1991) and ``One
More Mountain'' (1994). In 1995's ``Opus,'' she portrayed Rowena
Morgan, who stole the show and almost stole Mr. Holland's (Richard
Dreyfuss') heart. That was followed by a number of appearances on
TV, on stage and in other films, including ``The Fantasticks,'' one
of the most beloved musicals in American history.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 Columbia University graduate, Kelly married James Pitaro,
a New York attorney, in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Oxfam America was listed in an article as one of the relief
agencies accepting contributions for Kosovo refugee assistance.
What does it do, and how much of the money sent to it actually is
passed on to the people in Kosovo who need it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oxfam _ the name comes from the postal abbreviation for the
Oxford Committee for Famine Relief _ was founded in England to send
relief supplies to refugees in Europe during World War II. It is an
international organization with 11 divisions, one of which is Oxfam
America. The organization says it provides financial, technical and
networking assistance to grassroots groups; advocates policies
addressing structural impediments to ending poverty and hunger; and
educates people about world hunger and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam America says it doesn't send relief supplies, preferring
to provide funding and technical support to local organizations for
their own initiatives to ensure that supplies _ such as food,
water, shelter and clothing _ are appropriate to meet local needs
and to help strengthen the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Connolly, spokeswoman for Oxfam America in Boston, told
Q&AMP;A that 90 percent of the donated funds will go to help the
refugees in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that the Federal National Home Mortgage
Association has given a new house to the parents of the seven
surviving octuplets in Texas. Do you have any details? Who do I
contact to voice my disapproval?
</P>
<P>
   A: If your concern is that taxpayer money is being used, that
isn't the case, according to a Fannie Mae spokeswoman in Dallas.
Fannie Mae, a private New York Stock Exchange company, is the
nation's largest source of financing for home mortgages. What
happened is that the previous mortgage holders on the house, which
was built in 1992, weren't able to pay their commitment, so Fannie
Mae took possession of it. After being approached by Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee (D-Texas), Fannie Mae donated the house to a trust that
benefits the seven children of Nkem Chukwu and Iyke Louis Udobi.
</P>
<P>
   The house was appraised at $274,000, according to real estate
records. You can express your opinion by writing: Fannie Mae,
Southwestern Regional Office, P.O. Box 650043, Dallas, TX
75265-0043.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
