NYT-04-07-99 1029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-TAKE     04-07 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS08-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is it known which NATO countries are supplying what in the
way of equipment and personnel in the Yugoslavia campaign, in
addition to what the United States provides?
</P>
<P>
   A: The situation is fluid, so changes are occurring all the
time. As of late March, Britain, Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France,
Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain and Turkey
were contributing.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment from NATO countries other than the United States
included CF-18s from Canada; F-16s from Norway, Denmark, Portugal,
the Netherlands, Belgium and Turkey; Harrier jump-jets and Tornados
from Britain; Jaguars and Mirages from France; F/A 18s from Spain;
and Tornados from Italy. Among the naval strike assets from
countries other than the United States were one German and two
British frigates and what NATO described as ``significant Italian,
French, Spanish, Greek and Turkish naval units.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops ``in region'' include a 2,000-man European rapid
reaction force, led by France, which set up operations in
Macedonia. Since December, NATO also has operated two on-going
peacekeeping missions in the Balkans: one in Bosnia, a
multinational mission with 31,000 troops, about 6,100 of which are
American; the other in Macedonia, with a border patrol force of
750, about 350 of which are American.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is eligible for burial at Arlington National Cemetery,
and what is the procedure for making arrangements?
</P>
<P>
   A: The list of those eligible is lengthy and includes, among
others, active duty and retired members of the armed forces;
winners of such decorations as the Medal of Honor, Silver Star and
Purple Heart; former prisoners of war; and spouse, widow, widower
and minor child of those eligible. In some cases, restrictions
apply to those in the various categories.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington's hotline _ 703-697-9486 _ is a resource for
information about eligibility criteria. Or write: The
Superintendent, Arlington National Cemetery, Attn.: ANN-ADI,
Arlington, VA 22211. Internet users can get information at this
site: www.arlingtoncemetery.com/
</P>
<P>
   Q: I will be traveling to Israel, Egypt and Jordan. What are the
regulations about bringing a gun in my baggage?
</P>
<P>
   A: You should contact the official U.S. representatives of the
countries involved:
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Embassy of Israel, 3514 International Drive NW,
Washington, DC 20008 (202-364-5500).
</P>
<P>
   Egypt: Embassy of the Arab Republic of Egypt, 3521 International
Court NW, Washington, DC 20008 (202-895-5400 or 202-966-6342).
</P>
<P>
   Jordan: Embassy of the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, 3504
International Drive NW, Washington, DC 20008 (202-966-2861 or
202-966-2664).
</P>
<P>
   Q: We see on TV that the Pentagon spokesman speaking about the
NATO offensive in Yugoslavia is Kenneth Bacon. Wasn't he in trouble
not long ago for releasing some personnel information about Linda
Tripp? What's the status of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The information you're referring to was printed in the March
23, 1998, edition of New Yorker magazine. It reported that Tripp
had been arrested in 1969, at age 19, on a charge of grand larceny,
and that she later pleaded guilty to loitering. The article said
Tripp, who claimed she was the innocent victim of a prank played on
her by friends who carried out the theft, failed to state on a
Pentagon security clearance form that she had an arrest record.
Tripp said she thought the incident had been cleared from her
record.
</P>
<P>
   As previously reported, Bacon apologized last May for confirming
to New Yorker writer Jane Myer that Tripp had denied on her
personnel record any past arrests. In his apology, Bacon said he
should have consulted with Pentagon lawyers or Tripp's lawyers
before releasing the information, but he said he spoke neither to
White House officials nor Pentagon officials before doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The apology appears to have put the incident to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A colleague's finally seeing ``Saving Private Ryan'' prompts
my question. Did the beach areas of Omaha, Utah, Juno, Gold and
Sword have other names before Allied strategists so dubbed them? We
couldn't imagine some French family in summer 1938 saying, ``What a
beautiful day. Let's go down to Omaha Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   A: The family might have said (in French, of course), something
more like this: ``What a beautiful day. Let's go down to
Port-en-Bessines.''
</P>
<P>
   The beaches chosen for the landings that began June 6, 1944,
stretched from the estuary of the Orne to the southeastern edge of
the Cotentin Peninsula. The names used before then actually
referred to areas, said George Hern Jr., former public relations
director of the French Government Tourist Office. Before 1944, the
area code-named Sword would have stretched between Riva-Bella and
St. Aubin, Hern said; Juno, between St. Aubin and Asnelles; Gold,
between Asnelles and Port-en-Bessines; Omaha, between
Port-en-Bessines and Isigny; and Utah, between Isigny and
Quineville.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors in search of the invasion story 55 years later should
go to Arromanches, Hern advised, where they can have lunch at a
hotel near a diorama showing where the Allies went ashore. The
remains of Mulberry, the artificial port built by the Allies to
support the landing, are still there. The American Cemetery, at St.
Laurent near Omaha Beach, ``will drive home to visitors exactly
what happened here,'' Hern said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I attended an American Physical Society's lecture by Stephen
Hawking, who has been called Albert Einstein's intellectual
successor. Would a transcript of his remarks be available so I can
reflect on them?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately, Hawking doesn't make transcripts available of
his public lectures. Ben P. Stein, spokesman for the American
Institute of Physics, sister organization of the American Physical
Society, said he was told that Hawking prefers just to give the
lectures, and to avoid making transcripts out of concern that they
might be misused by others or sold for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Stein suggests that those who are interested in Hawking's
theories should read his book, ``The Illustrated Brief History of
Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm in the dark about the nickname Blue Devils used by Duke
University. What does it refer to, and how did it originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Duke is firm on one thing: The nickname isn't satanic. It was
derived from the French Blue Devils, a crack Alpine corps that wore
a blue uniform with a blue beret.
</P>
<P>
   It came to be used by Duke in the early '20s when R. Dwight
Ware, editor-in-chief of the Trinity Chronicle, wrote that the
then-current nicknames _ the Methodists and the Blue and White _
weren't satisfactory. Several meetings of the entire student body
were called, and any and all suggestions were aired. Blue Devils
was suggested by William Lander, an assistant editor of the
Chronicle, although he later admitted that even he wasn't
enthusiastic about it. No name got anywhere near a majority vote,
so at the end of the 1922 school year Duke still was without a team
nickname. The following year, Lander and Mike Bradshaw were named
editors of the Chronicle. They decided that before they departed in
June 1922, the Chronicle would start using the name Blue Devils for
the school and its teams. The name has stuck through the years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In view of current military operations, I'm curious about
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen. I once heard that he served in
the National Guard. Do you know when, and in what unit or units?
What rank did he attain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cohen, who was born in 1940, was never in the armed forces,
National Guard or otherwise. In 1988, when he was a Republican
senator from Maine on the Armed Services Committee, Cohen explained
how he avoided being drafted. ``I was exempt: college deferments
and so forth, all the way through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
