<HEADER>
A8785 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS08-COX     04-07 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quintessential Murphy bio is `Best Revenge'
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's a pleasure to welcome Living Well
is the Best Revenge ($16.95) to the Modern Library. Essentially a
slightly expanded New Yorker profile, Calvin Tomkins' book tells
the story of Gerald and Sara Murphy, the guiding lights of the
Paris expatriates of the '20s and the dedicatees of Tender is the
Night.
</P>
<P>
   In its cool, understated way, it seems superior to Amanda Vail's
recent biography of the Murphys _ more mystery, more bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   Living Well is the Best Revenge was first published in 1971 and
has dated not at all. Tomkins has contributed a new introduction
and rewritten the ending to accommodate new information about
Gerald Murphy's wonderful paintings, including the cover, which
features Cocktail, in the collection of the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Saskatoon? . . .
</P>
<P>
   According to the Places Rated Almanac, the best-read readers
live in the following places, from the top: Fort Wayne, Ind.;
Jamestown, Va.; Cleveland; Bangor, Maine; Champaign, Ill.; Columbus
and Toledo, Ohio; Long Island, N.Y.; Saskatoon, Canada; and Iowa
City, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   I assume this is somebody's idea of a joke. Including Wheeling,
W. Va., might have made it too obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Things to look forward to . . .
</P>
<P>
   In case you're not sick of the travails of Wild Bill Clinton and
his pursuers, hang on. The Washington Post's Susan Schmidt is
co-writing To the Point of Knives: The Triumph and Tragedy of Ken
Starr for HarperCollins, and St. Martins has signed up Joe Conason,
from the always entertaining New York Observer, and Gene Lyons of
the Arkansas Democrat to write The Hunting of the President: The
Ten-Year Campaign to Destroy Bill and Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the perennially best-selling Ann Rule is writing a
book on the Anne Marie Fahey/Thomas Capano affair, for Simon and
Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, over on the fiction front, Scott Turow will have a new
book out this fall. Personal Injuries is about a sleazy attorney
who pays off corrupt judges to avoid going to trial. Little, Brown
will publish.
</P>
<P>
   Things to avoid . . .
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt, one of the classier publishers, has laid off about
20% percent of its work force in an attempt to restore
profitability after some down years. Holt is also cutting its list;
after publishing about 250 books a year under various imprints,
Holt will put out about 200 titles this year.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Without magic, there is no art. Without art, there is no
idealism. Without idealism, there is no integrity. Without
integrity, there is nothing but production.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Raymond Chandler
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eyman writes for the Palm Beach Post, est Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
