<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Use my cell phone? 10-4, good buddy
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In his Monday column, editorial page editor
Arnold Garcia Jr. accused me of falling ``into the ranks of
yuppiedom'' because I own a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, Arnold Garcia is wearing a tie in his mug shot. And
as a new cell phone owner, I'd like to complain about this rush to
judgment people make when they see somebody with a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Y'all figure us cell phone users eat out of blenders and shop at
Saks. Pony poop.
</P>
<P>
   That's why today I'm suggesting we cell phone users get rid of
our upwardly mobile image by adopting handles.
</P>
<P>
   Why haven't unjustly branded cell phone users thought of this
before? Just like CBers, we talk from our vehicles, right? Like
CBers, we've got our ears on, good buddy. Like CBers, when pricked,
we bleed. The similarities between cell phoners and CBers are at
least slightly eerie.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that cell phoners are assumed to be stuffier than
CBers and less likely to smack someone over the skull with a pool
stick.
</P>
<P>
   This image problem would be fixed if we cell phoners would take
on handles like the Jolly Joker, Little Nanner or the Skanky Hanky.
</P>
<P>
   To lend panache to the cellular phone movement, I've decided to
take the lead and become the first cell phone operator in America
with a cell phone handle. Right now, I'm leaning toward calling
myself either the Analog Animal or the Digital Dummy.
</P>
<P>
   The second of the two handles would be more appropriate, because
I can't figure out how to use all of the options on my new cell
phone. For starters, I should never have fooled with the alarm
clock setting. Now I can't make it stop going off every night at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, I do have a legitimate reason for getting a cell
phone. I'm traveling around Texas, working on a book about goofy
stuff all over the state. So I'm visiting areas where pay phones
are sometimes hard to find. A few weeks back, I attended the World
Championship Rattlesnake Races in San Patricio, northwest of Corpus
Christi.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the folks who entered this contest brought their own
snakes. But I may have been the only person there who brought his
own cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Since I'm working in these out-of-the-way spots, my wife, Sally,
figured I should carry a cell phone in case of emergencies, like
finding yourself at a rattlesnake race. The suggestion sounded
good. But there's one problem. When you talk on a cell phone,
sometimes you sound like you have library paste in your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   When I called my wife at home to check in from the rattlesnake
races, I said over my cell phone, ``I just pulled into the parking
lot at the rattlesnake races.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the response I got from my wife, I think it came out
sounding like, ``I just ------ ---- the ----ing --- -- --- ---.''
Because she responded, ``I can't understand a word you're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   See, I could understand her just fine because she wasn't talking
on a cell phone. But she couldn't understand me, because I was.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse. I'm lucky my message didn't come out,
``I just pulled into --- -a------ lot -- --- rattlesnake ----s.''
My wife might have called 911.
</P>
<P>
   But who's complaining? My new cell phone tells darn good time.
And the alarm works daily at midnight sharp. And I still don't have
to wear a tie.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
