<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing frivolous about breastfeeding
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dana Derungs knew what some people would think if
she sued Wal-Mart for preventing her from breast-feeding at its
Lebanon, Ohio store two years ago:
</P>
<P>
   Just another frivolous lawsuit, clogging up the courts. Rush
Limbaugh material. Bob and Tom, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing frivolous about the right of a nursing
mother to go out in public. The only thing frivolous about this
case is that, in 1999, it should be an issue at all.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Lebanon mother of two had never been to a La
Leche League meeting, never been an activist of any sort until the
day in April 1997, when she took her six-week-old son, Devin,
shopping at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   She sat down at a bench outside the women's dressing room with
the baby, and, before she could even start nursing, a sales clerk
approached her and asked her to nurse the baby in the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her if she would feed her child in the restroom, or
eat her own lunch there,'' Derungs recalled, ``and of course she
said no.''
</P>
<P>
   She fled in tears, but came back two weeks later with about 80
nursing mothers, babies and their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   An activist had been born. Derungs testified before the Ohio's
Women's Policy and Research Commission, created by the state
legislature to study women's issues, and filed a complaint with the
Ohio Civil Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Derungs said, she has attempted to convince
Wal-Mart to offer an apology and adopt a breastfeeding-friendly
policy. ``Enough time has passed,'' she said. ``I don't want to see
any other mother go through what we went through.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart spokesperson Laura Pope said she couldn't comment on
the specifics of the case because of the lawsuit, but added, ``We
do allow mothers to breastfeed in our stores.'' Yet, six months
after the incident, Jennifer Gore of New Lebanon said she was asked
to stop breastfeeding her son at a Wal-Mart. ``She was feeding her
child so discreetly that the clerk had to ask her, 'How did you get
your child to stop crying?''' said attorney Susan Brasier, who
represents Derungs and Gore in their lawsuit against Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. ``If she had said, 'I just shifted positions,' nobody
would have known the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Montgomery County Common Pleas Court on
behalf of Derungs and Gore and their sons, asks for unspecified
damages. What they are really seeking, Brasier said, is a woman's
fundamental right to nurse her baby: ``What you see with a nursing
mom is less than what you'd see in the checkout line at the grocery
store on the cover of Cosmopolitan. It's socially acceptable to use
breasts to sell automobiles, but not for the purpose for which God
intended them.''
</P>
<P>
   Derungs wants an apology and a policy from Wal-Mart. That's not
a bad start, but Ohio mothers need more than that. Under current
law, the showing of the nipple in public is a fourth-degree
misdemeanor for a first-time ``offender.'' Does this mean
breastfeeding mothers can be charged with a crime? Maybe. Of
course, we could forever remove the ambiguity with a change
specifically making it legal to breastfeed in public. However,
since 1994 such legislation has been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, state lawmakers have another chance. Dayton's state Sen.
Rhine McLin and state Rep. Dixie Allen have introduced a bill, now
in judiciary committee, granting a mother the right to breastfeed
her child in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did they do in the Wild West to get some milk, unless
they had a goat?'' McLin said. ``What did Eve do?
</P>
<P>
   ``It just amazes me there's such uproar about doing the right
thing. Why belabor this issue when there are so many issues more
pressing?''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
