<HEADER>
A8796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX     04-07 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vegan holier than cow?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Animal terrorists finally forced the removal of a
``Jesus was a vegetarian'' billboard in Amarillo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Threats were made that animals would be mutilated if the
billboard wasn't taken down.
</P>
<P>
   The company that owns the billboard space bowed to threats and
public outcries and removed the message, according to People for
the Ethical Treatment of Animals, which put up the billboard.
</P>
<P>
   Faxed letters to the editor from PETA attempted get the word out
in time for Easter Sunday that Jesus was a vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   After concluding its argument that Jesus ate only vegetables,
PETA's letter said, ``On Easter Sunday, please bless the animals,
not by saying grace over pieces of them on plates, but by sharing a
peaceful, loving vegetarian dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   The billboard's message about Jesus' diet was erected in
Amarillo where the nation's press came to cover television star
Oprah Winfrey's trial for insulting Texas cows.
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers provided an irresistible opportunity for Texas
cattlemen to make themselves and the state look foolish. In 1995,
lawmakers passed the now-infamous ``veggie libel law.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year when Oprah said on her show that she was going
stop eating hamburgers after hearing reports of mad cow disease,
about 100 Amarillo cattlemen slapped leather in a quick-draw
contest to hire lawyers to sue Oprah for ``false disparagement of
perishable food products.''
</P>
<P>
   Oprah rode into town with her band of top-gun lawyers for the
big high-noon showdown. She also brought along her entire broadcast
retinue to continue her show while her lawyers blew away the
cattlemen's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides lawyers, an entire television cast and the usual media
mob, the Oprah trial also attracted the animal rights crowd, which
sided with the cows over the cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   As the world knows, Oprah mopped the courtroom floor with the
Texas cattlemen and rode out of town taking her lawyers, her
television cast, the national media and the imported animal rights
activists.
</P>
<P>
   What was left was the ``Jesus is a vegetarian'' billboard. And
now, according to PETA, even the message that Jesus wouldn't
swallow what Texas cattlemen were selling has left town.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its argument that Jesus was a vegetarian, PETA quotes
philosopher and theologian Arthur Schopenhauer. ``European
priestcraft,'' he wrote, ``knows no limits to its disavowal and
blasphemy against the Eternal Reality that lives in every animal.
... The fact that Christian morality takes no thought for beasts is
a defect in the system which is better admitted than perpetuated.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't see how Arthur's quote proves that Jesus was
a vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   But PETA's Web site, www.JesusVeg.com, has more theological
arguments to support its claim. The animal rights organization says
the practice of animal sacrifices during Jesus' time was an excuse
for humans to eat animal flesh. Jesus, PETA argues, condemned
animal sacrifices and eliminated the practice altogether at the
Last Supper, which is described as a vegetarian Passover meal.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting, if true, as an admired columnist used to say.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no theologian, but I recall where the Bible describes how
Jesus fed about 5,000 followers, not counting women and children,
who hadn't eaten for several days. He fed them fish and bread by
turning several loaves of bread and a couple of fish into more than
enough food for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   At another time he helped some fishermen catch fish.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound like evidence of vegetarianism to me.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I'm fond of fish. And I'm not saying that just
because I fear getting sued for bad-mouthing some Texan's catfish.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
