<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORRISBROWN-CROSS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Standing her ground at Morris Brown
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By her early teens, Morris Brown College President
Dolores Cross already had learned to make tough decisions without
blinking an eye, backing down or walking away.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 8, she overcame a stuttering problem by writing
and directing a school play, giving her more confidence. At 14, she
had to get a job to pay her family's rent in a Newark, N.J.,
housing project after her mother was institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the classic middle-class upbringing you normally
associate with college presidents,'' said Cross.
</P>
<P>
   So when she faced angry faculty members last month and told them
that, despite their pleas, they probably would be fired, it wasn't
completely out of character.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she fired 13 of them, fulfilling a promise to clean
house and restore, in her opinion, academic integrity at the
118-year-old historically black institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people need to be released,'' said Kisha Hopson, a
22-year-old senior. ``I think she probably has the best interest of
the school and the students at heart with the decisions she is
making.'' Cross came to Morris Brown after a two-year stint at the
GE Fund, the philanthropic arm of General Electric, where she
served as president, and, most recently, as Distinguished Professor
of Leadership and Diversity at the City University Graduate School
and University Center in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1997, she was the president of Chicago State
University, becoming the first woman and only African-American
president of a public college in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``She took over an institution really in trouble in every sense
_ academically, low morale ... that was neglected for years,'' said
Marva Jolly, who has taught in CSU's art department for 16 years.
``Now, CSU is recognizable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross eliminated tenure based on longevity in favor of more
scholarly research. She also engineered a $30 million expansion of
the university. The school experienced a 60 percent enrollment
increase, its retention rate rose to 67 percent from 18 percent,
and its graduation rate increased 57 percent. Cross' final year at
CSU came shortly after her mother died. ``It just seemed to be the
time,'' said Cross. ``Her transition became my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozie Johnson Tucker, who in the 1940s became the first
African-American woman to pass the telephone operator's exam in New
Jersey, raised her two daughters alone in Newark. Cross said that
when she was 13, racism and pressure led her mother to an emotional
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister and I went to live in the Salvation Army,'' Cross
said. ``At 14, I had to work to get money. We had to learn to be
independent very young.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross said her mother eventually got better and returned to
work, which inspired her daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my mother as a strong person who took risks. She always
encouraged me to be involved.'' Cross' plans for Morris Brown call
for creating more pre-college programs to attract, cultivate and
groom potential students as early as the sixth grade. She also
wants to set up partnerships with graduate schools in which Morris
Brown would serve as a feeder school.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the middle part of her plan that is the stickiest:
improving the academic quality on campus. ``We have to make sure
when the students come here, they have a quality education,'' said
Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get people who are excited about what they want to
achieve. I want Morris Brown to create a model of what I think
HBCUs (historically black colleges and universities) should do, a
model for what should happen at a quality undergraduate
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
