<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRAT-CONTRIBUTOR0     04-07 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRAT-CONTRIBUTOR08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democratic dynamo looks to empower party
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Monte Friedkin reaches up to put Bill
Clinton's gold braided, yachtsman's cap back on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing it carefully on Clinton's cardboard noggin, Friedkin
grins at the life-size figure that dominates the office of one of
Florida's biggest contributors to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   With the shades-wearing, saxophone-playing image of Clinton
peering over his left shoulder, Friedkin is tooting his own horn.
He wants you to know that the days of a placid Democratic Party in
Palm Beach County are over. He intends to turn the county party
into the most powerful political force in the state.
</P>
<P>
   What worries Republicans is that Friedkin has the money,
contacts and influence to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Already he has opened a party office, hired staff, bought
computers and now he is planning to raise more than $250,000 in
November with a dinner for 1,000 that will feature House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, a personal friend.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he says he wouldn't be surprised if Vice President Al
Gore shows up.
</P>
<P>
   He says this with the casual confidence of a man who has
contributed and raised millions of dollars for Democratic
candidates _ someone who expects phone calls to be returned by the
most important Democrats on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is fairly well-known on the national scene, particularly in
the Senate,'' says Ken Klein, who worked with the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee when his boss, U.S. Sen. Bob Graham,
chaired the committee in 1994. ``He's also known to the president
and vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Monte Norman Friedkin, a Youngstown, Ohio, native who
attended the University of Miami and returned to South Florida in
1985, was content being a member of an elite group of big
contributors who work largely in obscurity. Now he talks about the
radical right, the disarray in the Democratic Party and his
determination to destroy the one and rebuild the other even if it
means overpowering the state party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no personal agenda,'' insists the 59-year old Friedkin,
who is also vice president of the American Israeli Public Affairs
Committee, one of the strongest lobbying groups in Washington.
``I'm not running for public office. I have no desire to run for
public office. I'm here to make sure that we have a viable party
that elects Democrats and that once they are elected that the party
keeps their feet to the fire and makes them do what they are
supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am,'' he says unapologetically, ``a very partisan
Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   At Eleanor Roosevelt's knee
</P>
<P>
   As a young boy, he remembers being one of three Jews in school.
Coming from a wealthy family made it even harder. ``I wasn't just a
Jew, I was a rich Jew, and the other kids beat the hell out of
me,'' he says adding with a laugh. ``I learned to run faster than
any kid in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Roosevelt spent a weekend at his father's house when
Friedkin was a boy, leaving an impression that remains with him
today. ``She was helping to raise bonds for Israel, and I watched
her that weekend sitting on our living room couch talking to the
press, and she was very direct,'' he remembers. ``She never
flinched.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Friedkin say he never flinches either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very direct. You know where he stands. There is no
ambiguity,'' Klein says. ``And if he tells you he will do
something, you can count on him to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin's abiding passion for Israel is well-known on Capitol
Hill. He is a major contributor to Jewish causes, a founder of the
National Jewish Democratic Council, of which he is national
chairman, and a frequent critic of those, both Jewish and gentile,
who oppose his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a woman, especially a Jewish woman, be a Republican?''
he says. ``First of all, they are all pro-choice, and most
Republicans are not pro-choice. If it were up to Republicans, women
would not have the right to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   From car dealer to aluminum manufacturer, Friedkin has been
involved in numerous businesses. His wife, Skeets, is well-known in
the world of charity. They have two daughters and a son, Shawn, 35,
who founded Stand Among Friends, an organization involved in spinal
injury research. Shawn Friedkin was paralyzed in a 1992 car
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin credits state Sen. Tom Rossin and Rep. Lois Frankel,
both West Palm Beach Democrats, with getting him involved in the
county party. Both lawmakers were part of a move to use the local
organization to undermine the state party.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy with state party Chairman Mitch Ceasar, elected
officials who did not have the power to oust him began exploring
the idea of funneling contributions to the Palm Beach County party
office instead of the state office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to bleed the state party and just put it out of
business,'' says a Tallahassee Democrat who helped put together the
plan. ``Now with Ceasar out, we won't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Ceasar agreed to step down after getting a
face-saving job helping to organize next year's Democratic National
Convention. With him out of the way, Panama City car dealer Charlie
Whitehead, who led the party in the 1980s, agreed to become the new
state chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead says he was given assurances that the plan to make
Palm Beach County the de facto state party was no longer going to
happen. ``Their commitment to me was that the money would continue
to come to the state party,'' Whitehead says.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats should be excited about having someone like Friedkin
working with the party, says Whitehead. ``If he wants to help, I
sure want to use him. He has a lot of energy, and he doesn't mind
spending money.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that money and energy is going toward making sure that
every Republican officeholder in Palm Beach County has Democratic
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly there is no justification for having a
majority of Republicans on the county commission. It's illogical,''
he says. ``The majority of voters in the county are Democrats
(278,000 registered Democrats to 225,000 registered Republicans),
therefore why should we have Republicans control the commission?''
</P>
<P>
   Three- to five-year plan
</P>
<P>
   He talks about bringing more young people into the party and
increasing the size of the paid staff so volunteers can be better
organized. ``People who are just sitting around taking up space
have to go,'' Friedkin says. ``You have to get rid of people who
don't want to do anything, inspire people who do want to do
something to do more, and you have to bring in new people.''
</P>
<P>
   One challenge is getting newer younger Democrats working well
with older Democrats. ``It's not always easy but what we have to do
is to try and get the older generation, which is very good at what
it does, to train the younger generation,'' Friedkin says. ``At the
same time the older generation has to be willing to listen to new
ideas and new ways of doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to discourage Democrats from running against other
Democrats. In his view there are more than enough Republicans to go
after. And he warns that if any of the county's 21 Democratic Clubs
ever endorses or helps a Republican candidate ``it won't be a
Democratic Club for long, I'll throw them out.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time. When he assumed the chairmanship
last year, the first thing he did was kick 322 members off the
executive committee for missing three or more meetings during the
year. A few weeks later, facing an angry, booing roomful of
Democrats, Friedkin relented, admitting his blunt move ``wasn't as
sensitive as it should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Expecting party discipline, Friedkin has even discouraged the
clubs from inviting Palm Beach County Sheriff Bob Neuman to their
meetings because he is a Republican. ``One club invited me to a
meeting he was going to be at and I said if he is there, I will
embarrass him.'' Friedkin said. ``They didn't invite him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's part of his overall plan, which he says could take three to
five years, to not only build a powerful county party but to make
it one where, ``an endorsement from the Palm Beach County
Democratic Party means something.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wall covered with pictures of Friedkin and Bill,
Friedkin and Hillary, Friedkin and Bill and Hillary, he remains
loyal to Clinton, who he believes would be considered a great
president if only for that other thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people under stress get better. Some people under stress
get worse. I'm more interested in the big picture,'' Friedkin says.
``It's more important to me what's happening to this country,
what's happening to the economy, what's happening to the people.
That's why I'm doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
