<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMERY-DAYTONAIR08-COX     04-07 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMERY-DAYTONAIR08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emery Worldwide has vested interest in airport expansion
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton is unveiling a proposed billion-dollar,
long-range expansion of the Dayton International Airport to
increase its cargo handling capacity so Emery Worldwide could more
than double its local work force over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the plan would have Emery invest more than
more than $300 million and add 1,700 employees over the next five
years. Emery's investment would be coupled with a projected $200
million in federal, state and local spending to lengthen one
airport runway, reroute U.S. 40 and buy 1,100 acres of rural land
near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are completely behind this,'' said Tim Strauss, Emery vice
president for transportation and logistics. ``Without growth and no
changes, we are at a distinct disadvantage (in the industry).''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Tuesday how much Dayton might contribute. But
City Commissioner Mary Wiseman, said, ``Based on what I've heard, I
am confident that the city will work in partnership with Emery to
do whatever we can do in the short term to allow Emery to grow in
Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Lake, executive director of the Miami Valley Regional
Planning Commission, said, ``This is a major project both for the
communities involved and for the region as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials and Emery last week presented the 20-year plan
to local city managers and elected officials who make up the
MVRPC's transportation committee. Today, they will take it to
Dayton city commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, called the Air Cargo Capacity Enhancement Master Plan,
projects:
</P>
<P>
   Emery Worldwide would employ 10,260 in Dayton by 2018, up from
4,200 now.
</P>
<P>
   Overall airport expansion would be $1.2 billion for a fourth
runway, an extensive system of new roads around the airport and a
new Interstate 75 interchange by 2018.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 10 years, Emery would double the number of its
planes taking off and landing at the airport from 100 to 200,
including an increase in daytime flights.
</P>
<P>
   To come to reality, portions of the plan would have to be
approved by Dayton, then face scrutiny by federal aviation,
transportation and environmental agencies. The MVRPC would have to
add the roadway changes to the region's list of priorities for them
to be eligible for federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the first phase would begin after a series of
public meetings to be held this year. An environmental impact study
would be done over the next two years, with the buying of land for
phase one and rerouting of U.S. 40 beginning in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Emery has its North American sorting hub at Dayton
International, and its air traffic is growing so quickly that, by
2003, Emery planes would experience an average delay of 10 minutes
waiting to take off if the airport is unchanged, company
projections show.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is very vital to us, to reduce those waits,'' said Tim
Wendling, vice president of hub operations. ``If we have that sort
of queuing up on the ramps we are not meeting our outbound
schedules and our customers won't get their freight on time.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also projects an increase in the number of cargo
planes using the airport during the day in the next decade. The
long-range plan calls for a new runway to be built by 2018 to
accommodate the company's daytime flights.
</P>
<P>
   Wendling said the report's projected business growth is
conservative, and may happen even faster.
</P>
<P>
   Emery is the industry leader in air cargo for packages heavier
than 70 pounds, and is in its second year handling priority mail
for the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Wendling said the company has spent $65 million updating its
buildings and cannot invest more unless the airport's
infrastructure grows, too. The company foresees much of its
projected new business coming from international air cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Lake said Emery cannot bid on contracts to handle more U.S.
Postal Service mail unless it grows.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton officials said Emery's immediate need is for an
1,100-foot runway extension and the rerouting of U.S. 40.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's airport investments have not always panned out. While
investments for Emery have been fruitful, the city's passenger
terminal expansion has been largely underused since USAir closed
its Dayton hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were the city alone doing it, then I would be highly
uncomfortable,'' Wiseman said. ``If you look at the investment
Emery (would make), then that changes the dynamic. This is not the
city spending its dollars hoping that Emery will stay. It is the
city supplementing a huge dollar investment in Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   The project would be the second large expansion planned for a
local air freight company. Airborne Express in Wilmington expects
to add more than 40 flights a day over the next five years to the
107 flights it now handles.
</P>
<P>
   Residents north of the Dayton airport in Miami County and south
in Vandalia and Butler Twp. have voiced concerns over the noise
from increased air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten worse just in the last year and a half,'' said
George Burger, a Monroe Twp. resident.
</P>
<P>
   Burger said the airport plan includes so many long-range
projections he wants to know what projects are likely to go first
and what will take 20 years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   The master plan projects spending $40 million in next few years
for buying property, including sites affected by the increased
airport noise, according to a project summary.
</P>
<P>
   The airport would expand into largely rural areas to the north
and southwest. A 4,300-foot extension of the north-south runway,
called for in the second phase to be built after 2004, would run
into southern Miami County and force a rerouting of several Monroe
Twp. roads.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been growing, and added 975 jobs since 1997.
Many of the employees work part time, but the jobs come with
medical and dental benefits. The proposed new jobs are not
specified in the long-range plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the creation of a joint economic development
district, which allows cities and townships to agree beforehand to
share tax revenues from business developments.
</P>
<P>
   Miami County Commissioner Arthur Haddad, president of the
MVRPC's transportation committee, said his county endorses the
project because Emery employs Miami County residents and supports
other firms in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of our selling points (to attract businesses)
that we used when I was with the city of Troy,'' Haddad said.
``While (Emery) isn't a corporate citizen to Miami County it is
definitely an advantage to Miami County.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-range plan comes on the heel of a request for federal
airport funds to renovate runways and build a runway apron and
hangar for Emery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the cost is high, but the cost of not
making some of this investment would be even higher,'' said Dan
Curtis, vice president of the Miami Valley Economic Development
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
