r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCR-SYSTEM08-COX     04-07 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-SYSTEM08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR to debut customer-friendly system
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR Corp. is unveiling a new system that will
allow large companies to simulate the cozy familiarity of an
old-time neighborhood retailer by using huge computer databases.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Walters, NCR's director of Worldwide Marketing Customer
Interaction Solutions, said ``Interaction Plus'' will help
companies get and keep customers, who increasingly are less loyal
and more demanding.
</P>
<P>
   The system will let businesses collect customer data and then
turn around and tailor information to the customer the next time
that person does business with the company. For example,
information is collected when a customer goes on a company Web
site, calls the company's service center or uses a kiosk, such as
an automatic teller machine. The info is fed into a data warehouse
for analysis of customer behavior and sent to the Web site, call
center or kiosk the next time the customer does business.
</P>
<P>
   For a consumer, it might mean the ATM wishing you happy birthday
or asking you if you want your usual $50 withdrawal. Or a customer
will be greeted by a clerk on the other end of the phone who knows
his name, address and purchasing history.
</P>
<P>
   Walters said the market has evolved from the neighborhood
retailer who remembers each customer to mass marketing to
customized marketing on a massive scale.
</P>
<P>
   Walters said Interaction Plus is targeted toward
consumer-intensive industries such as retail, banking, utilities,
transportation and insurance. It will sell for about $1 million,
including the software, hardware and professional services, Walters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Walters said Interaction Plus capitalizes on NCR's two
strengths: point of sale interactions and data warehouses. NCR is
betting that customer management will be a big hit and it has
trademarked the slogan ``transforming transactions into
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in Dayton, NCR is a Fortune 500 company with $6.5 billion
in annual sales. It makes automatic teller machines, point-of-sale
scanners and registers and data warehousing systems.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
