<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOSHANNA-LINGERIE08-     04-07 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOSHANNA-LINGERIE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shoshanna's unmentionables
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I didn't ask the Jerry Seinfeld
question, so consider him _ and his four-year tryst with this gal
who was in high school when they met _ not mentioned. They split in
'97.
</P>
<P>
   So, if he's unmentionable, what else is there? Her
unmentionables. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Shoshanna Lonstein, 23, has launched a line of lingerie so
insanely popular that stores can't keep it in stock. There are
frocks, too, and soon-to-be sportswear separates, all for the
well-endowed woman.
</P>
<P>
   Lonstein, you may recall from those photo ops with
what's-his-name, is extremely top heavy. Thing is, she's thin as
Wassa Crispbread everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Hate her, hate her, hate her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had trouble finding clothes that fit,'' says
Lonstein, showing off her creations at C. Orrico in Palm Beach
recently. ``Clothes were only made for one body type, and it wasn't
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   She arrives in white jeans, a snug knit shirt and sandals,
looking like a college kid on spring break. Soon, though, she slips
into a strapless (strapless?!) royal blue stretch poplin dress, one
she designed.
</P>
<P>
   Supportive elements such as heavy-duty elastic, hidden laces and
metal boning (like in a corset) keep the top in place. In similar
fashion, Lonstein's bustiers also contain serious infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Her gingham thongs, meanwhile _ sold inside matching handbags
for $55 _ are more, shall we say, free form. Dresses range from
$125 to $160.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Shoshanna'' line, which debuted last fall, sold out in
three days at Bloomingdale's in Manhattan. Now, there are waiting
lists at some boutiques, and sales are expected to top $1million
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally overwhelmed,'' says Lonstein, who graduated from
UCLA in '97 (art history) and lives at home with mom and dad on
Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a 9-to-5 office job wasn't creative enough for me, and
I wasn't sure what I wanted to do. But my parents were, like, `OK,
it's time to go to work now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lonstein apprenticed at a lingerie company, then her dad, Zach,
a computer bigwig, loaned her the cash to get going. Critics, of
course, carp she'd be nowhere without yesteryear's 15 minutes of
fame.
</P>
<P>
   Although she won't discuss her ex (she stormed out of the room
recently when a 48 Hours chap uttered the S word), Kate White,
editor in chief at Cosmopolitan, has said the comedian fell for
what folks are seeing in Lonstein now: ``Her beauty and charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   I, however, have fallen for the idea of stuffing scanty panties
in a frilly purse and pulling down 55 bucks. Now THAT'S funny.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
