<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8812 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-JASPER-COX     04-07 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-JASPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After a disappointing freshman season, Jasper Sanks is out to
prove he belongs in the SEC.
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ To learn that you are not the person everybody
thinks you are is one of life's toughest lessons. Ask Georgia's
Jasper Sanks, who just now is beginning to find out who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks signed with Georgia out of Columbus' Carver High with much
fanfare. A USA Today and Parade Magazine All-American, people said
he was going to be the next Herschel Walker, the next Rodney
Hampton, the next Garrison Hearst. And Sanks believed them.
</P>
<P>
   But two things went wrong for Sanks: He failed to qualify for
admission to Georgia, and, after a year at Fork Union Military
Academy, he failed to maintain the physical conditioning he needed
to compete in the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   What resulted was one of Georgia's biggest recruiting busts. In
what was supposed to be an ``impact season,'' Sanks instead played
in two games and finished with 65 yards on 10 carries.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then. Now the Bulldogs are in the final week of
spring practice, and as they prepare for Saturday's G-Day Game,
Sanks is emerging as integral to their plans, going into his
sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   A year wiser and 19 pounds lighter, a new and improved Sanks
sees the 1999 football season as one of redemption. And not to
prove that he is what everybody thinks he is, but rather to prove
that he is who he is and that that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still be that caliber of player,'' Sanks said, referring
to the early comparisons to Walker and others, ``but right now,I'm
just being Jasper.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanks' new attitude is the result of the teachings of
running-backs coach Leon Perry. The former Oklahoma star running
back has a special relationship with Sanks and is fiercely
protective of 6-foot, 219-pound sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   His basic message to Sanks has been this: Forget what everybody
says about you and be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper Sanks is Jasper Sanks, not Robert Edwards, not Patrick
Pass, not Herschel Walker,'' Perry said. ``He's Jasper, son of Joe
and Jeanette Sanks, and that's all he needs to be. He may not be
living up to the expectations that the media and fans put on him,
but those are their expectations, not ours. We're pleased with what
he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's coaches weren't always so pleased. Sanks showed up in
Athens last summer grossly out of shape. He weighed 238 pounds,
nearly 30 pounds heavier than he was in high school, and the
closest thing to weightlifting he had done all summer was pick up
the TV remote control off the coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret not training like I should have coming out of Fork
Union,'' Sanks said. ``I took the summer off, took everything for
granted. I was just so happy I got my (SAT) scores. I had been so
far away from home in a military school, once I got back, I just
kind of relaxed. I just laid on my butt all summer, for about two
months straight.''
</P>
<P>
   So Sanks was already behind when he arrived with the rest of
Georgia's freshmen in August. Then, just a couple of weeks into
workouts, he suffered a severely sprained ankle. As the Bulldogs
hurriedly prepared for their season-opener, Sanks fell further and
further back in their plans. By the first game, he wasn't even on
the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, Sanks remained fresh in the minds of Georgia's
notoriously impatient fans. So when the Bulldogs' running game
began to struggle in mid-season, the shouts began to rain down from
the stands at Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Jasper! We want Jasper!'' fans called out. Sanks
cringes at the memory of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I kind of got caught up in that, thinking I should
be out there playing. But I can see now that I wasn't ready,''
Sanks said. ``It was kind of weird, people in the stands yelling
for the coaches to put me in and asking me questions on the
sideline during the game. I mean, it's been hard, one of the
hardest things for me to deal with since I got here.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks' first lesson was to stop listening, the second to start
working. With those instructions heeded, the Bulldogs are beginning
to see results.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's G-Day, Sanks is working both at fullback and
tailback, and he's getting a lot of snaps in the Bulldogs' one-back
set. He is competing for playing time with seniors Robert Arnaud
and Patrick Pass and juniors Nick Callaway and Brett Millican.
Three freshmen will join the competition in August.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks still isn't giving any signs that he might become the next
great running back in Georgia history, but indications are that he
will be a productive member of the 1999 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper Sanks is a good running back, but he's not Herschel
Walker,'' Perry said. ``All running backs are individuals. Jasper's
the biggest back we have, and he can do a lot of things for us. But
he's not out there trying to be Herschel Walker anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanks said, ``I think I learned a lot the last year. I wasn't
practicing and putting forth the effort that I should have. I was
just thinking my name alone was going to get me in and it was going
to be a cakewalk. College is a new ball game; it's a new level and
I didn't understand the work it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
