NYT-04-07-99 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COFFEE-TASTER08-COX     04-07 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COFFEE-TASTER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for the perfect cup of joe? Starbucks 'coffee
specialist' knows where to find it
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the realm of cool jobs for coffee
lovers, Eric Chastain's gig is definitely a double espresso topped
with a hearty dollop of froth.
</P>
<P>
   A ``coffee specialist'' who samples hundreds of cups of joe for
Starbucks each year, Chastain uses his tastebuds to choose which
batch of beans grown by farmers from Kenya to Guatemala should be
featured in the coffee chain's shops. The philosophy: If someone is
going to pay $3 for a cup of coffee, they're going to want their
money's worth in flavor.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent visit to West Palm Beach to promote a new line
of milder coffees and dark chocolates, Chastain explained what it
takes to slurp coffee for a living.
</P>
<P>
   At the Starbucks testing lab in Seattle, Chastain and other
specialists take turns cupping (tasting) samples. Just as judges at
a dog show look for standard shapes of each pooch, Starbucks'
tasters rely on an internal checklist called a ``flavor memory.''
Sumatran, for example, should be bold and intense with an earthy
aroma, while New Guinea Peaberry should be acidic and brisk and
slightly herbal.
</P>
<P>
   To save himself from a monster case of the jitters, Chastain
spits out each sample after smelling, slurping then swirling it in
his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain started in 1993 as counter help at the Starbucks near
his home in San Francisco, became a shift supervisor and answered
an internal job posting for a coffee specialist's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into it for the love of coffee,'' he said. ``It's an
unusual job in a small industry. But there's a lot of romance to
it. People tend to stay in the business. It gets into your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Q and A: So Eric Chastain knows his beans. But how much does he
really know about coffee culture?
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you were in a fancy restaurant and the waiter secretly
substituted Folger's crystals for your regular coffee, would you be
able to tell?
</P>
<P>
   A: That strikes me as amazing that people couldn't tell. Because
it's not just a Folger's thing. It's instant coffee. If you have
soluable coffee, it's pretty easy to tell if it's instant coffee
against any brewed coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the ``coffee achievers''?
</P>
<P>
   A: That was in the mid-'80s, right? Those commercials where
people said, ``I'm a coffee achiever!'' Wasn't David Bowie one of
those? Dionne Warwick was one. Ann and Nancy Wilson from the band
Heart were coffee achievers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   A: I have no idea what happened to them. I remember the comic
strip Bloom County had Opus the penguin talking about being a
coffee achiever. I cut that one out, it was so funny. But that was
before I was in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Juan Valdez, the Colombian guy who picks ``the richest coffee
in the world'' with help from his burro. What does his name
translate into in English? Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A: John Smith? John something . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q: Time's up. John Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Next question: What were the names of the man and the dog who
walked across country and were invited into strangers' houses to
drink coffee in those Maxwell House TV commercials?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Long pause) B.J. and the Bear?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Hal and Duke.
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh. I had no idea. B.J. and the Bear . . . wasn't that a TV
show with Greg Evigan?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Yes. And Bear was a chimpanzee, not a dog.
</P>
<P>
   A:Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Here's the Barbara Walters question: If you were a coffee
flavor, what kind of coffee flavor would you be?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would be Sulawesi. It's my favorite Indonesian coffee. It's
herbal, exotic, smooth, it's elegant and has a lot of character . .
. and may be slightly eccentric.
</P>
<P>
   Brew the best you can brew
</P>
<P>
   The basics for making a tasty cup of coffee are pretty simple.
Here are Starbucks' tips for brewing a perfect pot:
</P>
<P>
   Water _ Regardless of your brewing method, start with cold,
fresh (preferably filtered) water. Heat it to just shy of boiling,
around 190-205 degrees Fahrenheit, to best extract the coffee's
full range of flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Grind _ Use the correct grind for your coffee maker. The design
of the coffee maker determines how long the coffee grounds and
water will mingle in the brewing process. Cone-shaped filters
produce more flavor, for example, because water flows more evenly
through the coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Proportion _ The classic recipe for a great cup of coffee is 2
tablespoons of ground coffee for every 6 ounces of water. Adding
hot water to already-brewed coffee is the best way to adjust its
strength. A warning: Just because the lines on your coffee maker's
carafe reads ``12 cups'' doesn't mean you can fill 12 mugs of
coffee. Serving sizes vary.
</P>
<P>
   Freshness _ Start with fresh beans. Buy only what you can use in
a week's time. Store them in a dark, airtight container at room
temperature. Freezing coffee is OK on a short-term basis, but the
flavor can be damaged by freezing the same batch more than once.
</P>
<P>
   And, how hot should your batch be? Coffee's flavor deteriorates
when it's left on a heat source. Enjoy it fresh, within the first
30 minutes, or transfer it to a thermal carafe. Never reheat
coffee. And especially don't zap it in the microwave. ``That's
considered violence against coffee,'' said Eric Chastain, a
Starbucks coffee taster.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
