<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUST SETTLING ON MARINERS _ AND IT'S ONLY APRIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Outside the Kingdome Tuesday night, a vaguely valiant
effort was waged to make it seem like baseball matters.
</P>
<P>
   Gutsy vendors sold their peanuts, pizza, Cracker Jack and other
necessities. Nerds, Sour Patch Kids and Red Vines. One culinary
innovator was even hawking Mariner theme-dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until Major League Baseball Properties, or Alex Rodriguez's
bulldog agent, finds out about this. Along with these
quasi-appetizing pups, we can smell a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, an A-Rod Dog (all beef) was going for $3, a Buhner Dog
(Polish sausage) cost $3.50, and a Griffey Dog (top dog at a
half-pound of alleged all beef) was going for $4.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was you had to like your dog coated in dust.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, dust.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds of the stuff wafted through the chilly April air _ a
reminder that construction is under way in this neighborhood of
megabucks sports palaces.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome's south parking lot is gone. Springing up from the
rubble, cement pipes and dirt is the new exhibition center, which
explains the forklifts and bulldozers and half-ton trucks.
</P>
<P>
   It also explains why parking a car _ or worse, an SUV _ in
Pioneer Square has now become nearly as rare and prohibitive as
buying a house within city limits.
</P>
<P>
   Those precious swatches of asphalt are suddenly going for $20 a
pop, and office workers in Pioneer Square are actually being told
to vacate their monthly lots by 6 p.m. on game days since those
spaces have been sold out from under them.
</P>
<P>
   What will Bill Gates think of this, since some of his people are
actually being forced to go home in time for dinner?
</P>
<P>
   All said, conditions are not ripe for fan-friendly, feel-good
baseball. Indeed, this season the air is filled not with the sound
of hyper-excited fans filing down in samba-happy droves, a la 1995,
but of diesel engines, jackhammers, cement mixers and police
whistles making traffic snake and snarl.
</P>
<P>
   Also under construction is Mariner fan enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's in hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just doesn't feel like baseball weather,'' one diehard
Mariner fan said as he headed for the Kingdome Tuesday _ Day 2 of a
strange, new season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner organization is attempting to ward off more red ink
in anticipation of the sold out grand opening of Safeco Field. In
the meantime, what are we to make of these unpromising months left
at the Kingdome?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, if you looked around Tuesday night at the lack of
people, lack of hubbub, lack of energy.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday brought the smallest opening night crowd in 13
seasons, a mere 20,435 turned out Tuesday to watch the Mariners
lose again to the White Sox, 11-3.
</P>
<P>
   An occasional polite applause broke the silence, like a tennis
crowd, until Jamie Moyer started giving up homers and walks, and
then orneriness set in.
</P>
<P>
   More likely than hibernation though is that Mariner fans are in
suspended animation. They don't know what to think. The peripheral
fans are still numb from last season, and there doesn't seem much
reason to head back to the old ballgame now, not with the M's
sporting six rookie pitchers and the Kingdome offering its final,
mostly futile days of existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I hear them talking about most is whether they're
going to be able to sign Alex and Griffey,'' Rick ``The Peanut
Man'' Kaminski said Tuesday after surveying spring training and two
nights back on the beat at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're wondering whether or not, once the new ballpark is
open, will the team decide there still isn't enough revenue and
they'll have to get rid of players to get a payroll they can
afford.''
</P>
<P>
   It is strange that a city like Seattle, with the world's most
expensive new ballpark ready to roll and a fan base that proved in
1995 it could turn electric, does not know whether the owners of
its baseball team are prepared to hang tough with baseball expenses
or on the verge of panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think fans are taking a wait-and-see attitude,'' said
Mariner season ticket-holders David and Patty Arnold of
Woodinville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to see if the team can re-sign Alex and Junior, and
since costs are going up (at the new ballpark and in the free agent
market), I think the Mariners are trying to figure out what they
can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifelong fans like the Arnolds will show up these next three
months, no matter all the uncertainty. They didn't seem too peeved
that their ``secret little parking spot'' has gone from $10 to $15,
thanks to the squeeze on spaces.
</P>
<P>
   They said they really like new second baseman Carlos Guillen and
think the M's are worth watching, just as they believe the expense
and hassle of the new stadium are more than worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle is a huge metropolitan city. We're one of the premier
cities on the West Coast. If we had lost baseball again, like we
did with the Pilots, we would never get it back again,'' Patty
Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   So what if, until July 15, we are sitting here in limbo,
pretending baseball matters.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
