<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO HERE'S THE REAL Y2K PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I started in data processing in 1958. Y2K has
almost nothing to do with computer memory and everything to do with
storage media! If I keypunch a two-digit century on an 80-column
card, I have two fewer bytes to put ``real'' data in it. If I
include a two-digit century on a tape record (there were few disks
in the old days) that is written at 200 characters per inch, I can
waste a lot of tape! Please ask any of your fellow computerologists
who also spout this nonsense to correct this.
</P>
<P>
   _ All Huffy
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HUFFY: Ahhh, I see now. Programmers were either too lazy to
punch in another couple of bytes or too cheap to buy enough cards
and tape. And here everybody thought they were only incredibly
shortsighted. I'm sure this will give us all great comfort when
civilization falls completely apart in a few months and we're
living on roasted squirrel and shooting the neighbors because they
have the only operational can opener on the block.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have a problem with attempting to boot up my
system from the hard drive. The following message appears when the
attempt is made: ``DISK I/O ERROR Replace the disk and then press
any key.'' Using ScanDisk from the emergency bootup floppy yields
the following message: ``ScanDisk encountered a data error while
reading the FAT entry for cluster 789725. This error prevents
ScanDisk from fixing this drive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bootless
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BOOTLESS: You are, to use a highly technical term,
goobered. Something has messed up your file allocation table, the
table of contents for your hard drive. Your PC can't find its
start-up files anymore. ScanDisk can sometimes fix this problem,
using a redundant FAT on the hard drive, but it's not a dead-solid
certainty.
</P>
<P>
   See if you can find somebody with a copy of Norton Disk Doctor,
which sometimes has better luck. Don't get your hopes up, though. A
screwy FAT is almost always a sign from above that it's time to
reformat the hard drive and start from scratch. At least you can
still boot from a floppy so you can try to rescue whatever data you
can.
</P>
<P>
   To reformat, first make yourself a very stiff cocktail. I
suggest something with a lot of rum and fruit juice, since a
tequila hangover will be much more intense. Now boot from the
emergency floppy and get to a DOS prompt. Type in FORMAT C: /S and
press Enter. You should have time to mix another cocktail while the
drive is formatted.
</P>
<P>
   When that's complete, run ScanDisk or Disk Doctor, sit back,
take a large sip of your drink and try not to put your eye out with
that little umbrella. Make sure you do a surface scan, which can
identify potential trouble spots on the disk and lock them off. Now
you get to load Windows and all your programs again. Won't that be
fun? Hint: Rum is cheaper by the liter.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: What does the word ``Pentium'' mean?
</P>
<P>
   _ Hegelian Etymologist
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HEGEL: It means, ``I may be the best marketing weasel at
Intel, but I still can't build a campaign around a chip with a
stupid name like `80586.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay wanted to call the
80586 ``Layla'' but Intel couldn't get the rights to the song. He
can be reached at drbombay(at)Nstar-telegram.com or via snail-mail
at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101. Fax:
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-06-99 1704EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
