<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8854 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTERNET-COX &LR;      04-07 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Abilene Project produces next Internet generation 
By Ernest Holsendolph  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Internet, sometimes called the information
superhighway, could be compared to the swift Interstate highway
system, Internet 2 is like a space launch. Dedicated mostly to
education and research, it is superfast. No Sunday afternoon
drivers allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Abilene Project, this second Internet started much
like the first, mostly by a consortium of schools _ in this
instance a roster of some 37 universities, as diverse and widely
separated as Georgia Tech, the University of Washington, Harvard
and the South Dakota School of Mines.
</P>
<P>
   It is also assisted by the expertise and equipment of private
businesses like Qwest Communications, Cisco Systems, and Nortel
Networks.
</P>
<P>
   While the speed of e-mail and surfing on the Internet can be
impressive, this system, bolstered by banks of supercomputers, is
beyond compare with networks commonly in use. Gordon D. Wishon,
Tech information technology staff specialist, describes it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's Internet, even at its fastest, will not support
important research and education applications, such as remote
manipulation of scientific instruments and storage and transmission
of massive experimental data sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practical application of digital video, such as telesurgery,
will not be possible without the capabilities Internet 2 will
provide ... at speeds initially equivalent to 600 times as fast as
current (and relatively fast) T1-based networks.''
</P>
<P>
   T1 networks are commonly used now by business and other special
commercial operators for the high-speed transmission of data.
</P>
<P>
   Wishon and others add the new superfast networks will have
better quality, as well as speed.
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of the new network has been cooperation among
universities that often compete for talent and prestige, and
between the educational community and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   In this region specifically, an agreement back in 1997 between
Georgia and North Carolina laid some groundwork for the larger
system. The two states connected their two high-speed networks,
thereby establishing communication among universities in both
states.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year, universities in Georgia banded together to
produce something called the Southern Crossroads GigaPop, serving
institutions in this state as well as Florida and Alabama, filling
in the larger system now known as Internet 2.
</P>
<P>
   For the technical minded, the Abilene backbone spans more than
10,000 miles and operates at 2.4 gigabits per second _ that's
45,000 times faster than the familiar 56k bps modem employed in
many personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The system will be far-reaching by the end of this year,
possibly comprising a network connecting more than 70
</P>
<P>
   institutions of higher learning and research centers.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what the private partners have contributed: Qwest has
provided its special advanced fiber optic network and engineering
support. Cisco has contributed high-speed communications equipment
that facilitates the integration of data, voice and video, as well
as engineering support for 11 nodes or intersections of the system.
And Nortel has provided its expertise in networking, as well as
optical networking.
</P>
<P>
   The organization guiding the development of the Abilene Project
is the University Corporation for Advanced Internet
</P>
<P>
   Development (UCAID), headed by Douglas E. Van Houweling,
president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remarkable collaboration among the partners has provided
Internet 2 members with unsurpassed networking capabilities,'' he
said, and the benefit of this communication will pour forth through
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Where we are concerned here in Georgia, the Internet 2 network
is providing a communications equivalent of the air and ground
transportation network. And just as the transportation hub has
spurred economic growth in this century, the communications hub
could be pivotal in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
