<HEADLINE>
COMPANY MARKETS ELECTRICITY THROUGH INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WENDY TANAKA   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Internet has become a marketplace for
clothing, books, software and countless other consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   Now a California company is selling electrical service over the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Albany-based company, utility.com, is trying to carve a
niche for itself in California's $20 billion electricity market,
which was opened to competition a year ago so customers could have
a wider choice of energy providers.
</P>
<P>
   Customers don't actually receive electricity over their phone
lines. Rather, it markets, offers sign-up and billing through the
Internet, matching customers with power sources offering the lowest
rates. Those energy suppliers then transport electricity over power
grids, which are owned and operated by utilities such as the
Pacific Gas and Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   Chris King, chief executive of the company, said that on
average, his customers can save about 10 percent each month over
what they would pay to traditional electricity providers.
</P>
<P>
   King said utility.com offered better discounts than other energy
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, residential customers have been able to save only
about 1 percent on (electricity) bills after switching suppliers,''
he said, referring to data from the state Public Utilities
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Utility.com can offer lower rates for two reasons. First, King
said, the company doesn't have high administrative costs since its
services are automated on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a call center or have to process bills on
paper,'' King said. ``We use the Internet for all our customer
services, which includes signing up for the service and bill
payment.''
</P>
<P>
   Utility.com customers receive their bills by electronic mail.
They also choose the date they get billed.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, King said the company used special meters and
thermostats to track the exact time of day customers use power.
</P>
<P>
   This is important, he said, for creating precise bills since
electricity rates fluctuate during the day and are separated into
peak and off-peak prices.
</P>
<P>
   King said traditional utilities don't have these technologies,
so they estimate bill charges using an averaged rate.
</P>
<P>
   But the meters and thermostats that utility.com uses aren't free
to customers. The company charges $3.99 per month for them.
</P>
<P>
   Utility.com wouldn't disclose the number of customers it has,
but the company expects to have at least 50,000 by the end of the
year. The company also plans to start selling electricity to
customers in Pennsylvania, Massachusetts and Rhode Island this
summer. By next year, utility.com also hopes to be doing business
in Arizona, Nevada, New Jersey and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were skeptical about utility.com's chances because one
year after deregulation, few California customers have left the
traditional utilities.
</P>
<P>
   According to PUC data, only about 1 percent of the state's 10
million customers have switched to another energy provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deregulation is happening slowly in California,'' said Abhi
Chaki, an analyst at Jupiter Communications, a technology research
firm in New York. ``It's a combination of customer inertia and the
fact that electricity usage doesn't touch people in the same way
that, say, telephone service does.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaki said customers physically have to dial a phone, and this
makes them aware of the service. By contrast, he said, electric
service is less tangible.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Chaki said electric competition could ignite in
the future. ``Two years from now we might see more competition and
switching,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
