<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS INTERNET BECOMING A FORCE IN SEXUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ERIC DRUDIS   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An estimated 4.6 million daily Internet users
may end up having more sex with a mouse than a person, according to
a study published in a leading psychology journal.
</P>
<P>
   A whopping 4.6 million of the estimated 57 million people who
use the Internet daily could become hooked on cybersex, said Dr.
Alvin Cooper, the study's lead author and director of the San Jose
Marital and Sexuality Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, whose study is being published by the American
Psychological Association in the April issue of Professional
Psychology: Research and Practice, said the Internet has spawned a
sexual revolution with more than 9 million people visiting erotic
Web sites daily, sending suggestive e-mail or joining sexual chat
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen to 30 percent of the on-line population goes to sexual
Web sites, and sex is the most popular on-line search topic, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has evolved as a really powerful force in
sexuality because ... it offers affordability, accessibility and
anonymity,'' Cooper said Wednesday. ``It is not a good thing or a
bad thing. On-line sexuality is like a vehicle that can be driven
recklessly or enhance people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's study analyzed 9,177 of the 13,000 Internet users who
responded. According to Cooper, 86 percent of those responding to
the Internet survey were men. The survey was conducted over a
three-week period beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cybersex has gotten increasing attention and no research. It's
all hype and speculation and no facts,'' said Cooper, a training
coordinator at the Department of Counseling and Psychological
Services at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said 8.5 percent of the study's participants searched for
sexual material on line for more than 11 hours a week, generally
leading to serious problems in their lives. Most of these people
demonstrated signs of ``sexual compulsivity,'' or a very high
on-line sex drive, Cooper said. About 47 percent of his sample
spent less than 60 minutes a week on line for sexual activities.
They demonstrated no sexual difficulties in life, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   The study _ co-authored by Coralaie Scherer, Sylvain Boies and
Barry Gordon _ has come under fire because it collected all its
data on line from willing participants through the MSNBC Internet
site. No follow-up phone calls could be made by the researchers to
confirm the reliability of the respondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not a random sample,'' said David C. Heilbron,
a former statistics professor at the University of California at
San Francisco. ``I don't think it means anything about Internet
users of the population in general. It's just a group of people who
chose to respond to this particular inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper defended his research. ``You don't do a study about
on-line sex off line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this myth that people go on-line in an uncontrolled
way and cybersex takes over their lives,'' Cooper said. ``But those
who use the Internet as a recreational tool rather than in a sexual
way demonstrate no significant problems. It's like watching
`Baywatch' or looking at Victoria's Secret catalogs.''
</P>
<P>
   But psychologist Pauline Holmes of Christian Psychotherapy and
Family Counseling in San Francisco disagreed, calling cybersex
destructive to families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would look at it as a form of adultery even though it
doesn't necessarily involve physical contact,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people nowadays don't think oral sex is sex, so
looking at a computer definitely couldn't be sex, but the fact of
the matter is that cybersex is sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Because almost everyone has unfaithful thoughts, the real issue
becomes how serious cybersex becomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is looking at pornographic materials and sexual
literature,'' Holmes said. ``Getting involved with another person
on-line _ that's definitely another level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-01-99 1714EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
