<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYS TO WORK AROUND WINDOWS DESIGN FLAW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I recently had a close call. I installed an older program
that overwrote a crucial Windows 98 file in the windowssystem
folder. When I tried to start my computer the next time, Windows
locked up. When I called technical support for the maker of that
program, they knew what was wrong and told me I should reinstall
Windows _ or get the Windows 98 copy of the file that had been
replaced. Fortunately, I had another computer in the house with
Windows 98 and just copied the file. But is there any way I can
avoid this in the future?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the major flaws in the design of Windows is that it
does little to prevent older programs from placing outdated system
files on your hard drive. Usually this is not a major problem, but
occasionally users will run into the kind of problem you
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid the problem is to update to the latest versions
of your Windows software. Newer install routines often check the
dates of files being replaced, and you get a message that says
something like: ``This program is about to replace a file that's
older than the file currently on your system. Would you like to
keep your file?'' When you see this, always keep that file!
</P>
<P>
   If your system is functional when you've overwritten a system
file, Windows 98 provides a way to restore the file. The System
Information Tool (in the Accessories/System Tools folder) called
the System File Checker. It will make sure you have the proper
files. It also lets you extract a single file from the Windows 98
CD and put it back into the system folder.
</P>
<P>
   You might also find the file you need in the windowssysbkup,
which stores certain crucial components of Windows. Simply copy
what you need to the appropriate folder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Internet Explorer 5 is great, but there is one feature that I
really dislike. Whenever I type a Web address into the address
field, a drop-down box appears with suggested URLs. Is there a way
to turn this off?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure. Right-click on the Internet Explorer icon and choose
Properties, then click on the Advanced tab. Scroll down until you
see ``Use inline Auto-Complete for Web addresses,'' and uncheck
that box. Click OK.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been shopping for a new computer and have decided to
get a DVD drive in it, but I don't understand the pros and cons of
getting a drive with its own controller card, vs. one that controls
the drive with software. Can you talk about the trade-offs?
</P>
<P>
   A: A DVD drive requires either a hardware or software component
to decode what's found on a DVD disk into video. This is handled
one of two ways _ through a software program or an add-on card
that's inserted into a PCI slot.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the hardware configuration is going to be more robust
_ video quality will be somewhat better and playback smoother.
However, the card will occupy a free slot, which may be an issue if
you have lots of other devices added to your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Software decoding actually works fairly well, particularly in a
high-end computer. If you end up buying a PC with a processor
that's 400 megahertz or faster, software should be more than
adequate. However, if you plan on having a lot of other things
going on at the same you watch DVD video, you could experience some
jerkiness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Maybe Houston Chronicle
computing columnist Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-02-99 1236EST &QL;
