<SLUG> BC-CPT-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT LOOKING TO INVENT A BETTER MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little blue box, just big enough to hold a tub of margarine,
arrived in the mail the other day. What was inside was nearly as
intriguing as the lettering on the outside of the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``In technology, 30 isn't old. It's ancient.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're 30 years old (or older), it's a line that may make you
feel like you're old enough to be sucked from the bowels of the
earth and turned into the next barrel of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   The box opened on the opposite side of that slogan, and on the
bottom flap was printed another teaser: ``You don't use a computer
that was designed in 1968. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The year is a clue: What we're discussing here was originally
called the ``X-Y Position Indicator for a Display System'' when it
was shown publicly for the first time at the 1968 Fall Joint
Computer Conference in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It gained patent number 3,541,541 on Nov. 17, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   You know it better by its more descriptive handle: the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, on the inside flap of the box the teaser that began,
``You don't use a computer that was designed in 1968'' was
completed: ``So why use mouse technology that was?''
</P>
<P>
   The contents of the box was a single rubber-coated ball from the
aforementioned pointing technology.
</P>
<P>
   The box was from Microsoft, which, the inside flap said, ``has
thrown out the old parts used to create the mouse _ and will soon
introduce something better. Much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the mouse ball has been ripped out of some pointing
devices before _ although it's still the most common method used
for moving the cursor around the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Some mice use an optical-sensor system popularized by Logitech:
When the mouse is moved, a slotted wheel interrupts a light source
inside the mouse. Depending on how many times the light source is
interrupted determines how far the mouse moves.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1975, Microsoft will eventually move to the
30-and-older group that includes the dinosaur-like mouse it seeks
to redesign. Microsoft officials aren't saying much about the new
mouse, which will be introduced at Spring Comdex 99, a computer
show running April 19-22 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   With no ball underneath, it will either have to rely on an
optical or sonic system. And since Microsoft has shown a great deal
of innovation in pointing devices over the last two years, it may
even take a major leap forward and use some sort of laser that can
pinpoint its location precisely when used in conjunction with a
special computer mouse pad.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, Microsoft introduced IntelliMouse, a mouse
that had a small wheel on its back. With it, users could quickly
scroll through a document without moving the mouse. It's gotten
good reviews and it can actually speed up the computing process:
Studies show that it can increase productivity by about 25 percent
when used to review documents and perform other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft sells about 14 million mice a year and has a lion-size
share of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Comdex 99 may bring forth the mouse that roared.
</P>
<P>
   CHECKING OUT Y2K
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also has a free ``Tools for Y2K Assessment.'' A
company spokesman said the tools, available for download at the
Microsoft Web site (www.microsoft.com/year2000) scans a computer's
hard drive (as well as network drives) searching out Microsoft
products.
</P>
<P>
   It then generates a report with year 2000-compliance
information. If updating is required, the program supplies the
links to Web sites dealing with the products.
</P>
<P>
   It is now available in English and will be available in 14 other
languages by mid-spring. It will also be included in this month's
release of the Microsoft Year 2000 Resource CD.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is The Ledger's associate editor. He can be
reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His recent computer
columns are on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/business/tech/)
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-02-99 1804EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
