<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HEDDA-GABLER-HNS     04-07 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HEDDA-GABLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING IBSEN PLAY INTO FILM IS A FAMILY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, N.Y. _ History doesn't say whether Henrik Ibsen spent
time in rural New York, but if he did _ if he passed along its
hilly roads in winter, squinting at the sun-illumined ice _ it
might have reminded him of Norway.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? It might have inspired him. Holed up in a
clapboard house, bundled in wool and filled with the gloom of an
early dusk, he might have written ``Hedda Gabler.'' Few plays in
any language have so captured the suffocating horror of a false
life or the desperate lengths taken to escape it; few have trapped
their heroes in such wintry-cold, impenetrable cages. Ibsen knew
cages. Ibsen knew cold. And he certainly knew winter.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a touch of poetry in the ice around the eastern New
York community of Franklin, where a small clutch of cast and crew
were busy making a movie out of ``Hedda.''
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively called ``A Murder of Peacocks'' and set in the
1930s, the film was shot in a three-week blur back in January
taking over a Civil War-era, 20-odd-room Victorian manse owned by
Ken and Janice Stalter. Outside, a crowd of three dozen peacocks
minced about the yard, perching in trees and bristling imperiously
atop a tall barn roof.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the peacocks were dressed in velvet and lace.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, wearing a rust-colored gown and Constance Bennett
curls, was Hedda. The other, in lavender lace and a chocolate bob,
was Thea, a lovesick visitor and an unwitting target for Hedda's
abuse. The setting was an exquisitely appointed double parlor at
the front of the house; the scene was the passive-aggressive dance
that closes Act II.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand how poor I am, and fate has made you so
rich,'' said Hedda (Carmela Marner), and you could see the bile
forming in her belly.
</P>
<P>
   For those who haven't read the play since high school, it's like
this: Thea (Camilla Enders) is in love with a suffering writer
named Lovborg, who also happens to be an ex-flame of Hedda's. Hedda
is unhappily married to the decent, befuddled Tesman, who has just
carted off Lovborg to a debauch at Judge Brack's house. Thea is
worried about Lovborg; Hedda, penned in by her house, her loveless
marriage and her inability to move, decides to torture Thea. It's a
subtle, brutal scene in a subtle, brutal play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes across to me as an unbelievably modern play the way
it sort of strikes into an existential dilemma. It sounds pompous,
but I believe that,'' said David Bridel, the film's director (and
Marner's husband). The play, he said, ``goes to the heart of being
bored, the absolute terror of boredom and how it can drive you to
(insanity). It speaks of entrapment. ... Hedda is so bored and
looking so hard for something to entertain herself. And it all goes
terribly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridel, a 30-year-old Londoner with cornflower-blue eyes and a
gentle manner, was first approached to direct the play on stage for
the Franklin Stock Company's 1997 summer season. ``I knew the play,
and I hated it. I'd seen productions, and I'd hated them,'' he
said. ``But then I read it, and I got a little more fond of it, and
it became not an obsession, but I do love it very much now.''
</P>
<P>
   That initial stage production, which re-imagined Ibsen's play as
a bitterly funny battle between Davis-and-Crawford bombshells, drew
packed houses and sparked such positive responses that all involved
decided to take a crack at a film version. Bridel and most of the
cast returned, as did the Franklin Stock Company's artistic
directors, Carole Lucia Satrina and Eugene Marner as producers and
co-directors, with Marner tripling as cinematographer and Satrina
wearing an extra hat as script supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The pair are partners in filmmaking as well as marriage, having
shot numerous nonfiction works for the networks and PBS, among them
the Emmy-winning ``Creativity'' with Bill Moyers. They've lived in
Franklin off-and-on since 1971, so they're hardly Hollywood
outsiders. They're locals.
</P>
<P>
   And if ``Peacocks'' is starting to look like a family affair,
well, it is: Everyone knows everyone, and if they aren't related,
they're friends. Eugene and Carole are Carmela's parents. David is
their son-in-law. Carmela and Camilla have been chums since high
school, and Carmela has known David Conrad, who plays Lovborg,
since their days at Brown. Ray Bokhour, who plays Tesman, and Lolly
Susi, who plays the housekeeper, met Carmela and her husband at
London's Central School of Speech and Drama. Friends, all of them.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere on the set was easygoing, un-Hollywood, low on
stress and strutting. There was also a notable lack of ostentation,
not surprising for a $15,000 movie with a cast of seven and a crew
of not much more. Everyone in the film has a Screen Actors Guild
card, but no one's getting paid not until ``Peacocks'' does the
festival circuit and gets picked up (they hope) by a distributor.
So no Winnebagos. No bodyguards. No high-end caterers. Just bagels
and chips and help yourself to coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Costume changes? In the bathroom. Makeup? At the kitchen table.
Need to put your mug down? Shove aside that mound of base and
lipstick over there, by the tissues, next to the spools of thread.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the production it's like being at home,'' said the
play's Judge Brack, Charles Reiman, a carpenter-cum-actor who lives
in nearby Oneonta. ``It's like a home I didn't know existed. It's
like family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not at all a heavy production,'' said Satrina,
referring to both the set and the script itself. When told that
another producer had likened making a film to surviving a war, she
replied with a robust shake of the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not war,'' she said. ``This has been really lovely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
