<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM INDIANA WITH LOVE: SERVICE THE OLD-FASHIONED WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ours is a long and thriving business
relationship that involves no faxing, no e-mail, no Web sites, no
FedEx, not even a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four times a year, I pick up the telephone and dial a
number 2,000 miles away in Terre Haute, Ind. At the other end, Pat
Dowell (or his mom Lois or brother Mike) answers. We go through a
familiar ritual.
</P>
<P>
   I say I want to send flowers or a potted plant to one of my
parents for a birthday or other special occasion. I ask Pat what's
in bloom and looking pretty around his nursery. He runs through the
options.
</P>
<P>
   Hyacinths? Tulips? Daffodils? Maybe some ``awful nice yellow
roses'' that just came in that morning?
</P>
<P>
   I make a selection _ Pat knows my price range _ and tell him
what I want on the card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll drop 'em off at your folks' house on my way home,'' he
usually says.
</P>
<P>
   Pat lives about five blocks from my mother and father in the
same subdivision where I grew up. (I always liked riding my bike
down Pat's street because it was flat and I could let go of the
handlebars and coast.) Although it is no longer a community where
people leave their doors unlocked at night, it's still safe enough
to leave a plant or some flowers on someone's front door stoop.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of asking for my Visa number, Pat always double checks
my address so he can send me a bill in the mail. I send the bill
and a check back through the mail. The whole transaction takes
maybe 10 days or two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine. Handwritten bills, personal checks and snail mail? In
this era when everything absolutely, positively has to be somewhere
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother and I were just talking about that the other day,''
Pat said last week. (Daffodils for Mom's 69th birthday.) ``You
know, the gas company doesn't do business like this. You can't call
up and order some electricity or go get groceries at Kroger and
say, `Oh, just send me a bill.' It doesn't work that way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to think that, somewhere, John Jacob Schmidt and his
descendants are smiling at this situation. A German immigrant to
Indiana in the mid-1800s, he Anglicized his surname to establish
the J.J. Smith florist and nursery in Terre Haute in 1882.
</P>
<P>
   ``He already owned the biggest fruit and vegetable business in
Indiana,'' Pat Dowell said. ``The flower shop was started to give
his wife and daughters something to do. It was basically a toy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the toy _ and the Smiths' lovely white Victorian
house next door _ are all that survive of the once-wealthy clan.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``hardly any of 'em got married,'' a person must go out
to Highland Lawn cemetery to visit the Smith family. Pat Dowell's
dad Bill co-inherited the nursery from the last surviving Smith _
``Aunt Gussie'' _ in 1970. Lois bought out the partner in 1984 when
Bill died.
</P>
<P>
   The flower business _ like everything else _ has changed since
Pat helped out in the shop as a kid, but the Dowells can't imagine
doing anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in this place,'' Pat said. ``It's in our blood.''
</P>
<P>
   In most business transactions today, that probably doesn't mean
a whole lot to people. Certainly not compared to ``How much will it
cost?'' and ``How soon can you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   But when you live 2,000 miles from the people you love most in
life, it means a great deal _ especially when you want to reach
across the miles and put your arms around them.
</P>
<P>
   If you're really, really lucky, you find surrogate huggers like
the Dowells, folks with tulips and roses in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   Folks who still take the time to gather and arrange beauty and
know which front stoop to drop it off on when they head for home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
