<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8949 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-     04-07 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-BILL-BRADLEY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF DOLLAR BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 For release: Wed., April 7 or thereafter  
 By GERALDINE A. FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's no surprise when first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton delivers
a fantastic speech, as I heard her do recently in New York. Even
without the hype of a potential Senate run, she draws an
enthusiastic crowd. She's known as a dynamic speaker, and she never
fails to deliver.
 &HT;    But what are the odds that, only four days later, I'd hear at
least as good a speech from one of the most notoriously boring
public speakers in America, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley?
 &HT;    It was the largest gathering of alumni of Fordham Law School
since John F. Kennedy addressed the group _ far larger, I must
admit, than I've ever drawn when I spoke there, and I'm an alumna!
 &HT;    The audience that came out to hear the former senator was
predominantly male _ Fordham Law's entering class will be 48
percent women, but it's taken us time to get there. It was also
predominantly Catholic and Republican, predominantly successful
business people.
 &HT;    Not exactly the rousing, cheering type of crowd, in short,
especially for a candidate for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
 &HT;    And only one local cable station and one tabloid newspaper had
bothered to cover the event. I guess the others figured they
wouldn't miss much _ just another boring campaign speech from a
famously boring speaker.
 &HT;    Well, they were wrong.
 &HT;    Now, admittedly I hadn't heard Bradley deliver a speech for
several years, but it's quite a contrast. The man who as a
basketball player was nicknamed ``Dollar Bill'' for his
dependability and as a politician was nicknamed ``Duller Bill'' for
his flatness has finally figured out how to put himself over with
audiences.
 &HT;    For one thing, he isn't afraid to admit that he used to play
some ball. No so long ago an introduction like he received at
Fordham _ 10 minutes about his basketball career and the leadership
qualities he showed then (I didn't know he was captain of the
gold-medal Olympic team in 1960!) and one very short sentence
covering his 18 years in the Senate _ would have put Bradley on the
defensive.
 &HT;    This time he didn't squirm, though. Apparently no longer needing
to prove he isn't just a jock who got lucky and was elected to the
Senate, he went with the flow.
 &HT;    I could relate. When I was a young attorney, I worried that
people would dismiss me, not take me seriously, if I looked pretty.
I bristled when people commented on how I looked, rather than on
what I said.
 &HT;    But 20 years as a congresswoman, as an ambassador and as a
partner in a law firm gradually convinced me that people are paying
attention to what I am saying and doing, not what I'm wearing.
 &HT;    Over time, I've come to realize that my insecurity was a
frivolous concern. Getting older helped, too!
 &HT;    That may be what's happened with Bradley. He's mellowed and fits
comfortably in his skin. That was apparent in his response to his
introduction, but even more so in the speech that followed.
 &HT;    This was a whole new Bill Bradley. He appealed to the best in
his audience. He was funny and engaging, with a message that was
not only current and intelligent but also uplifting.
 &HT;    Most of all, he found the connection with his audience. He came
across as one of them, telling them that it's OK to want to make
money, it's even OK to complain occasionally about government laws.
But, while you're at it, think of those less fortunate. They need
your help.
 &HT;    Take it from someone who's made a few speeches in my time, it
was a heck of a speech.
 &HT;    But even more intriguing than Bradley's improved delivery was
the reaction of his audience. From my vantage point on the dais, it
was like watching a group of starstruck kids.
 &HT;    Maybe it's a male thing. Men really connect with Bradley. I've
seen it in my own family: When my husband and I were invited to a
party celebrating Bradley's new book, my husband immediately
accepted, bought the book and had it autographed to my son. At
Christmas he gave it to John Jr. _ just as John Jr. was handing him
the same gift.
 &HT;    At a dinner party recently, when the talk got around to
presidential politics, the men started waxing poetic about Bradley.
Just last Sunday, an old friend enthused, ``I'm a Republican, but
he's a candidate I would cross over to vote for.''
 &HT;    Well, the Fordham speech was more of the same, male bonding from
the minute the introduction started. Not only did they want to see
Bradley, though, they wanted to hear him. They listened attentively
to everything he had to say.
 &HT;    And then they gave him a standing ovation.
 &HT;    As a Democrat, I've always delighted in the Republicans'
problems with their gender gap. But, though we don't admit it too
often, Democrats have a gender gap, too. Women vote for our
candidates disproportionately, but men vote against them
disproportionately.
 &HT;    And maybe that's where Bill Bradley comes in. He can get men to
listen when he admonishes them, ``Whether you're a Republican or
Democrat, stay engaged.''
 &HT;    That is the key to a civil society. It's not a new message. But
it's a new and different messenger.
 &HT;    Keep listening.
 &HT;    (Geraldine A. Ferraro, a former congresswoman and the Democratic
nominee for vice president in 1984, is a Manhattan-based
attorney.) 
 c.1999 Geraldine A. Ferraro 
<TEXT>
