<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, April 7, 1999. If you have any questions, please call
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
INJUR (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Children's Mercy Hospital releases
Kansas City's first neighborhood-by-neighborhood study of childhood
injuries. Guns and automobiles were the leading causes of death.
The hospital hopes the study will be a first step toward grassroots
efforts to make neighborhoods safer for children. Graphics, a map,
and a photo of physician who led the study. By Alan Bavley. 35.
Will move in the ``a'' category.
GUNS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ In the final analysis, St. Louis County
put an end to the hopes of those who wanted to legalize concealed
weapons in Missouri. But the race was impossible to call for at
least part of Tuesday evening as the rural vote countered strong
anti-concealed weapons camps in Missouri's two largest metro areas.
We analyze the vote (91 counties passed Proposition B) and the spin
being put on Tuesday's painful blow to the NRA. By Kit Wagar. 25-30
inches. Will move in the ``a'' category
STAFF (Kansas City, Mo.) _ When Rod Anderson took over a Kansas
City restaurant company, his ratio of W2s to positions was 5 to 1.
That's a big annual turnover rate. Today the ratio is about 2 to 1,
which is good for the restaurant industry. Want to know his
employee retention secret? At Work column by Diane Stafford
(business desk). Will move in the ``a'' category
</P>
