<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BOCELLI08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bocelli offers too little variety
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too bad Andrea Bocelli has priced himself out of the Muzak
market, because that's exactly where his new CD, ``Sogno,''
belongs. In its 14 cuts, the tempos are unchanging, the harmonies
ever-sweet and the poetry full of meaning to the Teletubbies. It's
all pretty, all nice, all the same, and if you can tell one song
from the next, your ears are better than mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sogno'' is the fourth release by the blind Italian tenor, who
has a pleasant but unspectacular instrument, ideal for pop. (That's
not meant to be derogatory. His vibrato is too fast for opera, and
he doesn't have the chops to fill a hall without amplification.)
Here he's enlisted Celine Dion to join him for ``The Prayer'' from
``Quest for Camelot.'' Italian pop star Eros Ramazzotti comes on
for another song. The only guest that makes her visit memorable is
Dulce Pontes from Brazil, whose husky voice, unsugary part-singing
and idiomatic Portuguese add a welcome bit of spice, until Bocelli
overwhelms her with his patented shtick.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Carole Bayer Sager, who wrote the lyrics to ``The
Prayer,'' perhaps with the aid of refrigerator magnets, the only
recognizable name was that of film composer Ennio Morricone, who
wrote music for two of the indistinguishable songs. None of the
other credits belongs to the guys who wrote the stuff for ``Abba
Pater,'' the new CD by Pope John Paul II. This surprised me. The
music sounds like it all came out of the same can.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``Sogno'' (``Dream'')
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Bocelli. Polydor.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
