<HEADER>
A9022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS08-COX     04-07 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally''
</P>
<P>
   Blackstreet. Lil' Man/Interscope.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The news between Blackstreet's last million-selling album and
its latest was that co-founder Teddy Riley was _ once again _
looking for new members. ``Finally'' reveals that not only did
Riley enlist two capable replacements for the R&AMP;B quartet, but he
lifted obvious hunks of other people's records as well. Lazily
incorporated hunks. ``Can You Feel Me'' is the Jacksons' blaring
``Can You Feel It'' with new verses. And DJs can easily mix
Blackstreet's team-up with Janet Jackson, ``Girlfriend/Boyfriend,''
into Cam'ron's ``Horse &AMP; Carriage'' as the tunes share the same
stop-start rhythm. The less-mechanical, involving ballad ``Drama''
is one of too few examples here that Riley, the creator of new jack
swing, can still come up with something imaginative.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   ``Beaucoup Fish''
</P>
<P>
   Underworld. JBO/V2. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Though it lacks the visceral punch of 1996's ``Second Toughest
in the Infants,'' ``Beaucoup Fish'' sounds like the work of a more
introspective and seasoned band. Underworld can still make a
floor-shaking racket, with elastic bass lines, floating keyboard
figures and the often electronically altered voice of Karl Hyde
drifting over clattering percussion tracks. There are moments of
quiet here, too, such as the gentle ``Skym.'' ``Push Upstairs'' and
``King of Snake,'' a twisted take on the repetitive riff of Donna
Summer/Giorgio Moroder's ``I Feel Love,'' come closest to
recapturing the blissed-out groove of the last album's ``Born
Slippy.'' That track's high profile spot in the opening sequence of
``Trainspotting'' sent the group's stock soaring in 1997,
especially in its native Britain. The number of artists purveying
thoughtful dance music has multiplied in the wake of that success,
but few of them do it with the panache of Underworld.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray and Shane Harrison write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
