<HEADER>
A9024 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-BELOVED08-COX     04-07 0155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-BELOVED08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Mystery and beauty have part in adaptation of `Beloved'
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   An A-list epic that inadvertently suggests that Toni Morrison's
novels are unfilmable.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey plays Sethe, a former slave haunted by the ghost
of her dead daughter, who takes in the mysterious stranger Beloved
(Thandie Newton). The ghoulish, babylike newcomer disrupts a
household that includes Danny Glover as Sethe's lover and Kimberly
Elise as her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Basically an art-house horror flick whose mysteries are too easy
to guess, the movie (directed by Jonathan Demme) has moments of
intense beauty. But it winds up being too faithful to Morrison's
magic-realist prose; it substitutes mood for emotional power and
narrative clarity. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Consitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
