</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini video reviews
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American History X'' (R) _ As a young white supremacist
trying to keep his kid brother (Edward Furlong) from being eaten
alive by the racist dogma he once espoused, Edward Norton is
terrific. But the rest of the black-and-white movie preaches to the
converted. Like an ``Afterschool Special'' with skin and swear
words, it's a hopelessly square treatment of a volatile topic.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries'' (R) _ Family matters and
more are examined in this thoughtful adaptation of Kaylie Jones'
semi-autobiographical book about growing up in the '60s and '70s
(her father was writer James Jones). The vignette-ish approach may
bother some _ the movie is like a personal memoir divided into
three short stories _ but the film's sense of memory as an
emotional tapestry rings true. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer'' (R) _ Tepid
follow-up to last year's surprise hit, this teen slasher flick
transplants surviving cast member Jennifer Love Hewitt to an island
in the Bahamas. Back-from-the-dead killer Ben Willis is there too,
intent on using his deadly fishhook hand to finish off Julie and
her friends. Teenage singer and TV star Brandy is the only spirited
thing about this sequel. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska, Eleanor Ringel Gillespie and Steve Murray write
for the Atlanta Journal-Cosntitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
