<HEADER>
A9027 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RINGEL08-COX     04-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expect surprises from maverick Robert Altman
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You may not like every Robert Altman movie you see, but it's
unlikely that you'll forget one. A bona fide Hollywood maverick who
has managed to stay in the game _ or, perhaps more accurately, just
outside the game _ for 40 years, Altman continues to surprise us.
His newest film, ``Cookie's Fortune,'' opens Friday. A
magnolia-scented Deep South whimsy, ``Cookie's'' is just another
reminder that with Altman, best expect the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of an Essential Altman is probably an oxymoron, but
here are some other titles you might want to check out on video:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``MASH'' (1970).
</P>
<P>
   The movie that put Altman _ and, by extension, Alan Alda _ on
the map. Set in a Mobile Army Surgical Hospital during the Korean
War, the movie is full of parallels to Vietnam and takes its
nose-thumbing tone from the anti-war fever that swept campuses in
the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Sutherland and Elliott Gould play the original Korean
cutups with an appealingly anachronistic countercultural panache. A
prize winner with critics' groups and at Cannes (not to mention
five Oscar nominations), ``MASH'' was the right movie at the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected face: Yep, that's Robert Duvall as our anti-heroes'
nemesis, Maj. Frank Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Behind-the-scenes weirdness: The producers originally wanted
Jack Lemmon and Walter Matthau for the leads. They were dissuaded
by the argument that the football finale called for younger stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``McCabe and Mrs. Miller'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty is McCabe, a pretty good gambler, a pretty
transparent braggart and a pretty bad entrepreneur. Julie Christie
is Mrs. Miller, a no-nonsense madam who drives hard bargains and
finds refuge in an opium pipe. They come together in Altman's
radiant dream of the American West, a place bathed in gold and
white and a mournful Leonard Cohen soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got poetry in me,'' insists Beatty's McCabe. So does this
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected face: Rene Auberjonois of ``Star Trek: Deep Space
Nine'' plays the sneaky barkeep who goes into business with McCabe.
</P>
<P>
   Behind-the-scenes weirdness: Gould was originally considered for
McCabe, but Beatty's name was the only way to guarantee financing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nashville'' (1975).
</P>
<P>
   Arguably Altman's best-known film. A kind of deadpan social
study of the country music scene, the movie is actually a
scathingly hilarious and oddly poignant report on the state of the
nation circa the mid-1970s. All the trademark Altman-isms are
firmly in place: the revealing vignettes instead of a strictly
structured plot; the half-heard overlapping dialogue; the large
cast of eccentric characters bumping into one another in unexpected
ways, etc. Among the faces in the crowd: Lily Tomlin, Henry Gibson,
Keith Carradine, Geraldine Chaplin, Karen Black, Ned Beatty and
Scott Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected face: The ubiquitous and somewhat mysterious
motorcycle rider is Jeff Goldblum, who would later battle dinosaurs
in ``Jurassic Park'' and help save the world in ``Independence
Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind-the-scenes weirdness: Former President Nixon once wrote
Altman a note saying that ``Nashville'' was his daughter Tricia's
favorite movie and could he please have a copy for her.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Player'' (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Altman has Hollywood for lunch _ with a nice Chianti _ in this
devilishly wicked comedy about the brown-nosing and back-stabbing
that pass for business as usual in the movie biz. Studded with more
than 60 celebrity cameos _ everyone from Burt Reynolds to Bruce
Willis _ the film centers on an ambitious studio executive (Tim
Robbins) whose problems include an equally ambitious rival (Peter
Gallagher) and a series of threatening postcards from a disgruntled
writer. Behind the glittery dish is a dark vision of an America
disastrously hooked on the superficial.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpected face: Buck Henry, co-writer of ``The Graduate,'' is
briefly glimpsed pitching ``The Graduate 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind-the-scenes weirdness: The original choice for Robbins'
role was Chevy Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
