<HEADER>
A9036 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-REVIEW-COMEDY-HNS &LR;      04-07 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-COMEDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRANGERS WITH CANDY': SWEET SORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Comedy may not be pretty but the one thing it
absolutely must be is funny. If it's not, you might as well be
watching ``The NewsHour'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central is under a unique kind of pressure in that the
channel has to be funny. The cable channel succeeded tremendously
with ``South Park'' and several other wonderful and supremely
twisted shows. See, that's the thing about comedy. Being twisted,
being swathed in a blanket of irony, being so hip as to be nearly
unfunny is what passes for brilliant comedy these days.
</P>
<P>
   Bearing this burden, Comedy Central offers us ``Strangers with
Candy,'' the channel's latest effort in translating weird into
funny. Unfortunately, it doesn't translate very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers with Candy'' is about a 46-year-old woman named
Jerri Blank (``Second City'' alum Amy Sedaris), who comes back home
after 32 years as a runaway ``user, boozer and loser'' and
re-enrolls in high school as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty original for starters and offers up a great deal
of hope, but was squashed like a grape in the pilot and barely
allowed to surface in the second episode, if anyone isn't too bored
to come back after squandering the first 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps part of what's so defeating about watching ``Strangers
with Candy'' is realizing the wasted potential. A 46-year-old
hardened woman goes back to high school? Sign us up for 13
episodes. But the writing isn't there. Sedaris' portrayal is
spot-on and often times mesmerizing to look at _ her Tammy Faye
Bakker make-up and faux-Muppet overbite getting visual laughs many
times on their own.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 minutes of staring at her, you need writing. And
``Strangers with Candy'' simply plays as one extended ``Saturday
Night Live'' spoof on that most easy of TV targets, the
after-school special.
</P>
<P>
   Each episode ends with some kind of skewed lesson _ like ``South
Park'' _ and then moves the next week into new territory. The
pilot, about drug abuse and acceptance, defies you to laugh its
broadness, it's spoofiness, its coolness for pricking the
clueless-parent approach of all those retro TV specials.
</P>
<P>
   But it's just not funny. It's loud and brash and stupid and _
like a lot of ``SNL'' skits _ painfully long, and it implodes upon
itself.
</P>
<P>
   What this show looks most like is a brilliant kids show on
Nickelodeon, the late, lamented ``Adventures of Pete and Pete.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, ``Strangers with Candy'' was a good idea on paper but
never graduates to something better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
