 ART ADV.: Photos with RELIGION-COLUMN, REFUGEE-DOCTOR and
ISRAEL-HIGHTECH are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEE-DOCTOR (Blace, Macedonia) _ American doctor Tom Durant
flashes his Harvard ID to bluster his way past checkpoint guards.
Comforting refugee patients, he is doing a job he has done before.
By Kevin Cullen. 1300 words. PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-FOCUS (Aviano Air Base, Italy) _ The Yugoslavia strikes
have taken NATO into unexplored military and political terrain,
leaving it in a struggle to find its way in the post-Cold War
world. By Charles M. Sennott. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-ALBRIGHT (Undated) _ Hounded by the two biggest
oppressors of the century, Nazism and Communism, Madeleine
Albright's family turned twice to Yugoslavia for help. Now she's a
leader in one of the nations bombing the Balkan nation. By David
Beard. 930 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COURTROOM-CAMERAS (Boston) _ A proposal in Congress would allow
cameras in federal courtrooms, if the individual judge okays it, in
effect overruling a blanket ban in effect for years. By William A.
Doherty. 1180 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- As bleak as the prospect appears,
NATO's aim of returning the bulk of the Kosovar refugees to the
land of their birth is still the goal. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) -- On Opening Day, rich and poor
teams are even. By Martin F. Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Are fishermen trying to move too fast
on Georges Bank? By Derrick Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) -- Six years after Rev. Walter H.
Everett was outraged by the lenient sentence given his son's
murderer, he performed the convicted killer's wedding ceremony. By
Diego Ribadeneira. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GENDER-TRAINING (Undated) _ Under the careful guidance of two
behavioral scientists, teachers are trying to bridge a cultural
gender gap that becomes dangerously wide by adolescence, giving
rise to sexual harassment and assault in schools. By Allison Bass.
1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   BEAM-COLUMN (Undated) -- Transferring a portion of my pitiful
income to the federal treasury isn't such an onerous task, ever
since Bill Clinton transformed the United States of America into
the Republic of Me. By Alex Beam.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLAROID-MARKETING (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Polaroid has been stuck
in the dumps, with essentially no sales growth in more than six
years. By Ronald Rosenberg. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HIGHTECH (Boston) _ Dozens of high-tech firms have an
Israeli connection. Some serve as beachheads for Israeli companies
moving into the US market; others are American-based companies
founded on Israeli technical know-how. By Hiawatha Bray. 1340
words. (f and i coding) PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS-QUARTER (Undated) _ Funds invested in technology and
blue-chip stocks finish the first quarter with strong returns. By
Lynnley Browning. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Gillette stock drops 12 percent,
ruining CEO Alfred Zeien's plans to retire on a high note. By
Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS (Kansas City) _ No one would dispute that
Darren Lewis, picked up on the cheap a year ago, has made the Red
Sox a much better team. By Gordon Edes. 1050 words.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ If the choice is between capitalism or
nationalism, Predrag Mijatovic will place his country first. By
Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS (Augusta, Ga.) _ Greg Norman is content with his
life, despite having to undergo shoulder surgery a year ago. By Joe
Concannon. 700 words.
