<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, April 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) _ Air strikes are stepped up in
Yugoslavia and NATO claims to have hit some Serb tanks. By Eric
Schmitt and Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Albania) _ Yugoslavia closes
the main border crossing with Albania, and the thousands of
refugees who were backed up at the border are gone, apparently
moved back into Kosovo. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ The biggest Macedonia refugee camp
is now empty, as Macedonian guards clear everyone out. The Border
is clear too; but it is unclear if more refugees were driven back
to Kosovo by Serb authorities, as happened to some Kosovars on
Monday. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ NATO's top commander, Gen. Wesley
K. Clark, wants more equipment for the Yugoslav campaign; NATO
modifies its tactics for greater success against Serb targets. By
Michael R. Gordon and Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWS (Belgrade) _ The acting president of Cyprus says
that he's flying to Belgrade today and that Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president, may hand over the three captured U.S. soldiers.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Brussels) _ Diplomatic developments. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ American political parties are
divided on Kosovo, fracturing the post-Vietnam certainties about
where each party stood on military issues. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLL (Undated) _ Results of the latest N.Y. Times poll on
the crisis in Kosovo and U.S. policy options. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering, among others, stories on the economic
impact in Europe of the bombing of Danube bridges, the scene in
Turkey as refugrees arrive from Macedonia and a site in the Kosovar
capital, Pristina, where civilians are reported killed by NATO
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton makes speech on
China policy, other developments on the visit of the Chinese prime
minister. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHU (Washington) _ Zhu Rongji, the Chinese prime minister,
shows himself to be quite a card, winning friends and influencing
people with his amusing anecdotes. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-BURIAL (Kibeho) _ On the fifth anniversary of start of
the massacres, Rwanda reburies remains of 20,000 people killed in
one town. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Political developments in Russia. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SC-LOTTERY (Atlanta) _ The South Carolina House is expected to
complete legislative action on a lottery measure, becoming the
first of four long-term hold-out Southern states to adopt one. By
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-TEST-TAMPERING (Austin) _ The Austin school district and a
deputy superintendent were indicted Tuesday on charges of tampering
with statewide tests to make their students appear smarter. By
Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   MO-GUNS (Jefferson City, Mo.) _ Missouri's residents have
decided to keep the state's outlaw-era ban on carrying concealed
weapons, despite a $3.7 million campaign by the National Rifle
Association. By Andrew Bluth.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-KIDS (Undated) _ The first national survey of drug use by
children in the 4th and 6th grades shows that use shoots up as kids
enter middle school, but that levels are not high and are not
rising. The most commonly used drugs by far: beer and cigarettes.
By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIRTH-DEFECTS (Undated) _ A study from Norway being
published today in the New England Journal of Medicine is the first
to provide information about women with birth defects: they are
less likely than others to have children, and those who do give
birth have an increased risk of having a child with the same birth
defect as the mother. However, most give birth to healthy children,
and their children are not at increased risk for any type of defect
except the mother's. The study, based on birth certificates in
Norway, is the first to provide this kind of data, and researchers
say it could not have been done in the U.S. because of the way
records are kept here. By Denise Grady. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The column: Chinese entry into the
World Trade Organization would not have a huge economic impact but
would address specific goals of both China and the United States.
By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   REVLON (Undated) _ Confirming recent speculation, Revlon says it
is considering the sale of one or more of its businesses. Its
shares rise as much as 16 percent. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The European Central Bank
and the Bank of England are expected to lower interest rates on
Thursday. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (Undated) _ More about the online music joint
venture between Universal and BMG. Seagram stock is up as much as
7.7 percent. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Yahoo posts earnings. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   GM-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors' sales unexpectedly fell in
March, declining 2 percent. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 30
points, or 0.3 percent, and the Nasdaq index was off 17 points, or
0.7 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose half a percent in Tokyo and 4.9
percent in Hong Kong, which was open for the first time since last
Thursday. Shares rose 0.2 percent in Frankfurt, 1.2 percent in
London, half a percent in Brazil and 0.2 percent in Mexico. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 7/32 point. By Robert D.
Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   TIMES-APPOINT (New York) _ Thomas E. Helling is promoted to vice
president for advertising sales at the New York Times. By Leslie
Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
