<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ALBRIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA LOOMED LARGE IN ALBRIGHT'S YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hounded by the two biggest oppressors of the century, Nazism and
Communism, Madeleine K. Albright's family turned twice to the
Balkans for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my country was occupied by the Germans,'' her father once
wrote, ``my first thought of safety went to Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavs gave Albright's father, Josef Korbel, letters saying
they had worked for him in Belgrade _ and smuggled the Jewish
family away from the Nazis and the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Yugoslavia again provided a refuge for
Korbel and his family from the political struggle in their native
Czechoslovakia, where totalitarianism triumphed again with a
Communist takeover in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Madeleine, the little girl who spent her infancy in
Belgrade and several childhood years there later _ swimming in the
Sava River, taking walks through Kalemegdan Park with her governess
_ is the US secretary of state _ and the driving force behind the
US bombing of the Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
   Her family's experience with oppression in Europe, biographers
say, has forged her determination to roll back the persecution of
ethnic Albanians by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, she has lambasted Milosevic for human rights
abuses in the splintered Balkan nation, prompting him in one 1997
face-to-face exchange in Belgrade to challenge her knowledge of his
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madame Secretary, you are not well informed,'' Milosevic told
her in an exchange recounted in Ann Blackman's 1998 biography,
``Seasons Of Her Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright shot back: ``Don't tell me I'm not uninformed _ I lived
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Albright's years in the country _ and its role in saving her
family _ have irritated people who now must live under the
bombardment she has forcefully advocated, said Michael Dobbs, whose
biography ``Madeleine Albright: A Twentieth-Century Odyssey'' is
being released later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs dislike her intensely now, and one of the things
they raise is they helped out her family when it was in trouble,''
Dobbs said from Budapest, on his way back into Yugoslavia to report
for the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel it is a lack of gratitude,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She was brought to Belgrade shortly after her birth in 1937. Her
father worked as the press attache for the Czechoslovak Embassy. He
was fired because of his Jewish origins after Nazis surged to
control following the 1938 Munich accord, in which the Western
powers acquiesced to Hitler's demand for one-third of
Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   After being spirited to safety, unlike many relatives who were
killed in Nazi death camps, Albright returned to Belgrade after her
father's appointment in late 1945 as the new Czechoslovak
ambassador to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   To her father, it meant safety from the increasing divisions in
his homeland between the social democrats and the communists. It
meant a high-profile life hosting parties for the nation's
leadership, including one gala attended by socialist Josip Broz
Tito, the man who unified Yugoslavia for decades through his iron
rule.
</P>
<P>
   For 8-year-old Madeleine, who donned native Czechoslovak dress
for several embassy events, the years represented a style of luxury
she would not see for decades as an emigre, first to Britain and
then to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very heady time for her, but also a very lonely
time,'' said Blackman. ``She had a governness and servants, but few
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Her strict father maintained a steady tutoring schedule and
shipped Madeleine off to private school in Switzerland when she was
10. On her return in 1997, she said the only room she could recall
in her former embassy mansion was the bathroom, where she had often
been banished for misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, as political divisions inside Czechoslovakia deepened,
Josef Korbel came to understand that he could never return to his
homeland under communist rule. Facing a recall home after the
Communist takeover, he accepted a position with the UN committee
seeking to enforce a cease-fire in the Kashmir region of India and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Settling in the United States, Korbel wrote histories of
Czechoslovakia and of Tito's Yugoslavia, where he said he first
witnessed the suffocating nature of communism.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Korbel, an academic at the University of Denver,
initially supported the war in Vietnam by arguing the domino theory
_ that tyranny and communism would spread if allowed to bloom in
the Southeast Asian land. In recent weeks, according to Pentagon
officials, Albright has used a similar metaphor in demanding the US
military's help in ending the Serb oppression in Yugoslavia's
Kosovo region.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Albright, as US ambassador to the United
Nations, had similar battles with a reluctant Pentagon, urging
intervention in Bosnia. Eventually her view won out, and the US
military played a limited role in overseeing an end to the mass
killings in that Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
   ``She absorbed a lot from her parents,'' Dobbs said. ``In
Munich, this idea of giving in to dictators, that you should draw
the line before it was too late, that this should happen never
again _ all this comes to mind with the style she has used, first
as UN ambassador and now as secretary of state. Her rhetoric has
become the administration's rhetoric.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
