<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN DOCTOR ON THE NIGHT SHIFT IN MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Eds.: Language in 26th graf may be offensive to some readers.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Not surprisingly, Dr. Tom Durant volunteered
for the midnight shift.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his 70 years, Durant has been inserting himself into
the worst the world has to offer. So it was almost inevitable that
as dawn broke over this wretched corner of earth Tuesday, Tom
Durant was attending to one of the 50,000 refugees from Kosovo
stranded in a huge, muddy field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good night,'' said Durant, assistant director at
Massachusetts General Hospital and a longtime volunteer for the
American Refugees Committee. ``Nothing dramatic. A lot of
dehydration, hysteria, we had IVs going. Vomiting, diarrhea, some
serious leg and foot infections, a heart attack. But nobody died on
us, thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 65,000 people have been cooped up in this squalid
pen, surrounded by armed guards, for up to a week while the
Macedonian government refused to allow them into cleaner, more
orderly camps. Now, says Durant, buses are taking some of the
refugees the government is allowing out to the new camps.
</P>
<P>
   The field that people have taken to calling No Man's Land
presents what Durant and other doctors here describe as a
humanitarian disaster waiting to happen. Doctors say that unless
the bulk of refugees are moved from the field in the next day or
two, disease is likely to begin killing them in droves.
</P>
<P>
   As bad as it is, Durant said he was encouraged by what he saw
overnight. But, as he observed while commiserating with a
colleague, Dr. Sheri Fink from the Boston-based Physicians for
Human Rights, ``there are tens of thousands of refugees still in
Kosovo, waiting to cross the border. Once we move this crowd out,
we've got another one right in back of them.''
</P>
<P>
   As Durant put it, ``the longer they stay, it's a potentially
explosive situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fink, 30, a recent medical school graduate who is attending
refugees for the first time, said she admires Durant, who is
well-known in the small circle of physicians who volunteer their
services whenever there is an international human itarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been everywhere,'' she said. ``I want to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Durant's volunteer resume reads like a chronology of all
that is wrong with the world _ Vietnam, Cambodia, Afghanistan,
Iraq, Sudan, Somalia, Rwanda, Bosnia, Honduras, and now here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bad, but Goma was the worst thing I ever saw,'' he
said of the Rwandan refugee camp. ``We had 50,000 dead in two weeks
from cholera. Here, it's dysentery and measles we have to watch out
for. The measles in Cambodia in 1980 were unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Durant made his rounds dressed in blue jeans, a windbreaker,
and, for here at least, a distinctive Red Sox cap. Spying a visitor
from Boston as he tended to an old woman, he asked hopefully,
``How'd the Sox make out on opening day?'' But, turning back to his
patient, he answered his own question mournfully, ``No one here
knows, or cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Durant comforted a pregnant woman who shivered with fear, not
cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's petrified,'' he explained, offering her a hand on her
shoulder and soothing words in the little Albanian he knows. ``She
got separated from her husband, which is common here. This is her
first baby, and the poor girl is simply terrified.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters and analysts try to put the recurring tragedy of the
Balkans into some unique perspective. But where he sat, on a muddy
chair in a fetid tent with hypodermic needles strewn about, Tom
Durant saw only the human condition, unique to no one and nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is like every other I've seen over the years,''
he said, pouring gasoline into a generator that kept the tent
lights on all night. ``It's a case of the three Bs, and I don't
mean Bach, Beethoven, and Brahms.''
</P>
<P>
   Durant's three B's are bureaucracy, banditry, and baksheesh, or
corruption. The bureaucracy has seen Macedonians refuse to process
the refugees in large numbers, leaving them to stew in their own
squalor. The baksheesh has forced refugees to pay police for the
right to flee their homes. And the banditry has seen refugees
robbed of their possessions, their identity papers, and, in the
end, their dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow me,'' Durant said, wiping his hands, leading the way to
a place he calls the Tent of the Damned.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled back the flap to reveal two dozen people, most of them
elderly, some of them mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants these people,'' he said. ``There are no
organizations, no institutions to take them in.''
</P>
<P>
   The elderly, many of them suffering from dementia, babbled
incoherently. The retarded sat there, saying nothing, some of them
rocking gently.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would become of these people, Durant let the flap go
and said, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other volunteers here, Durant has an extraordinary ability
to focus on the things he can change and not be overwhelmed by
those he can't.
</P>
<P>
   He and the other doctors are providing battlefield triage and
engaging in emotional triage, with their patients, among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Durant said he has to adopt an attitude to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The border guards here beat the shit out of people and
intimidate the docs. They're almost as bad as the Serbs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His old friend, the former Boston Herald political columnist
Peter Lucas, taught him some Albanian, concentrating on swear
words, a skill Durant dispenses liberally here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to be able to swear in the local language.
It establishes instant credibility,'' he explained, examining a
woman suffering from bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonian police and special forces are a surly lot,
frequently and arbitrarily denying access to the field. Durant, who
attended Boston College and Georgetown Medical School, spent a year
at the Harvard School of Public Health. He has been flashing his
Harvard ID card, and for some inexplicable reason, it keeps
disarming the unsmiling guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmmmm, Hah-vud,'' a guard said Monday, waving Durant through,
apparently impressed, although his tone didn't suggest as much.
</P>
<P>
   Durant, who plans to stay here at least another week, said he
will continue volunteering his skills, wherever they are needed. He
finds a strange, inner peace in places like Blace. It puts his own
problems in perspective. It offers larger lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the proof of Original Sin, of good vs. evil, of man's
inhumanity to man,'' he said. ``But the most striking thing is that
this shows the resilience of the human spirit. Despite all that you
see here, there are still people who can laugh, who can show
kindness to others.''
</P>
<P>
   He also confessed to a selfish interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets me away from the horrible bureaucracy back home,'' he
said. ``There are many terrible things here, but there are no
lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun rose Tuesday, Durant stood outside on ground strewn
with trash and refugees who worried for their loved ones in the
tents. An indescribable stench wafted over from the nearby river
that refugees are using as an open toilet.
</P>
<P>
   He was supposed to be relieved at 8 a.m., to catch some sleep
before returning to the camp to help out and to take another
midnight shift. But his replacement was late, and it wasn't long
before Dr. Luan Jaha, the local doctor running the clinic, poked
his head through the flap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom,'' he said, almost apologetically. ``I need you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Durant, bleary-eyed but sure of purpose, ducked into the
tent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
