</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW HOOPLA MASKS LACKLUSTER RETURNS FOR MOST FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow climbs to 10,000, scaling a peak that only months ago
seemed a mirage in the clouds. So where are the thrills of the
summit for mutual fund investors?
</P>
<P>
   Many stock funds had so-so or disappointing returns last
quarter, with only those invested in a handful of the biggest
blue-chip companies or whiz-bang Internet and technology shares
joining the popular Wall Street benchmark in the climb.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first three months of 1999, growth funds, which invest
in large-company shares, gained 4.4 percent; funds mimicking the
blue chip-rich Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 4.8 percent; and
those focused on science, technology, and telecommunications gained
anywhere from 16.4 percent to 17 percent, according to fund
tracking firm Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the happy stories. Funds invested in just about
anything else got left at base camp.
</P>
<P>
   Those devoted to small companies backslid, losing nearly 6
percent. Indeed, in a quarter in which the Dow Jones industrial
average rose a heady 6.6 percent, closing above 10,000 for the
first time on March 29, the average US diversified stock fund
gained only a skimpy 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The chasm between funds doing well and those performing poorly
provides a glimpse into the strange new terrain of the stock
market, whose landscape is increasingly one of a few spectacular
peaks and many low valleys. ``This continues to be a large cap
environment, and there's a clear dichotomy between the winners and
the losers,'' said David Corkins, who runs the $464 million Janus
Growth &AMP; Income fund.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the gap is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Lipper said last quarter marked the largest outperformance of
growth funds over their small-cap brethren since the firm began
tracking funds in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   That outperformance-gap is also evident within large caps.
According to Laszlo Birinyi, an investment consultant in Greenwich,
Conn., fully 82 percent of the S&AMP;P 500's decent gain last quarter
came from only 10 stocks, including Microsoft Corp. and America
Online Inc. (The other 490 stocks in the index, which comprises the
country's biggest companies by market capitalization, did not gain
much.)
</P>
<P>
   The US stock market's narrowing of gainers comes as the domestic
economy stands tall and proud. Record-low inflation, declining
interest rates, and cost-cutting measures at corporations have all
pushed market indexes higher over the eight years since Wall
Street's recordlong bull market began.
</P>
<P>
   While fund investors have shuddered at Wall Street's volatility
in previous months and fretted overseas economic crises, they have
not forsaken equity fund investing. Americans now have an estimated
$5.6 trillion invested in mutual funds of all stripes, according to
the Investment Company Institute.
</P>
<P>
   So it is ironic that investors earned more last quarter from
money market funds _ about 1 percent _ than from the average
diversified stock fund. The average long-term bond fund returned
only 0.2 percent, below previous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Chasing performance, ordinary investors are pouring increasing
amounts of cash into the large-cap and tech-heavy funds that are
hogging all the gains. After sitting on the sidelines in February,
investors plowed a hefty $26.4 billion of new cash into stock funds
last month, the most in nearly a year, according to Trimtabs.com
Investment Research.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston-based Fidelity Investments, the nation's biggest
mutual fund firm, top sellers so far this year are all focused on
large-company stocks and include Blue Chip Growth, Fidelity Fifty,
Dividend Growth, and Magellan, according to Financial Research Corp
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Such a trend suggests that investors may be less enthused about
one of investing's crystal-clear rules: diversification. After all,
the market seems to be saying, what's the point of spreading one's
eggs into multiple baskets if only a few hold the golden ones?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants diversification in this kind of rip-roaring
market,'' said Charles B. Carleson, who comanages the Dow 30 Value
fund at Strong-Corneliuson Capital Management in Milwaukee. ``But
it's not a policy that should be abandoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, long-battered funds invested in Latin American,
Japanese, and Pacific region stocks all roared back last quarter.
(By contrast, Europe was no fun at all, with funds focused on that
area losing 2.6 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors _ who increasingly use mutual funds to save for
retirement _ might be forgiven for finding less reason to diversify
when they open their quarterly statements.
</P>
<P>
   Growth and income funds, which include value stocks, or shares
deemed good bargains, gained a piddly 1.8 percent last quarter.
Equity income funds, focused on companies paying dividends, shed
0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among sector funds, which concentrate on specific industries,
natural resource funds made a comeback with an average 7 percent
gain. On the other side were utility funds, which lost 3 percent,
and real-estate funds, which shed 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not all industry watchers find the stock market's increasing
narrowness cause for concern. In a recent research note,
PaineWebber Inc. sought to debunk what it termed two myths about
the reign of a narrow group of large-caps and the appetite of
ordinary investors and fund managers alike for those stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that large-cap stocks are doing well simply because
everybody is piling willy-nilly into the S&AMP;P 500 (mostly via index
funds such as the Vanguard Index 500) doesn't make sense,
PaineWebber said, because only a few S&AMP;P 500 stocks are doing well.
In other words, with far from all stocks in the index posting
gains, the general ``indexation'' phenomenon cannot be used to
explain the S&AMP;P's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Second, while it is possible that huge companies are
outperforming everything else simply because they are household
names investors like or liquid issues portfolio managers can easily
trade, there is another explanation for large caps' reign. Such
stocks are growing, PaineWebber wrote, not just because investors
are blindly pushing them up but because they have relatively strong
price-earnings expansion and relatively strong earnings. In other
words, high-performing large caps are growing on their own merits,
and are not just a fad (popular though they may be).
</P>
<P>
   That suggests investors are behaving rationally, not blindly, by
piling into funds that hold them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors might not want to get so excited.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber sees the Dow _ and, by extension, the S&AMP;P 500, which
historically correlates closely with its cousin-benchmark _ due for
a 5-to-15 percent correction sometime later this year. If that
happens, mutual fund investors pondering the zeniths and nadirs in
their forthcoming statements might find diversification appealing
after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
