<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, April 8:
</P>
<P>
   MONGIARDINO-DESIGN (Milan) _ Few outsiders were ever allowed
into the private world of the late Renzo Mongiardino, the legendary
interior designer. By many visitors to next week's furniture fair
here will be making a pilgrimage to the dour Palazzo Crivelli in
the center of the city, where Mongiardino's genius is being feted
prior to its final disbursement. By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ACCONCI-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ It is hard to reconcile the
quiet figure of Vito Acconci, aspiring architect, with the swath he
has cut as an artist over the last 30 years. Acconci, the enfant
terrible emeritus of the downtown art world, is using his
increasingly housebroken art to put a humane spin on contemporary
architecture. By Philip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   With phto.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LOGO (Undated) _ Even wars have logos these days, at
least on television, and the coverage of the Kosovo war invariably
features the Albanian eagle, splashed across the screen like the
NBC peacock. The Albanian eagle, angular, Gothic, almost medieval
in style, with its two heads and dragonlike claws, seems to sum up
the ancient nature of the conflicts in the Balkans _ and the fears
Americans have of an area they don't understand. It's a feathered
version of all the fears of foreign entanglements we've worried
about since Washington's Farewell address. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   MOTORCOACH-RESORT (Undated) _ A few miles, as the pelican flies,
from the warm green waters of the Gulf of Mexico, tan bodies
gathered round a patio table. The conversation paused when an
engine rumble neared. A new neighbor was moving onto Southern
Breeze Drive. ``Nice,'' Kraig Brechbuhler said as the newest home
on the block rolled by, its burgundy-and-gold sides sparkling in
the noon sun. In the gated community known as Pelican Lake
Motorcoach Resort, not only do the neighbors come and go, but so
also do the homes. No Winnebagos here, however. This resort is
exclusively for luxury motor coaches, most of them longer than 37
feet. They look like tour buses for rock stars. By Diane Ketcham.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLOR (Undated) _ Garden fashion is fickle: It used to be
perennials versus annuals. Then it was pastels versus hot, read
vulgar, colors. Now that beginning gardeners have learned what a
rhizome is, and red and orange have been reborn as respectable
garden colors, it's time for another category of plants to elbow
its way into the garden. By Mac Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
