<HEADER>
A9054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-FOCUS-BOS &LR;      04-07 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-FOCUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AT 50: NO FESTIVITIES AMID CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy _ NATO's 50th anniversary was supposed to
be a bright, shining moment.
</P>
<P>
   But at the nerve center of the NATO airstrikes against
Yugoslavia, this week's scheduled commemorations of the
half-century since the birth of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization have been called off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing on the work at hand,'' said US Air Force Major
Scott Vadnais at the command center of the base, as preparations
continued for intensifying air missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're too busy for any fancy dinners,'' he added, as pilots
strutted down a corridor with American, Canadian, Spanish, and
British markings on their gray flight suits.
</P>
<P>
   The ``work at hand'' has taken this 19-nation alliance into
unexplored military and political terrain, and the conflict in
Kosovo has crystallized NATO's struggle to find its way in the
post-Cold War world. At age 50, NATO is having a mid-life crisis at
a very busy time.
</P>
<P>
   Established on April 4, 1949, NATO's stated mission was to
answer the threat to European security posed by the Soviet Union.
After the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991, NATO was left without a
clear enemy, and without a clear mission.
</P>
<P>
   Now NATO has for the first time attacked a sovereign nation, in
what critics fear is a dangerous expansion of its mandate. But
supporters of the mission in Kosovo say it is a necessary, onetime
response to a unique situation, and that it is too early to say
NATO has structurally changed as a result.
</P>
<P>
   In less than three weeks, the leaders of the alliance are set to
meet in Washington for a summit that will focus on redefining NATO
and its goals for the next century. There, the key issue will be
whether NATO will continue to maintain its defensive posture or
transform itself into a global policing role _ fighting terrorism,
the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, and containing
conficts in the Balkans and elsewhere that could spill into Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is precisely what NATO should be doing,'' said Helmut
Sonnenfeldt, an expert on European military affairs at the
Brookings Institution in Washington. ``We are in unprecedented
times, so we are going to see unprecedented moves taken by the
alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO should be careful not to go too far in redefining its
role when the alliance leaders meet, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mandate should not be tampered with. They should continue
to assess their role in a case-by-case basis,'' he said. ``If they
officially expand its role to protect Europe against `legitimate'
threats, there will be serious divisions over how to define the
`legitimacy' of a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, would it include Iraq, where most of Europe
receives oil. What about Iran? This will get very difficult and is
fraught with problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Keeny, a senior member of the National Security Council
staff in the Kennedy and Johnson administrations and head of the
Washington-based Arms Control Association, is also wary of the
``new NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It poses a grave concern and will put great strain on the
alliance. The current crisis in Kosovo is not what disturbs me, but
the ripple effect of an expanded NATO. I'm worried about what it
will do to our relations with Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The massive Aviano air base, which has 3,500 personnel,
exemplifies the best of NATO's international makeup. There's an
Italian mess hall with a pasta buffet, a British pub that serves
Guinness, a Greek souflaki stand, and just about everyone flocks to
the Spanish mess tent for paella on Thursdays. And of course there
is an eclectic mix of Americana _ from junk food to classical jazz
on the radio station. People seem to get along.
</P>
<P>
   Not that cultural differences don't cause problems. American
officers are perturbed that their Canadian subordinates refuse to
salute them. And Spanish and Italian officers are furious that
American officers permit television news cameras on the base, which
they see as a dangerous breach of security.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Aviano refuse to give out the exact breakdown of
different nationalities, but a tour of the base makes it clear that
the nearly 150 fighter jets are almost all made in the United
States. And the personnel seems to be at least 70 percent American.
</P>
<P>
   The base seems to embody both the changes in NATO as it
redefines itself and the cumbersome political and diplomatic
structure that sometimes blurred its mission in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole way of doing business has changed,'' said Captain
Edward Thomas, who has been at Aviano on-and-off since 1995, ``a
transition from an on-call and stationary force to an expeditionary
force that is light, lean, and lethal, and capable of deploying in
hot spots quickly . . . times have changed, so we have to change
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with several senior officials from the United
States and two European countries suggest that the changes at the
base have also brought rising tensions, as the understanding of
NATO's mission diverges among some of the alliances members.
</P>
<P>
   It can cost officers their jobs if they criticize NATO publicly.
But in private, many of them, American as well as European, express
frustration with the layers of bureaucracy and interlocking chains
of command, saying they limit their ability to do their job
effectively. And then there are broader issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some fear that NATO is going to become an extension
of America's global interests,'' said a senior officer in a
European squadron of fighter jets, who spoke on the condition that
his name and nationality not be used. ``That is something forces on
base worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   But a senior American officer who has spent most of the last 12
years stationed at NATO bases in Germany, England, and Turkey said
he welcomed the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time we cleared up the role of NATO,'' he said.
``We've been adrift too long. So I say it's about time we did
something.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Europeans seem less comfortable with the new NATO,
especially with its role in the Balkans _ the fuse that helped
ignite two world wars. There is widespread resentment against the
United States, which many perceive as an arrogant superpower having
its way in Europe under the cover of a united NATO.
</P>
<P>
   To many who gather daily outside the air base, the Aviano-based
US Marine pilots who severed a ski area's gondola cable and killed
20 people represent the recklessness of an American-led NATO. That
resentment found expression in violence this week when a group
calling itself ``The Anti-imperialist Terrorist Cell'' claimed
responsibility for bombing a car that carried American military
markings. The group has conducted other sporadic attacks since
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Every night since the Kosovo crisis began, people have arrived
outside the main gate by the hundreds to watch _ and by the dozens
to protest _ the American-made Stealth fighters and F-16s that roar
off toward their targets in Yugoslavia, about 200 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Families set up lawn chairs, and others lean against the wooden
fence that separates the air base from the surrounding farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Barbera, 26, an English literature student, said she came
because ``war is not only an image on TV, but very real.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are horrifying,'' she whispered after the roar of the jet
faded into the distance. ``I disagree with this action very much.
It makes me feel we didn't learn anything from our past in
Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
