<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENCE NEEDED ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the world's TV screens filled with the most grotesque
scenes of refugee catastrophe since the Nazi reign, where is the
cause for hope?
</P>
<P>
   Things look dreadful, to be sure. But the civilized world is
rallying to the cause of the 400,000 stranded Albanians. And public
opinion, initially shocked at the ferocity of the NATO bombing
campaign, is now polarizing against the Serbs for the viciousness
of their leader, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   --What is the best outcome we can hope for? A quick end to the
NATO bombing, which in turn would require a stand-down by
Milosevic's rampaging forces. The clearing skies over Kosovo have
enabled NATO to rachet up the frequency, potency, and accuracy of
the air onslaught. NATO leaders vow they won't be outfoxed by a
Milosevic ploy to demand a bombing halt once he's butchered or
evicted most of the Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As bleak as the prospect appears today, NATO's aim of returning
the bulk of Kosovo refugees, now approaching 1 million, to the land
of their birth, is still the eventual goal.
</P>
<P>
   --How can that possibly be accomplished, given the ethnic
cleansing that has transpired? What seems likely, even inevitable,
is the partition of Kosovo, where the 2 million Albanians
outnumbered Serbs by 9-1. It is not hard to envisage a UN-directed,
NATO-enforced partition that would give the Serbs a northern
enclave of the current Kosovo, to be lumped into the Greater Serbia
the Serbs are always talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of what is now Kosovo must somehow devolve into a new,
enlarged, and dependent-on-the-West Greater Albania. It is also not
hard to envision the enlarged Albania, the most backward quadrant
of Europe, becoming a client state of the wealthy nations, a sort
of 51st state of the US, requiring economic development to lift an
undeveloped backwater into the 21st century. It will need roads,
bridges, housing, industrial development, power stations, the whole
rig. But the new Albania would still comprise only about 4 million
people, depending upon what happens to the enclaves of Montenegro
and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   --What happens with what used to be Yugoslavia? That probably
becomes Serbia; Belgrade remains the capital. Does Milosevic remain
the leader? That depends on a lot of things. Can the allies kill
him in an air raid? Is there a chance he'll be strung up by the
heels like Mussolini? Do his fellow Serbs turn on him? Can he be
brought to justice as a war criminal, a fate he richly deserves?
</P>
<P>
   All this is up in the air. What's also in the air is an
astonishing and punishing variety of NATO ordnance, which may turn
the tide and spare the 19-nation NATO alliance the unappetizing
option of introducing ground combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   --Is there any way Milosevic can work some sort of public
relations ju-jitsu and emerge from this as a nationalist hero
fighting to defend his tiny country, the size and population of
Ohio, against the combined might of NATO countries representing
over 700 million people? At first glance, you'd say no; but then
look at the long, and so-far uninterrupted runs, or similarly
bellicose dictators, like Saddam Hussein, Muammar Qaddafi, and
Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   However, the documentation of the Serbian war crimes, the sheer
scope of the atrocities, and the inevitable mass graves and
soccer-field-turned-into-boneyards that have characterized his
previous wars in the Balkans, suggest his image is permanently
blackened. ``He started four wars in the past eight years,'' said
US negotiator Richard Holbrooke Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This Serb's hands are permanently bloodied, and the first-hand
accounts of hundreds of thousands of Albanian deportees cannot be
eclipsed by a PR campaign, a captive TV network, or a rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   --Will the Clinton administration stay the course? As the most
criticized and vilified president since Truman, Clinton's enemies
are everywhere, but as ineffectual as ever. There is the ``the war
is over, we lost, Milosevic won,'' claque. The declarations of
surrender should at least wait until the outcome of the bombing
campaign, you'd think, but making sweeping declarations equivalent
to the-sky-is-falling gets a talking head off the sofa and onto the
tube.
</P>
<P>
   There is the ``we should have thought of all this before we
started'' school of diplomatic hindsight. Plainly, NATO's planners
did not envisage Milosevic acting with such Hitleresque
indifference to the niceties of civilized norms. But if you
criticize NATO for not doing enough last month, you can't criticize
NATO for not trying hard enough this month.
</P>
<P>
   --Who has this helped in America's domestic politics? Clinton,
for one; no one's talking about Monica now, and all the
flannelmouths who were braying two weeks ago about his ``legacy''
are finding new reasons to doubt his judgment, fortitude, or
diplomatic skills. The air war has also elevated Republican Senator
John McCain from the back of the pack toward the front. The
ineffectual ducking of GOP frontrunners George W. Bush and
Elizabeth Dole contrasts with the clear, sharp, hard position of
McCain, which is: bomb harder, send troops, go for the Serb
despot's throat.
</P>
<P>
   If presidential politics is unpredictable, so is the course of a
two-week-old war, and diplomatic attempts to corral the latest
Hitler stalking Europe. So be patient, don't panic, and remember
that we are on the right side, doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
