<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S BACK? ROGER! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ In sayings and stats, rules and maxims, lore
and legend, baseball leads the league in Talmudic scholarship. No
sage is savvier than Leonard Koppett, the former New York Times
scribe who now writes for the Oakland Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Koppett stresses defense, declaring that bad fielding loses more
baseball games than good hitting. The logic is mathematically
inescapable: In many games, one run can ensure victory, but in
nearly every game, winning requires making 27 outs.
</P>
<P>
   In the home opener for the Oakland Athletics, after Derek Jeter
singled for the New York Yankees, Paul O'Neill hit a ground ball to
the second baseman, Tony Phillips, who booted what would have been
a double play. Jeter later scored and the Yankees led, 1-0, after
the first half-inning.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Athletics led the league with 141 errors and
surrendered 100 unearned runs. Porous leather may explain why they
won 74 games while the Yankees won 114. If
</P>
<P>
   Tony Phillips is the answer, what is the question? Oft-troubled
and much traveled, he has been a toothless Tiger, an anxious Angel,
and a mediocre Met. Phillips is one of the 40ish veterans Oakland
hopes will inspire its 20ish rookies. Oakland's generation gap is
based on its bargain-basement payroll, $25 million against the $88
million paid by the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillips error chilled many among the 46,380 at Oakland
Coliseum because pitching for the Yankees was Roger Clemens, he of
the five Cy Young awards, two won during what one former employer
called ``the twilight of his career.'' For Clemens, the weather was
a letter from home, as cold and rainy as any season opener in
Boston or Toronto. The storm clouds over the California coast were
as nasty as a Clemens split-fingered fastball.
</P>
<P>
   A one-run lead? That is often all the Rocket needs. But in the
first inning, he walked two batters and threw 19 pitches, hardly a
complete-game pace. He settled down, as they say in baseball, and
even after a 47-minute rain delay, Clemens easily struck out
batters, eight in all.
</P>
<P>
   But in baseball, as the Yankee interim manager, Don Zimmer,
said, ``Everyone's even on the first Monday.'' Oakland's Opening
Day ceremonies honored the heroes of its 1989 championship, a
parade that included Dave Stewart, the longtime Clemens nemesis,
and Dennis Eckersley, now a rookie broadcaster. The Eck and Zimmer
shook hands at home plate, sharing memories, if they had any, of
1978, when both wore Red Sox uniforms soiled and sullied by a
Yankee juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Phillips was on that Oakland championship team, too. In the
fifth inning, he faced Clemens, who had inexplicably walked the
ninth batter. Phillips homered, tying the game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball can offer more acts of redemption in one night than a
three-day hoedown of the Christian Coalition. In the seventh, after
Clemens walked Phillips, Zimmer yanked the starting pitcher.
Oakland then erupted, eventually winning, 5-3. After another rain
delay and eight innings, the umpires ended the game at 12:27 a.m.
Oakland needed only 24 outs.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness in baseball today focuses on the disparity in payrolls,
willingly paid by owners and accepted by players. Gene Orza,
counsel for the players association, sniffs pro-owner propaganda in
these concerns, pointing out that rich teams beat poor teams
decades ago when players were chattel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big countries beat up small countries, too,'' Orza says.
``Revenue sharing is inadequate only to the extent that it dries up
the well of suitors. But there's always some guy in Charlotte or
Las Vegas who wants to buy a team under current conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Orza would love a Minnesota-Montreal World Series to confound
the critics. Maybe Roger's washed up. Maybe the Yankees will
stumble. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Among many sporting maxims is one from the Manhattan writer,
Damon Runyon, who amended St. Paul: ``The race is not always to the
swift, nor the battle to the strong. But that's the way to bet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
