u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-07 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING TOO FAST ON GEORGES BANK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What scorched earth was to Sherman, scarred earth is to
scallopers. The Union general, leaving nothing to chance after
taking Atlanta, left only the charred embers of Confederate
factories, mills, and food stores in his march to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Scallopers, leaving no profit untouched, leave a lifeless rubble
on the sea floor.
</P>
<P>
   Such a comparison, as brutal as it may seem to scallop
fishermen, should weigh heavily on the minds of the New England
Fishery Management Council. Next week the council is scheduled to
vote on whether to reopen Area 2 of Georges Bank that was closed in
1994 because of overfishing.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Area 2 was closed because of the crash of ground
fish, such as cod and flounder. Scallopers were included in the ban
because their metal dredges also catch flounder and other fish in
fearsome amounts. The dredges catch 2 pounds of fish for every
pound of scallops, part of the worldwide crisis of ``bycatch,'' in
which boats pursuing a particular fish decimate other species.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, scientists have discovered that scallops
have recovered dramatically in Area 2 in colonies so plump and
populous they are at the point of overcrowding. Almost immediately,
scallopers called for a lifting of restrictions. After watching
their catch drop from 20 million pounds a year to under 9 million
pounds in less than a decade, their cries of economic hardship have
resulted in Capitol Hill clout.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, US Commerce Secretary William Daley, escorted by
Senator Ted Kennedy, came to New England to meet with scallopers.
The council had already been considering a limited reopening of
Georges Bank. But Daley wrote a letter to the council urging it to
consider a reopening by June 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sympathetic to their plight and want these areas open to
scallopers as soon as possible,'' Daley wrote the council.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said: ``This is welcome news for hundreds of fishing
families. Their economic survival depends on access to these closed
areas. I commend Secretary Daley for making a decision that
recognizes the legitimate and urgent needs of these hard-working
fishermen.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Daley is committed to an expedited examination
of other currently closed areas to see if scallops can be fished
``at the earliest practicable date.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, none of these decisions appears to factor in any
full-scale pursuit of scientific evidence that would aid the
long-term survival of fish in these waters. Scallops may have
recovered quickly, but no one is even close to knowing whether they
symbolize a healed ecosystem or have merely become the crows and
starlings that quickly crowd out more delicate migratory birds as
humans cut down trees for cities and suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   We know that scallops can recover, but we know little about what
happens to the sponges, starfish, anemones, worms, and other
members of what is technically known as the benthic (occurring at
the bottom of the water) community. They have no value on your
dinner plate, but layer by layer, they end up as the food for cod
and flounder. Each run of a scallop dredge temporarily annihilates
that community. There is evidence they can begin to recover in a
couple of years or so, but no one knows how much battering _ in the
age of modern fishing _ such communities can take.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that scallopers should never be allowed to
fish again. But the fishing industry has proven itself to be an
almost complete failure at self-control. Daley is right to call for
expedited research, but not merely to confirm that $100 million of
scallops are ready to be picked.
</P>
<P>
   Any serious research should show whether enough of the ecosystem
has recovered so that any resumption of scalloping, with its
inescapable history of bycatch and a destruction of the sea floor
that includes flattening the terrain, will not endanger any of the
other ground fish.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have raised concern that it is impossible to
know any of these answers by June 15. ``Washington politics is a
poor substitute for hands-on science,'' said Robert Russell and
Jennifer Atkinson of the Conservation Law Foundation. Doug Hopkins
of the Environmental Defense Fund, who is a member of the New
England Fishery Management Council, said, ``The fact that the
secretary of commerce has expressed such a direct interest in this
decision is putting a great deal of pressure on the council to come
to the conclusion he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley is putting so much pressure on the council that
environmentalists fear that opening Area 2 is only the beginning of
a renewed scarred-earth campaign. As much as scallopers are
struggling financially, letting them plunder the sea without
sufficient science to know whether their fishing is safe or
foolish. They might get scallops to feed us for a day. Their march
under the sea might leave the underwater equivalent of charred
embers. Instead of glowing orange, these embers will be a dull,
barren gray that will haunt us for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
