<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTROOM-CAMERAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGES AREN'T ALL SMILING FOR THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- US District Judge Patti B. Saris remembers the trial _
and the experiment _ well. In 1994, an Indonesian general studying
at Harvard was sued by the family of a mourner who was massacred,
along with 270 others, by soldiers at a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The trial attracted international attention and, for the first
time, television crews. They were allowed into the federal
courtroom under a pilot program that Saris thinks worked well. But
shortly after the trial ended, so did the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, when Judge Judy has toppled Oprah from her perch as
queen of daytime TV, when the global village tunes in to the trials
of Louise Woodward and O. J. Simpson, the federal courts remain
resolutely unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their state counterparts, where cameras have been welcome
for at least two decades, the federal courts have resisted,
preferring the gentility of sketch artists to the intrusion of
videocams and tripods. But now, a proposal in Congress would allow
cameras in federal courtrooms if the sitting judge approves it,
overruling a blanket ban in effect for years.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in federal court in Boston have differing views, with
some welcoming the change as long-overdue and others fiercely
protecting their last bastion of low-tech justice.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents decry the snap judgments that flow from sound bites
and instant analysis, while proponents say it's about time the
federal courts joined the technological age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television does a bad job with court proceedings, which lose
something when they are overly compressed,'' said US District Judge
Michael A. Ponsor, who sits in Springfield and doesn't want cameras
in his courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television also subjects the parties, the judge, the lawyers,
and the witnesses to pressure which they really don't need,''
Ponsor added. ``It takes tremendous courage to take the stand and
describe things, like the death of a child, or losing a father
because of a botched operation, without having to worry about the
television camera focusing on their face to catch a tear forming in
the corner of an eye.''
</P>
<P>
   But US District Judge Nancy Gertner, who is familiar with
televised trials from her years as a high-profile defense lawyer,
said that after two decades of broadcast state court trials, ``the
genie is out of the bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is used to it,'' said Gertner. ``It is a medium to
be dealt with, not to be ignored. For years state courts have been
televising the worst gut-wrenching street crimes and the republic
still survives. I just hope we have television while there is some
collagen left in my face.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been triggered by ``The Sunshine in the Courtroom
Act'' filed recently in Washington by two senators and two
representatives, including Representative William D. Delahunt of
Massachusetts. The legislation would give federal judges the power
to admit cameras to their courtrooms, which is now banned by the
Judicial Conference, the governing body of the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt said cameras in federal courts would offer the public
``an unfiltered, unvarnished glimpse of the judicial process. The
goal is enhanced confidence in our criminal-justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which Delahunt filed along with Senators Charles
Schumer (D-New York) and Charles E. Grassley (R-Iowa) and
Representative Steve Chabot (R-Ohio), would allow cameras in both
appellate and trial courts.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven states, including Massachusetts, allow televised
coverage of state court proceedings, but federal courts, except for
the three-year experiment in the early 1990s, have never allowed
video cameras and have banned still photographs for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was one of six federal district courts that participated
in the pilot program, during which 14 civil cases were televised
here. But in the end, the Judicial Conference reimposed the ban,
citing a potential negative impact of cameras on jurors and
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, New York ousted TV cameras from its state courts, where
they had been allowed for a decade. Members of the defense bar
successfully argued that only sensational cases were broadcast,
there was little educational value, and criminal trials were
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham Law School Dean John D. Feerick, who headed a commission
that studied camera coverage in New York courtrooms, disagreed with
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television provides confidence in the process,'' he said. ``It
gives people information on how the rule of law is working in court
trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt acknowledged there are cases in which cameras are not
appropriate. When he was Norfolk district attorney, Delahunt
supported a ban on TV cameras at the trial of John Salvi, the
abortion clinic gunman who had a propensity to act out before the
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   With his colleagues on the federal bench here split on the
issue, Chief US District Court Judge William G. Young sides with
the opponents _ a shift in position for him.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras in the courtroom, he argues, denigrate jurors' work when
viewers, who heard only snippets of testimony, second-guess the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Young didn't always feel that way. While a state Superior Court
judge in 1984, he presided over the ``Big Dan's'' gang-rape trial
in New Bedford, the first widely watched televised trial in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I thought it was a good idea, that it served an
educational purpose,'' Young said. ``I bought the argument that
television can bring the courthouse to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, after the Simpson and Woodward trials, Young believes
the viewing public wrongly thinks it knows as much about the
evidence as the jury. As a result, viewers feel qualified to
disregard the jury verdict, Young says.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the protests in the streets outside the Cambridge
courthouse after a jury convicted Woodward of second-degree murder,
a verdict later reduced by the judge to involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trial is not rocket science and we think that after watching
five minutes, we can go on `Oprah' and think we know what it is all
about,'' said Young. ``Everyone in the world would be
second-guessing (jurors) and they may not be willing to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Young does not object to televising non-jury cases, noting that
the new federal courthouse on Fan Pier, which was built to
accommodate hidden security cameras, could easily _ and
unobtrusively _ handle TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   For attorney Frederic N. Halstrom, former president of the
Massachusetts Academy of Trial Lawyers, it's all about democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is entitled to see what is going on in their
courts,'' said Halstrom. ``They can't be there in person because
they are working to pay taxes, taxes which pay the salaries of the
judges and court personnel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
