<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE REPUBLIC OF ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a few days, I will be sending a pot of money off to the
Internal Revenue Service. I can imagine better uses for my swag
than bombing the bejesus out of a country whose hospitality I
enjoyed many years ago. But transferring a portion of my pitiful
income to the treasury coffers isn't such an onerous task, ever
since Bill Clinton transformed the United States of America into
the Republic of Me.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to notice that the entire country is being run for
my benefit. Not for my personal benefit, perhaps, but certainly for
the benefit of my generation. It's great being a member of the
still-active (Alex Beam) _ as opposed to the incipiently decrepit
(Al Gore) _ Baby Boom generation. We've got the numbers,
demographically and economically. We vote, we buy tons of stuff, we
whine, volubly. No need of ours goes unmet.
</P>
<P>
   We have children; Bill Clinton gives us a new Child Tax Credit.
Our kids are approaching college age; Bill Clinton awards us the
fifteen-hundred-dollar college credits. How are we paying for that
new Accord in the driveway? (Not in my driveway, alas . . .) By
selling stock, at the new lower capital gains rate.
</P>
<P>
   Now our ally and contemporary Mr. Clinton proposes pouring
billions of surplus budgetary dollars into the Social Security
system. The purpose is not to benefit today's oldsters _
fuhggedaboudem! _ but to benefit . . . me. ``Once self-indulgent
Baby Boomers have been enrolled in the AARP,'' predicts the Wall
Street Journal, ``the rest of the government may go begging.'' You
know how the HMOs are forcing the elderly to pay for prescription
drugs? How much do you want to bet those rules get changed by the
time I start quaffing Prilosec?
</P>
<P>
   This is great. This is living. Imagine what it would be like to
be on the wrong end of Mr. Clinton's list of priorities. Like on
welfare. Just a couple of years ago, Clinton confiscated $1,300
worth of annual food-stamp benefits from 11 million families living
at or near the poverty line. That was when he also tossed legal
immigrants out of the Supplemental Security Income program (he let
them back in two years later). Better that than tamper with my
mortgage deduction, I say. Alas, some people aren't full-fledged
citizens of this delightful Republic of Me.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the horror and blind ineptitude of Mr. Bill's Balkan
adventure, this little war is a classic Republic of Me production.
My generation's too old to fight; our children are too young. The
whole affair is blissfully far away, and even the newspaper-reading
public seems to be swallowing the ``humanitarian angle'' churned
out by Bill Clinton's Ministry of Propaganda. Milosevic as Hitler?
Why not? Heck, we believed the Rose Law firm files mysteriously
``reappeared'' in the White House library, didn't we?
</P>
<P>
   But why worry about the war? The minute I tire of it _ and that
will be the minute Albanian refugees show up on the Green Line _
Clinton will declare victory and go home. Let's enjoy the other
Republic of Me benefits all around us. Aren't those oldies stations
great? Who cares if nobody else likes our music _ we'll force them
to listen! Did you see that Bob Dylan and Paul Simon are touring
together this summer? Shag-adelic, baby!
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood panders to our teenage children (spending our money,
natch), but it still knows how to lure the HBO generation into the
cineplex: Re-release some vintage Boomer chaff (``Big Chill,''
``Star Wars'') is one way to go. Or better yet, churn out movies
suggesting that geriatric Boomer idols like Clint Eastwood (69) or
Robert Redford (62) remain alluring to women half their age. Who
says movies aren't realistic?
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about the Republic of Me is that it will last
forever. Because the Boomers think they're immortal, or the closest
thing to it. Some Harvard quack is pushing a book called ``Living
to 100,'' which I plan to ridicule under separate cover. Tough
news, kids. We'll give you your country back in 2050; another
half-century of Mary Tyler Moore reruns to go!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
