<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGIVENESS UNITES PASTOR, MAN WHO KILLED SON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In May 1988, the Rev. Walter H. Everett was furious as he
listened to a Connecticut prosecutor explain why the man accused of
killing Everett's son was about to agree to a plea bargain that
would result in a five-year jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Everett performed the marriage ceremony for his
son's convicted killer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Everett, 64, and Michael Carlucci, 39, the man who put a
gun to Scott Everett's head inside a Bridgeport, Conn., apartment
and pulled the trigger, are close friends who talk on the phone
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   What happened between Everett, pastor of the United Methodist
Church of Hartford, and Carlucci, who works for a trucking company
in Connecticut, is a powerful story of forgiveness, faith, and
healing.
</P>
<P>
   The men travel to colleges and churches, describing their
journey together, hoping to provide a stark lesson on the
possiblities of redemption and reconciliation even in the worst of
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Everett said he chose to forgive Carlucci because he could not
bear the alternative _ to live with the anger seething in him ever
since he learned his son had been murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me that the primary right of a victim's family is
not to have the rest of their lives consumed with anger,''
explained Everett. ``My son's life was taken. I don't want my life
to be taken by my anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness, Everett makes clear, does not mean in any way
condoning what Carlucci did. It means, he said, ``feeling good
enough about yourself to want the process of healing to begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's ordeal began July 26, 1987, as he sat in a restaurant
in Virginia. He and other church volunteers were on their way to
North Carolina to build homes for a Habitat for Humanity project.
</P>
<P>
   On that morning, a waitress called out Everett's name. She told
him he had a phone call. It was from the pastor of the church where
Everett had spent the night. Everett had to call home urgently. It
was an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   One of his sons answered and broke the news. Everett flew back
home that same day to plan his son's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Carlucci, meanwhile, was quickly arrested. He declines to go
into the details of how he and Scott ended up in an altercation in
the building where Scott lived. But after he shot Scott, Carlucci
called the police and said: ``I shot someone in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   At his sentencing, Carlucci expressed remorse for the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry for what I did,'' he told the court. ``I'm sorry I
killed Scott. I wish I could bring him back, but words can't do
that. I know these sound like empty words, but I don't know what
else to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlucci's words stirred something in Everett. He prayed for
some guidance. Eventually, he decided to write Carlucci. In his
letter, Everett described his fury, bewilderment, and frustration
over Carlucci's deed.
</P>
<P>
   But then he wrote: ``Having said all that I want to thank you
for what you said in court and despite how hard it is to write
these words, I forgive you.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlucci said he was stunned. When he first saw the return
address on the envelope, he was angry, believing Everett was
writing to harass him. He never expected to be forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had ever forgiven me for anything my whole life,'' said
Carlucci, whose life up until Scott Everett's killing had been
consumed with alcohol and drugs. He says he had been arrested more
than 40 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life was so bad I didn't care what happened to me and I
certainly didn't care what happened to anyone else,'' said
Carlucci.
</P>
<P>
   But that began to change when he was in prison for Everett's
murder. Carlucci asked Everett to visit him. After putting it off
for a while because he was not sure he could handle it, Everett did
come see Carlucci. Their meeting ended in a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me what unconditional love is,'' Carlucci said.
Carlucci started attending Narcotics Anonymous meetings. Everett
ended up testifying on Carlucci's behalf at his parole hearing.
Carlucci left prison after serving nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is married, owns a home, and is holding down a steady
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are worth giving a shot to change,'' Carlucci
said. ``Whether they can change, it's up to them.'' He says
speaking in public helps him remember where he came from and ``to
have gratitude for what I've been through and what I have.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Everett said, ``This isn't the guy who killed my
son. This is someone who has been changed by God.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Metropolitan Methodios, leader of the Greek Orthodox Diocese
of Boston, has issued a plea for peace in Yugoslavia, adding that
NATO bombing in the Balkans is exacerbating an already grim
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lamentation of the pain suffered by innocent men, women
and children in Serbia and Kosovo echoes to the depths of our
souls,'' Methodios said in a statement. ``We call for an immediate
end to atrocities on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   For Orthodox Christians around the world who follow a different
liturgical calendar than other Christians, Holy Week began April 5,
with Palm Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing attacks have proven only to harden the historic,
deep-rooted positions and caused more blood to be shed on the
Balkan landscape,'' Methodios said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
