<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HIGH-TECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH ALLURE DRAWS ISRAELI FIRMS TO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- There are many reasons why Greater Boston is a world
center for high technology. MIT. Harvard. Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Israel. Dozens of local tech firms have an Israeli
connection. Some serve as beachheads for Israeli companies moving
into the US market, while others are US-based companies founded on
Israeli technical know-how. But all of these firms are benefiting
from a combination of factors that have made the Boston area
especially attractive to Israeli technology firms. And the influx
of Israeli companies further bolsters the region's reputation for
technology leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here two years ago, there were about 30 Israeli
companies,'' said Michel Habib, Israel's economic consul in Boston.
Today, he puts the number at 65 ``that we know about,'' with
perhaps a dozen more operating below Habib's radar. The technology
mecca of Silicon Valley boasts 90 or more Israeli tech firms, but
Habib says Boston is catching up.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because of a powerful combination of time, money, and
brains. Obviously, the region's large population of technically
trained workers is a big advantage. ``This area is very high-tech
intensive,'' said Rami Hascal, planning and control manager for
Orbotech Ltd. of Billerica, maker of optical inspection machines
for printed circuit boards. ``There are a lot of technological
resources and knowledge in the area we can take advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Israel already produces a lot of extremely good
scientists and engineers. Its huge scientific university Technion
is as good as any in the world. According to the Israeli Economic
Mission, Israel boasts 135 engineers for every 100,000 citizens _
the highest proportion in the world. And every able-bodied man and
woman in the country must serve in the military, where many of them
receive exhaustive technical training.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel is not as well-stocked with trained business managers
who can turn a start-up firm into a star. ``We recognize they do
world-class engineering, but the marketing and sales of the product
leave something to be desired,'' says Joel Berkowitz, regional
director of the American Technion Society.
</P>
<P>
   Hillel Bachrach saw the problem back in 1974, three years after
he had graduated from Technion. ``At that time in Israel,''
Bachrach says, ``business schools were entirely unknown.'' Most
business managers were burnt-out engineers, not highly motivated
specialists. So Bachrach moved to the United States and earned an
MBA from Northwestern University. He went on to work for the
medical products division of General Electric Co., and today is
senior vice president of ESC Medical Systems Ltd. in Needham, a
maker of laser devices for use in cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ESC needs personnel who understand not only the products, but
also how to sell them. And such people aren't easy to find. ``The
industry of medical lasers has been my life for the last 11
years,'' Bachrach said, ``but compared to the rest of business,
it's not very big.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Boston area is home to several medical laser firms,
including Candela Corp. in Wayland, Summit Technology Inc. in
Waltham, and Cynosure Inc. in Chelmsford. Bachrach said this
concentration of talent helps keep his company staffed, sometimes
by hiring away workers from rival firms.
</P>
<P>
   Money is another of Boston's attractions for Israeli companies.
Local venture capital firms, eager to participate in the technology
boom, are ready to back sharp Israeli business people with bright
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country outside of the United States that is by far the
most active for early stage technology deals . . . is Israel,''
says Stephen R. Kahn, managing director of Boston's Advent
International. Advent has formed an alliance with Gemini Capital
Fund Management Ltd. of Herzlia, Israel, to invest in promising
Israeli firms. Advent and Gemini have invested in 17 Israeli firms
with operations in the United States; four of these are in the
Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   Investors such as Advent are attracted not only by the technical
skill of the Israelis, but also by their habits of teamwork and
discipline. Gemini president Ed Mlavsky gives the credit to
Israel's small population and its tradition of mandatory military
service. ``Many of these people get to know and trust each other
very well because they work together, and it's a small country,''
Mlavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Too small, in fact. With a population of fewer than six million,
Israel is simply not a big enough market for the technology it
produces. Shimon Alon, president of Precise Software Solutions Inc.
in Braintree, calls Israel ``the greatest island I've ever known in
my life. It's surrounded either by sea, or by people who don't buy
from you.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Israeli firms are aggressively moving into foreign
markets, with the United States at the top of the list. Alon, who
also serves as president of the New England-Israel Chamber of
Commerce, says there is no point trying to sell in the United
States without having a presence here. ``The success of a company
is its ability to serve its customers,'' he said. ``The majority of
the customers are here in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   While Silicon Valley is America's best-known technology center,
Greater Boston is its most convenient, from an Israeli point of
view. It is a matter of time _ the seven-hour time difference
between Israel and Boston, compared to 10 hours between Israel and
San Jose. It makes for an easier commute by air. More important, it
allows Israeli and American operations to communicate easily by
phone, fax, and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really impossible to have a daily interaction from office
to office when you have a West Coast operation,'' said Israel's
economic consul Habib. A 10 a.m. phone call from Silicon Valley
arrives at 8 p.m. in Israel, well after closing time. But 10 a.m.
in Boston is 5 p.m. in Israel, so the two offices can share
important information without having to wait until the next
business day.
</P>
<P>
   When Indigo N.V., an Israeli maker of digital printing
equipment, decided to come to the United States in 1994, it opened
its first sales and support office in Woburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, being a high-tech company, we wanted to be in a
high-tech area, where we could attract the right people to be with
us,'' said Roger Mattalon, Indigo's president of worldwide sales
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   One ironic attraction of the area is the presence in Bedford of
the US headquarters of another Israeli firm _ Scitex Corp., a world
leader in printing and scanning technology that has been in the US
since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Indigo has about 160 American employees. Many of them are
engineers who work with the company's printing clients to learn
about the ways customers use the firm's products. The information
they gain helps Indigo design its next generation of digital
presses.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston area's reputation as a haven for Israeli tech firms
is attracting still more of them. The New England-Israel Chamber of
Commerce, in cooperation with Massport, operates Market Gateway, a
technology incubation project to help Israeli companies put down
roots in Boston. A number of local firms, including Cambridge-based
Elron Software Inc. and RadView Software Inc. of Lexington, have
graduated from the program, with more firms in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Habib predicts a boom in biotechnology companies in
Israel during the next decade. He figures that these companies will
naturally gravitate to the Boston area, already a center of biotech
research. So the influx of Israeli firms may still have a way to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Said Habib, ``I believe were are in the beginning of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
