<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNING TRIPS GILLETTE SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This wasn't the send-off Al Zeien had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days before Zeien's final appearance as chief executive
presiding over Gillette Co.'s annual meeting, Wall Street gave the
company's stock a beating Tuesday the like of which it hadn't seen
since the 1987 stock market crash.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette shares plunged 7 3/4 to 50, responding to a company
warning about reduced expectations for the first half of 1999 that
had been issued the prior evening. Trading of Gillette stock was
briefly delayed in the morning because a crush of sellers had
created an order imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate problem: Weak sales in Latin Ameria, particularly
Brazil, and disappointing performance in the company's Braun
division will probably cut first-quarter earnings a penny per share
below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The more serious problem: diminished faith that Gillette can
pull off much more important advances in the second half of the
year, when business is expected to increase by 15 percent or more
over year-ago levels by the company's own public estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are no longer confident the company can generate quality
earnings per share growth of 15 to 20 percent'' in the second half
of the year, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst Catherine Lewis
wrote Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations for Gillette stock were reduced by at least
three brokerage analysts before trading began Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette stock has been trading at prices that suggest explosive
growth in the near future, about 64 percent higher than the average
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock when measured in relation to future
earnings forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company's actual business has been
dragging along at a pace that would be generously described as
pokey. It will generate first-quarter sales growth in the ``low
single digits.''
</P>
<P>
   The short analysis of Tuesday's stock activity: Reality got the
better of expectations. The market may have overreacted to some
degree Tuesday, but you couldn't miss the chill of doubt that set
in after Gillette's second performance warning in the last three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Zeien himself has been talking up the return of
historical sales growth rates of 15 to 20 percent for the second
half of the year. He touted a ``tidal wave'' of new products that
would boost business but didn't emphasize that battered results
from the second half of 1998 will make for easier comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Zeien, the manager rightfully credited with building Gillette's
global marketing machine, will retire April 15 at the company's
annual meeting in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette was sticking with its second-half comeback story
Tuesday. Company officials suggested several points of strength,
among them:
</P>
<P>
   --General international improvements. Gillette points to its own
business trends in Asia Pacific as evidence of better news ahead.
In the third quarter of 1998, sales were down 29 percent and gross
profit was off 52 percent compared to the same quarter a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth quarter, year-ago sales were off 11 percent and
gross profits were down 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   --The growing impact of Gillette's Mach3 razor, now clearly seen
as a successful new product. Substantial start-up and production
costs for the Mach3 are coming down this year. Sales of high-margin
blades will also have an increasing impact through 1998. Mach3
blades took a 15.8 percent market share in February and Gillette's
overall piece of the market increased by more than 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   --Expansion of product line and geographic distribution of a new
Ultra line of batteries made by its Duracell unit, which has been a
weak performer recently.
</P>
<P>
   But even analysts who don't take issue with Zeien's growth
forecast doubt it is a good reason to value Gillette stock
substantially higher than that of other companies. Is jumping over
a low bar so impressive, and what do you do the next time around?
</P>
<P>
   ``The second-half numbers last year were so hobbled by
international problems and start-up costs for the Mach3,'' said
Robert Izmirlian of Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. ``Once you get beyond
that, you have to wonder if it's sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette isn't the only global consumer product company with
problems. Coca-Cola Co., for one, has also warned about slower
sales and profits.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for these giant companies to make any handsome
gains in a balky global economy. The question is whether they
should remain darlings of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back on the shelf: Numeric Investors will reopen two funds that
were managed by John Bogle Jr. until he resigned from the
Cambridge, Mass. firm in February. Numeric's $96 million Micro Cap
fund and its $62 million Growth fund will reopen to existing
shareholders on April 19 and to everyone on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   The funds have been closed since 1997, when they reached $100
million in assets. Numeric cited an increased stock market
liquidity and ``moderate'' redemptions connected to Bogle's
departure as reasons to reopen the funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein also be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
