<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENDER-TRAINING-BOS &LR;      04-07 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENDER-TRAINING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG STUDENTS TAUGHT TO TRADE FEELINGS, NOT INSULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abby Alexanian, 10, is trying hard to make the boys in her
fourth-grade class understand. ``We don't all worry about what we
look like,'' she says with a determined frown. Abby looks down at
her dusty brown overalls and then at the scruffily dressed girls
seated beside her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not girlie,'' she adds. ``We like bugs and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   As Abby eagerly demolishes a few of the stereotypes raised by
the boys in her class, it is clear she doesn't think she is asking
too much. But what she and other children in Linda Bowden's class
at Glen Urquhart School in Beverly, Mass. are doing is akin to
tearing down the Great Wall of China.
</P>
<P>
   Under the careful guidance of two behavioral scientists, they
are trying to bridge a cultural gender gap that becomes dangerously
wide by adolescence, giving rise to what many see as a growing
problem of sexual harassment and assault in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The effort comes none too soon. Research confirms that boys and
girls begin to go their separate ways as early as kindergarten or
first grade. Before that age little children often play together
oblivious to gender, but beginning at age 5 or 6, cultural
expectations force boys and girls apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``This enforced separation reaches a crescendo in fourth grade,
where you see very little interaction between boys and girls. By
the time they get back together again in sixth grade, they are
mysteries to each other,'' says Dr. Stephen J. Bergman, a
psychiatrist affiliated with Harvard Medical School. ``That's why
we keep going into lower and lower grades. If we can start at the
beginning, perhaps we can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Bergman and psychologist Janet L. Surrey have
sold a few area schools on a program that teaches boys and girls in
grades 1 to 4 to connect with each other in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that if boys and girls can learn to be friends in
grade school, they may stop harassing each other as adolescents.
And they may even think twice about having sex too soon, says
Surrey, a clinical psychologist with the Stone Center at Wellesley
College.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman and Surrey's program, which they introduced at Glen
Urquhart last month, is built on a series of questions that boys
and girls ask of each other, first in same-sex and then in
opposite-sex groups. It evolved out of thousands of dialogues that
Bergman and Surrey, who are married, had with other couples, work
that resulted in their book, ``We Have to Talk,'' newly out in
paperback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults get stuck in old patterns of behavior that interfere
with new ways of opening up,'' says Bergman, who, under the same
pseudonym, Samuel Shem, is also the author of the cult classic
``The House of God'' and its sequel, ``Mount Misery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the kids seem to get it right away,'' he adds. ``And
what's such a lift is that they really go for it. They really want
to know about each other.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what worries some parents and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   A few have voiced fears that all this togetherness might turn
boys into wimps and girls into tomboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these programs are harmful; they will confuse kids,''
says Marsha Ciccolo, a parent who did not allow her teenage
children to attend health courses at the local public school. ``You
can stand on your head and try to change the fundamental
differences between the sexes, but it won't happen. Men and women
are totally different and you can't try to change the healthy
evolutionary course of things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time constraints are an even bigger stumbling block, teachers
say, especially now with the new standardized testing requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to get any kind of new curriculum in the
schools in Massachusetts, especially with this new testing mania,''
says Nan Stein, a senior researcher at Wellesley College who
created some of the first programs aimed at preventing sexual
harassment in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers at Day Middle School in Newton, Mass., Stein says, who
helped her test her ``Flirting and Hurting'' curriculum in 1993,
``say they would never have time to pilot test any new curriculum
now. They're too busy teaching review courses, all for an imperfect
and arbitrary test.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein's ``Flirting and Hurting'' course is taught in some
Massachusetts middle and high schools. Elements of both Stein's
curriculum and Bergman and Surrey's dialogue are also folded into a
yearlong health course taught to seventh graders at Newton's Day
and Oak Hill middle schools. The only elementary schools
experimenting with similar curriculum are the three Boston-area
private schools working with Bergman and Surrey.
</P>
<P>
   Yet new research shows that the earlier children are exposed to
curriculum that teaches them how to resolve conflict and recognize
each other feelings, the more effective the results. A study in
last month's Archives of Pediatrics and Adolescent Medicine found
that a curriculum targeted at children, parents, and teachers from
first grade through sixth was far more effective in reducing later
levels of violent behavior, heavy drinking, and sexual intercourse
among participants than the same program aimed at older grades.
Participants also achieved better academic performance in later
grades than did other students.
</P>
<P>
   Some educators see an immediate impact as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is just as important as academics,'' said Glen
Urquhart's Bowden. ``When boys and girls can talk to each other, it
makes the atmosphere of the classroom more cohesive and peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Bowden says, her fourth-graders come in from recess
``all grumpy'' and disgruntled over a misunderstanding on the
playground. Recently, a few of the girls in her class tried to join
the boys in a pickup soccer game and some of the boys promptly
walked off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``To just start the class and teach math doesn't serve the kids
very well; they can't concentrate,'' Bowden says. ``It really helps
to take a few minutes and discuss what happened on the soccer
field.''
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue Bergman and Surrey had just introduced to her class
that morning would be a perfect framework in which to do that,
Bowden adds. ``I wish this had happened earlier in the year; it
would have been a great way to start the class off,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Glen Urquhart that morning, Bergman and Surrey had first
separated the 12 boys and 7 girls into same-sex groups and asked
them to write down things they most wanted to understand about the
opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they so, like, picky?'' asked Eric Sherman, 10,
referring to girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picky about what?'' Bergman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picky about their hair, or what they eat; they're always on a
diet.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the girls kept circling around to the same
question, although they asked it in a number of different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do boys taunt and make jokes about girls when they like
them?'' asked one girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are boys so rough?'' asked another.
</P>
<P>
   Why indeed. A growing body of research (and a host of new books
by psychologists from ``Rescuing Our Sons from the Myths of
Boyhood'' to ``Raising Cain'') suggests that boys are ``rough''
because they are forced to disconnect from emotions and
relationships at an early age. Boys aren't supposed to cry, and
instead of being encouraged, as girls are, to reach out to others,
boys are steered toward silence and stoicism.
</P>
<P>
   They learn quickly that if they show their feelings, they may
get pummeled on the playground. And the pressure to be cool and
above any need for connection is reinforced by sexually violent
movies, television shows, video games, and rap songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys understand this part of themselves has to go
underground,'' says Surrey, who helped pioneer the Stone Center
theory that being in relationships with others is crucial to human
development. ``And some boys lose that part of themselves along the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls, on the other hand, learn to value restraint and worship
at the altar of popularity and good looks. That pressure, Surrey
says, can lead to eating disorders and the kind of subtle cruelties
and exclusionary games that preteen girls are famous for.
</P>
<P>
   Such cultural pressures, however, are still faint noise in first
and second grade, if the behavior of 16 6- and 7-year-olds at
Atrium School in Watertown, Mass. one recent morning is any
indication.
</P>
<P>
   The topic is ``connection'' _ what it means to feel connected to
others _ and Bergman and Surrey have spent weeks training the two
Atrium teachers on how to broach the subject, as the first
installment of their four-week program on gender.
</P>
<P>
   The children are already sitting in gender-separated clumps, and
as they begin to throw out examples of when they felt connected, it
is clear who their friends are: children of the same sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel connected to Tom because I can play soccer with him and
I love soccer,'' says one boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I was feeling a little sad, I was missing my mom, and
Briana came over and hugged me; that made me feel better,'' says a
girl.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gender divide, the children have no problem
expressing their feelings for each other.
</P>
<P>
   One boy named Jeremy says, ``I feel really connected to Max and
Evan. Right from our first play date, it was like the happiest
moment. . .'' He starts to cry and rubs his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, one of the teachers confides that up till now, Jeremy
has had problems expressing himself and reaching out to other
children. She sees what happened today as a kind of breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such power in this,'' Bergman later concludes, his
voice tinged with wonder. ``Boys are just as eager as girls to
connect; they just haven't been allowed to do so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
