<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS MAKES PLAYS, NOT HIGHLIGHT REELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There came a point last December, when Dan
Duquette confidently waited for Bernie Williams's agent to call
back to say the Yankees' star had accepted Boston's $90
million-plus offer, that Darren Lewis appeared bound for anywhere
but back in center field for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But when the season opened Monday, Williams was still in
pinstripes, while Lewis remained the center fielder of record for
the Red Sox. He didn't have a good game in the 5-3 win over the
Royals, going hitless in five trips and experiencing a rare failure
in not moving Jose Offerman over from second base with none out in
the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he usually does, Lewis still found a way to contribute.
He made one of his patented sliding catches in short center to take
a hit away from Joe Randa in the third inning. And, as left fielder
Troy O'Leary tells it, his mere presence helped O'Leary make the
day's best defensive play, a sprinting catch of Jermaine Dye's bid
for extra bases, preventing the Royals from roughing up Pedro
Martinez any further in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   No one would argue that the Sox are better off without Williams,
the defending American League batting champion who would have slid
nicely into Mo Vaughn's third spot in the order.
</P>
<P>
   But no one would dispute that Lewis, picked up on the cheap by
Duquette a year ago, has played a vital role in making the Red Sox
a much better team. And it goes beyond his defense, even though the
man did not make an error in center field last season and should
have been recognized with a Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   It's about preparation, dedication, and a knowledge of what it
takes to win. Most of all, it's about consistency. In short, he's
the type of player admired by teammates and managers _ including
his former Giants skipper, Dusty Baker, who over the winter named
his newborn son after Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a flashy-type player,'' Lewis said in a recent
conversation. ``You're not going to notice me if you watch me one
time. But watch me over the course of a season, and you'll see I do
the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Those little things added up to a three-year, $7.1 million deal
for Lewis, who signed last fall before Duquette put on the
full-court press for Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was aware of the Red Sox' interest in Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't faze me, to be honest with you,'' he said. ``I do
whatever is asked of me. I come ready to play. If they wanted me to
play right field, I'll play right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around a while now. I know there's nothing etched in
stone. When you start to believe that, you're setting yourself up
for trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to the Red Sox, Lewis had played for four teams in
three seasons and had lost his status as an everyday player, one
who batted leadoff and won a Gold Glove for the Giants in 1994.
He'd batted just .228 for the White Sox in 1996, and the following
season found himself playing behind a rookie, Mike Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   But after being installed as leadoff man by Jimy Williams last
May when Nomar Garciaparra was switched to cleanup, Lewis set
career highs in hits, average, runs, doubles, and RBIs. He hit .282
as leadoff man, .268 overall, and after tiring in August, when he
hit just .211, finished up by hitting .357 against the Indians in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Vindication?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you always want to prove people wrong,'' he said. ``As
a professional athlete, no matter how long you've been playing,
even if you're 39 years old, you're still trying to prove people
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've stopped doing that, maybe you've lost your edge.
For me, it's been that way ever since I was young.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, with Jose Offerman aboard, Lewis will hit second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not your prototypical leadoff hitter,'' he said. ``As a
No. 2 hitter, I can hit behind the runner, I can take pitches, I
can bunt, I can put the ball in play. I can hit all over the
lineup. To me, thart's a bonus that I offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who holds the major league record for consecutive
errorless chances by a center fielder, wasn't surprised that he
didn't win a Gold Glove; the outfielders honored were Jim Edmonds
of the Angels, Ken Griffey of the Mariners, and Williams. All
splendid fielders, undeniably, with Edmonds and Griffey
highlight-reel regulars.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the record, Griffey and Edmonds made five errors
apiece. Williams made three. Lewis, errorless in 109 games in
center field, made all three of his errors in right field, a
position for which he really doesn't have the arm. Lewis will be
playing when the Red Sox face Royals lefthander Jose Rosado, with
Damon Buford, who played errorless ball in 68 games in the outfield
last season, playing center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the type who's going to promote myself,'' Lewis said.
``It's not my style. It's not my priority. I'm going to show up and
leave everything I have on the field. As long as everybody in this
room respects what I do, that's where I get my gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis used to dress next to Mo Vaughn in the clubhouse and came
to become a great admirer of the first baseman. He keenly feels the
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He meant a lot to us as a group,'' Lewis said. ``We all liked
him and respected him. We all understand that. But it's time for us
to figure out how we're going to compensate for that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Vaughn's leadership was invaluable, Lewis said, that
doesn't mean this team will fall apart without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fear it being a problem when we have so many guys here
who have been in the game for six-plus years,'' he said. ``This is
basically a veteran-oriented ball club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had six or seven young players in the lineup, then I'd
be concerned. But most of the guys in this room know what to do.
They don't need anybody to get in their face.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a need for a whole lot of mentorship in this room.
I know if something needs to be said, somebody will say it. But on
this team, you're not going to have to say too much. Of all the
teams I've played on, this team is the most prepared and ready to
play that I've been around.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Jimy Williams preaches. It's what Darren Lewis
lives.
</P>
<P>
   And that alone is a good enough reason to keep him around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
