<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-07 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS, LEAGUES ADDRESS KOSOVO SITUATION IN DIFFERENT WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the choice is between capitalism and nationalism, Predrag
Mijatovic will place his country first. Mijatovic and five other
players of Serbian descent boycotted games in Spain last week, and
Mijatovic was fined 5 million pesetas ($32,400) by Real Madrid. If
he continues to sit out, Real Madrid has threatened to demote him
to the reserve team, which competes in the second division.
</P>
<P>
   Mijatovic, protesting the conflict in Kosovo, said, ``Players
are not going to play while our relatives can leave their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has caused the postponement of three European
Championship 2000 games, and players in Italy wrote ``Stop Violence
_ Stop War'' on their shirts for Saturday's games. The 11
Yugoslavian players in Italy wore black armbands.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one Italian legislator agreed with the German
Bundesliga ban on signs of protest, saying that if players did not
perform for their inflated salaries they should return to their
homeland, where the economy might be as healthy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   History lesson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though advancements toward big-time soccer in the US are
perceived as almost spontaneous, they in fact are part of an
evolution. In fact, the origins of club soccer in the US predate
those of most of the world's powers, including World Cup champions
Argentina, Brazil, France, and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the professional game has prospered only sporadically in the
US, because of a variety of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer is the latest attempt to inculcate the game
in the professional sports culture of America. MLS is a successor
to the North American Soccer League, which folded in 1985, and both
were preceded by the subject of Colin Jose's book, ``American
Soccer League 1921-1931/The Golden Years of American Soccer''
(Scarecrow Press).
</P>
<P>
   While it lasted, the ASL ``grew into a league of international
renown, a league which sent shock waves around the soccer world,''
according to Jose, a historian for the Soccer Hall of Fame in
Oneonta, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Like the MLS and NASL, the league was well-financed, by
prominent industrialists such as Horace Edgar Lewis of Bethlehem
Steel Co. and William Madison Wood of American Woolen Co., plus
entrepreneurs such as Samuel Mark, who lent his money and name to
the Fall River Marksmen, baseball's Horace Stoneham, and A.G. Wood
of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Mark constructed the first US stadium specifically designed for
professional soccer, predating the Columbus Crew's by about 75
years. Mark's Stadium had a capacity of 15,500 and was located in
North Tiverton, R.I., to avoid Massachusetts Blue Law restrictions
on Sunday games.
</P>
<P>
   The ASL's power base was in New England, which was predictable
since the first soccer club in the Western Hemisphere, Oneida FC,
was founded in Boston in 1862.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century, thousands of workers were moving to
the Eastern Seaboard, and many were top-class soccer players
seeking opportunities outside Britain's maximum-wage system. Player
movement was rare between countries, and Alec McNab shocked
observers when he left Greenock Morton's 1922 Scottish Cup-winning
team to join the Boston WonderWorkers. McNab tripled his earnings
to $25 a week and became the ASL's premier attraction, the Pele of
his time, according to Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1925, the offsides rule required three opposition players
to be between the goal and the attacker receiving a pass, but this
hardly discouraged ASL offenses. Archie Stark set an all-time first
division world record with 67 goals for Bethlehem Steel in the
1924-25 season, the last before the offsides rule was changed.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 2,000 ASL players were mostly foreign-born, the
league's high standards elicited the best in US players. The ASL's
top three scorers were US players: Stark, Johnny Nelson, and Davie
Brown. And, in 1930, Fall River's Bert Patenaude scored the World
Cup's first hat trick as the US defeated Paraguay, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The ASL's imaginative, moneyed owners and promoters had cause
for optimism. Their game had roots in the culture, there was a
tremendous influx of immigration that seemed tailor-made to
perpetuate soccer's growth, and there were not many competing
professional sports. The ASL had accomplished American players,
exotic foreigners, high-scoring teams, and seemed on the verge of
challenging baseball's popularity or at least providing a
high-profile, viable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   But the ASL's decline was rapid, as bureaucratic crises weakened
the league, then the Wall Street crash brought down the industrial
sponsors and their teams, reducing the league to semiprofessional
status through 1983. The current A League is a descendent of the
1990 merger of the ASL and Western League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the greatest testimony to the standard of play in the
ASL in those years was produced by the US national team, which
reached the semifinal of the World Cup in 1930,'' Jose writes.
``These were known as the `Golden Years' of soccer in the US, years
when the game seemed to have a bright future, both as a spectator
and participation sport. Great players such as Gonsalves,
Patenaude, and Stark, had they played in the mainstream of European
soccer, would have achieved international acclaim, but they chose
to live and play in the US.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zenga takes honor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's Walter Zenga was named MLS player of the week
after leading the team to a 1-0 win at Kansas City Saturday. Zenga
becomes the first player-coach to win the MLS honor . . . The
Revolution claimed striker Tony Kuhn on waivers from the Chicago
Fire . . . Midfielder Leighton O'Brien, waived by the Revolution
last week, was clamed by San Jose. O'Brien is the son of Fran
O'Brien, formerly of the Philadelphia Fury, Manchester City, and
the Republic of Ireland national team . . . Tickets for the
Revolution's July 21 exhibition against four-time European champion
Ajax are available.
</P>
</TEXT>
