<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-MARKETING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID PEGS COMEBACK TO MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ After years of stagnant sales and steep
losses, Polaroid Corp. is finally rolling out new instant
photography products that could determine whether the company can
shake off its decade-long slump.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the first time in more than five years that Polaroid
will have significant consumer products to launch, is a pivotal one
for the fallen instant photography giant. It's betting on a trio of
new cameras named PopShots, JoyCam, and PocketCam, all under $30
and aimed at a new generation of consumers _ preteens, teenagers
and young adults, many of whom would be new to instant photography.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year Polaroid has to break out of its no-growth
pattern,'' says Robert Stern, photography analyst at Merrill Lynch
Global Securities. ``These new products give (it) that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics say the products may be too little, too late.
Analysts wonder whether Polaroid's offerings may end up as novelty
items without staying power. And even if Polaroid's cameras are
winners, they may not be enough to fix the company's fundamental
problem: competitors eating away at Polaroid's once invincible
dominance in instant photography.
</P>
<P>
   The new cameras are a hallmark of Polaroid chief executive Gary
T. DiCamillo, a marketing expert hired in December 1995 from Black
&AMP; Decker to turn the Cambridge company around. His strategy: Focus
anew on Polaroid's core consumer photography business, repackage
existing technology, emphasize marketing, and come up with modest
product hits rather than bet-the-ranch initiatives. DiCamillo last
year said the company planned to introduce 20 to 30 products over
four years.
</P>
<P>
   DiCamillo's approach is a departure _ some would say a comedown
_ from the 62-year-old company's legacy of world-beating
engineering and pioneering products.
</P>
<P>
   In its golden era from the 1970s through early 1980s, under
founder Edwin Land and his immediate successors, Polaroid
flourished with a wide range of cameras and film for consumers and
industry _ all built on technological innovation, memorable
television advertising, and ironclad patent protection.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1990s have not been kind to Polaroid. The rise of new
technologies _ one-hour color film processing, single-use cameras
from competitors, videotape camcorders, and digital cameras _ have
drastically changed the world of photography. Not only are there
more choices for capturing images, but the total cost for each
picture has dropped substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to keep up, Polaroid has seen its annual sales stuck at
$2 billion since 1991. Last year, revenue fell 14 percent to $1.85
billion, the lowest since 1988. The company has lost money five out
of the last 10 years, including $359 million in red ink in the last
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Polaroid has made more headlines for laying off
nearly 3,000 people and closing manufacturing plants than for
delivering innovative products.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who bought Polaroid shares at $48 each in January
1996, a month after DiCamillo joined the company, have seen the
stock plunge to 17 a share in January. It closed Thursday at 19
15/16, down 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been watching Polaroid gradually circle the drain for
years,'' says B. Alex Henderson, photography analyst at Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, under DiCamillo, Polaroid aims to reach a new generation of
instant photography buyers by repackaging some existing camera and
film products, rather than developing products based on major new
technical innovations. That's a departure from the approach of the
Edwin Land generation of Polaroid leaders, who made heavy bets on
new products using advanced technology developed internally.
</P>
<P>
   In a contrast to such technology-driven management, DiCamillo
has brought in a team of consumer marketing executives such as
Jerry Noonan, a former marketing executive from Nabisco Holdings
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid's trio of new, inexpensive cameras aimed at the young
exemplify the new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going after markets that were never exploited by
Polaroid,'' says Noonan.
</P>
<P>
   To reach its youthful prospects, Polaroid is looking to sell
some camera and film products through toy retailers like Toys ``R''
Us and FAO Schwarz. Polaroid is also expanding sales of its
products through convenience stores, pharmacies, mass
merchandisers, and such discounters as Kmart, Wal-Mart, and BJ's
Wholesale Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are developing a new photography category for the retail
toy market, where stores like Toys `R' Us sell certain cameras and
film aimed at kids. Right now there is not much in photography for
9 to 14 year olds,'' notes Noonan, senior vice president of
worldwide marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, PopShots, the first of Polaroid's new cameras,
debuted on retail shelves. It's the company's first single-use
camera and is expected to compete against disposable cameras from
Kodak and Fuji that use 35-millimeter color film.
</P>
<P>
   PopShots is a 10-picture instant camera and film combination
that sells for $19.95 and includes a flash. A stiff tug on a yellow
ring removes the print, which takes about three minutes to develop.
Polaroid also offers a $4 rebate when the PopShots plastic camera
is sent back to the company for recycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``PopShots sales were slow until we advertised it to our members
and then it took off,'' says Michael Atkinson, vice president of
divisional merchandising at BJ's.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics note that Polaroid is late to the disposable camera
game. Other single-use cameras have been on the market for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid also plans to introduce a reusable version of PopShots
this fall. Called the JoyCam, it will cost $24.99 plus $9 per film
pack. It's a low-end camera targeted to young adults that uses the
same film as PopShots.
</P>
<P>
   In its boldest move to grab young consumers, Polaroid will
introduce its pocket-sized, instant camera called PocketCam this
summer to American markets. Aimed at children and teenagers, some
models feature cartoon characters, such as Tweety Bird and the
Tasmanian Devil, licensed from Warner Brothers. Polaroid has also
licensed Barbie from Mattel; the doll's image will appear on the
PocketCam, which comes with an attached folding mirror and
heart-shaped picture frame.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $24.99 including a six-picture film pack, PocketCam
takes up to 12 images, each the size of a large postage stamp. In
the fall, Polaroid will market a second PocketCam film pack that
turns out adhesive photos, which can be stuck on like decals.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid says the PocketCam has been a huge success in Japan,
where it was launched last year. The firm has sold 100,000 cameras
there, primarily to girls taking photos of their classmates and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Stern of Merrill Lynch expects Polaroid to sell $75 million
worth of PocketCam cameras and film worldwide this year. He expects
JoyCam will generate about $40 million in sales this year. PopShots
along with non-instant photography products should do about $50
million, he estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of new cameras and film could bring $130 million
to $165 million in critically needed new revenue to Polaroid this
year, rising to around $250 million annually in 2000, according to
several analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The new products, say analysts, should lift Polaroid to
profitability this year after four years of losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, Polaroid has the products to give them top-line
growth,'' says Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Polaroid's bet on the youth market has risks. It remains
unclear whether PocketCam's popularity in Japan can be duplicated
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Polaroid really want to bet on the purchasing habits and
whims of 13-year-old Japanese girls?'' asks Henderson of Prudential
Securities. ``Polaroid is playing in the toy business that is
hits-driven, where you can be hot as a pistol one day and ice cold
the next.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, critics say, Polaroid has been slow in launching
these products. They point to the company's show-and-tell
extravaganza in New York in February 1998, when it announced the
trio of new cameras. At the time, the company said that PocketCam
and PopShots would reach the nation's retail shelves during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They never did.
</P>
<P>
   And because of cost pressures, the company has indefinitely
shelved plans to create a combination camera that produces instant
photos and 35-millimeter negatives and another combination camera
that yields instant photos along with digitally stored images.
</P>
<P>
   While DiCamillo has received mixed reviews for Polaroid's
product initiatives, he has received high marks from Wall Street
for cutting costs and focusing more tightly on consumer markets.
The Polaroid chief, whose five-year employment contract expires in
November 2000, is shrinking the company to about 8,500 employees
worldwide _ from more than 11,000 when he took over and 21,000 in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   To keep costs down, the company makes virtually all new instant
camera and film products in China and other low-wage countries _ a
move that has prompted Polaroid to close some Massachusetts
production facilities. In another streamlining move, the company
left its longtime corporate home in Kendall Square for a
Polaroid-owned building on Memorial Drive that had been mothballed.
</P>
<P>
   And Polaroid is so focused on consumer photography these days
that it is looking to shed four of its businesses _ sunglasses,
polarizer filters for sunglasses, holography products, and graphic
arts equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Land launched the company back in 1937 with the polarizer
technology that he had invented. If Polaroid sheds the polarizer
business that had been its foundation, it truly will have wandered
far from its roots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
