<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-GRACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A COMEDY WORTH A SERIOUS LAUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The last few television seasons have not been
kind to sitcoms. With their predictable insert-joke-here moments
and embarrassing laugh tracks, sitcoms have not been kind to
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing the state of the sitcom has been as pressing in the TV
business as fixing the Y2K bug has been to the world. But along the
way dramas improved _ ``ER,'' ``The Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal,''
``The Sopranos.'' Then reality programs nearly ruined television,
taking us on a painful, circuitous detour from which we have yet to
return. And the few great sitcoms _ ``Seinfeld,'' ``The Larry
Sanders Show,'' ``The Simpsons'' _ joined a handful of good sitcoms
to distract networks from the urgency of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Sitcom writing was bad. Period. For the most part, it's still
bad. This made thin, toss-off shows that were merely cute _ like
``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' _ seem like strokes of inspiration. Never mind
that faded, past-their-prime offerings like ``Mad About You'' and
``Home Improvement'' sustained themselves in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   So many live-action sitcoms have come and gone _ or in the case
of ``Veronica's Closet'' and ``Jesse'' should be gone _ that it's
difficult to even dream of something consistently witty, like a new
``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there is one: ``Will &AMP; Grace.'' More miraculously, it's
on NBC, the network that did more damage by spinning off hordes of
lousy cookie-cutter sitcoms than good by having several classics
like ``Frasier'' and ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a network so clueless as to quality comedy that it can't
stop shifting the few good ones it has around the dial, effectively
bleeding audience along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is a gem. Call it a miracle because, true to
fashion, NBC put it on Monday night (surrounded by lameness), then
moved it to Tuesday night before finally settling on its new night
_ Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' has a loyal core. It's fairly regularly found
in the Nielsen Top 20. But it ought to be in the Top 10 or better,
given that it's one of the few sitcoms going these days that seems
infused with smart humor, pop culture savvy and a ridiculously high
percentage of payoff punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   In short _ finally, the next great sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is about two best friends, the gay (but not
obvious) Will (Eric McCormack) and the straight (and desperate)
Grace (Debra Messing). Theirs is a great friendship, a perfect
foundation for a relationship except for that one slight problem.
The writers have managed to make this coupling not only very funny
but touching as well, difficult territory in a sitcom that _
rightly so _ emphasizes put-downs over pouting.
</P>
<P>
   The characters click thanks to the obvious chemistry of
McCormack and Messing. But the cast is fleshed out in terrific
fashion by Will's gay friend Jack (Sean Hayes) and Grace's sassy
co-worker Karen (Megan Mullally).
</P>
<P>
   To know how strong this cast is you only have to imagine that
both Hayes and Mullally could _ and probably will someday _ have
spinoff shows. Without McCormack and Messing's acting strengths,
those other two would be scene stealers.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, that's a spritely foursome and each gets enough lines
to enliven the full 22 minutes. No amount of overstatement can tell
you how rare non-stop good writing is on sitcoms. Only the
curiously maligned ``Friends'' continues to have that level of
sustained quality.
</P>
<P>
   To sit back and quote line after line of ``Will &AMP; Grace''
dialogue would do a disservice not only to how well the jokes were
delivered but also to how effectively they rock the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   This freshman series is not yet in the league of a ``Seinfeld''
or ``Larry Sanders'' or ``Simpsons.'' But it will be on Thursdays
for the foreseeable future _ at least until the finale, May 13 _
and if NBC has any sense, for next season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
