<HEADLINE>
ROVING AMBASSADORS TO HIT SEATTLE STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVEN GOLDSMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Forty roving ``ambassadors'' will welcome tourists _
and try to keep street people from bothering them _ under a major
new program to make downtown Seattle more visitor-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown property owners will pay more than $3 million a year
for the program that includes the ambassadors, 24 graffiti removers
and sidewalk sweepers as well as other workers to spruce up
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Already approved by property owners and likely to win Seattle
City Council OK, the Downtown Business Improvement Area could be
operating by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The program will replace three smaller districts and also cover,
for the first time, downtown's high-rise midsection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be new strength in unification,'' said Kate Joncas,
president of the Downtown Seattle Association, which will run the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after similar operations in Portland, Ore., Baltimore
and Philadelphia, Seattle's program aims to put visitors and local
shoppers at ease in the urban streetscape.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassadors won't be police officers but will wear
distinctive uniforms, Joncas said. They can give tourists a smile
and a map, then steer a homeless, addicted or mentally ill person
to a social agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking through downtown Seattle can be a challenging
experience,'' says the new program's business plan. ``While some
blocks are clean and secure, others are poorly maintained and
become locations for criminal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Jan Drago, a strong advocate for the larger
improvement area, said the roving ambassadors will be a bit like
hotel concierges who can guide visitors through unfamiliar terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a particularly friendly presence on the street,'' said
Drago, who has made several trips to study Portland's program.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerald Sheehan, legislative director of the American Civil
Liberties Association, said the program should write guidelines for
the ambassadors to avoid stepping on individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan said city officials were overly zealous in keeping
dissenters out of view during the 1992 Asia-Pacific Economic
Conference hosted by Seattle, and he worries the new downtown
ambassadors could contribute to such an atmosphere when the World
Trade Organization gathers here in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we're definitely interested in knowing more
about,'' Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Less controversial are the crews to scour sidewalks every day.
The city now cleans downtown streets but not sidewalks. The workers
also will paint over graffiti and monitor eyesores such as grimy
alleys, burned-out street lights and overflowing trash bins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
