<HEADLINE>
WNBA FILLS EXPANSION DRAFT SPOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nykesha Sales finally has some teammates, but when they will
begin their season has suddenly been thrown into doubt.
</P>
<P>
   As the first player assigned to the Orlando Miracle, the former
University of Connecticut star has been the entire team since last
September. Thanks to Tuesday's WNBA expansion draft, the former
University of Connecticut star will soon be joined by Brandy Reed
(from the Phoenix Mercury), Kisha Ford (New York Liberty), Yolanda
Moore (Houston Comets), and Adrienne Johnson (Cleveland Rockers).
</P>
<P>
   On the other expansion team, the Minnesota Lynx, assigned player
Kristin Folkl has new teammates in Andrea Congreaves (Charlotte
Sting), Kim Williams (Utah Starzz), Octavia Blue (Los Angeles
Sparks), and Adia Barnes (Sacramento Monarchs).
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a labor dispute, the scheduled start of the
league's third season on June 10 is in question.
</P>
<P>
   According to the players' union, the league has set Saturday as
the deadline for a contract agreement. The players reportedly want
a minimum salary of $45,000 for the three-month summer season,
while the WNBA is proposing $20,000, although the league says its
total compensation package is worth $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is getting short,'' WNBA president Val Ackerman told USA
Today. ``We are committed to our players . . . but we are a
start-up business.''
</P>
<P>
   Also a point of contention: the number of players from the
now-defunct American Basketball League who will be allowed into the
WNBA. The league says 52, and wants to expand rosters to
accommodate them; the union says 24 and that players who opted for
the WNBA in the first place should not be shortchanged in the
aftermath of the ABL's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming it goes off as scheduled, the regular draft on April 27
would include the former ABL players as well as foreign players and
those coming out of college.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIT senior is exemplary &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Pierce, a senior at the Rochester Institute of
Technology who has worked in soup kitchens, babysat for families
who couldn't afford to pay, and counseled children with learning
disabilities, was presented with the 1999 Hockey Humanitarian Award
last weekend at the NCAA Division 1 men's championship. Pierce, who
missed her freshman season while battling Hodgkin's disease, is
from Mendon, N.Y. Since 1996, the award foundation, based in
Randolph, has honored one collegiate hockey player each year who
``best exemplifies the qualities of character, sportsmanship, and
devotion to the game and to the community.'' Sara Nelson, a native
of Hanover, N.H., and senior forward at Dartmouth, was among the
five finalists . . . The Avon Running Global Women's Circuit,
launched last year and directed by Kathrine Switzer, will stage its
first Global Championship 10K on May 22 in New York as part of the
27-year-old all-women's ``mini marathon'' that had been sponsored
by Legg's and then Advil before Avon took over last year. About
8,000 runners are expected, with $50,000 in prize money going to
the top 15 overall finishers and top three master's finishers. The
champions of 12 Avon races last year will be brought to the event,
which will also likely draw many other top-ranked athletes. The
circuit will conduct 29 races in 12 countries this year; the
closest to Boston is Hartford on July 10. For more information or
an application, see the website at www.avonrunning.com or call
212-282-5350 . . . Among the 76 girls' sports programs awarded $500
from the 1999 Grants for Girls program were the Boys and Girls Club
of Chicopee (tennis), the Waterville Area Boys and Girls Club YMCA
in Maine (volleyball), Girls Incorporated of N.H. (climbing), and
the Girl Scouts of Rhode Island Inc. (softball). The grants are
supported by Procter &AMP; Gamble, private donors, and the Women's
Sports Foundation . . . Billie Jean King will receive an honorary
degree next month from the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
