<HEADLINE>
NORMAN HAS NEW PERSPECTIVE ON THE MASTER'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Greg Norman seemed content as the 63d Masters
approached, content with his life and the inactivity following
shoulder surgery he had shortly after last year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked,'' he said, ``if I had a magic wand to wave, what
would I change? I'd change nothing right now. It's a great
reflection on the way my life is right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want things to keep going the way they are. I'm very
happy. I enjoy the way I'm hitting the golf ball. I know it's a
matter of time before I'll get back to the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to force it. I'm very easy about things. I'm very
relaxed. I want things to evolve. One thing I realized is golf is
not everything. There's nothing out there I enjoy doing more than
golf, and I think basically that's come out in the last 12 months
and why I am the way I am now. I don't have a sense of urgency
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman has been a dominant force in the game ever since he left
his Australian homeland and joined the US PGA Tour on a regular
basis in 1984, but he has been noted as much for the majors that
slipped away from him as for the two British Opens he has won. Just
three years ago, he saw a six-shot lead on Nick Faldo dissipate in
the final round of the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   That was the unkindest cut of all. Forget that he'd been beaten
by Bob Tway's holed-out bunker shot in the 1986 PGA Championship,
that Larry Mize had holed out from off the green to beat him on the
second hole of a playoff in the 1987 Masters, forget that he lost a
playoff to Fuzzy Zoeller in the 1984 US Open at Winged Foot, that
Marc Calcavecchia beat him in a playoff at the 1989 British Open at
Royal Troon, and that Paul Azinger beat him in a playoff at the
1993 PGA Chammpionship at Inverness.
</P>
<P>
   Norman also has been No. 1 in the world, has won 18 times on the
PGA Tour, and has 56 international victories. He's still the Great
White Shark, a dominant personality who has earned millions outside
the game through business interests and stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Though he says he has found inner peace, he still has a desire
to excel. ``It's not like it was when in my 20s the 30s, the
urgency to do it,'' he said. ``It's not the way it was 12 months
ago. I enjoy it so much more this way. I'm more in balance.''
</P>
<P>
   He still burns to win the Masters, and to that end he has worked
intensely with swing guru David Leadbetter. ``We're trying to
perfect my golf swing,'' said Norman, who has made three
appearances on the PGA Tour this year _ the World Match Play
Championships (second round), Doral (joint 19th), and The Players
Championship (missed cut). He withdrew from the BellSouth Classic
in Atlanta last week when he came down with a stomach virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was just happy to go through the motions, I wouldn't be
out there hitting balls Tuesday in 85-degree heat,'' he said. ``I
wouldn't spend hours with David Leadbetter. That's the other side
that's still there. You still want to do well, because you are a
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go out on the first tee of the Masters this week,
and nothing would give me greater pleasure than sitting up here (in
the press building) talking to you again in a happy environment,
not like it was a couple of years ago. I still feel that. You guys
will be the first to know when it's time to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   The drive to win still lurks within, especially at the Masters
and in the majors. ``Maybe I wanted to win this tournament too
much, but it's because of my nature,'' he said. ``I'm a very
forceful, hard-driven individual within myself. If I wasn't that
way, I wouldn't be sitting here today. Everybody's got a different
makeup. I'm a triple A personality. I might be a quadruple A
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found the right equation to get myself to where I want to
be. Sometimes that can be a little detrimental to you, and
sometimes it can be a great asset. In this situation with the
Masters, as much as you want it, sometimes you get it and sometimes
you don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I never get this golf tournament, there still wouldn't be a
golf tournament on this planet I can say I've enjoyed more than
this one. I've taken a lot of great things out of the Masters. If I
stopped this and it was my last tournament and I didn't win it, I'd
say the Masters had a great stamp on my life and how my life turned
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
