<SLUG> BC-MIDSHIPMAN-SEX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPULSION FROM NAVAL ACADEMY PENDING AGAINST TEXAS MIDSHIPMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Birk Billingsley's first love was the U.S.
Naval Academy, and his second, more recent, love was a freshman in
his squad.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 22-year-old Texan's affair with the academy could be
nearing an end because he broke the rules by having an ``unduly
familiar'' relationship with Kristina Shiroma, an underclassman,
also from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been expelled from the academy, 25 days before
Billingsley was to graduate. Their expulsions are pending approval
by the Office of the Secretary of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake. There's really no excuse for my actions _ I
fell in love,'' said Billingsley, of Dublin. But, he added, ``I
really don't think what I did warrants my expulsion from the
academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Billingsley, who was Shiroma's squad leader, could have to
repay $93,000 for his education or enlist for three years,
``neither of which are too appealing to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appalled because others that committed actions that were
far more egregious'' have not been expelled, Billingsley said in a
telephone interview yesterday from his mother's home in Paris,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Billingsley, who was a 1995 graduate of Dublin High School and a
straight-A student, said he and Shiroma, of Richardson, were
intimate but did not have sexual intercourse. He pleaded guilty to
sexual misconduct, fraternization and failure to maintain a proper
relationship with a plebe, and Shiroma pleaded guilty to similar
charges.
</P>
<P>
   They are not the first to be disciplined for sexual misconduct
or fraternization at the Naval Academy, where midshipmen are not
allowed to engage in sexual relations on campus or have a romantic
involvement with a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Four midshipmen were expelled this year, and five were expelled
last year, said Cmdr. Mike Brady, a Naval Academy spokesman, who
noted that the recommendations, including the one concerning
Billingsley, await approval by the Office of the Secretary of the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   But other midshipmen who have had sex or romantic relationships
with freshmen have not been expelled, said Billingsley's attorney,
Bill Ferris, a Naval Academy graduate. Some midshipmen who had sex
with freshmen off campus have not been expelled; others have been
expelled for much less intimate behavior, Ferris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is applied arbitrarily and capriciously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferris cited last year's case involving Navy quarterback Chris
McCoy, who was accused of having sex off campus with a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The freshman, who was also accused of having sex with two other
midshipmen on campus, was expelled, but McCoy wasn't, said Ferris,
who represented the freshman in the decision review process.
</P>
<P>
   And last fall, in an incident similar to Billingsley's, senior
Colin Gallagher had a relationship with a plebe who he'd requested
be placed in his squad, Ferris states in documents relating to
Billingsley's decision review process.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was expelled in that case, Ferris states in the
document.
</P>
<P>
   But each case will be handled differently because ``sexual
misconduct includes a wide range of prohibited behavior,'' Brady
said. ``It's wrong to assume that every case should be handled
identically.''
</P>
<P>
   And after Vice Adm. John R. Ryan assumed command as the
academy's superintendent in June, he met with all midshipmen last
fall and told them he was placing a ``bubble'' around all freshmen
and insisted on ``only professional relationships between plebe and
upperclassmen,'' according to a transcript of Ryan's speech that
Brady provided.
</P>
<P>
   Billingsley, who has studied astronautical engineering, said he
plans to apply to Stanford, Purdue and Georgia Tech to finish
college.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he and his attorney are hoping that the Office
of the Secretary of the Navy will review the decision and reinstate
Billingsley.
</P>
<P>
   Billingsley, who in high school was senior class president and
active in the honor society, said he's dreamed of graduating from
the academy since he was a child, and hoped to one day become an
astronaut. His experience at the academy has ``been great up to
this point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go back,'' Billingsley said. ``I love that school
and what it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
