<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
McCAIN'S POLITICAL STOCK RISES AS BOMBS FALL &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Until two weeks ago, Sen. John McCain of Arizona
was just one in a large field of likely Republican presidential
candidates struggling for recognition.
</P>
<P>
   But what a difference a war makes.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States and its allies have pounded Yugoslavia, the
former Vietnam War pilot and prisoner of war has seen his political
stock rise.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old Naval Academy graduate has been much in demand
on the national media circuit because of his military background
and foreign policy experience in the Senate, where he serves on the
Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the airstrikes, McCain put on hold his presidential
announcement scheduled for Tuesday. But he has gained more exposure
from talking about the strikes than his political plans.
</P>
<P>
   In one day, he appeared on all of the major television networks,
where he was almost always introduced as a former POW.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a guest on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' and
``Crossfire'' and ABC's ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Serbs captured three U.S. soldiers last week, it was
McCain whom the media sought to talk about his five-year ordeal in
a North Vietnamese prisoner-of-war camp.
</P>
<P>
   McCain advised the administration not to let the capture of
soldiers affect its military strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Ensuring more publicity, McCain joined Defense Secretary William
Cohen on a visit Wednesday to Aviano Air Force Base in Italy, where
the United States is launching its flights over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's stance on Kosovo is both critical of the Clinton
administration and at odds with the isolationist-leaning faction of
his own party.
</P>
<P>
   The senator blasted the White House for what he termed its
failure to articulate a strategy or endgame for the Yugoslavia
operation.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has broken with many of his Republican colleagues by
endorsing not only a strong air campaign but sending ground troops
into Kosovo as well.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his presidential ambition was not a factor in his
decision to speak out for strong military action in Kosovo. He
noted that he had been equally assertive about military campaigns
during the Persian Gulf War and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spoken out on these issues and have some credibility
for many years now,'' he said. ``I have not considered them in the
context of a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator also said there is a downside to backing heavy U.S.
military action abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I take a position where I advocate the president not rule
out the use of ground troops, I take a responsibility for any
casualties that may occur,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has postponed his formal presidential announcement,
McCain said, ``I am running.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, some political observers agree the military conflict
has helped McCain to stand out among the large GOP presidential
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings a weight and gravity to these matters that many of
the other candidates just can't match,'' said Steve Duprey,
chairman of the New Hampshire Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Duprey said foreign policy will likely be a bigger issue in 2000
than it has been in the past two elections because of Kosovo and
the Chinese spy scandal. But he doubted that foreign policy
expertise alone would allow McCain to ``break out of the pack,''
unless he spends more time in primary states talking about other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Polls consistently rank McCain well behind Gov. George W. Bush
and Elizabeth Hanford Dole.
</P>
<P>
   David Hill, a Houston-based Republican consultant, said McCain
may not be doing himself that much good because voters already are
familiar with his military record.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't know, Hill contended, is where McCain stands on
a host of domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it adds a lot to him. It doesn't round him
out,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   The boom for McCain may quickly die out when the conflict ends,
as former President Bush found out when his successes in the 1991
Gulf War did not help him win re-election more than a year later.
</P>
<P>
   For now, McCain clearly has been able to stand out from his
rivals as he effectively uses his platform in the Senate to
articulate a war strategy.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's strength on the issue may underscore the foreign policy
weaknesses of some of his opponents _ particularly Gov. Bush, whose
belated response to the crisis was criticized as tentative and
vague.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who served in the Texas Air National Guard, did not
publicly respond to the Kosovo matter until several days after the
bombing started and only after he consulted with his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he supported the airstrikes but said the
administration needed to develop an exit strategy. The governor
also said, ``If the mission is to win, all options ought to be
available to military planners.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said criticism of the governor has
been ``unjustified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when American lives are at stake is not the time for
political leaders to be grandstanding and second-guessing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle, the former vice president who served in the Indiana
National Guard during the Vietnam War, has criticized the Kosovo
mission and opposes the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who has supported the Clinton administration's policy in
Kosovo, was not eligible for combat duty because of her gender.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, who has opposed the Kosovo mission, did not serve
in the military because of rheumatoid arthritis. Magazine mogul
Steve Forbes, who has supported airstrikes but not ground troops,
served for six months in the New Jersey National Guard.
Conservative activist Gary Bauer, who has opposed the military
operation, did not serve because of college and law school draft
deferments.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, who has opposed the Kosovo
operation, served one year in Vietnam in the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore served one year
in Vietnam as an army journalist. Former New Jersey senator Bill
Bradley, who has criticized the U.S. mission in Kosovo, was in the
Air Force reserve from 1967 to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
