<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9134 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAA-Y2KTEST-TEX     04-07 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-Y2KTEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT WILL TEST FAA READINESS FOR YEAR 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When midnight rolls around Dec. 31, Federal Aviation
Administration chief Jane Garvey will be flying from Washington,
D.C., to Los Angeles, convinced that the agency's Y2K problems are
solved and that her plane won't crash into another because of a
computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   But just to make sure, Garvey will be in Denver this weekend as
the FAA conducts its first test to see whether its air traffic
control radar system is Year 2000-compatible.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. Saturday, the FAA will set its Denver air traffic
control clock forward to 10 p.m., Dec. 31, 1999, and fly one of its
planes on a four-hour loop around Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey won't be on the plane. She will be watching the radar
screens at Denver International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's going to be a nonevent, like Samuel Beckett
wrote in his novel Murphy: `The sun shone, having no alternative,
on the nothing new,''' said Paul Takemoto, the FAA's Y2K spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're spending millions of dollars on Y2K fixes to make sure
nothing happens on Jan. 1, that it's just another day like any
other day,'' he said. ``We're getting nothing new for our money,
just making sure we continue the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Denver test is above and beyond the individual systems tests
that the FAA is conducting on each of its computers nationwide, and
will be the first to track an aircraft in flight as the clock
changes from 1999 to 2000, said John Clabes, the FAA's Southwest
Region spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the FAA, we have 638 computer systems, and 425 of them are
considered mission critical,'' he said. ``Of the 425, we found that
151 needed to be renovated to avoid Y2K problems, and all of this
work is now scheduled to be completed by June 30.''
</P>
<P>
   As the FAA works to make sure all of its systems are go for
midnight Dec. 31, Dallas/Fort Worth Airport likewise is well into
its computer revisions to ensure a smooth transition into 2000,
said Jeff Fegan, Dallas/Fort Worth Airport's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have allocated $10 million to Y2K fixes, and we're on
schedule to have everything finished in September,'' he said. ``I'm
confident we will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem evolved from the practice of using only two
digits to designate the year in most computers. Y2K experts say
that means many computers will read the year 2000 as 00, and
interpret it as 1900 instead of 2000. Such a glitch could cause
many computers to shut down, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's major concern is tracking and control of aircraft in
flight, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver test won't affect any aircraft in the air at the
time, because the computers being tested _ at the Terminal Radar
Approach Control center that serves a 65-mile radius around Denver
_ are capable of being split into two separate-but-equal operating
systems, Takemoto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll leave one half of the system on real time for the
controllers to use, and we'll turn the clock ahead on the other
half to test for Y2K compliance,'' he said. ``Controllers won't be
using the half that we have set to Dec. 31.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, that half will be monitored by a huge staff of FAA
engineers and computer experts, as well as by Garvey and Ray Long,
director of the FAA's Y2K Program Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The VIP list for the test is pretty long,'' Takemoto said.
``We'll have airline people, air traffic controllers union people,
all kinds of people on hand to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   An FAA test plane _ a Learjet based in Oklahoma City _ will take
off from the Grand Junction, Colo., airport shortly after 10 p.m.,
fly to Denver and land, then fly to Colorado Springs, where it will
touch down just before the test period ends, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the test, 3 a.m. CDT, Garvey and Long will address
worldwide media representatives who also will be on hand but who
won't be allowed in the control room during the test.
</P>
<P>
   At the agency's Southwest Region headquarters in Fort Worth, Air
Traffic Manager Doug Murphy said he is convinced that the test will
show that the FAA has the Y2K problem under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 is on its way. We're going to be ready, people
are going to climb onto airplanes, and it's going to be as safe and
efficient as ever,'' he said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the FAA's Southwest Region, which encompasses Arkansas,
Louisiana, New Mexico, Oklahoma and Texas, ``We're in great
shape,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for pilots and passengers, because the FAA's
Terminal Radar Approach Control center at D/FW Airport is the
nation's busiest, airport officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the separate computers operated by the D/FW Airport
Board don't control aircraft in flight, there are systems under
D/FW's purview that operate essential services such as runway and
taxiway lights, emergency fire and medical services, terminal
heating and lighting, the interterminal train system, the parking
control system, and automated employee access to secure areas of
the airport, Fegan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 108 computer systems we identified that required some
form of action, and we're now at 72 percent complete,'' he said.
``We feel very comfortable we will be in good shape come Jan. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
