r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-07 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHALL I TAKE MYSELF OUT TO THE MINOR LEAGUES?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'd been figuring that the hard-core baseball boycotters had
washed their hands of me and that the nonboycotters were tired of
my ambivalence _ to boycott or not to boycott, that is the question
_ and so I wasn't counting on much of a response to last week's
pre-season baseball column.
</P>
<P>
   It was definitely a pleasant surprise when I received a
supportive e-mail from a reader who shares my love/disgust
relationship with big-league baseball. The message came from a
longtime baseball fan by the name of Kirby Stiening:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Norfolk Virginian-Pilot printed your column on baseball
today, and I wanted to express my appreciation for your sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Pittsburgh in the '50s when the Pirates were a
joke, but that didn't keep me from going to Forbes Field and
sitting in the left-field bleachers. The 1960 World Series was
probably the highlight of my baseball days. I have not attended a
Major League Baseball game in over 30 years and have watched as the
game was transformed from the national pastime to just another
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have an alternative way for you to maintain your boycott
while still watching old-time baseball. It's the minor-league
games. For under $10 I can see the Tidewater Tides from a better
seat than I ever saw Roberto Clemente, and the air is filled with a
spirit of family fun.''
</P>
<P>
   They are a breed apart, these baseball fans who grew up cheering
the exploits of all-time greats such as Clemente, Stan Musial of
the St. Louis Cardinals, Willie Mays of the New York/San Francisco
Giants, Mickey Mantle of the New York Yankees _ players who played
for the love of the game in an era when only the biggest stars
pulled down annual salaries in excess of $100,000, and when a
ballplayer never would have dreamed of charging a fan for an
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   One day during my deluded youth, I insisted that my mother take
me to a ribbon-cutting or some such event where Musial was the
featured celebrity. When he drove away, we followed him until he
had to stop at a red light _ at which point I jumped out of the
car, knocked on the window of his Cadillac and breathlessly
implored: ``Mr. Musial, could I please have your autograph?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me as if he thought I might be mentally deranged,
but he signed without so much as a grunt of irritation, and I've
been singing his praises ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine what would happen if a kid ran up to ... oh,
let's say, Albert Belle while the Baltimore Orioles star was
waiting for a traffic light to change and asked him for an
autograph?
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, let's not imagine; the possibilities are too
gruesome.
</P>
<P>
   If the Orioles are paying Belle $65 million over five years, how
much would a Musial or a Clemente pull down in today's market?
Belle drives in plenty of runs, that's for sure, but the Cardinals
and Pirates never had to worry about their star player attacking a
fan or a photographer; those guys would be worth $65 million for
good citizenship alone.
</P>
<P>
   As a Pirates fan, Kirby Stiening no doubt treasures the memory
of that 1960 World Series more than a Cardinals fan who stayed up
till the wee hours one late-season night to watch Musial beat
Pittsburgh with an extra-inning homer. But who could forget Bill
Mazeroski's seventh-game, ninth-inning home run that edged the
Yankees, 10-9, to give the Pirates their first world championship
since 1925?
</P>
<P>
   And what about Mazeroski, arguably the best defensive second
baseman in baseball history? What would he be worth to a modern-day
team that pays millions to bench warmers?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball doesn't like to say so, but its loyal and
long-suffering fans are picking up the tab for those outrageous
paychecks in the form of exorbitant prices for game admissions,
parking, concessions and licensed products such as caps and
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I'm staying away. I'll skip the minor-league games
as well because I'm worried that my $10 will work its way up to the
big-league affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The onetime pastime gets no dough from me. None.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
