<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-PHOTOS08-COX     04-07 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-PHOTOS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAVELING PHOTO EXHIBIT SHOWS DIVERSITY OF AMERICAN HISPANICS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New images of American life color the walls of the
Smithsonian Institution: photographs of astronauts, doctors, altar
boys, fishermen, White House staffers, soccer players and
ballerinas.
</P>
<P>
   All Hispanic-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we are. We're black. We're white. We're brown.
We're Asian. We're mixed. We're Catholic. We're Jew. We're
Protestant. We are everything that everyone is,'' said actor Edward
James Olmos, who developed a multimedia project documenting the
diverse experience of the nation's Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The photographic exhibit _ ``Americanos: Latino Life in the
United States'' _ opened Wednesday at the Smithsonian's National
Museum of American History.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which includes 120 photographs organized around
themes such as family, community, education and sports, will become
the largest traveling photo exhibit in the history of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   After September, it will travel to the Museum of the City of New
York and to the Eiteljorg Museum in Indianapolis early next year.
It is already booked through 2003, including stops in Houston and
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an honor and a real privilege to be standing here in the
Smithsonian Institution in this manner ... almost unbelievable,''
Olmos said at a news conference. Holding up a book of pictures from
the exhibit, he went from page to page, stating repeatedly, ``This
is an American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are images of people that have been here since the
existence of the human species in the Western Hemisphere,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Olmos said the exhibit is of major importance because Hispanics
are under-represented in the history, media and arts of American
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this to be the very first exhibit of its kind to get to
this level is a disaster. We are not talking about 1899, we're
talking about 1999,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The work of 30 photographers includes powerful portraits such as
the one of Bernadine Mendoza, wearing a Gap T-shirt and a gold
cross, sewing a new American flag in a Houston factory.
</P>
<P>
   Others, non-political but still dramatic, capture warm and
intriguing moments such as a bespectacled 8-year-old Carolina
Bernal gazing seriously at a chess board in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Olmos plans to visit San Antonio and Houston this month to
promote other parts of the multimedia project, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ A book of photographs from the exhibit published by Little,
Brown and Co. The book includes an introduction by Carlos Fuentes,
considered Mexico's leading novelist.
</P>
<P>
   _ A television documentary that will debut on HBO this fall. It
features a series of short profiles of American Hispanics,
including the San Diego writers and performers known as the Taco
Shop Poets and a Mexican-born agent of the U.S. Border Patrol who
apprehends illegal aliens for a living.
</P>
<P>
   _ The release of a CD of Latin artists representing a wide range
of music, including the tejano sounds of Flaco Jimenez, the classic
salsa of Celia Cruz and the Latin jazz of Tito Puente.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-PHOTOS08-COX     04-07 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-PHOTOS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRAVELING PHOTO EXHIBIT SHOWS DIVERSITY OF AMERICAN HISPANICS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
