<P>
   Olmos said the exhibit is of major importance because Hispanics
are under-represented in the history, media and arts of American
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this to be the very first exhibit of its kind to get to
this level is a disaster. We are not talking about 1899, we're
talking about 1999,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The work of 30 photographers includes powerful portraits such as
the one of Bernadine Mendoza, wearing a Gap T-shirt and a gold
cross, sewing a new American flag in a Houston factory.
</P>
<P>
   Others, non-political but still dramatic, capture warm and
intriguing moments such as a bespectacled 8-year-old Carolina
Bernal gazing seriously at a chess board in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Olmos plans to visit San Antonio and Houston this month to
promote other parts of the multimedia project, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ A book of photographs from the exhibit published by Little,
Brown and Co. The book includes an introduction by Carlos Fuentes,
considered Mexico's leading novelist.
</P>
<P>
   _ A television documentary that will debut on HBO this fall. It
features a series of short profiles of American Hispanics,
including the San Diego writers and performers known as the Taco
Shop Poets and a Mexican-born agent of the U.S. Border Patrol who
apprehends illegal aliens for a living.
</P>
<P>
   _ The release of a CD of Latin artists representing a wide range
of music, including the tejano sounds of Flaco Jimenez, the classic
salsa of Celia Cruz and the Latin jazz of Tito Puente.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
