<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSULIN-INHALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSULIN INHALATOR IN FINAL TESTING STAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY RICHTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A California company is in the final stages of
testing a device that would allow diabetics to administer daily
insulin doses through an inhalator rather than syringes.
</P>
<P>
   The device and the process for preparing inhalable insulin are
in the third stage of testing required for approval from the Food
and Drug Administration. If approved, the product could become
commercially available in three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Inhale Therapeutic Systems Inc. of San Carlos, Calif., is
developing the device that could drastically ease the routine
millions of diabetics no go through to take insulin shots.
</P>
<P>
   Insulin is used to treat diabetes, a chronic disorder that
results when the pancreas either stops producing insulin or
produces insufficient amounts to process glucose (sugar), which the
body uses for energy. Diabetes can lead to blindness, kidney
damage, heart disease or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Some 10.3 million Americans have been diagnosed with diabetes,
according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta, and millions more have undiagnosed diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Although some diabetics can control their condition with diet
and oral medications, 3.5 million must inject insulin several times
a day for optimum control, according to a research report by Inhale
Therapeutic Systems.
</P>
<P>
   However, many diabetics don't follow that regimen because of the
discomfort and inconvenience, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since insulin was first used to treat diabetes in the
1920s, scientists have been looking for alternatives to injection,
said Robert Chess, an executive with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Insulin isn't effective in pill form because the digestive
system breaks down the drug before it reaches the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   When Inhale Therapeutic Systems co-founder John Patton worked at
Genentech in the 1980s, he and his colleagues were looking for
alternatives to injection and discovered that the lungs' deepest
tissues readily absorbed insulin's molecules into the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech, a South San Francisco company, decided not to pursue
the concept. In 1990, Patton left Genentech and started Inhale
Therapeutic Systems.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge was to get the insulin delivered deep enough into
the lungs, which can't be done with inhalators like those used for
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Insulin presents an additional challenge because its molecules
are large and fragile, which makes it difficult to slip past the
natural barriers that protect the lungs from foreign substances,
Chess said.
</P>
<P>
   Inhale Therapeutic Systems developed four primary technologies
to solve the problems:
</P>
<P>
   _ Powder processing, which converts insulin molecules into tiny
particles that are small enough to reach the bottom of the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glass stabilization, which keeps the powder stable at room
temperature for a year or more, eliminating the need to refrigerate
the insulin.
</P>
<P>
   _ A powder-filling technique for measuring individual doses into
blister packs.
</P>
<P>
   _ A device that can deliver the drug into the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Working in partnership with New York-based Pfizer Inc. and
Hoechst Marion Roussel of Germany, Inhale Therapeutic Systems has
begun the third and final phase of clinical testing for inhaled
insulin. Trial studies have shown that the device delivers insulin
as effectively as an injection, Chess said.
</P>
<P>
   Inhale Therapeutic Systems has joined with other companies to
develop inhaled delivery for a variety of drugs, including
treatments for multiple sclerosis, osteoporosis, asthma, genetic
emphysema and lung ailments. The company also is seeking partners
to develop inhalable drugs for hepatitis, blood clotting disorders
and infertility, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA already has approved some of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Once the inhalable drugs are approved, the drug companies market
them. Inhale Therapeutic Systems will make its money by
manufacturing the powders, supplying the inhalators and receiving
royalties from sales of the drug in inhalable form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-SOMMELIER-HNS &LR;      04-07 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-SOMMELIER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMMELIER WITH TASTE FOR BEER DEFIES STUFFY STEREOTYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With SOMMELIER-PICKS)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTERTOWN, N.Y. _ If Brian Sweeney wasn't so unfailingly
polite, he might get edgy answering questions about his age. He
hears them often enough, almost every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you be a wine expert?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How old are you, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, are you sure you're old enough to drink?''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney realizes diners at Friends Lake Inn, in the Adirondack
Mountains community of Chestertown, aren't trying to insult him
with these questions. A bundle of energy with a boyish smile, he
is, after all, a mere 29 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the stereotype of a sommelier _ a stuffy,
nose-in-the-air man who took decades to accumulate a wealth of
knowledge about wine _ and it's easy to understand why Sweeney is
the recipient of so many good-natured comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people ask me in jest if I'm old enough to drink, and
people have asked me where I got my experience,'' he noted.
``Nobody's ever insulting. They're making jokes and I get a good
laugh out of it. The nice thing for me is, people are always
guessing I'm six, seven, eight years younger than I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it, though: Sweeney knows wine. The
central New Jersey native has completed both the introductory and
advanced courses at the highly regarded Sterling School of Service
&AMP; Hospitality in California's Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   This month he continues his formal training with a two-day
program in Hyde Park, put on by the Court of Master Sommeliers,
with his long-range goal to reach master sommelier status. Passing
muster with this London-based organization is akin to being given
the key to the Holy Grail.
</P>
<P>
   There are approximately 100 master sommeliers throughout the
world, and a mere three dozen in the United States. Which means
Brian Sweeney has sipped and savored and spat out an amazing amount
of wine in a relatively short time.
</P>
<P>
   He was not raised to drink wine with dinner, and developed his
keen interest in wine only after graduating from Rider College in
Lawrenceville, N.J. His degree was in finance and he was heading to
Colorado to be a ski bum. He was a beer guy, really. In fact,
Sweeney makes his own beer at home and appreciates a tasty pint.
But while working as a server at a classy steakhouse in Summit
County, Colo., he was introduced to wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The restaurant had a small wine list, but had some pretty
decent wines on it. The owner wanted the servers to be more
knowledgeable, and he had us attend a wine tasting lunch with
different wines to go with each course,'' Sweeney recalled. ``It
was my first introduction to fine wine and how to pair it up with
food, and I really fell in love with it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past two years he has been at Friends Lake Inn, and it's
hard to imagine a better place for an oenophile to expand his
knowledge. The inn, off the beaten path in the southern
Adirondacks, has, since it opened 15 years ago, developed a
well-deserved reputation for having an extensive wine list.
</P>
<P>
   Innkeeper Sharon Taylor figures her wine cellar has more than
16,000 bottles featuring about 2,200 varieties, give or take a
couple dozen. The inn's wine list received grand award status from
Wine Spectator magazine in 1997, making it one of 94 eateries in
the world to be so recognized. That year, 339 restaurants submitted
their wine list to the magazine, and only five were selected.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, familiar with the inn because his parents have a summer
home not far away, met Taylor and was enchanted with the
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   His wife had just completed training at veterinary school and
found a job nearby. He went to work for Taylor, thinking he might
work all sections of the inn, including the kitchen, with an eye
toward being a general manager. But Sweeney has never made it out
of the wine cellar, so to speak, and within six months was named
sommelier. He is also the inn's cheese expert, or frommagier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian's terrific,'' Taylor said. ``He's very personable and
does a great job. He really knows wine and he loves wine and I
think our guests appreciate his enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney doesn't try to push wine. Each table and each guest is
different, he explained. ``The first question I usually ask is red
or white, as well as what price range they want to be in,'' he
said. ``I try to find out if they're interested in having something
that will pair well with their meal, or if they're looking for wine
that's good on its own. One of the great things about wine is that
it's all individualistic tastes. Everybody's palates are different
and you drink what you enjoy drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to find what style they are looking for before we get
into subtleties. If I find the guest is getting a little
uncomfortable with the questions, I try to narrow it down in a
hurry. Other people are more than happy to spend five-plus minutes
going through every detail of the wine. It all depends. Every guest
is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who loves all styles of wines, is anything but a wine
snob. And prices don't always denote quality, he believes. Said
Sweeney: ``I've had some awful, awful $300 bottles of wine _
fortunately I didn't have to pay for them. I've also had some
terrific wines from the $10 range.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He prefers red Burgundies, he admits, after pausing to consider
his many favorites. Hearty-style wines with earthy flavors,
particularly Cote du Nuits varieties from the northern part of
Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the highlights of his job is sneaking down to the wine
cellar with Taylor's husband, Greg Taylor, after all the guests _
and Sharon _ have called it a night. There, Sweeney and Taylor, a
regional manager for a Manhattan-based fine wine import company,
will spend as much time choosing and debating which bottle to open
as they will actually drinking from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Brian's palate is really maturing,'' Greg Taylor
observed. ``What happens with a lot of younger wine tasters is that
they like a lot of bigger, bolder wines. Then their palate gets
into more esoteric wines and they start to discern the more finite
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian's moving into that zone where he's discovering little
esoteric flavors, and it's neat to watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
