<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS &LR;      04-07 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SULTAN OF SWOOSH SMILES IN THE FACE OF COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Hello, world. Surely you earthlings remember
Tiger Woods. He announced his arrival into professional golf with
enough fanfare to make a royal wedding look like a quickie Las
Vegas ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   And give him credit.
</P>
<P>
   The Sultan of Swoosh hit the ground running so fast, the
competition looked like it had been issued cement shoes. Seasoned
professionals stumbled like amateurs. He won the Masters when he
was 21. By 12 shots. It was the fifth victory _ and only the 18th
start _ of his professional career.
</P>
<P>
   He's 23 now, and the PGA Tour hasn't gotten around to renaming
itself Tigeria. Tiger Woods may still be the biggest name in golf,
but David Duval arrived at Augusta National for the 1999 Masters
with the most serious game.
</P>
<P>
   Duval has rocketed to the No. 1 ranking in the world with four
victories this year. He has won 11 times in his past 34
tournaments. Woods is No. 2. He has won three times since his 1997
Masters victory, which had fellow players wondering aloud about how
to Tiger-proof Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool,'' Woods said. ``No. 2? Actually, it's fine. It's one of
those things that's all cyclical. Everybody's going to have their
runs. David's having his run right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cool? An all-too-California-cool shrug from the same guy who,
after a runner-up finish in the 10th tournament of his professional
career, groused, ``Second sucks''?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that Earl Woods was boasting that his
son would make more of a mark on the world than Jackie Robinson,
Muhammad Ali, Nelson Mandela and Gandhi. Either Tiger can't stand
to admit how much it galls him to be a distant second to anybody,
or he has learned that he can't possibly live up to the those sorts
of standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it bother him? Probably, yes,'' said 1998 Masters
champion and Woods confidant Mark O'Meara. ``He wants to be the
man. David wants to be the man. Let's face it: In today's era of
unbelievably talented, deep fields, to win the amount of events
(Duval) has won is phenomenal. So is there a little bit of rivalry
between Tiger and David? Yeah, probably.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods made little secret of his ambition to impose a new world
order on the PGA Tour. He lined up $60 million in endorsements
before he took is first professional swing and starred in an ad
campaign that billed him as a man for all colors and creeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played a lot of golf with Tiger Woods; I've seen what he
can do,'' O'Meara said. ``In my stints after playing with all the
greats that have played, to me he has got the most talent of any
player I've seen. That doesn't necessarily mean he's going to win
every single tournament. He hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Woods has only himself to blame. His emergence was a
form of shock therapy that jolted his fellow competitors out of any
complacent urges they may have had.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tiger came out we were faced with the options of
improving if we wanted to compete,'' Duval said, ``or relegating
ourselves to finishing second.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval became a workout warrior, losing 35 pounds. Others headed
for the weight room or began spending more time at the driving
range and the putting greens. Woods still keeps himself in the hunt
more often than not. He just doesn't land his prey as easily as he
did when his competition stood around gawking at his sublime blend
of power and control.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won once _ at the Buick Invitational _ in eight starts
this year. He has finished second once, third once and fifth twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually having more fun,'' Woods said. ``I'm having so
much fun out there that it's actually pretty scary, because I
understand how things work. I understand a lot more about the tour,
about myself. And it's a beautiful thing right now, because I
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say that I look like I'm not having fun out there
playing because I'm not smiling. Well, I'm focused. I'm trying to
win. And you can't always smile when you're trying to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, being No. 2 doesn't seem so much like stepping in No.
2. Woods insists he is a better, more consistent player than he was
when he won the PGA Tour Player of the Year award in 1997. He
doesn't take so many chances. He is less prone to the double- and
triple-bogeys that have undermined him in majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you one thing: It's a lot easier to come to
tournaments and not have to do a mandatory press conference every
day,'' Woods said. ``Now David's doing that, and he can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Woods couldn't resist immediately adding, ``You know,
people still recognize me the same. It's just because my figure, my
persona, is on different products where people can see it in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, in other words, wants people to remember he's still the
biggest star in the golfing galaxy. For all of Duval's recent
string of successes, none of them includes a victory in a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Tiger being too far from David Duval right now,''
said Fred Couples, the 1992 Masters winner. ``Pete Sampras has been
No. 1 in tennis for six or seven straight years. If David Duval can
do that, then No. 1 will be a big deal. Tiger Woods can do
anything, you know. David Duval can do anything also.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval is 27 and fresh off of consecutive victories at The
Players Championship and the BellSouth Classic. He is the first
player in a quarter of a century to arrive at Augusta with four
victories for the season already in pocket. His response to the
arrival of the Sultan of Swoosh has been loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, world. Now it's Tiger Woods' move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing better, no doubt about it,'' Woods said. ``But I
like my chances, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
