<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Awaken your senses: Take a fresh look at seasons
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We are fortunate in America to have access to an
unprecedented variety of food choices. During any season,
supermarkets that are the envy of the world are brimming with a
seemingly endless bounty of produce, and the variety of prepared
and processed selections appears limitless.
</P>
<P>
   There may, however, be a drawback to all this choice and
convenience. With unlimited access to all foods all the time, we
risk losing touch with or at least failing to appreciate the ebb
and flow of the seasons and therefore dull our senses to some of
the richness of life.
</P>
<P>
   The life-affirming and tonic effect of eating locally grown
foods of the season is at risk of being lost, especially among
young people who are increasingly absorbed in technology and whose
diet year-round may consist only of frozen, processed and fast
foods. You know we're in trouble when so many people think that
pink, tasteless circle they find in a fast-food sandwich is
actually a slice of tomato.
</P>
<P>
   One effective way to balance the pace of 21st century life is in
the kitchen. By becoming more aware of what is available at local
markets and at least occasionally preparing family meals with foods
that celebrate and capture the vitality of the season, we can pass
on this increasingly tenuous but basic connection to nature.
</P>
<P>
   Searching the Internet for ``seasonal eating'' produced a wealth
of sites, some with helpful advice on how to incorporate seasonal
cooking into your routine and many with wonderful recipes
incorporating seasonal foods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At ``Seasonal Eating Tips,'' 144.92.121.151
</P>
<P>
   /vicdon/tips.htm, you will learn that in 1973, 21 cents of every
food dollar was spent on manufactured foods. In 1987, it was 41
cents. Today it approaches 90 cents. Produced by a farmers market
cooperative, the site also tells us that while seasonal eating
demands more thought, commitment and active participation on the
part of the home cook, the rewards are great. A number of helpful
tips may help you adjust your cooking habits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To familiarize yourself with what's available at local farmers
markets and roadside stands in every state, see
www.ams.usda.gov/farmersmarkets
</P>
<P>
   /map.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At /marketreport.com/ you will find seasonal eating tips, the
freshest seasonal produce coming out of California, information
about farmers markets nationwide and favorite seasonal recipes from
leading chefs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  homearts.com/depts/food/47calef1.htm provides lovely essays on
seasonal foods and recipes by the month.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.mccormick.com/recipe.nsf
</P>
<P>
   /Seasonal+Recipes?OpenView&AMP;Start &QC; 1
</P>
<P>
   &AMP;Count &QC; 200&AMP;Expand &QC; 44 offers menus and recipes for all seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, these sites focus on the foods of spring:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See internet.epicurean.com/latest
</P>
<P>
   /current/greens/leaves.html for a guide to greens.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For spring food recipes, see www.chatelaine
</P>
<P>
   .com/read/food+recipes/greens.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  detnews.com/1998/food/9804/29/04280034
</P>
<P>
   .htm is another choice.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Savory Greens Spread on Bread Rounds
</P>
<P>
   Makes 32 pieces Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: about
15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In southern Sicily one finds tasty and rather thick, doughy
impanatas filled with greens and a multitude of other things,
including raisins, capers, anchovies and cheese. Cookbook author
Paula Wolfert says that when juicy black olives are added, the
result is too heavy. So she developed this recipe using the
ingredients for a spread for bread.
</P>
<P>
   2pounds fresh spinach, escarole or Swiss chard, or a combination
(see note)
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1garlic clove, peeled and lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4flat anchovy fillets, drained and crushed with a fork
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salted capers, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chopped pitted purple or black olives (7 or 8 kalamatas)
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon seedless black or yellow raisins,
</P>
<P>
   soaked in warm water, drained, dried and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon hot red pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   32grilled or fried rounds ( 1/2 inch thick) of Italian or French
bread
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup coarsely grated Provolone or Caciocavallo cheese,
optional
</P>
<P>
   Wash greens until water runs clear. Remove stems, stalks and any
tough leaves; drain. Cook greens 10 minutes in boiling salted
water; drain, refresh in cold water, drain again and squeeze
thoroughly. (Or cook in microwave: Place in covered dish with a few
tablespoons water and cook on high until tender. Drain thoroughly
and squeeze dry.) Makes 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   In a small skillet, fry garlic in olive oil until lightly
browned; remove garlic and discard.
</P>
<P>
   Add greens to oil and fry 1 minute, stirring. Add anchovies and
capers and cook, stirring, 30 seconds longer. Remove the mixture to
a work surface. Allow to cool. Add olives, raisins and pepper
flakes and chop fine by hand or in a food processor. Cover and
refrigerate if preparing in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the mixture evenly and pile it onto bread rounds.
Sprinkle them with cheese and run under the broiler to glaze. Serve
warm or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Mix greens or use just one type.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid frozen spinach, which doesn't have enough taste.
</P>
<P>
   Drop greens by handfuls into lots of boiling salted water, then
keep water at full boil throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without optional cheese): 51 calories, 2 grams
protein, 1 gram fat (percent calories from fat, 26), 8 grams
carbohydrates, less than 1 milligram cholesterol, 127 milligrams
sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Asparagus Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 17-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Once you have tasted roasted asparagus, you will never want to
eat it any other way. The taste seems to be intensified by the dry
heat of the oven. Shavings of Parmesan cheese are the crowning
glory, but for a less rich variation, they can be omitted.
</P>
<P>
   1bunch asparagus (about 1 pound), rinsed and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1small piece (about 2 ounces) Parmigiano-Reggiano or Parmesan
cheese, shaved or shredded
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 400 degrees. Arrange asparagus in a 13-by-9-inch
baking dish. Drizzle with oil and toss to coat. Bake 12 to 15
minutes or until tender. Remove from the oven. Top with cheese.
Return to oven and bake just until cheese melts, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 107 calories, 7 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 61), 5 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 229 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
