<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-MONET-RECIPES08-     04-07 1834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MONET-RECIPES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A springtime menu worthy of Monet puts accent on fresh
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Perhaps it was all that free-flowing creativity. Or
maybe it was the mere matter of wanting to enjoy the success he'd
long fought for. But Monet had a predilection for overindulgence.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, makes a masterful host. When it came to food,
Monet would spare no expense, though often what he needed could be
found on his estate or in his kitchen garden. The key to his food
was fine, fresh ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   We perused ``Monet's Table: The Cooking Journals of Claude
Monet'' for a spring menu and found some gems, starting with
stuffed onions that will be a great way to showcase spring
Vidalias.
</P>
<P>
   Then we suggest mussels with fresh herbs, followed by a main
course of steak marinated in mustard and roasted wild mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a salad of greens dressed with an olive oil and white
wine vinaigrette, and if you want to mimic Monet, add heavy doses
of salt and pepper. For the finale, the famous apple tart.
</P>
<P>
   While we know Monet always entertained at lunch, we also know
that few of us have such an opportunity these days. The menu we
present here would work well as either lunch or dinner, with some
adjustment to portion sizes (4-ounce steaks at lunch instead of
8-ounce, perhaps). All the recipes can be doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Monet had a staff. Most of us don't. So remember to work into
your entertaining plan the fact that the mussels and the steak need
to be prepared shortly before serving. When I tested this menu, I
bedecked my kitchen table with lovely flowers and served the first
two courses there. That way I could cook and visit with my guests
at the same time. We moved into the dining room for the main course
and dessert. In warmer weather, I'd serve the whole thing on my
screened porch _ in keeping with Monet's penchant for dining
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH OR APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Lyses' Stuffed White Onions
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 45 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Monet loved getting recipes from friends, as is the case with
these onions, which came from Charlotte Lyses, a very popular
actress in Monet's time. These will be divine with spring Vidalias
and a nice new version to add to your favorite ways to stuff the
Georgia orbs. I roasted chicken livers in a shallow roasting pan,
then finely chopped them; for the herbs, I used dried thyme and
oregano. If the mixture is a little stiff, add a dab of Dijon
mustard.
</P>
<P>
   4 large white onions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ground cooked roast pork, chicken or calf liver
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dried mixed herbs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Gruyere cheese, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 hard-cooked egg
</P>
<P>
   Cut 1/2 inch off the tops of the onions. Blanch the onions by
putting them in boiling water to cover and cooking for 30 minutes.
Drain and cool. (Or put onions in a microwavable dish and cook for
7-10 minutes, until soft.)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Scoop out the center of each onion,
leaving about a 1/2-inch wall. Combine the ground cooked meat with
the chives, dried mixed herbs and half the grated cheese. Mash the
egg yolk and chop the white; combine with the rest of the mixture.
Stuff the onions with the mixture, mounding it slightly. Place
stuffed onions in a greased roasting pan and sprinkle with the rest
of the grated Gruyere cheese. Bake 30 minutes or until cheese is
lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 221 calories, 19 grams protein, 9 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 18 grams carbohydrates, 337
milligrams cholesterol, 91 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Mussels With Fresh Herbs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time:
15-18 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Monet loved cooking seasonally, so feel free to use fresh herbs
that are most available to flavor the mussels. Chervil is coming
into season, but if you can't find it, use the feathery tops of
fennel. Sorrel also is available in the spring, but you can
substitute the juice of one lemon. If you want to serve this as an
appetizer or second course, you can get by with three dozen.
</P>
<P>
   48 large mussels (about 5 pints)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 ribs celery
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chervil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sorrel
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch, sifted
</P>
<P>
   Wash the mussels well in lots of cold water. Discard any that
are not tightly closed or that are broken. Put them in a deep pot
with half the butter and with the onion, parsley sprigs, salt,
pepper and celery. Cover and cook over high heat for about 10
minutes, shaking the pot vigorously from time to time, until the
shells open. Discard any that are still closed. Drain the mussels
in a colander, reserving the cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   In a skillet, melt the rest of the butter and add the chervil,
sorrel, chopped parsley and tarragon. Add the cooking liquid from
the mussels and the wine. Add the broth and cornstarch, stirring
until smooth. Reheat the mussels in the sauce. If desired, the
mussels may be shelled before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 323 calories, 25 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 19 grams carbohydrates, 78
milligrams cholesterol, 1,067 milligrams sodium, 6 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Monet's Recipe for Cepes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 40
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Though Monet loved food and collecting recipes, this is the only
one that in his journals he claims to be truly his own. The artist
absolutely loved wild mushrooms and would organize hunts,
especially for morels. You can select among the many varieties of
mushrooms available now in grocery stores to make your mixture.
Most of us are used to sauteing mushrooms, but here they are
roasted, which complements the woody flavors.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound cepes (wild mushrooms)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Wipe and gently clean the cepes.
Discard the tip of the stem and chop the stems finely with a knife,
leaving the caps whole. (Or you may choose to simply cook the
mushrooms whole.) Arrange the stems in a shallow ovenproof dish and
lay the caps on top of them. Sprinkle with the olive oil. Bake for
20 minutes, or until the oil is transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the garlic and parsley. Remove the cepes from the oven
and sprinkle the garlic mixture over them. Season with salt and
pepper. Bake for another 20 minutes, basting at least twice with
the liquid in the dish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 121 calories, 3 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 80), 6 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 303 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Steak With Mustard
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 serving
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes Standing time: 2 hours Cooking time:
7-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a beautifully simple recipe that can be multiplied by
the number of guests. If you are planning a luncheon, you may want
to go with smaller cuts, about 4 ounces. I used a smooth Dijon
mustard, which created a thin crust when cooked in an iron skillet.
</P>
<P>
   1 filet steak (about 8 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Spread both sides of the steak with the mustard, and let stand 2
hours. Melt butter in a skillet or steak pan and saute the steak on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 517 calories, 52 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 4 grams carbohydrates, 174
milligrams cholesterol, 936 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Tarte Tatin (Apple Tart)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Resting time: 1 hour Cooking time:
45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This now-famous recipe was developed by the sisters Tatin, who
owned an inn not far from Giverny, and Monet reportedly loved to
visit and partake of this simple but elegant apple tart. This is
far less sweet than some apple pies and tarts, but the pure flavors
are a delight, especially with a scoop of vanilla or caramel ice
cream.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons confectioners' sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsalted butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   6 small apples, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   Pour the flour into a bowl, make a well in the center and into
it put half the sugar, the salt, egg yolk and 1/2 cup warm water.
Mix well. Add half the butter pieces. Mix the dough until smooth,
then roll it out into a rectangle. Fold up the rectangle by folding
one-third toward the center, then folding the remaining third over
the top of the folded part. Cover with a damp cloth and let it rest
for 1 hour. Roll out the dough again into a circle 1/4 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Arrange apple slices in a deep pie
dish. Add the rest of the butter pieces and sprinkle with the rest
of the confectioners' sugar. Cover with the dough. Bake for 45
minutes. Turn the tart out onto a plate so that the apples are on
top.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 388 calories, 4 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 41 grams carbohydrates, 88
milligrams cholesterol, 153 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO SEE MONET'S PAINTINGS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What: ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European
Museums'';
</P>
<P>
   ``Monet &AMP; Bazille: A Collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturdays-Wednesdays; 10 a.m.-9 p.m.
Thursdays and Fridays. Through May 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: High Museum of Art, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cost: Admission $5-$15, depending on age and viewing times.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: Woodruff Arts Center box office, Ticketmaster
outlets; by phone, 404-733-5000 or 404-817-8700; or online at
www.high.org, www.ticketmaster.com or www.impressionism.org.
</P>
<P>
   AND WHERE TO SAMPLE MONET-INSPIRED DISHES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What: ``Monet's Table'' tasting luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: 11:30 a.m.-2 p.m. Saturdays-Sundays. Through May 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: Atrium terrace of Park 75 restaurant, Four Seasons
Hotel, 75 14th St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cost: $19; $30 with VIP ticket to the High Museum of Art
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Menu: Moules au Vert (Mussels With Fresh Herbs) or Gratin de
Champignons aux Pate de Pommes de Terre (Baked Field Mushrooms With
Potato Pie); Chevreuil au Cynorhodons (Venison With Rosehips) or
Filets de Sole a la Florentine; Souffle aux Marrons (Chestnut
Souffle.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reservations: 404-253-3840.
</P>
<P>
   An artful menu
</P>
<P>
   The menu on this page is from ``Monet's Table.'' It includes:
Charlotte Lyses' Stuffed White Onions
</P>
<P>
   Mussels With Fresh Herbs
</P>
<P>
   Steak With Mustard
</P>
<P>
   Monet's Recipe for Cepes
</P>
<P>
   Green salad with vinaigrette dressing
</P>
<P>
   Crusty bread
</P>
<P>
   Tarte Tatin (Apple Tart)
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
