<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-MONET08-COX     04-07 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MONET08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Menu by Monet: Painter's passion for gardens is recorded not
only on canvas but in a book that celebrates the artist's love of
food
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For artist Claude Monet, the garden was a fertile
source of inspiration. He rose early each day to capture such
subtle moments as the lavender light of dawn caressing the
waterlilies in the pond.
</P>
<P>
   And he worked late in the afternoon to record with his oil
paints how the afternoon sun colored the blossoms of the plum
trees.
</P>
<P>
   But Monet found more than inspiration for his canvas from the
garden; he found inspiration for his kitchen as well. And as the
artist became more successful, his penchant for entertaining fellow
artists and friends with the finest seasonal foods flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Menus, recipes and photographs from such celebrations have been
preserved in ``Monet's Table: The Cooking Journals of Claude
Monet'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $34.50), which has been restocked in
many area bookstores in conjunction with a 60-painting exhibit of
impressionist works at the High Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Monet paintings, including ``Plum Trees in Blossom''
(1879), are included in the exhibit, which will be at the High
until May 16. Art lovers can dine on a Monet-inspired luncheon menu
at Park 75, at the Four Seasons Hotel just around the corner from
the High. Or to truly experience a slice of life from Monet's
fabled French estate, re-create a Monet meal at home with the menu
we provide inside _ ideal for a spring luncheon or dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monet's Table'' includes a warm and detailed text written by
Claire Joyes, wife of the great-grandson of Alice Monet (Monet's
second wife), which reveals much about the setting of his
special-occasion meals as well as the guests. And Joyes worked with
famed French chef Joel Robuchon to research and test some 160
recipes from the artist's cooking journals.
</P>
<P>
   Joyes' research shows Monet's cuisine was heavily inspired by
his kitchen garden, which during his years at the now-legendary
house at Giverny was actually located on the other side of the
village from his estate.
</P>
<P>
   The 2 1/2-acre walled kitchen garden, unlike the softer flower
and water gardens at his home, was laid out in straight lines, with
rows of cabbages, brussels sprouts, lettuces, lima beans, tomatoes,
artichokes, chile peppers, pearl onions and many other vegetables.
There were also pear, apple, cherry and plum trees, and herbs such
as sage, oregano, sorrel, chervil and tarragon.
</P>
<P>
   Monet bought seeds and plants everywhere he went, and he also
collected recipes. After one of his trips to London, his cook,
Marguerite, had to learn to make Yorkshire pudding as served at the
Savoy Hotel. The recipe in ``Monet's Table'' for Tarte Tatin
actually comes from the sisters Tatin. They owned a nearby inn that
Monet visited frequently to sample the famous dish.
</P>
<P>
   Monet himself did not cook but had a cook, a servant and a
number of gardeners. His staff grew with his notoriety,
particularly the gardening staff.
</P>
<P>
   Life at Giverny, where he lived with Alice, her six children and
his two children, was very regimented, Joyes' research shows. Monet
rose before dawn, often to a breakfast of eggs, bacon, grilled
tripe sausages, Dutch or Stilton cheese, toast with orange
marmalade and tea _ all customs he picked up in his travels to
England and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   He would work throughout the morning, until the gong sounded at
11:30, signaling lunch. As the key meal of the day, lunch would
include a hot first course, a meat and/or fish, a highly peppered
salad, a vegetable and a dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Among Monet's favorites were mushrooms and chicory, woodcocks
and wild game, duck and guinea fowl, pike and turbot. He loved
fruit desserts and a dense pistachio cake.
</P>
<P>
   Monet would work again in his studio throughout the afternoon,
breaking for a light meal at the end of the day, often with soup
and an egg dish, and retiring at 9:30 p.m. to rise early again the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   But routine frequently gave way to celebrations, especially for
luncheons or picnics with friends _ events that reflected his love
of food and finery. At least three of his paintings had luncheon
themes and titles. Because his cooking journals didn't include
everyday menus, Joyes' research actually reveals more about such
special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   An invitation to lunch at Giverny was coveted among his friends.
Frequent guests included art dealers and patrons, statesmen like
Clemenceau and fellow impressionists such as Renoir, Pissarro,
Degas and Cezanne. Because of his early bedtime, Monet never
entertained in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Guests would arrive midmorning and visit the studio and the
greenhouses, and then sit down to a lavish lunch, always served on
a table covered with a yellow tablecloth with either blue Creil
earthenware in the pattern Japon or, on the most special occasions,
white porcelain dishes with a wide yellow border and blue edging.
Centerpieces consisted of little bouquets of flowers from the
garden or the greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, guests could tour the grounds, stopping for
afternoon tea and cakes under the lime trees. When the weather was
nice, it wasn't unusual for Monet to order a whole feast packed up
for picnics, at times big affairs with china and tables, at others
little more than pate and fruit on a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Inside this section is a menu for a special meal, beginning with
a recipe for stuffed onions that would make wonderful use of spring
Vidalias and ending with the famous Tarte Tatin. Borrow a few of
Monet's entertaining ideas and set out china and small bouquets. An
invitation to your house may be as coveted as one to Giverny.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
