<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP08-COX     04-07 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Better late than never for chicken request
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was so long ago, Sonya Burnett (e-mail) may have
forgotten she asked for an oven-baked chicken recipe that produces
crispy chicken using even skinless pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But she did _ last June. Finally Holly Quinn of Chamblee (GA.)
sent this one that fulfills the requirements, cooking up quite
crispy. She serves it warm with soup or salad.
</P>
<P>
   Our tester suggests adding a pinch of salt to taste, if you
like.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Crispy Baked Chicken
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon tarragon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plain bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken breasts and pat dry with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In small mixing bowl, lightly beat the egg with a fork. Add
pepper, oregano and tarragon and stir.
</P>
<P>
   Place bread crumbs in a plastic bag. Dip each chicken breast in
the egg mixture, then in the bag. Shake until they are covered with
bread crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Place chicken breasts on a nonstick baking sheet (or spray the
baking sheet), and spray chicken with vegetable oil. Bake 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 375 calories, 57 grams protein, 9 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 22), 12 grams carbohydrates, 224
milligrams cholesterol, 282 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Samantha Svensson of Lithonia (Ga.) is looking for three
favorite recipes she lost: buttermilk fudge, made with buttermilk,
sugar, butter and vanilla, but no chocolate; an orange gelatin
dessert made with orange sherbet, mandarin oranges and, possibly,
whipped cream; and maple syrup made in home economics class in 1962
that included sugar, water and maple flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diane White (e-mail) of Cumming (Ga.) wants to make homemade
granola bars that do not include hydrogenated oils, the trans-fats
in ``virtually every cookie and cracker on supermarket shelves
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
