<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-POOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL APPROVES PLAN FOR USE OF RECLUSE'S FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The $5.1 million estate bequeathed to the city
by a reclusive Polish immigrant will create a perpetual fund for
aiding the poor and elderly under a plan approved by a committee of
the San Francisco Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Human Services Department General Manager Will Lightbourne said
he expects that Zygmunt Arendt's dying wishes will be realized
sometime this summer. Implementation of the plan is contingent on
its approval by Judge Lawrence Kay, who is overseeing the estate.
</P>
<P>
   Arendt died at 92 on Jan. 24, 1998, leaving a handwritten will
giving his entire estate to San Francisco, with the mayor and
supervisors as his executors.
</P>
<P>
   The retired railroad car inspector had lived frugally in a
sparsely furnished home in the city's Bernal Heights section. In
his old age, he got around in a wheelchair and subsisted on a diet
of tuna, bananas and sardines.
</P>
<P>
   But an examination of his estate disclosed that he had been an
exceedingly canny investor in the stock market. Near the end of his
life, his portfolio was yielding dividends of $20,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of Arendt's will, 60 percent of his estate is to
go to poor and needy individuals, and 40 percent to disadvantaged
seniors and disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   The spending proposal offered by the city Department of Human
Services would preserve the capital of Arendt's estate in a trust
fund and use the interest earned on the money to benefit the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Lightbourne estimated that the estate will earn $250,000 to
$500,000 in interest each year.
</P>
<P>
   The 60 percent share will be distributed to poor people seeking
work through the Personal Assisted Employment Services program. The
Arendt money will be used to help them pay for non-emergency
services such as eye care and dental care.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 percent share will go to organizations working with the
disadvantaged elderly and disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients will be selected by a board of trustees made up of
volunteers chosen by city officials.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, approved unanimously by the Audit and Government
Efficiency Committee of the Board of Supervisors, must next be
approved by the full board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
