r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     04-07 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONDDERING THE LONGEVITY OF `LAW &AMP; ORDER'
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by TV-DURABILITY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's quite a buzz right now about HBO's witty mob series
``The Sopranos,'' and rightfully so. What a tragicomedy for the
ages. In one season, it has outflanked anything the green-with-envy
networks have sent through the programming grinder in years. ``The
best drama on TV!'' gushed one impressed critic. ``Could it be the
best ever?!'' wondered another.
</P>
<P>
   That said, certain distinctions should be made when making
shout-outs to the best of anything, particularly a drama series
with a life span of 13 episodes. Or three years. Or five, even.
</P>
<P>
   Series durability came to mind recently after I'd digested
another episode of ``Law &AMP; Order'' and felt bloated with anger,
sadness, pity, amazement, amusement, surprise _ and it was a repeat
I'd caught before.
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, TV programs are like thoroughbreds: usually three to
five good years and then out to pasture. Part of it is the
difficulty of sustaining dramatic friction. Another is simply
viewer weariness.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Law &AMP; Order,'' recently renewed for an unprecedented three
seasons, is still trucking after nine years. It's not only the
longest-running drama on the tube, but also the most consistently
good TV series I've ever witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   You're certainly most welcome to argue, but ``L&AMP;O'' has had
good-to-excellent seasons ever since producer Dick Wolf introduced
it in 1990 as an odd, gimmicky show with a half-and-half structure
of gumshoe policing and courtroom theatrics. All would deal with
issues and/or ideas, from a greedy surgeon harvesting organs of
not-yet-dead crime victims for transplant operations to the
upcoming (May 4) episode touching on sex crimes, boasting a Julia
Roberts guest spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``L&AMP;O'' is usually among Emmy nominees for best drama (it won in
1997), so it's interesting that the show has managed to steer clear
of the critical backlash often meted out to programs that have
found some measure of success.
</P>
<P>
   My theory is that media heat is applied to shows that display
showboating hype; ``L&AMP;O'' has merely been the dutiful employee, the
quiet, roll-up-the-sleeves type getting the job done and leaving
without complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that whenever a hot-to-trot drama like ``NYPD
Blue'' and now ``The Sopranos'' enters the ring, we take ``L&AMP;O''
for granted, filing it away in our collective TV consciousness
because we know it will always be there if and when we need it.
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, ``L&AMP;O'' has been the butt of jokes and the envy
of producers over its inability to hang on to its regular cast
members. (This year's cast is set to return next season _ so far.)
That it can move along smoothly with new faces is a testament to a
storytelling formula that bucks the trend by relying far less on
character-driven situations.
</P>
<P>
   I can't count how many calls were logged here from fans steamed
about the addition of Dallasite Angie Harmon, whose resume is
peppered with modeling credits and ``Baywatch Nights.'' First
thought was that ``L&AMP;O'' producers were going soft, or that Harmon
wouldn't leave her sexuality at the door, blowing wide open Wolf's
refusal to deal with personal angst.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a few shots of Harmon's Assistant District Attorney
Abbie Carmichael strolling along a New York City street, her thighs
playing peek-a-boo out of the slit on a just-above-the-knee skirt,
her sexuality has been relatively tame. (Unless you count that
smoldering, just-out-of-bed voice, which Wolf can't do much about.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I'm of the minority who think Harmon is just as
effective in that role as were Carey Lowell, Jill Hennessy and even
Richard Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Exchanges between Carmichael and her boss, district attorney
Jack McCoy (Sam Waterston) are tinged with a level of suspicion _
as though there's a game of one-upmanship creeping into the
proceedings. How many times has Carmichael given McCoy the evil eye
after he's gotten what he wants or mumbled something indirectly
patronizing?
</P>
<P>
   Even the partnership of detectives Rey Curtis (Benjamin Bratt)
and Lennie Briscoe (Jerry Orbach) has grown on me _ Bratt's
stiffness is now offset quite nicely by Orbach's crankiness. It's
as if Briscoe is the young Turk to Curtis' road-weary veteran.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the infrequent screen time of cops boss
Lt. Anita Van Buren (S. Epatha Merkerson) was bothersome, what with
the tendency of cop dramas to hand roles of precinct captain to
black characters in order to downplay their existence. But how can
you have a beef with a character who remains true to the show's
formula?
</P>
<P>
   If ``NYPD Blue'' is a drama about the emotions of cops and
robbers, ``L&AMP;O'' has the market on ideas. Although it sometimes
pulls too heavily from real news stories, its added twists and
turns are always an intriguing take.
</P>
<P>
   When it doesn't pick apart an event, its tendency to add a
multitude of wrinkles is arresting. Take last week's episode, which
dealt with the unraveling of a 30-year-old murder. Before the hour
was up, it had delved into the atmosphere surrounding '60s
rebellion, the Vietnam War and cover-ups supplied by the U.S.
government and the police department.
</P>
<P>
   It was vintage ``L&AMP;O'' _ the way it's been nearly every week for
nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
