<HEADER>
A9237 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     04-07 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMATO MAN'S GOT PLUM GOOD PRODUCE AND JUICY STORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Around Sweetwater, they call Lavaughn
Freeman the Tomato Man. They do it out of admiration for his juicy
tomatoes; they wouldn't make fun of this guy. He's about
6-foot-forever and several hundred pounds. Several.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Freeman is becoming a fixture in downtown Fort Worth, where
he tends his produce stand at Third and Houston streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been selling produce beside the road for 30 years,'' he
said. ``I farm for a living, but you can't make a living farming.
So I started out taking a trailer or two of watermelons to the
Dallas market, and on the way back, I would sell the produce I
picked up there to restaurants along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he opened a stand in Sweetwater, and that was where
he gained his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's trying to get a foothold in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   He was at Fort Worth's Sundance market two years ago, and came
back again last year. He caught the attention of Sundance
management, and they invited him to set up permanent shop on the
parking lot at Third Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business has been real good,'' he said. ``Everybody is talking
about how good it is to have something like this down here. A lot
of people live downtown, and they are glad to see us. We're open
from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m., six days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The produce stand is closed Sundays, but Freeman said there will
probably be Sundays when he'll open up shop.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the biggest rush of customers comes about 7:30 a.m. when
women on their way to the office stop by for fresh fruit, he said.
Then, between 3:30 and 5:30 p.m., people grab bags of vegetables
for their nightly meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between those evening hours, I don't even get a chance to sit
down,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, much of the produce is from wholesalers. The tomatoes
come from a friend south of San Antonio. They are of the Celebrity
variety. Freeman said that in a couple of months, he'll be bringing
in his own.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family farm about 500 acres near Sweetwater, where
they produce tomatoes, melons, squash, cotton, hay and honey. The
cotton and the hay won't make it to downtown Fort Worth, but
everything else will.
</P>
<P>
   A few homemade items dot Freeman's shelves. Aside from his own
honey, he handles apricot and peach preserves made in Canton,
ribbon cane syrup from East Texas and sorghum from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   He has are grapes, onions, green beans, oranges and bananas,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fall, I'll bring in some of the best-tasting tomatoes
you've ever had,'' he promised. ``They come from caves in
Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if shoppers don't like the looks of the produce, they can
still get a good story from Freeman. He is a typical West Texan in
that he's friendly and knows no strangers.
</P>
<P>
   He's willing to spin a yarn if you want. He aims to please. So
does his daughter Tracy, who lives in Fort Worth and runs a produce
stand on East Belknap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time when a TV reporter asked me if I used
chemicals,'' he remembered. ``I told her no, and she wanted to know
how I kept the bugs off. I explained that I had some ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman had her picturing the ducks going to the field every
morning to peck the bugs right off the fruits and vegetables. Each
evening, Freeman said, he and his hired hands would herd the ducks
back into a house where they would be protected from wolves and
coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard my daughter telling the duck story one day, and she
added that I had a blue heeler duck dog. I thought that was
great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
