<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9249 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-ANGRY &QC; SEX &LR;      04-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ANGRY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN ROAR, WOMEN PUSSYFOOT 
</HEADLINE>
 SEX   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 F. BRINLEY BRUTON  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Dad gets mad, watch out. But when Mom is upset,
no sweat.
</P>
<P>
   That motto has prevailed in many American families, and now
researchers have found that there is actually a universal
psychological thread to the whole phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   In findings that will hit home with families of explosive or
moody fathers, a recent study revealed that Dad's negative emotions
are transmitted quickly and powerfully throughout his immediate
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a bunch of emotional retards out there,'' said
Douglas McKee, a psychotherapist who works in the Atlanta area and
focuses on issues dealing with men and anger. ``They are so out of
touch with their emotions that they are all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   All over their wives and children, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The new study, which appeared in the Journal of Marriage and
Family, confirms what many women have felt for a long time, that
husbands typically are senders of negative emotions in families,
and children and wives are the sponges.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, men's ``secondhand emotions are like secondhand
smoke,'' said David Almeida, a one of the primary editors of the
study and a professor of psychology at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   And men cannot blame their outbursts on workplace stress, since
Almeida's study shows that women who are the primary wage earners
in the home still bear the brunt of the emotional fallout rather
than taking on the man's role of dumping bad vibes on everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite an era of the New-Age, sensitive man, many American
men still simply don't get it. How can this be, in an age when the
male and female psyches have been so dissected that even the most
Neanderthal man must have some clue about getting in touch with his
feelings?
</P>
<P>
   It takes only a trip to the local newsstand to see how the
traditional stereotypes about men and women's emotions are not only
as entrenched as ever but are being reinforced in the popular
media. A recent issue of Mademoiselle featured ``Love Trends:
Pleasures and Perils of Practically Living Together.''
</P>
<P>
   Glamour, meanwhile, advised women on when ``Not to Submit Your
Sensitive Secrets to his Grand Jury Grilling.'' Trendy Marie Claire
tutored women on how to please their men with a story on ``What Men
Would Change About You.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to this well of self-help, men's magazines such as Esquire,
GQ, and Maxim offered not a single article dealing with squishy
``communication'' or ``feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Men just aren't talking about stress in their lives,'' Almeida
said. While they do seem to have no problem expressing anger, men
need to learn introspection to get beyond that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only how I'm feeling,'' Almeida said, ``but what is
making me feel this way.''
</P>
<P>
   But anger and resentment is the male emotion that is most
transmitted in families, according to the new study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are not given a lot of space to show fear and sadness,''
McKee said. ``They are fostered to be more independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's inability to be anything but angry and their ability to
ruin other people's days most likely stems from boyhood
insecurities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you are a star male athlete, you don't measure up,'' he
said. As the boys get older, requirements to be wealthy and
good-looking are stacked on men's plates. Empathy and communication
skills are notably absent from the list of character traits that
men are encouraged to develop.
</P>
<P>
   And men just don't seem to like the idea of digging around
inside their psyches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men can retreat from a conflictual situation,'' Dr. Katherine
Levin said. ``They swallow and swallow their feelings, and then
explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, McKee contends that when men do get to a place where
they try to communicate, the patterns are so ingrained that their
spouses are just not listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very feeling men out there,'' McKee said, but
many women are not pausing long enough to find out.
</P>
<P>
   In many couples-therapy sessions ``the wife just talks faster
than her husband and doesn't stop,'' McKee said. ``But if I make
the wife pause'' the man feels like he can express himself.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, all hope is not lost, as both men and women have plenty of
opportunity to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are not changing as much as we think,'' Almeida said. ``So
there's lots of room for men to change.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: F. Brinley Bruton is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-PATS-MARCH &LR;      04-07 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-PATS-MARCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCHING IN NEW YORK CITY'S ST. PATRICK'S DAY PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By BRENDAN JANUARY  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I was a wee lad, over a stretch of five years,
my mother wrote a note to excuse me from school every March 17th.
While my friends trudged to Bedford Road Elementary, my sister and
I were on train speeding into New York City to join my grandmother
at the St. Patrick Day's parade.
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous, beer-swilling crowds, the hum of bagpipes, the
booming cadences of drums, the festive banners in various shades of
green, the grinning marchers waving to the crowd is etched in my
memory. I also remember the fickle March weather, mostly chilly and
gray.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped going to the St. Patrick's Day Parade after I
graduated from elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   When my grandmother died eight years ago, I was drawn back. The
parade and my grandmother are merged in my memory. It felt more
natural to go to the parade than to visit her grave.
</P>
<P>
   As a young girl in Ireland, she had washed clothing for
occupying British soldiers. At 18, she left Ireland and came to
America. One of her greatest joys was being a live spectator at the
St. Paddy's Day Parade on Fifth Avenue, the most prestigious street
in America. Since the 1920's, she rarely missed the parade,
ensconced at her favorite corner near St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   She often remarked that she felt the parade was a celebration of
Irish success. This year, I wanted to honor her memory. Instead of
watching the parade, I wanted to march in it.
</P>
<P>
   Having an Irish grandmother does not qualify one to march in the
parade. I held no city office. I was not a member of a high school
marching band. I did not play the bagpipes.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Civil War re-enactors who marched every year as the
Irish brigade _ a unit that fought in the American Civil War _ was
my ticket. I contacted the brigade commander and was invited to
march.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Brigade holds a special place in Irish-American
history. Although 150,000 Irish-Americans fought in the Union army,
only the Irish brigade served as an all-Irish unit. Carrying bright
green battleflags next to the American colors, their exploits and
bravery on the battlefield helped Irish immigrants overcome rampant
anti-Irish sentiment and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The brigade has marched in honor of Irish soldiers in the St.
Patrick's Day parade since 1984. On the morning of March 17, I rode
a subway to the Fort Hamilton section of Brooklyn, and joined about
200 re-enactors at a spot near the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge. Around
noon, we formed into long columns and marched to the subway for a
ride into Manhattan to the start of the parade. Motorists braked
their cars to a stop and honked as we passed by. People on their
front stoops laughed and waved.
</P>
<P>
   We were dressed like authentic soldiers of the Civil War. I wore
a navy-blue, wool jacket, sky-blue wool trousers, leather shoes,
and a wool hat called a kepi. I kept my trousers up with a two-inch
wide leather belt with a bright brass buckle. A leather cartridge
box and tin canteen slung over my shoulder. To round out my outfit,
I hefted a 9-pound, five-foot long musket equipped with a bayonet.
</P>
<P>
   By 2:30 p.m., we stood in the shadows cast by office buildings
on East 47th Street, awaiting our turn to join the parade. St.
Patrick's Day had rarely seen finer weather, balmy with strong
sunlight driving the temperatures into the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, our wait ended. Following a high school band
dressed in bright royal blue and yellow trim, we turned right onto
Fifth Avenue and began the 40-block march uptown.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators were packed tight along the parade route. We strutted
smartly and smiled at the crowd. Somewhere, my mother and aunt was
among the revelers but I never saw them. People leaned on the
pale-blue police barricades and pointed at marchers. As we marched
those first blocks, applause and cheers came from both sides of the
street.
</P>
<P>
   At 51st Street, we paused in front of St. Patrick's Cathedral.
In the most solemn and hallowed moment of our march, the men
carrying the regiment's battle flags turned and faced the church.
Silently, Cardinal O'Connor stepped out and gestured a cross with
his hand, blessing the flag. It was the only time he personally
gave a blessing during the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal O'Connor inspired this tradition five years ago, when
he noticed the re-enactors in the parade. A Civil War buff, the
Cardinal contacted the re-enactors and offered to bless the battle
flags, just as the cardinals blessed the Irish battle flags during
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is such an honor,'' said Stephan O'Neill, who carried the
bright green Irish battleflag in the parade. ``I feel tremendously
proud when he blesses the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   We resumed marching up Fifth Avenue, passing the FAO Schwarz toy
store and the Plaza Hotel. From the street, the crowd was a blur of
bright faces in a sea of green.
</P>
<P>
   As we wound our way toward the end of the parade route, the
crowd lessened. At some spots, the bleachers stood empty. At one
point, it was so quiet that we could hear the stomp of our boots
against the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   The lull ended abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking good guys! Looking good!'' screamed five young women
who each wore T-shirts with a different word stamped on front,
which together said: ``Flown in fresh from Belfast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes right,'' shouted a brigade leader.
</P>
<P>
   A parade is not a parade without hecklers. ``The war's over!'' a
male spectator shouted.
</P>
<P>
   At 86th Street, we turned off Fifth Avenue and dispersed. I was
surprised instead of feeling elated, I felt a little flat. Perhaps,
it was the warm temperatures. Perhaps, it was knowing my
grandmother was not there at her usual spot, but I did not feel the
same electricity that I had from past parades.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked across Central Park to return to my apartment,
people acknowledged my uniform. ``Was it fun?'' asked a homeless
man.
</P>
<P>
   A jogger halted in midstride and offered congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian tourist asked if I fought for the South.
</P>
<P>
   A tour bus filled with Japanese excitedly took notice as I
waited at a street corner.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, even more than in the parade itself, I could
suddenly relate to what James Barker, a member of the parade's
organizational committee, had said, ``The whole world is Irish on
St. Patrick's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Brendan January is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
