<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MOVIE-GLUT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS STRUGGLE FOR MOMENT OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By STEPHEN SIFF  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Holly Hudson's first film cost $20,000, and she
cannot get anyone to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old off-Broadway actress poured dreams of stardom
and a small inheritance into her 10-minute short, ``Pipe Dreams.''
It was an investment _ Hudson hoped the movie would catapult her
into a career directing Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months later, the movie has been publicly screened only
twice. In October, ``Pipe Dreams'' had its debut at the Leeds
International Film Festival. The encore show came four months
later, at a New York City institution known for less ambitious
films _ Show World, the 25-year-old granddaddy of the dying Times
Square sex industry. Before a citywide crackdown on porn in
December, the screening room was Show World's peep show.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 young bohemians gathered in the screening room,
embellished with floor-to-ceiling mirrors and black and red tile,
applauded Hudson's film, one of seven shorts on a Friday night
program. But no one in the audience could jump-start Hudson's film
career or bankroll her next picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to win the lottery,'' said Hudson, who
submitted ``Pipe Dreams'' to about 20 film festivals, both in this
country and abroad. ``It was an alarming wake-up call for me. I
have had a hard time, and I know that there are a lot of films
worse than mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the rags-to-riches stories of directors like Spike
Lee (``Do the Right Thing'') and Steven Soderbergh (``sex, lies &AMP;
videotape'') a growing number of aspiring filmmakers are maxing out
credit cards, hitting up relatives for loans and spending trust
funds in chase of the golden ring _ fame, money and adulation.
</P>
<P>
   While every college campus and two-horse town has sprouted a
film festival, the number of filmmakers has increased even faster,
people familiar with the industry say. At the New York Academy of
Film, for instance, enrollment has doubled nearly three times since
1993, with high school kids, narcotics lawyers, archivists and
Buddhist monks filling out the student body. With so many movies
being made, the odds of a talented amateur being noticed by a
studio executive or industry insider has become increasingly slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indie films are like the garage bands of the 90s,'' said Steve
Gallagher, associate editor of ``Filmmaker'' magazine. ``There are
thousands of films being made and there is no way to show them _
not at industry shows, not at art houses, not at film festivals.''
</P>
<P>
   If festivals are now swamped with independent films, they will
soon be drowning in them. Filmmakers can now shoot their pictures
on digital video cameras for a fraction of the cost of shooting
16-millimeter film. Everyone who ever wanted to make a movie can
afford to get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the big fear,'' said Milton Tabbot, director of the
Independent Feature Film Market, an industry trade show in New
York. ``Now, everyone will go out and make a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Sundance Film Festival, the premier film festival in the United
States, is already so deluged with submissions that filmmakers
disgruntled by rejection slips spun-off a sister festival,
``Slamdance.'' This year, 1,310 short films jockeyed to be one of
58 shorts shown at Sundance, said publicist J.R. Millard. The
competition was just as fierce for full-length dramas: out of 840
entries, 35 were accepted. There's no guarantee the films that are
accepted will ever appear before a broader audience, or that the
filmmaker will be offered any money or a job. Four months after
Sundance ended, only nine of the 35 full-length movies and two of
the shorts had been purchased for release to movie theaters or
cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Even obscure film festivals are wildly competitive. This year,
the three-year-old Iowa Independent Film Festival rejected 80
percent of movies submitted. The P.S. 99 short film festival in New
York City is sifting through 900 movies to find 30 worth showing.
Out of 115 submissions, only 11 made it to the big screen at the
Weekly Alibi Short Film Fiesta in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Festival director Devin O'Leary said only one of these has
generated any kind of commercial interest: ``Feed,'' a three-minute
abstract film about a desert wanderer's internal monologue, earned
local director Brett Biescheid a flight to Los Angeles and
interviews for a job directing shoe commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a whole history of people making low-budget films and
finding commercial success _ the Cinderella story,'' said
Gallagher, the editor. ``Because so many films are being made, it
makes it so much harder for the distributors to wade through the
muck and find the gems.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young directors lack talent and originality, said Joe
Pilaro, coordinator of the graduate film program at Columbia
University. The chief bugaboo of bad indie films, he said, is a
humdrum plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of the films, the visual story telling is good, the
cinematography is good, but the story sucks,'' Pilaro said. What
they are missing, he said, is ``traditional storytelling _
protagonist, antagonist, all that good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The television show ``Ally McBeal'' provides a popular pattern
for low-budget films, Pilaro said. So is the chummy comedy
``Friends.'' ``In the grand scheme of things, these movies are very
similar,'' Tabbot said. ``Guys sitting around, talking about what
they are going to do with the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Hudson's ``Pipe Dreams'' resembles ``Ally McBeal'' to the
extent that the fantasy life of the protagonist, an actress played
by Hudson, is acted out on the screen. In ``Pipe Dreams,'' an
actress' overbearing, abusive mother materializes at a movie
audition to provoke a dramatic performance from her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson had several advantages in making the film. Her husband, a
production assistant on ``Martha Stewart's Living,'' lent his
technical know-how. And Hudson recruited friends from her years on
stage to act for free. Still, the movie couldn't have been made
without the small inheritance left by her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Expense must discourage many would-be filmmakers. An old-timer's
rule of thumb is to budget $1,000 for each minute of a
16-millimeter film, said Kelly Markus, programmer of the P.S. 99
film festival and the co-producer of a full-length documentary
about the 100th anniversary of Jell-O. The picture is in hiatus for
want of $50,000 to $60,000 to finish editing.
</P>
<P>
   But with a digital video camera, images are stored on computer
chips. There is no film to buy or develop. Each individual take can
be viewed by simply plugging the camera into a television, and
editing is done on a home computer. Software that costs about $500
produces effects available only in the fanciest film studios. Once
video is transferred onto film, only the most careful observer can
tell the movie was made digitally. Though this final transfer is
very expensive _ about $6 per foot of film _ shooting digital video
cuts the total cost of making a movie roughly in half.
</P>
<P>
   Already, several ``reality'' television shows are shot in
digital video, and one of the Independent Film Channel's 10 best
films of 1998, ``The Last Broadcast,'' was made on digital video
for less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The ``digital film revolution'' will democratize filmmaking,
predicted Peter Graham, editor of the Independent Film Channel's
Web site. Cheap digital video cameras will put movie-making tools
at everyone's fingertips, and the Internet will provide an
unlimited showcase for their work. Movies, he said, ``are the new
way people are going to tell their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Independent Film Channel's web site broadcasts
movies over the Internet, and many other Web sites allow visitors
to download a short clip. But few filmmakers will be satisfied with
just an Internet screening. The picture is only slightly larger
than a pack of cigarettes, and motion across the tiny screen
appears jerky. While the quality may be better with a high-speed
cable connection to the Internet, this technology is only available
in a few parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even more worrisome to some is the prospect of their film being
lost in cyberspace. Although some filmmakers make art for art's
sake, ``they all have the dream of winning the Academy Award,''
Pilaro said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tepid success of ``Pipe Dreams,'' Hudson still
clings to her dream of making it to Hollywood. She has already
started her second screenplay, which bears similarity to her first.
In the new full-length film, an actress is plagued by her mother's
ghost as she performs a one-woman play. If Hudson gets another
chance to put ``Pipe Dreams'' before a live audience, she won't
turn it down. Even if it means another porn house debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy for anyplace where people just want to screen the
film,'' Hudson said. ``That is what it is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Stephen Stiff is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
