</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MILITIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITIA MOVEMENT GROWS IN URBAN AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By WILLIAM MURRAY   
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In St. Mary's Episcopal Church, a flurry of fists
shot upward. Chants of ``black power, black power,'' rocked the
sanctuary, reverberating toward the stained glass windows and the
26th Police Precinct across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Militia of New York was meeting for the first time.
Applause rebounded every time a speaker proclaimed the need for
African-Americans to arm themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be said, brothers and sisters, some police have to
die,'' said Malik Shabazz, a lawyer who had traveled to New York
from Washington, D.C., to help start the group.
</P>
<P>
   Organizer Viola Plummer drew rousing cheers with her quote from
the Declaration of Independence: ``It is the people's right and
duty to throw off such government and to provide new guards for
their future security!''
</P>
<P>
   The gathering earlier this year was part of a growing movement
to organize African-Americans into armed militias, an effort that
has gained new prominence in the face of publicity about police
violence against minorities in New York. The armed militia
advocates envision a force ready to defend against police whom they
believe are no longer upholding the law but instead are
disregarding the civil rights of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not know that you are at war,'' Plummer told the
audience of some 100 men and women. ``But we in the movement know
we're waging war.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the idea of a people's militia has been most prominent
in recent years among rural, white racists and anti-government
skinheads, some black Americans now see militias as a way to gain
more control over their own communities. In New York, these
sentiments were fanned by the police shooting of an unarmed West
African immigrant, Amadou Diallo, and the alleged police beating of
a Haitian immigrant, Abner Louima, which resulted in the trial of
four officers this year.
</P>
<P>
   The disconnect between black residents and the New York police
dovetails with a resurgence of black nationalism nationwide along
the lines of the Black Panther Party. The Panthers, a
controversial, militant group that began in the 1960s, at times
participated in shoot-outs with police but also engaged in
community organizing to provide such services as health clinics and
neighborhood patrols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all surprised that the militia groups are seizing
on police brutality as a way to re-form themselves,'' said Hugh
Pearson, an African-American journalist who wrote a book on the
Black Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope they don't devolve into the crazy mess that the
old Panther Party became. There was infiltration into the party by
the FBI, but the principle reason for the party's downfall was the
thuggish behavior of genuine party leaders toward party members.''
</P>
<P>
   The romantic memory of the Panthers and its message of black
self-reliance
</P>
<P>
   motivate some of the current militancy. And police violence
against blacks has helped spawn black militia movements in
Milwaukee, Los Angeles and St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In Jasper, Texas, last year, armed members of the Dallas New
Black Panther Party arrived at a Ku Klux Klan rally armed with
guns, but the police arrived before violence could occur.
</P>
<P>
   Police organizations around the country are also paying
attention to the black militia movement and fear a return to a more
confrontational period.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems we're having is that people are mixing the
concept of police brutality and the police use of deadly force,''
said Mort Feldman, executive vice president of the National
Association of Chiefs of Police. ``If the Abner Louima allegations
are true, then justice should be served.'' But that alleged
brutality, involving a severe beating of Louima by four officers at
the station, should not interfere with legal use of force by
police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have are loose-knit groups which react to situations
of perceived brutality,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   The militia advocates, however, say the time has come for
drastic measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a people's militia whose sole intent is
the defense of our people,'' said Jonah Thomas, a lawyer who spoke
at the St. Mary's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When whites and blacks arm themselves, the motivations are
different, but the result is ``a kind of Balkanization,'' said Mark
Potok, spokesman for the Alabama-based Southern Poverty Law Center,
which tracks white supremacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing but different,'' Potok said. ``In black
communities the visceral reaction is police brutality. In white
communities it is seen as repression by the federal government's
tax system. But it's manifested in the same way _ in gunplay.''
</P>
<P>
   In a month of protests after the Diallo shooting, more than
1,000 people were arrested in front of New York City police
headquarters until a Bronx grand jury indicted four officers for on
charges of second-degree murder. Despite Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani's pledge to rebuild frayed ties between the police and the
city's minority communities, militia rhetoric paints a bleak
picture of race relations here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When crackers start dying in different parts of town, anytime,
anywhere, any day or night, then the enemy will think twice about
taking yours out,'' said Shabazz, who was the main organizer of the
Million Youth March in Harlem last September. Shabazz and his
organization, the Million Youth March Committee, is aligning with
the New Black Panther Party in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's justice,'' Shabazz said. ``That's in the Koran. That's
in the Bible. It has to happen. Only then will the enemy begin to
have a greater respect.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: William Murray is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
