<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9253 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-ETHNIC-PR &LR;      04-07 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ETHNIC-PR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC FIRMS PUT NEW SPIN ON PUBLIC RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By CHRIS NUTTALL-SMITH  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like most public-relations professionals, Vera Osmani
has a message, and she wants to be heard. But unlike most in her
field, she is usually happy pitching to a small audience.
</P>
<P>
   Osmani's Bronx business, the Albanian Media Group, works mostly
with Albanian clients and Albanian audiences, packaging information
for ethnic newspapers and other specialized media outlets. She also
tries to ``sell'' the Albanian community to America at large _
trying, for example, to get mainstream businesses to advertise in
an Albanian Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, such ethnic- or culture-specific marketing simply
did not exist _ such efforts were either bunched in with the
mainstream or ignored altogether. Now, as ethnic communities gain
market power, mainstream companies and organizations are realizing
they need a voice in those areas. And that means an opening for
Osmani and entrepreneurs like her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that there's a growing demand to focus
marketing on multicultural markets,'' said Richard George,
spokesman for the Public Relations Society of America, an industry
group.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic and African-American public-relations firms were the
first to spring up, starting about 20 years ago. Now they have
become commonplace, and firms that focus on Asian, Irish and
continental European communities are joining their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many communities have long had advocacy
organizations, cultural associations and lobbying groups to fight
for their interests, but for many, the idea of professional,
for-profit PR businesses is entirely new.
</P>
<P>
   Elena DelValle, director of the Public Relations Society of
America's multicultural caucus and president of LNA World
Communications in Miami, says she makes a living from a reality
that most corporations are only just beginning to face: ``You
wouldn't dream of addressing a Haitian group the same way as a
Hispanic group, or an African-American, or a Jewish audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic-focused start-ups take on a wide range of jobs. Lisa
Skriloff, of Multicultural Marketing Resources, in Manhattan,
concentrates much of her business on Hispanic and Asian clients.
</P>
<P>
   In one project, she is working to attract mainstream sponsors
for a multicultural food festival. She also distributes press
releases when women and members of minority groups get professional
promotions, and she publishes an annual book of minority sources
for mainstream reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's research. Skriloff learns cultural calendars _
something that mainstream PR firms often do not do _ so she can
advise her clients to observe ethnic holidays and celebrations with
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Much of her business comes from advertising agencies, which hire
her to publicize new ad campaigns focused at minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   She says her efforts are often rewarded with cooperation unheard
of in mainstream media. ``Ethnic publications are very receptive to
press releases,'' she said. ``In fact, many times when I send out a
press release they will ask that I send it by e-mail so they can
reprint it verbatim.''
</P>
<P>
   The business is not limited to small, boutique firms, however.
</P>
<P>
   Intercultural Niche Strategies Inc. has in four years built a
booming business marketing music to ethnic communities in the
United States. According to Holly Poirier, the company's
co-principal, the company has worked for major labels such as
Polygram (now Universal) and BMG to market its artists.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Polygram signed Andrea Bocelli, an Italian
tenor, to its label, Intercultural Niche Strategies worked to
promote the artist in the Italian-American community.
</P>
<P>
   Poirier said her company contracts work to marketing specialists
from within the communities. So far, it's worked on Asian and South
Asian campaigns, as well as Italian, Irish, Scandinavian and
African.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Brown, a vice president of Washington-based Walls
Communications Inc., has worked to help his firm tap into one of
America's most lucrative minority markets.
</P>
<P>
   All of Walls' 17 employees are African-American, and as Brown
describes it, they can help major companies and organizations build
bridges with black communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations certainly recognize not only the purchasing power
of certain groups, but also the demographics,'' Brown said. He
explained that as minority populations continue to grow, they claim
a greater portion of the consumer market. He also said that
African-Americans had $500 billion in annual purchasing power. The
business world is catching on, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walls Communications counts among its clients corporations such
as Shell Oil, DuPont, NationsBanc and Denny's, as well as
organizations such as the NAACP and the National Urban League,
Brown said. All of them want to speak to black audiences.
</P>
<P>
   They want to speak to each other as well, Brown said. He
describes how his firm helped Shell Oil executives connect with the
National Urban League. He boasts that Shell is sponsoring the
National Urban League's annual conference this year, as a result of
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such work brings rewards. Brown said his firm earned
about $3 million a year and is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the old-school firms are taking notice, sprouting
multicultural divisions of their own. Raul Garza, director of
multicultural communications for Hill &AMP; Knowlton, the international
public-relations firm, said the company started to specialize in
Hispanic audiences about five years ago because of demand from
existing clients.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the multicultural division has expanded to
specialize in 11 languages and 13 cultures, Garza said. The
expansion has helped them with scores of accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when one of Hill &AMP; Knowlton's clients, the Century
Council, a not-for-profit group that fights underage drinking and
drinking and driving, wanted to speak to Hispanic and Native
American audiences, the multicultural division was able to help.
</P>
<P>
   The firm helped the Century Council develop an education
campaign through the Catholic Church. In archdioceses with large
Hispanic populations, priests would deliver the Century Council's
message directly from the pulpit, and urge parishioners to stand up
in church and pledge not to drink and drive _ so-called La Promesa
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Hill &AMP; Knowlton helped develop Century Council
brochures aimed at Native American communities.
</P>
<P>
   Garza said that by custom-tailoring messages to specific
communities, they are more effective. ``You want to read about
yourself and you want to hear about yourself,'' he said. ``So don't
just tell me there's so many accidents a year from drunk driving.
Tell me what the incidence is among Native Americans _ just generic
information isn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Bronx, Vera Osmani yards the conversation between a
coffee-table book about Albania's beautiful landscape, her firm's
Web site and the violence in Kosovo. When people want information
about the Albanian community, she said, she wants them to come to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge community here, and it seems we're getting
everything we know from the American press,'' she said. ``I guess
it's time for us to have our say, to give our picture in this whole
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Chris Nuttall-Smith is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1603EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
