<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-THEFT-BIRD &LR;      04-07 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-THEFT-BIRD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR TAKES $20,000 BIRD _ THEN SINGS TO REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ALEX LANE  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Jan. 27, detectives stormed into Johnny Davila's
house in Brooklyn, dragged him out of bed, cuffed him and
interrogated him at his kitchen table, in front of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   News report about what led to Davila's arrest were sketchy _ the
23-year-old Brooklyn actor was being accused of stealing a $20,000
bird from the Central Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The real story is as strange as it sounds _ it involves the
quirky, over-dramatic actor, a pair of paraplegics, the pricey
parrot and an almost unbelievable coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Born and reared in Brooklyn, the tall, lanky Davila called
himself an ``outcast of society'' _ and then said in the next
breath that he has ``the best family life anyone could ask for _ a
loving mother, a loving brother and a loving dog named Juju.'' He
dreams of being a famous actor, and he starred in two small,
independent films: ``Latin Boys Go to Hell,'' and the
soon-to-be-released ``Muscle Car.'' The trouble started the night
of Dec. 17, 1998. At about 1 a.m., after a Christmas event near the
Central Park Zoo, a tipsy Davila wandered through an open gate.
(Zoo officials deny that a gate would have been open so late.)
</P>
<P>
   Davila continued into the dark zoo _ no one was in sight, and it
was eerily quiet save for some splashing from the sea-lion pool. He
walked until he came to a plain, low building, and to his surprise
found it open. Inside was a holding area for animals, and it is
here that he happened upon the bird. To hear him tell it, what
happened next was not exactly theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like there was this mist,'' Davila said, speaking
slowly and dramatically. ``And ssssshhh, and the bird was there.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the bird out of its cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so _ gullible,'' Davila said. ``I took advantage of his
vulnerability, just sitting in that cage by himself there. He sat
on my hand and nibbled on my finger with his tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   The bird looked at him. ``I said 'Wow, what the are you looking
at, man? Come on man, let's go.' And we went.''
</P>
<P>
   Davila's girlfriend later named the bird Holly because of its
Christmas-like colors _ brilliant green, with a red patch on top of
its head.
</P>
<P>
   What Davila didn't realize is that he had taken a thick-billed
parrot _ valued at $20,000, a member of an endangered species. His
new friend was on loan from the Sacramento Zoo, and was the female
half of a couple brought together under a breeding program called
the Species Survival Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Police began looking for the bird as zoo workers, angry and sad,
puzzled over the crime. Barbara Schwartz was completing her
internship as a veterinary technician at the Zoo while working
nights as a sound technician on the Broadway show ``Beauty and the
Beast.'' She remembers telling a co-worker on the show, Michelle
Hout, about the theft _ Hout understood the significance of the
loss, since her day job was at a parrot shop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Davila was trying to figure out what to do with the
bird. He thought that it deserved more love and attention than he
could give it. So he called a good friend of his, Ed Jupp.
</P>
<P>
   Davila met Jupp, who uses a wheelchair, two years ago on the set
of a movie called ``Harlem Aria,'' where both were working as
extras. Two or three times a month, Davila would stop by the
midtown-Manhattan apartment that Jupp shares with his longtime
girlfriend, Dawn Scuderi, and talk for hours.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, Davila called Jupp and asked if he could scan a
picture of a parrot into his computer and sell it on the Internet.
Jupp was intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   Scuderi, who uses a wheelchair because of a spinal-cord tumor,
loves animals and has always wanted a parrot. Though Jupp and
Scuderi are deeply in love, she often annoys him when he is trying
to work at the computer in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in my office to work and she comes in there every five
minutes,'' Jupp said. ``Then there are two wheelchairs in this
small room and she comes over and says, 'Kiss me, Honey,' and I'm
like 'How many times?!'''
</P>
<P>
   So when Jupp heard that Davila was selling a parrot he quickly
decided ``to get this bird that would keep her entertained so I
could work.''
</P>
<P>
   Scuderi loved Holly just as much as Jupp had hoped _ for a
while. But Holly did not talk much, aside from singing ``La
Cucaracha'' and the ``Woody Woodpecker'' theme, and she would
squawk loudly and often. When Scuderi let Holly out, the bird would
often just climb on top of the cage and lie down. So before long a
bored Scuderi was back to her old ways, rolling into Jupp's office
for attention _ only now Jupp had a squawking parrot in the next
room to deal with as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jupp told Scuderi to call around to pet stores and try to find
one that would be willing to trade a calm, talking bird for Holly
the thick-billed parrot. Most didn't believe she actually had a
thick-billed parrot, and they did not accept trades anyway. Then on
Jan. 23, Scuderi called up the Midtown parrot shop Thirty-third and
Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hout _ who worked with Barbara Schwartz on Broadway _
picked up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gotta get our hands on this bird,'' Hout thought to
herself, as she heard Scuderi offering a thick-billed parrot. She
ran to the back of the store and told the owner, Mike Held, of the
theft and the woman on the phone. Hout got Scuderi's phone number,
and Held called the police.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Jupp answered a knock on his door and six
detectives flashing badges strode into his apartment. The next day,
Davila was cuffed and hauled off to the 20th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, back in the hands of zoo workers, the parrot
died. Davila, Jupp, and Scuderi were unaware that Holly had a
dangerous respiratory infection for which she was being treated
with a regimen of antibiotics at the zoo. This smoke-filled midtown
apartment was clearly not the best place for a sick bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's major animal abuse,'' said Susan Healy, the lead
keeper of the Species Survival Plan at the Sacramento Zoo ``There
was a lot of anger over it. ... Her value in dollars is not worth
half as much as what she was worth as a living creature.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, Davila was arraigned in Manhattan Supreme Court on
charges of grand larceny, criminal possession of stolen property,
and burglary. He pleaded not guilty. Davila, who said he was
working on a plea bargain, said he did not think taking the parrot
was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   You can ``have this animal and people just gawk at it, and throw
little pebbles through cages at it, and all kinds of people just
staring at it,'' Davila said. ``Or you could have it in your home
and give it as much love as any other person would.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Alex Lane is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
