<SLUG> BC-CNS-LIBRARIANS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BUNS TO BYTES: IS THE IMAGE OF LIBRARIANS CHANGING ? 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By SARAH DOUGHERTY  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tattoos, nose rings, green hair _ sure signs of a
punk rocker, right? No, a librarian.
</P>
<P>
   The media may still get a lot of mileage out of the librarian
stereotype _ a stuffy older woman with her hair in a severe bun _
but librarians know their public image doesn't jibe with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Librarians know the stereotype well. They laugh at it, but also
discuss how it affects their self-image and professional status.
Sometimes they go out of their way to overturn it. But many agree
that the cliche has a certain basis in fact, and that the
information revolution, far from changing the stereotype, may
actually be reinforcing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Librarians love the image and hate it at the same time,'' said
Linda Absher, an in-house librarian for a company in Beaverton,
Ore. ``They are in fact self-absorbed about their image.''
</P>
<P>
   Absher believes that the stereotype is intimately linked with
the fact that the profession was always, and still is, dominated by
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public want a female authority figure, if only to rebel
against,'' Absher said. ``And there aren't many female authority
figures, maybe teachers and librarians, that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Absher and other librarians are trying to debunk some of the
myths.
</P>
<P>
   Absher has created a fictitious Web site character _ the
Lipstick Librarian _ an iconoclast who proves that librarians can
be smart, glamorous and take a joke. The site _
www.teleport.com/~petlinliplib _ offers makeup tips (Post-its as a
beauty aid) and a bibliography (``Circulate THIS!! When Circ
Librarians Go Bad'').
</P>
<P>
   There are also Web sites for ``Modified'' librarians (tattoos
and piercing),
</P>
<P>
   anarchist librarians (``Boring Mission Statement: We don't have
one'') and bellydancing librarians (Birkenstocks by day, ``I Dream
of Jeannie''outfit by night).
</P>
<P>
   Eris Weaver entertains incognito in Sonoma County, Calif., as
the Bellydancing Librarian. ``It's a cerebral job,'' she said. ``So
this gives me an outlet. I like playing with people. People's
reactions always crack me up when I tell them I'm a librarian.
Right now my hair is green, St. Patrick's Day and all.'' Weaver's
Web site is at www.wco.com/~eris/bdlib.html.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver does not believe her colleagues are a conservative group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met some of the wildest people. And our political beliefs
are not conservative,'' she said, referring to librarians' vigorous
stands on First Amendment issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Cherubin, a music librarian at the New York Public Library
and the Ska librarian on the Web, disagrees. He believes the
stereotype has a basis in fact. ``It does tend to draw a certain
type,'' he said. ``Quiet, non-confrontational. I'm a type A
personality, but there aren't many.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherubin says that for many of his colleagues, librarianship is
a second or third career, so they are older and more reluctant to
rock the boat. ``I wanted to stage a walk out to protest the fact
that we haven't had salary raises in several years,'' he said.
``But nobody wanted to make a scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherubin says this conservatism often extends to dress. ``I see
people in Earth shoes and I say, who still makes them?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alysse Jordan, a social work librarian at Columbia University,
finds that librarians also usually have something else in common: a
passion for research. ``I find myself being obsessed with
information,'' she said. ``And I get surprised when I catch myself
falling into that stereotype, like when I'm awake in the middle of
the night thinking about researching a small fact.''
</P>
<P>
   While the technological revolution has radically changed
librarians' work, it does not seem to have changed their image.
``Now our image is combining with that of the computer geek,''
Cherubin said.
</P>
<P>
   To compound this, the general public often assumes that
computers will make librarians obsolete. In fact, many librarians
believe that they will continue to be invaluable intermediaries
between the public and the vast amount and varied quality of data
available on line. ``I think of myself as hacking a trail with a
machete through the deluge of information swamping people,'' Eris
Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   American Library Association statistics show a steady increase
in library use in the 1990s. ``Librarianship is in fact a growth
profession,'' said Mohammed Aman, Dean of the School of Library and
Information Science at the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But while technology has forced librarians to master many new
skills, it continues to be a relatively low-paying profession. Many
attribute this to the fact that it is traditionally a woman's job.
``Salaries are going up as more men enter the field,'' Aman said.
</P>
<P>
   As librarians struggle with their image, some think that a
change of title would help elicit more respect. Cybrarian has been
one suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   The guest book from the Lipstick Librarian Web site had some
more playful suggestions: Information Goddess and Reference Diva.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Sarah Dougherty is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
