<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-CIGARETTES &LR;      04-07 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CIGARETTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO MARKETING: THE CAMEL HAS NINE LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ITAY HOD  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 11 p.m. on Feb. 23, Brian Panerali, a bartender at
the trendy Manhattan club Venue, received his weekly stash. At the
corner of the dark bar, Alicia, the beautiful tobacco agent,
presented her latest bag of goodies: T-shirts, trinkets and best of
all free Camel cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Panerali held up his booty and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome,'' said Panerali, 24, who receives two free packs
of Camels three times a week. ``I'm a smoker, so when they give us
free cigarettes, I don't have to buy them. For three dollars a
pack, that's a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the forced retirement of Joe Camel more than a year ago,
and the recent federal ban on tobacco billboards, big cigarette
companies have come up with new innovative ideas to reach their
consumers. Camel, Marlboro, Kool and other brands have signed bars
and clubs in all major cities around the country to exclusive
contracts. In return for their loyalty, the bars are showered with
gifts, cash, and free cigarettes. Another perk? Bartenders get free
access to all bars signed with the company in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated phone calls, neither Phillip Morris nor R.J.
Reynolds would comment on their newest promotional strategy.
Alicia, the Camel agent dressed in black, was not talking either.
She refused to give her last name or explain her work. ``I am told
not to speak to anyone about this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to bartenders and club managers, the gig goes like
this. Tobacco agents hop from bar-to-bar bearing gifts: caps,
darts, Benetton watches, bottle openers, Zippo lighters, leather
backpacks and key chains all displaying the popular Camel logo. And
of course, always, cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Panerali gets 10 packs every two days, two packs to keep, and
the rest to sell or give away to customers who want to ``bum a
couple of cigs.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, every week Camel runs a full-page ad in the
Village Voice, where bars signed up with the cigarette manufacturer
can promote special events. Again, free of charge. If a club
decides to throw a party, Camel will pay for posters and flyers,
provided they include a few key words: ``Camel is proud to present
... ''
</P>
<P>
   And once a year, managers receive a $2,000 cash gift, no strings
attached. One phone call and Camel delivers. ``If you show them
that you promote them, they'll give you more money,'' said Deborah
Jackman, lounge manager at the Evelyn.
</P>
<P>
   Camel is even willing to walk an extra mile, all the way to the
municipal building to pick up your license to sell cigarettes. They
will wait in the line for you. And pick up the $100 tab.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few small catches. Bars must sign a contractual
agreement that obligates them to display only Camel memorabilia,
and in big quantities. Also, bartenders must be brand loyal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a smoker and you don't smoke Camels, you can't have
your cigarettes seen,'' said Alicia Regan, 27, bartender at the
Evelyn, a bar on Central Park West. ``You can't promote something
else inadvertently.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone takes the bait. Rain Lampariello, bar manager
at Merchant's restaurant in Manhattan, has been solicited by Camel
three times this past year alone and consistently declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be selling cigarettes instead of a bar,'' said
Lampariello, who figures he could have saved a few thousand dollars
a month if he had signed up. ``It's cheesy to have beverage napkins
that say 'Camel' on them. You're inviting people into your place to
spend their money and then you try to stuff cigarettes down their
throats.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say tobacco critics are not wild about this latest
campaign. Cliff Douglas, a lawyer involved in the first class
action lawsuit against tobacco manufacturers in Florida, is not
surprised that the tobacco companies are mum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they're involved in something that's not necessarily
illegal but pushes the boundaries of what's expectable in
society,'' Douglas said. ``If they didn't think they were doing
something wrong, they would tell us all about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Polan, chief federal lobbyist for the American Cancer
Society, said, ``This is yet another decline we would rather not
see happem.'' Polan noted that 420,000 Americans die every year
from cancer and other tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Kawalec, senior vice president at Young &AMP; Rubicam, the
largest advertising agency in New York, thinks it is a brilliant
campaign. Unlike billboards which everyone sees, even those not
necessarily interested in the product, bar advertising captures its
target audience in a direct and fashionable way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about creating an image,'' said Kawalec, who declines
to work on cigarette or liquor advertising. ``It's very effective.
Basically what they are getting is an endorsement from these cool
bars. If Sky Bar, which has a very cool image only has Camels,
Camel will get the halo effect from that image.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a strategy that liquor companies have used for years.
Hennessy cognac used to pay beautiful models to sit at chic bars
and order their spirits. Impressionable onlookers noticed what the
women ordered and decided they wanted the same.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't used to be like this. Cigarettes started out on TV.
When that was banned in 1971, tobacco companies relied on print
media and billboards to promote their products. But those days
ended abruptly in 1994 when ABC aired an investigative report that
prompted a Food and Drug Administration investigation into tobacco
companies' manufacturing practices.
</P>
<P>
   The charge? Spiking cigarettes with extra nicotine to make them
more addictive. The federal government filed a class action
lawsuit. Cigarette companies settled for $246 billion. They were
also banned from billboard advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow tobacco companies always find new ways to woo smokers.
And non smokers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Evelyn in Manhattan, bartender Freddie Metara has seen
the new campaign in action. ``I know for sure that it has changed a
lot of smokers to Camel,'' he said. ``People who wouldn't go
outside to get more cigarettes, bum from the bar. It's making them
smoke more.''
</P>
<P>
   Metara, who was receiving at least six packs of free Camels a
week, said he had asked his agent to reduce his quota. ``I was
smoking like a nut,'' he admitted. ``You can't keep track. Now I
tell her to give me only one pack.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Itay Hod is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
