<HEADER>
A9257 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-REFUGEES &LR;      04-07 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-REFUGEES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN REFUGEES IN BAQA'A, JORDAN DREAM OF GOING HOME  
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By DIANE HANDAL   
 c.1999Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAQA'A, JORDAN _ The sweet scent of olive trees remains only in
Nareen Obeed's mind, a faint memory of her family's garden in
northern Palestine. To Obeed, that scent wafting through the open
windows of the simple farm house had always meant home, where the
land belonged to her father, his parents and their parents and
grandparents before them.
</P>
<P>
   But now the only scent surrounding Obeed's home today isn't
sweet at all. It is dusty and musty, the blending of dry air with
the wet cement that recently was poured to make cinderblock walls
where tent sides had been.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching a Bic lighter in her left hand, Obeed puffed hard on
her cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Her blue eyes stared straight ahead, her powerful, throaty voice
piercing the quiet room. She talked of her dreams to escape the
two-room hovel that she shares with her 12 children and
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're are not living,'' she said. ``We are just a number. We
have led a miserable life.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the 85,000 fellow Palestinians living in this refugee camp
north of Amman, Obeed spends a lot of time thinking about her
homeland. The disappearance of what was once Palestine from the
geopolitical maps has done little to erase its powerful lure to
these refugees who cling to their dreams of returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever we go, nothing can compensate for our homeland,''
Obeed said. But for now, life here is a grim existence that has
only deteriorated since the 1991 Gulf War between the United States
and Iraq. To escape the U.S. warplanes, Iraqi Muslims fled to join
their Palestinian brethren in Jordan's refugee camps, and
overcrowding, along with street crime, has become a serious issue.
</P>
<P>
   Schools have 50 to 60 children per class. Sewage backs up into
the dirt roads and the water shortage worsens each day. The influx
of the Iraqis also means competition in the already tight job
market.
</P>
<P>
   Obeed's family was among 700,000 Muslims who fled their villages
in land that Israel conquered during the 1948 war of independence.
Driven across the Jordan River, they settled in Karameh until 1967
when Israel invaded Jordan's east bank. This time, the refugees
fled to Baqa'a where the United Nations established a city of 5,000
tents. The population swelled over time, and today's encampment
consists of some 14,000 huts, constructed only recently in concrete
_ a sad testimony to the permanence of this place.
</P>
<P>
   A barber shop, hardware store, bakery and drugstore line the
entrance to the camp. Seven doctors work in two health centers, and
the United Nations runs 16 schools that educate children up to
junior high.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the only road are a bus station and taxi stand
where Jordanian commuters, attracted by the bargain prices for
fresh fruits and vegetables and live chickens, disembark to shop in
the camp's outdoor marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Obeed, 53, lives in a typically communal situation, sharing her
hut with her two daughters, two sons and their wives, and six
grandchildren. Their bedding is piled high in a corner of one room
_ thin mats covered in flowered prints. Three bookcase shelves hold
an old-style television, a small boom box and sundry pieces of
clothing. Pots on the floor collect water that leaks from the tin
roof. A large photograph of Obeed's late husband adorns the
water-stained cement wall near the one small window.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked for the PLO,'' Obeed said, ``and in1979, he was
killed in a plane crash.'' Since then she has supported the family
by working at a U.N. school as a maid. One granddaughter attends
the first grade there. Two others are old enough for kindergarten
but the family cannot afford the cost. ``I make 70 dinar a month
($100), barely enough for bread,'' she said, adding that there are
no jobs for her adult children.
</P>
<P>
   Her neighbors, the Khaleds, are not much better off. On their
wall are arrived 30 years ago with her husband, Mayadh, 55, from
the refugee camp in Hebron. Before his heart attack, Mayadh put
down linoleum floors in the camp. However, many huts still have
dirt floors.
</P>
<P>
   The Khaleds live with their oldest son who takes care of his
parents and 11 siblings. Fatma Khaled weeps openly when talking of
her son, Basil, whom she has not seen in eight years. He was 15
when he walked out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left for school at seven,'' she said, ``took his books,
some change, a small knife_ and never came home. It was March 28,
1991. He went with four of his friends to liberate Palestine and
fight the Jews.'' The boy's mother went to look for him last year
but only heard he was in a prison. What had begun as a young boy's
crusade, an innocent outburst of angry energy, turned into a
lifetime of detention in an Israeli jail.
</P>
<P>
   Never far from the surface here is a bitter resentment against
the Jews who now live in what was once Palestine. ``How do I feel
about them? I am supposed to say they are our cousins,'' said
Obeed, her voice dripping with sarcasm and an eerie laugh. The
coldness in her eyes revealed how she felt about the people who
conquered her land, moved into her home, and vanquished her family.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Obeed home, small children ripped pages from a
newspaper, the only ``toy'' they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young men have no jobs and no hope,'' said Mohammed Amaryeh, a
U.N. interpreter whose family lived in Baqa'a. ``Now gangs, drugs
and alcohol have moved into the camps along with homeless Iraqis
and Egyptians.''.
</P>
<P>
   Youths who complete the U.N. junior high school sometimes go to
vocational schools, said Khaled. But a university education is
usually out of reach. With Jordan's high unemployment rates, jobs
are difficult to find. ``If we're lucky, our children will go to
Russia to study. It's much cheaper there... and the Gulf States to
work as teachers, carpenters, and constructions workers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Escaping seems the only hope for a decent existence but few take
the option. Instead they remained stuck on the dusty streets of
Baqa'a, surrendering to a life of poverty and dreaming of returning
one day to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to go back,'' Obeed said. '' What could be worse than
this?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Diane Handal is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
