<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9258 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-BUSINESS-ETHICS &LR;      04-07 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BUSINESS-ETHICS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SET OF SULLIVAN PRINCIPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By JEROME LUSSIER  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man who wrote the ``Sullivan Principles,'' a
rallying point for protests and economic sanctions against
apartheid in South Africa, is now at work on ethical guidelines for
corporations that deal with regimes considered to be corrupt or
repressive.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Leon Sullivan is writing the code of voluntary ``best
practices'' in collaboration with the State Department.
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat has said the principles
are mostly aimed at fighting bribery, kickbacks and other forms of
corruption thought to have played a key role in the recent economic
turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But though the details of the ``Global Sullivan Principles''
have not been announced, the initiative has already generated some
skepticism, mostly on the part of human rights activists who fear a
global voluntary code will have little impact.
</P>
<P>
   The original Sullivan Principles were written in 1977 as a way
to fight the apartheid government in South Africa without resorting
to withdrawing operations or investments in that country. The six
principles, which dealt mostly with working conditions, sought:
integration of eating facilities and restrooms, nondiscrimination
in employment, equal pay for equal work, training programs to move
blacks into supervisory jobs, and corporate support for
improvements in housing, schools and hospitals for black South
Africans.
</P>
<P>
   The voluntary code proved relatively successful and served as
the inspiration for many subsequent initiatives. In June 1998, the
International Labor Organization adopted a Declaration on
Fundamental Principles and Rights at Work, including: freedom of
association, the right to collective bargaining, the elimination of
all forms of forced labor, abolition of child labor and the
elimination of discrimination in employment.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Craig Forcese, of the Canadian Lawyers
Association for International Human Rights, these guidelines only
address one side of the issue. ``Much attention has been devoted to
workplace human rights standards,'' he said, ``but little has been
done about the corporate complicity with repressive regimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Forcese, who is also a visiting professor of law at the
University of Ottawa, cited Myanmar and Nigeria as examples of
repressive regimes receiving substantial financial support from
multinational corporations. He hopes that global Sullivan
principles will address this issue, and recommend that companies
withdraw from countries that fail to comply with human rights
standards.
</P>
<P>
   However, a ``constructive engagement'' approach in countries
with governments that violate these standards holds that the best
way to encourage democratic reforms is through economic
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign policy experts and human rights activists consider
boycotts and shareholder activism to be more effective, especially
in the case of image-conscious corporations. When the working
conditions of some of the overseas employees of companies like
Nike, the Gap and Wal-Mart, attracted negative publicity, the
companies reacted vigorously to consumer pressure. The Levi-Strauss
company, often presented as a model of progressive management, has
even instituted what it calls ``country assessment guidelines,''
which address ``larger, external issues beyond the control of
individual business partners,'' for example, health and safety
issues and political, economic, and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy experts now express cautious optimism about a
variety of approaches to human rights violations. In 1996, Richard
Rothstein, a professor at Occidental University, said that
``whatever success we may now attribute to Sullivan's principles,
the outlook for today's codes is less hopeful.'' On the crucial
issue of monitoring, Mr. Rothstein added that some kind of
enforcement is needed to make corporate codes effective.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three years later, Mr. Rothstein says he finds
encouragement in the aggressive consumer-education campaigns in
industrialized nations, especially on university campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Because the new Sullivan guidelines are to be voluntary,
monitoring and enforcing them may be difficult. But, as Mr. Forcese
says, companies may comply with voluntary codes to preempt the
imposition of stricter, legally binding rules.
</P>
<P>
   He says tools for effective monitoring are already in place,
citing the independent annual reports of Amnesty International,
Human Rights Watch and the State Department as reliable sources of
information on the situation of human rights abuses worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   With generally agreed-upon guidelines, more and more voters
sensitive about the behavior of their corporate ambassadors and
credible international monitoring, the elements of an effective
supervision of corporate practices are in place. ``All that's
missing,'' Mr. Forcese said, ``is a system.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Jerome Lussier is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
