<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do I use a photograph as my computer's desktop's
background?  &QL; 
A. Once you find a digital photo you like (or have a photo scanned)
and the picture file is on your computer, you're ready.
</P>
<P>
   If you work on a PC with Windows 95 or 98, open the Paint
program (from the Start menu, choose Programs, then Accessories).
In Paint, go to the File menu and select Open; type the picture
file's name in the dialogue box and click on Open. With the picture
open in Paint, go to the File menu and pick Set As Wallpaper. You
can have the picture centered on your screen or you can tile it,
which will repeat the picture across the desktop. If you see a Web
page image that you would like to use as your wallpaper,
right-click on it and pick the Save As Wallpaper command from your
browser.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a Macintosh running OS 8.5, you can select your
picture of choice by going to the Control Panels under the Apple
Menu. Pick the Appearance control panel and click on the Desktop
tab. Click on Place Picture and use the dialogue box to find the
desired photo on your hard drive, or just drag the photo you wish
to use into the sample window. Use the pop-up menu to specify
whether you want it to fill, center or tile on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   For Mac users running OS 8, use the Desktop Pictures control
panel to place your pictures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
