<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     04-07 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN ANY TROOP POLICY REVERSAL, WOULD HAVE A PRECEDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Bill Clinton wants a precedent for any reversal
of his stand against sending American ground forces to Yugoslavia,
he can find it by turning the clock back to an incident that
occurred 50 years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   At that time _ April, 1949 _ the Senate was debating whether to
depart from the republic's long-held opposition to ``entangling
alliances'' and approve U.S. participation in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Dean Acheson was testifying before the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee and Sen. Bourke Hickenlooper, a
Republican from Iowa, was his interrogator.
</P>
<P>
   Is the United States, demanded Hickenlooper, ``going to be
expected to send substantial numbers of troops over there as a more
or less permanent contribution to the development of these
countries' capacity to resist?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer to that question,'' replied Acheson in his most
polished authoritarian manner, ``is a clear and absolute NO.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not one of the most glorious moments in the long career
of Acheson. Less than two years later he returned to the Senate to
seek and win approval for the commitment of U.S. troops to NATO. As
he himself then conceded, his reply to Hickenlooper in 1949 was
``deplorably wrong.'' But he contended that at the time he spoke
there was no commitment for America to send troops to Europe and he
was not convinced such action would be required.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton never has shut the door on troops-to-Europe as tightly
as Acheson appeared to do a half century ago. The president
shrewdly has left it ajar by declaring repeatedly that he had no
``intention'' of sending ground forces into Kosovo. That is not as
final as stating he absolutely would not do so.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is of any consolation to Clinton, historians regard
Acheson as possibly the greatest secretary of state of the 20th
century despite his dramatic and controversial reversal on troops
for NATO. And his boss, Harry Truman, is rated among the near-great
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Washington Post-ABC poll shows that 55 percent of
Americans support the dispatch of ground forces into combat against
Slobodan Milosevic's murderous forces. Acheson and Truman would
have welcomed such support for their monumental efforts to protect
Western Europe and then South Korea from communist aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were lambasted repeatedly by their political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, two of the nation's most prominent and conservative
Republicans, former President Herbert Hoover and Ohio Sen. Robert
A. Taft, launched vitriolic attacks against the whole
internationalist concept of the Truman-Acheson foreign policy.
Other Republicans followed their lead.
</P>
<P>
   A corollary assault was voiced by Joseph P. Kennedy, the
millionaire isolationist who had been Franklin D. Roosevelt's
ambassador to Britain in 1939 when the opening shots were fired in
World War II and whose son John would be elected president in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   When Acheson was denying in 1949 that troops would be sent to
NATO, the United States and its allies were just four years past
World War II, the bloodiest and costliest conflagration in history,
and many Americans were skeptical about joining a European
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cold War was surging across the world, and the
democracies of Western Europe felt threatened by the Soviet Union,
which already had subverted countries behind the ``iron curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   So with U.S. participation, the nations of Western Europe, led
by England and France, had begun to create the alliance that would
become NATO as a bulwark against Soviet expansionism. The initial
concept was that an attack on any one member nation would be an
attack on all of them.
</P>
<P>
   That policy has been broadened with NATO's current determination
to end the cruelty of ethnic cleansing and provide a protected
homeland for hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians driven from
their homes and stripped of all their worldly possessions by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Although American participation in an alliance with Europe was
first broached by British Foreign Secretary Ernest Bevin when Gen.
George C. Marshall was Truman's secretary of state, the proposal
did not reach fruition until Acheson succeeded Marshall in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   By then Acheson already had played a major role in formulating
the Marshall Plan to rebuild war-devastated Western Europe, the
program to aid communist-threatened Greece and Turkey, the Truman
Doctrine to contain communism and the Berlin Airlift to break the
Soviet blockade of that city.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his brilliance, Acheson _ a tall, imposing man whose
clipped mustache resembled that of the villain in an old-fashioned
melodrama and his aloof manner that of a snobbish British
aristocrat _ was easily caricatured and ridiculed by his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, when Richard Nixon was running for vice president on
the Republican ticket, he repeatedly asserted that the Democratic
presidential nominee, Adlai Stevenson, was a graduate of Acheson's
``Cowardly College of Communist Containment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph McCarthy, R-Wis., the unprincipled communist hunter,
was even more vicious. He accused Acheson of treasonous conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of their attacks was in the fact that the 1952 GOP
presidential nominee, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower, had played a major
role in implementing the Truman-Acheson foreign policy and upon
entering the White House rejected attempts by some congressional
Republicans to return to isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   As for Nixon, shortly before he died, he listed Acheson, John
Foster Dulles and Henry Kissinger as the three great secretaries of
state of the post-World-War-II era.
</P>
<P>
   Acheson, to his recent biographer, James Chace, was ``the
secretary of state who created the American world.'' He is
remembered not for his policy switch on troops for NATO but for his
amazing achievements on the international scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1610EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
