<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENDER PERENNIALS ADD LIFE AND COLOR TO THE LONG HOT SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAC GRISWOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garden fashion is fickle. It used to be perennials versus
annuals. Then it was pastels versus hot, read vulgar, colors. Now
that beginning gardeners have learned what a rhizome is, and red
and orange have been reborn as respectable garden colors, it's time
for another category of plants to elbow its way into the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Tender perennials (which survive year round in tropical zones
but not often in New England) bring color and texture to a garden
even in the heat of summer, when the garden droops. Many hardy
perennials like day lilies or peonies flower annually only for a
few weeks. By contrast, most tender perennials do their thing
exuberantly from May until October.
</P>
<P>
   They are the plants with tongue-twisting names that weave their
way through the border, that are the first to sprawl luxuriantly
from urns and pots, that can climb 10 to 20 feet in a season. Their
foliage can be feathery or bold, striped or fringed. Some of them,
like kangaroo paw (Anigozanthus manglesii), look like stuff only a
florist could have. Brugmansia, or angel's trumpet, has an
intoxicating fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   Many tender perennials have been offered as annuals in the
Northeast, though some, like Agastache rupestris, one of the giant
hyssops, a soft salmon-flowered, gray-leaved number, turn out to be
hardy in Zone 5, surprisingly far north.
</P>
<P>
   What the name tender perennial _ an English term _ points toward
is either a new mind-set or an attempt to convince gardeners that
they should pay perennial prices for plants that might well die off
in the cold. In either case, gardeners in the Northeast now seem
willing to take the risk. They may dig up the plants and lug them
indoors for the winter. More likely, they will treat tender
perennials like annuals, but plant them for the fireworks they
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The real roadblock for eager gardeners has been finding the
plants. Until very recently, they were almost impossible to buy at
garden centers stocked with six-packs of cactus-flowering zinnias.
Seed for Coleus Kiwi Fern, say, had to be ordered from specialty
companies and grown at home.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, there are two mail-order catalogs
that offer enough tender perennial plants to satisfy any color-mad
gardener. The Great Plant Co. sells tender perennials from Beds and
Borders, a wholesaler on Long Island. The company's prices start at
$14.50 for three easy-to-grow Salvia Indigo Spires,
4-to-6-foot-tall beauties with violet-blue flower spikes. Blue
Meadow Farm in Montague, Mass., grows its own plants and offers 29
pages of annuals and tender perennials.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Meadow Farm, in Zone 5, is at the coldest extreme for most
tender perennials. What survives the winter at the farm is noted in
the catalog and will be a reasonable bet for most of the Northeast.
Blue Meadow's prices run from $2.50 for a four-pack of an old
cottage garden favorite, corn cockle (Agrostemma githago Ocean
Pearls), which grows to three feet tall and is a great self-sower,
to $7.50 for a three-foot African rarity, Melianthus major, the
peanut butter plant, grown for its jagged, fuzzy foliage. (It
smells more acrid than nutty.)
</P>
<P>
   Steve Frowine, the president of the Great Plant Co., loves
tender perennials for what he calls the ``uninhibited carnival-like
atmosphere, like a vicarious vacation, that they provide.'' His
combination Blazing Sunset ($29) includes six plants that will fill
a 20-inch pot to overflowing by the end of June. The Great Plant
Co. offers them in four-inch plastic pots; $58 buys the plants and
an insulated Thermolite container that could pass for terra cotta.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the Great Plant Co. pot is frothy with rose-pink
Agastache Tutti-Frutti, a giant hyssop that will attract
hummingbirds. Off to one side is Petunia integrifolia TNT, whose
hot pink flowers are only one inch wide. It never ceases flowering
and never needs deadheading. (Shear it instead.) For gardeners in
Zone 7, which would include coastal Long Island and southern
Connecticut, this petunia self-sows.
</P>
<P>
   Front and center in the container is Coleus Alabama Sunset, a
rosy pink-and-yellow stunner. Coleus, of course, will shrivel at
the first frost. But it looks so wonderful, who can complain?
</P>
<P>
   Centaurea gymnocarpa is the other major focal point, with its
arching, deeply dissected white leaves. Alone among the plants in
this pot, it needs pinching to keep it in hand. Twining through its
long fronds is Alternanthera dentata Rubiginosa, which has deep
purple glossy ovate leaves. Below it are the little blue pleated
fan-shaped flowers of Scaevola aemula New Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are familiar with the work of Kathryn Pufahl,
celebrated for her balanced container combinations, will not be
surprised to find that the Great Plant Co.'s offerings come from
her wholesale establishment, Beds and Borders, 36,000 square feet
of greenhouse in Laurel, N.Y., on Long Island. Ms. Pufahl's eye and
determination have changed the face of summer gardening on the East
Coast. She pioneered the introduction of Petunia integrifolia and
the annual black sweet potato vine known as Blackie. And thanks to
her, there are now blue flowers available like the sky-colored
tweedia, Oxypetalum caeruleum, which twines through low plantings,
and the electric-blue Salvia guaranitica.
</P>
<P>
   Brian and Alice McGowan, the owners of Blue Meadow Farm, offer
all these and more. Forthright New Englanders and consummate
plantsmen that they are, they point out that most tender perennials
have only Latin names, which has been as much of a hurdle to public
acceptance as their doubtful hardiness.
</P>
<P>
   But then, who would not master Latin to have these plants?
</P>
<P>
   Tender perennials can be bought by mail order from the Great
Plant Co., Box 1041, New Hartford, Conn. 06057, (800) 441-9788, or
www.greatplants.com (there is no charge for the catalog), and from
Blue Meadow Farm, 184 Meadow Rd., Montague Center, Mass. 01351,
(413) 367-2394, or fax, (413) 367-0116 (catalog, $3).
</P>
<P>
   Nurseries that carry stock from Bed and Borders on Long Island
include: CONNECTICUT Beardsley Gardens, 157 Route 41, Sharon 06069,
(860) 364-0727; McArdle's Florist and Garden Center, 48 Arch St.,
Greenwich 06836-0717, (203) 661-5600; Old Farm Nursery, 158 Lime
Rock Rd. (Route 112), Lakeville 06039, (860) 435-2272.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's Nursery, 1159 Bronson Rd., Fairfield 06430, (203)
259-5609; Robert Treat Farm, 1339 New Haven Ave., Milford 06460,
(203) 878-4270; Twombly Nursery, 163 Barn Hill Rd., Monroe 06468,
(203) 261-2133.
NEW YORK STATE The Bayberry, Montauk Highway, Amagansett 11930,
(516) 267-3000; Hicks Nursery, 100 Jericho Turnpike, Westbury
11590, (516) 334-0066; Lynch's Garden Center, 175 North Sea Rd.,
Southampton 11968, (516) 283-5515; Marder's, Snake Hollow Rd.,
Bridgehampton 11932, (516) 537-3700; Martin Viette Nurseries, Route
25A, East Norwich 11732, (516) 922-5530; Paul's Nursery in Pine
Hollow, 841 Pulaski Rd., Greenlawn 11740, (516) 261-1148.
Poundridge Nursery, 6 Pound Ridge Rd., Pound Ridge 10576, (914)
764-5781; Rosedale Nurseries, 51 Saw Mill River Rd., Route 9A,
Hawthorne 10532, (914) 769-1300.
PENNSYLVANIA Fort Washington Garden Mart, 488 Bethlehem Pike, Fort
Washington 19034, (215) 646-3336; J. Franklin Styer Nursery, 914
Baltimore Pike, Route 1, Concordville 19331, (610) 459-2400.  &QL; 
NEW JERSEY Williams Nursery, 524 Springfield Ave., Westfield 07090,
(908) 232-2852.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
4
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
