<SLUG> BC-CIR-PINBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL PINBALL WIZARDRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Releasing the plunger and launching the silver ball into play.
Listening to the raucous sounds of points piling up. Snapping the
flippers to bat the ball up to the bumpers. Shooting at virtual
images? Pinball may never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Pinball 2000, brought out last month by Williams Electronics
Games of Chicago, mixes decades-old pinball mechanics with the
latest digital three-dimensional technology. It has traditional
features but bolsters them with sensors and virtual images that
place the player in a video battle to save Earth from invading
Martians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is a major step forward,'' said Tim Arnold, a member
of the important-sounding Las Vegas Pinball Collector's Club, which
Arnold described as a bunch of guys hanging out and having fun.
``Pinball used to be about a ball on a painted surface. Now it's a
ball in the middle of a movie,'' he said, ``with a plot and
graphics and video.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinball 2000 looks pretty much like most other arcade games on
the outside, but it uses a video monitor to produce 3-D images that
are reflected off the glass surface of the playing table. ``The
mind combines the reflection with the playing field beneath it,''
explained John Popadiuk, the game designer who headed the team that
developed Pinball 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The design started with the traditional mechanical features:
flippers, bumpers, targets and a ball. (The ball has been an
industry standard since 1934: 3 ounces of chrome steel, 1.063
inches in diameter.)
</P>
<P>
   A series of optic and magnetic sensors track the ball as it
caroms around the playing field. The system's heart is a
200-megahertz motherboard, flash memory and software. The computer
coordinates the moving parts of the game with the 3-D images of
Martians, spaceships, rockets and buildings to produce an
interactive effect.
</P>
<P>
   One traditional feature is even completely virtual in the game _
the spinner, the panel that rotates when the ball hits it. Sensors
imbedded in the playing field time the trajectory of the ball,
Popadiuk said. As the ball shoots under the spinner's projected
image, it makes it rotate like the real thing. Even though the ball
never hits anything physical, the virtual spinner racks up points.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the ball ``hits'' hundreds of other virtual images in
the game. When real stand-up targets in the playing field behind
the virtual images are hit, the computer launches a rocket or
destroys a bright green Martian. ``The physical design of the game
is simple because the virtual images provide the complexity,''
Popadiuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Players of Pinball 2000 work their way through several scenes,
or levels, including ones in which they are saving the White House
or Paris. The ultimate level is an attack on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, which has made pinball machines under its name and the
Bally label for 52 years, is selling the game to arcades and
distributors. Fanatics who must have one in their home should be
ready to shell out about $5,000. But it will still cost only 50
cents for three balls at an arcade. Williams has more information
on its Web site (www.pinball2000.com).
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, who restores pinball machines and keeps his collection
of almost 1,000 in an empty aircraft hanger, won a scoring contest
when Pinball 2000 had a premiere in Las Vegas. ``It's very
juvenile, with lots of gratuitous violence and things blowing up,''
he said. ``I really enjoyed it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
