<HEADLINE>
COOKIE POPS A SWEET TREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lane Bowles of Arlington, Texas, saw our request for cookie pops
using candy bars and sent along a Pillsbury recipe.
</P>
<P>
   PEANUT BUTTER COOKIE POPS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine or butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder 1/2 teaspoon baking soda 1/4 teaspoon
salt 10 wooden sticks 10 Snickers or Milky Way fun-size candy bars
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 375 degrees. In large bowl, combine sugar, brown
sugar, margarine, peanut butter, vanilla and egg; beat well.
Lightly spoon flour into measuring cup; level off. Add flour,
baking powder, baking soda and salt; mix well. Securely insert a
wooden stick into small end of each candy bar, forming a lollipop.
Shape about 1/3 cup dough smoothly around each candy bar, making
sure bar is completely covered. Place 4 inches apart on ungreased
cookie sheets. Bake at 375 for 13 to 16 minutes, or until golden
brown. Cool 10 minutes; remove from cookie sheets. Cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per pop: 370 calories, 19 grams fat, 45
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 23 milligrams cholesterol,
308 milligrams sodium, 46 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   JO ANN'S MARGARITA PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce container nondairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   2 dry packets margarita mix
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 chocolate or graham cracker crumb crust
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 4 ingredients and spoon into crust. Refrigerate or
freeze. Garnish with lime slices, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Request:
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bowles of Arlington, Texas, used to make a cookie in the
1970s that had an oatmeal-type base and top, and a fudgy center.
Lost the recipe when a similar mix became available, marketed under
the name Fudge Jumbles.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
