<HEADLINE>
CHAOS AND SENTIMENT FRAME THE TODDLERS' CLASS PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When little Sydney Stegint makes her first
million, people will want to see this picture. The same thing will
happen when Wade Westerheide gets drafted by the Texas Rangers and
when Hayden Redmon is elected to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``People'' magazine will want their class picture.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it works. We all have them taken, we all forget them.
We shove them under a bed until, years later, we get sentimental or
somebody does something famous.
</P>
<P>
   By then, we have forgotten how they came together. We have
forgotten the Doris Atwoods who combed our hair, the Merci Henrys
who tucked in our shirt, the Bebe Behelers who wiped our noses.
</P>
<P>
   This story is about how they pull it off. It isn't always a
pretty picture.
</P>
<P>
   We're inside University United Methodist Child Development
Center in Fort Worth. It's near 9 a.m. on a Thursday morning. The
photographer is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Till Hezel arrives with white umbrellas, giant lights, much
commotion and Mr. Mouse, an 8-year-old, fur-covered, glass-eyed
squeaky thing he bought at a photographers' convention. ``Where
else?''
</P>
<P>
   Picture Day comes to University four times a year: Portraits in
the fall, on a pony in winter, all together in April, with a teddy
bear in late spring. The center's director is a picture person.
</P>
<P>
   Beheler has every class picture her 13-year-old daughter has
ever taken, including the one from the year she tripped and had to
be photographed with a fat lip. Beheler bought it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are like that. So we find teachers Atwood and Henry
improvising the activities in the 2-year-olds' room. They stay away
from markers, Play-Doh and sand. Keeping a kid clean; that's the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The salt table is safe. So are Mr. Potato Head, the ``dress-up''
clothes, the jungle gym, construction paper and colored tape. The
clock ticks, the teachers watch. They break up a fight over the Sit
'N Spin.
</P>
<P>
   They have heard that the toddlers are going first. It's usually
the infants, but somebody's mother is late, so mixed reports come
down the hall. Snack time arrives. Peanut butter is out of the
question. Today, it's crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's their turn. They wander down the hall past the
cotton-ball bunnies on the toddlers' door, past the paper Easter
baskets on the wall, into Room 114.
</P>
<P>
   The children stand around the giant lights like moths. Their
teachers swoop: Atwood rakes every little head, combing hair. Henry
brushes off cracker crumbs and stuffs in shirttails. Another
teacher yanks the ``dress-up'' apron away from the future
millionaire. The photographer lines them up.
</P>
<P>
   Wait! Beheler spies a dirty nose.
</P>
<P>
   Wait! He's still dirty. The someday U.S. senator flinches under
a second scrub. Hezel waits with Mr. Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Then all of a sudden, just like that, it's over.
</P>
<P>
   The children leave, and Beheler sits. There's a touch of
perspiration on her brow. Hezel sits beside her. She tells him she
has a book in her office of every class picture taken since she's
been director. She gets sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``They change so fast.'' She wipes her brow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you never get those times back.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
