<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-RESEARCH-LIBRARY-     04-07 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-RESEARCH-LIBRARY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHIVISTS FACE CHALLENGE IN PRESERVING DIGITAL COLLECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The research library of today presents a comforting image: cool
marble stairs, orderly rows of volumes, a familiar, musty scent.
But gradually, as computer work stations replace stacks and the
clack-clacking of keyboards is heard above hushed voices, that
image is becoming a quaint reminder of a closing era.
</P>
<P>
   Research libraries, of course, are the warehouses of collective
scholarly memory, and librarians take seriously their obligation to
preserve academic material for future generations. Increasingly,
research materials are being added to collections in digital form,
through things like subscriptions to electronic journals.
</P>
<P>
   And a consequence of this technological wave is a persistent
debate over how the library materials will be preserved to create
the archives of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of preserving digital collections is complex and
vexing. First, there is the question of what hardware and software
to use. Digital archives are more vulnerable than their paper
counterparts. Not only do both computer hardware and software
quickly become obsolete, but the durability of magnetic storage
media, like tapes and disks, is limited.
</P>
<P>
   The storage issue cannot be resolved without considering the
question of ownership. Digital material is often not acquired by
libraries in the same way that paper material is, because libraries
often buy access to digital data housed on computers elsewhere.
That raises thorny legal and economic questions about who is
responsible for preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Reports and discussions on archiving and preserving digital
collections abound. ``We talk about it every day,'' said Ann
Okerson, associate university librarian at Yale University. ``Every
minute of every day.'' Still, no one has come up with a clear
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Digital collections are growing more quickly than many
librarians anticipated. In a study published last December and
commissioned by the Research Libraries Group, a consortium of 160
research institutions worldwide, nearly every library that
responded said it was handling electronic material or expected to
be within three years. But the survey also showed that the
libraries were not sure about how to preserve digital materials to
insure their availability in the future even as such materials
become a larger part of their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know libraries haven't stepped up to figure out how to do
it,'' said Donald Waters, director of the Digital Library
Federation, an alliance of large research libraries. ``We have to
solve this problem in order to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem is the fact that much of the digital
information that libraries license resides on servers maintained by
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fees we pay are mostly fees for access to online resources
maintained elsewhere,'' Ms. Okerson said. ``If it crashed, we'd be
in deep trouble. I don't know what we'd do. It's pretty sobering.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Okerson said that when she bought an electronic subscription
these days, she asked a series of questions: ``Will there be an
archive in perpetuity? Is whoever is creating these resources
committed to that, and how will I get at that information over
time? What will it take? Those are the big questions, and I don't
see many answers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic materials are a growing part of library budgets.
Yale, for example, spent just under $1 million last year on
electronic journals, called e-journals, and on databases and
reference services, double what it was spending three years ago.
That represents about 8 percent of its library acquisitions budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the digital age has also radically changed the nature of
library purchases. A library does not generally put its electronic
purchases on its shelves for perpetuity, as it would with a
reference book or issues of a scholarly journal. Most online
purchases come in the form of licenses. That means libraries buy
the right to look at something that has a permanent home on
somebody else's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Although licensing contracts vary, journal publishers generally
allow each reader at an institution with a license to read or
download material for personal use but not for wide distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ownership versus non-ownership takes you into one of the
hearts of the archiving problem,'' Ms. Okerson said. ``I don't know
how you can preserve something you don't own.''
</P>
<P>
   Many libraries now subscribe to journals in both print and
electronic form, which drives up their costs but gives them a sense
of security. But resources ranging from indexing services to
electronic journals are increasingly ``born digital,'' as a
Web-based scientific paper, say, or an electronic database.
</P>
<P>
   Librarians are mindful of the fact that materials born digital
have tremendous advantages for scholars. A Web-based research
article, for example, is filled with easily accessible links to
other documents, known in the hard-copy realm of scholarship as
references.
</P>
<P>
   Documents that are filled with links pose yet another
preservation problem because keeping an electronic research paper
vital and relevant means keeping its links alive. But as anyone who
has spent time on the ever-changing World Wide Web can confirm,
there is little guarantee that today's healthy link will not be
tomorrow's ``requested object does not exist on this server''
message.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of Web-based electronic research papers
also contain still or video images or sound. That could easily be a
problem if, for instance, the current technology for listening to
sound and viewing images alters drastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we increasingly as scholars rely on various digital
resources and those aren't preserved, we won't have that kind of
accountability and trail of how research develops,'' said Margaret
Hedstrom, an associate professor at the School of Information at
the University of Michigan at Ann Arbor. ``It's both the loss of
the information and the whole validation of scholarship. Those are
the implications of not solving this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As questions about ownership and the use of these resources are
being resolved, librarians must also consider the question of what
storage medium to choose. It is not a simple matter of putting
documents onto a CD-ROM, partly because storage media change
relatively rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   One approach is called migration, a term that is used broadly to
describe several different methods for transferring digital
information from old technology to new technology.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
