<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK WOULD SOLVE JEFF BECK'S CASH-FLOW PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to feel sorry for Jeff Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Now 54, Beck long ago earned his place in the pantheon of great
rock guitarists. He was in the Yardbirds, one of the most important
rock groups ever; he can still play like nobody's business; and
he's still popular enough to headline large American venues.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Beck's lot, we're told, is a tough one. It seems ol'
Jeff is running short on money, something he has mentioned in
numerous interviews to promote his latest CD, ``Who Else!'' He says
that his financial future is not stable, and that as far back as
his 1995 tour with Santana, he was desperate for money.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he's proud of the new CD (which he should be), but
if it tanks he's going to be in some serious trouble _ for a rock
star, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   What caused these financial woes? Drugs? Unscrupulous
management?
</P>
<P>
   Um, no.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Beck is broke because Jeff Beck spent much of the past, oh,
19 years ``not working very much.'' ``Who Else!'' is only his fifth
solo CD since 1980, and his tours have been even more sporadic.
</P>
<P>
   I remember one interview he gave to ``Musician'' 10 or so years
ago: The writer went to Beck's centuries-old mansion in the English
countryside, where he found the musician puttering away on one of
his fleet of antique cars. Beck said he was not really that
interested in making music any.MDNM/more, didn't need it, didn't
much care, and would be happy under a car hood for the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   About the time Beck was seriously slacking off, his peer Steve
Winwood was embarking on one of the biggest comebacks in rock
history. Like Beck, Winwood first became popular during the
mid-'60s. He recorded several classic records with Traffic, but
after that group broke up in 1974, he released only one solo LP.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly broke, he put out ``Arc of a Diver'' in 1981, recasting
himself as a more contemporary, R&AMP;B-drenched pop-rocker. It worked:
The record was a major hit, and he followed it with four CDs (and
as many tours) in nine years. And suddenly, Steve Winwood was a
very rich man. Amazing what a little effort can do.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling Beck's old attitude _ and how Winwood dusted himself
off _ it's hard to work up much sympathy for Beck's current woes.
At the dawn of the '80s, with several popular jazz-fusion LPs
recently behind him, he could easily have continued to tour and
record regularly, thereby keeping at least a large percentage of
his fan base and assuring himself a steady income.
</P>
<P>
   And even if he couldn't earn the sort of money a Mick Jagger or
an Eric Clapton could, he was certainly going to make one heck of a
lot more than you or I could make.
</P>
<P>
   He chose not to, and he paid the price in lost income and lost
fans. Very few people can go away indefinitely without experiencing
lower CD sales and fewer people showing up at their shows. It's
just human nature: If you aren't there, I'll listen to someone who
is.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nobody is saying that had Jeff Beck paid more attention to
his career he'd fill arenas at up to $300 per ticket, but then
again, he probably wouldn't be whining about his shaky bank
account, either.
</P>
<P>
   Say this for the Stones _ and Rod Stewart, and Sting, and
Aerosmith, and plenty of other veterans: They work. Hard. Year
after year, they get out there, recording and touring.
</P>
<P>
   The Stones, in fact, have been touring since the fall of 1997 _
not bad for a bunch of old guys who have millions in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that's WHY they have millions in the bank. They earned
it. .MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9291 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-RESEARCH-LIBRARY-     04-07 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-RESEARCH-LIBRARY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: new technology.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Migration can be as simple as transferring data from an older
storage medium to new storage formats,'' Dr. Hedstrom said, ``like
the transfer from seven- to nine-track tapes during the 1960s, or
the transfer from nine-track tapes to tape cartridges during the
1980s and 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   The process of migration grows more complicated when the
information that is transferred cannot be retrieved or used without
specific software. If documents created by an obsolete word
processing program cannot run on a newer system, then the documents
are converted to newer formats. A number of digital archives both
in and outside academia have already been preserved in this way.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts say migration has limitations. ``We can keep
the old stuff alive, but the problem is that that means
translation, and translation is always going to lose something,''
said Jeff Rothenberg, a senior computer scientist at the Rand Corp.
who has written widely on the topic of preserving digital archives.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg pointed out that migration means converting every
document in a collection every time the software that created it or
the hardware that can read it becomes outdated. ``You will have to
spend effort and energy and time every time you go through one of
these migrations,'' he said, ``because if you don't, and a document
is needed two years later, it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the migration approach is ``better then nothing,''
Rothenberg added, it is labor-intensive and very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg favors a method called emulation; under that policy,
libraries would continue to store documents in their original
forms, along with the original software that created them, and
software would be created to allow a more advanced machine to mimic
the obsolete hardware. With emulation, for instance, documents
created with Word Perfect 2.0, which ran on the DOS operating
system, would remain stored as is and an emulation program would
allow a future machine to read the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Emulation, Rothenberg said, is a tried and true technique in the
computer industry for other purposes. Anyone who has installed a
copy of Virtual PC on a Macintosh to run software written for the
Windows operating system has experienced emulation first-hand.
</P>
<P>
   But whether emulation will work for preservation is still
unproven. ``We've emulated old computers on newer computers,'' he
said, ``but we haven't designed an emulator for a current machine
that's supposed to run on a future machine we haven't designed yet.
That makes people skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   To assess the feasibility of emulation would require an intense
effort by computer scientists, Rothenberg said. But there seems to
be little interest in such research. Rothenberg is one of only a
few computer scientists looking for solutions to the problems of
digital preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Emulation turns out to be a very difficult computer science
problem, Rothenberg said. ``Unfortunately computer scientists
haven't gotten very excited about it,'' he explained. ``It just
hasn't caught the attention of the community yet. What computer
scientists do not like to do much is look into the past, because
that isn't very exciting. But we should be excited by dealing with
the past by looking into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A low-tech solution would be to print all digital documents, but
Rothenberg is not impressed with that suggestion, calling such a
plan little more than a ``rear-guard action.''
</P>
<P>
   He also dismissed what he called the ``computer museum''
approach, which would call for libraries to accumulate rooms filled
with obsolete equipment for reading old documents.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, of the Digital Library Federation, said he believed that
a palette of preservation tools would eventually emerge, based on
the concepts of emulation and migration and on what he called
``archaeology,'' the use of various techniques to recover lost
data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bunch of different problems so it will be a bunch of
different solutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More work will be required up front to insure a collection's
longevity, he said, adding, ``Librarians will work with creators so
they create documents that will last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
