<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRY-AND-LOUISE-NYTS     04-07 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRY-AND-LOUISE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CONTINUING SAGA OF HARRY &AMP; LOUISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Health Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    From coast to coast, a growing tide of dissatisfaction is
sweeping through the medical marketplace. Complaints against HMOs
and other health insurers are on the rise, and doctors and patients
across the country are registering their displeasure with a
managed-care system gone awry.
 &HT;    Somehow, just four years after ``Harry and Louise'' helped
trounce President Clinton's plans for healthcare reform, the public
is fuming over, well ... healthcare reform.
 &HT;    You remember Harry and Louise: the affable all-American couple
fraught with concern about the Clinton health plan and its promise
to introduce the dreaded M-word to American medicine. In a series
of national television ads, they shared their fears about the
perils of managed care with the public, cringing at the thought of
medical spending caps and a government healthcare bureaucracy.
 &HT;    The congenial pair appeared in a $17-million media campaign
funded by the Health Insurance Association of America. Their
mission was simple: to frighten the public into opposing the
Clinton plan by dwelling on the negative aspects of managed care.
 &HT;    It was an easy task. All they had to do was focus attention on
the reduction in health services that would accompany any effort to
rein in the nation's skyrocketing medical costs. Then they could
blame these sacrifices on the Clinton plan.
 &HT;    What Harry and Louise didn't mention was that some form of
restrictions -- or healthcare rationing -- was inevitable if we
were to avoid bankrupting the country. The nation simply couldn't
afford unlimited medical spending, which was already consuming
about 14 percent of our national economic output.
 &HT;    So in 1993, the president assembled some of the best minds in
the country in order to come up with a solution to the problem. The
result of their labors was the Clinton health plan.
 &HT;    Although the plan faced opposition from multiple constituencies
-- including the Chamber of Commerce and the National Association
of Manufacturers -- the HIAA, a trade group representing health
insurers, spent more on broadcast ads than any other group involved
in the debate. In the end, they succeeded in derailing the Clinton
plan, using two actors (whose names really were Harry and Louise)
to touch a chord in the American psyche.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, that chord still reverberates.
 &HT;    The irony is that the issues that rattled Harry and Louise are
the same issues that people are complaining about today. The only
difference is that now, instead of blaming the government, they're
blaming the new ``bad guys'': the HMOs. What the public is missing
in all this is the simple fact that somebody has to be the bad guy.
If we're to keep the country solvent, someone has to do the dirty
work of cutting medical expenses -- there's only so much money in
the pot, and we can't afford to pay for everything everyone wants
in terms of medical services.
 &HT;    So why are people still complaining?
 &HT;    Because when it comes to health care, the public has yet to come
to terms with a basic rule of economics: you can't spend more than
you've got. We recognize this reality in other sectors of the
economy, but medicine is often treated as if it's exempt from the
laws of economics because it deals with the sanctity of human
lives.
 &HT;    Yet even in life-and-death situations, someone has to pay the
bill. And the bill keeps getting larger.
 &HT;    This is why some form of rationing is inevitable. Indeed, we're
already rationing health care -- by denying health insurance
benefits to 40 million Americans, for example, we're greatly
reducing their access to medical services. We have the ability to
provide universal coverage, of course, but we'd have to allocate
billions of dollars to pay for it. Thus far, the nation has chosen
spend its healthcare dollars elsewhere.
 &HT;    Insured patients must also deal with the rationing of medical
services. When HMOs set limits for hospital stays, for instance,
they're rationing access to inpatient care. The same is true when
they require pre-certification for surgical procedures, allowing
coverage for some procedures and denying it for others.
 &HT;    Largely as a result of such controls, physicians and patients
are filing numerous complaints to state regulators over issues like
fee disputes and denial of care. But a more ominous sign is
emerging as well. Whereas complaints in the past tended to focus on
who would pay for a given medical service, insurance regulators
report that now it's a matter of whether the service is provided at
all.
 &HT;    While adapting to this restrictive environment, patients must
also contend with the fact that medical rationing is occurring in a
haphazard fashion. This is precisely what the Clinton
administration sought to avoid by developing a comprehensive
healthcare reform plan in 1993. It was an enormous undertaking, and
the plan represented the most significant effort undertaken so far
to reform our troubled healthcare system.
 &HT;    But it never had much of a chance, largely because it had to
reconcile the needs of too many different interest groups with
conflicting priorities.
 &HT;    Harry and Louise also did their part, misleading the public by
acting as if the hard choices could be avoided with a laissez-faire
approach to the healthcare problem. That helped kill the Clinton
plan, and it stopped the government from addressing a critical
issue.
 &HT;    Still, the situation isn't a total loss. Today, the perky couple
is probably at the head of the pack complaining about the cost
controls and spending caps imposed by their former employers in the
insurance industry.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1999 Stephen L. Cohen
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Stephen L. Cohen, M.D., is a medical journalist based in New
York.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
