<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9314 &Cx1f; tab-z
r c &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     04-07 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV25-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., APR. 25, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am building a large rectangular shaped desk and the
two-inch thick top will have rounded corners. I plan to cover this
top with Formica and I also want to cover the edges with the same
plastic laminate, using a regular contact cement. Should I apply
the laminate to the edges or the top first, and how do I handle
bending the edge strips around the curved corners without having to
use clamps to hold the strips in place?
</P>
<P>
   A: Apply the laminate to the edges first. Cut each strip about
1/2 inch wider than the edge of the top so that the plastic will be
wide enough to overlap the top and bottom edges of the core
material by about 1/4 inch. Apply two coats of contact cement to
the edge of the core material (two coats are usually needed because
edges are more porous) and one coat to the back of the Formica
strip. Allow each coat to dry for about 30 minutes, then press the
plastic strip in place against the edge so it sticks up about 1/4
inch above the top surface. When you get to the curved corners use
a heat gun set at `LOW' to heat the Formica and make it more
pliable (wear gloves to protect your hands). Use a hard rubber
roller to press it firmly against the edge and insure a good bond,
then use a flat file or router to trim off excess plastic that
sticks up above and below the core material.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are planning to paint the outside of our house and will
have to use a tall extension ladder to reach the higher portions.
The problem is that most of the ground around the base of the house
is bare soil around flower beds and bushes, so I am nervous about
my husband using the ladder when it is resting on this ground. Is
there some way to do this safely?
</P>
<P>
   A: Climbing a tall ladder always involves a certain amount of
danger, but it can be safe if you avoid working on windy or wet
days, and if reasonable precautions are taken. When necessary to
set the ladder up on soft soil, place a wide, one-inch-thick board
or piece of 3/4 inch plywood down first, then set the legs of the
ladder on top of this. For additional safety drive a heavy peg or
short length of pipe into the ground about one or two feet behind
the ladder, then lash the bottom rung of the ladder to this peg in
order to keep the ladder from slipping off the board.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our cabinets are made of some kind of molded plastic and have
a simulated wood grain finish that has begun to wear off in several
places. I decided to paint them and tried applying an off-white
latex paint on one of the panels, but the paint didn't seem to bond
very well. Is there a special type of paint I should be using?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's possible that the trouble is not just with the type
paint used, but also with the preparation of the old surface. Scrub
thoroughly with a good household detergent, then sand with a medium
grit paper and scrape off any old finish that is not adhering
tightly. Apply a first coat of a shellac-based sealer and primer
such as BIN to insure a good bond, then paint with two coats of
semi-gloss enamel. I would recommend an alkyd paint, rather than a
latex.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The wrought iron railings on each side of our entrance stoop
are peeling and showing a lot of rust. What should I do before
repainting them, and what can I do to prevent further rusting?
</P>
<P>
   A: Use a wire brush and coarse steel wool to scrape off as much
of the old paint and loose rust as you can. Then wipe down with
mineral spirits or similar solvent and apply a coat of rust
converter (sold in paint and hardware stores). This converts the
rust to a solid oxide that also forms an excellent base for
painting over _ and it helps prevent further rusting. After this
dries, paint with two coats of a rust-preventative metal enamel
that is especially designed for protecting against rust.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING A HEAT GUN TO APPLY PLASTIC
LAMINATE'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Plastic laminate can be bent around curves more easily
if heat is applied to make it more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
