<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUSIONFOOD-ART-W/RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLAVORS OF FUSION: AUTHOR HUGH CARPENTER BRINGS DIVERSE CUISINE
TO MAINSTREAM MENUS &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A touch of Thai peanut sauce on chicken salad.
Moroccan spices on Texas barbecue. Cilantro pesto on pasta.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 10 or 15 years, inventive chefs and home cooks
have played the mix-and-match game with cross-cultural combinations
that have worked their way into our everyday menus.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Carpenter, former California restaurateur who writes
cookbooks and teaches cooking classes in the Napa Valley, was one
of the first to fuse Asian and American ingredients, techniques and
style.
</P>
<P>
   His award-winning cookbooks ``Pacific Flavors'' and ``Chopstix''
helped introduce fusion cuisine. While in Houston recently to teach
classes at Le Panier, LaVerl Daily's cooking school, Carpenter took
a fresh look at the trend that became a cooking revolution.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Fusion Food Cookbook,'' published in 1994 by Artisan, was
``a little ahead of its time. Everyone was confused about what
`fusion' meant,'' Carpenter said. ``Fusion received something of a
bad name because some young cooks who are not chefs yet try all
sorts of bizarre combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   First you have to be thoroughly grounded in the foundations of
cooking and understand the different cuisines before you can put
together elements of other cultures as trained chefs would, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if you go to the trendy restaurants in France, they're
using Asian ingredients such as ginger and lemongrass.''
</P>
<P>
   Although fusion started with an East-West mixture of Asian and
American, it applies to techniques or ingredients from any other
cooking tradition _ Southwestern, Caribbean, Mediterranean ...
</P>
<P>
   Fusion fits right in with the current main trend in food that
Carpenter sees _ Americans want more flavor.
</P>
<P>
   At home, you can cook something in an authentic way, but give it
a little twist, he said. Make pesto sauce with cilantro instead of
basil. Or add fresh ginger to guacamole (slice the ginger thinly,
and force it through a garlic press). Rub the top of a meatloaf
with hoisin sauce, then oven-roast it.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, with its ethnic diversity and influences from Mexico,
the Southwest, and Chinese, Vietnamese and other Asian cuisines, is
a city where there will be a lot of melding of cooking traditions,
he said. He marveled at the Mexican food at Taco Milagro, Robert
Del Grande's Mexican restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``California Mexican food is still mired in Chilies Rellenos
made the traditional way, stuffed with cheese and Ortega sauce
poured over it. At Taco Milagro, they were stuffed with chihuahua
cheese, dried apricots and pecans with a guajillo chili sauce _
just astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fusion recipes have lengthy lists of exotic ingredients
that are not always available in supermarkets, Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   In his new cookbooks, which he does with his wife, photographer
Teri Sandison, Carpenter is simplifying recipes so there are fewer
ingredients and easier cooking techniques. Books in the recent
``Hot'' series (``Hot Chicken,'' ``Hot Pasta,'' ``Hot Wok,'' ``Hot
Barbecue'' and the newest, ``Hot Vegetables'') contain some
fusion-style recipes. They were published by Ten Speed Press;
$17.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter is concentrating on using only ingredients available
in supermarkets in his new books, including ``Great Ribs,'' to be
published in May by Ten Speed Press ($14.95). His next series of
books is on fast cooking. It will start with ``Fast Appetizers,''
to be published in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markets have really improved since ``Fusion'' came out in
1994. Almost every supermarket has soy sauce, oyster sauce, hoisin,
sesame oil, dried anchos and chipotles in adobo. There's been an
explosion in the availability of tropical fruits, mushrooms and
other varieties of vegetables _ particularly Asian vegetables. And
there's a vast increase in the quality and quantity of bottled
condiments _ chutneys, infused oils, salsas and ethnic condiments
such as Asian chili sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusion is more than a trend, Carpenter said. The ``forest'' is
fusion food, and the ``trees'' are the different authentic ethnic
ways of cooking. It will continue to be popular, he said,
especially cross-cultural cooking emphasizing freshness and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Fusion carries over to all his cookbooks. In ``Great Ribs,'' for
example, there's a mango sauce for ribs. In ``Hot Pasta,''
California Lo Mein blends spaghetti with Chinese long beans, baby
bok choy, ginger, orange zest, rice wine, sesame oil and Chinese
sauces.
</P>
<P>
   Fusion dishes are featured during Carpenter's eighth annual Camp
Napa Culinary Adventure. Five sessions are planned from June to
October for the food and wine adventure. Camp starts with a
reception at Carpenter's home in Oakville, Calif. It includes a
five-day tour of fine wineries and cooking classes hosted by
Cakebread Cellars. For information, call 888-999-HUGH (4844) or
write Camp Napa Culinary, P.O Box 114, Oakville, Calif. 94562.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
