<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A strong foundation for life
</P>
<P>
   (``Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Jerry Washington
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   EAST POINT, Ga. _ The sound of spring is in the air, and I am
about to reach a major plateau in my life. I'm turning 40 on May
21.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, it's hard to believe that I have come this far,
growing up poor
</P>
<P>
   on a dirt road next to a sewage treatment plant in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the small, tight community on 19th Terrace, 17th
Avenue and 15th Avenue, I received the total care of a community
that takes care of their little ones.
</P>
<P>
   I owe a world of debt to many people in my hometown for my
proper upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   I must thank Mrs. Sarah Pettis, my very first teacher, for
making kindergarten a wonderful, warm experience. She was the spark
that made learning real.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bonner, my middle school counselor/teacher, was a
lifesaver. She made the turbulent days of integration, puberty and
growing up poor a tolerable experience.
</P>
<P>
   Her kindness and her interest in me helped build up my
self-esteem. She nearly succeeded in adopting me. I am eternally
grateful for the love she so willingly gave.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Burroughs was a community activist, a mother, a teacher, a
businesswoman who took the time to invite an inner-city kid to her
home to sit at her table and experience dinner with the whole
family.
</P>
<P>
   She did this on a regular basis. I learned a lot from these
formal and sometimes informal dinners.
</P>
<P>
   I was allowed to share my views concerning current events and
family matters. We got to know each other a little better, thus
bringing us closer to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Burroughs holds a special place in my heart. Her family is
the epitome of what families should be.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bolden is a self-made man. He is the father of six children.
He is a hard worker and a loving husband.
</P>
<P>
   He would have family worship on Friday nights. He was a man I
trusted and valued as a person. I'll always appreciate the
man-to-man talks and direction he attempted to bring to me.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bolden provided a strong and positive role model for many of
us in the neighborhood. His children still call him Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   There are other people like the Boldens who provided wisdom and
understanding whenever I needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennedy was another soul who was a source of comfort and
moral support. She treated me like an adult, which allowed me to
see things more clearly.
</P>
<P>
   I'll always remember the churches I attended _ Mt. Olive Baptist
and First Baptist Piney Grove _ for nurturing and providing a safe
place in the midst of an urban environment.
</P>
<P>
   My life is for the best. I am self-employed, a father, husband,
lobbyist, writer and friend of the friendless.
</P>
<P>
   My attitude is on an even keel, although I have a short fuse
when it comes to ignorant and selfish people. I think we can all
lend a hand and give each other the kind of help we all need every
once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   Someone else who has inspired me is Dr. Kathleen Wright, who
insisted that we help each other and that we become friends. Dr.
Wright's example has led me to become active in many social and
civic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to her, I have coached young men and women to excellence.
I am teaching parenting classes throughout the city of East Point.
</P>
<P>
   I've made it my business to lobby for special causes, especially
as they relate to community, children and senior citizen affairs.
</P>
<P>
   From Sarah Pettis to Dr. Wright, from Fort Lauderdale to East
Point, I thank those people who have made turning 40 a nice way to
celebrate life.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
