<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROTEST THAT WON'T FUEL CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet as a rallying point for causes has as much
potential for silliness as it does for seriousness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest exercise in silliness is an exhortation to join
something called the ``Great Gas Out'' on April 30 to protest
soaring petrol prices. It's pitiful in a way, because it reflects
its organizers' lack of understanding of economics in general and
energy economics in particular. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The premise apparently is that if everybody stays away from
gasoline stations three weeks from Friday, this will somehow send
producers, refiners and marketers a message: Price relief is
possible if Americans stop consuming gasoline for just a day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was just ONE day when no one purchased any
gasoline,'' says one of the e-mail recruiting messages, ``prices
would drop drastically.'' The advisory _ somewhat curiously _
further advises prospective recruits to buy gasoline either on the
Thursday before or the Saturday after. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This approach raises a question. What's the effect if everyone
buys his or her normal gasoline ration before or after? Consumption
remains the same. It just gets accelerated or delayed. If the
``Great Gas Out'' crusaders really wanted to make a difference,
they would urge a moratorium on gasoline usage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why don't they urge an outright consumption holiday? Can you
imagine how it would hurt the industry if a day's revenues were
lost forever? The reason this approach is shunned is probably
because it requires sacrifice. Americans are great for crusades, as
long as it's not too much of an inconvenience. Otherwise, forget
it. A consumption boycott basically means not driving or otherwise
using any gasoline-powered vehicle or other form of machinery. Talk
about inconvenience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond these considerations, there is also a question of the
crusade's point. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline, contrary to what those with no appreciation of history
might think, isn't all that expensive. It's not expensive in
current dollars or inflation-adjusted dollars. At something over a
dollar a gallon, gasoline costs just about what it cost 30 years
ago in 1969 dollars. Put another way, the price of gasoline right
now pretty much reflects the rate of rise of consumer prices since
before the first oil shock of the early '70s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you can't remember back 20 years or so, predictions for
future oil prices then implied a cost of $4 or $5 a gallon by now.
If those predictions had proved accurate, rising energy costs would
have prevented the strong economic boom and bull market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the cost of gasoline has surged in recent weeks, it's
still within the same price range at which it's been selling for a
decade or more. The latest blip resulted from a pact by OPEC to
curb production in an effort to reduce oil supplies and thus drive
up prices. It's only the umpteenth such agreement by OPEC, none of
which has held before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each time the routine is the same. The market gets jittery, oil
prices rise, gasoline prices react similarly, within a few months
some OPEC members start cheating, and shortly thereafter gas prices
fall along with oil prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you really want gas prices to decline, stop using the stuff.
If demand falls enough, supplies will rise and prices will fall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
