<HEADER>
A9410 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DRIVING-GAME-NYT &LR;      04-07 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DRIVING-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU THINK YOUR COMMUTE IS BAD? TRY THIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN C. MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four hours on an interstate being tailgated by hulking
18-wheelers, cut off by speed demons in red sports cars and
surrounded by menacing sport utility vehicles with darkened windows
is good preparation for Rollcage. This new driving game from
Psygnosis, which was developed by a British company, Attention to
Detail, is the latest in the gaming genre that uses the automobile
as both a means of transportation and a means of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the object of driving games was just to
cross the finish line first. Some of those games still sell well.
But many of the most interesting new driving games are
testosterone-heavy shoot-'em ups inspired, apparently, by road
rage.
</P>
<P>
   What makes these games, and in this case, Rollcage, so
compelling is the detail. They are a variety I call Cyber Noir
because unlike the Formula One racing games, for example, the
rendering of the cars, the tracks, the landscape and the buildings,
while stunning, tend toward the dark and moody. It matches this
kind of game's moral underpinnings _ drive fast, shoot first and
take no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Rollcage, as the name implies, is a race car that can flip over
with no damage. In fact, the car appears to be indestructible and
can defy gravity. It can drive along walls and zip upside down on
tunnel roofs without falling, all the while blasting away with its
mounted weapons. The guns and rockets are used only to impede the
other drivers, since their cars are equally indestructible. You can
slow them down with homing missiles and ``electronic ice'' and
teleport them behind you if you hit one with the wormhole weapon.
</P>
<P>
   You can also just slow opponents down by putting obstacles in
their way. But the obstacles are collapsing buildings that you
bring down in front or on top of them with well-placed missiles.
Other obstacles include chunks of road blown away with eye-popping
fireballs and boulders that can be blasted from the side of
mountains. And then there is the old-fashioned method of simply
running them off the road.
</P>
<P>
   The game play is straightforward. You become one of seven
drivers (choosing from an ethnically diverse group of men and
women) and pick a racing environment. I say environment because
your options extend far beyond simply choosing a racetrack. You can
race in a city, by the shore, through the mountains and even on the
desolate terrain of Mars, with its lighter gravity. Each of those
four venues has four tracks, giving you 16 options. As a bonus,
four extra tracks are added randomly to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   You can race in league mode, where you have to win to advance.
Think English soccer. There are three leagues through which you
must advance, and there are 16 track options for each league. You
can race in arcade mode, where you just try to come in first _ 16
options for that. Then there is time-attack mode, where you just
try to score your own personal best time. That adds yet another way
to tackle the 16 tracks, so you can see that it might take a while
to get through all the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   There is also multiplayer mode. Up to four players can challenge
one another on one PC by daisy-chaining joysticks. The screen shows
all four views simultaneously. You can also play up to five other
people over a LAN or on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And there is practice mode, which you'll surely need plenty of
to gain even minimal control of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Once you do, you should start in arcade mode. I found the
Harpoon Island/Paradise scenario to be the easiest track. Of
course, easy is a relative term. Since a beach is on one side of
the track, it cuts down by half the problem of going off the track.
</P>
<P>
   But the walls on the other side are tricky. If you go up them at
the right angle, you can maintain your direction and speed as you
zoom sideways. Or you might flip over, become airborne and land
somewhere down the road. In these cars, airborne is good. It allows
you to zoom over and ahead of opponents and while you are above
them, they can't draw a bead on you.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you mess up, you do an aerial end over end
and come down heading for the rail on the opposite side of the
road. That is not good. If you are lucky, you hit the rail, bounce
a few times, straighten the car out and resume the race behind the
pack.
</P>
<P>
   But that rarely happens. You are more likely to get smacked by
another car going 320 miles an hour, sending you spinning. The game
moves so fast that you also very quickly get turned around
completely with the dreaded ``Wrong Way'' sign flashing in your
face.
</P>
<P>
   After you complete the three laps in an arcade race, you get the
option of continuing with another race or watching an aerial view
replay of the one you just completed. Replay is instructive,
embarrassing and fun. You get to see how spectacular that crash
really was or feel inept as you watch yourself endlessly bang into
the walls of a cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   Rollcage can be controlled completely by the keyboard, but I do
not recommend it. The slightest movement of the cursor keys causes
an instant response by the car. Until you spend a lot of time in
practice mode just learning to control the car, you will not be
able to keep ahead of the other cars, let alone take them out with
your weapons. You need a joystick, or even better, a steering-wheel
or force-feedback controller, to get the best out of Rollcage.
</P>
<P>
   Rollcage, which has its own Web site at www.rollcage-game.com,
picks up on another popular trend in video games: licensing music
from popular CD's or even original tracks composed by well-known
artists. Some of the music comes from the British rocker Fatboy
Slim's CD ``You've Come a Long Way Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   A caveat: the PC version of Rollcage requires a muscle machine
to work properly. The specifications call for a 233-megahertz
Pentium II with 32 megabytes of RAM and a 3-D accelerator card. I'd
crank up the memory to 64 MB or better.
</P>
<P>
   I played the game on a 400-megahertz Pentium II system with 128
megabytes of RAM and a serious sound system. Spending $3,000 for a
computer to play a $50 video game might seem excessive, but you
can't put a price tag on a good game experience.
</P>
<P>
   Rollcage, from Psygnosis; for Playstation and Windows 95 and 98;
$49.99; rated E for everyone (age 6 and up) by the Entertainment
Software Review Board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
