<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9418 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-KIDS-THEATER-ART-     04-07 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-KIDS-THEATER-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG SURVIVORS OF EVIL SHARE THEIR STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 Randy Gener, a reporter for BroadwayNow, an online theater news
service, also writes for The Star Ledger in Newark, N.J.  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By RANDY GENER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With reports of killings by Serbian forces crowding
the headlines as hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians are
forced out of their homes in Kosovo, Yolanda King can't help but
recall the suffering she saw on her travels with the Children of
War theater project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all flooding back now as I watch the news,'' said Ms.
King, who is haunted by the memory of displaced Bosnian women she
met three years ago in refugee camps. ``We ran into an old woman
who did not know where her children were. She was delirious in her
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. King felt the hardest hit emotionally in Cambodia. ``I
spent time with a woman who had watched all the men in her family
get killed or taken away and never return,'' she said. ``The
parallels were so striking.'' Ms. King was 12 in 1968, when her
father, the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., was assassinated in
Memphis. ``There was a period in my family,'' she added, ``when we
kept losing all our black men: my father, his brother, his oldest
cousin, my father's brother's oldest son. They died one after the
other, all of it happening prior to their turning 40.''
</P>
<P>
   From Tuesday through Sunday at the Asia Society, Ms. King will
share the stage with five actors in the world premiere of a
90-minute multimedia performance piece titled ``The Road Home:
Stories of Children of War.'' It dramatizes interviews with
survivors of war and social conflicts from Bosnia and Cambodia to
America's inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   Individual experiences are recounted by the actors from a script
by James Lecesne. Film footage by Barbara Kopple, who made the
movie ``Harlan County, U.S.A.,'' shows displaced people in
Yugoslavia and Cambodia, stone sculptures at Angkor Wat, Tibetan
refugees in Dharamsala, India, and an interview Ms. King held with
the Dalai Lama. The music has been composed, and is performed live,
by Nawang Khechog, a Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly four-year project was conceived and is directed by
Lawrence Sacharow, chairman of the theater department at Fordham
University. The sponsor of the piece is the River Arts Repertory
Company, which Sacharow originally founded in Woodstock, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road Home'' was inspired by the work of Children of War, a
nonprofit organization that existed from 1983 to 1994. It was set
up, Sacharow said, to ``bring together young survivors from
war-torn countries all over the world to tell their stories to one
another for purposes of healing and developing youth leaders.'' The
organization itself was inspired by the life of Arn Chorn, now 28,
a Cambodian _ portrayed in the play _ who eventually escaped from
the Khmer Rouge as a child. The two research trips abroad were
financed by the Rockefeller Foundation, the Trust for Mutual
Understanding and the Asian Cultural Council.
</P>
<P>
   Sacharow, who directed the Pulitzer Prize-winning production of
Edward Albee's play ``Three Tall Women,'' said he had asked Lecesne
to do the final script because he had seen a videotape of Lecesne's
1995 one-man show ``Word of Mouth,'' in which the actor and writer
impersonated a variety of characters. ``I loved the language and
humanity in it,'' Sacharow said, noting that Lecesne also has a
background in Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road Home'' focuses on the Buddhist goal of compassion,
the director said. ``Because the stories of the people in the play
are about violence, we want to make it a journey through the
violence, so that one feels compassion for all living beings who
have suffered.'' Another goal, he said, was to visit the Dalai
Lama, ``to interview him around the Buddhist teachings of
compassion in relation to violence in the world today.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes Priya Ayyar, who portrays Bosnian and
Cambodian women; Steve Harrison, as an American writer and
researcher; Ken Leung, who plays Chorn, and Wendy vanden Heuvel, as
a Holocaust survivor in a nursing home in New York. Ms. King and
Daniel Carlton, who was born in Harlem and is an AIDS activist and
an actor, portray themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Ayyar, who was born in India, the project represents a
labor of love and a personal journey. ``This has been a very
emotional process,'' she said. ``Our original vision was: How on
earth can we take these stories and present them in a theatrical
way that moves people to a state of compassion?''
</P>
<P>
   What makes it more difficult, Lecesne said, is ``our natural
disavowal of evil in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have such a reflex to make the experience of suffering
the Other,'' he said. ``It happens over there. It does not concern
me. It's something that's so foreign.''
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, Ms. Ayyar said: ``I came to learn that I can do
nothing for someone who has suffered so much except to listen.
There is power in that. The act of listening speaks of
compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   Khechog, the composer, who was 3 when his family fled Tibet,
described the play as ``like a rough sea raging with waves,
disturbances and cyclones; yet deep down, the ocean is still and
calm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what,'' he said, ``human beings reserve a space for
compassion and love. I try to create music that expresses that
sense of chaos and pain but at the same time the desire for hope
and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The play's effect, said Sacharow, hinges on the connections
among suffering men, women and children everywhere. ``It's
important that nobody be a victim,'' he said during a rehearsal.
``When you're telling these stories, it must come from the point of
view of strength. And the heightened physicality of that onstage
will say: `Yes, I've seen these things and that's why I'm here. I
must investigate it. I'm not victimized by it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road Home,'' all the performers agreed, is less about what
evil does to people than what survivors have done in the face of
evil.
</P>
<P>
   In Lecesne's text, Arn Chorn says:
</P>
<P>
   ``War makes place mute.
</P>
<P>
   War takes what is specific and flattens it,
</P>
<P>
   Makes it gone,
</P>
<P>
   War chips the landscape until you could be anywhere,
</P>
<P>
   A kind of nowhere _
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia. Cambodia. Just places. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Dull, general, nonspecific. Gray. Gone. . . .
</P>
<P>
   What I survived is unique, yes,
</P>
<P>
   but I am not that special.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody has a Pol Pot in them; everybody has Buddha.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
