<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLIN-CULTURE-2TAKES     04-07 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-CULTURE-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW BERLIN: ON THE CITY'S STAGES, AN EMBARRASSMENT OF (NOT
QUITE) RICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (also see BERLIN-SUBCULTURE, BERLIN-WALKING, BERLIN-IDENTITY,
BERLIN-REDEVELOP, BERLIN-ARCHITECTURE and BERLIN-VOICES)  
 Anne Midgette writes frequently on international art, music and
theater.  
 (bl)  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ For classical-music lovers in New York, Berlin's
orchestra is the Berlin Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   For music lovers in Berlin, the picture is more complicated. The
Philharmonic is the city's leading orchestra, to be sure, but its
counterpart in East Berlin, the Berlin Symphony Orchestra _ not to
be confused with the Berliner Symphoniker in the West _ also plays
to near-capacity audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin,
formerly the Radio Symphony Orchestra of Berlin, and its older,
Eastern counterpart, the Rundfunk Sinfonie-Orchester Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   There are also specialty orchestras, like the Akademie fuer Alte
Musik and the Berlin Baroque Orchestra. And the orchestras of the
city's three opera houses all give concerts of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Reunified Berlin is bursting at the seams with music. And not
just music. As a condition of German reunification in 1990, the
West was obliged to preserve the cultural institutions of the East.
Partly as a result, Berlin now has, in addition to all those
orchestras and the three opera houses, six major subsidized
repertory houses for spoken theater and several private theaters.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of these groups are presenting the same or similar
repertory. They are also being financed from the same pot. Berlin's
government doles out some $400 million a year to more than 100
cultural institutions. In the sober financial climate of the late
1990s, many have questioned whether Berlin ``needs'' so much music
and theater, or can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Does Berlin need three opera houses? Yes, said the great
conductor Otto Klemperer in the 1930s (for Berlin boasted three
opera companies before the city was ever divided), on the condition
that all three maintain high artistic quality. Whether that
condition is being fulfilled today is moot.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain hardening of the arteries in Berlin's opera
administrations. The stage director Goetz Friedrich, for instance,
is 68, and has led the Deutsche Oper Berlin for 17 years. Many of
his productions seem as tired as he must be. Harry Kupfer, another
renowned stage director and longtime director of the Komische Oper
Berlin, staged 19 of the company's 31 productions this season; the
Komische Oper is Berlin's equivalent of the New York City Opera in
terms of singers, and the young casts can be good, but Kupfer, too,
seems to be recycling old ideas. The third opera house (where
Kupfer also works) is the Deutsche Staatsoper Berlin, which, under
the direction of Daniel Barenboim, has reclaimed its prewar
position as the city's flagship opera, receiving the biggest
subsidy of the three houses and playing the fewest nights.
</P>
<P>
   The opera directors have not distinguished themselves through
their willingness to compromise. Ever since people began asking
whether one of the houses might have to close after reunification,
each has viewed the others as potential rivals in a fight to the
death. (Friedrich, seeming particularly resentful, used to
mispronounce Barenboim's name consistently as a sign of his
displeasure.) Rather than trying to develop a distinctive profile
for his house, each has tried to show that he can do standard
repertory better than the others. This season, all three companies
are presenting Mozart's ``Zauberfloete'' and Verdi's ``Falstaff.''
</P>
<P>
   One-third of all the money Berlin spends on culture goes to
these three theaters. It is not inappropriate, therefore, for the
Berlin senator for cultural affairs to step in. Most German
cultural institutions are government organizations, and the person
ostensibly responsible for orchestrating cultural life in Berlin is
a political appointee. But there is no law that says that the
cultural senator has to know a lot about art. The present senator,
Peter Radunski, is a career politician. He is meeting with the
opera directors regularly to help them discuss programming, as he
puts it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Staatsoper should focus on the pre-Classical repertoire,''
he said of theater that now specializes in Wagner as well as
pre-Classical music. ``The Deutsche Oper should have more
contemporary music: a lot of Henze, Enescu. And in general there
should be more Richard Strauss. After all, he was a Berlin
composer.'' Responding to a quizzical look from his interlocutor,
he amended the Strauss part: ``Well, he lived here.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between art and politics is complicated. When
Radunski's predecessor, Ulrich Roloff-Momin, the first cultural
senator of the reunited Berlin, took office in 1991, a big part of
his job was helping former East German institutions make the
transition to the Western system. But by 1994, the national
government had cut off the extra money it had pumped into the city
to ease reunification, and the job became less about supporting the
arts than about cutting back on them. Something had to go.
</P>
<P>
   That something was the Schiller Theater, the main repertory
theater in West Berlin. The Schiller's audiences were dwindling
while the theaters in the East _ the Berliner Ensemble, the
Volksbuehne and the Deutsches Theater _ were starting to boom, but
the press didn't care. In the impassioned outcry that arose around
the nation, the Schiller Theater became an emblem of all that was
good and true, and Roloff-Momin _ who had, in fact, brought to his
job considerable understanding and appreciation of the creative
process _ became the epitome of philistinism and ignorance, doomed
to go down in German history as the Schiller Killer.
</P>
<P>
   Those who had complained about Roloff-Momin may have wanted him
back when Radunski took office with his new broom in 1996. Radunski
had big ideas about streamlining and combining Berlin's cultural
institutions to save money. But his proposals were like engineering
blueprints, bringing institutions together on paper without taking
into account their personalities or artistic qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to fuse the orchestra of the Komische Oper and the
Berlin Symphony, because they're both Eastern orchestras,'' he
said. ``But it didn't work.'' Fortunately, one might add, since
each orchestra has its own profile, function and audience.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
