<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0408-CO     04-07 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0408-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ETHNIC TENSION BUILDS IN BOSNIA
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    With COX-KOSOVO-MAIN
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Since the airstrikes began,
Bosnians have anxiously listened for the sound of NATO planes that
fly over every day on the way to neighboring Yugoslavia. Many
observers worry the conflict next door holds more than noise for
this still war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is hardening ethnic divisions, causing worry that
it could cause Bosnian Serbs to try to secede from the country and
join Yugoslavia. That would mean the end of the Dayton Peace
Accords.
</P>
<P>
   The International Crisis Group, a policy research group working
in Bosnia, warned Tuesday (CQ) of the potential crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying there is going to be an insurrection,'' said
Bryan Hopkinson, Bosnia director for the International Crisis
Group. ``We're just saying that the forces are right for one. . .
Conditions are more favorable now than they have ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing tension is clear in the increasingly violent attacks
on the
</P>
<P>
   international community. Grenades have destroyed several
international vehicles and rioters have attacked three embassies
and several international offices.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past few days, a civilian working with the NATO-led
Stabilization Force was shot in the leg. A rocket-propelled grenade
was launched at a Stabilization Force helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NATO actions (n Yugoslavia) have caused the most critical
moment for us since the Dayton agreement was signed,'' said Branko
Todorovic, president of the Helsinki Committee for Human Rights
office in the Serb-controlled region of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very risky time for us. It is no exaggeration to say
that this could be catastrophic for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Dayton Peace Accords created two states in Bosnia, the
Serb
</P>
<P>
   Republic and the Muslim/Croat Federation, international
officials have been trying to get the states to work together like
a country. The NATO conflict in Yugoslavia has stymied that effort
and brought out the worst in the local political leaders.
Politicians on each side have accused the other of mobilizing
military forces to join in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The Stabilization Force, which monitors both states' militaries,
denies either is mobilizing. But the accusations are a startling
reminder of the pre-war propaganda here, when the nationalist
parties warned their members that the other ethnic groups were
preparing to
</P>
<P>
   slaughter them.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb Republic was already in a political crisis when NATO
began bombing Yugoslavia. Two weeks before the airstrikes started,
Bosnia's international supervisor fired the hard-line, anti-western
president of the Serb Republic. The same day, an international
arbitrator decided that Brcko, a strategic port town, should become
a special district, taking control of it from the Serbs and
effectively splitting the Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Those two events sparked demonstrations throughout the Serb
Republic. Serb officials withdrew from posts in the national
government in protest.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombing began, the protests became more violent, and
the Serb Republic information minister last week warned there might
be attempts to secede from Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   The violence had already forced most international officials and
aid workers to abandon the region, a fact that worries opposition
leaders like Todorovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very bad that the international community left,''
Todorovic said. ``It is a victory for the ultranationalists here.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Stabilization Force soldiers got in a gun
fight with two
</P>
<P>
   civilians, one of whom was killed. The soldiers were destroying
a stretch of railway in eastern Bosnia that's the only line linking
Belgrade to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Serb politicians immediately accused the Stabilization Force of
violating Bosnia's neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   The incident also concerned international officials working in
the Serb
</P>
<P>
   Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got enough problems right now,'' said one political
adviser who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``Why did they
have to pick the five miles of track in Bosnia when they've got
miles and miles in Yugoslavia? It flies in the face of everything
they're saying about Bosnia being neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Stabilization Force officials said the rail line was being used
or was about to be used to transport forces to Montenegro, a
violation of Bosnia's neutrality. And officials confirmed that
Yugoslav soldiers were seen in the area during the gunfight.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the uproar, diplomats like David Owen, European
Union's special negotiator here during the war, are suggesting
Bosnia should just be divided along ethnic lines, with the eastern
part of the Serb Republic given to Yugoslavia in exchange for
independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the crisis, international officials continue to
``cajole, push and encourage,'' Serb officials to resume their
posts in the national government, according to Simon Haselock,
spokesman for international supervisors. But their task is a tough
one.
</P>
<P>
   Susannah A. Nesmith is a free-lance writer who lives in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9424 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLIN-CULTURE-2NDTAK     04-07 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-CULTURE-2NDTAKE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BERLIN: and audience.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another example of Radunski's idea of streamlining is the Berlin
Ballet. The new company, 120 members strong, combines the ballet
companies of the three opera houses. Thirty dancers will be
available on some quasi-permanent basis to the Deutsche Oper Berlin
and its chief choreographer, Angelin Preljocaj, and 30 more to the
Komische Oper and Richard Wherlock; 60 will be based at the
Staatsoper, which, to make up for its superior numbers, will have
no resident choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   The equation is nicely balanced. But it seems like a recipe for
providing the city with adequate ``dance product,'' as if the arts
were no more than a social service that existed to cover the needs
of the public.
</P>
<P>
   Not that fusions can't work. Berlin's museums have managed to
grow together impressively. In 1990, there were 14 museums in West
Berlin, 12 in the East; the city found itself with two museums of
Islamic art, two painting galleries, two Egyptian museums and so
on. Today, there are 17 museums all told, with no repetitions.
Berlin's Old Masters have been moved from their former homes, East
and West, to a new central building, opened in 1998, near the
Philharmonie. The real work left to do is on Museum Island, in the
Spree River in East Berlin, where the museums ``still look like
1945,'' according to Michael Naumann, the new German culture
minister. All are undergoing renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Museums could fuse more easily than theaters, because there was
a general director for all the city's museums, who oversaw the
mergers of the collections. An overall general intendant might be
able to ease the deadlock in the city's theaters, particularly the
opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   What Berlin is getting instead is yet anther political
administrator responsible for supervising the apportioning of
funds, in the person of Naumann. The extent and nature of his role
remains to be seen. But Berlin, as the new capital, will receive
$65 million more a year in federal cultural subsidies, and Naumann
will surely have some say in their distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann tries to be clear about the limits of his power. ``The
cultural sovereignty of Berlin remains with Berlin,'' he said.
``Personnel decisions are made by Radunski. Instead of co-financing
little things, the government will come in on larger things. It's
tricky. Where we co-finance, we want to be listened to, but I
cannot and should not exceed my authority.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question is how far Naumann's role will intersect with
that of the cultural senator. So far, Naumann and Radunski have
presented a public facade of harmonious collaboration. Naumann can
afford to be generous, since city elections are coming up in a few
months, and Radunski is widely expected to lose his seat in the
senate.
</P>
<P>
   For Radunski, this uncertain future is additional incentive to
move quickly on the ``personnel decisions'' that are among the most
significant part of a cultural senator's job. The various
appointments give the senator a lasting influence not unlike that
of a U.S. president appointing justices of the Supreme Court
(though without the politically charged confirmation hearings);
Radunski may be shaping civic culture for years to come. A whole
string of contracts come up for renewal in the near future _
Friedrich's at the Deutsche Oper expires in 2001, and Kupfer's and
Barenboim's expire in 2002 _ and Radunski intends to put successors
in place.
</P>
<P>
   Today, an institution's director has become central, even
decisive, to its identity. In Berlin's confusion of orchestras, for
instance, the conductor's name is all that enables an outsider to
remember the difference between the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester
(Kent Nagano) and the Berlin Symphony Orchestra (Eliahu Inbal). But
finding big names can in turn become a stand-in for meaningful
cultural policy.
</P>
<P>
   And the names under discussion for Berlin's various cultural
posts are not really new. Radunski's pool for new opera intendants
reportedly includes familiar figures who have held similar
positions elsewhere: Udo Zimmermann, in Leipzig; Peter Rusicka, in
Hamburg, and John Dew, in Dortmund. Even the Berlin Philharmonic,
in its search for a new conductor to replace Claudio Abbado, is
looking at all the usual suspects, from Franz Welser-Moest to
everybody's favorite candidate of the moment, Simon Rattle. Its
wish list seems hardly different from that of the Philadelphia
Orchestra, which is also in the search process.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann warns against looking for salvation from one person or
from an all-knowing government, and he and Radunski agree as to the
need for restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet given the deeply entrenched nature of the system, the
difficulties of instituting change in a bureaucracy and the
attendant potential for political liability, far-reaching
structural changes seem a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   It is more likely that Berlin will maintain status quo: a
cultural life of rich diversity, tempered, at least in classical
music and opera, with an overriding aftertaste of mediocrity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
