<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9435 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLIN-SUBCULTURE-$AD     04-07 1889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-SUBCULTURE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW BERLIN: `CABARET' DAYS ARE GONE; NOW IT'S SHADES OF GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (also see BERLIN-CULTURE, BERLIN-WALKING, BERLIN-IDENTITY,
BERLIN-REDEVELOP, BERLIN-ARCHITECTURE and BERLIN-VOICES)  
 Ed Ward, the author of the first volume of ``Rock of Ages,''
Rolling Stone's rock history, is a freelance writer in Berlin.  
 (bl)  
 By ED WARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The Image: Trapped on a plane a few years ago, I
decided to start watching the film ``Company Business'' when the
opening credits faded and a title saying ``Berlin'' came on the
screen. After all, I was flying to the United States from Berlin,
so I was curious. The film wasn't actually made here, as soon
became obvious. But the reason I gave up on it was an early scene
involving Gene Hackman and Mikhail Baryshnikov, playing a CIA agent
and a KGB agent, respectively. They were in a situation in which
they needed to make a phone call. Hackman spotted a bar, an
ordinary enough looking place, and went in. Suddenly, there were
Barbra Streisand, Dolly Parton, Liza Minelli and Diana Ross. And in
the spotlight, crooning, was Marlene Dietrich as Lola in ``Blue
Angel.'' Drag queens all, leering at poor Gene.
</P>
<P>
   Just another bar on some side-street in Berlin, the film was
saying. And it's true: ever since the days of the Weimar Republic,
the city has had that sort of reputation, as a place with a seedy
netherworld lurking behind every door.
</P>
<P>
   The Reality: It was about 11 on a cold night some four months
ago, and I was out with a friend who is a rising star on Berlin's
art scene. If anybody would know where the art and club scenes
converged, the subject of much talk in the local press, she would.
We had had a late dinner in the Mitte district and were looking for
somewhere to go when I remembered that it was the opening night at
Bauhuette Gemuetlichkeit, the latest project by Canadian artist
Laura Kikauka, and we were just a few blocks away. Ms. Kikauka and
her husband, Gordon Monahan, have taken over a number of sites
temporarily, filled them with a bewildering array of artsy kitsch
and run an informal (which is to say, illegal) bar. Onstage,
Monahan plays an electronic organ and singers render a variety of
songs as bad lounge music. The pair calls the concept irritainment.
</P>
<P>
   The place was packed. We fought our way to the bar and then,
feeling claustrophobic, to the back of the room. A few minutes
later, the ridiculous music got to us, so we knocked back our
drinks and left. ``Isn't Loop somewhere around here?'' my friend
asked. In fact, it was, in another building in the complex. Loop is
a room created by a group of artists dedicated to ambient
soundscapes, and I'd always wanted to visit it. When we arrived, we
opened the door on a dimly lighted room with a few people lounging
on cushions, holding bottles of Beck's while a record (a scratchy
one, at that) played on a turntable making some indeterminate
sounds. We lasted about a minute there.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I know a place,'' my friend said. This one was also nearby
and was harder to get into because we had to squeeze through a tiny
hole in a wall to reach the front door. Here, at least, the crowd
density was tolerable, and two DJs were working hard on a pair of
turntables, albeit to no great effect. My friend knew some of the
artists there, so she made the rounds while I watched the lights go
out intermittently: the club was in an old East German building,
and the wiring was faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, my friend returned. ``Well, this is it,'' she said.
``The most underground place in Berlin. Fascinating, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophisticated,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot center of Europe,'' she said, deadpan.
</P>
<P>
   Collapsing in giggles, we squeezed back through the wall and
found a cab.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we're cynical, jaded, not to mention a bit older (she's in
her mid-30s and I'm even older) than the average 20-something
patron of the places we'd visited, but there are times when the
reputation of Berlin's artistic underground seems as silly to me as
Gene Hackman's drag-queen bar.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to deny that there is a scene here, although, as the
recent collection of mediocre art at the Berlin Biennale showed,
it's not quite as interesting as one might hope. It's also not to
deny that there is a history here, post-Wall, of era-defining
cultural change, particularly in art and fringe pop music. It's
just that it's not as thrilling, perhaps, day to day.
</P>
<P>
   It was music that gave the underground its initial shot in the
arm. In the months before the Wall came down a decade ago, the
techno scene in Berlin was beginning in small clubs in West Berlin,
but it wasn't until some entrepreneurial spirits crossed east after
November 1989 that it really took off. In the last days of the East
German regime, many buildings that the government had scheduled for
demolition were merely taken off the list, and as a result a large
number of buildings were left standing that didn't exist on paper.
Squatters quickly turned these spaces into clubs. An old power
plant that had been abandoned for years became E-Werk, while the
basement of a bombed-out bank building of which only one floor
above ground remained, was turned into Tresor-Globus. The artists
whose work flourished in these clubs _ which put Berlin on the
international musical map _ came from Detroit (where techno
originated) and, surprisingly, both East and West Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   There were no signs out front to mark these places for visitors:
like most of the interesting bars and clubs I have gone to in the
five years I have lived here, they were illegal, having foregone
the health and other licenses required by the local authorities.
(Both E-Werk, which is now closed, and Tresor-Globus subsequently
became legal, as has Bauhuette Gemuetlichkeit). Places like these
are necessarily temporary, often cropping up in the spring and
lasting until the weather turns cold, then vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   They show up in the most unlikely places: I remember one, run by
Brazilians, which was literally a hole in the ground. In the middle
of a lot covered with the rubble left by bombs, one could see a
tiny light. It was a candle, placed at the top of a stairway, which
led to the building's cellar. Other candles led to a door, and
through it was the club. Apparently there was live Brazilian music
some nights, but the real attraction was the caipirinha cocktails,
available there three years before they became de rigeur on the
scene. This was a good thing: most illegal clubs seem to serve
nothing but Beck's, for some reason.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are these places all in the east: four summers ago, the hot
place was Hop Sing, named after the cook on the television show
``Bonanza.'' The club, which was in the basement of an office
building in the Kreuzberg district in west Berlin, was meticulously
tricked-out as a barroom from the American Old West, complete with
swinging doors and an odd selection of country music on the sound
system. The first-time visitor was warned that the location of the
club was top secret. Not secret enough: the building's owner,
originally enthusiastic about it, saw how successful the club
became and raised the rent eightfold. Hop Sing passed on.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy, though, is a real concern. One owner of an illegal
club, an American, told me that he did not want his club mentioned
in print. (Although he didn't particularly like the idea, he said
he did know guys who beat people up for money.) The reason was
simple: he had a lot of his own money invested in the place, and
that summer the police were poring over the local media, checking
club names against a list of legal ones. The owner feared that a
raid would mean the end of his club, and, possibly, his stay in
Berlin. (In a bizarre coda, the club subsequently became legal only
to be torched late last year by persons unknown.)
</P>
<P>
   Not all illegal spaces became clubs, though: some were turned
into galleries or performance spaces. Often, the public space would
be on the ground floor, with the artists living as squatters on the
floors above. Even the buildings in East Berlin that were legal
were cheap, and the Mitte and Prenzlauer Berg districts attracted
artists from around the world. As with the clubs, a number of these
spaces eventually became legal (an easier process for them because
there were fewer heath-code restrictions, although last year the
process for becoming legal was greatly simplified for clubs and
bars, too), and a scene was born.
</P>
<P>
   Because the artists' spaces and the clubs existed in the same
legal limbo, it was inevitable that the two cultures would move
closer together. The first fusion I became aware of was the initial
`` . . . und ab die Post!'' _ an exhibit of the work of young
artists in an ornate former post office building on Oranienburger
Strasse _ two years ago. Each night, a different club event was
held. This exhibit was sponsored by the Aktionsgalerie, which is
down the street from the post office building. It is hardly your
typical gallery, since it looks like a bar, and, in fact, is one.
In the cellar, however, some of Berlin's most interesting art shows
have been held, while upstairs in the bar, on weekends, there is
frequently a DJ or other live performance.
</P>
<P>
   The art-club fusion gained attention internationally for the
first time at the 1997 Venice Biennale. The Art Club Berlin had a
space, designed by artists, in which DJs performed in the evenings,
and many critics thought it was the most innovative thing at the
event. (It will return this year). By now, it has become almost
unthinkable in some circles to have a gallery or show opening
without a DJ or some electronic musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Ina Wudtke is a 30-year-old who is something of a Renaissance
woman: an artist, DJ and publisher of Neid, a magazine of
avant-garde writings on gender and identity. ``I do art when art
pays, DJ when DJing pays, and use the money for the magazine,'' she
said. ``But I must say, it's frustrating when you're working the
turntables, trying to get people to dance, and they're staring at
screens.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing that the art crowd has arrived, however,
because back in clubland, the once-monolithic techno scene has long
ago shattered into dozens of micro-genres and record sales have
gone nearly flat. There is no longer any center to the scene since
E-Werk closed two years ago and the once-underground Love Parade,
both a parade and a club festival held the second weekend in July,
has become a major pop event attracting 2 million people from
everywhere in Europe to Berlin's clubs. The events have become
thoroughly commercialized; they are announced on posters with so
many corporate logos that it's hard to figure out at times who's
playing.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the nature of undergrounds, especially those that
flourish, to become mainstream. So as Berlin's art-club scene moves
inexorably in that direction, no doubt something else is fermenting
in a back courtyard somewhere in the Friedrichshain district, a new
hot center of activity. As the weather warms up, my friends and I
will probably go there to investigate. And with a warm Beck's in my
hand, I'll no doubt be torn between fascination and wondering what
all the shouting's about. That, too, is a hallmark of the Berlin
underground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
