<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9444 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLIN-IDENTITY-3TAKE     04-07 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-IDENTITY-3TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW BERLIN: A PHOENIX RISES FROM THE RUBBLE OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (also see BERLIN-WALKING, BERLIN-CULTURE, BERLIN-SUBCULTURE,
BERLIN-REDEVELOP, BERLIN-ARCHITECTURE and BERLIN-VOICES)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ No major European city displays its fractured history
more visibly than Berlin. In just the 19th and 20th centuries, it
was successively headquarters of the Prussian kingdom, the second
German Reich, the Weimar Republic and the Nazi regime. It was then
flattened by Allied bombers, occupied by the four victorious powers
and divided into hostile camps, with its eastern sector becoming
the capital of the communist German Democratic Republic. And each
political moment was recorded in its buildings, avenues and empty
spaces. By the time East Germany imploded in November 1989, Berlin
resembled a sprawling museum of architectural history.
</P>
<P>
   It then promptly set out to build yet another ``new Berlin,''
this time as capital of a prosperous, democratic and single
Germany. The problems of turning two cities into one were enormous;
the challenge of starting afresh was exciting. Overnight, Berlin
became a hothouse of discussion about what could or should be done.
Renowned international architects were invited to join the debate.
The past kept blurring visions of the future, but decisions were
finally made. And in the 1990s, more than $120 billion of public
and private money was poured into construction and renovation that
have transformed Berlin's profile.
</P>
<P>
   The Reichstag, Germany's pre-Nazi parliament building, has been
rebuilt; legislators will meet there April 19 for a session marking
the return of the German government to Berlin. Nearby, a modern
Chancellery is going up, while numerous old buildings _ including
some from the Nazi era _ are being prepared to receive government
officials. Private business groups led by Daimler-Benz are close to
completing a new neighborhood at Potsdamer Platz, the heart of
1930s Berlin. The city's prewar historic center between Museum
Island and Pariser Platz is filling up with new buildings. Even the
Stalinist apartment buildings on Karl-Marx-Allee in the former East
Berlin have new facades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Berlin about to resume its place at the heart of the
German nation, the new city is ready to be judged. More or less. In
truth, it is not yet complete: cranes still silhouette its skyline,
while the final homes and work places of many officials and
politicians moving here from Bonn won't be ready until 2002. But
more fundamentally, the main urban and architectural decisions
defining the new Berlin have been made.
</P>
<P>
   And the verdict? Well, those hoping for a showcase of
avant-garde architecture have been disappointed. For them, a rare
opportunity has been lost. So far, only Daniel Libeskind's new
Jewish Museum has been hailed as a stunningly original building _
and its design was approved before the Berlin Wall came down. After
reunification in 1990, however, the city's powerful building
authorities opted for what they called the ``critical
reconstruction'' of historic Berlin and imposed strict guidelines
on the size and appearance of all but the federal buildings.
Obsessed with recreating a traditional ``European city,'' they left
little room for innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result is dull and uninspiring,'' said Libeskind, who
still lives in Berlin. ``Now people are beginning to see what was
given to them. Dullness was the bureaucratic result of what the
planners wanted to communicate: power and order, a new `old
Berlin.' But you can't restart history by pressing a button. It
becomes a kitsch idea of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet from a strictly urban point of view, great strides have been
made toward reuniting the city. Remnants of the 100-mile-long
Berlin Wall remain as tourist attractions, but the deep wound it
cut through Berlin for 28 years is quickly being healed: in many
areas, it is hard to know where the wall once stood. As important,
the city's urban infrastructure is being renovated. North of the
Reichstag, for instance, the Lehrter railroad station is being
entirely rebuilt, with a vast hole announcing where a new tunnel
will lead trains in and out of the city. Another tunnel for road
traffic will keep many vehicles out of the city center, while
services like water and drainage are being modernized at huge
expense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the net result has not been to give the city a strong new
visual identity because, perhaps strangely, Berlin has always felt
insecure about itself. It claims to be over 750 years old, but it
was never an important medieval city. It could boast powerful
figures like Frederick the Great in the 18th century and Otto von
Bismarck, the so-called Iron Chancellor, in the late 19th century,
yet when the Prussian and German rulers dreamed of a monumental
city that mirrored their might, they looked elsewhere, notably
Paris, for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   And when Hitler dreamed of a 1,000-year Reich, he, too, felt
Berlin was somehow inadequate; he wanted it rebuilt on a pharaonic
scale and renamed Germania.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as a divided city, it lived the schizophrenia of
simultaneously symbolizing both capitalist freedom and totalitarian
order.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, as officials struggled to imagine the city's future,
Berlin's perennial identity crisis weighed heavily. And in the end,
they felt it safer to lower their sights, to shuffle through
Berlin's previous identities in search of one that was reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it was inevitable,'' said Bernard Schneider, an
architect and urban expert. ``In moments of insecurity, you rely on
regressive feelings and ideas. If you wake up after 60 years in a
coma and you're asked to dance a pirouette, you simply can't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Germany _ and perhaps the rest of Europe _ has
always viewed Berlin with suspicion. True, briefly in the 1920s, it
was the decadent fun capital of Europe and a laboratory for the
Modernist architects _ Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, Walter Gropius, Le
Corbusier and others _ of the Bauhaus movement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in thinking about Berlin of late, most West Germans do not
recall ``Cabaret'' and all that. For them, as much as Hitler or
even communism, the city represents Prussian militarism, Protestant
severity and a shift in Germany's focus from Western Europe to
Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   This distrust surfaced when the 662-member Bundestag, the German
parliament, voted in 1991 to move the capital from Bonn to Berlin:
the resolution was adopted by a majority of just 17 votes.
</P>
<P>
   The first idea mooted was to build a new government district on
a campuslike site in Berlin. But cost became a factor, and the Bonn
government decided instead to make maximum use of existing
buildings in Berlin, notably two vast ones constructed by the
Nazis: Hitler's Reichsbank, which later served as the headquarters
of the East German Communist Party, will become the Foreign
Ministry; and Goering's Air Force Ministry, called the House of
Ministries under communism, will serve as the new Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   For Berliners, it seemed natural to use these familiar
buildings, which look reassuringly Prussian with their stone
exteriors interrupted by long rows of rectangular windows. But the
Bonn government was always more sensitive to symbolism and, above
all, to a question that would color much of the debate about the
new Berlin: should Germany try to obliterate its past or learn to
live with its own (not always pleasant) history. The Communists had
already stripped these two buildings of all Nazi insignia, but
architects were appointed to try to give them a modern freshness.
In the case of the Foreign Ministry, for example, a new glass annex
is being added.
</P>
<P>
   The debate about the Reichstag proved even more complicated.
Built between 1884 and 1894 in an ornate neo-Baroque style, it
burned down _ supposedly on Nazi orders _ just weeks after Hitler
came to power in 1933. During the Battle of Berlin, it was then
reduced to ruins by Soviet artillery. The Bonn government decided
to restore it in 1961, but almost immediately the Berlin Wall went
up beside its eastern entrance. In the years that followed, the
Reichstag housed a permanent historical exhibition, but it was
never much loved. After reunification, many legislators in Bonn
thought it too small, too ugly and too Prussian to be the new home
of the Bundestag. But the yearning for continuity again won out.
</P>
<P>
   An architectural competition was organized and, in a display of
German self-consciousness about symbols of its power today, three
foreign architects were named the finalists: Norman Foster of
Britain, Santiago Calatrava of Spain and Pi de Bruijn of the
Netherlands. All three were asked to rework their proposals and,
after endless negotiations with Federal officials, Foster's design
was eventually approved. Shortly before construction began, in
1995, the Reichstag's imminent transition was announced magically
when it was wrapped by the artists Christo and Jeanne-Claude.
Today, with its signature glass dome intended to symbolize
democratic transparency (and offer splendid views over the city),
it is recognized as one of the architectural success stories of the
new Berlin. The building itself was gutted and a new brightly
lighted legislative chamber was placed at its heart.
</P>
<P>
   Bonn's debate about Berlin, however, had surprisingly little
echo in the city itself. Here, officials were less concerned with
symbolism than with creating a vibrant new city where Berliners
felt at home. And unknowingly they had prepared for reunification
in the 1980s with an urban construction program somewhat oddly
named the International Building Exhibition. It was born of concern
that West Berlin had turned its back on the wall, that its
commercial and social center was moving steadily west. Berlin
architects led by Josef Paul Kleihues were also alarmed that urban
planners in both West and East Berlin were ``deconstructing'' the
``European city'' by building wide avenues and social housing far
from the workplace. For them, Modernism had gone too far. They
favored what they called ``critical reconstruction'' of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The area chosen for the new buildings was to the south of
Checkpoint Charlie, one of the main accesses to East Berlin, where
contemporary architects _ among them, Aldo Rossi and Paolo
Portoghesi of Italy, Richard Rogers and James Stirling of Britain
and Peter Eisenman and Robert Venturi of the United States _ were
invited to recreate the ``European city'': a traditional
neighborhood with street corners and plazas and with privately
owned buildings of a limited height and size that mixed commercial
and residential functions. When the wall came down, then, much of
the theoretical thinking that would define the city's building
policy had been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the International Building Exhibition, the post-wall
era would have been a disaster,'' Kleihues said, adding that he
always favored ``more modesty, more silence'' over monumentalism.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a disaster, but it was not uneventful. Berlin wanted
big-name international architects to work here, and these same
architects wanted to be part of the new Berlin. But the architects
soon learned that Berlin's planners had the last word on what the
buildings would look like. Some foreign architects refused to make
their design fit the guidelines and walked away. Others argued,
complained and made concessions. But most competitions were won by
Berlin architects for the simple reason that they _ and carefully
selected juries _ shared Kleihues' vision. What had begun in the
1980s as an architectural backlash against urban planners became,
in the 1990s, a running battle between traditional and contemporary
architectural esthetics.
</P>
<P>
   The first major project, the reconstruction of Potsdamer Platz,
was already being planned when the wall came down; the land had
been acquired by Daimler-Benz in 1987 as an expression of faith in
Berlin. Then, in 1990, adjacent plots were bought by Sony and the
Asea Brown Boveri group. But when Daimler-Benz turned to design
questions, it ran up against Berlin officials. The officials
accepted the idea of high-rise buildings _ albeit limiting their
height to 260 feet, or about 20 stories _ but they also insisted on
using the area's original street plan and recapturing the spirit of
a European city with mixed commercial, entertainment and
residential spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after approval of a master plan prepared by Renzo Piano
and Christoph Kohlbecker, construction began in October 1994. Piano
himself designed eight buildings, including a new music
theater-cum-casino and a high-rise building for Daimler-Benz's top
management, while Richard Rogers built other Daimler-Benz offices;
Rafael Moneo of Spain designed the new Hyatt Hotel; Hans Kollhoff
built another high-rise, and Arata Isozaki of Japan built the
Volksbank headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Today, while construction of Helmut Jahn's vast glass and steel
Sony Center advances apace, Potsdamer Platz is virtually completed
_ and it can boast big-name architects as its authors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the result has not won unanimous approval. From afar, its
high-rises suggest a modern business district, but its narrow
streets are inevitably in shadow, while the attempt to create a
public space out of Marlene Dietrich Platz has so far been less
than successful. Still, the shopping mall is already a draw and,
once the music theater opens in June with Disney's ``Hunchback of
Notre Dame,'' things may become livelier.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the architecture in the district is listless. The
Hyatt Hotel, for instance, consists of stone walls with rows of
identical windows. Rogers' steel and glass buildings on the eastern
edge of the area are more imaginative, but even he was not
satisfied with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the limitations set, Potsdamer Platz is quite
successful,'' he said, ``but the limitations set were completely
ridiculous. I think Renzo has done brilliantly within a very
dogmatic approach. But why invite people like Renzo Piano and then
tie their hands? The result in Berlin as a whole is that having
employed some of the world's best architects, none of them has done
any of their best work.''
</P>
<P>
   For Pariser Platz and the nearby Friedrichstrasse area, city
officials were even stricter. They ruled that prewar streets and
blocks be restored, that the height of buildings be limited to 72
feet at the street and to 98 feet in total, that exteriors be
covered with stone, that glass not exceed 50 percent of facades and
that 20 percent of space be dedicated to private living space. In
this way, they hoped to recreate the scale, intimacy, density and
life style of their ``European city.'' Needless to say, architects
with an artistic bent were frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the center, with its stern rows of windows of the same
rectangular size, is dull and unimaginative,'' said Peter Conradi,
an architect and former politician who now heads the Chamber of
German Architects. ``I would have liked to have seen more
courage.''
</P>
<P>
   The only building on Friedrichstrasse that is different is that
of Galeries Lafayette, designed by Jean Nouvel of France. He got
away with a largely glass exterior simply because Berlin wanted the
prestige store, and Galeries Lafayette insisted on using Nouvel.
But he lamented the city's cautiousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they went about it as if nothing had happened, as if
they were erasing history between 1933 and 1989,'' he said. ``There
are some important architectural works in the city _ Libeskind's
museum and Piano's high-rise _ but `critical reconstruction'
reflected a desire for continuity, a policy of little risk, nowhere
near as adventurous or prestigious as you might have hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Brandenberg Gate, Pariser Platz _ the
western end of Unter den Linden, the monumental avenue that cuts
through historic Berlin _ is being completely rebuilt. Two bank
buildings, designed by Kleihues with stone facades and small
windows, now stand on either side of the gate. And its uniformity
is reflected at the entrance to the square by the Hotel Adlon.
Three buildings still to be completed, though, may disrupt the
current sameness. Frank Gehry's design for the Deutsche
Genossenschaftsbank provides for larger windows, although much of
his innovation will be inside the building. Christian de
Portzamparc's new French Embassy, still at the design stage, also
suggests something more modern. After heated negotiations, Guenter
Behnisch's new Academy of Arts building, tucked into a corner of
the plaza, will even have a glass facade.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once we won the battle,'' said Cornelius Hertling, the
president of the Berlin Chamber of Architects, who echoes the
criticism of official policy voiced by many international
architects. ``Pariser Platz was a baroque square with small
independent palaces, so it's all right to keep the size of the
square and the height of the buildings. But why should I be forced
to have Prussian windows? I told Portzamparc not to follow the
Prussian rules _ and he didn't. But the Adlon is retrograde to an
extent that is laughable. Once again, it's the museum approach.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an approach that has enjoyed the support of the Berlin
Senate, but its execution has been largely in the hands of one
immensely powerful city official, Hans Stimmann, who was the city's
building director from 1990 to 1997 and is now its planning
director. The 58-year-old architect-turned-urban planner has in
essence carried out Kleihues' idea of ``critical reconstruction,''
but he has added an inflexibility that even some admirers consider
excessive. And in the process he has become the nemesis of all
architects who hoped for something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``He single-handedly ruined Berlin,'' said Richard Meier, who
saw one of his projects vetoed by Stimmann in the early 1990s. ``He
got terrible, horrible results because he did not understand the
scale. But it was his view that counted. He had total authority.
When I presented my design, he said, `This isn't what we want.' So
I told him, `If you want a 19th-century architect, get a
19th-century architect.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tall, white haired, with a bushy mustache, accustomed to being
attacked by modern architects, Stimmann speaks with the quiet
conviction of a convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a 1968 man, interested in social and political problems,
but not in history,'' he explained. ``We associated nostalgia with
conservatives. But step by step my ideas changed. We slowly saw
that old things were not bad. And with the International Building
Exhibition, we accepted history. You know, the Berlin of 1989 was
not the result of bombing, but of politics and bad planning by
people who were against history. For me, 90 percent of old things
are better, so let's stop with experiments.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``experiments'' he meant what he calls architectural
``objects,'' free-standing buildings that may be applauded for
their sculptural value but that in his view have no place in a
traditional city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish Museum is a typical example of that,'' Stimmann
went on. ``It's a very important building as a museum, but
Libeskind tries to project his ideas for the museum on the whole
city. You can't. It doesn't work. Big architects feel like big
artists. You have to know immediately it's a Jahn building or a
Foster building. Our problem was not to build a picture collection
with a famous Picasso or a famous Jahn. A lot of architects didn't
like my guidelines, but I feel architecture should be part of
society.''
</P>
<P>
   The arguing will certainly go on but, in the battle over the
esthetics of the new Berlin, Stimmann and his backers appear to be
the winners. Now, in his new post as planning director, he is
looking to the bleak and ugly area around Alexanderplatz in former
East Berlin for the next stage of urban development. In the
meantime, though, one pending decision _ to be made jointly by the
federal and Berlin governments _ reminds again how the future keeps
being tripped up by the past.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, East Germany demolished the vast 18th-century
Hohenzollern Palace at the eastern end of Unter den Linden and
replaced it in 1976 with a smaller _ though still large _ Palace of
the Republic, which housed the rubber-stamp parliament but also
theaters, discotheques, bowling alleys, restaurants and the like.
When the city was reunited, this building was found to be
contaminated with asbestos and was closed. Almost immediately, a
grass-roots movement began campaigning for reconstruction of the
Hohenzollern Palace. But former East Berliners _ Ossies _ were
equally opposed to demolition of the Palace of the Republic, which
represented their few good memories of the Communist regime. And
for the moment, while being slowly stripped of asbestos, the palace
stands sealed and boarded, awaiting its fate.
</P>
<P>
   For a good many Berliners, it seems, sorting out the past is
still more important than stepping into the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
