<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLIN-REDEVELOP-2TAK     04-07 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLIN-REDEVELOP-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A CAPITAL WHERE TRIUMPH IS TABOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (also see BERLIN-WALKING, BERLIN-IDENTITY, BERLIN-CULTURE,
BERLIN-SUBCULTURE, BERLIN-ARCHITECTURE and BERLIN-VOICES)  
 (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The early 19th century French writer Stendhal once
remarked of Berlin that he had no idea ``who thought of planting a
town in the middle of this sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the damp sand, not far from the Reichstag, beneath the
countless cranes that are the sentinels of this city's shifting
heart, a hole has been dug. It is huge even by the standards of
this home of excavational excess; it will, so the planners say, one
day house Berlin's new central railway station, a hub of
north-south and east-west lines worthy of a European capital
reborn.
</P>
<P>
   North-south lines of any kind have been something of a taboo
here even since the Bundestag voted by a narrow margin in 1991 to
return the German capital to Berlin. The reason is that it was
along a majestic north-south axis that Hitler's architect, Albert
Speer, planned the Via Triumphalis of the Thousand Year Reich, an
avenue that was to lead to a victory arch twice the size of the Arc
de Triomphe.
</P>
<P>
   So it is perhaps not surprising that the north-south line
running through that hole will be underground. But however the city
masks its ambitions, the notion of standing at the center, of being
a ``Weltstadt'' _ a world city _ midway between Stockholm and
Venice, Paris and Moscow, is very much of Berlin: an extravagant
idea regularly summoned from the boggy plains of Prussia to provide
a beacon in an often featureless sea of provincialism.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Stendhal's dismay is understandable even
today. From the Hohenzollerns to Hitler, ideas for a great German
city have abounded; but Brl, the Slavic word at the root of
Berlin's name, means marsh, and the lofty has tended to sag or sink
here with an eerie repetitiveness. Now, once again, Berlin has set
out to attain its long-held dream of being a European cultural
capital and, by so doing, unite Germans and overcome the past.
</P>
<P>
   The road will be a long one. Berlin's tortured history at the
nexus of 20th-century conflict has left it oddly isolated. Beyond
the city's limits, the lake-littered flatlands stretch away,
scarred still with the tracks left by Soviet tanks exercising for
the great Cold War battle that never came. Within the city's vast
sprawl, something often seems to be missing, leaving the impression
of an urban area out of proportion to its content.
</P>
<P>
   Human density, the whiff and fever of money being made, high
society, city chic, the avant-garde excitement of a Bertolt Brecht,
the sensuous intrigue of metropolitan life _ much of this seems to
have been drained from Berlin by its long postwar incarnation as an
island in a Red sea, communist in the East, subsidized in the West,
almost entirely alien to the cut-and-thrust of private initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to reinvigorate the place, give it coherence, make
it whole, remains arduous even a decade after the fall of the Wall.
Parts of the former East, particularly Prenzlauer Berg and Mitte,
are now full of trendy cafes; the club scene is lively enough; new
art galleries are opening. But Berlin, observed Bernhard Schlink, a
novelist, ``still lacks a physical or psychological center.''
</P>
<P>
   Axel Schultes, one of the architects of the new Berlin
Chancellery that Gerhard Schroeder, a Social Democrat, will occupy
later this year, is frustrated by this enduring fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that Germany lost courage, identity and culture
because of the loss of our cities in World War II,'' he said.
``Look at Dresden, look at Berlin, and you see a facade of history,
empty behind its surface. I think a great deal of the German
anxiety comes from losing that urban fabric. And I am desperately
unhappy that it has proved so difficult to restore a palpable
texture of metropolitan life to this grayish, kaput city. Because
if we can ever regain German identity, it is here in Berlin.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot is indeed at stake in the return of the German capital to
Berlin 54 years after the fall of the Reich. Bonn, the small
Rhineland town hastily chosen as capital of the post-war German
Federal Republic in 1949, was a means to overcome the past by
avoiding it, ``a beginning, a city without a past,'' as Konrad
Adenauer put it. The town, placid and twee, betokened a muted
identity about as distant from Prussian militarism as could be
imagined. The aim, above all, was to be unthreatening.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, by contrast, involves a more complete, and critical,
German emancipation through direct confrontation with that past;
the Foreign Ministry, for example, is moving into Hitler's former
Reichsbank and the Labor Ministry into Joseph Goebbels' Propaganda
Ministry. In this tense dialectic _ between Nazi ghosts and
ambitious metropolitan dreams, between Cold War shadows and visions
of a Germany where old East-West tensions have gone _ lies the
potential and the danger of Berlin. As a backdrop for cultural
experiment, it is unusually rich.
</P>
<P>
   It is also uncertain. The risks are evident. This is the fifth
Germany of which Berlin has been capital in the last century: the
others were Imperial, Weimar, Nazi and Communist. A restlessness
redolent of the New World has characterized the city's apparently
insatiable appetite to reinvent itself. It is interesting, and
disturbing to some, that Germany is back at war, this time at
America's side and in Kosovo, just as the move to Berlin takes
place. Certainly, this is not the act of a political midget.
</P>
<P>
   Can the city be an unthreatening expression of this new German
desire to emerge from political tutelage and find the stability
that has long eluded it? On Berlin's success depends a
``normalization'' now craved by the vast majority of Germans. This
normality is not synonymous with conformity. In fact, the often
stifling conformity of the immediate postwar generation is now
rejected by many young Germans.
</P>
<P>
   These Germans do not shun the duty of memory. But they feel
there must be a life beyond inherited guilt and shame. For many of
them, the normality of a successful ``Berlin Republic'' should be
bold where Bonn was banal, weaving together political, cultural and
intellectual threads to form a vibrant city of a revived
Mitteleuropa.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What will distinguish Berlin from Paris or London is the fact
that it is the true meeting point of East and West, the one place
where the two mentalities are present day after day,'' said Ulrich
Eckhardt, the director of a millennium cultural festival that will
open in May. ``Berlin's future involves the return of Mitteleuropa.
If the city is to thrive, it must prove a cultural and intellectual
magnet to people from Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic and
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if two main elements of the culture of Mitteleuropa
were Germanic and Slavic, a third was Jewish. Although the Jewish
population of Berlin has grown in recent years to about 10,000,
swollen by arrivals from Russia, Hitler's work is irreversible.
Something was lost; it will not return. That loss still haunts
Berlin, and the city remains at a loss as to how to record it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most conspicuous, and embarrassing, empty spaces of
the many in this city is a 4.9-acre site beside the Brandenburg
Gate where a Holocaust Memorial has been mooted for a decade now
without agreement being reached on what, if anything, should be
built. Michael Naumann, the top cultural official in Schroeder's
government, has spent much of his time over the last six months
trying to resolve the issue. A vociferous critic last year of plans
for a field of about 2,800 stone pillars by New York architect
Peter Eisenman and New York sculptor Richard Serra. Naumann has
since become a champion of a modified project elaborated with
Eisenman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My original esthetic and moral hesitations remain,'' Naumann
said. ``In the country where the crimes were committed, it seems to
me that any artistic expression, any iconographic gesture, cannot
adequately carry the burden of remembrance. We are known as the
nation of the perpetrators, although most of the perpetrators are
dead, and so what we do will always be questioned by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he has become convinced since the Schroeder
government took office of the need for a memorial that would serve
a historical and educational function. ``I did not want to be
co-opted by the conservatives, and I had underestimated the
memorial's importance to the German state,'' Naumann said. The
revised plan, on which the Bundestag will vote in May, calls for a
field with a smaller number of pillars, an exhibition space, a vast
archive that will serve as a research center for scholars and a
65-foot high wall of books.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there have been objections from Berlin Mayor Eberhard
Diepgen and from the likely next president of Germany, Johannes
Rau. The discussions could even continue for another decade. But
Naumann said the chancellor was determined to push through the
latest project. Construction would begin next year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the polemics say much about the tensions still
afflicting Berlin. To be bold, culturally or architecturally,
requires a certain confidence, one that Germany and its capital
still lack. The subliminal questions persist: Can we ever be
trusted again? Will others trust us?
</P>
<P>
   Not for nothing, it seems, many of the major urban projects in
the city went to foreign architects. ``The idea was lurking
somewhere that if these foreigners built something too big or
imperial, it was not our fault,'' Schlink suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the results seem mixed. The Potsdamer Platz, the
heart of prewar Berlin and then a no man's land between East and
West, has emerged as a strange hodgepodge, where some fine
buildings, like Renzo Piano's Daimler-Benz complex, appear drowned
in a sea of anonymous commercialism: McDonald's, a vast shopping
mall, movie houses and a dislocated central plaza lacking in
grandeur. But the development has proved hugely popular, one of the
few places where ``Ossis'' and ``Wessis'' really mingle, and
perhaps the lowest common denominator of today's Berliners is
indeed a taste for global brands and the trappings of America.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the view of Christoph Schlingensief, one of
the most provocative young theater directors in Berlin, whose revue
``Die Berliner Republik'' is now showing at the Berlin Volksbuehne.
Largely improvised, the revue suggests a time of terrible
fin-de-siecle desperation, as a lascivious caricature of Schroeder
takes a moment off from groping every woman he can find to bang
helplessly on the glass wall of an elevator and denounce his lonely
fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalism is like a mirage in the desert _ you touch it and it
is gone,'' Schlingensief said. ``It suits many Germans because it
is a way out of national identity _ just look at Schroeder's
emotionless end-of-time smile. We are still very afraid of real
emotion; only the illusion of emotion is all right. Our whole
culture has no obsessions. Obsession is a fire you cannot put out.
That is the problem here in Berlin. I see nothing marked by
obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course as this city has repeatedly illustrated, obsession
can be dangerous. So, for the moment, Berlin makes its way
cautiously, a touch dutifully, with its three opera houses _ the
Deutsche Oper, the Staatsoper and the Komische Oper _ side by side
with streets that speak of an incorrigible provincialism. The new
``capital of Europe'' still has no direct flights to the United
States and little prospect of any in the near future. ``Berliners
do not want urbanity,'' Schultes, the architect, said in despair.
``They want trees.''
</P>
<P>
   They have plenty of them, for various reasons, among them the
fact that Berlin has swallowed a series of villages without ever
entirely integrating them. At the turn of the century, the writer
Arthur Eloesser remarked that, ``The extremities of the city have
become so monstrously swollen the insides are suffering from a
shortage of blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, of course, Berlin found much blood, but of the wrong
kind, and today it still lacks what Schultes called ``the muscles
that bind.'' Out of such a binding, one senses, a great city of
culture could emerge, but a decade or two will surely be needed.
Meanwhile, the Berlin experiment remains intriguing in its
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we at ease with each other here?'' Naumann asked. ``No,
not really. It will take decades, even centuries. But perhaps that
is a wonderful state to be in. For it keeps you perpetually on your
toes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
