<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9463 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-A     04-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET HIDE AND SEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He did his best to remain anonymous, but within
days after an expert programmer released the Melissa computer virus
into the world late last month, police reported that his identity
had been cracked. Investigators used a tracking mechanism that
Microsoft Corp. had secretly installed in its Office software to
gather information on its customers surreptitiously.
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia, meanwhile, messages poured onto the Internet from
the war zone, providing what appeared to be firsthand accounts of
Yugoslav atrocities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Privacy
advocates realized that if the Yugoslav authorities were able to
trace the identities of the writers, many lives could be lost.
Ominously, messages from some writers had stopped suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy groups moved swiftly to provide the writers with
special access to Anonymizer.com, an Internet service that allows
users to be anonymous and untraceable online, and with information
about PGP, a data encryption program so strong that the United
States prohibits its export.
</P>
<P>
   These two cases, worlds apart, underscore a growing dilemma that
now confronts the electronic world. ``Anonymity has incontestable
value in a huge number of situations, and it is constitutionally
protected,'' said Philip Reitinger, a prosecutor for the Justice
Department, speaking at a ``Computers, Freedom and Privacy''
conference here Wednesday. Moments later, during a panel
discussion, he added, ``If you're serious about prosecuting crime
on the global communications infrastructure, you have to have
traceability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should communications on the Internet be traceable in some
circumstances? And if so, what should the rules be?''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a broad one because anonymity is not of interest
only to criminals and dissidents, and not available only to the
technically astute. New technologies are emerging that enable even
casual Internet users to be anonymous online for the first time. At
the same time, new technologies are being deployed to gather ever
more personal information from users.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, debate has emerged over new technologies that
have been deployed to allow companies to track individual users on
the Internet. Intel Corp. embedded a unique identification number
in its Pentium III processor that would enable network operators to
identify individual computers on the Internet, and Microsoft Corp.
designed a ``globally unique identifier'' that secretly appears in
Microsoft Office documents and can be used to trace files back to a
specific person. The Microsoft Office identification number was
used in the Melissa investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy tools are being simplified and made available
commercially to a broad audience, allowing anyone to browse the
World Wide Web and use e-mail without being identified. The
technologies are morally neutral. They could be used, for example,
to commit a crime or to report one anonymously. The tools, like the
Anonymizer (www.anonymizer.com), are also useful simply for
browsing the Web without having to give up personal information to
marketers, for visiting sex-related Web sites without potential
embarrassment, posting messages on newsgroups using pseudonyms and
for avoiding spam, the bulk-mail advertising pitches that
advertisers send incessantly to e-mail addresses they have culled
from the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has shifted the balance away from privacy, and
these are attempts to bring it back,'' said David Banisar, an
officer of the Electronic Privacy Information Center
(www.epic.org).
</P>
<P>
   There are other anonymity systems in the works. At AT&AMP;T
Labs-Research in New Jersey, a system called Crowds is being tested
that operates on the premise, familiar to any New Yorker, that one
can be anonymous in a crowd. In the Crowds system, large groups of
geographically dispersed Internet users would be able to band
together and their individual Web page requests would be randomly
forwarded through a shared computer called a proxy server. The
operator of the Web site would not know which member of the crowd
submitted the request, and neither would anyone else in the crowd.
More information is available at www.research.att
.com/projects/crowds.
</P>
<P>
   At Lucent Corp.'s Bell Labs, another anonymity system called the
Lucent Personalized Web Assistant allows a Web user to create a
pseudonym for each Web site; the same pseudonym would be used on
each visit. The Web site operator would not know the visitor's true
identity but could still build a profile of the user's preferences
that could be used to tailor advertisements and content to the
customer on subsequent visits. More information about Lucent's
system is available at www.bell-labs.com/project/lpwa.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another anonymity system under development, this one at the
government's Naval Research Laboratory, is Onion Routing. An Onion
Router (www.onion-router.net) hides not only the content of
messages, but also the very fact that two people are communicating
over a public network.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more intriguing anonymity services under development
is Freedom, a Windows program developed by a Canadian company, Zero
Knowledge Systems (www.zeroknowledge.com). Freedom, which is
expected to be available for public testing next month, is similar
to the Lucent system in that it enables users to establish
pseudonyms that are consistent over time. That would allow a user
to participate freely in a discussion group without worrying about
being identified.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom is expected to cost $50 a year for five separate digital
pseudonyms (extra identities are $10 a year). These online personas
cannot be traced to reveal the user's identity.
</P>
<P>
   The technical details of the system, including strong data
encryption, masked Internet addresses and proxy servers, are hidden
behind a simple user interface, which I've tried in early form.
After a user chooses a persona by clicking on it, all identifying
information is stripped from the original request and replaced by
the information created for the pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Internet users already employ pseudonyms; America
Online, for example, calls them screen names and allows each
subscriber to have several. But in most cases a pseudonym can be
traced to its real owner, often when the Internet company is
compelled by a court order to divulge the information or is tricked
into doing so.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the giant defense contractor Raytheon Corp. sued
more than 20 employees earlier this year for posting pseudonymous
messages about the company on the Internet. At least two employees
resigned after Yahoo, in response to a court subpoena, revealed the
true identities behind the postings. Raytheon asserts that the
messages, which contained gossip and criticisms of the company,
divulged proprietary and confidential information.
</P>
<P>
   With Freedom, not even Zero Knowledge Systems can link the
pseudonyms to a user's real identity. The company knows only that
the person has a Freedom account.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest commercial service offering anonymity, and the only
one currently available to users of any Internet-connected
computer, is Anonymizer.com. Unlike Freedom, Anonymizer does not
require the user to download or install any special software. For a
fee of $5 a month, users can process Web browsing requests and send
messages through Anonymizer's proxy servers. (There is also an
unlimited free browsing service, but Anonymizer inserts a delay,
typically 10 seconds, on page views in the free service. The paid
service has no delays.) For an extra fee, Anonymizer will also
allow users to receive e-mail responses and set up Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the user types the address of the Web site to be
visited, and the request is sent to Anonymizer's proxy computer.
The proxy strips off the customer's identifying information and
forwards the request to the Web site, which knows only that the
request is coming from Anonymizer. The page or graphics file is
then returned to the user's computer, and the site can be
bookmarked for return visits with the anonymity intact.
</P>
<P>
   If a company is tracking Web usage by its employees _ which the
courts have ruled is legally permissible, along with reading
employees' e-mail and listening to their phone calls _ it will see
only that the user is connected to Anonymizer.com, but it will not
be able to find out what sites are being visited. For that reason,
a number of companies prohibit employee access to the Anonymizer
site. Other companies use Anonymizer regularly to visit the Web
sites of competitors and gather information, and law enforcement
agencies use it routinely to check up on people under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the line, some commercial sites do not allow
connections from Anonymizer, either because they require visitors
to provide personal information before granting them access or
because they have had bad experiences with Anonymizer users who
abused the system with bogus credit card scams or harassing
messages. Anonymizer was forced to block its users' access to the
White House Web site because customers were sending threats to the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymizer boots out customers who try to use the system to send
batches of spam, or in response to complaints from people being
harassed through the site.
</P>
<P>
   As with all of the anonymous services now being developed for
the Internet, the good has to be balanced with the bad. ``The real
world is routinely anonymous,'' said Lance Cottrell, Anonymizer's
chief executive. ``When you drive down the street, typically there
is no one photographing your license plate, no one keeping track of
where you park and how long you stay. What's unusual about the
Internet is that everything is by default logged and tracked.
What's aberrant is not the presence of anonymity on the Internet,
but that you have to take special steps to achieve it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9468 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRLOVE-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      04-07 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRLOVE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HEALTH CHIEF COURTS A NEW AGE &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Department of Health, state lawmakers
decided, has been looking for love in all the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the House Appropriations Committee needled Health
Commissioner William ``Reyn'' Archer III at his agency's recent
biennial funding review about questionable state spending on a
photo lab and an expensive junket to China. Yet what most riveted
their attention was a March posting for two $76,000 positions they
quickly dubbed ``Dr. Love'' and ``Commissioner of Love.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Qualifications: ``Knowledge or the ability to comprehend and
articulate the conflicting dynamics of love and alienation as root
causes of social dysfunction and marginal health status. Knowledge
of community ethos relating to dysfunctions and spirituality of
human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know where we're going on this,'' Rep. Leticia
Van de Putte, D-San Antonio, told Archer. ``I mean, is the Dalai
Lama going to apply for the job?''
</P>
<P>
   The job descriptions for the two associate commissioners alarmed
the elected officials who said they worried about what their
constituents might think. Archer, they noted, had earlier laid
plans to shift money away from underfunded basic health services _
such as school-based clinics _ and into an untested theory to
attack root causes of ``diseases of choice, of lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   For Archer, the son of a powerful congressman, the showdown
proved a firsthand lesson in politics. Considered an intelligent
man of lofty ideals, the commissioner's latest vision proved too
transcendental for the Texas Legislature to comprehend. In a
stinging rebuke, the committee passed measures calling for the
start-up of four school health clinics and another restricting
Archer's ability to shift money around in his own department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at risk of being misunderstood, in a sense, no matter what
I say, but the fact is the goal here is to really make a difference
in Texas public health. Obviously, people can misperceive our
intentions,'' Archer told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The health commissioner said he thinks his interest in
mind-body-spirit connections is mainstream, but several legislators
pointed out that attacking ``root causes'' of behavior takes the
idea into a new and nebulous dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Archer is asking the Legislature for a $150 million
endowment from the state's tobacco settlement. Anticipated interest
of $8.4 million a year could finance a research foundation for the
next decade to prove why cultural and spiritual issues of
alienation cause certain groups to smoke, engage in risky sex, take
dangerous drugs, eschew exercise, drink excessively and eat too
much.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's interest is in ``population-based'' health initiatives
aimed at communities with such common traits as their cultural
heritage, race, and, in the case of adolescents or obese children,
their youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Archer has articulated a belief that modern public health
problems arise from disordered interpersonal relations. They are
exacerbated by a reduction in societal cohesion and a rise in
alienation, especially among young people,'' according to the
department's four-page proposal calling for the creation of the
Texas Foundation for Public Health Research.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also says minorities and new immigrants ``continue
to bear the greater burden of certain diseases'' and ``today Texans
suffer largely from diseases of choice, of lifestyle. Roughly
speaking, a Texan can choose whether or not to place himself at
risk for these diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Days after his legislative encounter, the commissioner sat in
his office at the health department and wondered if his idea is
perhaps ahead of its time. Clearly the choice of words in the job
description meant too many things to too many people, said Archer,
an obstetrician-gynecologist and son of U.S. Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   To some, maybe it looked like an issue of separation of church
and state. He said he draws a distinction between spirituality and
religion that others might not understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously need to be careful about being perceived as a
proselytizing agency because that cannot be our goal. We can't work
with a diverse population if we come at it from one vantage point
that you're going to believe the way we believe,'' he said. ``It
won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he can't predict whether the Legislature will create the
$150 million endowment from the tobacco settlement that could be
put toward the preventive strategies he wants to try. House Bill
1676 by Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, he noted, includes language for
setting up an endowment for children's health care and grants to
local communities.
</P>
<P>
   Since the language is ``loose enough but not prescriptive,'' it
could open the door for the foundation, which would oversee grants
to local organizations and universities interested in studying and
proposing ways to strike at root causes of risky behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know that there's nothing radical,'' he said.
``They need to know these will help communities, not hurt them.
They don't know that yet, but we have an obligation to show that.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   At the appropriations committee earlier, Rep. Dianne Delisi, a
Temple Republican, spoke up for Archer's philosophy of public
health. She said she believes his approach could prolong life in
the next century the way polio vaccines did in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Archer then defended his concept of ``pre-primary'' preventive
medicine, saying it could help identify why Houston has the lowest
inoculation rates of any major city in the country. Is there an
identifiable cultural underpinning at work that could be addressed?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fascinating discussion, because every time I want to
talk about love and alienation, everybody wants to talk about
polio,'' said Rep. Kyle Janek, a medical doctor and Houston
Republican. ``Dr. Archer, if I can keep you on point here, I'd like
you to tell me what the lack of immunization has to do with love
and alienation.''
</P>
<P>
   Janek also asked why, when law enforcement officials have
understood the root causes of juvenile gangs for decades, no one
has figured out what to do to stop them. His scrutiny proved so
unrelenting that Archer finally gave up: ``Obviously, I'm not able
to justify it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he quickly noted that he probably could have avoided
such pointed questions if he had simply changed the language of the
job descriptions. More than 90 people applied for each job, the
health department said, but no one has been hired for either yet.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, noted later that Archer is a
``very nice man, very pleasant man,'' who nonetheless struck a
nerve with lawmakers who didn't want basic health services cut in
their communities to make room for a concept they found
ill-defined.
</P>
<P>
   What, exactly would the $76,000-a-year people do all day, asked
Janek, who later said he found Archer's responses unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we're going to shift money away from poor people to
this global Big Brother concept is bad policy, as far as I'm
concerned. Bizarre might not be too strong a word,'' Janek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds incendiary,'' said Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston,
``but what is the real agenda at this health department? He's
clashing with us in a sense that we want to provide direct services
to our constituents and we want a concrete explanation of the value
of this research he's talking about, the value of these
population-based programs that we can't get a handle on.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said he senses Archer has been pursuing a
``sociopolitical agenda'' at the health department. ``I believe he
has an ideology, and yes, I think he is moving forward with that
ideology. What that ideology is I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner, whose appointment two years ago was approved
by Gov. George W. Bush, was among organizers for Bush's conference
last week on ``right choices'' for youth aimed at educators,
doctors, law enforcement officials and others interested in guiding
the values of children.
</P>
<P>
   Janek, however, emphasized to Archer that it is difficult to
justify spending public money for ``love and alienation'' when the
state is already taking heat for alarming child abuse deaths and
too few child protection caseworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you see why we think that makes us look bad?'' he asked
Archer. ``(It) reinforces the negative perceptions people have
about government.''
</P>
<P>
   But Archer contends that mainstream medicine is showing a
growing interest in the mind-body-spirit connection. He cited
studies, including one conducted by the University of Texas M.D.
Anderson Cancer Center, that show higher healing rates for patients
with spiritual grounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been studies, for example, in universities where
individuals going through heart surgery who have connectedness and
have a faith in God have a significantly greater chance of survival
than those who do not. It can't be about promoting religion, but it
does need to be that we are open to the dynamics that lead to good
health,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But such thinking is relatively new for Western medicine, Janek
said, and has not been subjected to rigorous scientific research.
For the state of Texas to go forward with the idea, he said, would
make the state look foolish and reflect badly on the health
department.
</P>
<P>
   The department of health should gather data and identify public
health concerns wherever they pop up, Janek said, but the
government must always avoid temptations to intrude into the lives
of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as policy, twisting arms, encouraging people to be
healthy and sanctioning if they do not, that is not something I
want the department of health to do,'' he said. ``When (and if)
they want to start interfering and taking someone's personal
freedoms away, I draw the line.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
