<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTWORTH-BALLET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BALLET STAR STEPS INTO THE SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Don't expect the traditional wizened,
wizardly Dr. Coppelius when the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet dances the
humorous story ballet ``Coppelia'' at Bass Performance Hall this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For this production, the magician who throws a village into
comical turmoil when he creates a life-size, lifelike doll will be
a younger, more active fellow, reinterpreted to fit the unique
combination of acting and dancing skills that Igor Dombrovsky
brings to the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought of Coppelius as an old guy,'' Dombrovsky
says. ``Now, he's younger. He lives in his own world. He's slightly
kookier than the usual Coppelius.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the first starring role for Dombrovsky, 33, who is
finishing his second year with the company. His move into the
spotlight and his reinterpretation of Coppelius are symbolic of the
transformation the ballet has experienced this year. New dancers
are moving forward and new ideas are moving in, just as surely as a
younger version of Coppelius supplants the traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers such as Maria Terezia Balogh, Todd Edson and Maria
Thomas, who for a decade defined the look of the company, are gone
or leaving. Dombrovsky and a host of other dancers are molding a
company in keeping with the vision of new artistic director
Benjamin Houk.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences at Fort Worth Dallas Ballet, long accustomed to the
Balanchine repertoire, have seen a definite break toward greater
diversity this season. This revival of the 19th-century, classical
story ballet ``Coppelia'' represents another major new ingredient
in the repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Artistic director Houk, completing his first season at the helm
of the company, spotted Dombrovsky's ability to introduce character
development and acting into his dancing, even as a background
figure in ``Rodeo'' and ``The Nutcracker.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Kiev, Dombrovsky focused on the accordion as a
youngster. He planned on becoming a concert accordionist, a career
of the sort that could only exist in the old Soviet Union. But his
mother and father (a kindergarten teacher and sewing-machine
mechanic, respectively) were unhappy in the Soviet Union and gained
permission to emigrate to the United States when Igor was 15.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things young Igor brought with him from Kiev was a
taste for ballet, even though he had no training. Although he had
seen ballet mostly on television, he remembers seeing live
performances of ``Swan Lake'' and ``Don Quixote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so stricken by the beauty of them that I was almost
sick,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than moving to one of the major Russian communities then
sprouting up across America, where one could live surrounded by
transplanted Russian culture, the Dombrovsky family moved to San
Antonio and began assimilating.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Dombrovsky joined the ``Up With People''
touring musical group and began learning basic theatrical dancing.
After a year on the road, he entered college at United States
International University in San Diego, focusing first on theater
and then on musical theater, and studying ballet, tap and jazz
dancing. His first appearance in ballet was as a stepsister in
``Cinderella.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a turning point in my life,'' he says. ``I decided to
devote myself to ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although for many years Dombrovsky tried to avoid being labeled
as a ``character dancer'' _ a dancer who specializes in roles that
sometimes take more acting than dancing, such as the stepsisters in
``Cinderella'' or Drosselmeyer in ``Nutcracker'' _ it's not
surprising, given his background, that that's where he has landed
in the prime of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I was afraid of being called a character
dancer,'' he admits. ``I didn't want to be cast only in certain
roles. Character dancers typically aren't as concerned with clean
lines as other dancers. They are more concerned with catching the
eye of the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Houk, Dombrovsky brings both dancing and
acting to the role to an unusual degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as crotchety as the usual Dr. Coppelius,'' Houk says.
``Since he's such a capable dancer and actor, he does a lot more
than Coppelius often does.''
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music and arts for the
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
