<HEADLINE>
QUICK HELATH NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTIBIOTICS FOR THE HEART
</P>
<P>
   Antibiotics may prove as valuable in the treatment of heart
disease as they are against ulcers, which only in recent years have
been associated with bacterial infections, according to reports in
last week's issue of ``Circulation: Journal of the American Heart
Association.''
</P>
<P>
   Antibiotic treatment reduces inflammation in the blood vessels,
which plays a much larger role in coronary heart disease than was
once thought, says Dr. Jeffrey Anderson, chief of cardiology at the
University of Utah Medical Center and a principal investigator in
the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that such factors as high cholesterol, cigarette
smoking, high blood pressure and diabetes can cause inflammation in
the blood vessels, which contributes to atherosclerosis, the cause
of heart attacks,'' Anderson says. ``If common infectious agents
such as chlamydia `rev up' the atherosclerotic inflammatory
process, antibiotic therapy could become a major breakthrough
treatment against a disease that kills more Americans each year
than any other disease.''
</P>
<P>
   More study is needed to determine the role of antibiotics in
preventing heart attacks, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   The recent film ``Patch Adams'' has renewed interest in the
effectiveness of using laughter as medical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A growing number of health professionals recognize the value
of humor and are using it with patients to help relieve anxiety and
promote recovery,'' says Dr. Ron Berk, reporting in the ``Johns
Hopkins Health Insiders'' newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laughter can help decrease anxiety and stress and improve the
perceived quality of life, important factors during times of
illness,'' Berk ways. ``Studies show that laughter may also trigger
physiological changes such as stimulating circulation, improving
respiration, boosting production of pain-reducing endorphins and
possibly even increasing immune system activity and response.''
</P>
<P>
   STRESS 'N' SNIFFLES
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have identified what may be the biological link
between stress and the common cold: interleukin-6 (IL-6), a
chemical pathway used by the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sheldon Cohen of Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh,
who earlier found a clear link between psychological stress and
infection by respiratory viruses, says the new study provides
concrete evidence of a mind-body connection _ the biological
pathway through which psychological stress influences
upper-respiratory infectious illness.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and his colleagues had previously established stress as a
risk factor for respiratory illness but had only been able to
speculate on the potential biological pathway that links stress to
greater risks of colds and flu.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
