<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-INFOOD-2400(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WHETS AMERICA'S APPETITE FOR PACKAGED GOODS, HOUSEHOLD
APPLIANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Hotel in Omaha.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1914: The outbreak of war in Europe leads to the expansion of
U.S. pasta production. Until now, most of the macaroni and
spaghetti have come from Naples, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   1915: Per capita consumption of white sugar doubles from 1880
levels as Americans move away from molasses and brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1916: The invention of the fortune cookie is attributed to
George Jung, founder of the Hong Kong Noodle Co. in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   1916: War looms and the Edwardian good life becomes passe.
Delmonico's, the most influential restaurant of the past century,
closes.
</P>
<P>
   1916: Piggly-Wiggly opens in Memphis, Tenn., and becomes the
first supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   1916: U.S. food prices jump 19 percent because of crop
shortages, rail car shortages and increased demand from
war-strapped Britain. By 1917, price increases result in riots in
Boston, New York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   1916: Streit's matzos are introduced in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   1916: Cosmetics for women are frowned upon, unless the woman is
of a certain age and so can perk up her faded looks with a bit of
rouge. Most ``cosmetics'' are homemade _ such as lemon juice to
lighten and soften hands, as promoted by the Sunkist cooperative.
Quaker Oats promotes its product as ``making flesh rather than fat,
but enough fat for reserve force.''
</P>
<P>
   1917: The United States declares war on the Central Powers,
joining an exhausted Britain and France, which have been fighting
since 1914.
</P>
<P>
   1917: The hamburger becomes a ``liberty sandwich'' and
sauerkraut is ``liberty cabbage'' during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   1918: President Woodrow Wilson orders a 1,700-piece service of
Lenox china, the first U.S.-made porcelain to be used in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   1919: Coca-Cola goes public. A $40 investment, with dividends
reinvested, is worth $7.5 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   1919: KitchenAid, seeking to move beyond supplying the U.S. Navy
and commercial bakeries, produces a domestic version of its mixer.
Four a day roll off the Ohio assembly line and are sold by a female
sales force that takes the 65-pound product door to door. The model
sells for $189.50.
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   GREEN CORN, CREOLE STYLE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 cups corn kernels cut from cob
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tomato soup
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon onion juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter and cook pepper in it until tender. Add flour,
blend, and add tomato soup. Stir until smooth. Add seasonings and
corn, heat thoroughly, and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 235 calories, 14 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 35 milligrams cholesterol,
955 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat. _
Campbell's
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH CHERRY DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1/3 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons maraschino cherry juice
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 maraschino cherries, mashed fine
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients and stir thoroughly before pouring over
lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 56 calories, 5 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 237 milligrams
sodium, 88 percent of calories from fat. _ ``White House Cook
Book'' by Hugo Ziemann and Mrs. F.L. Gillette (Saalfield Publishing
Co., out of print)
</P>
<P>
   LUNCHEON ASPARAGUS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches asparagus
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soft bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 hard-boiled eggs, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Pimento, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Wash and scrape asparagus. Tie in small bundles and cook in
boiling, salted water with heads out for 15 minutes. Put heads
under water and cook for 10 minutes. Drain and arrange on a hot
platter. Remove strings.
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter and fry bread crumbs to a pale straw color. Sprinkle
over asparagus. Arrange egg slices around asparagus, garnish with
strips of pimento and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 139 calories, 10 grams fat, 9
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 91 milligrams cholesterol,
134 milligrams sodium, 64 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``White House Cook Book''
</P>
<P>
   POTATO CARAMEL CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-12
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups light-brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup hot potatoes, cubed
</P>
<P>
   3 squares baker's chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Filling/frosting:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Cream sugar, egg yolks and shortening; add milk, then melted
chocolate beaten in while hot, and the cubed potatoes. Reserve 1/4
cup flour and nuts. Add rest of flour, salt, baking powder and
spices sifted together; fold in floured nuts and stiffly beaten egg
whites. Pour into greased and floured cake pans and bake at 375
degrees for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To make filling, cook cream, butter and sugar together until it
forms a soft ball in cold water, remove from fire, add vanilla,
beat until creamy. When cool, spread between layers and on top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 674 calories, 33 grams fat, 94
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 100 milligrams cholesterol,
346 milligrams sodium, 44 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Bewley's Best'' recipe pamphlet
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Louis Rukeyser's ``Book of Lists'' (Owl, $15.95); John
Mariani's ``The Dictionary of American Food and Drink'' (Hearst,
$19.95); ``Soda Pop! From Miracle Medicine to Pop Culture'' by
Gyvel Young-Witzel and Michael Karl Witzel (Town Square Books,
$35); ``The Food Chronology'' by James Trager (Owl Books, $22.50;
``Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren (Macmillan, $25);
``Mechanical Brides,'' Cooper-Hewitt National Museum of Design
(Princeton Architectural Press, $24.95); ``Jewish Cooking in
America'' by Joan Nathan (Knopf, $30); American Frozen Food
Institute; ``The Motley Fool's Rule Breakers, Rule Makers'' by
David and Tom Gardner (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25); ``Revolution at the
Table: The Transformation of the American Diet'' by Harvey
Levenstein (Oxford, 1988); ``Neighbor, How Long Has It Been?'' by
Wallace O. Chariton (Self-published, $14.95); ``Eating in America:
A History'' by Waverley Root and Richard De Rochemont (Morrow,
1976); McDonald's; Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDNM/ nn
</P>
