<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-INFOOD-2400(2     04-07 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-INFOOD-2400(2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WHETS AMERICA'S APPETITE FOR PACKAGED GOODS, HOUSEHOLD
APPLIANCES
</HEADLINE>
 Takes)-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1910s began with a roar and ended with a whimper _ a
tempestuous decade of high living, high prices, the introduction of
income taxes, women's suffrage, World War I, an influenza pandemic
that killed between 20 million and 50 million people, and _ as if
to put a lid on this Pandora's box _ the proclamation of
Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   America's economy was chugging along, having evolved from
agrarian to industrial. Immigration was at full throttle. The
number of house servants, who often came from the newly arrived
masses, continued to decline as immigrants found jobs in factories
and mines.
</P>
<P>
   Through the end of the decade, the number of domestic servants
dropped from 1.8 million to 1.4 million while the number of
households rose from 20.3 million to 24.4 million. This meant that
homemakers, once the managing directors of housework, became
responsible for the hands-on duty. But industry was there to offer
a helping hand. This was the decade that saw the first big
introduction of household appliances.
</P>
<P>
   But all was not progress. A depression in 1914-15 led the
nutrition reformers, the eat-by-the-numbers zealots of the previous
decade, to poke their noses into the eating habits of immigrants
and the poor. Concern was valid, as many immigrants lived in
cramped quarters in large Eastern cities where disease was rampant.
But food was one area where a little knowledge could be a dangerous
thing.
</P>
<P>
   One system of judging malnutrition, the Dumferline Scale, ranked
height, weight, eyesight, breathing, muscularity, mental alertness
and rosiness of complexion as benchmarks of health. This worked
fine for British and German children but was inappropriate for
olive-skinned Italians, Greeks, Turks and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced of widespread malnutrition, the school lunch program
ballooned, but the American food ideal wasn't necessarily that of
the immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   Italian immigrant John Fante recognized the two worlds of his
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the lunch hour I huddle over my lunch pail, for my mother
doesn't wrap my sandwiches in wax paper and she makes them too
large and the lettuce leaves protrude. Worse, the bread is
homemade; not bakery bread, not `American' bread. I make a great
fuss because I can't have mayonnaise and other `American' things,''
Fante recalled in ``American Mercury'' magazine in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   And Fante's family no doubt drank wine with its meals _ unlike
nonimmigrant families. But that, too, was about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State William Jennings Bryan, a Prohibitionist,
served Welch's grape juice instead of wine at a 1913 dinner for the
British ambassador. The next year, Secretary of the Navy Josephus
Daniels ordered that the Navy's traditional rum grog be replaced
with Welch's grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   By 1919, the Temperance League had won out and the sale and
distribution of alcohol was banned. In 1920, saloons were shuttered
and distilleries closed, and America would begin its Noble
Experiment.
</P>
<P>
   1910: Seventy percent of U.S. bread is baked at home, down from
80 percent in 1890. Processors employ more than 68,000 people to
can 3 billion cans of food in factories per year.
</P>
<P>
   1910: The first refrigerated tank car for wine brings California
wine to the East, but most Golden State wine is shipped by steamer
around Cape Horn in oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   1911: The first canned chili and tamales are produced in San
Antonio by William Gebhardt. The term ``tamale pie'' first appears
in print.
</P>
<P>
   1911: Procter &AMP; Gamble introduces Crisco, the first solid
vegetable shortening. The product is a hard sell to women who had
been taught to cook with butter and lard. To promote its product,
the manufacturer suggests glazing sweet potatoes with brown sugar
and Crisco, and spreading sandwiches with Crisco mixed with an egg
yolk, Worcestershire sauce, lemon juice and vinegar. Orthodox Jews,
however, love the shortening because it is neither meat nor dairy,
so it can be used at any kosher meal. Crisco has better luck late
in the decade, when lard and butter become scarce because of the
war effort.
</P>
<P>
   1912: Ohio chocolate manufacturer Clarence Crane develops
LifeSavers as a ``summer candy'' that can withstand heat better
than chocolate. The next year, he sells the rights to the
peppermint candy to Edward Noble for $2,900. Noble develops
tin-foil wrappers to keep the mints fresh (they had been packaged
in cardboard rolls).
</P>
<P>
   1912: Nabisco introduces Oreo Biscuits to compete with the
Hydrox ``biscuit bonbons'' rolled out in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   1912: Immigrants pour into the country. Between 1910-1924, 12
million come through Ellis Island. All are examined for health
problems; 2 percent are sent back across the Atlantic. Meanwhile, 1
million emigrate from Mexico during 1910-1930. Many of these
immigrants have large families and are desperately poor, leading to
abusive child labor. Five-year-old Manuel, standing on a mountain
of oyster shells, is a shrimp picker in Biloxi, Miss. He has worked
at the cannery for a year and speaks no English.
</P>
<P>
   1912: New York deli owner Richard Hellmann begins packing his
mayonnaise in glass jars. The product is such a success that he
gives up the deli in 1915 and devotes his energy to manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   1913: General Electric markets toasters, irons and an electric
range.
</P>
<P>
   1914: The first electric refrigerator is introduced for
commercial use, but it's not until after World War I that the
miracle machines are widely available. By 1937, more than 2 million
American households have a new refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   1914: Campbell's promotes its soups as a recipe ingredient to
help the much-burdened housewife.
</P>
<P>
   1914: Lettuce, asparagus, watermelons, cantaloupes and tomatoes
grown in irrigated fields in California are transported 3,000 miles
away in refrigerated rail cars.
</P>
<P>
   1914: George Washington Carver's experiments prove the value of
peanuts and sweet potatoes in replenishing soil fertility.
</P>
<P>
   1914: The Reuben sandwich is created at Reuben's Restaurant in
New York City. (This claim, however, is hotly disputed by
Cornhuskers. Nebraskans believe the sandwich was created in 1922 by
grocer Reuben Kolakofsky during a poker game at the Blackstone
Hotel in Omaha.) (MORE) &QL; 
.MDNM/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCOMONEY-HNS &LR;      04-07 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCOMONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE FLARES OVER FUNDING FOR TOBACCO EDUCATION &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Health-care providers and advocates were of one
mind last year when the state negotiated its $17.3 billion deal
with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette companies' payments to the state should go to
health care or related programs, they insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, blessed with the windfall of riches, some health promoters
are fighting each other over how much money should initially be
spent on a key, underfunded program to discourage Texans from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society of Texas, the American Lung
Association's Texas division and the Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids
_ a single-interest, anti-tobacco group _ are waging an uphill
battle against key legislative budget-writers, the Texas Medical
Association and the rest of the state's health-care and advocacy
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   They want lawmakers to budget $82 million over the next two
years for a tobacco education program, which would include
aggressive television advertising, community outreach and other
efforts to reduce smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer society insists that $82 million is necessary to make
a dent against smoking in a state as populous as Texas, where 23
percent of adults smoke and teen smoking is believed to be on the
rise.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed two-year budget for 2000-01 approved last week by the
House Appropriations Committee would set aside $200 million of the
tobacco settlement proceeds for a smoking-reduction program. But,
under related legislation, the money would be in the form of an
endowment, and only the earnings _ an estimated $20 million over
the next two years _ would actually be spent to fight smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hard time with that because we know it takes more
for a successful prevention program,'' said Cindy Antolik, director
of government relations for the American Cancer Society's Texas
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's plenty of money for health care and also
prevention in the tobacco settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature will have about $1.8 billion in tobacco funds
either to spend outright or to establish endowments in the new
budget. The amount represents the first few payments _ plus
interest _ that cigarette companies are making under the 25-year
payout agreement they negotiated to settle a lawsuit brought by
former Attorney General Dan Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House Appropriations Committee's bill, the largest
outright appropriation _ as much as $179 million _ would go to the
children's health-insurance program, which is designed to expand
health coverage for children of the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Money also would be distributed among a number of other
health-related initiatives, including other children's health-care
needs, drugs for the Department of Mental Health and Mental
Retardation and endowments for medical schools and other university
health-education programs.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the proposed distribution follows an
agreement that Morales made last year with state Rep. Rob Junell,
D-San Angelo, and state Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, the
Legislature's budget chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Junell said an endowment would significantly increase the Texas
Department of Health's funding for anti-smoking efforts. The agency
had only about $1.5 million, including federal funds, to spend this
year.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent health department survey, 43 percent of
Texas high school students, nearly one-third of middle school
students and one in four sixth-graders use tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   But Junell said the state needs time to develop new tobacco
education programs and evaluate their effectiveness before
committing more funds.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, whose Senate Finance Committee is still deliberating
its version of the budget, also questioned the wisdom of spending
$82 million on anti-smoking programs now. He said that it was
better to save the money for long-term use.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have done some good for one set of kids. But if you
run out of money, what happens to the next set of kids?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Junell-Ratliff approach has been endorsed by the Texas
Medical Association, the Texas Hospital Association, the American
Heart Association's Texas affiliate and a host of other health-care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ensures that there will be money there forever to fund
tobacco prevention programs,'' said Tom Banning, a lobbyist for the
Texas Academy of Family Physicians, which also is part of the
so-called Coalition for a Healthy Texas, which backs the two budget
chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Antolik said the cancer society's $82 million request, which
would include about $21 million in start-up costs for the first
year and $61 million the second year, is based, in part, on
aggressive anti-smoking campaigns in Florida, California and
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   She said Florida, the first state to use tobacco settlement
proceeds to pay for an anti-smoking program, saw smoking among
teen-agers decline by more than 2 percent in the past year, meaning
about 31,000 middle school and high school students stopped smoking
or decided not to start.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida program, initially funded at $70 million, included
television spots and other advertising, which young people helped
create, that ridiculed smoking and tobacco executives.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   But the Florida effort has been mired in recent controversy,
apparently caused partly by the change in administrations from the
late Democratic Gov. Lawton Chiles to Republican Gov. Jeb Bush, the
younger brother of Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush budgeted $61.5 million, a 12 percent reduction, for the
program next year, and Florida legislators have been fighting over
its future.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, George W. Bush has endorsed the concept of putting
some of the tobacco funds into long-term endowments but hasn't
taken sides on the anti-smoking program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He, at last check, was continuing to be aggressively
neutral,'' Antolik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what works in other states,'' added Kelly Boyles,
southern regional director for the Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't do it'' for $10 million a year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
