<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR; 
 &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation cannot do everything,'' says Mr. Clinton. For
instance, it can't require all politicians talking about Kosovo to
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mr. Milosevic wants to do,'' Mr. Clinton says, ``is to
keep the land of Kosovo and rid it of its people.'' America's
central cities know how to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The argument continues over the use of ground troops in Kosovo.
Can't we just talk the Serbs into using airborne forces?
</P>
<P>
   Tax tip: You might want to write ``But Not That One'' on your
1040 after your name if it's Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Using U.S. fighter planes in the Balkans has meant a suspension
of patrolling Iraq's northern no-fly zone, reports say. Maybe
that's why they call it the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made tremendous progress in our efforts to address the
year 2000 computer problem,'' Mr. Clinton says. Have we stretched
it out, like Social Security, so it's now a 2003 bug?
</P>
<P>
   The White House Easter egg roll this week was the 121st one in
history. One of these times we'll have to ask Strom Thurmond how it
all got started.
</P>
<P>
   For the Easter egg roll, White House volunteers prepared 7,000
eggs. At Gov. Jesse Ventura's house in Minnesota that's called
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Ilse from Oelwein is upset. She stored her spring clothes
in the attic over the winter and somehow they shrank.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball season opened this year with a Colorado-San Diego
game played on Easter in Mexico. The surprise was the Rockies.
After all, you expect Padres to work on Easter.
</P>
<P>
