<P>
   &UR; MONICA STUFF IS A BUST &LR; 
 &UR; By DAVID GRIMES &QC;  &LR;  I have been searching night and day for the good
that has supposedly come out of the Clinton scandal and I think, at
last, I've found it: Monica Lewinsky memorabilia _ even the really
tacky stuff _ is not selling well.
</P>
<P>
   I will leave it to the pundits to decide whether our democracy
has been strengthened or weakened by the scandal; what, if any,
damage the office of the president has sustained and how long, if
at all, we must continue to endure Barbara Walters' celebrity
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   All I know is if the American people, after going through all
this, are reluctant to spend their hard-earned money on Monica
Bobbing Dolls or Monica Lewinsky Down-On-Your-Knees Hot Sauce, then
there is hope for our great nation after all.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article in The Washington Post by David Segal,
entrepreneurs who hoped to use our national disgrace for personal
enrichment have been sorely disappointed. Tim Flynn of New Jersey
has been pushing Monica Lewinsky ties on the Internet but so far
has yet to sell one.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not because the ties aren't sufficiently tacky. The
$7.89, Korean-made ties feature a cigar, a brunette humanoid who
could be Monica or, perhaps, Marlo Thomas, and the word ``Tabu''
blaring out from a cheesy, fire-engine-red polyester blend.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a bomb,'' Flynn said. ``Everybody thinks Monica is hot,
and it's a big fallacy. After a certain amount of time, this stuff
is going to be worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   That certain amount of time may have expired. Why is Monica
kitsch selling so poorly? Experts say Americans are keeping their
wallets and pocketbooks tightly shut because the whole scandal was
just too ... unseemly.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. A country that tripped over itself buying velour
Elvis wall hangings, Pope John Paul lawn sprinklers and Spiro
Agnew/Mickey Mouse wristwatches has some standards after all. Low
standards, admittedly, but standards nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I hear what you're saying. You're saying, ``Dave, it's one
thing to pass on Monica Lewinsky's Down-On-Your-Knees Hot Sauce _
there are, after all, a lot of other quality hot sauces out there _
but what if Monica gets her famous blue Gap dress back and decides
to sell it? What kind of standards will we have then, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   A good question and a fair question. For an answer let us hear
from Vredy Lytsman, a spokeswoman for the august, prestigious
auction house, Christie's: ``We're an established business, and
there are just certain things where you have to draw the line. Even
if there were a lot of money in it, we wouldn't do it. It's just
unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention pretty darn nasty.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is not to say that some people aren't buying some
Monica memorabilia. A Seattle company, MMD Global Marketing Inc.,
has sold a few thousand Monica yo-yos. The yo-yos, which cost
$14.95, have the president's caricature on one side and Monica's on
the other. Each comes with a booklet of helpful hints about tricks
like ``robbing the cradle'' and ``around the office.''
</P>
<P>
   A $49 set of Russian nesting dolls bearing the likenesses of
Kenneth Starr, Henry Hyde, Linda Tripp and Lucianne Goldberg is
also selling well, according to the Post story.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of sucker buys this stuff?
</P>
<P>
   As someone who has invested a small fortune in baseball cards
only to see his collection depreciate steadily until it is now
barely worth its weight in bathroom tissue, I would seem a likely
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   And I probably would have thrown away some money by now were it
not for the fact that Bobbing Head dolls give me a migraine and hot
sauce upsets my stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The yo-yos, though ... they sound pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   _(The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune
</P>
</TEXT>
