<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION: RELIGION, FEATURES AND NEWS EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   This is part of a yearlong series from Cox News Service
examining the state of Christianity as it approaches its 2,000th
anniversary. Included with the package are MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY,
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN, MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS, MILLENNIUM-LUTHER,
MILLENNIUM-BOX and MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND. A package of photos and
graphics is moving from the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   A page with this material is also available for purchase in
paginated form at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress. A Quark page will be
available by Friday at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The third installment in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution's
yearlong Christianity 2000 series, a detailed look at Christianity
as we approach the millennium, is available now with an embargo
date of Saturday, April 10. This package of stories offers a
historical perspective on the church in Europe, with its roots in
Martin Luther and the Protestant Reformation, and examines why the
European church today faces serious problems. Here is a budget of
the stories and graphics in the package:
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN _ On Oct. 31, 1517, Martin Luther tacked a
paper to the Palace Church door in Wittenberg, sparking a movement
that changed Christianity. But the church Luther founded finds
itself in deep trouble in Europe, where the Lutheran World
Federation reported a ``general reduction in numbers.'' And the
problem is even greater in Germany, the homeland of Protestanism,
where more than a million people have left the church rolls in the
1990s. (Gwhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 67. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS _ Most German Protestants spend little
time in the pews, but the history of northern Germany, the
birthplace of the Protestant Reformation, can be traced through
three churches: The Palace Church in Wittenberg where Luther nailed
the theses that started the Reformation; the Berliner Dom, or great
emperial cathedral, that survived the tremendous forces that shaped
20th century East Berlin; and, St. Michael's in Hamburg, a city
famous for its churches and its red-light district, where the
rebuilding of St. Michael's after World War II has become a major
point of pride for the city. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-LUTHER _ Although Catholic monk Martin Luther never
intended to form his own church, millions of Christians around the
world are now in a family of denominations that bear his name.
Millions more are in other groups _ Reformed, Methodist,
Presbyterian _ that are part of the Protestant Reformation Luther
sparked. A brief bio of Luther. Photo. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.5.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-BOX _ Although the government of Germany collects
funds for the Protestant and Catholic churches along with income
tax, many people have chosen to disaffiliate themselves from the
faith. And many of those who still pay money to the church seldom
attend. We take a quick look at the numbers. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 7.5
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND _ The Church of England has become a stodgy,
picturesque part of the British Isles. It is a place tourists
visit, but a church in which few British are actually involved.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Two graphics are available with this package:
MILLENNIUM-CHART, A country-by-country chart of European religious
affiliation and MILLENNIUM-TIMELINE, a detailed look at the
highlights of Christianity through the Middle Ages. (Both graphics
are being produced by the Atlanta Journal-Constitution Art
Department).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
