<HEADER>
A9488 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND-CO     04-07 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old religious traditions often blamed for religion apathy in
England
 &HT;    Eds: This is part of a yearlong series from Cox News Service
examining the state of Christianity as it approaches its 2,000th
anniversary. Included with the package are MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY,
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN, MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS, MILLENNIUM-LUTHER,
MILLENNIUM-BOX and MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND. A package of photos and
graphics is moving from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    A page with this material is also available for purchase in
paginated form at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress. A Quark page will be
available by Friday at 5 p.m.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, APRIL 10, 1999)
 &HT;    By Melinda Ennis-Roughton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   West Horsley, England _ It is a surprisingly bright morning on
the last Palm Sunday of the millennium in this village.
</P>
<P>
   Like the majority of people in this largely Christian country,
most villagers are pursuing pleasures outside in the rare English
sunshine, even though it is a holy day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a small assembly of worshipers pull off a busy highway on
the outskirts of town, park their cars in a muddy lot and enter an
ancient church that is older than the diminishing national faith
that is practiced there.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's, the Anglican parish church of West Horsley, was
erected in 1030, while the Anglican Church of England is relatively
youthful by British standards at just over 450 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But the old traditions of the Church of England and the country
are sometimes blamed for the religious apathy that is now
widespread in the nation. ``Our message has soaked up the culture,
and the culture has fossilized into yesteryear,'' says the Rev.
Peter Robinson, rector of West Horsley Anglican Parish Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Anglican Church of England first began in 1534, when a
monarch _ who is better remembered for beheading his wives _ wanted
a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   England's King Henry VIII wanted out of his marriage so he could
marry his mistress, Anne Boleyn. But Pope Clement VII refused to
grant the king an annulment, so Henry broke with the papacy and
became ``supreme ruler of the faith.'' It was his daughter,
Elizabeth I, who established the independent, Anglican Church of
England by proclaiming the Protestant ``Book of Common Prayers''
the official national liturgy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three centuries, Anglicanism was spread throughout
the once global British empire, including the American colonies,
where it evolved into the autonomous Episcopal Church. Today the
worldwide Anglican Communion has 73 million members.
</P>
<P>
   The Anglican Church of England is structurally much as it was in
the days of Elizabeth I. The monarch, a second Elizabeth, continues
to preside over the country's official national faith. And the
church and government are still intertwined, with church law often
the law of the land.
</P>
<P>
   Although The Church of England remains the spiritual center of
Anglicanism, the major growth of the faith comes from other nations
in the worldwide Anglican Communion. The mostly evangelical
Anglicans in Africa and Asia now represent almost one third of the
church's global community.
</P>
<P>
   The 27 million member African Anglican Church often took the
lead in policy debates at the denomination's recent Lambeth
Conference, a meeting of the worldwide Anglican Communion held
every 10 years in Canterbury, England. Their conservative,
biblically literal interpretation of Anglicanism influenced the
Conference rulings to maintain the condemnation of homosexuality as
a sin and prevent the ordination of women as a clerical mandate.
</P>
<P>
   First introduced to the Anglican faith by British missionaries,
African Anglicans have now outgrown their English parent church.
``Those we ministered to now minister to us,'' says Jim Rosenthal,
spokesman for the Anglican Worldwide Communion, headquartered in
Canterbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can foresee an Archbishop of Canterbury from Africa or
Asia,'' says West Horsley Parish's Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Most Reverend Right Honorable George Carey is the current
archbishop, the official head of The Church of England and the
``unifying symbol'' of the worldwide Anglican Communion. Like all
of his predecessors, he is British.
</P>
<P>
   ``A non-English archbishop is a possibility,'' said Rosenthal,
``but based on current tradition, he must swear allegiance to the
British monarch and I don't see that changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The zealous style of evangelism that Africa introduced to the
church has achieved results that would have daunted their staid
English forebears. While third world numbers boom, Anglican
religious practice in England is often as reserved and understated
as the nation's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   There are only 1.3 million members on the electoral roles of
England's 13,000 parishes, about 2.6 percent of the country's 50
million inhabitants. But according to the British government's own
1999 handbook, ``many people who rarely, if ever attend services
still regard themselves as belonging to the Church of England.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help that local football and rugby matches are
regularly scheduled on Sunday mornings,'' says Stephen Jenkins,
press officer for the Anglican Church of England. Jenkins defends
declining church attendance statistics by pointing out that the
surveys don't take into account the habits of contemporary
believers.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson cites another reason; the ``irrelevance'' of the church
in the lives of most English citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church must reach out or die out,'' says Robinson. ``We
can learn a lot from our African colleagues,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   British churches have developed their own evangelical efforts to
combat religious indifference. Programs like the ``Alpha Course,''
promoted as a practical introduction to Christianity, have spread
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   But these efforts are often viewed suspiciously by more
traditional, ``high church,'' Catholic-oriented British Anglicans.
``We are an island, both literally and mentally,'' says Robinson
about resistance to change in the mother country.
</P>
<P>
   For many English citizens, the most startling change of all
would be the separation of the church from the state. With 26
Anglican bishops sitting in the House of Lords and religious
education mandatory in the schools, the partnership between the two
bodies is almost seamless. But with speculation that the House of
Lords will disband and that the next monarch, Charles, will be a
``defender of faith,'' not ``the'' faith, the talk of
disestablishment also grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not necessarily be a bad thing,'' says Robinson. ``A
spirit-led church that is not reliant on the government could
motivate a tremendous revival.'' While Rosenthal, of the Anglican
Worldwide Communion, agrees that parishioners need to take
ownership of their own churches, he believes the legal structure of
the English parish church system ``assures a religious center to
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The duties of an English parish priest are principally the same
as they have been for half of this millennium. In West Horsely
Village, Robinson tends to the souls of his small congregation and
solemnizes the baptisms, weddings and funerals of his parishioners,
whether church members or not. ``By law, I must even bury atheists
if they live within my parish,'' he says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a pew in the rector's dusky church, the century could
just as easily be the 16th as the 20th. Aged, wooden beams secure
chapel walls that have stood almost 1000 years.
</P>
<P>
   But walking outside, the speeding cars on the highway in front
of St. Mary's are a reminder that time has moved on. And the
Anglican leaders, in England and around the planet, now prepare to
minister to a complicated new world that would have baffled and
bewildered the restless king and powerful daughter who gave birth
to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
