<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-C     04-07 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Wittenberg: Roots of Lutherism can be traced to this German town
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is part of a yearlong series from Cox News Service
examining the state of Christianity as it approaches its 2,000th
anniversary. Included with the package are MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY,
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN, MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS, MILLENNIUM-LUTHER,
MILLENNIUM-BOX and MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND. A package of photos and
graphics is moving from the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   A page with this material is also available for purchase in
paginated form at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress. A Quark page will be
available by Friday at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, APRIL 10, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   By Gayle White
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Wittenberg
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schelhaas, small and earnest, pops around the counter of
a bright, warm information center to greet guests as pellets of
snow fall outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like to see a video about Wittenberg?'' he asks.
``Twenty minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it tell about Martin Luther?'' a visitor wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Luther, there is nothing to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, 1517, Luther tacked his famous ``95 Theses'' to the
Palace Church door across the street from what is now Schelhaas's
little domain and sparked a movement that challenged Catholicism
and changed Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The church has been destroyed and rebuilt twice _ first by fire,
then by Napoleon's army. The door has been replaced by a brass
replica. But Luther's nail hole still defines this town.
</P>
<P>
   As one pamphlet on Wittenberg says, ``We have the door _ and we
make a living out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schelhaas hopes to use Luther's heritage to make this village on
the northern bank of the River Elbe into a destination for
tourists, pilgrims and scholars interested in the birth of the
Protestant Reformation. He imagines 2000 as a ``Holy Year'' in
three great centers of the faith: Jerusalem, Rome and Wittenberg.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts are accelerating as the church Luther founded finds
itself in deep trouble in Europe, where the Lutheran World
Federation reported a ``general reduction in numbers,'' and
especially in its homeland of Germany, where more than a million
people have left the church rolls in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The state of the church is at its worst in the former East
Germany _ which includes Wittenberg _ where decades of communist
rule after World War II stifled Christianity. Ten years after the
fall of the Berlin Wall, there is little evidence that religion is
making a comeback. In the former German Democratic Republic,
three-fourths of the population does not identify with any
Christian group.
</P>
<P>
   Anga Winkler, 19, illustrates the effects of communism. The high
school student from East Berlin identifies herself in terms of
religion as ``nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents aren't religious,'' she says, ``and they never
asked me what I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk may have Luther spinning in his tomb below the pulpit
of the Palace Church. The crux of his famous theses is that faith
alone _ through the power of Jesus _ brings about salvation.
</P>
<P>
   From a movement within the Catholic church, Lutheranism
eventually became a separate denomination and the starting point
for the Protestant Reformation that became the dominant religious
force throughout much of Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   Today, each of 24 regions of Germany has its own Protestant
church _ some Lutheran, some the ``unified'' church that is both
Lutheran and Reformed, and a few Reformed. These are considered
``state churches'' and funds for them are collected by the
government along with income taxes from anyone identified as a
member.
</P>
<P>
   Some German churchmen say this official relationship has done
almost as much to damage the church in western Germany as decades
of communism did in the east.
</P>
<P>
   In America, churches compete with each other for members, said
the Rev. Uwe Hollm, 68, a retired probst _ or administrator _ of
the state church in Berlin. ``In Germany, tter the region had come
under control of Prussia. Its sanctuary, much more elaborate than
the original simple room, serves as a memorial to the Reformation.
It is lined with statues of Reformation figures and its balcony
railings feature the seals of princes who split away from
Catholicism to support Luther's movement.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday in Wittenberg, a pony-tailed pastor in
black slacks and a taupe sports coat conducted the regular mid-week
service in the famous church. He read Psalm 91 _ ``You who live in
the shelter of the Most High, who abide in the shadow of the
Almighty, will say to the Lord, `My refuge and my fortress ... '.''
_ and spoke briefly from notes.
</P>
<P>
   The statues outnumbered the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Church of Prussian pride
</P>
<P>
   Called by a guidebook an ``ostentatious symbol of monarchical
power,'' the Berliner Dom was completed in 1905 as the cathedral of
the last German emperor, William II.
</P>
<P>
   This was the ``church of Prussian pride,'' according to Frank
Haussler, a theologian who once worked as a tour guide in the Dom.
In the days it was being built, the monarch was head of the church
as well as head of the state.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the royals, an underground passage led from the
palace across the street to an elaborate wooden staircase in the
cathedral, which, in turn, took the emperor to his special box.
Lest anyone miss its significance, the imperial gallery was
decorated with a gilded Prussian eagle holding a crown.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end of World War I, the royal House of Hohenszollern
used the cathedral for special family and governmental occasions.
After the emperor's abdication in 1918, officials of the new Weimar
Republic continued to hold special ceremonies in the church.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, in an effort to influence church as well as state, the
newly empowered Adolf Hitler introduced the idea of a Reichbishop,
or national bishop, in the Berliner Dom.
</P>
<P>
   After Hitler's ignominious end, the communists in control of
East Berlin tore down the palace across the street and built a pink
glass party headquarters building on its site. That building now
stands empty, marked with graffiti. But party leaders let the Dom
stand. It remained seriously damaged from World War II bombs until
the late 1970s when repair work on the exterior began. The work
continues.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the golden cross on top of the dom shines over a unified
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of Hamburg
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the magnificent Michaeliskirche _ in English the
Church of St. Michael _ sexton Tobias Jahn is nearly nose-to-nose
with a tour guide. The woman, it seems, wants to show her bus load
of tourists around the ornate sanctuary of the church. Jahn is
balking because in less than half an hour the city's new Protestant
bishop _ the first woman to hold that office _ will preside over a
special service at which the Catholic archbishop is a guest.
</P>
<P>
   Jahn and the woman argue until the guide and her troupe meekly
walk down the aisle and take seats to stay for worship. Jahn goes
back to sticking worship bulletins into hymnals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Michel,'' as Hamburgers affectionately call it, is the
most famous of the churches whose towers define the skyline of the
city, which seems as much Dutch, British or Scandinavian as German.
The copper tower of the church, green with patina, greets ships
entering the port of Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   While St. Katherine's and St. Jacob's churches were
reconstructed with modern fixtures after World War II and only the
tower of St. Nicholas remains, St. Michael's was restored to all
its former glory.
</P>
<P>
   Jahn is the church's guardian. And tourists are both boon and
bane to him and his church.
</P>
<P>
   Many Protestant churches in northern Germany stand nearly empty
on Sundays, but ``The Michel'' consistently draws a congregation of
about 500 to its 3,000-seat sanctuary. Fewer than 150 are members
of the 8,000-person parish. The rest are tourists or guests.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the church may be the city's second most famous tourist
stop, behind the famous Reeperbahn, or red-light district, just
three or four blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday services are over and the bishops have left the
building, tourists in sweat suits with cameras are already buying
tickets to see the church at a booth in the vestibule. Also on sale
are St. Michael's espresso cups, medallions and watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michel is a wonderful church, the attraction of Hamburg,''
said opera mezzo-soprano Corinna Meyer-Esche. She is in the balcony
of the church for services with her daughter, Antonia, 7, who was
baptized in the church. Meyer-Esche has attended St. Michael's
occasionally since she moved to Hamburg 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She is undaunted by the tourists. ``I think it's OK to have
them,'' she said. ``I think it's important.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, she comes because of ``my own history, my own
feelings. It's community.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
