<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-BOX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BY THE NUMBERS
 &HT;    Eds: This is part of a yearlong series from Cox News Service
examining the state of Christianity as it approaches its 2,000th
anniversary. Included with the package are MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY,
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN, MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS, MILLENNIUM-LUTHER,
MILLENNIUM-BOX and MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND. A package of photos and
graphics is moving from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    A page with this material is also available for purchase in
paginated form at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress. A Quark page will be
available by Friday at 5 p.m.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, APRIL 10, 1999)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the government of Germany collects funds for the
Protestant and Catholic churches along with income tax, many people
have chosen to disaffiliate themselves from the faith. And many of
those who still pay money to the church seldom attend. Here's a
snapshot of the state of Protestantism in Germany today:
</P>
<P>
   -- Losing members: Studies from the Evangelische Kirche in
Deutschland (EKD), the umbrella organization of German Protestants,
show that the country's 24 regional churches lost nearly a million
members from 1992 until 1995. The hemorrhage continued, with more
than 200,000 fleeing the churches in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   -- Observing the sabbath: Of those who still identify themselves
as Protestant, few attend services although Germany has a
constitutionally protected Sunday when stores are closed. In a
December '97 report, the EKD estimated that weekly Protestant
church attendance in Germany is about 1.4 million _ or 4.9 percent
of the roughly 28 million members, except on Christmas Eve when
approximately a third of all members go to church.
</P>
<P>
   -- Beliefs track participation. A 1997 survey by the publication
Das Sonntagsblatt called ``What do the Germans believe'' showed
that 49 percent of Protestants and 35 percent of Catholics agreed
with the statement, ``I see myself as a Christian, but the church
means nothing to me.'' Six in 10 respondents to the poll said their
feelings were expressed in the statement, ``The churches have no
answers to questions that really concern me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
