</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-LUTHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    His challenge to authority inspired a new movement
 &HT;    Eds: This is part of a yearlong series from Cox News Service
examining the state of Christianity as it approaches its 2,000th
anniversary. Included with the package are MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY,
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN, MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS, MILLENNIUM-LUTHER,
MILLENNIUM-BOX and MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND. A package of photos and
graphics is moving from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    A page with this material is also available for purchase in
paginated form at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress. A Quark page will be
available by Friday at 5 p.m.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, APRIL 10, 1999)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Catholic monk Martin Luther never intended to form his
own church, 61.5 million Christians around the world are now in a
family of denominations that bear his name.
</P>
<P>
   Millions more are in other groups _ Reformed, Methodist,
Presbyterian _ that are part of the Protestant Reformation Luther
sparked.
</P>
<P>
   Luther was born Nov. 10, 1483, in Saxony, the son of a miner.
While studying for the law, he gave his life to God and became an
Augustinian monk.
</P>
<P>
   He reached adulthood when Europe, or the collection of assorted
countries and principalities that dominated it, was in flux. The
``new world'' had recently been discovered by Christopher Columbus.
The plague known as the Black Death periodically threatened death.
{swept the continent.? The printing press had unleashed a flood of
literature to those who could read.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, much power remained in the hands of local princes,
some of whom also served as Catholic bishops, appointed by the
pope.
</P>
<P>
   Examining the scriptures as a professor of biblical studies,
Luther became convinced that faith alone _ through the power of
Jesus _ brings about salvation. His position placed him directly at
odds with the hierarchy of the Catholic church which was, at the
time, selling indulgences or grants of forgiveness of sin.
</P>
<P>
   The more Luther studied, the greater his frustration became
until he marched down the street of Wittenberg and pounded his 95
Theses to the door of the Palace Church on Oct. 31, 1517. The
church served not only the ruling family of the region, but also
the university where Luther taught.
</P>
<P>
   The core principle of Luther's document stated that only God can
remit guilt and does so only when a sinner repents.
</P>
<P>
   Luther maintained that he intended only to stimulate discussion.
Instead, he started a firestorm that eventually led to his
excommunication by the pope, who called him ``a boar in the
vineyard of the Lord,'' and his condemnation by the Diet of Worms,
which referred to him as ``a demon in monk's garb.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther, meanwhile, continued writing and produced his own
translation of the New Testament in German.
</P>
<P>
   No longer a monk committed to celibacy, Luther married Katharina
von Bora, a former nun, on June 13, 1525. Together they had six
children and adopted four more.
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in Luther's former monastery, which had been
dissolved. It is now a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Luther died Feb. 18, 1546.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
