<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-C     04-07 2266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Wittenberg: Roots of Lutherism can be traced to this German town
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is part of a yearlong series from Cox News Service
examining the state of Christianity as it approaches its 2,000th
anniversary. Included with the package are MILLENNIUM-ADVISORY,
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN, MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS, MILLENNIUM-LUTHER,
MILLENNIUM-BOX and MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND. A package of photos and
graphics is moving from the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   A page with this material is also available for purchase in
paginated form at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress. A Quark page will be
available by Friday at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, APRIL 10, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   By Gayle White
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Wittenberg
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schelhaas, small and earnest, pops around the counter of
a bright, warm information center to greet guests as pellets of
snow fall outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like to see a video about Wittenberg?'' he asks.
``Twenty minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it tell about Martin Luther?'' a visitor wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Luther, there is nothing to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 31, 1517, Luther tacked his famous ``95 Theses'' to the
Palace Church door across the street from what is now Schelhaas's
little domain and sparked a movement that challenged Catholicism
and changed Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The church has been destroyed and rebuilt twice _ first by fire,
then by Napoleon's army. The door has been replaced by a brass
replica. But Luther's nail hole still defines this town.
</P>
<P>
   As one pamphlet on Wittenberg says, ``We have the door _ and we
make a living out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schelhaas hopes to use Luther's heritage to make this village on
the northern bank of the River Elbe into a destination for
tourists, pilgrims and scholars interested in the birth of the
Protestant Reformation. He imagines 2000 as a ``Holy Year'' in
three great centers of the faith: Jerusalem, Rome and Wittenberg.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts are accelerating as the church Luther founded finds
itself in deep trouble in Europe, where the Lutheran World
Federation reported a ``general reduction in numbers,'' and
especially in its homeland of Germany, where more than a million
people have left the church rolls in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The state of the church is at its worst in the former East
Germany _ which includes Wittenberg _ where decades of communist
rule after World War II stifled Christianity. Ten years after the
fall of the Berlin Wall, there is little evidence that religion is
making a comeback. In the former German Democratic Republic,
three-fourths of the population does not identify with any
Christian group.
</P>
<P>
   Anga Winkler, 19, illustrates the effects of communism. The high
school student from East Berlin identifies herself in terms of
religion as ``nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents aren't religious,'' she says, ``and they never
asked me what I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk may have Luther spinning in his tomb below the pulpit
of the Palace Church. The crux of his famous theses is that faith
alone _ through the power of Jesus _ brings about salvation.
</P>
<P>
   From a movement within the Catholic church, Lutheranism
eventually became a separate denomination and the starting point
for the Protestant Reformation that became the dominant religious
force throughout much of Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   Today, each of 24 regions of Germany has its own Protestant
church _ some Lutheran, some the ``unified'' church that is both
Lutheran and Reformed, and a few Reformed. These are considered
``state churches'' and funds for them are collected by the
government along with income taxes from anyone identified as a
member.
</P>
<P>
   Some German churchmen say this official relationship has done
almost as much to damage the church in western Germany as decades
of communism did in the east.
</P>
<P>
   In America, churches compete with each other for members, said
the Rev. Uwe Hollm, 68, a retired probst _ or administrator _ of
the state church in Berlin. ``In Germany, this is not the case. If
you are born the child of Lutheran parents or a child of Roman
Catholic parents, you are in the church. You are confirmed, married
and buried. It's a very official thing. You see very few pious
people who have had a personal conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollm, tall and thin, his gray hair cut like Julius Caesar,
speaks English with a bit of a British accent from time as a
minister in London. He has experienced both American and German
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   A Hitler youth from age 9, he was devastated when he learned of
Adolf Hitler's suicide and further disturbed when he began to
realize the horrors of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler was a divine person to us. If he had told me to jump
down a wall and kill myself, I would have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, in his mid-teens, Hollm said, ``I felt a deep
emptiness in my heart.'' The feeling began to dissipate at a camp
organized by American members of the Church of the Brethren in
Hamburg, near the North Sea coast. The following year he attended a
similar camp sponsored by First Presbyterian Church of Hollywood,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   From the Brethren, Hollm said, he learned about Christian
pacifism. From the Presbyterians, he learned ``that there could be
a personal relationship with God through prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   On a subsequent trip to the United States, while working with
his friends at Hollywood Presbyterian, Hollm decided to be a
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call came because I saw a living, vibrant community of
Christian people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany today, he sees little evidence of life in the
churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nominal membership is the normal thing,'' he said. ``Active
membership is the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardiologist Lars Hennig, 39, who lives in the southwest section
of Berlin, considers himself a Lutheran and attends services about
once a month. ``Mostly there are some old people, not many young
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hennig, who has visited church services in the United States,
said he is impressed with the family orientation of American
congregations _ which he says is decidedly lacking in German state
churches.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, alternative ``free churches'' not affiliated with the
state are having limited success in attracting fallen-away German
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tendency for evangelicals to say our churches aren't
hurting like the Lutherans or Catholics, but they're hurting,
too,'' said the Rev. James Smith, Europe liaison for the
Atlanta-based Cooperative Baptist Fellowship. Figures from the
Union of Churches, a German free-church coalition, showed a
combined membership of 87,848 members, with losses of 962 people by
disaffiliation, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Germans just don't see much need for church,'' Smith
said. ``I think Europeans are just very skeptical about religion.
They don't really go to church. They don't practice anything.
They're very jealous of their free time. The weekend is holy.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, to celebrate its 100th anniversary and prepare
Berlin to assume its role as capital city of a unified Germany, the
church Smith attends, Charlottenburg Baptist Church in Berlin,
hosted a workshop for church leaders of state and free churches.
The featured speaker was one of America's most famous church growth
gurus, the Rev. Bill Hybels of Willow Creek Church in Illinois,
which regularly draws a combined attendance of more than 16,000 to
five weekend services. The church was filled, and German public
television recorded the conference to be televised in June.
</P>
<P>
   Hybels encouraged the churches to be relevant to people's lives
and to remember that their role is to change the city ``one person
at a time from within.''
</P>
<P>
   Luther had the same expectation of the church, according to
Frank Haussler, 32, a theologian and fervent Luther fan. Haussler
has degrees from the universities of Tubingen and Heidelberg _
world-renowned centers of Protestant scholarship _ but there is no
place for him as a pastor at a state church in Germany because of
declining membership.
</P>
<P>
   The German Protestant church has been consumed by
``self-secularization,'' Haussler said. Comfortable for years in
its guaranteed income, the church ``neglected its duty of preaching
the gospel to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, while some churches are closed, many others have become
even more secular, serving almost exclusively as tourist sites or
concert halls.
</P>
<P>
   Haussler worked for a while at the Berlin Dom, the grand German
Protestant cathedral intended to rival St. Peter's Basilica, the
seat of the Catholic Church in Rome. He quit his job when the
cathedral began charging fees to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there is this big mosaic of Jesus, opening his arms,
saying, `Come to me you who are troubled','' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fees are one way churches are trying to cope with shrinking
coffers as people in Germany increasingly take the initiative to go
through the paperwork and red tape to have themselves
``de-registered,'' or removed from the church rolls, thus ending
their obligation to pay the church through their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Randolf Kaivies, 43, a native of West Berlin who owns a toy and
gift shop, is an example of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are jumping out of the church,'' he said.
``Me, I don't pay any more. On paper, I'm Protestant, but I don't
pay. Many people pay, not because they like it but because it's
automatic. You have to make many different processes to the
government not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of waning membership and high unemployment, officials
estimated that between 1995 and 2000, churches will have lost 30
percent of their funds.
</P>
<P>
   The losses are threatening both congregations and historic
church buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The region of Sachsen-Anhalt, which includes Wittenberg and is
called ``Lutherland'' by the local tourist board, has an estimated
2,400 churches, many pre-dating Luther. Of those, only 5 percent
were classified as in ``a good state of repair,'' while 30 percent
``are in such bad condition that they should actually be abandoned
or demolished,'' according to a 1996 Church Buildings Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The two famous churches in Wittenberg _ the Palace Church,
rebuilt to honor the Reformation, and the Stadkirche St. Marien, or
City Church of St. Mary, where Luther preached _ escaped the
neglect specifically because of their ties to Luther.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the historic village of Wittenberg is thriving while
its region of the country suffers.
</P>
<P>
   Sachen-Anhalt is known as the poorest state in Germany in per
capita income, and 20 percent of its people are unemployed. But
Luther's old habitations, part of an industrial town of 50,000 now
often designated Lutherstadt-Wittenberg, shine with fresh, colorful
paint.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, to mark the 500th anniversary of Luther's birth, the
former East German government began a restoration program in
Wittenberg. The Wittenberg video in the information center gives
credit to celebrations of that occasion for starting the demise of
communist control of the old East Germany, officially the German
Democratic Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Since the unification of Germany, renovation has increased and
tourism is better, said Dieter Meinecke, a guide for the
information center. The East German government insisted on showing
only ``the best side of the town,'' he said. ``We had tourism, but
not the kind of tourism we can offer you now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lutherhalle, the former monastery which became Luther's
family home, is a museum. And visitors may also tour the home of
Phillip Schwarzerd, Luther's foremost lieutenant, who is generally
known as Melanchthon.
</P>
<P>
   The grandest event of the year in Wittenberg is a three-day
festival celebrating Luther's wedding, held annually in June since
1994. Local residents are chosen to portray the former monk and his
bride, a runaway Cistercian nun named Katherina von Bora. They
married in 1540.
</P>
<P>
   There are theater productions, music and handicrafts throughout
the town, drawing tens of thousands of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Some go away with the favorite souvenirs of the visitors'
center, pairs of socks embroidered with Luther's famous saying in
defiance of the Catholic church: ``Here I stand, I can do no other,
so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   The socks were the idea of a group of German Lutheran pastors,
Meinecke said. ``Guests are divided into two parts,'' he said.
``Fifty percent say they're great. Fifty percent say they're
horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are under way to take advantage of Wittenberg's history
to make it a center of Protestant study. In February, Dean Bard
moved to Wittenberg to establish a center for the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America, the largest Lutheran group in the
United States. Bard, 53, a Nebraska native, fell in love with
Berlin as a young man stationed there in the Air Force. He returned
home, attended seminary, and went back to Berlin to pastor an
English-language church.
</P>
<P>
   Bard is putting together ``substantial educational and spiritual
experiences'' for ministers, Lutheran lay leaders and college
students. He plans for the program eventually to include partner
churches from Africa and Asia. And, he hopes the center will serve
as a clearinghouse for scholars who want to tap into ``the
treasures of this area.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees the efforts to bring attention to Wittenberg as greater
than an economically motivated plan to increase tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a sign of something deeper going on
underneath,'' he says. ``These tangible symbols reflect deeper
realities sometimes. They're not only sprucing up the buildings,
but trying to revive the spiritual context.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
