u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVASION-SCENARIOS-HN     04-07 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVASION-SCENARIOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO GROUND TROOPS COULD FOLLOW TWO SCENARIOS IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As NATO forces unleashed a 15th day of air strikes
against Yugoslavia Wednesday, two scenarios were emerging for the
possible invasion by ground troops to force President Slobodan
Milosevic to end the war on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration says there are no plans to
send NATO ground troops to Yugoslavia, the failure of the air war
to pressure Milosevic to withdraw his forces from Kosovo has
stirred speculation that NATO ground forces eventually will have to
complete the job.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO ground attack would face a formidable foe in Kosovo where
the Belgrade government has about 40,000 troops, 16,500 police, 300
Soviet tanks, 700 artillery pieces and 700 armored vehicles. In
addition, there are about 80,000 more soldiers, 1,200 tanks and
1,400 artillery pieces scattered throughout Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A major goal of the ongoing NATO air campaign is to destroy much
of this military equipment that is being used to suppress or kill
ethnic Albanians. Other goals are to force Milosevic to restore
autonomy to the Yugoslav province and to allow NATO troops to
enforce a peace agreement there.
</P>
<P>
   One invasion plan _ the more wide-ranging and complex _ is being
proposed by retired Army Lt. Gen. William Odom, a former director
of the National Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, writing in the Wall Street Journal, envisions an invasion
by 40,000 NATO troops led by tanks, sweeping south from Hungary
into Serbia down to the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed invasion force would travel down the same
corridor the Germans used successfully in World War II when the
Wehrmacht captured much of Yugoslavia in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Odom would couple the southward swoop with a separate thrust of
44,000 NATO troops pushing north through Macedonia to repel
Yugoslav forces stationed in Kosovo and create safe areas for
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of the Odom plan is that it could take several
weeks or longer to prepare. The troops and materiel would have to
be flown into Hungary and the tanks and artillery likely would have
to move by rail and roads from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put together a full-scale attack is going to take a long
time,'' said retired Army Gen. George Joulwan, the former top NATO
commander.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Cordesman, a senior military analyst at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies, pointed out that the
relatively long preparation time would allow more time for
Yugoslavia to continuing expelling or killing ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may now be too late in physical terms for a major ground
force option to save the refugees,'' said Cordesman.
</P>
<P>
   John Steinbruner, a foreign policy expert at the Brookings
Institution here, warned that a wide-scale invasion through Serbia
could spark intense fighting and destabilize the region.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbruner said such a large-scale invasion would be
``disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO would risk appearing to seek the overthrow of Milosevic, a
goal that Steinbruner asserted could divide the international
community, which currently is united behind the effort to halt the
ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting the population in Kosovo and establishing legal
order there is a legitimate purpose for a ground force, but
overthrowing Milosevic is not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is the dominant republic in Yugoslavia. Kosovo is a
province of Serbia that is dominated by ethnic Albanians now under
siege from the Serbians. Two weeks of punishing NATO air raids have
failed to bring Milosevic to the peace table to sign a treaty with
the Albanian population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A second ground attack scenario, proposed by Joulwan, would
require around 30,000 troops and could be set in motion in less
time and would be focused on invading Kosovo to protect the ethnic
Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   It would be spearheaded by the 14,000 NATO troops now stationed
in nearby Macedonia. They currently are training for entry into
Kosovo as part of a peace-keeping force in the aftermath of a
possible peace settlement. However, they are not outfitted with
sufficient numbers of heavy tanks and artillery needed to become an
offensive battle force.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a similar number of troops would invade Kosovo from
the west in Albania, according to the Joulwan plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, we could mount an operation to restore the
territorial integrity of Kosovo, seal off and deny the Serb army
any access to Kosovo,'' said Joulwan.
</P>
<P>
   Joulwan called the option ``a much more prudent, quicker
option'' than a massive ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of the Joulwan plan is that it lacks the huge
three-to-one numerical superiority that military planners have long
favored in designing invasion forces to crush the opposition
quickly and keep U.S. casualties relatively low.
</P>
<P>
   With 40,000 Yugoslav troops in Kosovo, U.S. war planners likely
would seek a force of about 120,000 to 150,000 NATO troops,
according to retired Army Maj. Gen. Edward Atkeson, a senior fellow
at the Institute of Land Warfare in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, an invasion from Macedonia and neighboring Albania
_ where NATO is stationing tank-killing Apache helicopters manned
by U.S. crews _ would face potential logistics logjams because of
poor road, rail and port systems, said Atkeson.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential downside of either option is the possible
repercussion for the ethnic Albanians, who have faced stepped up
attacks from Yugoslav forces since the air strikes began.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO has to slowly fight its way in, the ground options can
produce just as much killing (of ethnic Albanians) as the air
option,'' Cordesman said.
</P>
<P>
   While Secretary of State Albright reiterated Tuesday that there
were no plans to send U.S. ground troops into Kosovo, an offensive
force is gathering in the region. This includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ 14,000 NATO troops in Macedonia, including about 400 U.S. GIs.
The force is comprised mainly of light infantry but also includes
tanks and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   _ 2,200 U.S. Marines aboard ships in the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   _ a 1,200-member reinforced U.S. infantry battalion in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   _ 8,200 troops in Bosnia from the elite U.S. 1st Cavalry
Division, which has some heavy equipment such as tanks.
</P>
<P>
   _ 6,000 Italian ground troops in Albania or heading there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two armored divisions in Germany, totalling about 24,000
troops. In addition, the United States could dispatch the 101st air
assault division and the 82nd airborne division, parts of which
could move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Other NATO forces that could be tapped include 41,500 French
rapid reaction troops, 20,000 multi-national NATO rapid reaction
troops, the German 2nd Corps, which includes an armored division,
and five air mobile British battalions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
