<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-0408-     04-07 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GOVERNOR-0408-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH SUSPECT ON THE LAM, DRUG CASE AGAINST MEXICAN GOVERNOR AN
EMBARRASSMENT
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY -- Mexicans fear that one of the highest ranking
politicians to be implicated in drug trafficking will escape
justice.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mario Villanueva's term as governor of Quintana Roo
state expired, and Tuesday evening -- after weeks of speculation --
a warrant was issued for his arrest. By that time, however,
Villanueva, had gone into hiding, as suggested by a letter his
lawyer delivered to Mexican newspapers Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now a case that promised to become a spectacular victory for
Mexico's fight against corruption threatens to explode into a major
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of international disrepute and a loss of
credibility nationally,'' Guillermo Velasco, president of the group
Mexicans United Against Delinquency, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. congressional source familiar with Mexico's law
enforcement officials said: ``It's got to be embarrassing for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   The case against Villanueva symbolized ``hope that at last the
Mexican political system was beginning to fight impunity enjoyed by
governors and ex-governors involved in organized crime,'' said
Velasco.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement announcing the arrest warrant for Villanueva, the
attorney general's office in Mexico City said it could not detain
Villanueva sooner because he was constitutionally protected against
arrest while governor.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also said that the last confirmed sighting of
Villanueva was March 27, in the city of Merida, in Yucatan state.
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers suggest Villanueva was under
surveillance and said they find it hard to believe Mexican police
don't know where he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did escape from their watch there should be another line
of investigation into whether it was negligence or complicity,''
said Raymundo Riva Palacio, a well-known Mexican political
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Velasco said he's concerned that the hunt for Villanueva will
fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that there are thousands of arrest warrants issued
that are never carried out in Mexico,'' he said, ``and the only
explanation for that is that those who are supposed to carry them
out negotiate with criminals. We hope that this isn't happening in
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter delivered to the news media by his lawyer,
Villanueva said he had left his ``turf'' to pursue his defense. The
letter does not make it clear if he is still in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva claims he is the victim of a political vendetta
because he is
</P>
<P>
   out of favor with dominant members of his party, Mexico's ruling
Revolutionary Institutional Party.
</P>
<P>
   Quintana Roo, the Caribbean coast state Villanueva governed for
six years, is home to Mexico's premiere tourist resort, Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   It has also become a haven for drug traffickers who smuggle as
much as 15 tons of cocaine a month into the United States,
according to law enforcement sources.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva is accused of using his official airport hanger as a
transshipment point for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
