<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 8, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A compact storm moving from Kansas into southern Iowa will cause
a variety of turbulent weather Thursday. Showers and gusty
thunderstorms will precede and accompany its fronts crossing the
Mississippi and lower Ohio Valleys. Conditions may be favorable for
a complex of severe storms in Missouri, southern Illinois and
Arkansas later in the day. These could spawn several tornadoes.
Gale force winds in the wake of the disturbance will raise clouds
of dust in Oklahoma and northwest Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A cold rain will drench sections of Nebraska and South Dakota
with wet snow possible in the Black Hills, but more likely across
the higher terrain of eastern Wyoming. Strong winds descending the
east slopes of the Rockies may cause damage in a few areas near the
Front Range as gusts surpass hurricane force.
</P>
<P>
   A thick plume of high clouds associated with a southern branch
of the jet stream will spread from east Texas across the Gulf
states. These clouds will dim the sun and keep afternoon
temperatures mainly below record high maximums.
</P>
<P>
   A weakening cool front in the Northeast will cause a few showers
in central and northern New England. Ahead of the front, it will be
very warm along the Northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   An extraordinarily cold air mass will move southward along the
Pacific Coast into California. Snow levels will lower to near 1,000
feet in the northern coastal range. Showers may be mixed with sleet
in the Central Valley. Strong winds on the Coast will enhance the
unusual chill. The Southwest will turn dry and brighter.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: L.A. Hail
</P>
<P>
   A thunderstorm with hail rumbled across parts of Los Angeles
Wednesday as a compact but potent jet stream disturbance arrived
from the Pacific. April thunderstorms affect Los Angeles only two
out of every five years, on average, but April hail is extremely
rare. By April, temperatures aloft have begun their climb toward
summer levels, limiting the possibility that any hail that might
form in a thunderstorm could survive to the ground. But very cold
air aloft was the signature of Wednesday's disturbance, a rarefied
chill that will help to spawn severe weather over the Middle West
on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
