<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROOKLYN-SENSATION-NY     04-07 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-SENSATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTRAGEOUS SHOW OF YOUNG BRITISH ARTISTS HEADS TO BROOKLYN MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Visitors to the Brooklyn Museum of Art this fall may
be in for a shock. Rather than sun-dappled Impressionist landscapes
or forthright Rodin bronzes, its classical galleries will be filled
with work by young British artists who have made a worldwide
reputation creating art that disturbs and outrages.
</P>
<P>
   Prominently featured will be Damien Hirst's infamous dead shark
floating in a tank of formaldehyde, Marc Quinn's cast of a man's
head made of his own frozen blood and Ron Mueck's sculpture of his
naked, dead father, reduced to the length of three feet.
</P>
<P>
   These works are part of ``Sensation: Young British Artists from
the Saatchi Collection,'' a show that drew record crowds and a
hailstorm of praise and criticism when it opened in late 1997 at
the staid Royal Academy of Arts in London.
</P>
<P>
   The show drew extreme reactions from both viewers and critics.
Those who liked it said it captured the excitement and innovative
talents of British art today. Those who damned the show felt its
content was offensive, intended to shock for shock's sake, or just
plain bad. Some pointed out that the show also served to increase
the value of Saatchi's collection.
</P>
<P>
   The most extreme reaction was to the artist Marcus Harvey's
depiction of Myra Hindley, who was convicted in the macabre ``moors
murders'' of children in western England in the 1960s. Protesters
splattered ink and raw eggs on the painting, saying that it
trivialized her victims' suffering and glorified her crimes.
</P>
<P>
   After London, the show traveled to the Hamburger Bahnhof in
Berlin where it was just as popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a defining exhibition,'' said Arnold L. Lehman,
director of the Brooklyn Museum. ``Rarely can you get enough works
to accurately capture the spirit of what's happening at a specific
moment in time. Museums, especially New York museums, ought to
bring to their audiences the art happening today from all parts of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensation'' will be the largest exhibition in the museum's
102-year history, occupying more than 20,000 square feet of gallery
space. Among the other artists whose works will be on view are Mona
Hatoum, Sarah Lucas, Chris Ofili, Fiona Rae and Rachel Whiteread.
</P>
<P>
   All are well known figures in London, and most have been shown
internationally, exploring themes like sexual identity, feminism
and social criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The collection belongs to Charles Saatchi, the advertising
magnate who is London's most important contemporary art collector
and one of the earliest and most passionate supporters of these
artists, who are often referred to as YBA's (Young British
Artists).
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 90 works in ``Sensation'' were bought during the
1990s. They constitute little more than a sampling of his
collection of 20th-century art, which totals about 1,500 works.
</P>
<P>
   He was among the first collectors to buy these artists' works
and to show them publicly; he owns an exhibition space on Boundary
Road in London's St. John's Wood. (Some art critics who saw the
show in London said they felt it gave too much weight to the taste
of one collector.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sensation,'' which will run from Oct. 2 through Jan. 9, has
been in the planning stages for well over a year. The size of some
of the works and the complexity of their installation has made it a
logistical and economic nightmare for the museum, with financing
being the biggest problem, museum officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The provocative nature of the work is generally thought to be
too daring for corporate sponsors and has made it difficult to
raise the $1 million necessary to mount the show.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Lehman said, a number of individuals have agreed to
contribute to the show, as has Christie's, the auction house, which
was a supporter of the Royal Academy's show. The museum is still
looking for other sponsors but would not say how much had been
raised so far.
</P>
<P>
   The show's installation will be unusually tricky, not to mention
expensive. In order to comply with New York City health and
environmental ordinances, for instance, dead animals have to be
hermetically sealed in cases of steel and glass with tubes
connected to carbon filters eliminating the smell of decay. ``Our
conservation department has been in discussions with people who
have been involved in installing these objects and are aware of
every aspect that must be dealt with,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks the show will cause as much of a stir as it
did in London, he added, ``I think New Yorkers are incredibly
sophisticated and believe like I do that they should be exposed to
works that are both emotionally engaging and ones that make us
think.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is likely to bring a kind of audience to the museum
that it wants to attract: young, hip people who tend to frequent
its neighbor, the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this show is important for people of every age,'' said
Lehman. ``Brooklyn is becoming a center for contemporary art. We
have something like 4,000 artists living here. It's terrific for
them to see what their colleagues have been doing across the
Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
