<HEADER>
A9515 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM08-COX     04-07 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Year 2000 radio contests to reward metro couple having 1st child
of year
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you want to make a Y2K baby, now's the time.
</P>
<P>
   So light the candles, disconnect the phone and dance with
destiny on Friday and Saturday nights _ considered the optimum time
to conceive a baby slated to be born on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're psyched,'' said Carolyn Reed, 30, who is hoping to hit
the target. ``Not many people get to witness the turn of the
century. And to have a chance to have a baby right as it starts is
very, very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Christopher, aren't the only ones with love
on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Six couples will be marking their calendars _ and spending time
in Atlanta hotels this weekend _ as part of radio promotions at
Hot-97.5 WHTA-FM and WSB-FM, or B98.5, to create next year's first
baby.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany and Taurus Maddox of Decatur (Ga.) already have two
children. But this weekend, they will be one of three couples
trying for another child as part of the contest held by Hot-97.5.
Out of 30 couples who wanted to participate, the three were
selected by an obstetrician on the basis of the women's cycles,
ages and history of childbearing, according to Twana James, co-host
of WHTA's morning show.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Maddox said they decided to enter the contest because
they had planned to have another baby anyway, and she had hoped to
have it before a spring wedding for a relative next year. ``I
thought I need to get this out of the way. And then I started
thinking it would be really great to aim for Jan. 1, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say, however, anything to do with the birds and the bees
is a fickle business.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the mood is right and the body is willing, less than 10
percent of the world's women of childbearing years will actually be
ovulating this weekend. And if ``you're one of the lucky women
ovulating, then you've still got to have a cooperative egg and
plenty of sperm,'' said Dr. Michael Randell, an obstetrician and
gynecologist who practices at Northside Hospital (Atlanta).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, couples only have a 25 percent to 30 percent chance of
conceiving, even if the timing is right.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who become pregnant, up to a third miscarry, doctors
say. And finally, actually hitting the date set by doctors is a
little lik winning the lottery _ only 5 percent of women actually
go into labor and give birth on their due date.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some couples might try to stack the odds by trying to
schedule their C-section on Jan. 1, but most doctors say they won't
allow it because they are more concerned about the health of the
baby than a celebration of 2000. (And Jan. 1 falls on a Saturday _
not during normal office hours.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't schedule an elective C-section just because of the
new year,'' said Dr. Stephen Blank, an obstetrician and the former
chairman of Northside Hospital's obstetrics and gynecology
department. ``And to be honest, at Northside, they're so busy
anyway, it would put an unnecessary burden on the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Northside, the region's largest baby-birthing facility, already
experiences between 30 and 50 deliveries a day, he said. ``And if
the load increases by one or two times, there's no way they're
going to be able to satisfy any more requests.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples sometimes ask to hurry along a C-section at the end of a
year so they're guaranteed a tax break, doctors say. ``So asking
for a Jan. 1 C-section would be sort of a novelty,'' Blank said.
</P>
<P>
   So let's say lots of couples succeed at creating the first batch
of Y2K babies. What might these kids be like?
</P>
<P>
   A child born right after the stroke of midnight would be a
Capricorn _ serious and tenacious, with good concentration and the
capacity to work long and hard, according to Kathryn L. Silverton,
an astrologer who also holds a master's degree in psychology. But
because the moon will be in Scorpio, the child will also be
emotionally intense, according to Carol Garlick, who writes a
column with Silverton in Aquarius, an Atlanta New Age magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. But one thing is true: Y2K babies will face a
remarkably changing world. And _ with advances in medicine _ they
also have a good chance of seeing Jan. 1, 2100, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think how much has happened since the last turn of the
century,'' said Reed. ``We can only imagine what a baby born on
Jan. 1, 2000, will experience. But it's very exciting to think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
