<HEADER>
A9516 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTERS-RETARDE     04-07 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTERS-RETARDED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOY OF E-MAIL LIGHTS UP THE LIFE OF A RETARDED TEEN-AGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBRA NUSSBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My 15-year-old son charges down the back stairway and into the
kitchen with an entrance reminiscent of Kramer entering Jerry
Seinfeld's apartment. ``We have to check my e-mail,'' he announces.
``Jenn is sending me an e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago we would never have heard this coming from
Zachary. While his siblings discovered e-mail long ago, it has just
become a factor in his teen-aged world. The joy of hearing ``you've
got mail'' is a new phenomenon to him.
</P>
<P>
   My son Zachary Bissinger is mildly mentally retarded and reads
and writes at about a second-grade level. He and his twin brother,
Gerry, each weighed less than two pounds when they were born in
1983. But because Gerry's lungs were developed, he was a fairly
healthy baby and is a typical, normal teen-ager (as normal as
teen-agers can be). Zach's lungs were not as well formed and he
spent seven months in Philadelphia's Pennsylvania Hospital, hooked
up to a world of modern medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   He came home from the hospital at 7 months old and by the time
he was 3, he was found to be mildly retarded. His IQ is in the 70s.
While he is very friendly and has a good vocabulary, his biggest
struggle these days is with regular social conversation. He's great
at firing questions (he could be the next Sam Donaldson), but he
has trouble forming answers to questions asked of him.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Zach _ who loves maps _ can give you
directions from just about anywhere in New Jersey to any street in
Philadelphia. He can tell you the day of the week your birthday is
on this year if you give him the date. He remembers street
addresses from 10 years ago, but it's hard for him to remember to
shave every day.
</P>
<P>
   While Zach loves Nintendo games, we could never seem to get him
interested in the computer. He has a computer in our home and two
at his dad's house, but even with the colorful games and enticing
software, Zach didn't have any interest.
</P>
<P>
   But Zach is interested in developing his social life. As a
student at Haddonfield (N.J.) Memorial High School, in the school's
special-education program on living skills, Zach and his half-dozen
school friends spend much of the day learning basic skills that
will help them get jobs. They take several classes, like gym or
nutrition, with the other high school students. Even though they
don't go to the high school dances and won't go to the prom (by
their own choice), they want to socialize and fit in.
</P>
<P>
   Zach's friends, many with Down's syndrome, listen to the
Backstreet Boys, love Leonardo DiCaprio and watch ``Dawson's
Creek.'' Zach is less hip than his classmates, but they are
bringing him into the world of pop music enough that he buys the
occasional CD.
</P>
<P>
   Most of their socializing is with one another. They go to dances
and theater rehearsals through a local organization called Hometown
Opportunities for the Mentally Handicap, which was started in the
1980s by several parents who wanted disabled young adults to have
continuing education. Ted Sery, who runs Homh (pronounced Home),
has a 31-year-old daughter who is disabled. He is active in the
group because he did not want her education and socialization to
stop at the age of 21, when school ends for many disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   When the notice came home for the Homh computer class at
Haddonfield High School's night-school program, I decided to sign
Zach up.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Zach had tried a regular high school keyboarding
class. While he and the teacher, Karen Rauba, got along famously,
the class was too much for him. With 19 other students in the
class, he found it hard to focus on the keyboard and the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more of an attention problem'' than a skill problem,
Mrs. Rauba said. After a few weeks, we moved him out of the class.
</P>
<P>
   When I signed Zach up for the evening Homh class, I wondered if
a kid who had benefited so much from technology early in his life
could ever master some technology to use in his life now.
</P>
<P>
   The first few classes were the basics _ turning on the computer,
getting a log-on name and a password. The teacher, Christine
Costantino, encouraged the 13 students, who ranged in age from 14
to 40, to pick their favorite food as their password because it's
easy to remember.
</P>
<P>
   The students sat in front of the lab's Gateway computers _ each
participant was helped by a high school student _ and got a chance
to research a favorite animal. By the second class, a mother
suggested that her daughter would much rather research the
Backstreet Boys than tigers. The printer was very busy that night
with shots of the Backstreet Boys in various poses.
</P>
<P>
   Students from the high school's National Honor Society sat among
the students and encouraged them to send e-mail to one another and
to them. Zach lit up when a senior, Jenn Leonard, leaned over his
computer and said, ``Send me an e-mail, and I'll write back to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The students, including Zach, all needed prompting from the
helpers, but they loved going to the printer and getting pictures
and just talking to the other kids. Most had no trouble maneuvering
the mouse, and no one got frustrated enough to quit before the hour
was up.
</P>
<P>
   Each student was given an address at Hotmail, the free Web-based
e-mail provider. Each e-mail address was handed out on a piece of
paper so the student could share it with friends and family and use
it to check e-mail at the class' next session.
</P>
<P>
   The students started out by doing an Internet search for a music
group. Zach typed with one finger but wanted to do it himself. Adam
Karpman, a high school junior, helped him navigate the Web. Zach's
friend Laura Klein, who is in his living-skills class, brought her
Backstreet Boys CD to class. Her mother, Joy, said that Laura had
seen ``www'' on the back and figured out that it meant she could
see the group's Web site on the computer while she played the CD.
The girls cheered when the music came out of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to classes in public schools and programs sponsored by
community organizations, it's rare to find a disabled child or
teen-ager who hasn't logged onto a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child with a special need will be involved with
computers one way or another,'' said Bridget Lyne, managing editor
of Exceptional Parent magazine (www.eparent.com). ``The learning
possibilities, I couldn't even begin to quantify.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, published since 1971 as a guide for parents of
children or young adults with disabilities or health problems, has
increased its focus on technology in the past few years. A
four-part series that started in November and covered learning
software and adaptive devices can be ordered from the magazine at
(800) 372-7368.
</P>
<P>
   The Exceptional Parent 1999 Resource Guide, which is published
every January and is available in bookstores or through the
magazine for $12, also lists technology resources. Ms. Lyne
recommends checking with local public schools or night-school
programs to see if they offer technology classes.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill Industries International (www.goodwill.org) offers
computer training and job-skills classes at about 100 offices in
the United States, said Christine Nyirjesy Bragale, a Goodwill
spokeswoman. The classes vary in price. To find the closest local
office, call (800) 664-6577.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Technology Access (www.ATAccess.org), a
nonprofit group that began 11 years ago as a consumer-driven
technology and resource center, now has 40 offices across the
country. It offers information about software and other assistive
technology, and consumers can try out the equipment at its centers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
