<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANY TYPES AND IMPORTANCE OF PAINTBRUSHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brushes are important tools in any kit. Inexperienced
do-it-yourselfers tend to think that all brushes are alike. This
might seem like a logical assumption, considering that all brushes
are made up of only three components: the fibers or filling, the
handle and the ferrule.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, significant differences in the materials
used to make these components, and they can affect quality,
performance and price. Consider the filling, for example. It is
made up of filaments bonded together, or set. Most brush fillings
are bonded with vulcanized rubber. This makes them impervious to
volatile spirits used to thin paints and clean brushes.
</P>
<P>
   Other types of brushes, washing-down brushes or paste brushes,
usually have fillings bonded together with pitch or natural resins.
Solvents will dissolve these bonding agents so the brushes can only
be used with water.
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of different filaments used to make the
fillings. Natural fibers include bristle, horsehair, sable, ox
hair, badger hair and fiber. While most people refer to the brush
filaments as bristles, this term should be used only for brush
filaments obtained from the pelt of a boar.
</P>
<P>
   Individual boar bristles are slightly tapered with naturally
split ends commonly called flags. The flagged ends of bristles
enable them to hold more paint than other types of filaments. In
addition, bristles are very resilient so they spring back when
flexed. These qualities make natural-bristle brushes an ideal
choice for jobs with oil-based paints. They are not good for
applying water-based paints because the water in the paint swells
the bristles and distorts their shape, making it difficult to get a
smooth, even coating of latex paint.
</P>
<P>
   Horsehair is a relatively cheap filament that comes from the
mane and tail of a horse. It has neither the flagged tip nor the
resilience of bristle, so it is not used exclusively in fillings.
Instead, it is added to provide bulk and body to natural-filament
brush fillings. Ox hair is similar in quality to horsehair. It is
used to make small brushes for craft jobs, graining and sign
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Badger hair filaments are easily recognized by the color
gradation from white to black. These are fine-quality filaments
with natural resiliency and flagged tips. They are more
water-resistant than boar bristles, so they can be used with
water-based paints.
</P>
<P>
   Sable filaments come from mink, weasel or squirrel. They are
available in short lengths, so sable brushes are round, small and
suitable only for detail work and graining. Some manufacturers
offer flat sable brushes two or four inches wide. They are used
primarily by furniture refinishers for brushing on natural varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Boar bristle, horsehair, ox hair, badger hair, and sable are
natural filaments obtained from animals. Another natural filament
is fiber. It is a cheap, tough filament obtained from the stalk of
a palm tree. Fiber is rather coarse so it can be used only in
brushes designed for applying paste, whitewash, or in scrub
brushes.
</P>
<P>
   Many brushes manufactured today have fillings made up of
synthetic filaments -- usually of nylon, although other materials
are sometimes used. Modern synthetic filaments have the same taper,
resiliency and flagged tip of bristle filaments. They are durable,
hold paint well, and are usually more economical than natural
filament.
</P>
<P>
   When purchasing any brush, tug the filling gently to make sure
the filaments are firmly bound to the stock. Fan the filling
between your thumb and fingers. The filaments should spread easily,
then spring back into place. Test the resiliency of the filling by
stroking it against a surface, as if you were applying paint. The
filling should flex without losing filaments.
</P>
<P>
   Most brush handles are made of one piece of wood or molded
plastic. The base of the handle, the wide part that mates with the
filling, is called the stock. A few specialty brushes have a
separate turned handle that fits into a hole in the stock. This
handle configuration, sometimes called the Dutchpattern, is used
with round, faux-finishing and decorating brushes. Good-quality
brushes have smooth handles shaped to fit the hand and offer a good
grip.
</P>
<P>
   The handle and filling are joined by a band of metal called the
ferrule. The ferrule is secured to the handle with small nails or
rivets. When inspecting a new brush, make sure that the ferrule is
firmly attached to the handle.
</P>
<P>
   If a good brush is properly cared for, it will last a lifetime.
After using any brush, be sure to clean it thoroughly in the proper
solvent to dissolve all traces of paint or varnish from the
filling. Afterward, wash the brush in warm, soapy water to remove
the solvent. Shake out the excess water, then dry the filaments
with a towel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
