<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-RIVALRY-N     04-07 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-RIVALRY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A NEW GOLF RIVALRY IN THE MAKING? NOT SO QUICK!
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID CARAVIELLO   
 The Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It has been nearly 30 years since Arnold Palmer
has been competitive at the highest level of professional golf, and
over a decade since Jack Nicklaus last won a PGA Tour event. Yet
the rivalry between them remains the most storied of the sport's
modern era, and has left golf yearning for another to pick up where
it left off.
</P>
<P>
   Golf fans and golf media dearly want to see another
Nicklaus-Palmer type of rivalry unfold where two players rise above
an anonymous pack and battle against each other as much as the rest
of the field. Many believe the beginnings of golf's next great
rivalry will be found among the dogwoods and azaleas of the 63rd
Masters, which begins Thursday at Augusta National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval enters the tournament ranked No. 1 in the world. He
is on a hot streak that has seen him win four times this season and
11 times in his last 34 tournaments. Behind him is world No. 2
Tiger Woods, who has won once in the last year but becomes the man
to beat at Augusta National the minute he steps out of his courtesy
car.
</P>
<P>
   Duval and Woods are comparable in age (27 and 23, respectively),
experience (six and four years) and professional victories (11 and
10). Duval has his wraparound mirror sunglasses, Woods his menacing
stare. They are both young, photogenic, talented and marketable.
They are two stars rising at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   All are reasons why they cannot provide the kind of
Palmer-Nicklaus rivalry everyone in golf craves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those two players will be the best for two players for
a long time,'' said Fred Couples, last year's runner-up. ``But
Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus, that's a one-time thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus burst onto the scene in 1962, by which time Palmer had
already been playing professionally for seven years. Palmer was
golf's most dominant and beloved player, having won three majors
before Nicklaus arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry began when the chunky kid from Ohio knocked the king
off his pedestal in the 1962 U.S. Open Championship, and evolved to
an epic level as the two battled in nearly every major tournament
over the next 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Duval, by contrast, are contemporaries. They have one
major title between them, Woods' victory in the 1997 Masters. Over
the decade that saw their most heated competition, Nicklaus and
Palmer combined for 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason why Arnold and I became a rivalry was
because Arnold was winning most of the major championships at that
time,'' said Nicklaus, who will miss his first Masters since 1958
because of recent hip replacement surgery. When the tournament tees
off, he'll be fishing in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I can't really see that there's a rivalry yet,'' Nicklaus
said. ``One fella has won one major championship, and the other
hasn't won any. That doesn't mean they aren't the two best players,
I think they are. If you want to create a rivalry, wait until one
of them wins the Masters and the next one wins the U.S. Open. Then
you've got a rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's tough to be rivals when you hardly ever play in
the same tournaments. Of the four events Duval has won this season,
Woods competed in one, the Players Championship. And Duval didn't
play in the Buick Invitational, the tournament Woods won this year.
</P>
<P>
   Another key factor to consider is that Woods and Duval are only
two members of a cluttered class of 20-somethings that has made the
PGA Tour deeper and more competitive than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, Duval was a perennial bridesmaid who
couldn't finish off a final round. One year ago, Justin Leonard and
Woods were supposed to be the next Palmer and Nicklaus. Two years
ago, it was Phil Mickelson and Ernie Els. The Tour has proven too
difficult for any one of them to break free of the pack, much less
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd certainly embrace it if it came to pass, but I think it's
hard to say that we have a rivalry right now,'' Duval said. He said
Ernie Els, Phil Mickelson and Justin Leonard also must be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a little bit of a rivalry between Tiger and David?
Yeah, probably,'' said defending Masters champion Mark O'Meara.
``But I also believe there are other fine players we cannot
overlook. And if you get so wound up in those two guys, these other
guys are going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the elements that will always set the Palmer-Nicklaus
rivalry apart is the way it began, with Nicklaus beating Palmer in
a playoff in the 1962 U.S. Open at Oakmont Country Club, in western
Pennsylvania near Palmer's hometown of Latrobe. Woods-Duval, if it
is to ever become a rivalry to begin with, needs such a defining
moment.
</P>
<P>
   That moment could come Sunday in the late afternoon, when both
players are expected to be near the top of the Masters leader
board. But, Nicklaus said, it needs to happen on its own. What
passes as a rivalry now between Woods and Duval seems almost
manufactured, a product of wishes by fans and stories by the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our games created the rivalry,'' Nicklaus said of he and
Palmer. ``The rivalry was not created by the media. I think that's
what has to happen with these guys. Their games have got to create
that.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Journal in Spartanburg, S.C., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
