<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WILL-GRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILL &AMP; GRACE' MAKES HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WILL &AMP; GRACE 
Starring: Eric McCormack, Debra Messing, Sean Hayes, Megan
Mullally 
On: NBC, Thursday night at 8:30 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A small bit of television history will occur when ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' moves on up to Thursday nights at 8:30. No, it's not
because NBC has finally made a sensible decision by banishing
``Jesse'' to the mysterious land of Early Hiatus, where mediocre
shows go to find spiritual peace before, hopefully, dying.
</P>
<P>
   The historical moment has more to do with the fact that, with
hardly a rah-rah or a boo-hoo from gay and right-wing factions, a
sitcom about a gay man and his friends will finally take up
residence in TV's hottest neighborhood. Willfully, but gracefully,
``Will &AMP; Grace'' has inched its way from the Nowheresville of
Mondays and the Promised Land of Tuesdays to the heights of
Thursday nights, in the Nielsen-topping block that reaches from
``Friends'' to ``ER.'' It will continue to be the gayest show on
TV, and because it's on Thursdays, and because it's on NBC, and
because America finds it hard to reach for the clicker between good
shows, it will be among the most watched TV series in America every
week.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope ``Will &AMP; Grace'' keeps its head. It's quite possible
that this move into high visibility will blow up the sort of dust
storm of controversy that plagued ``Ellen,'' but that has not hit
``Will &AMP; Grace'' so far. The ``pro-family'' folks who have been
fighting for an HC TV rating _ for ``Homosexual Content'' _ and all
the Falwell followers will probably turn up the volume on their
anti-gay lobbying and get their fax machines a-churning. And the
gay organizations that find the show's image of gay life too
``safe'' will accuse the writers of de-sexualizing the characters
to make them palatable for the homophobic public. When, they will
ask, will we see Will Truman kiss another man? When will he have
all the rights of the straight members of the sitcom community?
</P>
<P>
   Once ``Ellen'' caught the eyes of the world in 1997, it made a
wrong move by trying to force an understanding of gay life onto
viewers. After a few hysterical episodes about coming out and the
awkward moments between straights and gays, ``Ellen'' sacrificed
its good humor to educate the masses _ forgetting that few of us
turn on sitcoms to get a PhD in social issues. The show overlooked
the great subversive powers of comedy, tearing the velvet off the
pink hammer before bringing it down upon viewers' heads.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is first and foremost a comedy, with
no agenda other than to cause laughter. With first-rate repartee
that is jam-packed with hip allusions, its sensibility makes me
think of Sandra Bernhard, the comic whose monologues and songs are
meaningless without a good knowledge of pop culture and an ear for
camp. This episode includes bits about Petula Clark, Tinky Winky
from ``Teletubbies,'' ``Dead Man Walking,'' the James Brolin-Barbra
Streisand marriage, Sal Mineo, Soon Yi Allen, and the song ``I
Fought the Law,'' among other icons large and tiny. The show is
very New York, very up-to-date, and very Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   But all the cleverness would be nothing, of course, without a
strong cast of characters. The four ``Will &AMP; Grace'' regulars are
in the process of developing the kind of rich ensemble dynamic that
marks the very best sitcoms. Roommates Will and Grace are happily,
and miserably, codependent, both single and wishing for but fearing
love affairs. During the course of the season, actors Eric
McCormack and Debra Messing have been refining their chemistry,
with McCormack letting Will be more temperamental and needy, and
Messing making Grace less high strung and ``I Love Lucy''-esque.
Initially, the scripts portrayed Grace as the more pathetic of the
pair, still harboring hopes for a man who has his eye on other men.
But more recently Will has been seen moping over Grace's
independence and romantic involvement, notably a dalliance with
Will's brother. Now, the two characters are equally screwed up.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble gains its brio from the more cartoonish supporting
turns by Sean Hayes as Jack, Will's queeny friend, and Megan
Mullally as Karen, Grace's mink-wearing assistant. Hayes brings a
winning physical comedy to Jack's barbs, swishes, and one-liners
(``Welcome to Cynical Island. Population: You''), and Mullally
takes Karen's unapologetic superficiality and indolence to
delightful new depths. Gradually, the writers have let the two
expand their unique rapport, which is bound up in sexual
attraction, cattiness, fabulousness, and an inexplicable enthusiasm
for rubbing bellies together. Also, Karen has been cultivating an
amusing dislike for Will, and Jack has been in and out of a dislike
for Grace, both of which give the group some needed quadrangular
tension.
</P>
<P>
   Along with external pressure to be more gay or less gay, ``Will
&AMP; Grace'' will now face internal pressure to dumb down its humor to
appeal to the broader Thursday night audience. ``Frasier''
succumbed to the same pressure when it replaced ``Seinfeld'' last
fall, with the writers jettisoning the sophistication that made
their show a hit in the first place. (Recently, ``Frasier'' has
recovered some of its former drollness.)
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope this ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is not a harbinger of a new
Thursday night modus. The laugh track seems a little louder, the
characters are slightly broader, and the plot devolves into the
kind of shenanigans that we generally find respite from on shows
like ``Will &AMP; Grace.'' The episode has Will becoming soulmates with
a new female friend, now that Grace is caught up in her work.
(Molly Shannon, from ``Saturday Night Live,'' is appealing as the
Grace replacement, and NBC may well be testing her out for a future
sitcom.) By the end of the half hour, Grace's insane jealousy turns
violent, and the show resorts to the sort of catfighting gimmick
that ``Dynasty'' was famous for. Not a series high point.
</P>
<P>
   If everyone can let ``Will &AMP; Grace'' be ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC
will have a Thursday night troika of top-notch comedies on its
hands. Those who feel the need to futz with a sitcom should turn
their creative attentions to ``Veronica's Closet,'' the abominable
9:30 show that coasts into the Top 10 on its neighbors' ballast.
Now there's one closet that never should have been opened up.
</P>
</TEXT>
