<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS CROSS BORDER FOR BARGAINS ON GASOLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ While droves of Americans cross into Mexico for
bargains on blankets and beer, increasing numbers of Mexicans are
driving to the U.S. side of the border for an inexpensive tank of
gas.
</P>
<P>
   It costs about half as much to fill up in Texas border cities as
it does across the Rio Grande in Mexico, where the government owns
the national oil company.
</P>
<P>
   The price disparity has left dust gathering on gasoline pumps
while steady streams of Mexicans head to gas stations and
convenience stores to the north.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a gallon unleaded gasoline cost $1.03 in the
border city of Laredo; across the Rio Grande in Nuevo Laredo, the
cost was $2 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the American Automobile Association reported that
the average price for regular self-serve unleaded gasoline was
$1.08 per gallon nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors of major Mexican border cities plan to go to Mexico City
next week to urge the federal government to subsidize gasoline
prices along the border to make them competitive with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Jose Zarate, a spokesman for Nuevo Laredo, said the mayors
want the federal government to bring gasoline prices back under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stations are on the verge of closing,'' Zarate said by
telephone. ``There is a tremendous difference. We have got to
equalize the prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attribute the higher prices in Mexico to the
cash-strapped government siphoning away profits from the state-run
oil company, Pemex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government tends to lean heavily on Pemex during times of
financial distress,'' said Michael Patrick, a professor at Texas
A&AMP;M International University in Laredo who specializes in border
economics. ``There is less of the pie to divide up, and the
government is still taking its fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lichtblau, spokesman for the Petroleum Research Foundation
in New York City, said Mexico would use Pemex to get as much money
as it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one market there, and they (Pemex officials) can
charge whatever they want,'' Lichtblau said. ``If it costs twice as
much as Texas, that is their choice.''
</P>
<P>
   While prices at Mexican pumps are high, they are still a little
more than half of those in Europe or Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the pumps, there is no doubt more people are heading
north for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to know why the gasoline is not cheaper,'' said
Isabel Campos, 31, as she filled the tank of her pick-up truck in
downtown Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, I need about $10 to fill the tank. There, I need $20,''
said Campos, who lives in Nuevo Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of customers from Mexico,'' a manager for a
convenience store in Brownsville said by phone. ``It has increased
a lot in the past six or seven months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1806EDT &QL; 
