<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICEMAN-COMETH-ART-2TA     04-07 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICEMAN-COMETH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$100 A TICKET?! HERE'S WHY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every time the producers of ``The Iceman Cometh''
want to have a light bulb changed, they need to use a three-man
crew, each member earning $43.36 an hour. To fashion the three
women's wigs they needed, the producers paid $2,250, saving at
least $750 each by having molds made of the actresses' heads and
having the hairpieces made in England. And $3,000 went for dirtying
up some of the the show's rented costumes to make them more
appropriate to the Bowery-like mise en scene.
</P>
<P>
   Such are some of the more arcane expenses behind Broadway's only
$100 ticket, for orchestra seats to the latest production of Eugene
O'Neill's barroom epic, ``The Iceman Cometh.'' The show,
transplanted from London and starring Kevin Spacey, opens Thursday
night at the Brooks Atkinson Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iceman'' is only the third show in Broadway history to get
$100 a seat; the two-part ``Nicholas Nickleby'' did so in 1981, as
did ``Miss Saigon'' a decade later. But some Broadway veterans
suspect it is a harbinger.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, the Roundabout Theater Company announced
it would increase the top price for the hit revival of ``Cabaret''
to $90. ``The Lion King'' charges $80 for a prime seat, and several
shows have had special packages that top $100 but include amenities
like private lounges, gift packs and champagne at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Producers say the price increases are justified by rising
production expenses, costs that far eclipse dirt, wigs and bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate this, Emanuel Azenberg, lead producer of
``Iceman,'' recently took the unusual step of opening his books and
budgets to a reporter. Many of the budget figures were estimates,
and the figures have not been audited yet by an accountant. But
several other experienced producers said the figures looked
accurate and were, if anything, somewhat lower than what they have
been paying.
</P>
<P>
   What emerges is not only Azenberg's rationale for the $100
ticket but also the intricate and sometimes laborious processes by
which ``Iceman'' and other Broadway shows spend _ and save _ money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iceman Cometh,'' written in 1939-40, tells the story of a
group of down-on-their-luck patrons of a seedy bar and the genial
salesman, Theodore Hickman (played by Spacey), who arrives in their
midst. Before its premier in 1946, O'Neill said it was a play
``about pipe dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   By Azenberg's figuring, it is a vision that will cost $5 million
to present on Broadway for 13 weeks. This broadly breaks out as a
$1.5 million initial capitalization to mount the show _ that is, to
bring in the stage equipment, cast it and otherwise get it ready to
open _ and $3.25 million, or $250,000 a week, in running costs.
Azenberg also expects some unbudgeted costs, like advertising for
Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   With the maximum potential weekly gross at roughly $500,000,
Azenberg says a sellout of the run would mean income of about $6.5
million to $6.6 million, depending on variables like possible
standing-room tickets. Subtract about 1,400 free house seats
($140,000) for Tony voters and about 300 for the press ($30,000),
and the final profit for a sellout will be roughly $1.5 million.
``A million-dollar profit, maybe, on a $1.5 million risk, is not
excessive,'' Azenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Iceman'' also presents unique challenges for a producer.
The first is its large cast: 19 actors and seven understudies. Then
there is the show's length, four and a quarter hours, which means
overtime for backstage employees and only seven shows a week. (The
Broadway standard is eight.) Finally the limited run _ 13 weeks,
the term of Spacey's commitment _ leaves a small window for
producers to earn back their $1.5 million and make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play has a giant cast, it's in overtime from the get-go,
and we're only doing seven performances a week,'' Azenberg said.
``You charge any less, you're suicidal.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the show had few of the gigantic costs that typically
drive up expenses of blockbuster musicals. It has only one set, no
orchestra or pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   The producers and their general manager, Abbie M. Strssler,
have scrimped and bargained to cut costs. They bought a dishwasher
for $600 to eliminate hand-washing _ and possible overtime.
Costumes were rented in England to avoid an international duty on
their purchase. And Azenberg's negotiating mantra for actors and
designers was, ``Everybody works for minimum.'' Indeed, the $1.5
million capitalization is remarkably low for a play of its size.
</P>
<P>
   Azenberg, who has been producing on Broadway for over 30 years,
said he knew sitting in the audience at the Almeida Theater in
London last May how much it would cost to move it to Broadway.
``You can do the math in about five minutes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Strassler, who oversees costs, did similar calculations. The
show has four union stagehands, each earning a weekly base of
$1,234.58 plus two hours of straight time pay a day because of the
show's length and for preshow prep work. But Ms. Strassler said the
weekly total for one backstage worker is $3,575, including base
pay, overtime, benefits, a supervision fee stipulated by the union
and a 17 percent payroll tax.
</P>
<P>
   There were other sacrifices for the art. To accommodate the set,
designed by Bob Crowley, 59 of the $100 seats were eliminated from
the front rows. That's a loss of $536,900.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Azenberg did when committing to the show was to
ask Spacey to work for $1,135 a week, the minimum allowed by
Actors' Equity, the actors' union. He agreed, as did the rest of
the cast. (Spacey, as a producer, will also share in any profit, as
will the rest of the cast, the O'Neill estate, the director and and
the five other producers.) The director, Howard Davies, and
designers are also taking the minimum fees for their work.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Ms. Strassler, the show's general manager, went to
London with the show's technical supervisor, who oversees
construction of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Several crucial budget decisions were made. The team realized it
would be cheaper for the producers to buy the set from the Almeida
for $35,000 and spend $15,000 to ship it to New York than to build
a new set here. Props, including dozens of glasses, were bought in
New York. The three women's wigs ran about $750 each, against $1500
to $2000 here.
</P>
<P>
   The original costumes were rented for about $3,500 and altered
for the American actors. Still, the three women's costumes were
worn out in London and were refashioned in New York at a cost of
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other costumes from England arrived too clean. Ms. Strassler
said the show had to pay wardrobe workers to distress them. One
wardrobe specialist used oil and dirt to create a Bowery look.
``All I know is they came out looking really yucky,'' said Ms.
Strassler, ``and we paid for every nickle of it.'' The cost:
$3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Azenberg said that fully one-sixth of his preproduction budget,
$250,000, went to advertising, from mailings to splashy ads in The
New York Times. And $350,000 was set aside to buy or rent the stage
equipment and pay laborers to get and adapt the set, costumes,
lights and sound gear for the theater. Rental of the theater is
$10,000 a week plus an undisclosed percentage of the show's gross.
Theater owners charge producers for much of the cost of running the
theater (about $5,000) and for the salaries of a dozen or so
theater employees ($21,000).
</P>
<P>
   When a production enters a Broadway house, it finds an empty
stage. Crews have to haul in every piece of lighting and sound
equipment and the computers to coordinate it all. The initial light
budget for ``Iceman'' was $75,000, including about $20,000 to buy
bulbs, gels and other equipment. A bulb for a spotlight can run
$700, and don't even talk about burnouts.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing light bulbs is ``a major operation,'' Ms. Strassler
said. For one thing, the stage at the Atkinson is raked, so the
surface is leveled with a wedge and men support the cherry picker;
other times other equipment has to be used. Either way,
three-person crews are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of some technical elements was overestimated and others
were eliminated, including a projected announcement at the
beginning of the play asking patrons to turn off their cellular
telephones. This will save $275 a week for renting a projector.
</P>
<P>
   The set, which arrived in January, also had to be adapted at a
shop in the Bronx to fit into the Atkinson. It cost $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Discoveries during rehearsal also swelled the budget. Four
positions not originally budgeted _ a fight director (about five
specialists do all the coaching on Broadway), a dialect coach, an
assistant director and a song teacher _ were added, costing
$15,000. Salaries and fees in rehearsal for actors, production
staff and the creative team also totaled $308,561.
</P>
<P>
   On March 29 the show had its first preview. This ended the
preproduction period and started the weekly, up-and-running
expenses, some large, some small.
</P>
<P>
   Labor, of course, is the biggest expense. Weekly salaries, from
actors to press agents, run $57,601 plus payroll tax, pension and
welfare, vacation pay and sick leave. The technical supervisor,
casting director and designers each get a weekly fee, budgeted at
$4,000. Weekly the cost is $79,489.56. Total for the entire run:
$1,033,364.20.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's miscellaneous, about $2,500 a week, from tips for
stage door staff to throat lozenges to backstage coffee. ``It's a
four-hour show,'' said Ms. Strassler. ``We can spring for coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the audience sees bread and roses onstage, those are
part of the budget, too. Every night the show uses two loaves of
bread ($2.79), a jar of pickles ($1.19) and olives ($1.59) and a
dozen roses ($8-10). Because the show has two performances on
Saturday, $700 is spent to cater a meal for actors and crew.
</P>
<P>
   Even closing a show is an expense. Azenberg has budgeted
$100,000 for it, a figure Ms. Strassler says covers trash bin
rental, landfill fees, stagehands, shipping, theater restoration
and ``sending people home.''
</P>
<P>
   And if all goes well, some money is returned. The unions for the
stagehands, actors and press agents each ask for bonds and deposits
in the event that their producers can't pay their members fees. For
``Iceman,'' that means some $82,250 is frozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a veteran of this, I'm always grateful getting some money
back,'' Azenberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
