<P>
   CHECKFREE _ Shares of CheckFree Holdings, the metro Atlanta
provider of electronic commerce services to financial institutions
and businesses, continue to defy gravity. The stock is up more than
$5 to $52.75 as the company continues to benefit from a report that
it may be an acquisition target for Yahoo!. Year-to-date, CheckFree
is up 126 percent. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SALON-WELL _ Web magazine Salon purchases ``The Well,'' one of
the first ISP's to foster community and gather mainstream
attention. A major deal of the redesigned Salon.com, which debuted
this week, with 10 new areas. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STEAKOUT _ Atlanta-based Steak Out, is embarking on an agressive
franching expansion outside of the southeast. New operations are
opening in California, Corlorado, Kansas and Nevada. (Poole,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WEBMD _ DuPont (NYSE: DD) and WebMD, Inc., a leading internet
healthcare site, today announced a $220 million internet healthcare
alliance designed to bring the value of DuPont's knowledge in life
sciences to consumers and healthcare professionals, while providing
physicians across the nation the benefit of WebMD's comprehensive
suite of web-based services. Will have Chronology chart showing
major events in time line. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ Home Depot, United Parcel Service, BellSouth,
Coca-Cola and Delta Air Lines held on to their one-through-five
status as the biggest Georgia companies on the Fortune 500 list
this year. But none was close to the top, Home Depot ranking 32nd.
Ten other Georgia companies made the list, or one more than last
year. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EMERY-DAYTONAIR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton is unveiling a proposed
billion-dollar, long-range expansion of the Dayton International
Airport to increase its cargo handling capacity so Emery Worldwide
could more than double its local work force over 20 years.
(Bebbington, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NCR-SYSTEM _ DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR Corp. is unveiling a new system
that will allow large companies to simulate the cozy familiarity of
an old-time neighborhood retailer by using huge computer databases.
Scott Walters, NCR's director of Worldwide Marketing Customer
Interaction Solutions, said ``Interaction Plus'' will help
companies get and keep customers, who increasingly are less loyal
and more demanding. (Bischoff, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
