<HEADER>
A9551 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-64BIT-CHIPS-NYT &LR;      04-07 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-64BIT-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IA-64 CHIP: INTEL BREAKS THE MOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For two decades, Intel Corp. has built its astonishingly
successful computer chips on the same basic plan or architecture.
The 8086 gave way to the 286, 386, 486 and Pentium, a kind of 586,
which is why many people call this line of chips the x86.
</P>
<P>
   But all good things come to an end. Beginning next year, Intel
will begin introducing chips that follow a new plan it calls IA-64,
short for Intel's 64-bit architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture of a chip is more than just wires and
transistors _ it is the structure and plan for processing
information. A computer architect specifies how big a chunk of data
a central processing unit can process at a time, what type of
mathematics can be done with the data and just how long the job
takes. It's like designing an assembly line for a data factory.
</P>
<P>
   The IA-64 architecture bears little resemblance to the old
Pentium and 486 chips. The most striking difference is that the new
chips will move data 64 bits at a time instead of 32 bits at a
time, as the current line does. The new chips are not destined for
the consumer market any time soon. Intel plans to sell the machines
to Web sites, corporate databases and other high-end users.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average user won't see one on their desktop, but when they
log into a Web site, they'll see one,'' said Ron Curry, the product
marketing manager for the new line. In other words, the servers
that hold the Web-site information may have these new chips, which
will be able to juggle more memory, more tasks and more disk space.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling out a new architecture is not easy. It is even more
difficult for Intel because its franchise is built upon supplying a
line of chips that run the same software. When Apple made the jump
from the line of chips that powered the original Macintosh to the
Power PC chips that have driven its recent computers, the company
created an unusual software emulator that allows the new chips to
simulate the old chips so people can still use their old Macintosh
programs. The transition was successful, but after five years,
Apple is just finally retiring the last bits of software for the
older machines.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is taking a different tack for its transition and
integrating a hardware-based emulator into the IA-64 chips. The new
chips will convert the old x86 software into IA-64 instructions on
their own. Curry said that kind of hardware emulation was ``the
only way you can insure real compatibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The old software will still run on the new chips, and
programmers will not need to worry about the differences if they
don't want to. Still, ambitious programmers will be able to convert
their software into IA-64 code to get greater speed.
</P>
<P>
   Changing architectures is such a complicated job for everyone
that it is a miracle that companies attempt the job at all, but the
alternative is decreased performance. Redesigning everything from
the ground up lets Intel optimize its chips to take advantage of
the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to one of the first IA-64 chips, nicknamed Merced,
Curry said: ``Five years ago, people said to me, `Why would I ever
need 128 megabytes in my desktop machine?' Merced is able to
address terabytes of memory, and already some server guys are
talking about using it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ways computers are used helps create a need for better
chips. Early machines strained to display some text on the screen
for word processors and spreadsheets, while it is common today for
video cards with sophisticated graphics to display
three-dimensional slime-slinging monsters. And computers once sat
like islands on desktops, but now they are tightly integrated with
the Internet. Intel would like to redesign its chips to serve these
new needs as well as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change Intel is making to its architecture is adding
new codes that tell the chip when several instructions can be
executed at the same time. They named this approach explicitly
parallel instruction computing, or Epic for short.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it is common at tax time to run software that
checks to see if an income is above a certain level. If it is, then
the tax is computed by multiplying by one rate; if it isn't, a
lower rate is used. In the past, the computer would compare the
income level with the cutoff in one step before doing the right tax
calculation in the next step. Intel's new instruction set will
allow all three computations to be done at the same time. If the
income turns out to be above the cutoff, the result using the
higher rate of multiplication is used; otherwise, the lower figure
is used.
</P>
<P>
   That approach is faster but wasteful. The results emerge in one
step instead of two, but one-third of the computation is thrown
away. This profligacy is becoming increasingly acceptable because
more and more transistors can be squeezed onto a chip. By doing
more calculations at once, greater overall speed is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Executing multiple instructions at one time is not a new
challenge. Much of the intellectual heritage for the IA-64 comes
from supercomputing companies like Multiflow Computer and Cydrome;
they both tried to develop earlier versions of Epic computers.
After those companies failed, some of their scientists moved to
Hewlett-Packard. In the mid-'90s, Intel formed a partnership with
Hewlett-Packard that has led to the IA-64. Speaking of Multiflow
and Cydrome, Curry said: ``Certainly that technology was a
contribution to the Epic design philosophy. We tried to build upon
the best concepts available at the time and add new research that
we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard has said it is going to take advantage of the
IA-64 chips. Software written for Hewlett-Packard's PA-RISC
computers, high-end machines that are often used as workstations,
can be quickly converted into software for the IA-64 line.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is being relatively quiet about the IA-64 line of chips
while it focuses its marketing efforts on its Pentium III chip,
which was just introduced. The first chips will not even become
available until next year, and each one will probably cost more
than many consumers pay for an entire system. High-end users, like
Web sites and graphic design firms, however, are likely to pay the
price.
</P>
<P>
   Curry said the company did not anticipate selling many IA-64
chips to consumers in the next five years. It plans to extend the
current 32-bit line, which it now calls the IA-32. ``We're working
on several 32-bit processors for consumers,'' Curry said. ``We
don't see the need for 64 bits in the consumer space anytime soon.
It doesn't mean we won't get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
