<HEADER>
A9553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACCONCI-ARCHITECTURE-     04-07 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCONCI-ARCHITECTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ALWAYS, PLEASE TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By PHILIP NOBEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is hard to reconcile the quiet figure of Vito
Acconci, aspiring architect, with the swath he has cut as an artist
over the last 30 years. Can this kind-eyed 59-year-old, almost lost
among the computer-aided design stations and unopened crates in his
cavernous new Brooklyn studio, be the same man who, in his 1969
``Following Piece,'' recorded a month of days spent stalking
strangers through the streets of New York? Or who, in his infamous
``Seedbed'' installation of 1972, broadcast his erotic fantasies
about gallery-goers to them as they walked above him on a plywood
ramp and he indulged himself in privacy below?
</P>
<P>
   In his celebrated career, Acconci's Bronx-bred skepticism and
unshackled intelligence have taken him from raw poetry to body-art
performances that tested the sharpness of the edges where the
public and private worlds meet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, his attentions are focused on gentler things.
Vito Acconci, the enfant terrible emeritus of the downtown art
world, is using his increasingly housebroken art to put a humane
spin on contemporary architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his small team at Acconci Studio completed several
projects that are playfully at odds with the buildings in which
they are sited but in tune with the physical and psychological
needs of those who use them.
</P>
<P>
   At a new U S Airways terminal at the Philadelphia International
Airport, Acconci designed a waiting area where harried travelers
can hide within huge curls that peel from the building's terrazzo
floor. In a similar move at a convention center in Milwaukee, he
pulled the material of an exterior walkway through a glass wall,
folding it over at different points to form droopy benches and a
bus shelter. Like many of his works, his 1995 installation at
Queens College, a surreal constellation of inhabitable orbs
scattered around a small plaza, inserts a human scale that spars
with the humorless public space around it, in this case creating
sheltered nooks that fill with smoking students between classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take the word `public' as literally as possible, so
our work should be public in the sense that it is publicly usable,
publicly available, publicly accessible,'' he said in a voice so
thick and resonant that words tend to rattle around in it before
they tumble out.
</P>
<P>
   In its impish refusal to respect traditional limitations, his
architectural work echoes the urges that drove his art. ``The main
reason to start doing art was a resentment against the `Do Not
Touch' signs in a museum,'' he said recently, between drags on the
first of a chain of Gaul-oises. ``In every other field of life, you
come across something for the first time, and you pick it up, you
turn it upside down. But in art, the tradition was: `You're here.
It's there.' So you're always in the position of desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustration with hands-off art led first to projects like
``Claim,'' in 1971, in which Acconci dramatized the distance
between artists and the public by wielding lead pipes and a crowbar
while sitting blindfolded at the bottom of a stairway in a SoHo
gallery. Beginning in 1980, he used a lighter touch to erase the
same boundary with a series of installations in which viewers had
to complete a sculpture by operating a system of pulleys attached
to a swing, a go-cart or a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   From its antisocial beginnings, Acconci's work has gradually
engaged ever more with the public, culminating in his current
almost-architectural work. (While he is not trained as an architect
_ his clients are often public agencies with money for art _
Acconci's recent commissions would be the envy of any young
architecture firm.)
</P>
<P>
   Holly Solomon, the pioneering New York gallery owner, has
followed Acconci's career since the early 1970s, when he performed
regularly at a space near her original gallery at 98 Greene St. She
said recently that she thinks ``Vito Acconci, architect'' makes
perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a far-flung occupation, or preoccupation,
for Vito,'' she said. ``Instead of just stating the cruelty of
modern society, he's making a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Still images from a videotape of ``Corrections,'' a 1972
performance in which Acconci burned a tuft of hair from his neck
with a match, are on view through May 4 as part of the ``Sight
Gags'' exhibition at the Museum of Modern Art. The distance that
Acconci has traveled from those angrier days was evident last month
at a ceremony to honor the winners of the New York City Art
Commission design awards. Trolling through a reception at the top
of City Hall's floating spiral stairway, clad from head to toe in
black artist's fatigues, he seemed perfectly at home, despite the
fact that his only previous visit to the building had been to
protest changes to the loft laws in the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   The award Acconci received that night at City Hall recognized
his design for a perimeter fence at the Newtown Creek sewage
treatment plant, a sprawling, 53-acre installation in Brooklyn.
Jean Parker Phifer, president of the Art Commission, said the
project was selected because of the respect it shows for its
surroundings. ``It literally brings the neighborhood into the
plant,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Newtown Creek, as in his art, Acconci could not resist
touching things that are normally off-limits. He tried to soften
the edges of the site as a way to ``mix'' the neighborhood and the
plant. The approved design, which will be completed with an upgrade
of the plant sometime before 2010, is a skein of concrete walls
that create small parks and pools of water as they coil around the
property line.
</P>
<P>
   Where the proposed border meets the plant's visitor center, one
of a number of buildings at Newtown Creek designed by the New York
architectural firm of Polshek Partners, Acconci's aversion to
boundaries takes over in force. As designed, his walls will
penetrate the building's glass facade to enclose pockets of public
space within, even sending a low tendril around the elevator core
to form a tranquil pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, we saw it as the architects inviting us in,''
Acconci said. ``Maybe this betrays an amazing innocence or false
innocence on our part, but we didn't think we were trying to attack
the building. We thought, `Let's take the building, and let's play
with the elements.'''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Polshek Partners, which prides itself on its
seriousness, was not amused by what some saw as Acconci's
sensationalism. The community, however, seemed thrilled. Bob
Gormley, community liaison for the Newtown Creek Monitoring
Committee, said the plant's neighbors appreciated the way he was
``tweaking Polshek's design.'' And they showed they appreciated
Acconci himself by showing up in larger than average numbers to see
his understated, poetic presentations at design panels and
community board meetings.
</P>
<P>
   At a terminal now under construction at the San Francisco
International Airport, Acconci again pushed the edge of the
envelope _ and the architects from the local office of Skidmore,
Owings &AMP; Merrill _ with a proposal for the entire complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expected response was, `You're trying to take over our
building,''' he said with a smile. ``We probably were.'' The
parties eventually agreed on a site in an 800-foot-long transfer
corridor, for which Acconci has designed a lighting system that
doubles as an enclosure for public telephones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
