<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton says Belgrade's
cease-fire is ``not enough'' to avert more NATO air strikes. The
president said it's not enough for Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic
to halt attacks in a Kosovo. Clinton said Milosevic must withdraw
his forces, allow Albanian refugees to return and permit an
international peace force to deploy in Kosovo. Meanwhile, a
representative from Cyprus has flown to Belgrade to try to secure
the release of three U-S captives. He told reporters he's confident
his mission will succeed. The plan is to turn the soldiers over to
American officials once they're freed. Also, NATO claims to have
hit some Serb tanks. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ Since the
airstrikes began, Bosnians have anxiously listened for the buzz of
the NATO bombers that fly over every day on their way to
neighboring Yugoslavia. But many observers worry the conflict next
door holds more than noise for this still very war-torn country. It
is hardening the ethnic divisions here, causing some to worry that
it could ultimately cause the break-up of Bosnia and the end of the
Dayton Peace Accords. Because while half the country listens to the
planes and hopes NATO will bomb the Serbs into submission and
rescue the Kosovo Albanians quickly, the other half, the Bosnian
Serb half, listens angrily to what they see as an attack on their
brethren across the border and talks of armed resistance. (Nesmith,
Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO _ PODGORICA, Montenegro, Yugoslavia _ In an
interview, Montenegro President Milo Djukanvoic says the U.S.-led
NATO air strikes are destabilizing his government. Under his
leadership, Montenegro has adopted pro-Western reforms but remains
part of the Yugoslav federation. Those reforms, and even his
well-being, are at risk as rumors of a possible coup continue to
circulate. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLDIERS _ TIRANA, Albania _ For U.S. soldiers who have
been thrust into the middle of a major military and humanitarian
crisis, the comfort of their American homes suddenly seems far, far
away. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). With PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Story expected to include quotes and photos of soldiers
from Texas, Florida and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Wednesday
that the United States should improve trade and other relations
with China, saying it was in the U.S. interest to do so. (Shepard,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHICK _ SANDTON, South Africa _ For Dan Cathy, as for his
father, Chick-fil-A founder Truett Cathy, doing business is as much
about helping people as it is about making money. Which is
fortunate, because the Atlanta-based fast-food chain is finding
that the economic climate in South Africa poses significant
challenges, including interest rates in the high teens and an
economy that shrank in the last quarter of last year. But there's
no denying that, in a country where unemployment is estimated at
nearly 40 percent, Chick-fil-A, by opening stores, is helping
people. Today April 8 the chain will open its third store in South
Africa, this time in a mall in Sandton, an upscale northern suburb
of Johannesburg. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-GOVERNOR _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's attorney general has
issued an arrest warrant on drug-smuggling charges for the former
governor of Mexico's Quintana Roo state. But the warrant was issued
just one day after Mario Villanueva left office and confirmed in a
letter to Mexican newspapers that he had fled Mexico, fearing he
would be arrested. He says he is the victim of a political
vendetta. Authorities say he helped Mexico's Juarez drug-smuggling
cartel move tons cocaine into the United States. Mexico could now
face criticism they let Villanueva escape. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-PHOTOS _ WASHINGTON _ Wearing a Gap T-shirt and a gold
cross, Bernadine Mendoza sews a new American flag in a factory in
Houston. Wearing glasses and a flowery blouse, 8-year-old Carolina
Bernal ponders her next move on a chessboard in Chicago. These
images of Hispanic women in America represent a tiny slice of
``Americanos: Latino Life in the United States'' _ a Smithsonian
multimedia project conceived by actor Edward James Olmos exhibit
that debuts here Wednesdayand later travels to San Antonio, Houston
and other U.S. cities. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-INDICTMENT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Fallout from the multiple
indictments against the Austin Independent School District and its
No. 2 administrator on charges of tampering with state achievement
test data. This is the first time in Texas history that criminal
charges have been filed against a school district. (Jayson, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TAXRALLY _ U.S. Rep. Bob Barr and Congressman Joe Barton of
Texas hold rally at the Marietta Town Square to generate support
for a constitutional amendment that would require a two-thirds
supermajority of both chamber of Congress to pass any tax increase.
(Farber, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ORAL-UNC _ Chapel Hill, N.C. _ Chapel Hill's Southern Oral
History Program, one of the nation's first to document common
folks, is celebrating its 25th anniversary Thursday. Burritt will
interview the people who started program about its influence in
documenting the region's often turbulent history and about the
program's influence in spawning others, such as one at Georgia
State University. Burritt also will listen to tapes and read
transcripts from more than 2,000 interviews with textile workers,
civil rights activists and others with links to Atlanta. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK _ ATLANTA _ Mayor names four member Freaknik committee.
It includes two local businessmen and two college students.
Committee members say they believe Freaknik's popularity is waning
but they want to be prepared for those who do attend. (Campos,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA _ State Agriculture Commissioner Tommy Irvin has issued
a warning to Vidalia onion farmers: don't send onions to market too
early. Irvin mailed a letter to all registered growers this week
after an eight-member committee governing the Vidalia onion
industry expressed concern that in recent years, some farmers have
tried to rush early onions to market early in order to get the best
prices. Such onions are not fully developed, therefore they don't
have the hallmark sweetness of Vidalias and they can go bad quicker
than fully ripe onions. Fully ripe onions are expected to hit
grocery shelves in about two weeks. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   OCTOGENARIAN-DIES _ ATLANTA _ Grover Cleveland was president
when Geneva O'Kelly McDaniel, 111, of Duluth was born. That was
during his first term, only 23 years after Atlanta surrendered to
Gen. William T. Sherman. An Atlanta celebrity known for teaching
aerobics well past her 100th birthday, Mrs. McDaniel was featured
on national shows such as 20/20 and Late Night with David
Letterman. Mrs. McDaniel died of pneumonia Tuesday at Briarwood
Nursing Home in metro Atlanta. (Thomas, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MORRISBROWN-CROSS _ Even in her early teens, Morris Brown
College President Delores Cross had made tough decisions without
blinking an eye, backing down or walking away. At 14, she had to
get a job to pay her family's rent in a Newark housing project
after her mother was committed to a mental institution; she also
overcame a stuttering problem. ``I didn't have the classic middle
class upbringing you normally associate with college presidents,''
Cross said. So, when she stood in front of an angry crowd of
faculty members on March 9 and told them that despite their pleas,
they would probably still get fired, it was not out of character.
Last Thursday, Cross fired several faculty members, fulfilling her
promise to start cleaning house to, in her opinion, restore
academic integrity at the 118-year-old historically black
institution. (Suggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRAT-CONTRIBUTOR _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Monte Friedkin reaches
up to put Bill Clinton's gold braided, yachtsman's cap back on his
head. Balancing it carefully on Clinton's cardboard noggin,
Friedkin grins at the life-size figure that dominates the office of
one of Florida's biggest contributors to the Democratic Party. With
the shades-wearing, saxophone-playing image of Clinton peering over
his left shoulder, Friedkin is tooting his own horn. He wants you
to know that the days of a placid Democratic Party in Palm Beach
County are over. He intends to turn the county party into the most
powerful political force in the state. What worries Republicans is
that Friedkin has the money, contacts and influence to make it
happen. 42. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
