<HEADER>
A9568 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONORING-CHARLESIVES-     04-07 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONORING-CHARLES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU HONORS CRUSTY AMERICAN COMPOSER
</HEADLINE>
 IVES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For the music lovers of my generation,
composer Charles Ives will always be a hero _ a crusty American who
anticipated major innovations of modern music decades before anyone
else, and who beat the system in a way only baby boomers can
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   We loved the way he enshrined unmistakably American materials,
such as ``Old Black Joe'' or ``Rock of Ages,'' within sturdy
traditional forms such as sonatas and symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   We loved the way that thick, almost incomprehensible dissonance
overwhelmed the listener _ only to be interrupted by a comforting
wisp of familiar melody, be it a bit of Beethoven or a scrap from
``Come Thou Fount of Every Blessing,'' ``Jesus Loves Me'' or
``Shall We Gather.'' Few composers have so successfully created a
dreamlike sensation, in which familiar reference points drift in
and out of a tangle of musical noise.
</P>
<P>
   But those of us for whom Ives stood as an affirmation of
American culture in the midst of the mess of Vietnam, Watergate and
social decadence are getting older. There are fewer and fewer of us
who grew up singing ``Rock of Ages'' to the accompaniment of an
out-of-tune piano, and who learned what a camp meeting was from
people who had really been to one. We are surely the last
generation that will hear Ives' music with this sort of emotional
attachment.
</P>
<P>
   Ives died in 1954 at 79; this week, Texas Christian University
commemorated the 125th anniversary of his birth with an ``Ives of
Texas'' festival Monday through Wesnesday.
</P>
<P>
   Born in small-town Connecticut, the son of a local bandmaster,
Ives went to Yale University and studied composition with Horatio
Parker, whose music and tastes reflected a style predominant in
Europe decades earlier. Ives quickly headed in a different
direction, writing tough, difficult music in which the beauty is
not in the sound, but in the ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Ives realized early on that he would never be able to earn a
living writing the sort of music he heard in his mind. Thus came
about the huge joke he played on the world, and the joke we still
love: He became rich as an insurance executive in Manhattan, and
spent his weekends on a farm in Connecticut, writing the music he
wanted to write without regard for fashion or trend.
</P>
<P>
   Heart disease forced his early retirement from the business
world; fortunately, he already had plenty of money. Unfortunately,
the disease also weakened his creative drive, and his long
retirement produced no new significant works.
</P>
<P>
   Was Ives really the musical Whitman, Thoreau and Lincoln all
rolled into one that we imagined? Will his music endure in the new
century?
</P>
<P>
   Some already say no.
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Companion to 20th Century Music,'' the acerbic British
commentator Norman Lebrecht dismisses Ives as ``a figure of supreme
importance in America and curiosity value elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much speculation and evidence that the early advocates
of Ives in the 1930s and 1940s did a bit more than the customary
arranging, shuffling and editing to give his most powerful scores
their impact. Even composer Elliott Carter, one of Ives' early
admirers, has said that Ives added some of the modernisms in his
music retrospectively.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some of Ives' writings and comments have, in the age of
political correctness, become a bit of an embarrassment. There are
moments of poetry in his prose, but there are those sticky
paragraphs in which music that he considered bad is associated with
femininity, and music he considered good with rugged masculinity.
He refers to Chopin ``with a skirt on,'' and Richard Strauss'
``Salome'' as a ``money-getting costume of effeminate
masculinity.'' A critic in Boston who didn't take to Ives' music
was ``a nice old lady.'' On one passage of his own music, he
scrawled, ``This is music for men to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these problems, J. Peter Burkholder, professor of
musicology at Indiana University and president of the Charles Ives
Society, points out that recordings and performances of Ives' music
are increasing _ and that the TCU event is the third Ives festival
he is attending this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better than any American of his time, he integrated popular
music with his superb classical training,'' Burkholder says.
``There's something about the sound of an American hymn or fiddle
tune that's recognizable even if you don't know the music
beforehand. The idea that Ives' importance is only as a radical
experimenter is fading; there's real staying power in his music.''
.MDSU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
