<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO RELEASE NEW EDITION OF WINDOWS 98 IN FALL &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. will release an updated version of its Windows
98 operating system this fall, though users who want its new
features will have to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   The update's bug fixes, though, will be free for the downloading
from Microsoft's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   News of the new version, to be called Windows 98 Second Edition,
caused a stir in online discussion groups after early reports
indicated its bug fixes would only be available at an $89 cost _
the price of Windows 98 itself.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft spokesman Peter Keller said the new version would
replace the current Windows 98 upgrade CD on store shelves. That
disk is used to go from Windows 3.1 or Windows 95 to Windows 98,
and costs $89.
</P>
<P>
   Another CD aimed at existing Windows 98 users will be sold
through the Microsoft Web site for a much smaller price tag that's
yet to be determined, Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   The updated version will be sent to computer manufacturers
sometime in the third quarter, and will show up on PCs and on store
shelves in early fall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bug fixes, to be bundled together into a package called
Service Pack 1, will be posted on Windows Update, a Web site that
lets Windows 98 users grab patches and fixes.
</P>
<P>
   But users will not be able to download the new features included
on the CD, including one that lets computers on a network share a
modem connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar to Microsoft's release of OSR1, an
update to Windows 95 that came in 1997. That update was only found
on new PCs and was not available to existing Window 95 users.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
