<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WRITING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: TWO VOICES FROM THE PAST THAT ECHO IN TODAY'S
BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the treats of ``Writing New York,'' the new Library of
America anthology edited by Phillip Lopate, are generous excerpts
from a pair of remarkable 19th-century diaries that speak to us
from a charmed distance in a sometimes uncharmingly immediate way.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Hone (1780-1851) and George Templeton Strong (1820-75)
had much in common. As well as being inveterate and invaluable
diarists, both were successful businessmen and civic personages.
</P>
<P>
   As certified members of the city's self-designated elite they
were accustomed to running things until their set, with its
Colonial credentials and nativist assumptions, gave way to a flood
of immigrant insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   As Strong was in the throes of chronicling the decades in four
million words, the action was moving uptown from its center around
Wall Street. (``How this city marches northward!'' he exults.)
</P>
<P>
   The diarists' accounts of social, commercial and political
doings are larded with New York names: Ogden and Tappan,
Schermerhorn and Olmstead, Griswold and Astor, Fish and Field. From
such descendants of Olde New York were drawn the masters of the
Stock Exchange, who traded tips at the Union Club, the Episcopal
elders who worshiped at Trinity Church, the lords of Fifth Avenue
mansions, the guest lists for brilliant fetes, the benefactors of
the needy and the names of many city landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they were writing, the patricians were being swamped
by families of no wealth or distinction. The young profession of
urban demography found its subject as one group of newcomers gave
way to others and to still others in an inimitably American saga.
</P>
<P>
   For the 19th-century Establishment, it was an invasion of the
unwashed; that at any rate was how the best and the brightest, like
Hone and Strong, greeted the Irish who sought succor in America and
whose muscle built the city both horizontally and vertically. They
were lumped by many Anglo-Saxon Protestants as an ignorant and
superstitious mass.
</P>
<P>
   Hone, not a particularly mean-spirited man, saw the early
immigrants as an alarming element that was susceptible to
rabble-rousing incitement against ``the aristocracy,'' a word the
patricians took unironically for themselves despite their
revolutionary pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the devastating potato blight of the 1840s that gave
the city a Celtic cast, Hone wrote: ``These Irishmen, strangers
among us, without a feeling of patriotism or affection in common
with American citizens, decide the elections in the city of New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that ``the same brogue'' in which political demagogues
instructed them to shout ``Hurrah for Jackson!'' would in time be
turned to cries of ``Down with the natives!'' Everything about the
Irish seemed to invite terror or mockery. Strong called the tale of
St. Patrick's campaign against snakes ``a popish delusion.'' He
preferred to believe that the snakes perished of biting Irish
people.
</P>
<P>
   By the financial crisis of 1857, in Strong's view, the
subversive contingent included German socialists, many of whom were
out of work and were even more dangerous than the Irish. True
Americans, after all, did not gather in alehouses to listen to one
another rant their foreign-bred opinions, sometimes in a foreign
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   While admiring the charitable efforts of women of his class,
Strong had little compassion for the rowdy unemployed: ``Certainly
the destitute are a thankless set and deserve little sympathy in
their complaints.'' To counter the corruption and violence
associated with the underclass, he liked the idea of a vigilante
group of well-born respectables who would take the law into their
own hands.
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments have been expressed, though not always so
candidly, down the decades. No immigrant group has been spared.
Being deemed a threat by self-advertised patriots is a rite of
passage in America. And hard times or political commotion, as
Strong's compelling account of the ferocious 1863 draft riots
attests, brought out truly murderous passions.
</P>
<P>
   The one group for which Strong found sympathy, out of opposition
to slavery and perhaps because the New York Irish were among their
tormentors, were blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is given to racial epithets, he wrote after reports
of beatings and lynchings: ``They are the most peaceable, sober and
inoffensive of our poor, and the outrages they have suffered during
this last week are less excusable _ are founded on worse pretext
and less provocation _ than the St. Bartholomew's or the
Jew-hunting of the Middle Ages.'' Thus did another widely despised
minority, the Jews, benefit at that hour at least from not being
Irish.
</P>
<P>
   But of course neither blacks nor Jews, neither Italians nor
Latinos have been spared the cruel attentions of those who came
before. George Templeton Strong and Philip Hone were far from
vicious; by most standards they seem to have been honest dealers.
Yet like so many other Americans, they made life miserable for the
strangers who arrived among them with their odd and threatening
ways.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Writing New York'' is not altogether a cheering excursion.
But reassurance is available in the fate of the once denigrated
groups who caused the descendants of the Founders such distress and
in turn were distressed by the arrival of even more foreign-seeming
folks than themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The likes of Ralph Ellison, Isaac Bashevis Singer, Mario Puzo,
Mary McCarthy and Al Smith, among the many contributors to these
rich pages, evidence the unstoppable American odyssey that has been
both the country's dream and its nightmare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
