<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LOGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EAGLE AS ICON: PREDATOR OR FAT HEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even wars have logos these days, at least on television, and the
coverage of the conflict in Kosovo invariably features the Albanian
eagle, splashed across the screen like the NBC peacock.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle, carried by Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, is angular,
Gothic, almost medieval in style. With its two heads and dragonlike
claws, it seems to sum up the ancient nature of the conflicts in
the Balkans _ and the fears Americans have of an area they don't
understand. It's a feathered version of all the fears of foreign
entanglements we've worried about since Washington's farewell
address.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to national heraldry, on flags and seals, the
eagle has no competition. The bird rears from the Defense
Department seal behind Secretary William Cohen as he chats with
Katie Couric, and ripples in banners in civilian rallies in
Belgrade. In Germany recently, the eagle was the subject of debate
in the Bundestag, the German parliament, which will meet for the
first time April 19 in its new home, the restored Reichstag
building in Berlin, under the eyes of a new eagle.
</P>
<P>
   The building, given a glass dome by the architect Sir Norman
Foster, required a larger version of the federal eagle Germans have
seen for decades. That eagle was a figure iconically familiar to
Germans who grew up in the 1950s and '60s, said Bernd Polster, a
design critic, author and filmmaker, who lives in Bonn and who was
born in 1953, the year the eagle went up in the Parliament
building. ``It matched the Bauhaus architecture of the Bundestag,''
Polster said. ``It was always on the screen when TV showed speeches
from the parliament. But it was better known as the `fette henne'
or `fat chicken.'''
</P>
<P>
   The fat hen was the work of Ludwig Gies, an Expressionist
sculptor whose credentials included being officially marked as
``decadent'' by the Nazis. His flat aluminum bird, speckled with
lights, was presented as the Bundesadler, the federal eagle, as
opposed to the old imperial eagle, the Reichsadler. It came to
represent a modernized parliamentary Germany, but at the same time
the fat hen summed up the returning prosperity of the 1950s and
'60s, along with a certain plump self-satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Europe and many Germans themselves have looked
warily at the government's move to Berlin, alert to signs of
over-aggressiveness. A leaner, perhaps meaner, eagle, designed by
Foster's office, was rejected in favor of a larger version of the
Gies eagle: a huge bird made of two and a half tons of aluminum.
The Foster bird had been criticized as aggressive and imperial _
too close to the eagles that Albert Speer set atop the buildings he
designed for Hitler. When the enlarged chicken-eagle was unveiled,
Bundestag President Wolfgang Thierse declared that it was ``as
peaceful as an eagle can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Germans have long worried about the retrograde qualities of
their eagles. Only clever updating made the imperial eagle
acceptable for the logo of Lufthansa, the national airline. That
bird seems to have been folded in half like a paper airplane and
tilted for takeoff. It suggests the eagle as phoenix, rising from
ashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian eagle is the kind that the Germans are at pains to
avoid. In appearance, it is a relative of the imperial eagles of
Russia and Austria. The eagle has long been associated with empire,
topping the standards of Roman legions, heralding Russian and
Austro-Hungarian domains. It admits of many variants. The Mexican
eagle fights a snake; the American bald eagle clutches arrows in
one set of claws and olive branches in the other.
</P>
<P>
   That such ornithological subtleties should signal political
shades of meaning is testimony to the power of the image. The
American bald eagle is flourishing, well on its way to escaping
endangerment. Today, when F-15E Strike Eagles are flying, and
Screaming Eagle paratroopers may be in the wings, it's clear that
Benjamin Franklin's suggestion of the nonaggressive wild turkey as
national bird never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   In creating the new, reassuringly nonbelligerent Berlin eagle,
the designers faced another quandary. Because of the placement of
the eagle, it is visible from both sides, and its rear end had to
be modeled, too _ no easy task. The eagle must turn tail feather
toward the former East bloc with suitable dignity. Universal as is
their heraldry, few eagles ever show their backs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
