<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     04-07 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE AND POLITICS MAPPED ON A WOMAN'S BODY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Author identification and publication notes are at end of
review.) 
(nk) 
 By MARILYN YALOM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Natalie Angier's dazzling new book calls upon biology and
evolution to celebrate the female body. Its upbeat message _ that
women are far stronger, more sexual, aggressive and adaptive than
usually given credit for _ is supported by rigorous scientific
underpinnings. In laying out her argument, she takes on those
currently fashionable evolutionary psychologists who present women
as fundamentally less interested in the joys of sex and worldly
achievement than men and therefore programmed for monogamous unions
with older, higher-status males.
</P>
<P>
   Tain't so, says Ms. Angier, a Pulitzer Prize-winning science
writer for The New York Times. Look again. What you'll see through
her eyes will startle and amaze you.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, there are the sex chromosomes: two X chromosomes
for women, and one X and one Y for men. In the view of Ms. Angier's
father (a major presence in her psychic life), chromosomes prove
the case for male superiority: X and Y equal diversity and genius,
while X and X are ``chromosomal bores.'' Yet as Ms. Angier takes
pleasure in noting, the X chromosome is six times larger than the Y
and has a ``vastly higher gene richness.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the egg, the largest cell in the body and the only
spherical one, ``a geometer's dream'' likened to a pearl that lasts
for decades and is hard to crush. It is ``the true sun, the light
of life.'' Such flights into poetic rapture can be counted as one
of the book's stylistic strengths, along with the first-person
anecdotes that add a wryly humorous note.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from the microscopic to bigger body parts, ``Woman: An
intimate Geography'' dramatizes female anatomy and physiology. A
chapter on the evolution of the clitoris reminds us that Freud had
it all wrong: His theory that clitoral orgasm is ``infantile'' and
vaginal orgasm ``mature'' should be seen as ``a blot on history's
understanding of female sexuality.'' Instead, Ms. Angier writes,
the clitoris has no greater end than to serve women's pleasure, and
that is end enough. Unlike its drudge male homologue, the penis, on
duty for both urination and ejaculation, the clitoris is a
specialized organ capable of repeated stimulation and multiple
orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   Given these facts, we are asked to ponder why men's sexual
satisfaction is more aggrandized than women's. And we are asked to
consider the reasons that clitoridectomy is still practiced on some
two million women each year, mainly in Africa. Here Ms. Angier does
not mince her words: ``Genital cutting is an extreme abuse of human
rights. Like slavery and apartheid, it is unacceptable.'' She says
it must be fought by every possible form of political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   While the crestlike clitoris exists solely for the gratification
of its owner, the mouthlike vagina can accommodate a variety of
objects ranging from a tampon to a baby's head. The vagina is an
``ecosystem,'' easily disturbed by venereal microbes, though it is
usually healthy and robust, especially when one considers all the
fluids that flow in and out of it.
</P>
<P>
   And one must not forget that other quintessentially female body
part, the uterus. Here, too, the reader of ``Woman'' encounters a
bracing mix of fallacy, science and politics. For example, in one
of his drawings, Leonardo da Vinci established a connection from
the uterus to the breast under the mistaken Renaissance belief that
menstrual blood somehow became maternal milk.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point today is the question of ownership. Pro- and
antiabortion spokesmen claim the right to determine what may or may
not take place in the uterus. Does the uterus belong to the woman
who houses one, or, in the case of pregnant women, does it belong
to the fetus, or the fetus' representatives in the form of church
and state? Or to doctors who, Ms. Angier says, overindulge the urge
to cut by performing more Caesarean sections and hysterectomies
than are warranted? This self-proclaimed ``feminist, pro-woman''
writer takes pains to suggest that each woman should be the
mistress of her own corporeal house.
</P>
<P>
   That house includes ovaries (``gray and pitted and as lumpy as
oatmeal''), hormones (``at least 60 forms of estrogen''), breasts
(both functional and esthetic), muscles (more than 600) and fat (27
percent of the standard woman, as opposed to 16 percent of the
standard man). Though these facts can be excavated from a medical
text, they are undoubtedly more compelling in Ms. Angier's
colorful, passionate and frankly idiosyncratic account.
</P>
<P>
   The interconnections between biology and psychology are
reconfigured in fascinating chapters on female aggression, love,
pair bonding and intergenerational nurturance provided by mothers
and grandmothers, all of which are seen as adaptive in the grand
scheme of things. And it is here that Ms. Angier takes issue with
the hard-core evolutionary psychologists who claim that men are
``naturally'' more promiscuous than women and that women are
inherently more interested in stable relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeble data,'' Ms. Angier declares. Her own data, culled from
observing women and other female primates, especially baboons,
suggest different conclusions. When one remembers that women have
been traditionally punished for promiscuity, adultery and other
displays of sexual desire, it is surprising that they evidence as
much lust as they do.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Angier never hides her political agenda. Nor does she hide
the insights derived personally from her life, especially from her
experiences as a daughter, wife and mother. Her own small daughter
has made her exquisitely sensitive to kinship with ``the tribe of
woman,'' starting with their similar bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Her reflections on the fierce bonds of womanhood, extending back
to prehistoric times when foraging grandmothers may have made more
difference to the survival of progeny than unpredictable hunts
conducted by men, turns evolutionary theory toward a gynocentric
vision of human endurance: one that is no less fanciful, it must be
said, than male-centered visions. But because Ms. Angier speculates
on the basis of massive hard data, she demonstrates that the term
``feminist science'' does not have to be an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WOMAN: An Intimate Geography'
</P>
<P>
   By Natalie Angier
</P>
<P>
   398 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $25.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Marilyn Yalom, a senior scholar at the Institute for
Research on Women and Gender at Stanford University, is the author
of ``A History of the Breast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
