u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISONERS-STRIPES-NYT     04-07 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONERS-STRIPES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 SHERIFF WANTS ALL PRISONERS TO `LOOK LIKE A ZEBRA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIRSTEN B. MITCHELL   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ In the colorful world of Davidson County Sheriff
Gerald Hege, sex offenders don green-and-white striped uniforms
while flons sport orange and white stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Black and white stripes that hark back to a bygone era are
reserved for work crews and blue and white stripes are earmarked
for low-security misdemeanants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're either going to be buck naked or you're going to have a
striped uniform,'' declares Hege, a Republican who has critics
seeing red.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is state Sen. Tony Rand, a powerful Fayetteville
Democrat, who is working to reverse a requirement that state
inmates sport stripes while working on Davidson County road crews
or community work squads. He argues that all state inmates should
be clothed alike in all counties.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul ``Jaybird'' McCrary, a Lexington Democrat who retired
in 1990 after 16 years as Davidson County sheriff, agrees. But he's
trying to stay out of the stripe strife.
</P>
<P>
   Rand's bill is the latest hand grenade in a political battle
that started last summer when the sheriff persuaded state lawmakers
that his uniform system should apply not just to county jail
inmates, but to state prisoners working in the county. Davidson
County is in North Carolina's Piedmont, near Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security-wise, you just can't beat it,'' Hege said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Correction opposed the plan, but the
sheriff found an ally in Rep. Jerry Dockham, a Republican who had
the proposal inserted into the state budget with the blessing of
Republican House leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, 91 state inmates working in Davidson County
aren't wearing stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been stalling,'' Hege said of state Department of
Correction officials. ``They've fought it from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Correction officials concede that they oppose the stripes, but
say they are trying to decide whether to ask prison-run garment
factories to sew the striped uniforms or order them from the same
California company Hege uses.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the price tag could hit $10,000. That's because each
inmate has 15 uniforms _ five in his locker, five in the laundry
and five spares in storage. Add to that the range of sizes needed
and ``it can become an expensive proposition,'' said Gregg Stahl,
assistant state correction secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Correction officials are wondering where to find the money, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hege, who made headlines several years ago after painting county
jail cells pink with teddy bear trim, argues that state officials
could easily come up with $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Since Republicans no longer control the House, Rand's bill has a
good chance of passing, said Dockham. ``It is kind of frustrating
to get something done and then six months later wait to have it
undone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCrary, who oversees public-safety spending in the House,
doesn't think much of striped uniforms. But since Hege and his
stripes are popular in Davidson County, McCrary isn't lobbying for
Rand's bill.
</P>
<P>
   State correction officials now require minimum-custody inmates
to wear green uniforms and medium- and close-custody inmates to
dress in brown. They say allowing striped uniforms for state
inmates in one county could be a Pandora's box in a state with 100
counties.
</P>
<P>
   The department also maintains that inmates in a county jail, who
are typically behind bars for 90 days or fewer, should be treated
differently from state prisoners, some of whom have been
incarcerated for years and have been promoted to minimum security
road crews and community work squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we view striped uniforms as being helpful in
preparing an inmate to return to the community,'' Stahl said. ``The
inmates don't like it. We expect we'll have some work stoppages and
interruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   In his push to get lawmakers to require stripes for state
inmates, Hege had in his arsenal color photos of a Davidson County
woman beaten by an escaped inmate who persuaded her to let him use
her phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had been in stripes, she would have gone into her house
and locked the door,'' said Hege, first elected in 1994. He's had
no escapes from jail or work crews in two years _ thanks, he said,
to stripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look like a zebra out there,'' he said. ``You can't
hide.''
</P>
<P>
   (Kirsten Mitchell is Raleigh, N.C., bureau chief for the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
