<HEADER>
A9580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-51     04-07 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WRETCHED ALBANIAN CAMPS, KOSOVARS SHARE HORROR STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS,
KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO) 
(kd) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ The Hader family of Kosovo held a pathetic
picnic Wednesday. They ground a plastic beach umbrella into a field
of rubble, laid down their coats like blankets over the rocks, and
sat single file sharing their last bottle of water and their final,
stale loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a new tent city was already packed, and the
sign on its gate directed newly arrived refugees to the next town.
But like many others, the Haders were too exhausted to keep going
so they parked their tractor in an empty lot, creating their own
makeshift refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like a sip?'' Mehmed Hader, 34, asked, extending the
water bottle. Then he pulled it back. ``No, I'm sorry. I cannot
afford to be polite. I will save your sip so later we can wash
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Albania's stark, mountainous countryside is dotted with the
wrenching images of a displaced population. The official camps and
even the unofficial ones are safe zones for the ethnic Albanians
who fled for their lives from their villages in Kosovo. But to
outsiders they look like horrific limbo zones for refugees who are
too numb to be anxious about the future.
</P>
<P>
   At the gates of the camp here, a small boy slept fitfully on a
filthy blanket Wednesday, occasionally reaching out a dirt-caked
hand for bread crumbs and stuffing them into his mouth. It was a
chilling sight.
</P>
<P>
   Many first-time visitors to the camps, even if they have
followed the exodus on television, lose their emotional grip when
they first take in the scope and detail of the situation. One macho
young man, an Albanian immigrant from Queens, thought he was
prepared, but ended up Wednesday with his head between his knees,
crying and retching.
</P>
<P>
   Albania's rutted roads wind through an almost lunar landscape,
dotted with skeletons _ shells of gutted cars, frames of half-built
houses and frail scarecrows guarding shaggy fields. But Albania,
the poorest country in Europe, is for the moment a verdant jewel to
the quarter of a million refugees who have landed here since the
Serbs began driving them from Kosovo in retaliation for NATO's
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is a striking irony that this small country, whose
limitations have pushed so many Albanians to emigrate, finds itself
the save haven for a wave of grateful refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not our home,'' said Selim Nivokazi, who stood outside a
crisp green tent in the official camp here. ``But right now it is
beautiful to us. We go knocking on doors with our empty bottles,
and the people give us water and make us welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Their flight is far too recent for the refugees to feel bored by
empty days that stretch before them like giant question marks. Even
the children do not yet seem restless; those who are not too tired
or weak play marbles between the tents while their parents trade
horror stories with other refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our six-year-old son, they held a knife to his throat,'' one
woman, Nivokazi's cousin, said, lifting the boy's neck to show
where the blade sat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father, an old man, they hit his eye with the butt of a
gun,'' another woman answered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Italian relief workers who set up the five-day old refugee
camp here, some 30 miles north of Tirana, quickly found themselves
in the uncomfortable situation of turning their back on those they
could not accommodate. They had to post guards at the gate, and
issue small pink tickets to refugees who wanted to leave _ and
return _ to the compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 220 tents, and as soon as we put one up, it was filled
with people,'' said Marco Agnoloni, who is running the relief
effort for the Italian Government. ``At night, we took the little
kids standing outside the gate and squeezed them into tents. Now we
are set to open another site, about 5 kilometers down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees arrive directly here from the border, while others
come from Tirana, after they are kicked out of the ``Sports
Palace,'' which was meant to be a soup kitchen but turned into a
kind of transit camp for elderly and disabled refugees. An indoor
arena, the gymnasium floor is carpeted with bare mattresses, and in
the bleachers, refugees stare listlessly at those lucky enough to
be stretched out on them.
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, the loudspeaker announces that a local
resident is offering a room, and Kosovar refugees rush down to
appeal for the lodging. Some hoteliers have turned over all their
empty rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In the countryside, Idris Cruziery, who is 34 but looks 50,
looked all day Wednesday for someone so generous but could find
only rental rooms that he could not afford. He returned to the
rubble lot here defeated, but the faces of his family members lit
up: he had a bag with bread and sausage.
</P>
<P>
   In the lot, the Cruziery family _ and cousins _ has been living
in the uncovered wagon behind their tractor, which in Kosovo they
used for transporting animals. There are 20 of them, and at night
they sleep like spoons, holding each other for warmth. The children
cough and cry until the darkness lifts. For five days, they have
not left the wagon, except to use the rubble as a bathroom; there
is not even a scrubby bush to hide behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only wonder how long we will survive like this,'' said
one of the cousins, Floria Masraka. ``We don't know what to do
except wait for someone to come and tell us what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Masraka's 85-year-old grandmother, a brown scarf tied at
her chin, cried out, ``Is there a God?''
</P>
<P>
   No one answered her, but her great-granddaughter said, ``Look,
an ice cream man!''
</P>
<P>
   Operating out of a supermarket cart, a local entrepreneur was
scooping out cones for the refugee children, many of whom still
wore the pajamas and slippers they had fallen asleep in on the
night they were chased from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The man was selling them: 10 cents each, a special deal, he
said, because he felt bad for the Kosovar people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
