<HEADER>
A9583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-KEUHNE-BOS &LR;      04-07 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-KEUHNE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEUHHNE TEARING UP THE COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The foursome was fulsome. The last two Masters
champions were matched against the reigning United States and
British amateur champions: Mark O'Meara and Tiger Woods vs. Hank
Kuehne and Spain's Sergio Garcia. For fun, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely. For lots of fun.
</P>
<P>
   It was their last practice round before Thursday's Masters gets
under way, and, to make the walk through the piney woods even here
more interesting, the pros matched themselves up against the
amateurs. And, if the scores were counted, it was no contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great match and it was very good fun,'' the
19-year-old Garcia (the fame of his game in Spain vibrant enough to
call him the next Seve Ballesteros) said at day's end. ``Ahhh . . .
but they beat us. It was amazing. We couldn't win a hole and I
think we made like six or seven birdies in four-ball, Hank and
myself, and we didn't win a hole. I find it all amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But if scores were not counted, the day belonged to the
amateurs. For one, none other than Jack Nicklaus himself scooted up
to them on the 15th fairway on his golf cart. Nicklaus, recovering
from hip replacement surgery, wanted to have a friendly word or two
with the whole foursome, but particularly to these amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the rumors of what Texan Hank Kuehne had done off the
13th tee already were filtering back from Amen Corner to the
clubhouse, and Nicklaus had just seen for himself what Kuehne had
done off the tee on the par-5, 500-yard 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a fellow play a driver to wedge in there,'' Nicklaus
said later in his annual State of Golfdom address to the media.
``Driver to wedge!''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus said he asked Kuehne whether it was a pitching wedge or
a sand wedge.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Oh, it was a pitching wedge.' '' marveled Nicklaus at
Kuehne's response. ``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Garcia nor Kuehne had a clue that Nicklaus would be in
Augusta, let alone on Augusta National, this week ``and it was such
a surprise when he came up to talk to us,'' said Garcia, still
thrilled at the recollection. ``He talked to us and asked us a few
questions and wished us to have a nice week.''
</P>
<P>
   And Nicklaus could not stop bringing up up Kuehne, the
23-year-old senior at Southern Methodist University. When talking
about the changes this year to the course, Nicklaus paused in
mid-thought to marvel once again, ``Incidentally, Kuehne knocked it
right over the top (of the trees) at 13. You're going to have to
buy Augusta Country Club (which adjoins the 5th, 11th, 12th, and
13th holes of Augusta National) and move (the 13th tee) back.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus did not see what happened at the 13th tee, but for
those who did, adjectives flowed. And those who heard what
transpired on the 13th tee only added to the ballooning of the Hank
Kuehne Tale.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Garcia each had taken out their drivers and each had
caught the trees that line the left edge of the 485-yard hole.
``And when it was Hank's turn,'' said Garcia, ``Mark (O'Meara) was
saying, `See those pine trees there. Aww, you can hit it over those
pine trees. Try.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Few golfers attempt this dangerous shot. And, most likely,
Kuehne will not try it once competition begins this morning, but
the amateur pulled out his driver, let loose and his ball flew the
trees and landed far down the left edge of the fairway, no more
than a wedge _ maybe 100 yards _ to the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Woods and O'Meara) were kind of joking about it on the tee,''
said Kuehne. ``They were saying, `Knock it over the gap in those
trees.' There's like a little gap there. So I did and I knocked it
over. And they said, `You're supposed to try and hit it over there,
but you're not supposed to be able to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So the ball ended 100 yards from the green?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like 105,'' said Kuehne. ``It would have been a
wedge.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Kuehne's drive was 100 yards farther than O'Meara's,
70 longer than Garcia's, and 60 beyond Woods's. But Kuehne picked
up the ball, played his other practice shot off the tee _ a safe
3-wood to the middle of the fairway _ and flung the ball to the
gallery, which cheered wildly. The crowd began spreading the word
anew that Woods and John Daly might have the reputation but Kuehne
is the one who can drive the ball farther than any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Woods and Kuehne had had a he-man contest off the eighth tee,
the 550-yard par 5 that is perfectly suited for a show of strength.
The fairway is wider than the Savannah River that flows nearby.
Kuehne outdrove Woods by about 25 yards, ``and that was decent,''
said Kuehne. ``That was a decent tee shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, recounted Kuehne, ``had hit his drive pretty good, and I
was just trying to keep my drive up there but I hit it just a hair
thin. I was just trying to keep it in the fairway, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, good enough to top Woods by 25 yards. ``Naww, it was about
20,'' said Kuehne. ``I pretty much hit it all day long 5 yards, 10
yards by him. Then, on 15, I really got that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne hits his tee shots so far that Augusta National officals
had to shut him off on the practice tee Monday. A huge screen, 50
feet or higher, some 285 yards from the practice tees, protects
cars along Washington Road from being pelted with golf balls.
Kuehne's drives were going over the screen so often that he was
told to pull back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made me quit hitting,'' said Kuehne, who'll be playing in
his first Masters. ``So I can't even hit one hard the rest of the
week (off the practice tee).''
</P>
<P>
   As much as his tee shots, Kuehne's personal story once bore a
budding _ and baleful _ resemblance to that of Daly, the huge
hitter who has struggled with alcoholism. Kuehne began his golf
career at Oklahoma State, but was an alcoholic by the end of his
teens, drinking as much as a fifth of whiskey a day with many a
beer for chasers. He was involved in an automobile accident in
Stillwater, Okla., in February 1995 that broke some of his ribs and
injured another person.
</P>
<P>
   He spent time at a rehabilitation clinic in Hazleton, Minn.,
transferred to SMU from Oklahoma State, and reportedly has been
sober since his accident four years ago. Golf buffs are well aware
of the Kuehne family line. His sister Kelli, a two-time US Women's
Amateur champion, is on the LPGA Tour and his brother Trip lost in
that famous US Amateur title match to the charging-from-behind
Woods four years ago. Trip is Hank's caddie here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank's drive there on 15 was so long,'' said Garcia, ``but he
needs to hit them a little shorter and a little straight.''
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent college golf tourney, Kuehne went 81-76-76 in
the Morris Williams Tournament in Austin, Texas, three weeks ago,
taking a horrendous 36 putts in the round of 81. And putting, not
driving, is the magic elixir at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   But the loosey-goosey, ever-smiling, ever-laughing Kuehne will
have many an eye on him when he tees it up Thursday. And drives the
ball far, very far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1840EDT &QL; 
