<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9592 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGIOUS-DESTINY-NYT     04-07 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-DESTINY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGSLAVIA'S DANGEROUS MIX OF RELIGION, POLITICS AND MANIFEST
DESTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    During the Easter service at our Episcopal parish, my
17-month-old daughter escaped from our pew. Emma ran up and down
the aisle waving at each stained glass window and babbled happily,
``Hi Jesus! Hi Jesus!''
 &HT;    Her exuberance over the resurrection prompted giggles from even
the most stodgy of our fellow parishioners.
 &HT;    When her father returned her to her seat, she was still chatting
with Jesus in the windows. How does she know that is Jesus? Elmo
and Tinky Winky I can understand --they have videos. But Jesus?
 &HT;    Nearly every Sunday since she was born, Emma has attended church
and was baptized at three months. No wonder she recognizes Jesus.
She has heard about him her whole life.
 &HT;    When it comes to religion, some theologians have argued that
``geography is destiny.'' If you are born in a Christian country,
you will most likely be a Christian. An Islamic one, a Muslim. A
Buddhist nation, a Buddhist. And so for Emma: born of Protestant
parents in the United States, she is being shaped by Christianity.
 &HT;    In spite of growing multiculturalism, the major world religions
still dominate much the same geographical territory as in previous
centuries: Christianity dominates Europe and the Americas; Islam
holds the Middle East and North Africa; Hinduism, south Asia;
Buddhism, southeastern and eastern Asia.
 &HT;    The major regional shifts have been three: the decline of tribal
religions in South America and southern Africa, the creation of
Israel as a Jewish nation, and increased religious pluralism in
urbanized areas across the globe.
 &HT;    Historically, conflict occurs where religious regions touch.
Border areas between faiths are places of intense rivalry and
warfare. Religion gets mixed up with politics, manifest destiny and
nationalism. In these cases, religion justifies, and sometimes
creates, the conditions for violence.
 &HT;    So it is in Yugoslavia. Three historic religions meet in this
small area -- Roman Catholic western Europe, Eastern Orthodox
southern Europe and Russia, and the Islamic Mediterranean. For 2000
years, this area has traded political hands as a crossroads of
three great world religions.
 &HT;    The current conflict between Serbia and its neighbors comes as
no surprise. The Serbs are Orthodox; the Croatians, Roman Catholic;
and the Kosovo Albanians, Muslim. According to conventional wisdom,
religious conflict is inevitable -- maybe even a defect of Balkan
religious fanaticism.
 &HT;    But Yugoslavia has often defied conventional wisdom. The people
of the Balkans, the southern Slavs, have not always been at war.
They have experienced extended periods of multireligious
cooperation. For centuries, Catholic and Orthodox churches existed
alongside Islamic mosques and created a unique European religious
society long before contemporary multiculturalism.
 &HT;    Unlike their northern European neighbors, who lived in
religiously isolated nations, the Slavs learned to live with
difference. For them, geography meant a destiny of religious
pluralism -- but not necessarily conflict.
 &HT;    On occasion, pluralism resulted in conflict. Balkan
multiculturalism failed when one of the religious cultures asserted
itself against the others. But when Catholic, Orthodox, and Islamic
parties shared power or when an outside group (such as the Ottomans
or the Communists) enforced religious balance, the groups at least
tolerated each other.
 &HT;    Beginning in 1989, ascendant Serbs upset this balance. Serbia
reinvented itself as the persecuted embodiment of Christ and their
Muslim neighbors as ``Christ killers.'' They pursued a policy of
``ethnic cleansing,'' a euphemism for an Orthodox Holy War against
Islam. Militarily strong enough to enforce this program, Serbia
began to ``purify'' their society of religious undesirables and
consolidate national power.
 &HT;    Steeped in our own religious prejudices, the United States and
Europe have been slow to act in the Balkans -- clearly reluctant to
defend Muslims and condemn their Christian oppressors. However,
with this NATO action, the historic Roman Catholic and Protestant
western countries have finally sided with Muslims against the
Orthodox Serbs.
 &HT;    Not since the Crusades has a western Christian alliance
conducted such an intense military campaign -- with such overt
moral and religious overtones -- against an Eastern Orthodox
country. Pleas from Yugoslavia to stop the bombing during Eastern
Orthodox Holy Week (coming one week later than western
Christianity) met with even less sympathy than pleas from Iraq to
stop bombing their nation during Ramadan.
 &HT;    As a Christian, I grieve for innocent Serbians suffering during
this holy time. I do not, however, grieve for their guilty leaders
who, in a perversion of Orthodox Christianity, have murdered their
neighbors. While the bombs fall, I pray for the Yugoslavia that
once existed: a place where people of many faiths lived as
neighbors. If that multireligious culture is completely destroyed,
its ruins stand as a sad warning to all of us. Perhaps from the
ashes of Belgrade, we might yet see the resurrection.
 &HT;    I hope so. With religious multiculturalism increasing around the
world, Yugoslavian geography -- for good or for ill -- might be
destiny for us all.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
