<HEADER>
A9594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RWANDA-BURIAL-ART-NYT     04-07 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-BURIAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORING VICTIMS OF THE RWANDAN BLOOD BATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIBEHO, Rwanda _ The floor of the church is now covered with
moss. The burnt-out roof is open to the sky, and in a macabre
memorial just down the hill, the corpses of people who died are now
mummified, lying twisted on shelves, some with rosaries around
their necks.
</P>
<P>
   It was five years ago Wednesday that thousands of Tutsi, one of
two major ethnic groups in Rwanda, gathered at the church here,
afraid of bands of Hutu who had begun an attempt at genocide. In
100 days, more than 500,000 Tutsi died around Rwanda, several
thousand of them here.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the leaders of Rwanda came here to give some of
the dead a proper burial, in the biggest of several memorial
services around the nation. Corpses were placed into coffins draped
with purple cloth and interred in four brick-lined pits, the same
pits where the bodies were buried by their killers five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's respect we are giving them,'' said Selestin Ntubwiriza,
50, a farmer who hid at the church in April 1994 and escaped. His
two wives and nine children did not survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just leave our sisters and brothers where they were
scattered,'' he said. ``It's also a lesson to those who did it
never to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kibeho was one of hundreds of places around the country where
well-organized bands of Hutu militia attacked their Tutsi
neighbors, mostly hacking them to death. But Kibeho holds a
distinct place in the lore of the genocide. Since the late 1970s,
villagers say they have seen apparitions of the Virgin Mary near a
soccer field on a hilltop.
</P>
<P>
   Before the genocide, the Virgin, believers say, predicted that
the hills would flow with blood. A month afterward, it was reported
on radio around Rwanda that the Virgin Mary had appeared to claim
Rwanda's Hutu President, Juvenal Habyarimana, who died when his
plane was shot down.
</P>
<P>
   The radio report was interpreted as an attempt by the Hutu
government to justify the killings. The Virgin never appeared
again, villagers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why,'' said Innocent Ruganintwari, 42, who
survived the church massacres. ``Maybe it's because so much blood
was spilled here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kibeho is also where, in April 1995, Tutsi-led government troops
cleared a huge refugee camp they claimed was full of Hutu
extremists. Human rights officials say that at least 4,000 Hutu
were killed, many shot and many trampled.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official mention of that incident Wednesday, but
President Pasteur Bizimungu told a crowd of several thousand people
that Rwandans must unite against ``injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must come together to say no to another genocide,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bizimungu raised the issue of NATO airstrikes against
Yugoslavia, asking the difference between the ``ethnic cleansing''
of Kosovo Albanians and the eradication of one group of Rwandans
because of their ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Rwanda remain bitter that outside nations did nothing to
stop the killings in 1994, and Bizimungu used that failure to
justify Rwanda's intervention in the war in Congo, where remnants
of Hutu militias are fighting on the side of Congo's president,
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outsiders, especially Europeans, ask us what we are doing in
Congo,'' he said. ``But I tell you, those who started the genocide,
most of them are in the Congo. Most of those who killed are in
Congo.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was mostly Tutsi, but one of the men who helped lower
the coffins into the graves was a Hutu hotel worker, Kome
Rukeribuga. He jumped down into the pits, still covered with the
clothes of the dead, along with the others to settle the coffins
into their resting place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the families respect,'' he said. ``The way these
people were killed, they were chopped up and put into these
holes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
