<HEADER>
A9596 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     04-07 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROPER CREDITS FOR A FILM FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Help settle an argument: Were the Warner brothers really
brothers? _ S.P., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Warner Bros., now part of Time-Warner, was founded by
siblings Albert, Harry, Jack and Sam Warner in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Warner died in 1927 only hours before the studio released
``The Jazz Singer,'' the first film with synchronized dialogue and
music.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. became a major studio with the introduction of
talking pictures, producing 100 films a year in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   After his brothers retired, Jack Warner became company president
in 1956 and was actively working in production until 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Warner wasn't the family's birth name: The father, Benjamin
Eichelbaum, emigrated from Poland in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the song lyric ``aba daba daba daba daba daba daba
said the monkey to the chimp'' come from? _ V.T., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: That's from ``Aba Daba Honeymoon,'' a 1914 song by Arthur
Fields and Walter Donovan that has been used in several movies.
</P>
<P>
   The popular vaudeville song appears in 1930's ``King of Jazz.''
Composer Saul Chaplin remembered the song 20 years later, turning
it into a duet for Debbie Reynolds and Carleton Carpenter in ``Two
Weeks With Love.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the lyrics, ``aba daba daba'' means either ``monk I
love but you'' or ``chimp I love you too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aba Daba Honeymoon'' is included on several song compilations:
``Best of Debbie Reynolds, Top Movie Hits _ 1950-1954'' and
``Golden Age of Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I send a letter to Yankees manager Joe Torre? _
L.A.O., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Torre in care of the New York Yankees, Yankee
Stadium, Bronx, NY 10451.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, 58, took a leave of absence from the team in March for
treatment of prostate cancer. His illness was discovered during
team-mandated tests that followed Yankees player Darryl
Strawberry's colon cancer diagnosis in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, Torre has led the Yankees to a 302-184 record
and two World Series championships. He previously managed the New
York Mets, Atlanta Braves and St. Louis Cardinals.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
