<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AARON-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      04-07 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AARON-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGING EDITORS, SPORTS EDITORS, WIRE EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls to your attention a
package of stories from  &UR; Cox News Service &LR;  marking the 25th
anniversary of Hank Aaron's home run record.
</P>
<P>
   On April 8, 1974, in Atlanta, his home stadium, Aaron hit his
715th home run, to pass Babe Ruth as baseball's all-time greatest
home run hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The stories recount Aaron's career and his life since retiring
from the Braves, recall the national fascination leading up to his
record and tell what has become of the ball, bat and uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are accompanied by photos, including a recent color
portrait, which are available to subscribers to the New York Times
News Service photo and graphic service (nonsubscribers can arrange
for special purchases by calling (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories, moving tonight for publication Thursday
and thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HANK-CHASE (Atlanta) _ Those who were around 25 years ago
during Hank Aaron's chase of Babe Ruth's all-time HR record try to
describe how that event would have been different had it taken
place today. (Rosen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED (Originally moved last week as part of Cox's baseball
preview.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HANK-BALL (Atlanta) _ The ball, the bat, the uniform from
Hank Aaron's chase of Ruth. Where are they and what would they be
worth on today's memorabilia market? (Rosen, Atlanta
Journal-Constituion). MOVED (Originally moved last week as part of
Cox's baseball preview.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HANK-HAMMER (Atlanta) _ The Transformation of the Hammer: He
has gone from apolitical, backwoods superstar to star-crossed
middle-aged activist to the senior statesman of baseball. The Hank
Aaron that will be honored tonight on the 25th anniversary of his
career home-run record is a kindler, gentler Aaron, who has been
portrayed in any number of ways. (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-HANK-BUSINESSES (Atlanta) _ Hank Aaron is expanding his
outside business interests. Already the owner of several Church's
Fried Chicken stores, he's also opening a BMW dealership. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BBOP-HANK-LIST (Undated) _ Hank Aaron's home-run list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
