<HEADER>
A9598 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAYERS-FORKOSOVO-TEX     04-07 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAYERS-FORKOSOVO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL WE EVER LEARN? RELIGIOUS LEADERS PRAY FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Compiled by TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HEALING OF FORGIVENESS
</P>
<P>
   Fear, revenge, jealousy, anger, prejudice. Lord God, these human
dispositions brought Jesus to the cross and to his death. They
stoke the flames of violence and destroy the bonds that would draw
mankind together today. The players are different, but the scene
appears painfully familiar: power threatened by a challenge to its
authority and a critique of its methods, and the consequence _ one
people stirred up against another to eliminate the threat. When, Oh
God, will we ever learn?
</P>
<P>
   Memories and imagination. They are the excuses that justify
human behavior that could bring peoples together for peace. Why do
we so easily hold onto hurts caused generations and centuries ago
and fail to recall the forgiveness extended to us by a God who
forgets our evil at a word? Serbs and Muslims. Whites and blacks.
North and South. Jews and Christians. Arabs and Israelis. Catholics
and Protestants. Will we ever learn, Oh God?
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, God, you created us as one people. We
disobeyed you and went our own way. You sent prophets and plagues
to remind us of our inability. You sent your Son to show us how to
reconcile and live in peace. We continue to forget the good offered
to us by you as we refuse to forget the evils done to us by others.
We cannot heal ourselves. We cannot resolve our differences by
force or violence. Unless we turn to you, however we understand
you, all this destruction will continue. Have mercy on us, Oh God,
and do to us what we cannot do to ourselves. Heal our memories.
Soothe our pains, and make us once more a people to give you praise
and serve each other in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Charles B. King
</P>
<P>
   Pastor, St. John the Apostle Catholic Church
</P>
<P>
   North Richland Hills, Texas
</P>
<P>
   DIGNITY FOR ALL GOD'S CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   Oh God, recalling the exodus from Egypt at this season of
Passover, we pray for freedom and dignity for all your children
everywhere. This year especially we pray for those who suffer in
and around Kosovo. May they soon, once again, know peace.
</P>
<P>
   As our ancestors reached the far shores of the sea and the
waters closed over the Egyptians, according to Jewish lore, the
heavenly hosts burst into song. You chastised them: ``My children
are drowning, and you sing praises?'' We cannot rejoice, Oh Lord,
as the bombs fall. Yet we know that liberty and human dignity must
be fought for, and that if no one stands up against evil, evil
triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Master of history, too often otherwise decent people have said
little and done less as innocent populations have been slaughtered.
The Holocaust still haunts our dreams. We rejoice that this time in
Kosovo, America and its NATO allies have had the courage and
fortitude to stand against ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Be with our American soldiers and their allies. Return them to
our homes and loved ones safely. Fill the hearts of refugees and
innocent victims on all sides with strength and hope, but confound
the plans of those who plot evil.
</P>
<P>
   May the day come speedily when peoples of every religion, race
and nation will learn to live together in mutual respect. Then
shall you reign in justice, peace and love. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Ralph Mecklenburger
</P>
<P>
   Beth-El Congregation
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   SHOWER MERCY ON KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   All praise be to Allah, the cherisher and sustainer of worlds.
Most gracious. Most merciful. Master of the day of judgment. You
alone we worship and you alone we seek for help. Guide us to the
straight path, the path of those on whom you have bestowed your
grace, those whose portion is not wrath, and who go not astray.
Amen.
</P>
<P>
   There is no god but Allah. To him belongs all sovereignty and
praise. Oh Allah, none can prevent what you have willed to bestow
and none can bestow what you have willed to prevent. Oh Allah, it
is your mercy that we hope for. We place you before our enemies and
take refuge in you from their evils. Oh Allah, you're our support
and helper. Protect us from all evils and guide us in all our
endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Oh Allah, there is no ease except that which you make easy. Oh
Allah, make easy the affairs of the people of Kosovo and all those
in pain. Relieve them from all their distress and hardship. Give
them patience and assist them to overcome their problems. Shower
your mercy upon them. Oh Allah, recompense them for their
affliction and replace for them whatever they have lost. Answer our
call, for none can assist them except you, the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   Oh Allah, the creator of everything, our Lord, keep the hearts
of the oppressed and the afflicted from deviating from your path
after you have guided them aright. Grant them mercy and love from
your presence. Oh Allah, guide and assist our leaders to serve and
make prudent decisions for truth and justice for all people. All
praise belongs to you, the Lord of all worlds. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Yushau Sodiq
</P>
<P>
   Department of Religion
</P>
<P>
   Texas Christian University
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   SHELTER IN THE TIME OF NEED
</P>
<P>
   Our Father, I lay to you the dilemmas abroad. Father, I know you
have control over everything; I know that you have demonstrated
your awesome power time and time again. Master, we recognize that
in your word it speaks of wars and rumors of wars, but Lord, your
help is desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   My God, we ask for hearts to be touched, minds to be opened, and
love to be expressed through the leadership of NATO and our
country. Our Father, we pray to you to show everyone that there is
a way to solve the problems besetting Kosovo. Show them, God, you
can work it out; you and only you can bring peace.
</P>
<P>
   Now, my Father, many are homeless, without food and fleeing to
safety. I ask that you provide protection for them; be shelter for
them; be a supplier during their time of need.
</P>
<P>
   My God, watch over the troops. See about innocent civilians.
Provide safety for them as well. Now, Father, I know that all
things work together for good, so I leave it all in your care. I
close this prayer knowing that you are a keeper and you will make
everything all right.
</P>
<P>
   This I pray in your Son's name. Amen.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ralph W. Emerson
</P>
<P>
   Pastor, Rising Star Missionary Baptist Church
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth, texas
</P>
<P>
   REPLACING HATRED WITH LOVE
</P>
<P>
   Oh God, our creator, who has placed in us a wondrously ordered
harmony, within which life flourishes, and whose shalom is always a
possibility _ we are deeply saddened and greatly perplexed at the
dominating presence of hatred in your creation.
</P>
<P>
   We are especially aware of the violence in Kosovo and the
destruction that hate brings. We ask your blessing on refugees and
those who work with them, on the peace process and those who seek
to negotiate it.
</P>
<P>
   We pray for the healing of nations, because we know this is your
desire. We know that you hate nothing you have made, and we pray
for us that same spirit of compassion.
</P>
<P>
   I, also, pray for myself, that hatred will be pushed out of my
life by love. My concern for Kosovo must begin with me, so I commit
now to being vigilant against hate in myself. In whatever place I
have an effect, I pledge my life to be an instrument of your peace.
Amen.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard P. Lord
</P>
<P>
   Pastor
</P>
<P>
   Rush Creek Christian Church
</P>
<P>
   Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
