<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMPER CRANBERRY CROP DEALS OCEAN SPRAY A SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Wis., Mich., Ore.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Back-to-back surplus harvests have taken a toll on the
country's cranberry industry, driving down prices nationwide and
leading to another round of layoffs locally.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. said Wednesday it plans to cut 100
jobs at its Lakeville headquarters by the end of the month, the
latest sign the cranberry business is in turmoil. At a time when
surplus harvests have driven down prices for the entire industry,
The layoff is the grower cooperative's third since mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, those three layoffs will downsize Ocean Spray's
work force by 500 jobs, 335 of which are in Massachusetts
operations. Two years ago, Ocean Spray employed 2,600 workers.
</P>
<P>
   When its latest round of cuts goes into effect, Ocean Spray will
employ 1,900 workers, including 600 at its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Another 200 jobs have been eliminated through attrition and
early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, the second-largest cranberry growing state behind
Wisconsin, is estimated to employ 5,500 workers in the cranberry
industry; they earn a total of about $200 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in memory, Ocean Spray has also suspended
1999 redemption payments to some growers looking to cash out Ocean
Spray stock. That decision has hurt some older growers who were
counting on the payments to help finance retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's illegal, but I think it's immoral,'' said
Cape Cod cranberry grower Dave McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Growers who belong to the cooperative are required to buy stock.
Traditionally, when growers leave the cooperative, Ocean Spray buys
back the stock over five years in annual installments. It is a
tradition that regrettably and temporarily has to be suspended due
to tough times, said Ocean Spray, which claims to be under no legal
obligation to make payments within a certain time frame.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, 60, said he expected to receive a check for nearly
$45,000 from Ocean Spray on Feb. 28, but on Feb. 27 he learned he
would not receive a check this year.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years as an Ocean Spray grower, McCarthy left the
cooperative in 1995. He said he is still owed about $135,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray president and chief executive Thomas E. Bullock
defended the austerity measures as necessary for Ocean Spray to
survive a difficult period and to retool itself to adjust to a
highly competitive marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of cranberries has dropped like a rock,'' said
Bullock, who added: ``A lot of people are upset. It's a tough time
for the cranberry industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Ocean Spray's market share of the supermarket
juice aisle dropped from 70 to 60 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, record harvests have hurt an entire industry.
Basically, North American growers have been harvesting about 7
million barrels of cranberries per year for the last two years, but
consumers are eating or drinking only about 5 million barrels'
worth of cranberry products, said David Farrimond, executive
director of the Cranberry Marketing Committee, a part of the US
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``A surplus is a farmer's worst nightmare,'' said John Decas,
president of Decas Cranberry Co. in Wareham. ``There are just too
many damn berries.''
</P>
<P>
   Growers harvest cranberries in 100-pound barrels. In 1996, some
growers earned as much as $85 a barrel. For berries that will be
harvested this fall, barrel prices could fall to between $42 and
$48, or even lower.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Ocean Spray formed in 1930 was to protect growers
from volatile price fluctuations that affect many other crops. By
setting a yearly barrel price, the cooperative looks to smooth out
a feast-or-famine cycle for growers.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, Ocean Spray has also had great success
in marketing the cranberry. There were ad campaigns with themes
like ``Crave the wave,'' and scientific studies that claimed
cranberries were good for some women with bladder complaints.
Together, these efforts transformed a Thanksgiving condiment into
the makings of a popular juice drink.
</P>
<P>
   But in creating demand for the cranberry, Ocean Spray may also
have created rivals who saw a bonanza in fruit drinks.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, after a drought shrank demand and sent
prices soaring, many farmers in Quebec turned to the cranberry.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray also saw competition from Northland Cranberries Inc.
of Wisconsin, the first publicly traded cranberry company.
</P>
<P>
   (Amid tough times, Northland has seen its stock take a beating
in the last year. Shares have dropped from just above 19 last May
to 7 Wednesday, near a 52-week low.)
</P>
<P>
   With all that surplus, Ocean Spray can be underpriced by
supermarket store brands at the same time it feels the squeeze from
juice brands owned by big conglomerates such as Coca-Cola Co.
(Minute Maid) and PepsiCo Inc. (Tropicana).
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a 64-ounce bottle of cranberry juice could sell in a
supermarket for about $2.48; now those same bottles can be two for
$3, said Farrimond of the Cranberry Marketing Committee.
</P>
<P>
   One might think consumers would now see cranberry juice as a
bargain, but lower prices haven't increased consumption, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the surge in sales of juice drinks in the early 1990s,
consumption has leveled off, added Gary A. Hemphill, vice president
of Beverage Marketing Corp., a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps consumers prefer something else at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Ocean Spray doesn't compete just with other cranberry
companies, but with almost anyone who sells beverages _ from orange
juice to soda to iced tea and bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year that ended Aug. 31, Ocean Spray reported
sales of $1.48 billion, an increase of 3 percent. Proceeds, the
word that cooperatives use for profits, were $280 million, up from
$273 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray warned that troubles in the cranberry industry could
hurt proceeds for the current fiscal year _ and this at a time when
Ocean Spray is looking for a new distributor to deliver its
single-serve products to convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the fiscal year, 808 cranberry growers and 121
grapefruit growers belonged to the co-op, Ocean Spray said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ocean Spray remains bullish on the cranberry.
</P>
<P>
   It thinks sales overseas will continue to grow and that once
Ocean Spray becomes leaner and more focused, it will regain
momentum when cranberry prices stabilize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be optimistic,'' president Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   No severance package has yet been formulated for the Ocean Spray
workers who will lose their jobs, but a spokesman said, ``We treat
people fairly and with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it could be a year of hardship for many in the business.
David Gradt of Bandon, Ore., may be a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   A retired grower, Gradt said he lost a loan application for a
new home recently because Ocean Spray didn't send him a redemption
payment he expected to receive for the stock he accumulated over
his 18 years as an Ocean Spray co-op member.
</P>
<P>
   Gradt said he has heart trouble and was looking to move closer
to his cardiologist in Portland, nearly 300 miles away. But without
the money he was counting on from Ocean Spray, he said couldn't buy
a new house. Gradt, 59, said he continues to live on the cranberry
farm he has already sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not only out the Ocean Spray money, but we're out the
rent we're paying on the house we once owned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of troubles in the cranberry industry, ``a one-year
hiatus'' on Ocean Spray's stock-redemption payments is a
regrettable necessity, Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, the Cape Cod grower, estimated that there are about 55
growers in the same fix as he and Gradt find themselves. Will they
receive a check from Ocean Spray next year? they wonder. And why
should they take a hit when Ocean Spray's proceeds _ or profits _
have risen for its last three fiscal years?
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen next year, I don't know,'' Bullock said when
asked when growers such as McCarthy and Gradt can expect to receive
payment for their stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
