<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-613     04-07 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-613&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO FIRES ON SERB FORCES IN MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS,
KOSOVO-POLL) 
(kd) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ After a week without air attacks here,
NATO warplanes fired on a Yugoslav army missile battery in this
tiny Yugoslav republic on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The attack came after a Yugoslav army missile was fired at NATO
airplanes that were flying over the republic on the way to bombing
runs in neighboring Kosovo, according to a State Department
official in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the pro-Western Montenegrin government Wednesday
agreed with Washington's version of events, saying that NATO had
hit four military targets near the capital, causing no civilian
casualties and no significant damage to civilian property. The
officials said NATO planes launched missiles and bombs after they
came under fire from Yugoslav army anti-aircraft weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav 2nd Army in Montenegro, which is loyal to the
regime of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and has about
12,000 troops here, announced that NATO's missiles and bombs were
aimed at civilian targets in the city. The twisted metal remains of
what appeared, by its English language markings, to be a NATO
missile were seen by Western reporters in a residential
neighborhood in the center of Podgorica on Tuesday night. An
explosion there broke a few windows, but caused no other damage.
</P>
<P>
   The army here did not provide any information on damage to its
facilities, but a State Department official said a Yugoslav missile
launcher was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on Montenegro have caused severe political problems for
President Milo Djukanovic, who was elected in 1997 by promising
voters that a turn to the West would bring Montenegro peace and
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   This poor mountainous republic, with a population of only about
640,000, is part of Yugoslavia, but is split between those who
support Djukanovic's shift to the West and those who believe that
Montenegrins should be loyal to their Serbian Orthodox brothers and
back the Milosevic regime in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombings seem to have tipped the popular balance, for the
moment, at least, against Djukanovic. He and his ministers have
been on the defensive for the past two weeks. After a meeting last
Friday with army generals, government officials here agreed to
major changes in state and private television coverage of the war
in Kosovo. They issued orders that have eliminated nearly all
rebroadcasts of reports from CNN and western TV news networks.
</P>
<P>
   The bombings have also revivified the pro-Milosevic Socialist
People's Party, which was soundly beaten last year in parliamentary
elections. The party Wednesday night staged its fourth consecutive
pro-army, anti-NATO concert here.
</P>
<P>
   After the concert, several thousand noisy supporters of the
pro-Milosevic party, many of them waving a vulgar fictional
obituary of Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, marched from the
city's central square toward nearby government buildings. The crowd
broke up peacefully before reaching the government center.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gelbard, the U.S. special envoy to the former Yugoslavia,
said in a telephone interview from Washington that the Clinton
administration is in regular contact with Djukanovic, explaining to
him why the NATO attacks have occurred on Montenegrin soil and
reassuring him of U.S. support for his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning of this campaign, we knew and we let
Djukanovic know, that there were certain minimal military targets
that we were going to have to hit in Montenegro, and he was well
aware of it,'' Gelbard said. ``The only time that we have actually
targeted ground installations in Montenegro was on the first and
second day of the campaign.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gelbard added that he has told Djukanovic on several occasions,
including during a telephone conversation Wednesday, that while
there are no more planned targets in Montenegro, if missiles are
fired at NATO aircraft or if they are caught in Yugoslav ground
radar, then NATO will respond.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sunday night, Djukanovic said that he had
argued for months with the Americans that a bombing attack on
Yugoslavia would weaken his government and raise the willingness of
pro-Milosevic forces here to try to stage a coup. Djukanovic was
highly critical of Milosevic in the interview, but stopped short of
declaring that he wanted Montenegro to secede from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts here agree that the bombing has firmed up
support for Milosevic and that any referendum on secession would
fail by an overwhelming margin.
</P>
<P>
   A three-member film crew for German television was detained here
on Tuesday night by army forces while filming near an army base
where one of the explosions had set some woods on fire. Five
members of a British television crew, including one American, were
also detained Wednesday by army troops near the Montenegrin town of
Niksic.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin government, in sharp contrast to the authorities
in Belgrade, has welcomed foreign journalists. But the welcome ends
when reporters come across members of the Yugoslav army. Those
troops have detained at least six television crews in the past two
weeks, taking away all their equipment and, in several cases,
taking their cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
