<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9604 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-ELDERLY-VOTERS-2T     04-07 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ELDERLY-VOTERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FLORIDA'S RETIREE NUMBERS DWINDLE, SO DOES DEMOCRATIC VOTING
STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ac) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Their accents have not faded, even after decades in the
Florida sun. It has been years since they worked on the Newark
docks, pressed shirts in New York City or argued with their
delegate in a Brooklyn union hall, but passersby can hear echoes of
Flatbush in Sam's deli in Deerfield Beach, or the Bronx on a
Broward County boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   It is what Democrats sound like.
</P>
<P>
   These blue collar workers, office workers and small business
owners retired to South Florida condominiums during the booms of
the 1960s and 1970s, and brought their machine politics with them.
They used their condo associations and social clubs the way they
once used the meeting halls, synagogues and church basements back
home, shifting from Roosevelt, Truman and Kennedy to Carter and
Clinton, becoming a steady, swelling political force. They voted
religiously, and they voted Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, the Republican Party never did a thing for
you, me, or anybody else of our caliber,'' said Miriam Radow, a
secretary from Brooklyn who retired here in 1976 and became part of
that New Deal Democrat stronghold in northern Miami-Dade and
Broward counties.
</P>
<P>
   But with all their influence, in the State Legislature, in
Washington, in city hall, they never got anyone to build them the
thing they needed most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fountain of Youth,'' said Mrs. Radow.
</P>
<P>
   While their New York and New Jersey accents still buzz in the
cabanas, poker rooms and shuffleboard courts, their political voice
is fading. The New Deal Democrats are dying out, being replaced in
the condominiums by Hispanics, Caribbean blacks, American blacks,
Canadians, European immigrants and younger, working people who
moved here from other parts of the country, said political experts
who have studied the change.
</P>
<P>
   It is more than merely a changing political and social
demographic in communities like Sunrise, Hallandale, Lauderdale
Lakes, Deerfield Beach and other places where most of the New York
area's retirees settled, bringing their socially liberal attitudes
on issues like abortion rights, gun control and taxes. It was these
tens of thousands of loyal condo voters who helped the Democratic
Party to keep electing governors like the late Lawton Chiles as
immigration from Cuba and retirees from more conservative states
made Florida increasingly Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between now and 2010, the Democratic Party will be losing its
most stable and loyal core,'' said Lance de Haven-Smith, a
political science professor at Florida State University who is
associate director of the Florida Institute of Government.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of casting block votes for Democrats, the new condo
residents are either less inclined to vote, cannot vote because
they are not U.S. citizens or, as in the case with Cuban-Americans
who have migrated north from Miami, usually vote Republican, said
Jim Kane, Editor of the Florida Voter, a news service that does
polling and analysis of Florida politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hawaiian Gardens condo, in Lauderdale Lakes in Broward
County, more than 4,000 registered voters, mostly Democrats, once
filled its rooms. But in the past decade, as Canadians and younger
families have moved in, that number of registered voters has fallen
to 2,000, said Kane. Other condos have shown similar shifts in
their makeup, all around this part of Florida, said Kane and others
who have tracked the shift.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past four years, the average age of voters in
Broward County has fallen from 64 to 57, said Kane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that will have an overnight effect on
elections in South Florida,'' said Kane.
</P>
<P>
   But it does signal the end of an era. ``These old people are
primarily from the northeast, retired postal workers, garment
workers, who bought modest condominiums,'' said Kane. ``They were
primarily blue collar, people who had belonged to unions, who had
good pensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would rather vote for the devil himself than vote for a
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   In a special report by the Miami Herald in March, an analysis of
voting in districts dominated by what people here call the ``condo
commandos'' found that, while these older still vote at a higher
percentage than other groups, fewer and fewer elderly residents are
voting in elections. And, the analysis predicted, it is only a
matter of time until those New Deal Democrats are no longer a major
factor in elections here.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts in Florida, and some of the people who make up
that demographic, agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a certain age, you grow infirm, or you go bye-bye,''
said Mrs. Radow, whose own age, she stressed, is nobody's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just say I'm a senior citizen,'' she said, and adds with pride
that she still volunteers during elections, still works the phones
to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees are still coming to South Florida, but they are not the
same generation, or from the same world, as the ones who came south
in the 1960s and 1970s, as Mrs. Radow, or men like David Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin survived three months a German prison camp after he was
captured in the Battle of the Bulge. Voting, to him, is a not just
a right, but a duty. He voted for ideals, not for tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever voted Republican,'' said Goldin, 88, a
widower who lives in Century Village, a condo in Deerfield Beach.
``I'm mad about them now, because of that impeachment. They're just
so _ what's the word? _ partisan.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his living in the garment industry, as a buyer for
retail stores, worked hard and wanted to prolong his life in the
warmth of the Florida sun.
</P>
<P>
   It worked, he said. He feels he added years to his life, and
years to the power of his vote, much to the Florida Republicans
dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics, particularly the Cubans, have been the political
force in Miami-Dade County for years. But in northeastern areas of
that county and in Broward, elderly Democrats stood tall for a
quarter-century. If they went to city council meetings to get a
stoplight at a busy intersection, they got it. Presidential
hopefuls treked to their temples. And unlike the tax-phobic
Midwesterners who retired to the Gulf Coast, they supported new
schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   It was the old South Florida Republicans, who held power here
before the arrival of the New Deal Democrats, who ushered in this
exodus of elderly, more liberal voters. They built the condos that
lured them here.
</P>
<P>
   But their votes were not a resource that could be replenished.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the crown jewels of South Florida politics has long been
the massive Century Village condo in Deerfield Beach, home to as
many as 15,000 people _ the number slips to 12,000 in the
oppressive heat of summers. Most residents are elderly, and
politically active. It has not just one Democrat club, but two.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over that bounty of votes is Amadeo ``Trinchi''
Trinchitella, a retired bar and restaurant owner from New York. No
one gets elected in this part of Florida, everyone here says,
unless first they talk to ``Trinchi.'' The President of the United
States knows him, as have past Presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted Roosevelt, Truman, Kennedy, Democrat all the way,''
said Trinchitella, the condo president and a Deerfield Beach
commissioner who is considered a master at getting out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But he has seen that power base, once in their vibrant 60s,
begin to grow older, more infirm. ``We have fallen 2,500 votes in
the past decade,'' he said. In that decade, half of the condo has
passed away, he said, and he has worked hard to re-fill the
registration rolls with new Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to sit here and cry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trinchitella, 81 years old and recovering from heart surgery,
was too sick to make his usual hard push for votes during a
county-wide referendum on a issue to build new libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Broward averages a 22 percent voter turnout on such elections,
but the bond issue decision drew only 10 percent of voters (the
bond issue was approved). Political experts see that as another
small sign of the waning strength of the older Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A more significant sign was the 1998 Florida Governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in Broward County still vote Democratic, but the
loss of the elderly Democrats can be found in a drop in voter
turnout, said Kane. In the 1994 race for Governor, Lawton Chiles,
the Democrat, beat Jeb Bush, the Republican, and carried the county
with 64 percent, winning 120,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Lieut. Gov. Kenneth H. ``Buddy'' MacKay, who lost the
election to Jeb Bush, carried Broward County with 61 percent, but
with just 83,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one time, condos made up 40 percent of the voting,'' said
Edward Pozzuoli, chairman of the Broward County Republican Party.
He believes that number has slipped to between 25 and 28 percent,
</P>
<P>
   The majority of registered voters between the ages of 35 and 50
are Republican, but overall, Democrats still outnumber Republicans
by 18 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeb Bush tried to target and spend time with seniors, but the
impact of that effort was three or four points, not a lot,'' said
Pozzuoli. ``That takes a lot of effort, so we focused on a younger
population. That's where the county is going _ the issues affecting
young familes.''
</P>
<P>
   Condos that once cost as much as $40,000, two decades ago, are
selling for as little as $16,000, as older residents die out and
leave them to their children, who do not want to retire in this
altered South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``When those families moved here, traffic wasn't that bad,
getting to the grocery store wasn't a problem,'' said Kane. ``All
of that has changed. Now they tend to go to other areas, like the
west coast of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   That means an abundance of cheap housing here for immigrants,
who are moving in and living side by side with the older retirees.
</P>
<P>
   A long drive through South Florida proves that out. Children on
bicycles spin through older people propped up by walkers in
northeastern Dade County. In Wolfie's deli on Miami Beach, Spanish
drowns out the yiddish still being spoken at a table here and
there. From the Miami Beach condos, through Broward and up into
Palm Beach County, condos that were once filled with the elderly
now have baby strollers.
</P>
<P>
   It is a different world from the one the older Democrats made
for themselves here, with the power of their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as if only people my age care about the issues, and
that is ridiculous,'' said Sam Weinstein, 83, who now lives in
Deerfield Beach. ``I vote in ever single election. I started the
time I got back from the service in the F.D.R. days. I feel like
that process is dying, and it saddens me.''
</P>
<P>
   People 20 years younger see the process differently. They have
grown up with political scandal, with candidates who failed them in
many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, I don't go out and vote because I know I am not
going to mame a difference,'' said Guenter Huebschmann, 60, a
registered Democrat living in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are expected, in the long term, to recoup some of
those lost votes, said Trinchitella, and that is something he and
the other older Democrats are working on.
</P>
<P>
   As their own number fade, they recruit Hispanics who disagree
with the Miami Cuban-Americans' conservatism, and try to register
people from other social and economic groups.
</P>
<P>
   And they work hard to keep the elderly voting, even if they have
to vote on walkers or wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't travel much, these days,'' said Goldin, but he can
make it as far as the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   Political activists like Trinchitella refuse to give up, even as
they see familiar faces fade away. ``It's a slow process to catch
up,'' he said. ``I just look to the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
