u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POLL-ART-NYT &LR;      04-07 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST AMERICANS EXPECT YUGOSLAV CONFLICT TO DRAG ON, COST U.S.
LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Hawaii. N.C., Miss., Tenn.)   (With KOSOVO-POLL-BOX on how poll was conducted.)  
(ART ADV: Poll graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO) 
(nk) 
 By R.W. APPLE. Jr. With JANET ELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks into the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia, most
Americans expect the conflict there to drag on for months or years,
to involve the deployment of U.S. ground troops and to cause the
loss of American lives, according to the latest New York Times/CBS
News poll.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Americans support President Clinton's policy in
the conflict between Serbia and Kosovo, the poll shows, with 52
percent expressing approval, 36 percent voicing disapproval and 11
percent unsure. But fewer than a third of the 811 adults
interviewed by telephone on Monday and Tuesday said they thought
the current NATO bombing campaign against the forces of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic would stop ethnic cleansing in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember Vietnam?'' asked Jim Demarco of Dunbar, Pa., who
works for a water-supply company. One of the respondents
interviewed in follow-up sessions after the poll, he insisted,
``You can't do anything with air strikes'' by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Suyama, a retired schoolteacher in Hawaii, reflected the
fatalistic sense that many Americans seem to feel about the events
in Kosovo. An advocate of heavier bombing, she argued that NATO
needed ``to wipe out most of Pristina and Belgrade'' _ the capitals
of Kosovo and of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the bad guy,'' she acknowledged. ``They don't want us
there. We're damned if we do, damned if we don't. It's not worth
the loss of American lives. American soldiers will be mired down
there for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey showed considerable public caution about the
commitment of ground troops, which Clinton has opposed from the
start. Overall, 46 percent of Americans said they favored the use
of ground troops, while 48 percent opposed it. And when given three
options _ sending ground troops, continuing air attacks or pulling
out altogether _ only 21 percent opted for ground troops. If
sending ground troops meant a lot of allied casualties, even fewer
said they would back the use of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Yet majorities of those interviewed in the poll, which has a
margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage points,
expressed the view that any of several goals would justify the
introduction of ground troops. Among them: preventing a widespread
European war, driving Milosevic from power and stopping the further
destruction of ethnic Albanian communities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Backing for ground forces was strongest among those who said
they had been following the fighting most closely, 55 percent, and
is slowly growing among voters in general as the bombing campaign
and the plight of refugees are dramatized on television screens.
That runs counter to the conventional wisdom that TV coverage
undercuts political leaders' ability to expose troops to danger.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Wednesday that he and his allies were ``determined
to stay united and to persist until we prevail.'' Thus far, the
public accepts that strategy, even though it doubts that Milosevic
will buckle soon.
</P>
<P>
   There were only scattered signs in the poll of the isolationism
that many Europeans profess to detect in the United States these
days. Only a little over a third of the public said that this
country lacked responsibility to do anything to help in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But there are danger signs for the president. Asked whether they
had confidence in Clinton's ability ``to deal wisely with an
international crisis,'' respondents split evenly. Forty-seven
percent said they had such confidence, but 48 percent said they
felt uneasy about Clinton. And only 28 percent _ less than a third
_ said they thought the president had a clear plan for Kosovo; most
of the rest said he was just reacting to events.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, four out of 10 voters said the president had still not
explained American policy to their satisfaction, despite repeated
statements, speeches and other comments recently.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also indicates that voters are paying unusually careful
attention to the events in Kosovo. Almost nine Americans in 10 said
they were watching developments there closely or very closely _ an
exceptionally high figure for any foreign-policy subject in the
post-Cold War era. That suggests that many people are in a
watch-and-wait mode, reserving final judgment until the conflict
has evolved further.
</P>
<P>
   If that is indeed the case, overall support for Clinton could
soften rapidly in the face of adverse developments on the ground in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, despite general approval, there is an undercurrent of
nervousness in people's comments about the president, especially
among Republicans. Tina Colbert, a 23-year-old bank worker in
Jefferson City, Tenn., near Knoxville, said she thought ``Americans
get way too involved in other countries' problems, and not enough
with our own.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, she added: ``I don't have a lot of confidence in
Clinton. It makes me wonder about his motives.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Broughman, 47, who runs a cleaning company in Kannapolis,
N.C., and describes herself as a political independent, said she
thought the United States should stay out of Kosovo and attend to
domestic problems like homelessness. Although she tries to learn as
much as she can about Kosovo, she said, ``Lately, I don't know
who's telling the truth and who's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Phyllis McGraw, 51, an apartment manager in Jackson,
Miss., said, ``I favor helping the people, but there are times that
things are done for other reasons _ political reasons.'' Her
comments and others hinted at doubts arising from the president's
conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Casualties, if any, will inevitably have an impact on public
support.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have not become so accustomed to televised, high-tech,
easily winnable wars that they expect the American military to win
the next one without casualties. At least as far as Kosovo, the
poll shows, attitudes are much more subtle than that.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a hypothetical question dealing with winning wars
vs. limiting casualties, about half of those polled said the United
States and its allies should use whatever force was necessary to
win, regardless of casualties. The other half favored restraint.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the current conflict, however, a clear majority
of Americans say they would rather risk a protracted involvement
than run the risk of casualties. Hence they oppose escalating the
current level of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   From the president's point of view, the best news in the poll,
politically speaking, is that about half of all Americans see the
war, as Clinton does, as a moral imperative. Voters who view
conflict in those terms are less likely to cut and run at the first
sign of trouble than are the pragmatists.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll found a growing sense of responsibility for
providing aid for the refugees, apparently a response to the
horrific scenes of thousands of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo forced
to live in the open, in bad weather and without adequate sanitation
or nourishment, in Macedonia and Albania. Nearly eight of 10
respondents said the United States had such responsibilities, up
from 66 percent just four days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent said that it was right to airlift 20,000
refugees and care for them at the Guantanamo Naval Base in Cuba,
and 21 percent said more aid should be provided. Nearly half of
those polled said that aid to the Kosovo refugees should have begun
sooner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
