<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-713(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEARING ALBANIAN BORDER, THOUSANDS OF REFUGEES DISAPPEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS, KOSOVO-POLL,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ Tens of thousands of refugees from Kosovo
waiting to cross the border here vanished in the middle of the
night, ordered out of a column stretching 20 miles or more by
Serbian forces and sent walking to an unknown fate.
</P>
<P>
   This shabby little border crossing, swamped for more than a week
with ragged, weeping ethnic Albanians driven from their homes, was
eerily empty Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:30 Wednesday morning, Serbian forces walked up to a jumble
of six chest-high concrete pyramids that marks the midpoint of the
no-man's land between the two customs posts, according to observers
at the border from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe. Those on the Albanian side could keep on going; those still
in the Serbian zone were ordered to turn around.
</P>
<P>
   No one here knows what happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea,'' said Jacques Franquin, a spokesman for the
U.N. high commissioner for refugees. ``We are very worried. There
is reason to be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   From observation posts in the surrounding hills, the road into
Kosovo appeared to be empty of any vehicles for two miles or so
north, Franquin said, up to the next village, Szure, which the
Serbs have been using as a dropping-off place for refugees being
transported in bus and truck convoys after being rounded up farther
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, he added, there were lines of abandoned farm
tractors and cars. When the column was turned back on Tuesday
night, the refugees were backed up to the city of Prizren, about 22
miles away, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned aid officials here could only speculate on the latest
twist in the tactics of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is happening, you can rest assured it is not to the
benefit of these refugees,'' said Eugene O'Sullivan, the chief of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation observer team based
in nearby Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation included the possibility of a new propaganda
ploy by Milosevic in which he would maintain that the ethnic
Albanians were not being systematically hounded out after all, but
were being allowed to return to their homes voluntarily. It was
also possible that the refugees were being herded back to some
collection center, either as some form of hostages or even human
shields against NATO bombing attacks or attacks by Apache
helicopters, which, unlike the bombers, can fly close to the ground
and take aim at concentrations of troops and tanks.
</P>
<P>
   During the ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign in Bosnia, Serbs used
captured U.N. soldiers as shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty sinister turn of events,'' said Doran
Vienneau, an observer on the border. He predicted the border would
be closed for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials estimated that roughly 80,000 refugees were in
the line when it was turned back, based at the rate at which
refugees have been flowing through here and the length of time the
last group Wednesday morning had been on the road. NATO has
estimated there are some 300,000 people who have been uprooted from
their homes but are still displaced inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   From midnight until the refugees were turned back at 3:30, some
2,850 people made it out of Kosovo, making a total of 238,415 who
have crossed the border here since the Serbian campaign of
depopulating the province began. In addition, 51,850 have crossed
the even more remote and primitive mountains of the Hass District
to the northwest of here, most of them on a track over the
mountains which can only be traveled on foot because the Serbs have
mined it. That border crossing was sealed on Tuesday; the day
before, some 14,000 people crossed over.
</P>
<P>
   And, incredibly, one more man somehow wandered over the border
at midday. Ismet Hoxha said he had only encountered one Serbian
police patrol as he walked from his remote village, Gjonas. He said
the police inspected his hands _ apparently to see if he looked
tough enough to have been digging trenches for the Kosovo
Liberation Army, although most of the refugees are work-hardened
farmers _ and let him go. He said he had passed a line of empty,
abandoned tractors more than a mile long on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the luckiest Albanian in the world,'' Vienneau said. ``He
should buy a lottery ticket. This is his day.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For a week and a half, this border post, with its peeling paint,
chipped concrete and broken iron gate, has been a scene of chaos as
the refugees have poured across at the rate of 20,000 to 50,000 a
day with only what they can carry. Often it is a wooden cradle,
decorated with folk patterns that is a particularly valued family
heirloom among the Albanians strapped to the back of their farm
carts. Some people have been walking for days, carrying only a
blanket or a few clothes. They cry in relief as they cross the
border.
</P>
<P>
   All have harrowing _ and strikingly similar _ accounts of being
ordered out of their houses by Serbian special policemen, soldiers
and ultra-nationalist irregulars, many wearing masks or head bands.
They are robbed at gunpoint, herded to collection centers in the
larger towns, and robbed again along the way. All of their
identification is stripped away.
</P>
<P>
   Many say they have witnessed the Serbs killing people, sometimes
apparently at random, but often in what appears to be a systematic
manner, targeting, for instance, people who housed, worked for or
otherwise aided the Organization for Security and Cooperation
observer teams in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been accounts of mass killings. While the
accounts cannot be independently verified because foreign
journalists and relief workers, including the observers, have been
expelled from Kosovo, they are being given credence here because of
their striking similarity, the specific details provided by the
refugees and the past behavior of Serbian forces during the ethnic
cleansing of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday the crossing was empty and silent, save for a few
listless Albanian policemen and mystified aid workers. There were
only a few refugees sprawled on the hillside, now muddy and
littered with scraps of plastic, cardboard and squashed cans from
emergency ration packets, where people have rested after reaching
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Across the empty patch of no man's land the Serbian and Yugoslav
flags flap from their poles. The Serbian forces were digging
trenches with pickaxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refugees have been in a state of complete shock and terror
when they arrive here,'' said Vienneau, the observer at the border
post Wednesday morning. ``They are in an absolutely deplorable
state, with just the possessions they have on their backs. They
have been witness to very horrific crimes. We've had multiple
reports of people being rounded up and executed en masse. We've had
reports of constant brutalization throughout the journey here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel almost sick to my stomach because I have no idea what
happened to these people,'' he said, speaking of the missing tens
of thousands of refugees, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine being the guy on the first tractor when the
Serbs said, `Go back,' and they were so close to the border. I
would say the state of terror of these people is probably
absolutely indescribable, wondering what is going to happen to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One can only assume that things are very bad for them at the
moment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
