<HEADER>
A9619 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACEDONIA-MISSING-BOS     04-07 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACEDONIA-MISSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS WORKERS DESCRIBE MASSIVE EVACUATION OF REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ In the dead of night, tens of thousands of
ethnic Albanian refugees who had been hemmed in for days along the
Kosovo border were abruptly herded onto buses Tuesday night and
taken against their will to neighboring Albania and unknown
locations, human rights workers said.
</P>
<P>
   By dawn Wednesday, the swift forced move, carried out in less
than seven hours, left the squalid encampment in Blace, which had
been bursting at the seams with more than 40,000 refugees, a
desolate wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   In the chaotic evacuation, families were torn apart and
thousands of people forced to leave without knowing where they were
headed, according to human rights workers who were present at the
scene or helped eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly condemn these involuntary displacements,'' said
Paula Ghedini, spokesperson for the UNHCR. ``This was done in a
dark night. People were terrified and had no idea where they were
being taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Local television footage showed Macedonian police, armed with
rifles and wearing white masks against the stench and disease,
pushing the refugees into a long line of buses.
</P>
<P>
   But, Gehdini added, it appeared some of the refugees _ desperate
to flee the camp's open sewers, spreading disease, and lack of food
_ seemed to prefer the evacuation to spending any more time on a
muddy hillside in Blace, just past the ``no man's land'' between
Macedonia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday night, aid workers said they had traced about
10,000 people to Albania and another 10,000 to a holding center at
Stenkovec in Macedonia. The center, set up by NATO, is a transit
point from which the refugees are either sent to permanent camps or
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We essentially cannot account for somewhere between 10,000 to
20,000 people. We don't know where they were taken,'' Ghedini said.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee camp in the border town of Blace, some 20 miles
north of the Macedonian capital Skopje, had become a worldwide
symbol of the misery and desperation of the ethnic Albanians who
had been forced out of Kosovo by the Serbian forces of Yugoslav
president Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of refugees also threatened to dangerously disrupt a
delicate ethnic balance in Macedonia, which is 67 percent Slavic,
23 percent Albanian and a 10 percent mixture of ethnic backgrounds,
including Serbs. Many human rights workers said they believed the
Macedonian police had forced the refugees out to prevent the
turmoil that could ensue if tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians
settled permanently in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Literally overnight, the authorities appear to have emptied the
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the only sign of life in the camp was an old
woman wandering through an eery haze of smoke from still-smoldering
campfires and a mangy black dog picking through piles of garbage.
The putrid smell of human feces and rotten food lingered in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Hida Ajeta, 81, of Pristina, was the last refugee.
</P>
<P>
   She told a Globe photographer that she had been separated from
her family and was going to wait for them to return. Confused but
stubborn, she refused to leave. She explained that her sister had
grown ill in the camp and been sent to the hospital, and that she
would not leave without her.
</P>
<P>
   There was visible evidence that many had left without time to
collect their belongings. Passports, unopened packages of diapers,
baby food, clothing, blankets, pillows, and winter coats lay
discarded amid the abandoned rows of tents fashioned out of plastic
tarps and tree branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are leaving on their own don't leave behind baby
food and passports,'' said UNHCR's Ghedini.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian officials defended their decision to push the
refugees out of the encampment along the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to do our utmost,'' said Tihomir Ilievski, under
secretary in Macedonia's Foreign Ministry, ``but the situation on
the border was very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, he said the government of the republic,
which broke away off from Yugoslavia in 1992, feared that the
situation would ``upset the ethnic balance in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we have said from the beginning we could accept
20,000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 125,000 refugees from Kosovo had fled to Macedonia
since the NATO airstrikes began two weeks ago, according to the UN
refugee agency, which said precise numbers were impossible to
obtain. About 45,000 were in a chain of refugee camps set up by the
UN and NATO inside Macedonia. About 10,000 had been sent to
Albania. Between 40,000 to 60,000 refugees have been absorbed into
the homes of ethnic Albanian relatives, friends and former
neighbors inside Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The United States expressed anger at Macedonia's late-night
evacuation and reminded the government that it must adhere to
international standards in dealing with the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said, ``We have sent a
strong message to the government of Macedonia that we will hold it
to the highest standard of humanitarian law and expect it to uphold
internationally accepted laws in the treatment of refugees and
evacuation procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin added that the United States understands the concerns of
the Macedonian government, which faces considerable pro-Serb
sentiment from its Slav majority and fears the influx of ethnic
Albanians will swell its Albanian minority and destabilize the
nation of 2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless, we believe that for example it's simply wrong to
separate family members or to have people not volunteer to leave
and to ship them out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that as international relief efforts increase and
refugees are moved to other countries _ 100,000 going to various
European countries _ the crisis will ease in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Some 600,000 people have left Kosovo since the conflict between
ethnic Albanians and Yugoslav forces began in the Serbian province
in March last year, according to the UN refugee agency..
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said that in addition to the closing of the
Macedonia border, Albanian authorities had closed border crossings
at the Morini and Qafe Prushit Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A statement said, ``There were disquieting reports from inside
Kosovo that authorities there were now sending people back to their
home areas and turning them away from the Macedonian border.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
