<HEADER>
A9622 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-KILBORN-SFCHRON &LR;      04-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KILBORN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRONY AND NARCISSISM ON `LATE, LATE SHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You're frighteningly like my ex-boyfriend,'' pop star Shirley
Manson told Craig Kilborn this week on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing Kilborn gets that a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn, the new host of ``The Late Late Show,'' could be the
prototypical ex-boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   He's the guy who started watching a ballgame with his buddies
and forgot the dinner date to meet his girlfriend's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Or the one who lent his shoulder when you were crying and held
you, until you realized he was sneaking peeks at himself in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   That's the persona Kilborn cultivates. But then you're also
supposed to know it's an act. Still, you can't help thinking that
the fact it's an act might be a head feint, masking the chance that
Kilborn really is a preening, insensitive, soulless automaton.
</P>
<P>
   When a TV talk show is as aggressively deconstructive as
Kilborn's ``Late Late Show,'' your head is bound to spin with these
uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it's David Letterman's fault. Letterman brought the
architecture of mockery to his old NBC show and later to CBS.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to tell a media-savvy generation that TV was asinine,
his own show was stupid and, for that matter, he was probably a
jerk. So let's chisel some mirth out of all that with an ice pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not really very sincere,'' guest Charles Grodin said to
Letterman on Monday night, in one of their feigned sparring
matches.
</P>
<P>
   But the answer should be real enough: no. That's precisely the
point. On TV, sincerity excuses itself and goes to bed right after
the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Letterman was a visigod _ which is to say, TV deity
_ to hundreds of thousands of guys in college frat houses and
dormitories?
</P>
<P>
   What happened to all those boys? Well, one of them was Craig
Kilborn. And now he has his own show, right behind Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   One of the differences is that Letterman hates himself, or
pretends to, or pretends to but (set ital)does(end ital) hate
himself, while Kilborn's trick is to love himself. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   In one gag, the camera catches Kilborn in midnarcissism, holding
a hand mirror and looking adoringly at himself.
</P>
<P>
   In another, he finishes his opening and then stands pensively by
a window on his woody, masculine set. In voice-over, he
congratulates himself on the progress of that night's show. This is
after the monologue and Kilborn's ``In the News'' segment. The
monologue is the most sparse around, a few lean slices of processed
joke material. If Jay Leno serves up the TV monologue equivalent of
Wagner's ``Ring'' tetralogy, then Kilborn is a quick ``Saber
Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the News'' apparently gets more attention. The segment is
Kilborn at his cruelest. Refugees from Kosovo have been
consistently amusing since Kilborn's show premiered last week. All
things Mexican seem to be funny, too, in the way Letterman targets
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   On Kosovo: ``Some even believe the events unfolding in Kosovo
could lead to the ultimate horror _ another crazy Oscar acceptance
speech by Roberto Benigni.'' On a Mexican money-laundering scandal:
``The first time in history anything in Mexico has ever been
laundered.''
</P>
<P>
   Save us all from the curse of political correctness. Yet, a
modicum of taste and a teaspoon of empathy is mandatory for WASPish
men.
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn has also been poking fun at the hunk Fabio, who somehow
was plastered by a migrating goose while riding a roller coaster.
Now that (set ital)is(end ital) funny. Must these distinctions be
explained?
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn has done his best work with his guests. Shirley Manson
was a match for him, taking an airy punch in his direction when she
disapproved of something he said. Jeff Goldblum always seems to
wash in on a wave of helium. (But did Kilborn really need to ask
him, ``By the way, what are you promoting? Why are you here?'')
</P>
<P>
   Bill Murray is foolproof, and the stars of the Telemundo version
of ``Charlie's Angels'' were suited for Kilborn's leer routine.
Thursday night, Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Kilborn has been showing some spark. He listens to his
guests. He asks questions based on what they say, rather than
rattling them off an index card. There appear to be bolts of
extemporaneous give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   This is what used to be called conversation, and once upon a
time talk shows were based on it. Kilborn seems to have the
wherewithal to handle conversation, if he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   So there is always hope for civilization on the airwaves. More
likely, though, the mask of comic irony will stay firmly in place,
and viewers will be asked to feel they're part of some big snicker.
</P>
<P>
   Then, whenever Kilborn takes his leave _ six months from now,
six years, 10 years or 20 _ we'll be as indifferent to his fate as
he is to some desperately terrified refugee in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, it won't be as if we really (set ital)knew(end ital) the
guy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
