<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIERS-COX     04-07 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Air Force Troops Do Their Bit On the Ground Against
Milosevic
 &HT;    With PHOTOS 
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FORCE BASE, Albania American airmen started laboring
Wednesday to turn this broken down airfield into the nerve center
of NATO's Task Force Shining Hope, the rescue mission finally
organized to save hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees
driven from their Kosovo homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my boys I had to go away to work to help some people
out,'' said Staff Sgt. Wesley Paul Eidson, 26, of Bowdon, GA., who
left his wife and two sons back at Ramstein Air Base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after stepping off an Air Force C-17 transport Wednesday
onto the cracked concrete runway, Eidson was burying water pipes at
the grassy air base still dotted with scores of abandoned domed
concrete bunkers, the former headquarters of the Albanian Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get potable water to the shower units,'' said
Senior Airman Mitch Raney, 27, of Waco, Texas, who was taking a
break with Eidson in the sunny and still warm late afternoon.
``We're still not entirely sure if it's potable ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's the only water available from the capital city Tirana
15 miles to the southeast, just as this air base that doubles as
the nation's single commercial airport is the only big field
available to handle the bulky cargo transports and mega-tons of
supplies that are beginning to ferry in aid from governments around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Rinas airfield is but one example of the obstacles military and
relief organizations are encountering in Albania, a threadbare
nation where the best roads are awful, supplies hard to find and
equipment so marginal that aid workers said there was a single
forklift in the country just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The American airmen and a few airwomen are taking the lead for
NATO at this site where Albanian, French and Italian military also
are working, according to the U.S. Air Force spokesman here, Master
Sgt. Michael Land, 33, of Lakeland, Fla. The first U.S. contingent
arrived at Rinas Air Base Sunday night, and by this weekend an
estimated 400 American troops will be on the ground and working.
</P>
<P>
   Their job is air traffic control and circulation and loading and
unloading humanitarian aid that comes in. On Wednesday the NATO
soldiers handled six American C-130 transports and five of
America's larger C-17 transports, along with an assortment of
planes from the Middle East to the Atlantic. Two of the wide-bodied
cargo planes one with Russian markings and another from Egypt were
still sitting on the air field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the only K-loaders and forklifts. So we can do the
job,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has yet to announce where it will headquarter Task Force
Hawk, the combat forces that will include 24 U.S. Apache helicopter
gunships and 2,000 support troops. The Apaches are expected to
begin arriving as early as next week in a marked escalation of the
assault on Yugoslav military forces that NATO charges have been
carrying out ethnic cleansing of the Albanian
</P>
<P>
   population across the border in Yugoslavia's suffering province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women of Relief Force Tirana, the American component
of Task Force Shining Hope, are on a humanitarian rather than
combat mission. But some of the troops are edgy nonetheless, and
some have gotten indications that their jobs may not be limited to
digging ditches or guarding the shabby perimeter fence surrounding
the airfield.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Sgt. Noah Coon, 26, of Cocoa Beach, Fla., is a security
officer whose unit had six weeks of special training for this
assignment at Charleston Air Force Base in South Carolina, where he
is stationed. The crash course was in weapons training, map and
compass use and land navigation, Coon said, the kinds of skills
more useful out in the field, not guarding a gate as he was doing
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a little scary, just being in a different country,
being so close to Yugoslavia,'' acknowledged Eidson, the Georgia
airman.
</P>
<P>
   Eidson said his wife back at Ramstein was frantic, at least
briefly, when she learned he was being shipped out to the NATO
operations here.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was worried we'd be in Macedonia where those guys got
captured,'' he said, referring to the three U.S. soldiers still
being held by Serb authorities who claim they had infiltrated into
Yugoslav territory during a perimeter exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is Eidson totally sanguine about the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what will happen,'' he said. ``That's what's so
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
