<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9631 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      04-07 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, April 8. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Ledeall. The NATO allies move
to press home their stepped-up air attacks against Yugoslav
military targets in Kosovo, with a diplomatic offensive aimed at
probing for signs that President Slobodan Milosevic might be ready
to back down. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With map and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Morini, Albania) _ Tens of thousands of
refugees waiting to cross the border here vanished in the middle of
the night, ordered out of a column stretching 20 miles or more by
Serb forces and sent walking to an unknown fate. By John Kifner.
(MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLL (Undated) _ N.Y. Times poll shows support for ground
troops but questions about Clinton's ability to lead in a crisis.
By R.W. Apple Jr. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ELDERLY-VOTERS (Deerfield Beach, Fla.) _ These blue collar
workers, office workers and small business owners retired to South
Florida during the condominium booms of the 1960s and 1970s, and
brought their machine politics with them. They used their condo
associations and social clubs the way they once used the meeting
halls and church basements back home, shifting from Roosevelt and
Truman to Kennedy, Carter and Clinton, becoming a steady, swelling
political force. They voted religiously, and they voted Democrat.
By Rick Bragg. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   PAIRGAIN-WEB-FRAUD (NEW YORK) _ One of the oldest frauds on Wall
Street has been updated for the Internet age. Using a personal web
site designed to look like the Internet page of Bloomberg Business
News, someone posted a fake news story that said an American
technology company called PairGain Technologies Inc. was being
taken over by an Israeli rival. The report spread to a Yahoo
message board and then to other sites frequented by stock traders,
who quickly bid up PairGain's stock by more than 30 percent. By
midday, the stock had retreated as the takeover story was debunked.
By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
</TEXT>
