A9634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAYTHEON-STARS-BOS &LR;      04-07 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-STARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TARGET DATES SET FOR RAYTHEON AIR-TRAFFIC CONTROL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A new national air-traffic control system being
developed by Raytheon Co. has missed its debut date at Logan
International Airport and won't enter service anytime soon, the
Federal Aviation Administration said.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion system was supposed to be rolled out at Logan in
December in what was touted as the first installation for the new
nationwide network.
</P>
<P>
   But slow development work and the need for input from
air-traffic controllers has forced the agency to scrap that
schedule. No new target dates have been set, for Logan or
elsewhere, said William Shumann, FAA spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, kinks that have surfaced mean that the system may not
be introduced at all at Logan, but at a civilian airport with far
less traffic, the FAA said. ``Right now, the specifics of the
entire system are up in the air, so to speak,'' Shumann said.
</P>
<P>
   Delays in the system, known as the Standard Terminal Automation
Replacement System, or STARS, have been reported before, but the
FAA previously hasn't discussed rollout dates at most airports.
</P>
<P>
   The slips at Logan were disclosed amid continuing criticism of
the project. Including maintenance contracts, STARS will cost $2.2
billion by 2025. Construction, development and installation will
account for $1 billion of that.
</P>
<P>
   The system is meant to replace an aging analog-based air-traffic
system blamed for a plethora of mishaps and near-misses. Among
other things, the FAA says the aging technology caused a 37-minute
outage at a New England tracking center in Nashua, N.H. in August,
forcing air-traffic controllers to keep track of planes with
handwritten notes.
</P>
<P>
   A team led by Raytheon, based in Lexington, Mass., was awarded
the contract for the STARS project in September 1996, and had
planned to finish the job by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a report in USA Today, the FAA also confirmed
that tests showed a component of STARS known as an ``early display
configuration'' wasn't meeting expectations. The component,
essentially an advanced radar display, is meant to provide new
features for controllers using the agency's existing radar-tracking
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The displays were scheduled to be installed in Washington's
Reagan National Airport last month, but that hasn't happened and
the agency says it plans to revise the schedule sometime this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The agency had previously mentioned problems with the displays
in early February. The agency also noted the tests reported by USA
Today were performed by a competitor of Raytheon's, Lockheed
Martin, which is trying to sell the FAA on a competing product. A
spokesman for Lockheed didn't return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokesman David Polk defended STARS and said the system
has performed well in tests at Eglin Air Force Base in Florida. But
executives there weren't available to discuss the project in
detail, he said. Raytheon has not been penalized for the delays in
the STARS schedule, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the group led by Raytheon include Sun
Microsystems and United Faculty Associates of Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they are more puzzled than concerned about
Raytheon's work on the contract to date. ``You've got to believe
that Raytheon will have the system up and running soon,'' said CS
First Boston analyst Peter Aseritis. ``The negative aspect is, it
was supposed to be up and running by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Raytheon fell 1 1/4 in New York Stock Exchange trading
to close at 59 3/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
