<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ELAMIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EL-AMIN STAYS WITH UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The advice University of Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun gave
sophomore point guard Khalid El-Amin was simple. Wait a year.
You'll be better off in the long run. And so will we.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, after considering all the options, El-Amin, the heart
and sometimes soul of UConn's national championship team this
season, decided to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think doing it a second time will be even better,'' said
El-Amin, whose decision to return should make the Huskies one of
the preseason picks to contend for the national title again next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors played into El-Amin's decision, including where
he would fall in a draft expected to be top heavy with guards, and
whether another year of college would work to his long-range
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10-inch sophomore has been a leader on the Huskies
since he arrived from Minneapolis two seasons ago. Calhoun gave
El-Amin more freedom to do things on the court than he had allowed
any freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khalid is something special,'' Calhoun said more than once
during the Huskies' 36-2 championship season.
</P>
<P>
   A starter in 71 games and only the third player in UConn history
to score at least 1,000 points by the end of his sophomore season,
El-Amin ran the Huskies offense, averaging 13.8 points per game
this season as well as leading the team in assists.
</P>
<P>
   But it was El-Amin's spirit, as shown when he made key free
throws in wins over Gonzaga in the NCAA West Regional final and
over Duke in the the championship game, that drew Calhoun's praise
and affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Khalid obviously played a major role in our national
championship journey,'' Calhoun said. ``I believe he will enjoy an
even more dynamic role as he expands his wonderful leadership
qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   With Richard Hamilton, who is likely to leave early for the NBA,
and Ricky Moore gone, El-Amin's leadership and skills will be
needed if the Huskies can come close to repeating this year's
success.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin, who has two children, could have chosen the financial
security he expects to find in the NBA, but for the time being, he
has chosen to stay with a family of Huskies instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
