<HEADER>
A9646 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-DEFENSE-497(2TA     04-07 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DEFENSE-497(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN IS FLEXING ITS MILITARY MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ When Japan fired warning shots at suspicious boats that
ventured into its territorial waters last month, it was the
clearest signal to date that this staunchly pacifist country is
taking its gloves off.
</P>
<P>
   There is a new willingness to assume a public role in regional
defense that Japan has long shunned because of its militarist past
and the fears of neighbors it once threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese legislators are openly talking about once-taboo
possibilities such as building first-strike capabilities and
putting Japanese troops in peacekeeping operations that would
expose them to combat. There are plans to buy new weapons, and
there is a heated debate about loosening restrictions on Japan's
military support for the United States in the region. There is a
renewed sense of vulnerability, too, about threats from North Korea
and even China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has gained the confidence and courage to speak
out about the need for a strong defense, and that's a very big
change,'' said Kenzo Yoneda, a legislator from the governing
Liberal Democratic Party who has taken a leading role in pushing
for Japanese forces to gain first-strike capability. ``The taboo on
the discussion of defense is fading.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues of defense and, more broadly, what defines the
Japanese nation, are now being debated broadly and heatedly. ``We
are increasingly concerned as a nation that our basic defense
system is inadequate,'' Yoneda said.
</P>
<P>
   The government has authorized the purchase of four sophisticated
reconnaissance satellites for deployment by 2002, and despite
China's strenuous objections, it has agreed to pay a significant
part of the research and development expenses related to building a
missile defense system for the region.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions are under way about plans to buy airborne refueling
equipment and to outfit assault ships with decks that would allow
helicopters and Harrier-type aircraft to land in mid-sea.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Democratic Party, normally somewhat dovish, has
established a study group to come up with a policy on North Korea
that is likely to include proposals for strengthening Japan's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   For most of Japan's postwar years, Article 9 of the
constitution, which forbids all military activity except
self-defense, was sacrosanct. Now talk about changing it has
evolved from the demands of a handful of right-wing legislators to
a serious give-and-take that many feel may indeed lead to
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a real move away from what might be considered a
pure hedgehog defense,'' said Richard J. Samuels, an expert on
Japanese defense matters and head of the Japan program at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``In full public view,
there's this whole set of measures that the Japanese government is
taking _ sometimes with America's support, sometimes at its request
and sometimes despite its consternation _ to shift away from a
strictly defensive defense.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To be sure, there is still a great deal of traditional
ambivalence surrounding the subject of the military here, where
many still harbor memories of the imperialistic militarism that
brought Japan into World War II and made it the scourge of its
neighbors. That ambivalence is reflected in the debate under way in
Parliament over revisions to the military guidelines that govern
cooperation between Japanese and American forces in the region,
forcing Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi and others to hint that they
may have to water down the proposed changes to get them passed.
</P>
<P>
   As they stand, the revisions would enable the Self-Defense
Forces, Japan's army, to support American troops in ``areas
surrounding Japan,'' as well as offer logistical support,
search-and-rescue operations and inspections of suspect ships. In
other words, if sparks fly in the Taiwan Strait or between North
and South Korea, Japanese forces would be required to play a
substantial supporting role.
</P>
<P>
   More than 45,000 American troops are stationed in Japan,
including an aircraft carrier and a Marine division, but the old
guidelines are sketchy on Japan's obligations to support those
troops in the event of a military crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Americans regard the changes as long overdue, an effort to make
Japan shoulder responsibility for its own defense.
</P>
<P>
   But many Japanese consider the changes a sign of the waning
American interest in attending to Japan's defense concerns now that
the Cold War is over. If Japan becomes more militarily powerful,
the argument goes, it will force the United States to stay involved
in the region, if only to keep an eye on what the Japanese are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``China and North Korea are not really the direct cause of the
increased interest in enhancing defense capabilities,'' said
Masanori Nishi, an official at the Defense Facilities
Administration Agency. ``They're a type of reasonable excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real worry is that the American commitment or the logic
behind the American participation in the maintaining regional
stability is shaky, that it's necessary to encourage and support
American interest in the Far East,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is helping in that effort. The two ships the
Japanese chased this week are believed to have been sent by North
Korea, which has become increasingly bellicose.
</P>
<P>
   In August, North Korea sent a projectile known as the Taepodong
soaring toward Tokyo. It ultimately landed in the Pacific Ocean,
but it riveted the attention of the Japanese public on the issue of
defense in a way that little else has.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the Taepodong was the biggest boon that
proponents of a stronger Japanese military policy have had in
years. Former Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, regarded as one of
the more hawkish members of Japan's political elite, has even joked
privately that he is so grateful for that incident that he half
considered sending Kim Jong Il, the North Korean leader, a present
for his birthday this year.
</P>
<P>
   How much of a threat the Taepodong posed to Japan remains in
question. The North Koreans contend that it involved a satellite
launching, a contention supported by American intelligence but
countered by Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Japan's moves, though, have alarmed its neighbors. The
Chinese government strenuously objects to Japan's planned
investment in a missile defense system, which is likely to cast its
umbrella over Taiwan, and was angry about recent remarks by a
senior Japanese politicians suggesting that the revised guidelines
would include China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea, too, has misgivings, although it also shares with
Japan concerns about North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese are also concerned, pointing to the similarities
between Japan's current economic woes and a depression in the early
1930s, which was brought to an end in 1935 by a rise of militarism
that pulled the economy out of its slump, fueled a brutal, regional
imperialism and ultimately led Japan into World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels are immediately dismissed by those who note that
the government would have to invest vast sums of money and overcome
overwhelmingly negative public sentiment to achieve a buildup even
remotely similar to that of the early Showa era.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nonsense,'' Motoo Shina, a legislator known for his
interest in defense matters, said of the comparison of eras. He
said Japanese business and financial interests were too widespread
now to allow the country to embark on a military adventure on
anything like the scale it did in the past. ``Look at our current
army,'' he said. ``Probably we'd even have trouble occupying
Guam.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the government recently said the four
reconnaissance satellites it intends to have in place by 2002 would
be made by Japanese manufacturers from Japanese components, which
suggests that there might be at least a bit of an economic element
to the current hawkish noises emanating from Japan. American
defense manufacturers often rely on components made abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Japan's military abilities are already more
substantial than many people realize. Even though Japan has
officially spent no more than 1 percent of its gross domestic
product on defense since the 1960s, the sheer size of its economy
means that it is the second- or third-biggest spender after the
United States. Most experts contend that its real spending levels
are obscured by the practice of deferring payments for weapons
systems, shifts in exchange rates and the difficulty in assessing
how much the private sector is investing in de facto defense
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Japanese defense issues from year to year, it
doesn't change much; it's pretty boring,'' said Masashi Nishihara,
a professor at the National Defense Academy. ``But if you look at
it over a five-year period, there's a big difference. No one has
paid much attention to it until last summer, but now that people
are looking, they've found out a lot has changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
