<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATHROOM-BONDING-2400(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND CLOSED DOORS; FEMALE BONDING IN THE BATHROOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas: won't turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy: ``I can't believe we're doing this. I haven't even
shaved!''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley (to an invisible third party): ``We're not normally like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy and Ashley charge out of the bathroom for the second time,
leaving a group of conversing women at the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Woman  &LR;  wearing a green snap-front dress: ``That guy Carlos in
the Navy, don't you think he's kind of fine? He put his arm all
over my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman 3, at the opposite end of the counter, to Woman 4: ``You
using Clarins?''
</P>
<P>
   Woman 4: ``No, it's Merle Norman.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman 5, to no one in particular: ``I have too much hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Fade to black
</P>
<P>
   SECOND INTERMISSION
</P>
<P>
   Not all ladies' rooms are created equal. Restrooms in bars such
as USA Cafe _ where women have been drinking alcohol, where the
goal might be to ``hook up'' or at least spark some interest in a
potential partner _ are vastly different from a bathroom, say, at a
museum.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday afternoon at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort
Worth, a steady stream of women waited _ and waited _ for the
restroom. Most never spoke; if they did, it was to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, two women angrily but quietly discussed the
behavior of a man they both knew. ``I am so sick of his attitude,''
one woman commented.
</P>
<P>
   Their conversation represents one way women's relationships
differ when they are in intimate, female-only spaces, says Beth
Anne Shelton, director of the women's studies program at the
University of Texas at Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just because there are no men around,'' Shelton says,
noting that there are plenty of occasions when women are alone, in
restaurants or at work, and that this kind of interaction still
won't occur. The reason it happens in women's rooms is ``that it is
a female-only space,'' she adds, ``a safe space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you see two things (in women's rooms),'' Shelton says.
``Women sort of forget about the gender scripts of appropriate
behavior. They are less genteel, they talk about more personal
things, things that in other contexts might be viewed as somewhat
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, a lot of their hostility toward men comes out. I don't
mean women really hate men and when they go in the bathroom it all
comes out. But often men are the butt of the jokes. It's not women
being disdainful, but the ways in which men are different are
commented upon.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other audible comments in the Kimbell ladies' room that
afternoon were about appearance _ another unifying factor for
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cut too many layers,'' one petite blonde noted to another
petite blonde while both fixed their hair in the mirror. ``I told
her not to cut so many layers.''
</P>
<P>
   The women observed in restrooms at the 8.0 restaurant, the Pig &AMP;
Whistle Pub, USA Cafe and the Kimbell all showed respect for one
another. They shared makeup, complimented clothing, boosted one
another's egos and handed toilet paper from stall to stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a forum for self-deprecating yourself and
complimenting your friends,'' says Catheryn Koss, a 25-year-old
from Oklahoma City. Koss and Austinite Jenna Martin, 25, had been
in the Kimbell restroom briefly discussing Martin's bad-hair day.
</P>
<P>
   Martin recalled a time she struck up a conversation with a woman
in the bathroom of a furniture store after noting that the woman's
perfume was the same brand Martin's mother wore. ``It just totally
opened her up to me,'' Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   The ladies' room might be the great equalizer among women,
Shelton suggests. ``In a sense, a lot of what women are doing in
the bathroom is preparing for the outside world,'' she says. ``So
there is a recognition that your true essence is exposed in the
bathroom ... which serves to diminish distinctions among women.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondell's most surprising discovery, she says, was how gender
issues spanned generations of women, from high schoolers to the
elderly. ``There really is something that binds us,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ACT 3: At 11:45 p.m., Amy and Ashley return to the USA Cafe's
ladies' room along with Kelli, who carries an athletic bag full of
bikini tops and bottoms. The three rummage through the bag, grab a
handful of Lycra and pile into stall No. 2. Several other women in
the bathroom _ Sandy, Dominique and Pamela _ also have begun
changing into bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   Amy, still in the stall: ``OK, I'm stripping!''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley, searching for her bikini bottom: ``Where's the bottom to
the white one?''
</P>
<P>
   In a few seconds the women pile out of the stall. Amy is wearing
a red, tie-dyed two-piece with fashionable trunk bottoms; Ashley
has on a floral yellow and orange suit, which looks like a
Victorian wedding gown next to Sandy's leopard-print, itsy-bitsy
thong number. Sandy, a very pretty women who works at Hooters,
begins covering her exposed parts with baby oil.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley, staring a Sandy's ample chest: ``Can I ask you, are
those fake?''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy, nonplused: ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley: ``Darn. I want mine to look that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy: ``Baby, you have (breasts). I was a double-A before I got
this done.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy, who meanwhile has changed into a more daring French-cut
bikini like Ashley's: ``Ashley, have you ever imagined this. I'm
half-naked in front of the whole world!''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley, lifting her face toward Kelli, who is brushing blush on
Ashley's cheeks: ``You look good, Amy. ... This is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy, to Ashley: ``She looks like Barbie. Baby, you don't need
more blush.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy, who doesn't normally smoke: ``I need a cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   The women are escorted out of the restroom, offstage, each
wearing a short, sheer robe. Moblike catcalls, cheering and
applause can be heard over the beat of the music each time the
bathroom door opens.
</P>
<P>
   The lights dim as one last women enters the now-empty ladies'
room.
</P>
<P>
   Woman 6: ``God. I hate my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
