<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATHROOM-BONDING-2400     04-07 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATHROOM-BONDING-2400(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND CLOSED DOORS; FEMALE BONDING IN THE BATHROOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACT 1
</P>
<P>
   We first meet Ashley and Amy, our protagonists, in the ladies'
room at USA Cafe, a swinging singles spot in downtown Fort Worth.
It's a Wednesday night, and the club is kicking off its Spring
Break '99 party, which includes, among other hallowed events, a
midnight bikini contest.
</P>
<P>
   The room is packed with pods of aimlessly wandering males,
grasping beer bottles, and lip-glossed females in Lycra clothing.
The DJ is spinning the Commodores' ``Brick House:''/ ``She's
mightay, mightay, just lettin' it all hang out ...''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley and Amy _ two attractive, petite coeds who attend a
nearby private university _ are here by default. Their tropical
cruise fell through at the last minute, so they've tagged along for
the evening with Ashley's big sister, Kelli, and Kelli's husband.
At approximately 10:30 p.m., Ashley, Amy and Kelli remove
themselves from the chaos and huddle in the women's restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley: ``He's a sophomore, but he's 21.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelli: ``What about the other one?''
</P>
<P>
   Amy: ``They're cute, they're both cute, but I don't like it when
he does this.'' (She lifts her arms over her head and thrusts her
hips around spastically.)
</P>
<P>
   Kelli: ``Yeah. And his teeth are all messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   They all agree the teeth are a problem, and after a brief check
of their own appearance, quickly file out of the restroom. Just
then, Woman 1 enters the ladies' room and walks to the mirror. She
tousles her bangs.
</P>
<P>
   Woman 1, frowning: ``Fluorescent lights _ the worst possible
thing you could put in a bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman 2, also frowning: ``My hair is, like, huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Fade to black.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST INTERMISSION
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Salzman Mondell's fascination with public restrooms
developed decades ago. When Mondell was a child, a momentarily
confused aunt led her into a men's lavatory. The rows of white
porcelain urinals awed the sheltered 6-year-old. ``What,'' she
asked her aunt, ``are all these fountains?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Mondell would become an independent filmmaker based in
Dallas who would turn her lens toward the same subject, albeit a
different gender. ``The Ladies Room,'' her 1998 documentary, takes
an unflinching look at how women relate to one another in the
closed quarters of restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Mondell contends that women speak more frankly and freely in the
ladies' room than in mixed (i.e., male-female) company. The
documentary portrays ladies' rooms as sanctuaries of a sort, where
female camaraderie blossoms and where women feel safe letting down
their emotional guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We relate to each other in a very unique way in the
bathroom,'' Mondell says, ``because there are no male rules.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Mondell began camping out in women's restrooms with a
small-format video camera, a microphone and a pretty good notion of
what she might find. She filmed scenes in more than 25 Texas
restrooms over the course of five years, camping out in places like
the ladies' rooms of the Dallas Museum of Art, J.J. Pearce High
School in Richardson, the YWCA, the Jewish Community Center, Dick's
Last Resort restaurant, a lesbian bar, and several hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a pastiche of blunt repartee about sex, men, hair,
sex, mothers, eating, sex, harassment and relationships. Did we
mention sex?
</P>
<P>
   Mondell organizes the conversations under themes: ``Dating,''
``Bathroom Therapy,'' ``Mother Knows Best,'' ``Mr. Wrong,'' etc.
Her camera captured sometimes hilarious and sometimes moving
interactions between friends as well as total strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Mondell introduces a discussion group of
twentysomethings and fortysomethings that spontaneously forms in
one gleaming white restroom and generates this remark: ``I'm
involved with someone who's 19 years younger than I am,'' says a
woman in a black hat. ``He's real flexible, and that's what I like.
I've told people, I can't imagine dating 40-year-old men. They're
like half dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, a woman finds solace from two others she's
never met when she begins talking about her failing marriage. The
pseudo-therapy session ends in tears and hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been fascinated with how you can make a friend for
the period of time you're in the bathroom,'' Mondell says. ``You're
not necessarily friends when you leave that space, but for those
minutes ...''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, prom girls complain about their dates, like
the ``Texas Tech dumb jock'' who wore cowboy boots with his suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My date?'' says one lovely young woman, speaking directly to
the camera, ``I hope he drowns.''
</P>
<P>
   ACT 2
</P>
<P>
   At 11 p.m., the women's restroom has become increasingly
crowded. Space in front of the mirrors that stretch over two sinks
is especially coveted. Staring at their reflections, the women
primp, applying lip liner and face powder, pulling miniature
bottles of hair spray from their purses, tousling their bangs,
flipping their heads, yanking down and hiking up various articles
of clothing. They purchase single cigarettes, sticks of gum or a
single application of lipstick from Leticia, the conscientious
ladies' room attendant who sits with a roll of paper towels in her
hands.
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Lisa has locked herself into stall No. 3, head
slumped over the toilet. When two female strangers come to retrieve
her (as a favor to the men outside the ladies' room who have been
calling Lisa's name for 15 minutes), they notice that Lisa has some
tissue paper protruding from her brassiere. They hurriedly tuck the
offending stuffing back from whence it came.
</P>
<P>
   It is into this scene that Ashley and Amy burst yet again,
laughing and breathless. The duo make a beeline to the empty stall
for the disabled and disappear. Much hilarity emanates from within.
</P>
<P>
   Narrator, entering stage left: By now, Ashley's brother-in-law
has persuaded our two protagonists to enter the bikini contest;
he's already left to retrieve a drawer-full of bikinis from
Ashley's house. With only one other person signed up and cash
prizes for the top three entrants, Ashley and Amy see an
opportunity for some quick cash. But who will wear which bathing
suit?
</P>
<P>
   Amy: ``I'm worried about the butt on the white one. How much
does it cover?''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley: ``Don't worry about it. You just won't turn around.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
