<SLUG> BC-MA-ROADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTED REPORT RATES MASS., N.J. ROADS AMONG POOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A university research group that regularly compares
transportation systems nationwide has ranked the Massachusetts and
New Jersey highway departments as the least efficient in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The University of North Carolina at Charlotte's Center for
Interdisciplinary Transportation Studies said that highway
management was most efficient in Western and Southern states. The
study's conclusions were based on five financial measures, such as
maintenance costs, and seven performance ratings, such as levels of
congestion and accident rates.
</P>
<P>
   For the six years covered by the last federal highway funding
bill, the study found, North Dakota and Wyoming got the most for
their money; New York, Hawaii, Rhode Island, Massachusetts, and New
Jersey got the least, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts and Louisiana were the only states that spent more
on administration than on maintenance, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts highway commissioner Matt Amorello spared no
adjectives in denouncing the study. ``This is a pointy-headed
intellectual in North Carolina compiling a report filled with
misleading bunk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amorello said states' different conditions and ways of keeping
records cannot be compared. He said the North Carolina professor
who conducted the study, David T. Hartgen, compared six-lane
highways in Massachusetts with one-lane highways elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do that,'' said Amorello, adding that Massachusetts,
unlike some other states, includes pension costs in its
administrative budget. ``It's just hokum to sell reports and
probably make some money for UNC.''
</P>
<P>
   A national organization of highway departments has also taken
issue with the North Carolina center's approach in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
