<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAD-RAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE TO SEEK AGGRESSIVE DRIVERS ON HOUSTON FREEWAYS &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By S.K. BARDWELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Houston Police Department and the Metropolitan
Transit Authority Police on Wednesday launched an initiative aimed
at improving traffic safety on area freeways.
</P>
<P>
   A team of officers from both departments will be assigned to a
different freeway from 9 a.m. to 2 p.m. each weekday, said Houston
Police Chief C.O. Bradford.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said the teams will target ``speeders and aggressive
drivers who act out more between rush hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're dangerous and they provoke many complaints from
citizens. Seeing more officers on the freeway should slow down some
of them and make the roads safer for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Metro Police Chief Tom Lambert said while the main goal of the
program is safety, ``We're also looking to improve mobility. And
nothing grinds mobility to a halt faster than accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Unmarked cars also will be used to target aggressive drivers on
the city's freeways, Bradford said Wednesday, and patrol officers
have been asked to spend their uncommitted time enforcing traffic
laws on freeways in their beats.
</P>
<P>
   About two weeks ago, HPD assigned all 40 of the motorcycle
officers in its Solo Division to focus on inspecting 18-wheelers on
the city's freeways, and HPD Lt. E.J. Smith said that move has
increased the number of truck inspections from about 100 per month
to 100 per week.
</P>
<P>
   The most common problems being found, said Smith, are bald
tires, missing mud flaps, leaking brake fluid, loads that are too
heavy, wide or high, or problems with manifests or driver's
licenses _ all violations of regulations that can be enforced by
any police officer.
</P>
<P>
   HPD's efforts to beef up highway safety come on the heels of two
particularly deadly traffic accidents on Interstate 45.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 12, four people died on the Gulf Freeway when an
18-wheeler ran into the back of a chain-reaction collision caused
by a car. On March 16, three people died on the North Freeway when
a tanker truck lost control and veered into oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
