<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THERE ARE CLOUDS IN THE CRYSTAL BALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you're out of tea leaves, and his palms are furry and you
still want to tell his fortune. The latest issue of Twist, a
magazine for teens, tells how to assess people's character by their
salad dressing choice:
</P>
<P>
   _ If he likes French dressing, which is ``a little sweet,'' he
has ``an even sweeter heart. ... A real mother hugger.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If she likes blue, she has a mature palate and is probably a
``mature mamacita.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Thousand island dressing fans are ``adventurous and not afraid
to try new things.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A lover of Italian dressing is ``not one for quiet nights at
home watching a video.'' She likes ``to go out and rage!''
</P>
<P>
   _ If you like honey dijon dressing, ``Everyone thinks you're a
sweetie pie, but we know there's a little spice behind that
innocent smile.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar night is a high-pressure situation for me. One year I
did Cindy Crawford, Tom Cruise, Nicole Kidman and Geena Davis. It
was too much. This year, Cate Blanchett asked me to work on her. If
I had to choose somebody, that's who I would choose, but she chose
me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hairdresser Sally Herschberger in Self magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUCCESS IS BEAUTIFUL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Life Is Beautiful'' brings to mind  &UR; Jerry &LR; 
 &UR; Lewis &LR; ' unreleased 1971 film, ``The Day the Clown Cried,'' writes
 &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR;  of MSNBC. A print of the movie, which was never
released and is about a clown hired by the Nazis to entertain at
Auschwitz, is kept in Lewis' private vault.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say the movie was put away because its acting is
terrible, writes Walls. Others claim that Lewis couldn't find a
distributor. Lewis' agent denies there are any  &LR; plans to release
the film now &LR; , but Walls writes that the comedians' friends are
urging him to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   In another development arising out of the movie's success, a
Philadelphia travel agent is offering a 12-day tour of Italian
Holocaust sites, including places featured in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHARPER THAN A SERPENT'S TOOTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gerald Sheindlin &LR; , who, like his wife, Judge  &UR; Judy Sheindlin &LR; ,
is a retired New York City judge, is talking to producers of
``People's Court'' about presiding on that show.
</P>
<P>
   If Sheindlin gets the gig, he would be putting  &UR; Edward Koch &LR; ,
who as mayor of New York had appointed both Sheindlins to the
bench, out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   An executive with the show said that Judge Judy's audience is
twice that of ``People's Court.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Liz Smith &LR;  wrote Wednesday that  &UR; Cher &LR;  entertained at the
recent White Party in Palm Springs, but one of the many revelers
who was there reports with great certainty that the performer of
Cher's song was a drag queen.
</P>
<P>
   _ An ad in the Berkeley Bark for the cafe the Musical Offering
pictures a chihuahua-like dog with the legend ``Yo quiero
Pachelbel.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; James Allen &LR; , whose STR8 T-shirts, hats and bumper stickers
are sold via his web site, www.str8flag.com told Details magazine
he doesn't understand why they are controversial. ``STR8
merchandise basically says, `I know you're gay. I'm heterosexual.
So what!' ''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; John Matterney &LR;  noticed the credit on a recent KQED program:
``Mobil, The Fuel That Powers Masterpiece Theatre.'' With gas
prices so high, he suggests, maybe we ought to forget about pledge
nights and make donations directly to Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Amy Tan &LR; , &UR; Oscar Hijuelos &LR; ,  &UR; Roy Blount Jr. &LR;  and  &UR; Dave Marsh &LR; 
sang last night at a New York party celebrating the release of
``Stranger Than Fiction,'' an Oglio records CD produced by San
Francisco's  &UR; Kathi Goldmark &LR; , to raise money for the PEN Writers
Fund. Marsh told the New York Daily News that he and his fellow
writers, included among 40 authors who perform on the album, ``play
music like Metallica writes novels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
