<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-BOS &LR;      04-07 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS HOPES TO PLAY IN JUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Jack Nicklaus arrived at Augusta National GC
Tuesday, was taken on a tour of the course by Masters tournament
chairman Hootie Johnson, hit a shot into the par-3 12th green and
said he is hoping to play in the Memorial Tournament at the course
he designed in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Just over two months after undergoing hip replacement surgery in
New England Baptist Hospital in Boston, Nicklaus has discarded the
cane he was using when he visited the Doral Open on March 4-5. He
now says he feels on schedule to play a tuneup event prior to the
Memorial (June 3-6) and may eye the three remaining major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   After attending Tuesday's past champions dinner, Nicklaus left
Augusta for his home in Hobe Sound, Fla., missing the Masters for
the first time since he played in the 1959 event as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus's physical problems began to mount last fall and
intensified to the point that he decided to undergo surgery in
Boston. In a remarkable recovery the past week, he went from
exercising in a swimming pool to playing four rounds of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the doctor this morning,'' said Nicklaus. ``He
said, `Go ahead and push it a little more. You'll find out what you
can do and what you can't do. Your body will tell you. I'll be
playing pretty solidly probably within the next two or three weeks,
and I think I'll make the Memorial. I might even play the week
before to get a little practice. Right now, the hardest thing is
walking the nine then playing 18 in a cart to see the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus started to talk of maybe the US Open at Pinehurst No.
2, the British Open at Carnoustie, and the PGA Championship at
Medinah. ``I'm 59,'' he said, ``and I'm certainly not going to
compete against the kids anymore. I feeI I'm not going to be that
competitive, but I didn't do this operation for golf. I did it more
so my wife didn't have to put up with me and having my hip dominate
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   What do his colleagues feel about playing the Masters without
Nicklaus? ``It's like your wife losing the diamond out of a wedding
ring,'' said Greg Norman. ``He put the Masters on the map for the
modern-day player. He is it, the Masters. it will be a sad weekend
without him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
