<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON'S FATE TO BE DETERMINED AFTER SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Coach Larry Robinson's future with the Los
Angeles Kings will be determined after the season, which almost
certainly will end on April 18, with the team out of the playoffs
for the third time in his four years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Kings decide they would like Robinson to return
next season, Robinson said Wednesday he is not certain he wants to
be back. ``I don't know,'' Robinson said following practice as his
team prepared for tonight's home game against the San Jose Sharks.
``It's been a tough year. When even my wife is finding it tough, I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearing the end of a season that began with great optimism, the
Kings are a dismal 28-43-5, and almost certainly would have to
finish 6-0 to have any chance at all of squeaking into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Kings management has deferred all decisions on personnel and
coaching until after the season. Robinson, whose tenure with his
team is longer than all NHL coaches other than Detroit's Scotty
Bowman and Edmonton's Ron Low, is in the final year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I think about it,'' Robinson said when asked if he's
been contemplating the fact that these could be his final days as
the Kings' coach. ``But it's not something I let keep me up at
night. What keeps me up at night is that we're not winning hockey
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his uncertain status, he added, ``It's not just me going
through it. We're a close family: (assistants Jay) Leach, (Rick)
Green, (Don) Edwards. We spend a lot of time trying to find ways to
make the team win. It's very draining on all of us, not just me.
Their jobs are at stake, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson dismissed a recent report in the Toronto Sun saying
he's been telling friends he plans to take next year off and spend
it on his farm in Florida. He did say that he has discussed with
General Manager Dave Taylor the possibility of taking another
position in the Kings' organization if he isn't back as coach.
Robinson said he would enjoy working at developing prospects if he
wasn't the coach.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted the season has worn him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to some of my friends back home,'' he said. ``They ask
me, `How are you?' I say, `Why?' They say, `Because you look
awful.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I never looked at whether I wanted to do (coach next year)
until my mother passed away (five weeks ago). At Christmas, I
talked to mom, and the first thing she said was `When are you
coming home?' It's sad, it was the last Christmas I had to spend
with her, and I wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at 47, Robinson said he wants to remain involved in
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm to leave this position, it's not to get out of the
game,'' he said. ``I still love the game.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE PUCKS: The Kings recalled winger Jason Podollan and goalie
Manny Legace from the Long Beach Ice Dogs and returned goalie Ryan
Bach to Long Beach. Podollan was acquired two weeks ago from
Toronto for center Yanic Perreault, and is expected to be in the
lineup tonight, his debut as a King. The moves with the goaltenders
are the result of an ankle sprain suffered by Jamie Storr last
week. ... Defenseman Garry Galley probably will miss the final six
games because of an abdominal strain. The injury had bothered him
in recent games. Trainer Peter Demers said Galley will undergo
tests to determine the proper course of treatment, with surgery a
possibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
