<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-HEALTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR HOUSING HURTING CHILDREN, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The doctors and nurses taking care of a boy with a
serious liver disorder thought they had everything lined up last
year when they sent him home, including a feeding tube to deliver a
sugar solution he needed through the night.
</P>
<P>
   But what they didn't factor in were the rats in the
17-year-old's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 o'clock one morning, Jorge Martinez's mother woke up to the
sound of rats scurrying around. She found the rats had chewed
through her son's feeding tube, spilling the sugar solution out
onto the floor and sending his blood sugar level dangerously low.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the ambulance,'' said Francisca Diaz, who works at a
nursing home as a nursing assistant, and is still looking for safe,
affordable housing for her and her son. ``He was shaking. His lips
were turning blue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything medically was in place,'' said Dr. Steven Chapman,
a pediatrician at the Greater Lawrence Family Health Center and one
of Jorge's providers, in recalling the incident. ``But what
happened is, they lived in an apartment that is just not a safe
place.''
</P>
<P>
   With the worsening housing crisis across the nation, children's
health is increasingly being threatened, according to the first
comprehensive national report about the crisis's impact on health.
</P>
<P>
   The story about Jorge joins others from Philadelphia, Seattle
and elsewhere in illustrating the growing problem chronicled by two
Boston Medical Center physicians and a San Francisco housing
advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Children are showing up at hospitals and doctors' offices with
rat bites, lead poisoning or asthma from exposure to cockroaches
and other pests, according to the report. Or they're going hungry
as more family income has to go to rent, rather than to nutritious
food. Or they're failing in school because their family has to
constantly move in search of housing.
</P>
<P>
   Across America, an estimated 14 million young children live in
housing with lead paint, and 10,000 children between the ages of 4
and 9 are hospitalized for asthma attacks each year because of
cockroach infestation, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are doctors interested in housing? People have trouble
understanding,'' said Dr. Megan Sandel, a pediatric resident at
Boston Medical Center and Children's Hospital, who along with
co-author Dr. Joshua Sharfstein brought Jorge's rat-bitten feeding
tube to a news conference, where the report was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a factor in my patients' lives. Not to consider it,
not to ask about it, ignores a facet of their life that impacts
their health. The best medical intervention that I can do for them
is to find better housing,'' said Sandel in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Last year one of her patients, an 18-month-old girl from the
Boston area, was hospitalized with internal bleeding in her lungs,
as a result of breathing toxins from a fungus growing in the
basement of her family's apartment. Luckily, she recovered, Sandel
said. Three children in Cleveland with the same housing-related
health problem died, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   But finding better affordable, safe housing around the country
has becoming increasingly difficult, as a result of cutbacks in
housing funds, coupled with skyrocketing rents.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976 federal housing funds have been cut by 61 percent
nationally, including a drastic reduction in so-called Section 8
housing vouchers, according to Randy Shaw, a San Francisco attorney
and housing advocate, and director of Housing America, a national
initiative launched this year to address the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no new Section 8 in three years,'' from 1996
through 1998, said Shaw. And the recent addition of 90,000 vouchers
for 1999 pales by comparison to the 200,000 new vouchers a year
that the federal government used to average.
</P>
<P>
   US Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo welcomed
the report as bolstering his agency's concerns about the housing
shortage. Cuomo, whose agency published its own study last month
detailing the difficulty families have finding good homes they can
afford, said, ``This new report confirms our warning that there is
an affordable housing crisis in this country and further, its human
impact is unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The new report calls for increased Section 8 vouchers,
protection of existing affordable housing units and an increased
low-income housing tax credit, among other steps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
