<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-SECRETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-PROFILE WAR HOLDS FEW SECRETS, WORRYING SOME EXPERTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All warfare is based on deception.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Chinese general Sun Tzu, ``The Art of War''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AVIANO AIR BASE, Italy _ Warriors through the ages have kept
their military tactics a closely guarded secret. Winston Churchill
called truth during warfare so precious that it must be shielded by
a bodyguard of lies.
</P>
<P>
   But the wisdom of war _ from Sun Tzu 2,500 years ago to
Churchill a half-century ago _ seems to have gone unheeded by NATO
in the high-tech age of military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Day in and day out during the conflict in Kosovo, commanders
from NATO headquarters in Brussels to US brass at the Pentagon have
given detailed explanations of their targets and their strategy.
Each nightly takeoff of warplanes is announced; new phases of the
offensive are elaborated days before they are put into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk too much _ plain and simple,'' said retired US Army
Major General William Nash, who served as a commander of troops in
Bosnia from 1995 to 1996 and now directs the Washington-based
National Democratic Institute for International Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (NATO and US military commanders) tell the media so much
that it loses meaning. The daily briefings are becoming cheerleader
sessions,'' said Nash, who taught a course on media and the
military at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government. ``It makes it
all a bit awkward, and a bit dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of this is a sincere desire on the military's part to
cooperate with the media,'' he explained. ``And some of it is a new
vogue in international relations, which is to talk to the other
side through live television. When they spell out the details of
sustained attacks it is designed to send a message to Milosevic
that this thing won't be stopping. They are using the media.''
</P>
<P>
   But this spin doctoring in war, many critics feel, is
ill-advised and potentially dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Spurgeon Keeny, a National Security Council member under
Presidents Kennedy and Johnson and now president of the Arms
Control Association, said daily ``boasts'' by military leaders of
the successes of the awesome power and sophistication of America's
laser-guided arsenal could have a ``boomerang effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gulf War was a television advertisement for America's
military competence. The world was amazed, and it projected a sense
of omnipotence. And we're doing the same thing again in Kosovo,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if we get mired down in the Balkans, there is a danger of
a secondary impact that exposes an American vulnerability. The bad
guys will ask, ``How come if these guys are so great, they can't
stop some ragtag Serbian troops on the ground?''
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking American military officer with experience in the
Balkans expressed even graver concerns. He said he worries that
Milosevic is taking all this information in and quietly planning a
retaliatory strike that may catch the NATO forces by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not lighting up his air defense half as much as he could.
He's waiting. And I think all this transparency helps him in
that,'' the officer, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said.
``It makes this triumphalism we see in the press conferences that
much more dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
