</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TURKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES AT TURKISH CAMPS WORRY ABOUT FAMILY LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS,
KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLARELI, Turkey _ Last week, Venera Limani, an 18-year-old
university student from Kosovo's capital, Pristina, lost her home
and all her belongings. Wednesday, on the border of Kosovo and
Macedonia, she lost her family.
</P>
<P>
   As she and hundreds of other refugees waited for buses headed
for the airport at Skopje, police began to separate the crowd at
random. Ms. Limani found herself being pushed forward as a
Macedonian policeman ordered her father and stepmother, three
brothers and a sister to step back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pushed them away and I didn't see them again,'' she said.
``I cried out, but the police weren't interested if they were
family or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, like many other refugees at a Turkish military encampment
near the Bulgarian border, Ms. Limani is waiting to see if her
family shows up. She has made sure their names are registered on
the computer list, but there's little else she can do.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the 2,768 refugees who have been brought here over
the last two days, the relief of being out of the teeming refugee
centers on the Kosovo border has been spiked with bitterness and
worry at being separated from their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are families coming from Macedonia whose mother and
father have gone to Norway while the sons and daughters are in
Turkey,'' said Turkhan Kazaz, a Kosovo Turk from Prizren who
managed to arrive with his family intact. ``People are getting on
planes not knowing where they were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the crush of refugees and their increasingly desperate
state, some confusion was probably inevitable. But some of the
refugees said the Macedonian police made no effort to keep families
together or to inform people of where they were going.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't ask us, they just told us to get in the bus,''
said Ms. Limani. ``They would say, `you go, you go, you stay.' When
we got to the airport in Skopje, they said we were going to
Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Merita Shala, also from Pristina, was lucky. When they tried to
separate her from her mother, she began to scream. Her mother was
allowed to join her on the bus but her brother was left behind in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey, which has agreed to accept 20,000 refugees from Kosovo,
moved quickly to get the refugee encampment here ready in time.
Originally built for the exodus of ethnic Turks from Bulgaria in
the late 1980s, the camp was later used to house Muslims driven
from Bosnia during its 1992-95 war; 177 of them still remain. As of
Wednesday, 900 tents had been erected, out of a planned total of
1,500, and 400 prefabricated huts were filling up fast.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm spring evening, children clambered over swings and
jungle gyms, teen-age boys played basketball while their mothers
filled buckets with water to wash the few clothes the Kosovo
families brought with them.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the heavily guarded camps, clusters of people _ some of
them Kosovo Albanians who lived in Turkey for more than a
generation _ waited to greet their long-lost relatives. Inside
there was a line for the telephones but it was not that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anywhere to call,'' said Ms. Limani.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit paid the refugees a visit
Wednesday, promising both to help them while they are here and to
help them return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call you our guests, not migrants, because we want you to
return to your homes as soon as possible,'' he told the cheering
crowd. ``We will do all we can to save your homeland from this
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   As they stood in line at dinner time to fill tin pots with
chicken and rice and their pockets with oranges, the refugees said
they were grateful for the Turks' warm welcome, particularly after
the nightmarish flight from their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Turks are so kind, but home is home,'' said Ms. Shala.
``We all want to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Limani said that if and when she does return to Pristina,
nothing will remain of her family's apartment. When Serbian police
arrived to order them out last week, the family was given no time
to collect their belongings, not even their documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us, `you must go quickly, quickly, quickly,' '' she
recalled, ``so we couldn't take anything. Like everyone we want to
be back in our homes, but we don't know if there will be anything
left. If the Serbs can't have our homes, they will destroy them and
we will have nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
