<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VEGGIE-LIBEL-HNS &LR;      04-07 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGGIE-LIBEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL OFFERED TO REPEAL TEXAS' `VEGGIE LIBEL' LAW &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legislation that would repeal a 4-year-old ban
on false disparagement of perishable foods, better known as the
``veggie libel'' law, was formally presented to a House committee
on Wednesday amid predictions it wouldn't reach the full House.
</P>
<P>
   The law, used unsuccessfully in the 1998 trial that pitted
Panhandle cattlemen against talk show host Oprah Winfrey, allows
farmers and ranchers to pursue monetary damages if their products
are publicly maligned with false information.
</P>
<P>
   In Winfrey's case, a federal judge in Amarillo never ruled on
the constitutionality of the Texas law but decided that the
cattlemen could not rely on it in their lawsuit. Left with only
standard business libel protections, the cattlemen failed in their
bid to recover damages for cattle-market losses that they
attributed to a 1996 Winfrey broadcast dealing with dangerous foods
and ``mad cow'' disease.
</P>
<P>
   While Winfrey said the outcome was a victory for free speech,
cattlemen and farmers responded that Texas needs the law to allow
recovery of damages when the target of libel is a foodstuff, not a
person. A year later, the still-raging debate led Rep. Ruth Jones
McClendon, D-San Antonio, to submit a terse bill that repeals the
1995 law. She contends other libel laws are sufficient to protect
farmers and ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an anti-agriculture bill. It has more to do with
preserving our rights to free speech than disputing the rights of
food,'' McClendon said. She said the law was passed with good
intentions, but ``is unfortunately so vague and ambiguous that its
merits are very, very questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   McClendon added that ``the veggie law stifles free speech by
people like Oprah Winfrey or you or me who may not mean to harm but
who are interested only in talking about public health and safety
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Winfrey declined an invitation to testify in favor of
McClendon's House Bill 126, but Tim Bennett of Chicago, president
of Winfrey's Harpo Productions, Inc., said Winfrey supports
McClendon's repeal bill because the food disparagement law is a
``catalyst for frivolous types of lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   He testified that Winfrey's attempt to air a helpful debate on
food safety resulted in a protracted court battle costing several
million dollars and a chilling effect on critics of food safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the law's author, Rep. Bob Turner, D-Voss, said it is
constitutional and serves an important purpose in protecting
agricultural interests without infringing on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill has made some people give some serious thought to
facts and truth in what they say. It definitely has stopped or
slowed disparaging remarks. That's for sure, and that's all I
intended the bill to do,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Oprah case had nothing to do with the bill, really. I
never dreamed there would be an Oprah case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in Winfrey's case were her vow not to eat beef and her
allowing a guest, vegetarian campaigner Howard Lyman, to
characterize beef as unsafe. Editing of the show was criticized as
unfair to the cattle industry.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he agrees with a suggestion of Rep. Harold Dutton,
D-Houston, to authorize a post-session study of the law to
determine if it needs ``tweaking,'' particularly its legal
definition of a ``perishable'' food product. The Amarillo federal
judge had questioned whether frozen sides of beef would qualify as
perishable.
</P>
<P>
   Turner predicted the House Civil Practices Committee, which left
McClendon's bill pending without taking a vote, would not send it
to the House floor because it would be greeted by significant
opposition from members who represent rural districts.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying against McClendon's repeal bill were dairymen,
cattlemen and agriculture groups.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Dutton said serious questions remain about the wisdom
of Turner's law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We protect broccoli better than we protect people in this
state,`` Dutton said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
