<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ President Clinton vows the NATO
alliance will continue military pressure on the Serbian-run
government of Yugoslavia, dismissing cease-fire overtures and the
possible release of three American GIs as insufficient. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   INVASION-SCENARIOS (Washington) _ Two scenarios are emerging for
an allied ground-troop sweep into Yugoslavia. Under one, the main
invasion force would be about 40,000 NATO troops massed in Hungary
who would head south to encircle Belgrade. Under the other, the
main invasion would come from 14,000 NATO troops already stationed
in Macedonia and an equal number in Albania. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has postponed
his announcement of his campaign for the presidency, saying it
would be inappropriate during a time of conflict. But the crisis in
Yugoslavia has been the best thing to happen to the only combat
veteran and former POW among announced or likely presidential
candidates. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ZHU (Washington) _ On the eve of meeting Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji, President Clinton says his policy to maintain open
relations with China will not change, despite recent events that
have highlighted fault lines in Sino-American relations. By
JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-GAS (Laredo, Texas) _ While droves of American tourists
cross the border into Mexico to shop blankets and beer, Mexicans
are driving to the U.S. side of the border for inexpensive
gasoline. A gallon of gasoline in Mexico costs about twice as much
as it does in the United States. By DANE SCHILLER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXPLOSIVES (Houston) _ A Freeport, Texas, gang known as
the Vatos Locos (``Crazy Dudes'') planned to use stolen plastic
explosives from Fort Hood to blow up the Freeport police station
and the home of a police officer, federal agents testify in hearing
for a gang member charged with drug trafficking. By MARK SMITH and
STEVE OLAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-MONEY (Austin, Texas) _ Blessed with a windfall from
last year's tobacco settlement, some health promoters are fighting
one another over how much should initially be spent on an
underfunded program to discourage Texans from smoking. By CLAY
ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-KOSOVO (San Antonio) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a
possible Republican presidential candidate, says it is in America's
best interest to ``stop genocide'' in Yugoslavia, but he cautions
that the United States must have a clear strategy in ending the
conflict. By MATT FLORES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DR-LOVE (Austin, Texas) _ The latest vision of Texas Health
Commissioner William ``Reyn'' Archer has proved too esoteric for
the Texas Legislature to comprehend. Indeed, the House
Appropriations Committee is questioning an job posting for a
position that is being dubbed ``Dr. Love.'' By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   VEGGIE-LIBEL (Austin, Texas) _ Legislation that would repeal a
4-year-old ban on false disparagement of perishable foods, better
known as the ``veggie libel'' law, is formally presented to a Texas
House committee. By JOHN W. GONZALEZ. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROAD-RAGE (Houston) _ Houston launches a program to curb
excessive speeding and aggressive driving between the rush hours to
