<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BIRTH-DEFECTS-468&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DATA ON BABIES OF WOMEN WITH BIRTH DEFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new report from Norway describes the first large study to
provide information about the lives of women with birth defects,
and the health of their children: the women are less likely than
others to have children, and those who do give birth run an
increased risk of bearing a child with the same birth defect that
they themselves have. But most children born to women with birth
defects are healthy, and they face no increased risk of any type of
defect except their mother's.
</P>
<P>
   The study, being published Thursday in The New England Journal
of Medicine, was based on the birth certificates of 459,433 women
born in Norway from 1967 to 1982, including 8,192 with birth
defects. Dr. Allen Wilcox, an author of the report and chief of the
epidemiology branch at the National Institute of Environmental
Health Science, said it would be almost impossible to conduct a
study of this kind in the United States, where about 150,000 babies
are born with birth defects each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the capacity to link a woman's birth records to
the birth of her children,'' Wilcox said. ``The system in Norway
offers a resource for epidemiologists that doesn't exist in most
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald Mattison, medical director for the March of Dimes, a
national birth defects foundation with headquarters in White
Plains, N.Y., said: ``It's a really good study. We're going to be
talking to our chapters about this. They end up working with
professionals who give counseling to families about their own risks
and those to their children.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, he said, provides information that was not available
before and could help people to estimate the risks of passing
specific birth defects along to their children. ``And it assures
them that they're not at greater risk for something other than what
they have,'' Mattison said.
</P>
<P>
   The March of Dimes estimates that there are 3,000 to 5,000
different birth defects, but the researchers conducting the new
study sorted their subjects' defects into 24 broader categories.
The more common ones included heart defects, cleft palate, cleft
lip, club foot and limb defects. Also counted were disorders of the
spine and nervous system and Down syndrome, which causes mental
retardation. The study included only defects that were obvious
enough when a child was born to have been noted on the birth
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Because some of the conditions were severe, death rates during
infancy and childhood were higher in the girls born with defects.
Nearly 20 percent had died by the age of 15, as opposed to only 2
percent of those without birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors with birth defects were less likely than other
women to have children of their own. By the age of 30, only 53
percent had given birth, as compared with 67 percent of the women
without birth defects.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the researchers did not know why fewer of the women had
children: they could not tell whether the women were less likely to
find partners, or chose not to become pregnant or were physically
unable to have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to distinguish whether it's social or
physical,'' said the first author of the study, Dr. Rolv Skjaerven,
of the division of medical statistics at the University of Bergen
in Norway. ``But we haven't done that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers speculate that some birth defects might have
an unrecognized link to infertility.
</P>
<P>
   Children of the women with birth defects did have a somewhat
increased risk of being born with the same defect as their mothers,
but the number actually affected was small. Of 1,613 children born
to 1,101 women, only 62, or 3.8 percent, had birth defects. Among
children born to the other women, 2.4 percent had birth defects,
meaning that the overall risk of any birth defect occurring in
children whose mothers had birth defects was only 1.6 times that of
children whose mothers did not.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 cases, mothers and children had the same birth defects.
They were cleft palate, cleft lip, clubfoot and limb defects, and
for those conditions, the children's risk ranged from 5 to 82 times
that of a child whose mother did not have that defect.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings were not surprising, researchers said, because it
has long been recognized that those disorders sometimes run in
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that was striking to us is the fact that women with
birth defects contribute such a tiny amount to the burden of birth
defects in the next generation,'' Wilcox said. Their children
accounted for only 5 out of 1,000 birth defects in the next
generation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Mekdeci, director of the Association of Birth Defect
Children, in Orlando, Fla., said, ``The good news was that these
women did not have a huge incidence of recurrence of birth
defects.''
</P>
<P>
   The lower birth rates did not surprise Ms. Mekdeci. ``Let's face
it,'' she said. ``If you're born with a major birth defect, you've
gone through a lot in your life and may not want to put a child
through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
