u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZHU-VISIT-HNS &LR;      04-07 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZHU-VISIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE WON'T CHANGE POLICY ON OPEN RELATIONS WITH CHINA &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JENNIFER DAY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of meeting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji,
President Clinton said his policy to maintain open relations with
China would not change, despite recent events that have highlighted
fault lines in U.S.-Sino relations.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, on a nine-day U.S. tour, arrived Wednesday in Washington
where recent reports have outlined espionage, illegal campaign
contributions from Chinese military intelligence officials, and
human rights abuses. Tensions also have been exacerbated by Chinese
objections to NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia and a U.S.-sponsored
United Nations resolution condemning human rights abuses in China.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have criticized Clinton's approach toward China,
believing the president is wrongly putting economic growth before
human rights and military concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not change our policy in a way that isolates China
from the global forces that have begun to empower the Chinese
people to change their society and build a better future, for that
would leave the people of China with less access to information,
less contact with the democratic world and more resistance from
their government to outside influence and ideas,'' Clinton said
Wednesday at the U.S. Institute for Peace.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that policy, the Clinton administration negotiated a
civil aviation agreement expected to be signed today that would
greatly expand air service between the two countries over the next
two years, White House officials revealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, three U.S. carriers _ United Airlines, Northwest
Airlines and Federal Express _ are permitted to provide a total of
27 flights weekly to three Chinese cities, Beijing, Shanghai and
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
   China's three international carriers currently can operate 27
flights to 10 U.S. cities, while funneling passengers to an
additional 10 American locations through ``code-sharing''
arrangements with U.S. carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will double the number of weekly flights from each
country to 54 by April 1, 2001. A fourth American carrier will be
permitted to fly to China, and U.S. airlines will be allowed to fly
to two more cities.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, U.S. carriers may sign code-sharing arrangements
with Chinese carriers to route passengers to another 10 Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese carriers will gain rights to fly to two additional
U.S. cities and sign code-sharing agreements for another 30
American destinations.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation agreement comes as negotiators are still trying to
work out a deal to allow China to join the World Trade
Organization, which enforces international trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stressed in his speech that Chinese membership in the
trade organization is in the United States' interest because it
would open Chinese markets to American businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is this: If China is willing to play by the
global rules of trade, it would be an inexplicable mistake for the
United States to say no,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL ADD END)
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators doubt whether China's admission to the trade
organization is in U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
   Majority leadership members from both the Senate and House, Sen.
Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Rep. Dick Armey, R-Irving, said they found
it difficult to support Chinese membership in the World Trade
Organization. Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., and Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., a ranking Democrat
on the Senate Commerce Committee, announced they would present
legislation requiring congressional approval for any deal allowing
China to join the trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   Two California representatives, Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, and
Christopher Cox, a Republican, held a joint news conference to push
Clinton to discuss human rights and allegations that China stole
U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Cox questioned whether the United States should trust China,
considering that it signed onto a human rights covenant, but
continued to crack down on democratic activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the track record, why should we believe that the
(People's Republic of China) will keep its promises for the
future?'' asked Cox, who headed a panel that investigated whether
sensitive military technologies were transferred to China.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
