<HEADER>
A9716 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DSL-SFCHRON &LR;      04-07 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DSL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A Faster Way to Surf the Web
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
You may have seen them while tooling around the Bay Area: ads on
billboards and buses that promise speedy Internet connections at an
affordable price.
</P>
<P>
   Called a digital subscriber line, or DSL, the new technology
lets home users access the Internet at speeds up to 50 times faster
than a traditional modem at a cost only two or three times that of
regular Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, which uses the same copper wires that provide
telephone service, lets users talk on the phone and surf the Web
simultaneously, without adding a second line. It also provides an
``always-on'' connection, meaning users don't have to dial their
Internet service provider each time they want to check out a Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, DSL service cost &UR;  &LR; more than $90 a month.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, prices started to tumble after Pac Bell lowered
its price on DSL service from $89 per month to $39 for unlimited
use. Customers still must pay for Internet service, which generally
costs another $10 to $20 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell also charges a one-time fee of $198, which pays for
installation, a DSL modem and a hardware card that's installed in
the computer.
</P>
<P>
   America Online plans to offer DSL service through Pacific Bell
to Californians by the end of the year for about $20 (on top of
AOL's $20 monthly service charge). Other companies, such as Covad
Communications, Concentric Networks and Northpoint Communications,
are selling DSL to ISPs, which offer the service to small- and
medium-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody can get DSL, and the technology is not without
flaws. Industry watchers say DSL may not be the right solution for
every Internet user.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, DSL looks great and it's very exciting, but ... how
good it's going to be in the home market is yet to be proven,''
said Nancy Kaplan, who follows the high-speed data market for
Renaissance Worldwide, a consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; It Has Problems
</P>
<P>
   ``You still end up with technical glitches and it's still very
new ..it definitely does have some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   DSL signals, which carry digital data, travel over the copper
phone wires that run between a customer's home to a Pac Bell
central switching office. Phone calls travel over the wire at a
very low frequency. DSL signals travel at a higher frequency over
the same wire and do not interfere with phone calls. That's why
users can talk on the phone and surf the Web simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   DSL is just one of several technologies competing to speed up
the Internet. Its closest competitor is the cable modem, which is
faster than DSL and costs about the same, but is not widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   DSL isn't available everywhere either. To get DSL, a user must
be within three miles of Pac Bell's central switching office.
That's because the farther the DSL signal travels, the more it
degrades. This limitation applies to all DSL service, because all
DSL providers in the Bay Area place their equipment at Pac Bell
central switching offices.
</P>
<P>
   While customers who live one mile from a central switching
office may get super-fast service, those who live 2.9 miles from
the office will have slower connections. Even at a distance of
three miles, Pac Bell guarantees speeds of 384 kilobits per second,
which is still seven times faster than the fastest dial-up modem.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone outside the three-mile radius is out of luck, at least
for now. Companies are working on ways to extend DSL's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding Service
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, Pac Bell plans to have 262 central offices
equipped for DSL. At that point, about half of Pac Bell's customers
in California should be able to get DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Since announcing the price drop, Pac Bell has been overwhelmed
by customers who want DSL service. The company has gotten about
three times as many calls as it expected and has had trouble
accommodating the demand, officials said. Some customers say
they've waited two weeks to get service, but Pac Bell says the
maximum wait is seven days and that it is hiring more technicians
to keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Once they've been hooked up, some customers have complained
about not being able to access the Internet. Others said they were
promised service and then told, on the day of installation, that
the service could not be installed because of in-home wiring
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dimmitt, vice president of consumer marketing at Pac Bell,
said he expects that the company eventually will have 2 million DSL
customers, but declined to say how many it has now.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Big Business
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say the DSL service is the answer for
telecommuters, most home offices and people who do a lot of Web
surfing. But they're not the answer for bigger companies or anyone
who can't tolerate temporary slowdowns.
</P>
<P>
   DSL, like cable modem and dial-up modems, suffers from
``bottleneck'' problems when thousands of users try to use the
service at once, said Greg Howard, principal analyst with the
High-Tech Resources Consulting Group in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Two other high-speed alternatives _ T1 and ISDN service _ do not
have as many bottleneck problems because there is one line for each
customer, although that customer may have many users. However, ISDN
is about three times slower than DSL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I subscribe to DSL at my home office and performance-wise, as
a home user, it is perfectly acceptable,'' Howard said. ``However,
as time goes on and more subscribers are added, I have to wonder
how my performance will be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said companies are working on ways to avoid bottlenecks,
but those solutions may be months away.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan agrees that DSL isn't for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal of DSL is small- and medium-size businesses and
users who don't go to the Internet enough to justify the expense of
a T1 line,'' Kaplan said. ``It's unlikely that DSL is going to be
universal. It's more of an interim service that people will take
advantage of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
