<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9719 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON &LR;      04-07 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 No Avoiding Dreaded Spam
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Help! I am being inundated with unwanted e-mail. I'm a
computer novice and don't know what to do about this problem.
Should I change my ISP, my e-mail address, or is there some
security feature on my computer that can help?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Welcome to the club. Almost everybody who uses e-mail
knows what it's like to log on and find your in-box stuffed full of
junk mail. Also called spam, these nuisance messages usually take
the form of advertisements for sleazy products, get-rich-quick
schemes or online pornography sites _ all pretty yucky stuff. By
some estimates, spam now accounts for more than one-quarter of all
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Spam, like regular junk mail, is sent to thousands of people at
the same time, using mailing lists. Spammers get addresses in a
number of ways, often buying them outright from ISPs or marketing
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's not a lot you can do to stop spam, and
changing your ISP or your e-mail address will bring only a brief
respite until spammers discover you again.
</P>
<P>
   There also is no truly effective spam-filtering software for
your PC. America Online lets you block messages from specific users
and Internet domains (the name to the right of the  &LR;  sign in an
e-mail address). But because AOL users get more spam than just
about anyone, that's not much comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, says Paul Hoffman, director of the Internet Mail
Consortium in Santa Cruz, ``you just have to learn to live with
it.'' He holds out hope, however, that new anti-spam technology
might bring relief in the near future. One San Francisco company,
Bright Light Technologies, already is selling a sophisticated
spam-filtering system to ISPs and is developing one for home users.
</P>
<P>
   My advice is to call your ISP and suggest that they get the
Bright Light system or one like it. In the meantime, you have my
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Backup System
</P>
<P>
   Q: My old Windows 3.1 backup software doesn't work with Windows
95, and there aren't any upgrades available for it. I was
considering a Zip drive, but someone suggested using recordable
CD-ROMs instead. The discs are less expensive than Zip cartridges,
and they hold much more data. Also, the data can be transferred to
any computer that has a CD-ROM drive. Is this a reasonable
direction to go for backups?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Seems to me you've answered your own question. CD-Rs, as
recordable CD-ROMs are known, provide excellent backup storage. A
CD holds up to 660 megabytes of data, compared with 100 megabytes
for a standard Zip cartridge. Plus, as you say, you can use them in
almost any PC, without the need for a Zip drive.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to create CD-Rs, you'll need a CD-R drive. That's
because regular CD-ROM drives can only read information off of
discs, not put data on them.
</P>
<P>
   But prices on CD-R drives are dropping fast. A basic model can
be had for under $200, though faster models can cost nearly twice
that much.
</P>
<P>
   Switching WebTV Service
</P>
<P>
   Q: We recently got a WebTV and are enjoying it a lot. My
question is: Can we use a different Internet provider? We pay
$24.95 a month for WebTV's service, but I hear others advertised
for less.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: WebTV would like you to use its Internet service, but the
company understands that some folks won't have a local dial-up
number for WebTV in their area, while others may want to use the
same ISP they have for their home computers. And still others, like
you, are determined to get the best possible deal on Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, you can use any ISP with WebTV. Check out the WebTV Web
site at  &LR; www.webtv.com &LR;  for details of their OpenISP policy.
</P>
<P>
   PC Turn On
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a new stay-at-home mother and am able to get on the
computer to access the Internet two or three times a day for short
periods. Which is better for the computer, to leave it on for eight
hours or turn it off after each use?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Leave the computer on (but not the Internet connection).
It won't hurt your system, and you'll save the time it takes to
boot up each time you want to use it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_  &UR; E-MAIL UPDATE: &LR;  In response to a question last week about using
e-mail at work for personal messages, I noted that bosses usually
can spy on employees' mail if they want. There is a way around
that, however. If you have access to the Internet at work, set up a
Web-based mail account with Hotmail or one of the big search
engines like Yahoo or Excite. That way, your mail will never go
through your company's e-mail system.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Want to follow your favorite baseball team throughout the season
even when you're not near a radio or TV? Several Web sites provide
pitch-by-pitch accounts of games, complete with instantly updated
statistics such as batting averages. Three popular sites are
 &LR; www.sportsline.com, www.espn.com  &LR; and  &LR; www.totalbaseball.com. &LR; 
Another site,  &LR; www.broadcast.com &LR; , offers live radio broadcasts of
most Major League games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
