<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VISIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE PREMIER'S US TOUR COMES AMID GROWING TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With anti-China criticism rising in Congress and resentment of
America spreading in China, Premier Zhu Rongji's current tour of
the United States could become the most important visit here by a
Chinese leader since Deng Xiaoping donned a 10-gallon hat at a
Texas rodeo in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   US-China relations have seesawed wildly in the intervening two
decades, from unbridled optimism through most of the 1980s to
hostility and confrontation for most of the 1990s. Human rights,
trade, and the balance of military power in East Asia all are areas
of friction not likely to be resolved any time soon. President
Clinton is a short-timer beset by critics.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Chinese have sent the most personable and pragmatic
of their top leaders to try to calm the roiling waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This visit is very important because the atmospherics are so
bad and the relationship is spiraling downward,'' says Thomas
Christenson, a specialist on US-China relations at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where Zhu will speak next
Wednesday after stops in Washington, Denver, Chicago, and New York.
``When things are going well, summits are window dressing. When
things are really bad, that's when visits like this are most
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu gave indications of what Americans could expect from him
even before he left Beijing, when a proliferation of accusations
that China was backsliding on its human rights commitments and
stealing US nuclear secrets led to speculation he would cancel the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions that ``my forthcoming visit is unlikely to
be successful,'' he added at a rare press conference: ``I will go
anyway to lend (Americans) a chance to vent their anger or
complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   William Alford, director of East Asia legal studies at Harvard
Law School, says this ``confirms what we heard about Zhu _ that he
is fearless, and smart enough to understand what this is about. The
major purpose of this trip may be the patching up, healing, playing
to the US audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between Zhu and Chinese President Jiang Zemin is
stark. Confronted by pro-Tibet demonstrators in Bern last month,
Jiang questioned Swiss officials' ability to run their country, and
told them they had lost a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, when Jiang, the last Chinese leader to visit the
United States, appeared at Harvard in 1997, questions that he would
be asked from the audience had to be submitted and screened in
advance. Zhu's representatives told MIT officials the premier
wanted the questions following his speech to be completely open.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts note that the modern history of US-China relations
has been a cycle of over-enthusiastic warmings and disillusioned
chills, and that this has been particularly true in the Clinton
Administration. The president picked a fight even before his
election, vowing to use trade as a weapon to make China respect
human rights, then backed down when China refused to yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton Administration has really exacerbated'' the
extreme swings in American attitudes toward China ``by mishandling
China policy for so long,'' Alford said. ``Clinton really oversold
how rosy things were (on his trip to China) last summer, for
domestic political reasons, and it was a disservice to public which
has come back to haunt us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had not oversold, and stayed closer to the underlying
reality,'' Alford said, ``the relationship would be less vulnerable
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself said, in a speech in Washington Wednesday, that
Chinese and Americans often holds extreme, inaccurate ideas of each
other's motives and policies, and argued that ``we have to follow a
different course.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Chinese had reason to help Clinton make his trip
last summer be seen as a success in the United States, whether it
actually was or not, the US now has an interest in having Zhu's
trip play as a success in China: The premier is seen as highly
intelligent, open to Western economic ways, and above the
corruption plaguing much of Chinese officialdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is tough, efficient, has a sense of humor, and is
self-deprecating,'' says Merle Goldman, a Boston University
professor who specializes in Chinese intellectual history. ``Of all
the Chinese leaders, he is the one with character traits which most
appeal to Americans. He is the best emissary they could send.''
</P>
<P>
   China specialists stress that the US-China relationship is bound
to be fraught with difficulties, given the enormous differences in
the two countries' histories, economies, and political systems.
But, they add, there are also common needs _ particularly for
market access and for political stability in northeast Asia _ which
provide strong incentives to both sides to do repair work when
relations fray too badly.
</P>
<P>
   Ezra Vogel, director of Harvard's Fairbank Center for East Asian
Research, suggests that the decision to persevere with the visit
despite the deepening problems ``reflects a decision in China that
even though relations will be on a bumpy road through the next (US
presidential election) it is important to keep them on track
nevertheless.''
</P>
<P>
   It is usual for the party out of the White House to criticize
the China policy of the sitting president, Vogel said, then to
learn to deal with China when it regains the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Chinese understand they are in for a tempest over
the next 15 months,'' Vogel said, ``and then things will get down
to business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
