<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-07 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MEANWHILE, IN ISRAEL ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bring an end to the expulsions and the killing in Kosovo,''
says Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon of Israel, which has a field
hospital in operation near the Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suffering of innocent people is unacceptable and must be
stopped immediately,'' the imposing ex-general adds, ``or even
earlier. All the people must be able to return in safety under full
autonomy, with the Serbian army out.''
</P>
<P>
   He lays great emphasis on this, monitoring my writing-down of
``immediately'' and ``autonomy,'' because of an additional concern:
``From a global view, I don't think the best solution is to change
the boundaries of Yugoslavia.'' The candid Sharon worries that a
``greater Albania'' might attract an assortment of Bin Ladenites,
Chechens and Hezbollah to complicate the control of terror in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That may turn out to be a farsighted assessment, but it seems to
me that the separation from Serbia of most of Kosovo is fit
punishment for Slobodan Milosevic's war criminality and a just
reparation for the uprooted and bloodied Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, running for re-election,
wants no part of that independence controversy. He says, ``The
Israeli government should not meddle in the future arrangements of
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Like hawkish doves and dovish hawks in America, Israelis are
afflicted with cognitive dissonance about the Balkan war. Many
remember help given Jews in World War II by anti-Nazi Serbs, and do
not identify with Muslim Kosovo Liberation Army leaders; this is
overwhelmed by their loathing of the way innocents are being loaded
into boxcars, evoking remembrance of sealed trains to Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, in New York Thursday, will go to Washington to confer
with Madeleine Albright, who will be focused mainly on the visit of
China's premier, Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   That's timely; one of the questions sure to be asked of Sharon
has to do with charges of the transfer of American technology. So I
put it to him: Have you guys been passing our secrets to China and
Russia?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say without doubt,'' says the foreign minister, ``that
there is no Israeli government policy to transfer any know-how
about sophisticated U.S. technology to any third country.''
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, Arik, that sounds a little artful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find any Israeli individuals doing any leakage,'' he
amplified, ``we'll cut it off right away. In fact, we heard of an
Israeli satellite-launching expert, working with an American
company, who may be trying to do some business in Russia. We need
specifics, but if it's true, we'll stop it. We'll fully cooperate
with the U.S. on this.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow last month, Netanyahu and Sharon made clear to Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov their concern about leakage of technology
to Iran and Iraq _ ``it's a danger to Israel, to Russia, to
Europe'' _ and supported U.S. pressure on Russian institutes
helping Iran's nuclear and missile work.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear that Arik has a fondness for Russian culture:
``my mother, working barefoot in the fields, recited Pushkin by
heart.'' He sees the Russians re-entering Middle East politics, and
wants to break the pattern of their usual 100 percent support of
the Arab side. (He's working with his Russian counterpart in a
long-shot try to spring Serbia's U.S. prisoners.) And he wants a
million more Russian Jews to immigrate to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're into politics. ``The key to next month's election is
the Russian Israelis,'' goes his analysis. They want better
Russian-Israeli relations, a free economy and a strong stand
against Arab claims. ``Two-thirds of the Russian Israelis are for
Bibi now. If I can get that up over 70 percent, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   His polls show Bibi's Likud with 38 percent, Labor's Ehud Barak
at 35 percent, the third-party candidate Yitzhak Mordechai 12
percent, right-winger Benny Begin 5, and 10 percent undecided. In
the runoff, Sharon thinks two-thirds of the Mordechai vote will go
to Barak and almost all the Begin vote will go to Bibi, with the
undecided splitting evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look too good a few weeks ago,'' he concludes, ``but
now there is a fair chance we'll win. It is _ what is your
expression? _ neck by neck!''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever's neck wins, Sharon is certain, a unity government will
be formed to deal with Yasser Arafat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
