<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-RATES-ART-760&AMP;     04-07 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-RATES-ART-760&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SOME ECONOMIES SOFT, EUROPEAN BANK CONSIDERS INTEREST RATE
CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Hans-Joachim Becker thought he had endured
the worst, until a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a managing director at Barmag AG, a manufacturer of textile
machinery near Duesseldorf, Becker pushed his company through a
brutal restructuring that eliminated 2,000 out of 5,000 jobs in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to work brilliantly. Sales bounced back to a nearly
record level of 1.1 billion marks last year and profit soared 49
percent, to 75 million marks.
</P>
<P>
   But now his market has collapsed because of financial crises in
Asia and Latin America. Orders for new machines have plunged 44
percent, and Becker predicts that sales this year will drop to 630
million marks, currently $347 million, from 1.1 billion marks, or
$606 million. Two hundred people were laid off last month and
another 200 may have to go before the year is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no investment in this business,'' Becker
said Wednesday. ``We have millions if not hundreds of millions of
consumers who are not able to afford a new shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Barmag's case is extreme, it is not unique and goes to
the heart of the challenge that confronts the European Central Bank
when it decides on Thursday whether or not to lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe that the new central bank, which has until
recently dismissed a need for rate cuts, has become sufficiently
alarmed about Europe's economic growth prospects and is about to
reverse course. The same is true for the Bank of England, which has
already cut interest rates several times in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is at stake. As guardian of a new single currency, the
European Central Bank is worried about establishing its credibility
with financial markets. It must also deal with contradictory
trends: growth is stagnant in Germany but still strong in Spain,
Portugal and Ireland; business confidence is low in many countries,
but consumers are more optimistic than they have been in years.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question is whether a moderate cut in interest rates
will make all that much of an improvement. Europe's biggest
problems stem from the decline in exports to Asia, Russia and Latin
America, where many countries are still in deep recession, and
those problems have very little to do with European interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have an expansionary monetary policy,'' said Petra
Koehler, a senior economist at Dresdner Bank here . ``Monetary
policy is not what is burdening the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, interest rates in the 11 euro-zone countries have been
at 3 percent since the individual central banks, acting in
coordinated fashion, lowered rates from 3.3 percent last December.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Europeans have cut rates less than the Federal
Reserve in the United States, the benchmark short-term rate is
still well below the American federal funds rate of 4.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Economists widely expect the Bank of England to cut its
benchmark rate by one-quarter of a percentage point, to 5.25
percent. Those who think that the European Central Bank will reduce
rates do not expect more than a quarter-point cut, which would put
the rate at 2.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's economic troubles have been aggravated because exports
of machinery and equipment were its major source of growth. Like
Barmag, which makes machines that produce and weave synthetic
fibers, scores of German engineering companies put themselves
through wrenching cost-reduction programs earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1997, German engineering companies cut their
combined work forces by more than one-third, to 925,000 from 1.49
million. But they also became shrewder about marketing and design,
and persuaded unions to be more flexible about overtime or weekend
work.
</P>
<P>
   Those strategies bore fruit over the last two years. Aided by a
decline in the value of the German mark, which made products
cheaper in other markets, German exports enjoyed double-digit
growth until Asian financial crises deepened early in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The problems have now sunk into many of Germany's and Europe's
biggest industries. The German chemical industry, led by companies
like BASF and Hoechst, saw exports decline by 9.5 percent in the
last quarter of 1998 and are only limping along, with selling
prices under intense downward pressure.
</P>
<P>
   For people like Becker, there is little the European Central
Bank can do to help. ``With overcapacity so high and prices so low,
there is nothing you can really do to stimulate the market,'' he
said. ``The market will come back only when the buying power of
consumers, mainly in Asia, comes back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Economists note that manufacturing is only once facet of German
business and that Germany does not represent all of Europe.
Consumer confidence, even in Germany, is generally higher than it
has been in a long time. Although retail sales remain flat, people
are warming up to the use of credit cards, spending money on travel
and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   While most economists predict that Germany will grow less than 2
percent this year, down from 2.8 percent in 1998, Spain is growing
by 3.4 percent, Portugal 4 percent, and even France is expected to
grow by at least 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those differences would make the European Central Bank's
decision tricky enough. But the bank is also concerned about
ensuring the credibility of the euro, which has dropped nearly 8
percent in value against the dollar since it was introduced on Jan.
4.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives have repeatedly said that they are not concerned
about the exchange rate, viewing it merely as a result of
underlying economic trends. But they are worried about being
perceived as too relaxed on monetary policy or too vulnerable to
political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The political pressures on the bank have in fact eased since
Germany's left-wing finance minister, Oskar Lafontaine, resigned
last month. In recent weeks, bank officials have dropped numerous
hints that they are more receptive to a rate reduction. They have
emphasized concerns about slowing economic growth and said they see
no signs of resurgent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Economists are about evenly divided between those who expect a
rate cut on Thursday and those who do not. But investors have been
betting on a reduction _ if not on Thursday, then at the next
meeting on April 22 _ and they have expressed that view by pushing
down the value of the euro, which settled in New York Wednesday at
1.0772 to the dollar, down from 1.0848 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a clear decision, and there are several arguments
against it,'' said Stephan Bergheim, an economist at Merrill Lynch,
who is nonetheless betting on a rate reduction.
</P>
<P>
   A cut, he noted, would provide a bit of insurance against a
deeper economic slowdown. But it could also lower the euro's value
further and rekindle price pressures _ particularly with recent oil
price increases.
</P>
<P>
   What a rate cut would not do, he said, is rescue German industry
from its current doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason for the slowdown is export-related,'' he said,
``and there is not much that the ECB can do about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
