<HEADER>
A9728 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRONICFILING-HNS &LR;      04-07 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTRONIC FILING OF CAMPAIGN REPORTS GETS STRONG BACKING &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 FILING-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer and public interest groups teamed up
with lawmakers from both major parties Wednesday to strongly
endorse legislation to require state political candidates to file
their campaign finance reports electronically.
</P>
<P>
   The concept also picked up the conditional endorsement of Gov.
George W. Bush, who voluntarily filed his reports electronically
last year after the Houston Chronicle reported that he had failed
to keep a 1994 promise to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the requirement, which some other states already
have, would allow voters to more easily learn who is financing
races for public office by simply turning on their home computers
and connecting to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal ran into strong opposition from a key Democrat,
state Rep. Debra Danburg of Houston, chairwoman of the House
Elections Committee. She argued that it would benefit relatively
few people and require expensive software and other changes at the
Texas Ethics Commission to put in place.
</P>
<P>
   The Elections Committee heard testimony Wednesday afternoon on
several electronic filing bills but took no action.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, the concept was endorsed by Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry, the House Republican Caucus and the leadership of the Texas
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor ``supports
major candidates having to file electronically'' so that voters can
make ``informed decisions.'' However, the governor is not endorsing
a specific bill, and several have been filed on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are divided. Several Democratic legislators are
sponsoring electronic filing bills. But in addition to Danburg's
opposition, the Texas Democratic Party has reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Cook, the party's executive director, said Democratic
leaders were concerned that modestly funded candidates would be
hurt by the requirements to file electronically, even though
several bills would exempt candidates who spend little money.
</P>
<P>
   Both major parties have opposed mandatory electronic filing in
the past.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fred Lewis, an Austin attorney who heads a nonpartisan coalition
seeking electronic filing, said the bills would require candidates
and committees to file their finance reports by modem or diskette
for public review.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes the data available to the public immediately
because once it's filed it can be placed on the Internet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates for statewide office and the Legislature already
voluntarily file their contribution and expenditure reports
electronically with the Texas Ethics Commission. The bills that
would require electronic filing would exempt candidates who raise
and spend only limited amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those exceptions, Danburg said, many candidates would
have to spend a lot of money on a ``bunch of computer
technicians,'' when they could be spending the money on other
campaign activities.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
