<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-NYT &LR;      04-07 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARNS 9 YUGOSLAVS OF POSSIBLE WAR-CRIMES PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS,
KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO) 
(mk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department warned nine Yugoslav
commanders Wednesday that they faced possible prosecution for war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commanders can be indicted, prosecuted and, if found guilty,
imprisoned not only for crimes they themselves commit, but also for
failing to prevent crimes occurring or for failure to prosecute
those who commit crimes,'' the State Department spokesman, James
Rubin, said at the opening of his press briefing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin reiterated that the United States would provide evidence
to the international war crimes tribunal. The NATO spokesman in
Brussels, Belgium, Jamie Shea, has said repeatedly that NATO
governments would do just that.
</P>
<P>
   But tribunal officials raised questions Wednesday about whether
NATO actions matched the rhetoric, and there were also questions as
to what the tribunal was doing to gather evidence. Rubin said that
much of the evidence that the United States had against the nine
commanders came from interviews with refugees. Villagers are often
able to identify military units operating in an area, and it would
not be difficult for NATO to know the commanders of various units.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably missing from the State Department's list of
commanders was the Yugoslav commander-in-chief and president,
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking on the condition of anonymity, two senior American
officials, from different agencies of the government, said
Wednesday that they had no doubt that Milosevic bore responsibility
for the atrocities in Kosovo and should be indicted.
</P>
<P>
   One of them said he would personally like to deliver the
indictment to Milosevic. He added: ``I think there are a lot of
candidates that want that delivery job.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said Wednesday that he
would like to see Milosevic indicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me personally, I would say yes,'' he should be
indicted, Solana said in an interview with the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the view of NATO's supreme military commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark, a person who met with him recently said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One problem the allies face in considering whether to push for
the indictment of Milosevic is political: It would be hard for the
allies to negotiate with Milosevic if he were an indicted war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of evidence. The United States has
evidence that from the beginning, Milosevic sought to build a fire
wall around himself, to distance himself from indictable criminal
acts carried out against Muslims during the war in Bosnia, a senior
American official said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has been in meetings where brutal operations against
civilians were discussed, but he has allowed his underlings to do
the talking, apparently fearing that the conversations might be
monitored by sophisticated listening devices, according to American
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever evidence the United States has gathered from
eavesdropping or telephone intercepts, it would be reluctant to
turn over to the tribunal for fear of exposing sources and methods,
American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said Wednesday that the
department would make some information ``of an intelligence
nature'' available to the tribunal, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   At the tribunal Wednesday, the deputy prosecutor, Graham
Blewitt, expressed some irritation with the NATO allies and their
promises to help develop evidence of war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the repeated statements out of Washington and
Brussels that war crimes were being committed in Kosovo and those
responsible would be punished, Blewitt said, ``that causes us some
frustration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being tantalized with this evidence,'' he said, adding
that the tribunal had not received as much as it expected from the
United States, Britain and other NATO countries based on their
public statements.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt declined to say how much the tribunal itself was doing
to gather information.
</P>
<P>
   One tribunal official said that investigators were being taken
off other cases to work on the Kosovo cases. He declined to give
the number.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the tribunal had six people working on Kosovo, out
of a staff of nearly 800.
</P>
<P>
   American officials and human rights workers working among the
Kosovo refugees, who have personal accounts of atrocities, said
they did not believe that more than one tribunal investigator was
now in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin identified the Yugoslav commanders who have been warned as
follows:
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Milos Mandic, 252nd Armored Brigade in central Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maj. Gen. Vladimir Lazarevic, Pristina Corps.
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Mladen Cirkovic, 15th Armored Brigade, headquartered in
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Dragan Zivanovic, 125th Motorized Brigade, headquartered
in Kosovska Mitrovica and Pec.
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Krsman Jelic, 243rd Mechanized Brigade, headquartered in
Urosevac.
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Bozidar Delic, 549th Motorized Brigade, headquartered in
Prizren and Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Radojko Stefanovic, 52nd Mixed Artillery Brigade,
headquartered in Gnjilane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Col. Milos Djosan, 52nd Light Air Defense Artillery-Rocket
Regiment, headquartered in Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maj. Zeljko Pekovic, 52nd Military Police Battalion,
headquartered in Pristina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      04-07 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: MINUTES OF FED'S MEETINGS INCLUDE INTRIGUING
PHRASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The minutes of the Federal Open Market Committee, the
policy-making arm of the Federal Reserve, can be more illuminating
than the cryptic utterances of the central bank's chairman, Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the minutes from each meeting, though, is delayed
until after the next meeting is held, usually about six weeks
later. And by then the group's members _ Fed governors and some
presidents of the regional reserve banks _ have often conveyed
their thoughts to the financial markets in speeches and other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the minutes from the November, December and February
meetings describe an important shift that has gone largely
unnoticed. Changes in just a few words indicate that Fed
policy-makers have all but discarded hope that the economy will
slow down significantly this year.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy does not slow, the Fed will be more likely to
raise interest rates later this year. Higher rates are used to
reduce the inflationary pressures that generally build in a rapidly
expanding economy but that have been nonexistent of late.
</P>
<P>
   Whether an economic slowdown materializes or not, the mere
expectation of one has helped persuade the Fed's policy-makers to
hold off raising short-term interest rates in recent years. With
such expectations dashed, they might have to adjust their thinking
as well, especially if inflation starts to rise moderately.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are beginning to recognize _ this is the process that you
are seeing in the minutes _ that their forecast for any type of
slowdown this year is not going to happen,'' said Ian Shepherdson,
chief U.S. economist at High Frequency Economics in Valhalla, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are changing their mind,'' he added, ``then it becomes
a question of when will they raise interest rates, not if they will
raise interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the minutes of the November meeting, with the
world's financial markets still in turmoil following Russia's
effective debt default, the central bank staff that prepares
economic forecasts for the policy-makers said that the economy
would slow ``to a pace appreciably below the estimated growth of
the economy's potential,'' which officials have suggested is around
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean a slowdown from the 6 percent pace of the fourth
quarter to a pace much closer to 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By December, when American financial markets were rallying
again, the hope for such a slowdown was fading. According to that
meeting's minutes, the staff was then forecasting that growth in
the year ahead would slow ``to a pace somewhat below the estimated
growth of the economy's potential.''
</P>
<P>
   And in February, according to minutes released last week, any
suggestion of a significant slowdown seemed to vanish.
</P>
<P>
   The staff now predicted a slowdown ``to a rate commensurate with
the growth of the economy's potential,'' or about 2.5 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the policy-makers seemed to think the economy might be even
stronger than the staff suggested. Committee members, according to
the minutes, expected growth to slow ``to a pace close to or
somewhat above that of the economy's long-term potential.'' And
many members agreed that the biggest risk was that the economy
would grow at an even faster pace.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's meeting, Fed policy-makers left interest rates
alone. And they apparently left their policy indicator on neutral _
which means that in their view the next move on interest rates,
whenever that might be, is just as likely to be up as down.
</P>
<P>
   But the rising expectations for economic growth, as reflected in
their subtle word changes, may herald a change in attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Stand by. The minutes of the March meeting are scheduled for
release the third week of May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
