<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIANS-TRANSLATE-B     04-07 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIANS-TRANSLATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN-AMERICANS SOUGHT AS TRANSLATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The crisis in their ancestral land hit home Wednesday
for dozens of Albanians in Boston, as the Red Cross began reaching
out to them to sacrifice a month of their time to help translate
for 20,000 refugees expected to arrive this week in Guantanomo Bay,
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Now, students, business owners and retirees in the Boston area _
the nation's second-largest Albanian American community _ are
wrestling with just how much they want their lives to be entangled
in this growing crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying to them `We need your help,' '' explained Renita
Hosler, spokesperson for the Boston chapter of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The organization combed the Internet, and called churches and
radio shows, seeking people who speak the Albanian language and
know the Albanian culture. More than 120 callers have responded to
the plea, but most have been non-Albanians who can't speak the
language, said Hosler.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just really want to help,'' she said. ``But we need to be
prepared. We need to have speakers of the Albanian language.''
</P>
<P>
   William Botka is one who received the Red Cross's call. A
first-generation Albanian American, Botka said he and his wife,
Harriett are willing to sacrifice their time to help those in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need some help. This is horrendous. This has gone on much
too long,'' said Botka, a retired businessman from Framingham.
``There will be a lot of people at odds with themselves (in Cuba) _
happy to be away from where they were but still not living the kind
of life they are use to living. Nobody wants to be a refugee.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Americans say refugees, some already separated from
their families, are wary of living even temporarily in a place so
far from their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are mixed feelings. First of all, at least they
will be in a safe environment and some will be with their family
members,'' said The Rev. Arthur Liolin, chancellor of the Albanian
Orthodox Archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   But Liolin and other local Albanian Americans said they were
sure the refugees are hungering for a return to a peaceful Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely sure that 99 percent of the Albanians want to
go back to Kosovo,'' said Ferik Abdullai, a native of the former
Yugoslav republic of Macedonia. ``But for them _ it's a welcome
change anywhere they go, but the bottom line is everyone wants to
go back home after the situation is resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced earlier this week that it was willing
to take 20,000 Kosovar Albanians as part of the NATO effort to
relocate about 120,000 refugees who would be airlifted out of the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Military authorities believe refugees could arrive at Guantanomo
Bay within the next two days, said Barry Higginbotham, spokesperson
for the Atlantic Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday the first of 350 military engineers are expected to
arrive at the base to build 1500 tents which will house the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 28 stretched tents, used in the early 1990s when
51,000 Cubans and Haitians were housed at the base, are already
available. Those tents will be used as schools, hospitals, and
kitchens, said Higginbotham.
</P>
<P>
   The local Red Cross is only anticipating that they will be
called to help out because the Boston-Worcester area, with an
estimated 60,000 Albanian Americans, is one of the largest
communities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the local Albanians are orthodox christians, sharing the
same religion as the Serbs but not the same culture, said Liolin.
The first Albanian immigrant arrived in Massachusetts around 1886,
he said. But sometime around 1912, during the beginning of the
Balkan War, hundreds of Albanian immigrants arrived in Boston and
Worcester, creating a large community.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Red Cross officials worry they will have a hard time
recruiting a few dozen people who are willing to be away from home
for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the realistic side _ it's very hard to pack up a
suitcase and leave families and a job for a month,'' said Hosler.
``Some would like to help but they know they have their lives they
need to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Those willing to go to Cuba are likely to be retirees and
students, said Regina Szwadzka, a coordinator of International
Services for the Boston chapter of Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers must be willing to stay for a three-week assignment
and to be trained to deal with mental and psychological anguish of
the refugees, said Szwadzka.
</P>
<P>
   Even local Albanian American students, eager to help, are
worried they could miss their final exams, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullai said he wishes he could travel to Cuba but he must tend
to his Pizza restaurant in Webster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very glad to help my people in Albania but what am
I going to do with my restaurant?'' he said. ``If I go then my
business will go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rev. Liolin, who has been calling members of his church,
insists that many area residents of Albanian ancestry will answer
the call for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just starting,'' he said. ``The response is very
favorable. People really want to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
