<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five Georgia firms repeat Fortune 500 performances
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot, United Parcel Service, BellSouth,
Coca-Cola and Delta Air Lines turned in repeat performances this
year on the latest list of the 500 biggest U.S. corporations,
Fortune (April 26) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked by sales, they were first through fifth among companies
headquartered in Georgia, for the second straight year. But while
Home Depot was tops on the Georgia list, it ranked 32nd on the list
of 500.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings are based on fiscal 1998 financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 15 Georgia-based companies are among the prestigious
Fortune 500. In order, the others are Coca-Cola Enterprises,
Georgia-Pacific, the Southern Co., SunTrust Banks, AFLAC, Genuine
Parts, First Data, Shaw Industries, Flowers Industries and AGCO.
</P>
<P>
   The top five nationally are General Motors, Ford Motor, Wal-Mart
Stores, Exxon and General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia ranks 11th in the nation as a headquarters state, with
15 companies, and metro Atlanta ranks fourth among cities with 11.
New York state and New York City topped both those lists.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Coca-Cola and Georgia-Pacific have made the most
frequent appearances on Georgia's top-five list. Starting in 1997,
economic problems in Asia and elsewhere affected Georgia-Pacific's
performance. It ranks seventh among Georgia companies on the latest
list.
</P>
<P>
   The Fortune 500 list was composed of industrial corporations
until 1995, when the magazine's editors decided to diversify the
list to reflect the increasing role of service companies in the
U.S. economy. That was the first year that BellSouth and Delta Air
Lines made the list.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   _ Corporations have always had a public relations problem with
populist-minded Americans, and the latest battleground is the Web.
Business Week (April 12) says hundreds of Web sites have been
created by a variety of disgruntled consumers and business critics.
The criticism is defended by the Supreme Court as a First Amendment
right, which has forced corporations to learn to fight back on the
Web, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many small vendors are willing to take their lumps as the
price of doing business with Wal-Mart, the world's biggest
retailer, according to Inc. (April). But Chuck Mitchell, the CEO of
a small company that makes automatic gates, took his beef against
Wal-Mart to court in David and Goliath fashion _ and got his money
back. _ The revamped Georgia Trend (April) is out with its annual
economic yearbook, which looks at Georgia's economy from the
mountains to the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
