<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DuPont to invest $220 million in WebMD
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD said Wednesday that chemical giant DuPont will
invest $220 million over five years in the Atlanta-based Internet
medical services provider and take two seats on its board.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with DuPont is the latest in a string of big deals
WebMD has recently struck. Among others are agreements with CNN and
Lycos. The company has raised $70 million from various partnerships
since July and is planning to go public sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The investment will make DuPont WebMD's largest single source of
revenue and greatly advance the company's goal of becoming the
leading brand for health care services on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the Amazon.com of health care for the Web,''
said WebMD Chairman and Chief Executive Jeff Arnold, referring to
the Net's largest seller of books and music CDs. ``This investment
is a vote of confidence in our company.''
</P>
<P>
   What DuPont gets in exchange for its investment is a
high-profile start for a new unit called Digital Consumer Health,
which will provide online medical and health information.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, DuPont becomes WedMD's exclusive
provider of information about medicines, vitamins and nutrition.
WebMD will use that information to create a new section on its
popular site dedicated to what both companies call life sciences.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont's pharmaceutical arm is one of the largest makers of
drugs and vitamins. Its brands include AIDS treatment drug Sustiva,
anticoagulant Coumadin and Revia, which helps alcoholics curb the
desire to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important new step for DuPont,'' said Kurt
Landgraf, a DuPont executive vice president. ``WebMD is the first
place consumers will meet DuPont on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched early last October, WebMD is a play for the attention
and pocketbooks of some 30 million people who search the Internet
for medical information. These people spend an estimated $150
billion annually on medical services, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
   WebMD is trying to lure both consumers and doctors and put the
two in touch with one another through its Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Access is free for consumers but doctors pay $29.95 a month to
use WebMD's various Internet services. More than 2,000 doctors have
subscribed to those services so far, said Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Services for doctors include an online medical library,
real-time insurance verification and continuing medical education
courses.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont's investment will play a key role in expanding the pay
service for doctors, said Arnold. He explained that $180 million of
the money would be used to buy subscriptions for physicians. WebMD
will use those subscriptions as trial memberships for doctors as
well as in other promotional efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining $40 million buys DuPont its exclusivity as WebMD's
provider of pharmaceutical and related information.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont will also get an undisclosed equity stake in WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between WebMD and DuPont extends beyond information.
DuPont will also help recruit other pharmaceutical companies to
WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Explained Arnold, ``DuPont will quarterback a larger effort for
us to pull the pharmaceutical industry together behind our
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
