<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      04-07 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO COMMANDER SEEKS MORE AIR POWER TO PRESS ATTACK AGAINST
YUGOSLAVS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS, KOSOVO-POLL,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO's senior military commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark, said on Wednesday that he wanted significantly more
American and allied warplanes to intensify NATO's attack on
Yugoslavia, and the Pentagon assured him he would get whatever he
needs.
</P>
<P>
   With the allies continuing to rule out ground forces and engaged
in a military operation tougher than expected, Clark has been
forced to seek still more air power and employ new tactics. These
have included stepped up patrols over Kosovo, luring the Serbs out
of their hiding places so they can be bombed and low-level attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As the third week of bombing began, Clark said he was
considering several options to further expand the alliance's
striking power, but declined to disclose details. A senior NATO
official said the general wanted ``vastly increased assets'' over
the 600 aircraft already involved. A major aim would be to improve
NATO's ability to bomb Yugoslav armored forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen, who met with Clark on
Wednesday at the general's headquarters near Brussels, said the
Pentagon would provide whatever forces the commander needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever General Clark feels he needs to carry out this
campaign successfully, he will receive,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for intensifying the military campaign came as Slobodan
Milosevic has sought to exploit tensions within the Western
alliance by declaring a unilateral cease-fire and offering to
negotiate with the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has rejected Milosevic's proposal as sorely deficient. But
Belgrade's maneuvers have increased the pressure on the alliance to
break the will of its adversary before political factors interfere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no time to pause,'' Cohen said at NATO headquarters on
Wednesday. ``We will reject any settlement that freezes the results
of Milosevic's genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Military officials noted that the Serbs did not appear to be
observing their own cease-fire. ``We've seen no change in the
pattern on the ground,'' Clark said. ``In fact, we've seen the
opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the raids began on March 24, the United States and its
allies have steadily increased the number of aircraft involved in
the attack. After the Yugoslav military surprised NATO by launching
a brutal campaign to evict ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, the number
of warplanes grew from 430 to more than 600, including 75 combat
and support aircraft on the aircraft carrier Theodore Roosevelt,
which joined the raids on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, NATO flew 439 bombing, fighting and support
missions, the largest number since the campaign began. The planes
pounded command posts, fuel depots, air defenses and, according to
a NATO military spokesman, scored its first major ``breakthrough''
against Serbian forces in the field.
</P>
<P>
   That occurred when a patrol of British Harrier jet caught a
Serbian armored column on the move north of Pristina and attacked
it with cluster munitions. The NATO spokesman, Commodore David
Wilby, said that some of the seven to 12 vehicles in that column
were damaged or destroyed. But he acknowledged that other attempts
to bomb Serb columns were not successful.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, appear to be preparing for a long and
grueling fight. Yugoslavia's strategy is to ride out the allied air
strikes in the hope that NATO's unity will crack. On Wednesday,
Western military officials said the Serbs are continuing to hunker
down and hide their tanks and heavy weapons in churches, forests
and near civilian buildings.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has also received reports that the Serbs might be herding
some of the fleeing Albanians back from border areas and putting
them near Yugoslav military forces in an effort to ward off allied
attacks. Allied officials said, however, that they could not
confirm these reports. The alliance has sought to counter the Serbs
by employing new tactics. One approach, an allied military officer
said, is to maximum the element of surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces, for example, had become accustomed to leaving their
hiding places soon after allied military planes pass overhead,
trying to take advantage of gaps in the allied patrols to attack
the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   So NATO warplanes have been changing the timing of their combat
flights to make them less predictable. Sometimes planes have been
sent soaring over Serb positions with other allied aircraft flying
close behind. NATO has also stepped up its day-time patrols, hoping
to catch Serb columns on the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ramped up operations,'' Wilby said on Wednesday. ``We
are keeping aircraft over the area as long as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   British Harriers, for example, are no longer attacking in group
of six aircraft. Instead, they are attacking in pairs, which
maximizes the time they can loiter over the battlefield. The
French, too, have stepped up their low-level attacks, using Jaguar
and Super-Etendard aircraft. Even with better weather and new
tactics, Clark made it clear that Yugoslavia's military remains a
potent enemy that required still more firepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia has a very, very significant military
infrastructure and a full array of military forces, with alternate
and secondary positions, with storage depots, very well concealed
and dispersed,'' he said. ``There are many, many targets that have
not been struck. We know where they are. We're coming after them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Clark's request, the United States has already dispatched
another dozen F-117 ``stealth'' fighters and five B-1 bombers. The
Pentagon has also approved the deployment of 24 Apache helicopter
gunships to Albania, though officials said it could take a week or
longer to send them.
</P>
<P>
   General Clark's request for additional air power first arose at
a meeting with the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen.
Henry Shelton, who visited NATO's headquarters on Tuesday. A
Pentagon official familiar with the discussion said that Clark felt
he could make better use of the clear skies if he had more planes.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the official said, Clark believed the campaign
could use additional A-10 jets, designed to kill tanks, and B-1
bombers, which are able to drop enormously lethal clusters of bombs
on ground forces. Although Italy's air fields are already
overcrowded, the official said NATO could not take full advantage
of the recent good weather because it had no more planes to use.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is he's got more than he can handle when there's
bad weather,'' the official said, referring to the many nights NATO
has had to scrub bombing runs because of rain and clouds. ``What he
wants are more assets when there's good weather.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
