<SLUG> BC-SALON-WELL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salon.com buys pioneer Net site
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Salon.com, the online magazine of politics, arts and
opinion, has acquired a pioneering Internet community, the Well
(www.well.com).
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The Well was founded in 1985 by Stuart Brand, publisher of the
Whole Earth Catalogue, and technologist Larry Brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the Internet, before the World Wide Web,
the Well was a hot destination for Net surfers looking to connect
with like-minded souls. It featured discussion groups on a variety
of topics including parents of children with disabilities, Grateful
Dead fans, jazz aficionados and gardening.
</P>
<P>
   The Well is a members-only (about 7,000 members) community,
which costs $10-15 per year depending on the type of service. Salon
says it will continue to operate it as a distinct online community
linked to the newly revamped Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com, which changed its name and added more staff and areas
to its Web site Monday, says the Well complements what Salon is
trying to do. ``The Well and Salon have a shared heritage of
stimulating conversation,'' said former Well owner Bruce Katz in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   David Talbot, Salon founder and chief executive, moved the
magazine into the limelight last year with its controversial
coverage of the Clinton impeachment scandal. Talbot saw the Well as
a model for what he said was ``community-building that the Net
makes possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Well Executive Director Gail Ann Williams said there has always
been a friendly relationship between the two companies. Cliff
Figallo, Salon's director of community development, was the Well's
second director. Another Salon staffer, Table Talk host Mary Beth
Williams, also hosts a free-lance writers conference on the Well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very strong ties, and we have always been very aware
of each other,'' Williams says. ``The founding members of Salon did
some of the primary planning in a private conference on the Well.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the Well and Salon are respectful of each other's
online communities. ``The Well is an existing community, and
Salon's Table Talk is also an established community with its own
relationships. And there's no reason to mess with that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Salon hopes to be able to draw on the Well's ability to build
and maintain a subscription-based revenue stream, but Williams says
it's too soon to say just how.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so early for us,'' she says. ``I feel like a pioneer. I
was a pioneer when I logged onto the Well in 1990, and I feel like
a pioneer again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
