<HEADLINE>
BC BUYS PROPERTY IN DUBLIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Boston College has purchased two Georgian townhouses
on St. Stephen's Green in Dublin, the first step to what the school
hopes will ultimately become a BC campus in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston College Center in Ireland, as it will be known when
it opens in the fall, will house the newly created BC-Ireland
Corp., as well as the school's Irish Institute, and will provide
library and administrative resources for student exchange programs.
</P>
<P>
   The plans for an Irish campus are still at least several years
away.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, BC officials see the purchase of the property as a
badge of true green: they point out that the University of Notre
Dame, BC's traditional rival, has only rented property in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The school said the center would establish BC as the preeminent
US university working in Ireland, and serve as the hub of BC's
outreach to political, business, and education leaders in Ireland
and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it also has great symbolic meaning,'' said BC
president the Rev. William Leahy. ``It represents a recommitment to
the homeland of BC's Jesuit founding fathers who invested so much
of themselves in establishing Boston College 136 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The property, renovated 254-year-old buildings at 42 and 43 St.
Stephen's Green, is close to Grafton Street and the Irish
Parliament buildings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX-08     04-07 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-COX-08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    FEARS GROW THAT RETURNING REFUGEES MAY BE USED AS HUMAN SHIELDS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 750
 &HT;    NOTE: The State Department warned nine Serb commanders about
possible war crimes. They are named separately at the end of this
story.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Yugoslav troops sealed a crowded Albanian border
crossing Wednesday, ordering tens of thousands of refugees fleeing
Kosovo to turn back and march into an area where NATO warplanes
have focused furious attacks in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Amid fears that the civilians might be used as human shields,
the Pentagon said the refugees could complicate attacks on Yugoslav
troops and tanks. At the same time, the State Department warned
nine Serb commanders by name that they could be held accountable
for any war crimes their forces commit.
</P>
<P>
   The warning came on a day when NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said
Yugoslav troops had already begun holding ethnic Albanians as
``human shields,'' near artillery pieces prime targets of
increasingly aggressive NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied forces pressed their air war into its 16th day
early Thursday, dropping bombs and firing cruise missiles at
military forces and facilities across Yugoslavia. The air campaign
seeks to end repression that has driven more than 1 million ethnic
Albanians from their homes in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Two explosions rocked central Belgrade around midnight local
time near Yugoslav army headquarters, the Associated Press reported
from the Yugoslav capital. There were reports of other explosions
in the industrial town of Pancevo, to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, former Cypriot President Spyros Kyprianou was
scheduled to fly from Athens to Belgrade on Thursday to meet with
Yugoslavia's president, Slododan Milosevic, over the possible
release of three U.S. soldiers captured last week near Yugoslavia's
border with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials said they would guarantee safe passage
for Kyprianou's aircraft. They said they would welcome the release
of the Americans, but would not halt the air campaign regardless of
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic does the civilized thing and releases
them, we would welcome that,'' said Shea. ``But, as for paying a
price, of course not. The mission goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   As the number of ethnic Albanians fleeing Kosovo's borders
surged above 600,000 with more than 400,000 others believed
displaced inside Kosovo there were signs that the exodus was
triggering desperation in neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   In Blace, Macedonia, authorities emptied a transit camp of
35,000 refugees without warning in a heavy-handed sweep so chaotic
that panicked families were separated and scant belongings left
behind as refugees were jammed into buses or forced onto aircraft.
They were transferred to camps as far away as Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Details were sketchy. But in an operation the United Nations
High Commissioner on Refugees described as ``a situation of mass
confusion,'' roughly 10,000 refugees were shunted to neighboring
Albania, 25,000 more to camps deep inside Macedonia and hundreds of
others were flown to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The mounting refugee crisis has placed an unanticipated burden
on NATO planners reacting day by day to difficult and changing
battlefield conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The forced transfer of an estimated 25,000 refugees back into
embattled Kosovo, however, portended a potentially more ominous
crisis, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in trouble right now, big trouble,'' said former U.S.
Army Col. William Taylor, a defense expert at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies, a Washington think tank.
``Forget strategic bombing in that region of Kosovo,'' said Taylor.
``We're not going to hit them with air power not while they have
hostages.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of four successive nights of relatively clear
skies, NATO forces have hammered at Yugoslav army troops and police
units deployed across a swath of southwest Kosovo, roughly parallel
to the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, for example, officials said a column of armored
vehicles was destroyed by a massive attack that mixed supersonic
B-1 bombers, dropping wide-area tank-piercing cluster bombs, with
low-altitude strikes by A-10 Warthog jets, built to knock out tanks
and armored personnel carriers.
</P>
<P>
   F-18 Hornet and F-14 Tomcat fighter bombers flying from the USS
Roosevelt aircraft carrier in the Mediterranean also pounded troops
in the same sector, as did British Harriers and other warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied pilots flew 439 sorties over Yugoslavia on
Wednesday, hitting 28 fixed targets and several groups of tanks and
troops in the field, NATO air commodore David Wilby told reporters
at alliance headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the weather remains good, and we continue to put heavy
emphasis on our operations against forces in the field,'' said
Wilby.
</P>
<P>
   Those forces have been concentrated for days in a rectangular
pocket of southwestern Kosovo. Troops have concealed tanks in
forests and abandoned buildings, near churches and, in some places,
among remaining civilian populations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Can End Here. Optional Add Follows
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By and large, though, civilians had fled the region over the
past two weeks in the face of advancing Yugoslav troops who have
shelled, torched and terrorized one village after another.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, however, Yugoslav forces sealed off the border
near the Albanian town of Morina, several miles from the southern
edge of the most intensive NATO strikes on Yugoslav ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   By late Wednesday, Pentagon officials said thousands of refugees
who had hoped to cross into Albania at Morina had been forced to
return to their ravaged villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our understanding is they have been asked to move back into
Kosovo and they're dispersing,'' said Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles
Wald, vice director of strategic plans and policy for the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``We're not sure where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   That complicates efforts to hit military units from the air,
particularly through the use of wide area cluster bombs, which NATO
has resisted using in areas near civilian centers or refugee
routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will NATO be looking for those? Of course we will,'' said
Wald. ``We always are very careful about collateral damage. That's
one of the difficulties of this mission, is where the civilians
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Without accusing Milosevic of using the refugees as human
shields, he made clear his concern over that prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using refugees as a tool for his strategy obviously is
something that we as professionals aren't used to to doing or
understanding,'' said Wald. ``You'd have to get into Milosevic's
mind to see what he's trying to do with those refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin did not directly link his
warning on war crimes with the forced movement of civilians back
into the battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours after that development, though, Rubin said ``we're
deeply alarmed'' by the move.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing civilians into harm's way is a violation of the Geneva
Conventions, the basis of international law governing the behavior
of troops during hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is investigating alleged atrocities committed by Yugoslav
forces in nearly 50 different villages or communities across
Kosovo, where ethnic Serbs have targeted ethnic Albanians, who make
up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomat David Scheffer, ambassador at large for war crimes
issues, interviewed roughly 200 ethnic Albanian refugees at Blace,
Macedonia last week. He has concluded from the eyewitness reports
that Serb troops, police and paramilitary units have committed
widespread atrocities across Kosovo since NATO air strikes began
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   EDS: State Department spokesman James Rubin named nine
commanders he said have recently overseen the operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Mandic, commander of the 252nd armored brigade, deployed in
central Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Vladimir Lazuruvic, commander of the Pristina Corps,
Third Army.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Mladin Serkovic, commander of the 15th Armored Brigade in
Pristina. (NATO has reported that this unit was one of three that
pinned down fleeing refugees in the Pagarusa Valley, where they
were repeatedly shelled.)
</P>
<P>
   Col. Dragan Djovanovic, commander of the 125th Motorized Brigade
in Pec and elsewhere. (NATO reported last week that Yugoslav tanks
virtually destroyed Pec, a centuries-old city in western Kosovo.)
</P>
<P>
   Col. Djelic, commander of the 243rd Mechanized Brigade,
headquartered in Jurasovec. (NATO reported that this unit was also
involved in the Pagarusa Valley operation.)
</P>
<P>
   Col. Delic, commander of the 549th Motorized Brigade in Prizren.
(Also involved in Pagarusa Valley.)
</P>
<P>
   Col. Stephanovic, commander of the 52nd Mixed Artillery Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Djozen, commander of the 52nd Light Air Defense Artillery
Rocket Regiment in Djakovica. (scene of some of the most intensive
repression.)
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Pekovic, commander of the 52nd Military Police Battalion in
Pristina. (Where an estimated 200,000 ethnic Albanians were rounded
up and forced into trains and buses bound for the border and
countless others have disappeared.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
