<SLUG> BC-BCLAW-DEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME PROFESSOR NEW DEAN AT BC LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Boston College announced a new dean of its law school
Wednesday, after a long and frustrated search that began when the
former dean was forced out. The search was marked by two other
candidates falling through at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   John H. Garvey, a professor at Notre Dame and a noted
constitutional law scholar, will take office July 1.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard Law and Divinity Schools, Garvey has
argued many prominent cases before the US Supreme Court,
representing the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in assessing fines
against Karen Silkwood's employer, and arguing to maintain a
state's tax deduction for parents who pay parochial school tuition,
among other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey has spoken extensively at conferences and law schools
around the country on constitutional freedoms, with special focus
on the difficulties faced by Catholic judges in death penalty
cases, and the problems created by paying for private school
vouchers with public school funds. He is also the author of several
constitutional law books.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I have moral, philosophical, and religious differences,
but I just find him a remarkably open-minded, insightful kind of
person,'' said Frederick Schauer, a law professor and
constitutional law scholar who is academic dean at Harvard's
Kennedy School of Government. ``He displays a remarkable ability to
make the best arguments against his own position.''
</P>
<P>
   Schauer praised him for combining his views on his faith with
his views on the law _ a perspective, he said, that is often
missing in scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his distinctive contributions has been trying to think
about these issues of constitutional freedoms from inside the
perspective of faith, inside the perspective of a person of
belief,'' Schauer said. ``A large number of writings about freedom
of religion tend to treat the believers as the other. With respect
to questions of belief, John is not an other.''
</P>
<P>
   BC President William P. Leahy praised Garvey for diversifying
the faculty at Notre Dame as head of the faculty appointments
committee, and for supporting student work at the intersection of
social justice and the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Garvey is a widely acclaimed scholar and an accomplished
teacher who cares deeply about the important role that law plays in
American society,'' Leahy said. ``We are delighted to have him join
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The dean's position has been empty since the fall of 1997, when
Aviam Soifer was forced out after disagreements with Leahy, then
the new president of BC. At the time, faculty said the
disagreements concerned relatively flat fundraising at the school.
A National Law Journal article in May 1998 suggested that Soifer,
who is Jewish, had been forced out by a ``cabal'' of priests _ a
suggestion that provoked vehement denials by professors both Jewish
and Catholic, who said they had not witnessed any anti-Semitism at
BC.
</P>
<P>
   The search was abandoned about a year ago, after two candidates
withdrew, one to assume the presidency of Grinnell College in Iowa.
The other, a minority candidate, was said to have remained at his
job in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The search resumed in August, resulting in Garvey's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``BC is convinced we got the very best possible candidate,''
said Jack Dunn, the BC spokesman. ``That he's Catholic isn't an
issue to us. He's clearly the best-qualified person.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble filling the dean's chair at the law school is by no
means limited to BC. Seven law school deans were ousted from their
jobs from 1997-1998, and a quarter of the nation's 180 law schools
had vacancies in the position this year, according to the American
Bar Association. Deans cite the growing pressures of fundraising,
which has become more crucial as competition for top students and
professors has accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey has been a professor at Notre Dame, where he did his
undergraduate work, since 1994. Before that, he was a professor at
the University of Kentucky College of Law for 14 years, a visiting
professor at the University of Michigan Law School, and an
assistant to the Solicitor General at the US Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Of BC, he said, ``It is such a great place. What legal academics
see is that it has a terrific reputation among scholars. What real
world lawyers see is that it has such a big heart. It's a place
that really takes seriously the commitment that kids ought to get
out of school and give something back to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also realistic about the challenges of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' he said, ``It needs some new buildings, a
lot of money, and a lot of support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
