</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS AIR ATTACKS CONTINUE, NATO LOOKS TO OPEN DIPLOMATIC OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Map-graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-CONGRESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-ECON, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-POWS) 
(ac) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO allies opened a diplomatic
offensive Wednesday aimed at probing for signs that President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia might be ready to back down, and
continued to press home air attacks against Yugoslav military
targets in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With the air campaign now in its third week, NATO officials said
foreign ministers of the 19 members would meet here on Monday to
take stock of the operation and show their determination to keep on
bombing until Milosevic accepts a political solution.
</P>
<P>
   The allies rejected Milosevic's announcement of a cease-fire in
Kosovo as ``a hollow sham,'' as the British foreign secretary,
Robin Cook, dismissively called it on Wednesday. But they also
began a flurry of diplomatic activity to see if it could just be
something more.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire declaration, together with a claim by the speaker
of Cyprus' Parliament that Milosevic could be ready to release
three captured American soldiers, led some allied officials to hope
the bombing campaign is beginning to erode their adversary's
morale.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes took to the air 439 times between Tuesday and
Wednesday morning and bombed 28 targets throughout Yugoslavia, the
military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby of Britain, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bombers also scored what Wilby called their first major
breakthrough against Serbian armored forces that are carrying out
attacks against Albanian civilians in Kosovo, the province in
southern Serbia. Allied planes bombed a column of seven to 12
armored vehicles between Pec and the Albanian border, he said.
``Today the weather remains good,'' Wilby said, ``and this morning
we have had very encouraging results once again.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the intensified air strikes, NATO's civilian spokesman,
Jamie Shea, said the alliance is concerned by reports that the flow
of refugees across Serbian borders has stopped, and the tens of
thousands who had been backed up in Kosovo have disappeared. He
also said 50 villages in Kosovo had been set afire by Serbian
forces since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said half of the 1.8 million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo had
been driven from their homes since fighting began a little more
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted Milosevic to say on Tuesday that he was ordering a
cease-fire was a question that many people here asked themselves.
If nothing else, Milosevic forced allied leaders to ponder yet
another set of questions. Officials here say they have no evidence
that Yugoslav and Serbian forces have actually stopped their
attacks in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we should try to speculate what his
motivations are for calling for the cease-fire at this time,''
Secretary of Defense William Cohen told reporters flying with him
to Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, based on what I've seen as far as the bomb damage
assessment on a daily basis, that yes, this is starting to take
hold,'' he said of the allied bombing. ``So it could be related to
the fact that he has now seen he's going to suffer considerable
pain in the coming days and weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen added: ``It may be that he feels he's accomplished his
mission and it's simply a charade that he's engaging in terms of,
`Well, time for peace now that I've done my job.' What we have to
do is make him understand that this is completely insufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   A French official said it was too early to conclude that
Milosevic is ready to crack. ``But the aim of the military campaign
is a political agreement, and until we get a clear answer that he
is ready for one, we have to continue the bombing,'' this official
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night word came from Belgrade that NATO bombs had
hit a courtyard of the headquarters of the Yugoslav army's general
staff. Many windows were blown out, but no fires were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he had no independent information about the statement
by Cyprus' acting president, Spyros Kyprianou, who has close ties
to Milosevic, that he is about to reach a deal with Belgrade about
the release of three American soldiers who were captured last week
along Serbia's border with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to restart diplomatic cooperation with Russia on
Kosovo, officials of the United States, Britain, France, Germany
and Italy met here Wednesday with a Russian deputy foreign
minister. Diplomats said they hoped that the meeting of all six
members of the so-called Contact Group, the first since the bombing
started, would enlist Russian help in answering some of the
questions about Belgrade's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Milosevic prepared for verifiable cessation of all combat
activities and killings?'' the five western members of the group
asked in a coordinated public response to the cease-fire
announcement. ``Is Milosevic prepared to withdraw military, police
and paramilitary forces from Kosovo? Is Milosevic prepared to agree
to the deployment of an international security force? Is Milosevic
prepared to permit the unconditional return of all refugees and
unimpeded access for humanitarian aid? And, finally, is Milosevic
prepared to join in putting in place a political framework for
Kosovo on the basis of the Rambouillet accords?''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's refusal to sign an agreement worked out in March
that provides for autonomy for the ethnic Albanian population of
Kosovo under continued Serbian rule and a force of 28,000 NATO
peacekeepers brought on the allied air campaign on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing will not stop, the allies said Wednesday, until the
Yugoslav leader gives positive answers to all their questions.
``This is no time to pause,'' Cohen said. ``We will reject any
solution that freezes the results of Milosevic's genocide and
rewards his brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Russia, whose leaders have urged the allies to consider
Milosevic's cease-fire proposal in a more positive light, is also
pressing diplomatic efforts of its own.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin sent letters to the leaders of Japan,
Canada and the five western countries in the Contact Group,
officials in Moscow said. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said the
letters contained ``initiatives on a peaceful solution to the
conflict in Yugoslavia.'' Russia has also asked for a meeting of
foreign ministers of all eight countries to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The French Foreign Minister, Hubert Vedrine, said in Paris
Wednesday that the allies were also consulting intensively on a
strategy for seeking a political accord after the bombing stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is work to be done on this political solution on the
basis of the Rambouillet accord,'' he said. ``What should we adapt?
What should we keep? What form should the international security
measures take on the ground?''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is whether, after the horrors of the past few
weeks, Milosevic is still an acceptable negotiating partner for the
allies. ``I think as each day goes by, it becomes more difficult to
arrive at a settlement with him,'' Cohen said, ``but I think that's
up to the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the absence of a negotiated settlement, allied diplomats
say they would be ready to send peacekeepers into Kosovo even
before a Yugoslav signature on a final agreement, but only if the
Serbian forces withdraw and do not try to prevent the peacekeepers
from escorting refugees to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   And European officials say that to get Russia participate in
such an international security force, the allies might not insist
on calling it a NATO operation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The talks Wednesday on Russia's role involved Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott, Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Avdeyev
of Russia and officials of the other four Contact Group countries.
They were held at the German Embassy here, but the diplomats said
little about the talks after they ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was quite important because we are in a very
critical situation as far as developments on the ground are
concerned,'' said Gunter Pleuger, the German official who presided.
``We will continue this dialogue with the common goal of finding a
political solution to this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees seem to present the most pressing problem. Foreign
ministers of the 15-nation European Union plan to meet Thursday in
Luxembourg to decide on a proposal from the Executive Commission
for $231.5 million in relief and economic aid for the refugees and
for Albania and Macedonia, the two impoverished Balkan countries
where most of the Kosovars have fled.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday the allies also plan to meet here with Foreign
Minister Aleksandar Dimitrov of Macedonia, whose Prime Minister on
Wednesday accused Western countries of unleashing the crisis with
the bombing and leaving countries like his to deal with the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 15 days after the air strikes started, Macedonia
cried out that something dramatic was going to happen,'' Prime
Minister Ljubco Georgievski said. ``The United States and European
Union have done nothing to help. We have also been forced to allow
more refugees than the limits of Macedonian acceptance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2044EDT &QL; 
