</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELL-BEING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON INSTITUTIONS TEAM UP TO STUDY SOCIAL FACTORS IN ILLNESS &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Three academic and medical powerhouses are joining
forces to explore how social factors contribute to illness and to
develop public policies to increase wellness and productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious program, to be launched this fall, combines the
resources of Rice University, Baylor College of Medicine and the
University of Texas-Houston Health Science Center, officials
announced Wednesday. It is the first time the three have done a
major research project together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public health people tend to think they can keep more people
from getting sick if we only control risk factors,'' said
UT-Houston Health Science Center President Dr. David Low, who
initiated the program. ``The medical people tend to think we can
help prevent people from getting sick if we control the biological
factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is simply completing the picture, broadening
our understanding of why some people are well and some aren't by
including social, economic and environmental factors.''
</P>
<P>
   A research team led by Harvard School of Public Health professor
Alvin Tarlov will be based at Rice's James A. Baker III Institute
for Public Policy. Tarlov's position is funded by a $2 million
endowment from the Sid Richardson Foundation and distributions from
the Ray Endowment and UT-Houston, where Tarlov, who is leaving
Harvard, has accepted a professorship in the school of public
health.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Baylor College of Medicine is joining Rice to
establish an endowed chair for a scholar who will specialize in
health policy and health economics. Rice and UT-Houston will
appoint a medical sociologist and two social epidemiologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new effort begins with the recognition that our current
health care system is geared much too strongly to treatment of
those who are most seriously ill,'' said Rice President Malcolm
Gillis. ``Medical intervention far earlier in the process could
significantly reduce the number of people who become seriously
ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarlov, an internist, is a leading figure in a field known as
``social determinants of health.'' He is a professor of health
promotion and chairman of the Mind/Brain/Body/Society and Health
Initiative at Harvard. He is the former chair of University of
Chicago's department of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   He describes societal factors affecting health as those that are
``outside the skin of human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Factors such as family structure, community, neighborhood,
workplace, income and education, as well as more abstract
influences such as a sense of fairness, a feeling of physical
security and ``the interrelationships with all living things,'' all
feed into overall health, according to Tarlov.
</P>
<P>
   He said the task in Texas will be fourfold: to understand how
all of these influences affect human health, to discover ways
cities might improve health and interventions, to propose public
and business policies that improve health, and to be a local health
improvement resource for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Health Commissioner William ``Reyn'' Archer III applauded
the initiative _ which is similar to one he recently proposed to
state lawmakers. Legislators criticized Archer's idea to fund two
$76,000-a-year positions for researching ``root causes of social
dysfunction and marginal health status'' as too nebulous to be
funded by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds very much like what we are trying to do,'' Archer
said. ``In the end, it's really about health and reducing the cost
of health care that we're all concerned about. Health care costs
are driving the inability of employers to provide insurance so if
we can find ways to improve health status in the community by
working on social dysfunctions, then we can reduce the cost of
health insurance and close the gap for the uninsured.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
