<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-WASTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DELAYS UTILITY'S SUIT AGAINST U.S., ORDERING SETTLEMENT
EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Nev.)   (rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge has ruled that a Minnesota utility
that is seeking $1 billion in damages from the federal government
because of a delay in establishing a nuclear waste repository must
try to reach a settlement with the Energy Department before it can
sue.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, made on Tuesday and announced Wednesday, is a blow
to the company, Northern States Power, and nine other utilities
with similar suits because such a settlement would have to be paid
from the Nuclear Waste Fund, money collected from the utilities and
set aside to construct the repository. If that fund runs short, the
department could demand more money from the utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is essentially robbing Peter to pay Paul,'' said a lawyer
for Northern States, Michael C. Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   If the companies had been allowed to sue and won, damages could
be paid from general federal funds instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department signed contracts with the utilities to
bury their nuclear wastes, beginning in January 1998, in exchange
for a payment of one-tenth of a cent for each kilowatt-hour
produced by nuclear power. The department is trying to build a
repository at Yucca Mountain, Nev., near Las Vegas, but says it
cannot be ready before 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Northern States says it is running out of space for spent fuel
at its twin Prairie Island reactors, near Red Wing, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   It has built giant casks to store some wastes above ground
temporarily, but the Minnesota Legislature, resenting the extra
expense for the company's customers and fearing that the casks
could become permanent, has limited how many it can build. Northern
States expects to run out of storage by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision on Tuesday, Judge John Weise of the Court of
Federal Claims noted that ``a 12-year postponement in the
commencement of the government's promised performance would seem to
stretch the concept of `delay' to the breaking point.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weise pointed out that the contract was signed 15 years
before the Energy Department was supposed to take the waste, and
that the department is supposed to continue filling the repository
for decades, and thus ``long-time horizons are an inherent
character of the contract's design.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Anne Sullivan, the general counsel for the Energy
Department, said the decision was a precedent for the other cases
pending against the department, and suggested that if the companies
and the department reach a settlement, the department could cut
future payments by the utilities to the nuclear fund by the amount
of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sullivan added, though, that the courts have held that three
utility companies that have already retired their reactors can seek
damages in court.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly, of Northern States, said he would appeal Weise's
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0430 </DOCNO>
