<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN HAVE STAKE IN SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coming reform of Social Security _ and it is coming _ is not
likely to affect everyone equally. The system already is a complex
mixture of cross-subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Consider men and women. In most countries, women outlive men. In
the United States in 1996, for example, life expectancy at birth
was 74 for men, and 80 for women.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, any retirement plan offering the same monthly
benefits to men and women will offer higher lifetime benefits to
the average woman than the average man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have a real stake in the Social Security debate,'' says
Rep. Barbara Kennelly, D-Conn. Kennelly, who left Congress in
January, was the ranking Democrat on the House Social Security
subcommittee and is now a counselor at the Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Men and woman pay the same 6.2 percent Social Security tax, with
another 6.2 percent contributed by their employer. But more men
than women work in the economy, and they take off less time for
their families. Women contribute only 38 percent of all Social
Security tax receipts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, says Kennelly, ``We're 60 percent of the beneficiaries.
We've got a good deal going.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if women don't get 60 percent of the money _ it's actually
just more than half _ they get a higher rate of return on their
Social Security taxes than men do.
</P>
<P>
   Living long is one reason for that. Another is the Social
Security benefit formula, which, like the federal income tax,
favors lower incomes. Social Security's tax is regressive, because
it stops after $72,600 in earnings, but the benefit formula cancels
out that effect. The system strongly favors lower incomes. And
because women's earnings average 74 percent of men's, a greater
proportion of the average woman's salary is replaced by Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   The system also allows the stay-at-home spouse to collect half
what the working spouse collects, even if the homemaker never paid
a penny in tax. That's a deal for women. As Kennelly says, ``How
many househusbands do you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Her conclusion is to keep Social Security much as it is.
```Let's not give up what we've got,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who would give it up for something else,
generally a system of insurance and individual accounts, often with
a guaranteed minimum. They reply first that the system mainly
favors housewives. Working women who qualify for benefits under
their husbands' taxes often find that their own taxes earned them
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Furchtgott-Roth of the American Enterprise Institute,
author of the new book ``Women's Figures: An Illustrated Guide to
the Economic Progress of Women in America,'' says such women would
be much better off with individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could take that tax and put it into the stock market,
they could have hundreds of thousands of dollars when they
retire,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The reformers' major argument, though, is that the system as a
whole offers a low return on investment. Because Social Security
pays out most of the money almost as fast as it comes in, the
average American born in 1950 is earning something like a 2 percent
return. Women do better, men do worse. Big deal. It's fighting over
peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Here we come to the half-empty, half-full debate. ``Without
Social Security,'' the agency says, ``50 percent of all
beneficiaries would fall below the poverty line.''
</P>
<P>
   That's correct. If they qualified for benefits but didn't get
them, they would be poor. But if they had invested the money in
stocks and bonds instead of paying Social Security taxes, they
might be rich.
</P>
<P>
   Today's workers won't get the option of putting 12.4 percent of
their pay into such accounts. They have to support today's
beneficiaries. Of the three plans proposed by the Advisory Council
on Social Security in 1996, the most radical would allow today's
workers to put 5 percent of their incomes, now going to tax, into
individual accounts. Even that plan would create federal deficits
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   It would, however, allow a way around the system's conundrum:
that taxes will fall short of benefits in 2014. Cutting benefits or
raising taxes are political losers. That leaves investment _ but by
government or by individuals?
</P>
<P>
   Individual accounts have a huge attraction. It's your money with
your name on it. But they are sums, not annuities. They would have
to last the average woman six years' longer than the average man.
</P>
<P>
   If saving is to be compulsory, perhaps the longer-lived gender
should be under greater compulsion. But none of the proposals I've
seen even suggests that.
</P>
<P>
   That would be discrimination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
