<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9764 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      04-07 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPAN FACES NEW CHALLENGE WITH ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Another year, another challenge for Jeff Suppan.
Could this be the year the former Red Sox righthander reaches his
potential?
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals must think so, for they have put Suppan
in the rotation despite an up-and-down career that has him on his
third team in less than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan wore a Boston uniform from 1993 until he was chosen by
Arizona in the 1997 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, after watching Suppan go 1-7 in 13 starts, the
Diamondbacks opted to drop him in favor of more consistent
veterans. Arizona signed free agents Randy Johnson and Todd
Stottlemyre this past offseason. Suppan was sold to Kansas City
last Sept. 3 and was impressive in four appearances (one start),
allowing just one run in 13 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Suppan, No. 3 in the Royals rotation, will take
on the team with which he cut his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to give him a couple of starts to see how far we
can take him,'' said Royals manager Tony Muser. ``I think it's a
good spot for him. We're taking some chances on some people and
he's one of them. We believe in his ability. But he's going to have
to back up the ability with the consistency of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked him two years ago. We know he was highly thought of
by Boston. He came up and did a pretty good job. But he had a tough
time in Arizona the way he was pitching. Basically, we're trying to
get him downhill with his fastball. You can't live upstairs unless
you throw 2,000 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   That Suppan is attractive to the Royals should surprise no one.
One of baseball's low-budget franchises, Kansas City has nothing to
lose. Suppan brought impressive credentials to the table in his
Boston days. Many cried foul when the Red Sox let Suppan, who
pitched 22 games for Boston escape to Arizona. But with prospects
such as Carl Pavano and Brian Rose right behind him, the Sox had to
make a decision on whom to protect for the expansion draft. They
left Suppan exposed, and he was the No. 2 pick of the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't protect everybody,'' recalled Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``Arizona was looking for pitching and he happened to be
there. It happens all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppan was openly disappointed and said he didn't understand the
system that had dictated his demise. Now he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter who drafts you,'' said Suppan, ``you think you'll
stay with the same team forever. I felt that way about Boston but
for me it was a quick two- or three-year experience. I've gone from
team to team. I just hope to make a name for myself here with the
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I realize that leaving the Red Sox was part of the game.
I wasn't hurt by not being protected. That's how things go
sometimes. Actually, it's been a good process for me to go
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppan's problems with control and location held him back in
Boston. The Diamondbacks just weren't impressed with his stuff. The
Royals think a new enviornment and a spacious park might make a
difference in his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Command is a big part of pitching,'' said Muser. ``Also change
of speeds. If you can get your fastball to either side of the plate
and use your second pitch on even counts, you've got a chance. A
lot of guys don't have his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told there was controversy about whether to throw the
slider or curveball. People said he had a great slider at one time
and tried to go to the curveball. Maybe he got lost in between.
We're trying to get one or the other and then develop his changeup.
He's got a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppan says his struggles last year with Arizona may have been a
blessing in disguise. He was sent down to Triple A and performed
well. Now he must regain command of his fastball while still being
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have some problems at Arizona,'' he said, ``and I
understand why they sent me down last year. But once there, I
started to iron things out. I finally felt like I was back where I
should be. The rumors started after that and I came over here and
played in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the game is today only a few pitchers can step up and
have instant success. Kerry Wood has overpowering stuff and made it
until he got hurt. Guys like myself have to go down the middle of
the road. You struggle. You have some good games, bad games. I'm
more aggressive. I have a little better idea of what I can do out
there. Hopefully, it will help me for this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Muser said the Royals can't hope to develop a talent like Suppan
overnight. So until they do, he's worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's tough,'' he said. ``But today's kids are learning
on the major league level. We're moving them so fast and getting
them here very quickly. That's not always good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they might have a major league arm, we move them
without insisting they have substantial success on the minor league
level. Many times, they're able to get by the many divisions of
baseball and make the big leagues without really learning those
things that get you by at the highest levels. Now we have to teach
those things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
