<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-INDICTMENT08-C     04-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-INDICTMENT08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No. 2 Austin school official put on leave amid test tampering
indictment
 &HT;    By Sharon Jayson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Kay Psencik, the Austin school district's deputy
superintendent charged with tampering with state achievement test
data, was placed on administrative leave with pay Wednesday until
further notice.
</P>
<P>
   Psencik worked Wednesday, but late in the day interim
Superintendent A.C. Gonzalez issued the statement regarding her
leave and named Darlene Westbrook as acting deputy superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to seek legal counsel regarding this personnel
issue, as well as the criminal indictment against the School
District, (cq-caps)'' Gonzalez said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Psencik and the school district were indicted Tuesday by a
Travis County grand jury on charges of tampering with governmental
record (cq-no ``a'' before governmental). The criminal
investigation, which has drawn national attention, focused on
changes made to 16 student identification numbers on the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills. The test is at the heart of the
state's school accountability system. As a result, Blackshear,
Bryker Woods and Travis Heights elementary schools received higher
performance ratings than they deserved. The Texas Education Agency
later lowered those ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Psencik, 51, announced her retirement in February, effective at
the end of the school year. She earns $124,200 plus expenses. She
has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Psencik, former district research analyst Ricky Arredondo and
four principals, including the campus leaders at the three
elementary schools, were disciplined by the superintendent for
their part in the TAAS data manipulation. Arredondo, who reported
to Psencik, pleaded no contest to the same tampering charge March
25.
</P>
<P>
   County Attorney Ken Oden said Wednesday that there was not
sufficient evidence to charge the principals. An audit said the
principals were asked to gather data that the district used to keep
some TAAS tests from being included in the accountability ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The tampering offense is a Class A misdemeanor subject to up to
a year in jail and a $4,000 fine. The district, which is liable for
a maximum fine of $10,000 for each of 16 indictments, one for each
student whose identification number was swapped, could face fines
of up to $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Oden said he doubts the district will pay any fines. He said his
goal in holding the district accountable was to ensure that the
district gives extra TAAS help to students who need it, rather than
hide poor school performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was to remedy a wrong,'' Oden said. ``What I'm out
for is a meaningful remedy for the schools damaged and meaningful
provisions for real help in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In charging the district as a whole, Oden said the legal
definition of ``association'' includes ``government or governmental
subdivision,'' which is how the school district is defined in this
matter. He said his office looked at all the options under the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it became clear that a true organizational remedy couldn't
be obtained without organizational responsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin school district may be the first school district in
the country to be indicted on criminal charges, said Julie
Underwood, general counsel for the National School Boards
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably served quite well to draw attention to a problem.
It does serve that purpose, but I question whether it will stick,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin school trustees will meet next week with attorneys about
the case _ during the same week of community meetings on the search
for a permanent superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Trustee Ted Whatley said he doesn't think the indictments will
hurt the search.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it probably clears the air,'' he said. ``I think
people have been waiting to see what would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Board President Kathy Rider said with or without an indictment,
the district has to restore the integrity of the central office.
``We already had integrity problems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David Justice, a Johnston High parent, said the indictments may
help in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be good, a wake-up call,'' he said. ``It's the
same old problem. People have good intentions setting up the
testing system. What happens is as time goes on people lose sight
of what the fundamentals of the law are.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Urps, president of the Austin Association of Teachers,
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that really needs to be looked at,'' she said.
``Maybe this is an eye-opener. It shows the pressure is really
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Education Commissioner Mike Moses said Wednesday the
indictment of a Texas school district emphasizes to him how some
school districts have gotten ``off course'' over the statewide
accountability system. ``This whole situation has certainly made me
reflect on what we can do at the agency and I can do as
commissioner to set the proper tone and set the right climate for
assessment and accountability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Moses asked 11 school districts to investigate
excessive TAAS erasures at some campuses. Houston's investigation
has resulted in personnel changes at some campuses. Dallas has
asked for more time to investigate. Of the remaining districts,
three found some irregularities, said Debbie Graves Ratcliffe, a
TEA spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The county attorney's office also is investigating the Austin
district for data manipulation in other areas, including dropout
data.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a legislative committee will consider a measure by
State Rep. Domingo Garcia (D-Dallas) that would make altering
student records a felony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe the indictments will give more impetus to my
bill and what happened in Houston and what's happening in Dallas
all indicate it's a major problem and it's time we deal with it in
this legislative session,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Michele Kurtz contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
