<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICK08-COX     04-07 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICK08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chick-fil-A stores in S. Africa aim to profit, offer aid
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDTON, South Africa _ For Dan Cathy, as for his father,
Chick-fil-A founder S. Truett Cathy, doing business is as much
about helping people as it is about making money.
</P>
<P>
   That's fortunate, because the Atlanta-based fast food chain is
finding that the economic climate in South Africa poses significant
challenges, including interest rates in the high teens and an
economy that shrank in the last quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no denying that, in a country where unemployment is
estimated at nearly 40 percent, Chick-fil-A, by opening stores, is
helping people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Chick-fil-A opened a store in Durban. In 1997, it
opened a store in the East Gate shopping center on the southeast
edge of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as mall management and local officials gather for a
celebration, the chain will open its third store in South Africa,
this time in a mall in Sandton, an upscale northern suburb of
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   While the volume in the first two stores has not yet lived up to
expectations, the new store will give more than two dozen South
Africans, most of whom were previously unemployed, regular jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 25, 30 people that we took off the street,'' said
Cathy, who is president of Chick-fil-A International and executive
vice president of the chain. ``It may be a candle in the night, but
at least it's still glimmering.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the three stores, about 100 people are now employed,
said Danie van den Heever, one of Chick-fil-A's South African
partners. On a continent where each wage-earner often feeds five or
six people, about 500 lives may have been improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And those employees are learning skills, such as dealing with
the public and managing others, that will serve them in good stead,
van den Heever said.
</P>
<P>
   It costs about $350,000 to open a store in a mall, Cathy said,
and that is being divided between the chain, a silent partner and
van den Heever.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many whites are leaving South Africa, van den
Heever is investing in it instead. It was a decision the
eighth-generation African made with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat round the table and we made a decision: What does God
want for us in the next 10 years? If we're going to stay here,
we're going to be part of the solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Cathy doesn't want to make money. He hopes interest
rates go down, so the stores can keep their prices low enough to do
the volume they need to do, and he hopes unemployment drops, so
more people can afford chicken sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all those people were employed, they'd be coming in and
eating with us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chick-fil-A decided to do business in South Africa shortly after
Cathy visited the country as part of a trade mission led by Atlanta
Mayor Bill Campbell in 1995. Company officials also took to heart
the recommendation of Donald Keough, then president of the
Coca-Cola Co., who said South Africa was fertile ground because so
many American fast food chains had stayed out of the country during
the apartheid years.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's chicken wars may soon heat up. Kentucky Fried
Chicken, which caters more to the dinner market than lunch, has a
number of stores in South Africa. And Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises
has opened one store in Durban and plans to open one in the
Johannesburg area this year.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is the only foreign country in which Chick-fil-A
currently does business, and the company is proceeding cautiously,
Cathy said. But the low initial volume reminds him of times when
Chick-fil-A entered new U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   There are no billboards with cows holding ``EAT MOR CHIKIN''
signs. The brand is not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   But Chick-fil-A is working at it, distributing free sandwiches
to mall employees in hopes of giving them the chicken sandwich
habit. Then, Cathy said, those employees may recommend the store,
or leave Chick-fil-A cups sitting around, and the word will get
out. ``This is hand-to-hand combat,'' he said. ``This is guerrilla
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
