<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BORDERS-BO     04-07 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BORDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA CLOSES MAJOR EXITS FROM KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Yugoslavia-Soldiers)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslavia sealed off Kosovo's main border
crossings Wednesday, forcing tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians
back toward the burned villages they had been fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   US officials decried the move as a cruel attempt by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to give the appearance that the crisis
is over, even as NATO kept bombing the country.
</P>
<P>
   After forcing more than 400,000 refugees out to neighboring
countries, Yugoslav authorities closed the main exit routes into
Albania and Macedonia, apparently telling Kosovo refugees it was
safe for them to go home because of a unilateral cease-fire
declared Tuesday by Yugoslavia for Orothodox Easter.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO bomb blasts were heard again Wednesday night in
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, the acting president of Cyprus was
waiting in Athens for clearance to enter Belgrade, where he plans
to travel Thursday to seek the release of three US soliders
captured by the Serbs a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   --An unmanned US Army reconnaissance plane was downed over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   --The US government named nine Serb commanders who could face
prosecution for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   --Diplomatic efforts continued to try and resolve the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO announced its first major breakthrough against Serb
ground forces in what it called its heaviest daylong attack to
date.
</P>
<P>
   As Yugoslavia closed its borders, pushing upward of 10,000
ethnic Albanians into the interior of Kosovo province, according to
one US official, German Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping warned
that the Yugoslavs might be planning to use the civilians who were
turned back into Kosovo as ``human shields'' against NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A National Security Council official, who spoke on the condition
of anonmity, said the border closings ``could well be part of
Milosevic's peace offensive. He's trying in a tragically
manipulative way to say to the Kosovo people, `the crisis is over,
you can go home now.'''
</P>
<P>
   While Kosovo's borders were being closed, Macedonia, which has
been criticized for the squalid conditions at its makeshift camp,
shipped 10,000 refugees to Albania and moved 25,000 to NATO tent
camps farther away toward the Macedonian capital of Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate front, the United States accused nine commanders
of Yugoslav military units operating in Kosovo of committing war
crimes and warned that the perpetrators would face international
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are naming these commanders because they ought to know that
their forces, in our view, are commiting war crimes and crimes
against humanity,'' said James P. Rubin, a spokesman for the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States wanted the military officials to know
``the world is watching and that the war crimes tribunal is there,
and we are going to assist them in this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said it was up to the International War Crimes Tribunal
whether to indict anyone suspected of wartime atrocities, but the
United States would be providing detailed information and names.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was an apparent effort to stoke division among
Belgrade's military and security forces at a time the
administration believes it is seeing some positive results from 15
days of NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the US warning was issued Wednesday because ``we have
every reason to believe that in the coming days, terrible things''
could happen in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cypriot leader Spyros Kyprianou waited for the green
light to enter Yugoslavia to seek the release of the three solders
captured a week ago while patrolling the Yugoslav-Macedonian
border.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they hope he succeeds, but they vowed that
NATO airstrikes would continue regardless of the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   A top Clinton administration official told the Globe Wednesday
that Milosevic's apparent willingess to consider freeing the
soldiers falls in the same category as his cease-fire proposal and
was another sign that NATO's bombing campaign was hurting the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they are trying to bargain,'' the official said.
``We are not going to let there be a backdoor approach to
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger, the national security adviser, was
cautious about the mission but said, ``We certainly would welcome
the release of the three American soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, addressing the Kosovo crisis during a speech
on US-China relations, said, ``It is not enough for Mr. Milosevic
to say that his forces will cease fire in a Kosovo denied its
freedom and devoid of its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must withdraw his forces, let the refugees return, permit
the deployment of an international security force,'' Clinton said.
``Nothing less will bring peace with security to the people of
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, NATO said it had launched its heaviest air raids to
date, hitting an armored column in southwestern Kosovo on Tuesday
in its `first major breakthrough'' against Yugoslav ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that NATO forces are beginning to inflict
increasing damage on Yugoslav forces,'' Defense Secretary William
Cohen said in Brussels, where he is meeting with NATO leaders.
``This is no time to pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Major General Charles Wald, vice director for
strategic plans and policy for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said the
low- and slow-flying ``tank killer'' A-10 aircraft hit Serb forces
in Kosovo overnight Tuesday, the first time the planes, nicknamed
Warthogs, struck enemy targets in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, an unmanned Army reconnaissance aircraft _ a
twin-engine plane, known as a Hunter, crashed after apparently
being shot down.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Albania's parliament approved NATO plans to
send in 24 US Apache attack helicopters _ a move that should
bolster the alliance's firepower against Yugoslav tanks and armor.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the air war continued, there was movement on the various
diplomatic fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a traditional ally of Yugoslavia, stepped up its search
for a political agreement over Kosovo, with President Boris Yeltsin
urging world leaders not to dismiss Belgrade's latest unilateral
proposals out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin said Yeltsin sent a letter to the leaders of the
Group of Seven _ the United States, Britain, Canada, France,
Germany, Italy, and Japan _ that spelled out Milosevic's ideas and
asked the countries to be constructive.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they welcomed Yeltsin's efforts with
Milosevic. ``The Russians have been part and parcel of our effort
to try to find a peaceful solution to the problems in Yugoslavia
from the beginning,'' said Rubin from the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate front, the Canadian government, in a major shift
in position, said it was considering the possibility of using NATO
ground troops in Kosovo, even without a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Canada and ground troops, Wald of the Joint Chiefs
said: ``Any prudent military planner probably would plan, not only
in this case but any case, for all possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added. ``On the policy side, our intention is not to put
any ground troops in, period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
