<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAIRGAIN-WEB-FRAUD-AR     04-07 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAIRGAIN-WEB-FRAUD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAKE NEWS STORY ON PHONY WEB SITE SENDS STOCK PRICE SOARING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See the Bloomberg business story,
BC-PAIRGAIN-SHARES-UPDATE1-BLOOM) 
(Eds.: the hyphen in the word `E-trade' in the 3rd graf has been
used instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to many
newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the oldest frauds on Wall Street has been
updated for the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   Using a personal web site intended to look like an Internet page
of Bloomberg News, someone posted a fake news story early Wednesday
that said an American technology company called PairGain
Technologies Inc. was being taken over by an Israeli rival for a
hefty price. The report spread to a Yahoo message board and then to
other sites frequented by stock traders, who quickly bid up
PairGain's stock by more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, the stock retreated as the takeover story was
debunked, but it finished the day as the 12th-most heavily traded
on Nasdaq, ahead of such popular shares as Amazon.com and E-trade.
</P>
<P>
   The hoax, which is already under investigation by the Securities
and Exchange Commission and the Nasdaq Stock Market, shows the
startling power of Internet chat rooms and day traders, who make
rapid-fire trades in and out of relatively small stocks in which
they can easily move the price.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who were duped into buying shares at the temporarily
inflated price have suffered at least paper losses, though it could
be weeks before regulators are able to sort out who was trading.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said the report was not from one of its reporters, and
the prankster had not been identified last night. PairGain, a
Tustin, Calif., maker of telecommunications equipment, and its
alleged suitor, ECI Telecom Ltd., denied that they were in merger
talks.
</P>
<P>
   False rumors about a company have percolated as long as there
have been markets, and prank announcements of takeovers have
occured during times of intense interest in the stock market, like
the late 1980s, when corporate raiders garnered headlines. But
market analysts said that the false PairGain story, which made
generous use of the scrolling text, web links and icons so familiar
to Internet users, is one of the most technologically sophisticated
examples of such fraud in years.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Elgindy, an online stock trader who operates a stock
service called Pacific Equity Investigations, called the fake
report ``incredibly believable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was detailed enough _ with quotations and remarks and
attributions _ that it reads as if it came from a press release
that the company wrote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud was well orchestrated. The posting appeared on the
Internet just a half hour before trading began on the Nasdaq
market, leaving little time for anyone to check with the companies
but enough for investors to place orders to buy shares.
</P>
<P>
   It started at 8:55 a.m. ET, on a page of Angelfire.com, a web
site operated by Lycos Inc., which allows individuals to create
their own web pages containing personal or business information.
The story first appeared not on a message board or in a chat room,
but on a personal page that could have been created by any
registered Angelfire user. The news story carried the Bloomberg.com
logo and announced that ECI had agreed to buy PairGain for $1.35
billion in cash, twice the company's market value just a day
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   How the news traveled to broader investment circles on the
Internet is not yet clear. But roughly a half hour later, a
reference to the Angelfire posting and a link to the page appeared
on a Yahoo message board devoted to investment topics, which was
quickly followed by postings on other Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wahooooo!!! I knew this day would come!,'' wrote one
enthusiastic investor on the Yahoo message board for PairGain,
minutes after word of the ``takeover'' appeared. Another calculated
a takeover price of $19 a share, quite a jump from PairGain's $8.50
closing price the previous day. A third noted that PairGain's
products, which allow for high-speed transmission of data over
traditional copper wires, ``Will `pair' well'' with ECI's products
for digital communications.
</P>
<P>
   Once stock trading began, PairGain shares rose sharply on heavy
volume, peaking at $11.125. At the end of Wednesday, PairGain was
priced at $9.375, up 10 percent from $8.50 on Tuesday. And 13.69
million shares changed hands in one day, roughly 13 times its
average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   The stock began to retreat as Internet investors began to
question the veracity of the takeover report and fell further after
PairGain and ECI denied that they had reached a deal or were even
in talks.
</P>
<P>
   The fake announcement seemed to confirm what had been rumored
for months. Charles McBrayer, the chief financial officerof
PairGain, said that the same or similar rumors have cropped up four
times in the past year. In addition, two Israeli newspapers
reported last month that ECI was in talks to acquire an American
technology company, possibly PairGain. ``On the one hand, the
Internet should be helpful to individual investors,'' McBrayer
said. ``But in this case, the fakery was done so well that it
looked little different than if the news came from a legitimate
source.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of fraud, however, were picked up by Baker Street
Irregulars who scan many of the online chat rooms for signs of
misbegotten investment hype. By shortly after 10 a.m., one Yahoo
participant noted that the web page announcing the takeover was not
in fact part of Bloomberg's larger web site, and the real Bloomberg
site had no indication of the news. Another chipped in that
PairGain's investor relations phone number in California did not
mention there would be a major news announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Securities and Exchange Commission and the
Nasdaq market declined to comment on whether they were
investigating the hoax; as a practice, they rarely comment on
investgations. But McBrayer said he had talked with officials from
the SEC's Internet Fraud division, as well as the market
surveillance staff of the Nasdaq market, both of which were looking
into the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Payea, a spokesman for Lycos, which operates the Angelfire
web site, said the company had not yet been contacted by
regulators. He declined to indentify the individual who created the
fake web site, saying it was company policy not to release
information on members unless compelled by legal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Angelfire said it removed the posting early Wednesday afternoon
after it was contacted by Bloomberg's lawyers. Chris Taylor, a
Bloomberg spokeswoman, said the news service's own computers were
not involved in the hoax.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Virtually anyone with Internet access can save the image from a
particular web page and then, using that template, insert their own
text to create an authentic looking but fraudulent web page. In
fact, said Payea, Angelfire removes from its site several pages a
day of users who have co-opted the copyrighted material of other
sites and drawn the ire of the material's owners.
</P>
<P>
   The relative ease with which computer users can create
sophisticated web sites has contributed to the Internet power and
attractiveness, in much the same way that the personal computer and
laser printers gave small publishing operations the ability to
produce slick documents that look professionally typeset.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, the investment hoax was an old tale in a new
guise. In recent years, the financial markets and news services
have been occasionally duped by false reports that seemed
authentic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a caller to the Nasdaq market's market surveillance
unit identified himself as the chief financial officer of Sybase
Inc. and asked that the company's stock be halted for a pending
news announcement. Trading was halted for more than a half hour
before Nasdaq officials determined the call was a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the stocks of NWA, parent of Northwest Airlines, and
Pan Am were halted in trading on the New York Stock Exchange after
the Reuters news service reported on a fake takeover bid for both
companies. And in 1987, a financial adviser from a prominant
Cincinnati family called the Dow Jones News Service and announced a
takeover bid for Dayton Hudson, the Midwestern retailer, which the
news service reported. The bid was later determined to be a hoax,
and securities regulators brought charges of fraud against the
adviser, in 1989 barring him from the securities business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
