<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr, Isakson lead anti-tax rally
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About 50 supporters gathered on the Marietta Square on
Wednesday at an anti-tax rally hosted by Republican U.S. Reps. Bob
Barr and Johnny Isakson, who were pushing a constitutional
amendment to make tax increases harder to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Barr is attempting to build steam for a House vote on April 15
to refer the amendment to the 50 states. If ratified, federal taxes
could not be raised without approval by a two-thirds margin in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Now, taxes can be raised by simple majorities. ``The power to
tax is the most fundamental power that the government has,'' Barr
said. ``It's far too much power now.''
</P>
<P>
   The main speaker was U.S. Rep. Joe Barton (R-Texas). ``We don't
say it should be impossible to raise taxes, but it should take a
super majority,'' Barton said. ``Two-thirds makes sure that it's a
big issue and the country's behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters in the crowd included Christina Jeffrey, who opposed
Isakson in the race to fill former House Speaker Newt Gingrich's
seat; Paul Ploener, leader of Concerned Taxpayers in Cobb County;
and Bob Terrell, Georgia chairman of Citizens for an Alternative
Tax System.
</P>
<P>
   Since the impeachment of President Clinton, taxes have become a
national Republican focus. ``I wish he'd push the national sales
tax as hard as he does impeachment,'' Terrell said of Barr.
</P>
<P>
   Barr responded that he is not yet ready to commit to a national
levy on sales. He said either a sales tax or flat tax would be
preferable to the current system.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
