<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAK     04-07 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC'S NEW VERSION OF REALITY WILL BE HARDER FOR NATO TO
DISMISS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-POWS, KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-CONGRESS,
KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES) 
(sw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ NATO has rejected Slobodan Milosevic's
latest move, a unilateral cease-fire, as insufficient for the
bombing to stop, but once again it is the Yugoslav president who is
creating the facts to which the West is responding.
</P>
<P>
   And Milosevic appears to be constructing a new form of reality
in Kosovo that will be harder for the Washington and NATO to
dismiss out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government is essentially declaring that the crisis
is over, the Kosovo Liberation Army is vanquished, and negotiations
for an internal solution are taking place with acceptable ethnic
Albanian leaders, and as a result there is no reason, except NATO's
bombs, for refugees not to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is talking peace, urging (or forcing) refugees to
return to Kosovo and dangling the possibility of releasing three
captured American soldiers as a good-will gesture. At the same time
he continues to ratchet up the pressure on neighboring Macedonia
and sister republic Montenegro, giving the West another incentive
to stop further Balkan chaos.
</P>
<P>
   However disingenuous, cynical or even malevolent this may seem
to Western policymakers, there is enough reality in the Yugoslav
version to further divide the alliance and the six-nation Contact
Group, which includes the United States, Western European countries
and Russia, and whose task it is to deal with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians in particular are urging NATO to consider
Milosevic's plan as a serious way to restart negotiations, at
least, and it is not easy for Washington to follow its usual
pattern and brush the weak Russians off.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have indicated that Washington is seeking
Moscow's help to find an acceptable diplomatic end to the air
campaign before NATO's 50th summit meeting three weeks from now in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable information from Kosovo is almost nonexistent in
Belgrade, even as the first carefully guided reporters were bused
by the army on Wednesday into Pristina, the capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yugoslav military and police seem to have accomplished
many of their aims on the ground in Kosovo without being too badly
mauled by NATO air power.
</P>
<P>
   Milan Bozic, minister without portfolio in the Yugoslav
government, said: ``We're offering a unilateral cease-fire in
Kosovo because we believe that the terrorists who used the NATO
bombings to put pressure on our country are now virtually
destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   His claims may be exaggerated, but the KLA has been routed and
has proven no match for Serbian armored might, even with NATO air
power in support. While the Serbs are not likely to eradicate the
KLA guerrillas, Yugoslav officials privately admit, they make the
point that the KLA is not like the well-trained and traditionally
organized Croatian army, which only needed NATO air support to see
off a demoralized Serb army in Bosnia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA, unlike the Croats, cannot serve as NATO's ground
troops in Kosovo,'' said one Foreign Ministry official. Without
ground troops, he said, and with the KLA in retreat, ``there is no
reason for Serb forces to leave Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire may be a sign that Milosevic is ``rattled,'' as
the Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, has said. But it is more
likely to have been a ploy to discomfit the Contact Group and
affect public opinion in Russia, Greece and Italy, the countries
that have displayed the most unease about the bombing. It is almost
inconceivable that Milosevic expected the West to follow his lead
and declare a pause in the bombing _ every Western leader had
stated publicly that NATO would ignore a unilateral Easter
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is following similar tactics with the three captured
American soldiers, not only using their possible release as a way
to look like a peacemaker, but also to underline Yugoslavia's
position that the conflict is _ or should be _ over, and that talks
should begin.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, it is clear that Milosevic will try to create
his own internal political settlement for wide political autonomy
for Kosovo that will look very much like the Western-drafted peace
plan of Rambouillet, but without the introduction of NATO forces,
an element he has consistently rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and senior Serbian officials have met with the ethnic
Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova, who has long advocated a
nonviolent path to real political autonomy and, ultimately,
independence. Rugova was regarded by Washington as the most
important Kosovar leader until the emergence of the Kosovar
Liberation Army as a military and political player about a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As Rugova's influence declined, Yugoslav officials argue,
Washington switched its support to the armed insurgents of the KLA,
while continuing to insist that an independent Kosovo was not an
American goal. Rugova was part of the ethnic Albanian delegation
that signed the Rambouillet peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and American officials have consistently questioned
Rugova's current freedom of movement and speech. But Russian
officials who have spoken or met with him, including Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov and Yuri Kotov, Moscow's ambassador to
Belgrade, insist that Rugova is free to act.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even if Rugova is not a free agent, Milosevic may simply be
using him _ as he is using the refugees _ to pressure the West into
more serious negotiations, which would have to be predicated on a
mutual cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova's apparent willingness to find an internal solution for
Kosovo, if only to save lives, has been one more nail in the coffin
of the Rambouillet plan, at least that part that envisioned a NATO
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Even the chief European Union negotiator at Rambouillet,
Wolfgang Petritsch of Austria, was quoted on Wednesday by InfoRadio
Berlin as saying: ``We know that both sides no longer recognize
Rambouillet as a basis. Both the Yugoslav and the Kosovo Albanian
side are of the opinion that Rambouillet is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, French and Italian officials are talking about the
need to revise Rambouillet, and even NATO's current demands on
Milosevic to answer, as announced on Wednesday by member nations,
suggest a step back from the demands that set off this bombing war
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions were summarized on Wednesday by President
Clinton, who said: ``It is not enough now for Mr. Milosevic to say
that his forces will cease-fire on a Kosovo denied its freedom and
devoid of its people. He must withdraw his forces, let the refugees
return, permit the deployment of an international security force.
Nothing less will bring peace with security to the people of
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference to an international force instead of a NATO force
was a small but significant shift. In a little-noted resolution of
the Serbian Parliament just before the bombing, when that hardly
independent body rejected NATO troops in Kosovo, it also supported
the idea of U.N. forces to monitor a political settlement there.
</P>
<P>
   And NATO said that Milosevic must ``withdraw military, police
and paramilitary forces from Kosovo,'' not necessarily withdraw all
his forces.
</P>
<P>
   So the two sides seem to be getting closer, even as the
war-inspired language continues to steam, with both sides accusing
the other of Nazilike tactics.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomacy could also continue to fail. As a fallback
position, said one Yugoslav analyst considered close to the regime,
who spoke on the condition of anonymity, Milosevic may be willing
to endure a NATO ground invasion, on the assumption that his forces
can inflict more casualties than Washington could bear, and then
agree to a partition of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Belgrade authorities believe, this analyst said, that it
will be difficult for NATO to put forces on the ground if Kosovo
appears, at least, to be pacified, with a form of political
autonomy and the return of a reasonable number of refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
