<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panel is named to plan Freaknik
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two businessmen and two college students have been
appointed by Mayor Bill Campbell to help oversee Black College
Spring Break weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will meet formally for the first time Monday, just
five days before the event kicks off, to talk about the city's
traffic plan, events, and efforts to coordinate volunteers to walk
the streets during the weekend of April 16-18, said DeWayne Martin,
Campbell's chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is composed of Charles Kelly, vice president of a
local printing and graphic design company; Yergan Jones, president
of a local sound and lighting company; Markel Hutchins, a student
at Morehouse College; and Byron Amos, a student at Clark Atlanta
University. Last year's group of 18 men and women included business
people, elected officials, police officials and students.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said it's possible additional people will be appointed to
the committee in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   He said the reduced number of members is not a reflection of the
dwindling size of Freaknik. Martin said the city's plans to handle
crowds and traffic are no different than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, there's not been as much media coverage this
year,'' Martin said. ``That's not any indication we haven't planned
as extensively as we have in previous years.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the only city-sanctioned events are a weekend street
festival on Auburn Avenue and a job fair on April 17.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said it's impossible to predict how many college students
and partygoers will converge on the city, but Kelly, co-chairman of
the committee, said he thinks fewer people will show up than in
past years.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all indications it will indeed be a smaller event this
year,'' said Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the committee won't have to meet as much, because it
is using lessons learned from past Freakniks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Black College Spring Break Committee issued a report
after the event recommending that the city discourage Freaknik,
based on reports of lewd behavior, assaults on women, traffic jams
and strains on city services, such as police and sanitation.
Campbell has said on several occasions in recent weeks that people
are welcomed to the city for the event, as long as they obey the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Jones, a spokeswoman for the Atlanta Police Department,
said the department is completing a traffic plan for release in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
