<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDALIA08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vidalias: We will sell no onion before its time
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you come across small onions with greenish outer
skins labeled ``Vidalia'' in the next few days, be warned before
you chomp.
</P>
<P>
   They won't have the signature sweetness of Vidalias _ or the
blessing of Georgia Agriculture Commissioner Tommy Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin issued a stern warning: Farmers attempting to send onions
to market before their time will be halted.
</P>
<P>
   He took action this week after a committee that helps govern the
Vidalia onion industry expressed concern that in recent years some
farmers have tried to rush young onions to market in order to get
the best prices.
</P>
<P>
   The onions in question are small and have had their tops chopped
off _ they are not the ``Baby Vidalias,'' which are a scallion
variety and still have their green tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fear selling the onions on the fresh market would damage
the reputation of the Vidalia,'' said Tina Wheeler, director of the
Vidalia Onion Committee. ``They have a more bitter taste and they
are mushy.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin told farmers in a letter he would issue a stop-sale order
if unripe onions were discovered in the grading and inspection
process. The onions would have to be destroyed or used only in
processed foods.
</P>
<P>
   A good harvest of fully ripe Vidalia onions is expected to hit
grocery shelves in about two weeks. Then onion lovers will be able
to commence one of their favorite rites of spring _ stuffing the
sweet orbs with bouillon cubes, butter and all sorts of sauces for
roasting.
</P>
<P>
   The Vidalia onion is grown only in Georgia, in a region around
the Toombs County town of Vidalia, where the onion was first
planted in 1931. Today it yields a $90 million industry _ an
estimated 280 million pounds will be harvested this year.
</P>
<P>
   The soil conditions and climate around Vidalia produce onions
that are low in sulfur and high in water, making them milder than
most _ thus their reputation for being ``sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a reputation that's sternly guarded. In 1986, the Georgia
Legislature established a 20-county region around Vidalia as the
only district where onions could belabeled ``Vidalia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
