u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-COX     04-07 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-COX-08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    BALKAN LEADER IN A HARD SPOT, LIVING WAR AND TALKING PEACE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro, Yugoslavia A democratic reformer,
President Milo Djukanovic
</P>
<P>
   wants closer ties to America and Europe. Tuesday night, his
friends from NATO sent warplanes to drop bombs on his capital.
</P>
<P>
   These are difficult days for Djukanovic and his small Balkan
republic, which with Serbia
</P>
<P>
   forms the Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his ministers openly criticize Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic, even with 10,000 or more of Milosevic's federal
troops on Montenegrin soil.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of coup or civil war is thick on the streets of Montenegro,
a plight the president
</P>
<P>
   himself concedes has caused profound concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montenegro is deeply divided. Tensions are running very high.
We are managing to keep
</P>
<P>
   the situation under control with great effort,'' Djukanovic told
Cox Newspapers in an
</P>
<P>
   interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic has condemned Milosevic's ``ethnic cleansing'' of the
Serbian province of Kosovo and has defied Serbia by refusing to
declare a state of war against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, tensions were heightened when NATO warplanes
bombed suspected Serb military targets here. They caused no
injuries and little property damage.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack, Serb army forces frantically fired
anti-aircraft fire into the skies. Because the NATO planes were
long gone, there was suspicion the Serb forces were trying give the
impression of a battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the army did last night was not really a serious attempt
to harm NATO aircraft,'' Djukanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   His government has walked a fine line between the West and
Milosevic's government in Belgrade. He has enacted pro-Western
democratic reforms but has not called for outright independence
from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a risky political approach,'' he said. ``By trying to
preserve a normal democratic situation in the republic we are in
very much aggravated circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal army and the national currency, the dinar, are
virtually the only aspects of life shared by Serbia and Montenegro.
But U.S.-led attacks on Serb targets have whipped up anti-NATO
sentiment in Montenegro and charges that the Western-leaning
Djukanovic is sleeping with the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a part of the Montenegrin public which is strongly
resentful and they want to interpret this in typically Milosevic
style,'' he said. ``They find it much easier to just divide into
two camps: patriots and traitors.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
