<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-LOTTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA MOVES CLOSER TO A LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.C., Tenn., Ga., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A legislative measure to allow South Carolinians to
vote on the lottery hurdled its tallest obstacle Wednesday as the
Republican-majority House of Representatives passed the bill by a
comfortable margin.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate, which is controlled by Democrats, approved a
lottery bill in January, but attached it to another measure that
would also allow voters to decide whether video poker should remain
legal in South Carolina. The House bill does not include that
amendment and the two chambers now must negotiate an agreement on a
common version.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect that to be difficult,'' said Nina Brook, a
spokeswoman for Gov. Jim Hodges, a Democrat who won election last
year by campaigning relentlessly for a statewide lottery that would
benefit education. Ms. Brook said Hodges favors a lottery bill that
is not encumbered by unrelated legislation.
</P>
<P>
   With Wednesday's vote, South Carolina becomes the first of four
Southern states considering lottery measures this year to win
approval for such legislation in both houses. The Legislatures in
Alabama, North Carolina and Tennessee also are debating the lottery
this spring. They are among 13 states that do not have lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   A lottery measure passed the Alabama House late last month and
is under consideration by the Senate. Neither of the chambers in
North Carolina and Tennessee has voted on the issue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hodges and Gov. Don Siegelman of Alabama made the lottery
the central issue in their campaigns last year. Both are Democrats
who unseated Republican incumbents, largely by arguing that the
success of lotteries in neighboring states like Georgia and Florida
made it pointless for their states not to share in the bounty.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina's lottery debate, the House Republican
majority was long considered the most significant impediment to
gaining the two-thirds vote needed to place a constitutional
amendment on the ballot in the 2000 general election. The House had
voted down lottery bills in previous years, and a number of
prominent Republicans, including Speaker David Wilkins, continued
to oppose the measure. ``Simply put, I don't think it's good for
the state of South Carolina to be in the business of gambling,''
Wilkins said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Typically in Southern states, Republicans have opposed gambling
measures out of both personal conviction and the need to curry
favor with conservative Christians, an active and well-organized
Republican constituency group.
</P>
<P>
   But after Hodges used the lottery issue to upset David Beasley,
the incumbent Republican governor, in last November's election,
many Republicans dropped their opposition and said they would
support giving South Carolinians the right to decide. Public
opinion polls have indicated broad support in South Carolina for
the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone knew that the votes were there and that it
was inevitable, but it still was somewhat disappointing,'' Wilkins
said of Wednesday's 88-31 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote was clearly a significant victory for South
Carolina's rookie governor, who demonstrated his interest in the
legislation by making an unusual visit to the House floor when the
debate on the lottery bill began on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges said Wednesday that South Carolina's Legislature had
``made history today'' and predicted that ``South Carolina will
have a lottery with a positive vote of the people.'' He added:
``Now our next goal is to get this bill in final form in both
chambers of the Legislature, to move it on to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved Wednesday does not specify how South
Carolina's lottery law would be written or what programs its
proceeds would benefit. But Hodges, a former lottery opponent who
became a convert to the cause while campaigning for governor, has
proposed dedicating the lottery's proceeds to college scholarships,
pre-kindergarten programs, reducing class sizes and other
educational initiatives. That would be similar to Georgia's
lottery, which began in 1993 and has been wildly popular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
