<HEADLINE>
CAMPERS: DON'T EXPECT DEEP FREEZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. _ Boating and camping often go hand in
hand in the Eastern Sierra, and anglers towing vessels for the
trout opener should have no trouble with frozen campsites.
</P>
<P>
   All major roadside lakes and surrounding campgrounds are
ice-free, a far cry from last year's opener, when resilient snow
precluded camping at Convict Lake, Crowley Lake's North Landing and
the June Lake Loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so much grass growing, we had to mow it. And we had
flowers growing. Then we just got a foot of snow,'' Convict Lake
Resort general manager David DeSurra said Wednesday after a
late-season storm. ``But we're sure it's going to melt soon, the
sun is shining so bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat launching at Convict is free, but overnight dock spaces are
sold out. Boat rentals are $65 per day. Camping is $11 a night,
first-come, first serve, starting at 2 p.m. April 21. Information:
(760) 934-3800.
</P>
<P>
   Camping at Crowley is $20 a night or $40 for five nights, April
22-26. Launching is $12, or $30 for the season. Dock spaces are $85
for the five nights (launching not included). Boat rentals have
been booked since Jan. 4. Day-use parking is $6. Information: (760)
935-4301.
</P>
<P>
   At June Lake: Launch fees are $10 at June Lake Marina, dock
spaces are $20 a night (launching included) and a three-day boat
rental is $170. Information: (760) 648-7726. Launching is $5 at Big
Rock Landing, dock spaces are sold out (but shoreline tie-ups are
$5) and a two-day boat rental is $85. Information: (760) 648-7717.
Campsites within the June Lake Loop are $12 and managed by Pyramid
Enterprises, (800) 416-6992.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on ramp fees and boating restrictions for
individual lakes, check out the www.thesierraweb.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Most campsites in the Inyo and Humboldt-Toiyabe national forests
are first-come, first-serve; reservations for those sites that have
them available can be made by calling the National Recreation
Reservation Service, (877) 444-6777 or (800) 280-2267. (Note:
Forest Service officials warn that callers have experienced
``terrible'' problems in getting through to the service and
securing reservations.)
</P>
<P>
   For other public campgrounds, call the Bureau of Land
Management, (760) 872-4881, Inyo County Parks and Recreation, (760)
878-0272, and Mono County Parks and Recreation, (760) 932-5252.
</P>
</TEXT>
