<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS SERB COMMANDERS COULD BE CHARGED WITH WAR CRIMES &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States warned Serb commanders Wednesday
that they could be charged with war crimes for carrying out the
brutal ``depopulation'' of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As allied forces entered the 15th day of their bombing campaign
aimed at driving the forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic out of Kosovo, there were reports of a Cypriot diplomatic
mission to Belgrade aimed at winning the release of three U.S.
soldiers who were taken captive last week by Serb troops on the
border of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian officials said the three were being treated well and
confirmed that Milosevic was planning to meet today with Spyros
Kyprianou, the acting president of Cyprus, who hopes to win their
release.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration welcomed the news of Kyprianou's
surprise trip to Belgrade, and State Department officials said the
United States would provide a plane to help facilitate his mission.
But they made it clear that the release of the soldiers, including
Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, of Huntsville, Texas, must have no strings
attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that will be acceptable is an unconditional
release,'' said State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Gilbert and Rosie Gonzales of
Huntsville, who learned from television of the efforts to free
their eldest son, said the development ``really raises our hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization headquarters
in Brussels, Belgium, made it clear that even if the soldiers are
freed, the bombing and missile attacks on Serb military targets
will continue with ``unremitting'' and ``ruthless efficiency,'' as
Air Commodore David Wilby put it.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby's remarks were reinforced by Defense Secretary William
Cohen, who was in Brussels to meet with his NATO counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO indeed intends to stay the course. This is no time to
pause,'' Cohen said, referring to what he called ongoing acts of
``unspeakable brutality'' by Milosevic's forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Cohen spoke with reporters, the allies again hit
targets in downtown Belgrade and throughout Serbia and Kosovo.
Serbian television reported another military headquarters building
was hit, and Pentagon officials confirmed that a small unmanned
NATO reconnaissance drone was shot down by Serb anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, meanwhile, rejected continuing efforts by
Milosevic to end the bombing by pushing his cease-fire proposal.
Belgrade officials said it calls for the resettlement of nearly
600,000 Kosovar refugees now in camps in Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough now for Mr. Milosevic to say that his forces
will cease fire in Kosovo, denied its freedom and devoid of its
people. He must withdraw his forces, let the refugees return,
permit the deployment of an international security force. Nothing
less will bring peace with security to the people of Kosovo,''
Clinton said in a major foreign policy address here.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO entered its third week of bombing, allied officials
reported what Wilby referred to as the most ``robust'' and
successful day`` yet for allied planes. Wilby said that 439 sorties
were flown Tuesday night, with targets ranging from Serb armored
columns to oil refineries and weapons factories in 28 areas in
Kosovo and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials also reported that for the first time, NATO
warplanes were able to carry out low daylight attacks on several
armored units operating in Kosovo, including one column of seven to
12 vehicles. Wilby said the pilots flew close enough to have a
clear view from the cockpit as their cluster bombs hit their
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the missions flown prior to Tuesday night, Wilby said,
were carried out from greater distances using guided bombs and
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby quickly added, however, that Serb forces still have
significant air defense systems, including surface-to-air missiles.
He said at least one SAM site was taken out along the border of
Montenegro on Tuesday night when it locked on to group of NATO
warplanes. Three more Russian-made MiG fighters were destroyed
during an attack on a military airstrip in Pristina, Kosovo, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing intelligence sources, Pentagon officials said Wednesday
that there is growing evidence of dissension within the ranks of
both the Yugoslav army and security police.
</P>
<P>
   In a message aimed at fomenting more division, the State
Department released the names of nine Serb commanders in Kosovo,
warning them that they will be held responsible for atrocities
carried out by troops under their direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are naming these nine commanders as a warning to them that
the world is watching,'' Rubin said, adding that ``in the coming
days, terrible things further could happen in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and NATO released a report Wednesday that
will be presented to the international war crimes tribunal at The
Hague in the Netherlands outlining evidence of killings and other
atrocities by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
