<HEADER>
A9818 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBYA-EXCLUSIVE-BOS &LR;      04-07 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-EXCLUSIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SEEKS TALKS WITH LIBYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Clinton administration has secretly
approached Libya through a UN mediator to request the first
face-to-face talks since the two nations broke diplomatic ties
nearly two decades ago, according to senior US and Libyan
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative by Washington reflects a desire to explore
improved relations with Tripoli following its handover of two
suspects in the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103. But senior
administration officials cautioned that Libya's continued support
for terrorism remains an obstacle to a significant thaw in
relations between the two adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan delivered a request for talks
from the US representative to the United Nations, Peter Burleigh,
to Libya's UN ambassador, Abuzed Omar Dorda, more than two weeks
ago, according to sources. The discussions _ which are to focus on
UN sanctions against Libya _ would be hosted by Annan and include
the ambassadors of the US, Britain and Libya, according to Dorda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready any time they are,'' Dorda said in an interview.
``Dialogue is the solution. Any normalization of relations, any
cooperation will be to the benefit of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is planning to use the meetings to seek
further assurances from Libya that it will renounce terrorism,
adequately compensate the relatives of the Pan Am victims, and
cooperate with a Scottish court trying the Lockerbie suspects in
the Netherlands. Libya hopes to obtain guarantees that sanctions
will be lifted once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Burleigh declined to comment on the talks. However, a senior US
official confirmed that the initiative was under consideration. The
official said it was simply one among ``a number of proposals'' to
be debated by members of the UN Security Council over the coming
months as it considers whether to lift sanctions on Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil Matar, a Lebanese journalist who has covered the UN for
more than a decade, said Britain, South Africa and Saudi Arabia _
the key mediators in the current dispute with Libya _ have pressed
the US in recent months to reward Libya for its surrender of the
two suspects with face to face talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans initially didn't want a meeting,'' Matar said.
``They were forced into it.'' But he added that Washington's
willingness ``to sit down at the same table'' represents a tacit
recognition that ``Libya has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Libya's ambassador said that Annan and Britain's UN ambassador,
Sir Jeremy Greenstock, are still hammering out the final details of
the negotiations. He said he did not know if the discussions were
intended to be held in secret. But he added that he hoped the
discussions would lead towards smoother ties with Washington, which
broke ties with Tripoli in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the UN Security Council voted to suspend a ban on air
travel and a series of economic sanctions imposed on Libya between
1992 and 1993. Annan is due to report on whether Libya has met its
obligations to have sanctions lifted permanently. The discussions
are aimed at helping reaching an agreement between the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Libya's handover of the two Libyan intelligence
agents marked a major shift in Libya's relations with the outside
world. And it has set the stage for the diplomatic initiative in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the most significant development in US-Libyan
relations since Lockerbie,'' said Gideon Rose, deputy director of
national security at the Council on Foreign Relations. ``The
surrender of the suspects for trial is setting in motion a huge
chain of events that are going to fundamentally alter Libya's
relations with the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   Libya has been among the top of America's list of foreign
enemies since Washington severed relations in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   It has retained a place on the State Department's list of
terrorist nations.
</P>
<P>
   Its alleged sponsorship of terrorist acts against US citizens _
primarily the killing of 189 Americans aboard Pan Am 103 _ remains
a huge obstacle to any efforts to improve Libya's relations with
Washington, said Bruce Hoffman, the head of Rand Corp.'s Washington
office.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, the author of ``Inside Terrorism,'' said Libyan leader
Moammar Khadafy has sponsored numerous attacks against US and
British targets. But he said that while US of intelligence still
suspects Libya of developing chemical weapons agents, Tripoli has
moderated its position since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have shied away from sponsorship of terrorism,'' said
Hoffman. ``These talks could pave the way for Libya being taken off
the list of terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   A key obstacle of any rapproachment is the opposition of the Pan
Am 103 relatives. Many fear the case in the Netherlands will
overlook Khadafy's involvement. The handover Monday already angered
some relatives, such as Susan Cohen of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of justice is this?'' said Cohen, who lost her
20-year-old daughter in the explosion. ``This deal exonerates
Khadafy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
