<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MONEY WINNER MAY BE BOSTON CABBIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Michigan, Illinois, Virgina, Georgia, Maryland)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The winner of the $197 million lottery jackpot did not
come forward Wednesday, but drivers for a local taxi company
believe it was one of their own: an African immigrant who drives a
taxi 60 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   John Ford, the vice president of Town Taxi in Boston, said a man
who drives one of his cabs asked a pool of cabbies at Logan Airport
Wednesday if they knew the winning numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Someone read aloud from a newspaper, ``12, 17, 22, 33 and 44,
and Big Money Ball number 25,'' and the man said with a laugh,
``That's my ticket! I won!''
</P>
<P>
   The others didn't believe him until they crowded around to look
at the ticket, according to Ford, who said he talked to two drivers
who said they have seen the ticket. ``Oh my God, you won!'' someone
screamed, and then more people started rushing over.
</P>
<P>
   The driver became frazzled, jumped into his cab and drove off.
His cab, No. 697, hadn't been found by the taxi company by
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't find him anywhere,'' Ford said. ``We'd like to know
how he's doing. . . . I'd like to adopt him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was supposed to turn the cab in at 4 p.m., but never returned
and didn't respond to radio dispatches.
</P>
<P>
   Ford knows little about the man, and wasn't sure how to spell
his last name. Since he is an independent contractor, his name is
not listed in company documents.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery spokeswoman Susan Frigoletto said that at this point,
any speculation is purely rumor. Until the person walks into
lottery headquarters in Braintree with the winning ticket, there is
no winner.
</P>
<P>
   Frigoletto said it's not uncommon for a person to wait days,
even weeks, before walking in to claim their prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to gain their composure, find an attorney,''
Frigoletto said. ``From what I've heard from winners I've met, it's
kind of like a state of shock. . . . Someone is holding on to a
piece of paper and it's worth $197 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever has the ticket will win the largest jackpot in
Massachusetts history and the second largest jackpot in the
country, behind the $295 million Power Ball win last year.
</P>
<P>
   The winner can choose one lump-sum payment of $70.2 million
after taxes, or $5.1 million every year, after taxes, for 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Six states participated in the Big Game lottery: Michigan,
Illinois, Virgina, Georgia, Maryland, and Massachusetts. The chance
of winning was 1 in 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a sweeping banner stretched across a metal awning at
the Star Market in the Fenway, where the ticket was sold, which
read: ``WE SOLD THE $197,000 MILLION DOLLAR BIG GAME WINNING
TICKET.''
</P>
<P>
   Store Manager Martin O'Halloran said he, too, had heard the
rumor of a winning taxi driver, and said he just hopes it's someone
who works hard and needs the money. The Town Taxi where the rumored
winner works is near the Star Market where the ticket was sold.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the dispatch office for Town Taxi, dispatchers kept
talking about the cabbie who apparently won.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was me, I would've parked the cab and left,'' said Phil
Sales, a dispatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who said he doesn't know the driver well, described him as
``a kicked-back, quiet'' guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not very excitable. He's a very pleasant guy. A calm,
quiet guy,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   He's in his mid-30s, married, has several children, and lives in
working-class Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   He works the 4 a.m.-to-4 p.m. shift, and Ford said he believes
he's from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said he works long hours, ``But not anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporter Daniel Vasquez contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
