<HEADER>
A9823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FOX-430&AMP;ADD(2TAKES     04-07 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-430&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX MOVES TO RECLAIM COMMERCIAL TIME FROM ITS AFFILIATES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move that could help radically alter the
relationship between broadcast networks and their affiliated
stations, the Fox network is unilaterally reclaiming for itself
more than 20 percent of the commercial time now sold by its local
affiliated stations in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Fox television network, Lawrence Jacobson,
informed the network's affiliated station owners in a letter dated
April 6 that starting July 1 it would cut back to 70 a week from 90
a week the number of 30-second commercials available for local
affiliates to sell in Fox's prime-time shows. The result will be a
shift of an estimated $50 million to $100 million a year from the
stations to the network, which is owned by the News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox move is the boldest in a series of recent moves by the
networks to try to change their traditional relationship with
affiliates, which dates back to the early days of radio, and
executives at several of the other networks said it might encourage
them to take stronger action. One senior executive at a competing
network said the Fox decision was ``a revolutionary move in this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast networks, other than General Electric's NBC, the
industry leader, have struggled in recent years to make any profit
at all, as program costs have escalated and audiences have
continued to shift to cable television. At the same time, local
television stations are enjoying profits margins of as much as 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the networks, CBS, NBC and Walt Disney's ABC, still pay
affiliates an annual fee to carry their programs. The networks have
tried in recent years to adjust that fee or to receive financial
help from the stations in paying for expensive programming like NFL
games and the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In several instances they have succeeded. But the affiliates
have resisted any attempt to eliminate or cut back the annual
compensation fees they receive from the networks.
</P>
<P>
   In a system that was established in the early days of radio,
networks provide programming to stations and they divide up the
commercial time sold for the programs, with the networks keeping
most of the slots.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the managers of Fox stations only received the letter
Wednesday, and several declined to comment until they could study
the information.
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis Fitzsimons, the president of Tribune Broadcasting,
which owns six Fox affiliates, said: ``At first glance this is
surely not in our economic interest. It's something we're going to
have to evaluate to decide what our options are. We are not
particularly happy about it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson declined to comment or to make the letter available
Wednesday. In a copy obtained by The New York Times, Jacobson told
the managers of the Fox affiliates that the network had
``determined that it is necessary to make an adjustment to the
economic relationship between the network and Fox affiliates to
take into account the ever widening imbalance in profits between
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter cites a clause in the Fox affiliate agreement that
allows the network to change the ratio of network and local
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The 178 Fox affiliates may be more vulnerable to pressure than
the affiliates of other networks because many of them were weaker
independent stations whose asset value increased enormously after
they joined with Fox in the late 1980s and the network became
successful. It would also be more difficult for many of them to
defect to another network in the same city because of pre-existing
affiliation deals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year CBS, ABC and Fox all tried to win some financial
concessions from their affiliates to help pay for the new
television deal with the NFL, which will cost each of those
networks at least $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   CBS said it received about $50 million from its affiliates. In
exchange CBS established a floor level for the number of
commercials it would allow the affiliates to sell in prime time.
The network has achieved the most compatible current arrangement
with its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also made a deal with affiliates to gain money to pay for
the NFL. But when ABC tried to secure help on football, it ran into
stiff resistance. One big area of dispute came over the issue of
the exclusivity that affiliates expect for network programs. ABC
wants to sell its programs to secondary markets.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week a new effort by ABC to work out an affiliate deal
to help pay for football fell through. It was affected by a deal
that NBC, which has had its own confrontations over the exclusivity
issue, struck with the USA Networks television studio, which
produces NBC's hit series ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for a lower price for new episodes of that series,
NBC agreed to take a new series from USA Networks, and allow it to
be replayed on the USA Networks cable channel within 10 days. ABC
asked its affiliates for a ``most favored nation'' clause that
would permit it to make the same kind of deals that other networks
made. The affiliates refused and talks broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Now ABC intends to make deals with affiliates on a case-by-case
basis. One senior executive familiar with ABC's affiliate
negotiations said: ``The Fox deal has to help. The affiliates have
to see it's getting to be the Wild West out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms presented to the Fox affiliates, they would be
compelled to give back the 20 commercials, but could buy them back
for a price less than top market value. The stations would lose the
money entirely if they did not agree. To add to the pressure, Fox
said it would sell the commercials wherever it could get the best
price. That would include the local markets _ meaning Fox would be
selling against its own affiliates in some cities.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimons acknowledged that ``Fox is making the most powerful,
most aggressive move to change the structure of the
network-affiliate relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But he disputed the notion that networks need to redefine their
relationship with affiliates in order to survive economically,
saying that when networks lament the lack of profits, they never
include the enormous profits being made by the stations they
themselves own, nor the profits they make in sales of shows they
own in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   As for what he thought the Fox affiliates would do in reaction
to the move, Fitzsimons said: ``I'm sure there are going to be a
lot of discussions among the stations. Everyone will be evaluating
their options.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
