<SLUG> BC-MO-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI VOTERS REJECT PLAN TO PERMIT CONCEALED GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Kan.)  (mk) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Voters in Missouri have narrowly defeated the first
referendum in the nation that would have overturned a longtime ban
on concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum passed in all but 12 of the state's 116 counties,
but voters in St. Louis and Kansas City overwhelmingly defeated the
measure, leading to its defeat by a statewide ratio of 52-48. In
St. Louis alone, 74 percent of the votes were against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials said the 1.3 million votes cast set a state
record for voter turnout in an April election. The high turnout was
mainly attributed to activists on both sides who lobbied
relentlessly in recent weeks, saying that for the first time the
public, as opposed to politicians, would have a say in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   High-profile gun advocates like the actor Charlton Heston,
president of the National Rifle Association, made frequent visits
to the state, as did gun opponents like Sarah and James Brady, the
former press secretary for Ronald Reagan who was shot in an
assassination attempt on the former president.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton lent her voice to the campaign against
the proposition. In a recorded telephone message that backers said
was mainly aimed at women and was sent automatically to 75,000
homes statewide, the first lady said of the proposition, ``It's
just too dangerous for Missouri families.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brady, who is chairwoman of Handgun Control Inc., a
lobbying group in Washington, called the victory ``a huge step
forward for public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of putting more guns on the street is just a
disaster, and this vote shows people agree with that,'' Mrs. Brady
said. ``People in Missouri understood that this would've allowed
people to take guns into bars and stadiums and made the streets
much more dangerous. Common sense prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing broad support for a concealed weapons law among the
state's rural population, proponents played down the defeat and
vowed to continue their fight. ``You win some and you lose some,
and we've won our fair share elsewhere,'' said James Baker, the
rifle association's chief lobbyist. ``You can be sure we'll be back
in Missouri at some point, and you can be sure we're in this for
the long haul. We're not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign had drawn national attention and huge amounts of
resources from the rifle group, which spent close to $4 million,
more than five times what its opponents spent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, gun opponents cited the referendum's defeat as a
major gain for their cause, saying it was part of a trend in which
they have been gaining momentum. They cited a referendum in Florida
that requires background checks for gun buyers at trade shows, and
the filing of lawsuits against gun manufacturers by New Orleans,
Chicago and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election after election, referendum after referendum and poll
after poll are showing that what the gun lobby is pushing is not
what the public wants,'' Mrs. Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Clarence Harmon of St. Louis said the vote showed that
``the power of the people is greater than the power of the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   The referendum's proponents had hoped to add Missouri to a list
of 31 states that permit concealed weapons. The Missouri
Legislature had previously passed legislation that would have
permitted concealed weapons, but Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat,
vetoed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be sure we will be doing everything we can to elect a
pro-gun governor in Missouri,'' said Baker, the rifle association
lobbyist. ``And I predict the citizens in Missouri will have their
right to carry concealed weapons in the not too distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said that his group and other pro-gun lobbyists would
continue to push for such laws in other states, but said that their
strategy would probably return to passing the laws through the
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it makes sense to spend that kind of money
for one state's concealed weapon referendum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said immediate attention would be shifted to Colorado and
Kansas, where similar bills are likely to come out of the
Legislatures in the current sessions.
</P>
</TEXT>
