<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTENARIAN-DIES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Geneva McDaniel, exercise fan, dies at 111
 &HT;    By Harry Thomas
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Born in the 19th century _ only 23 years after the end
of the Civil War _ Geneva O'Kelly McDaniel, 111, of Duluth caught
on early to what became a late-20th century trend _ physical
fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in 1998 by a reporter for the secret of her longevity, she
replied: ``Exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps you fit and it's what keeps me pretty.'' After a
moment's pause she added, ``and water, lots of water. And candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDaniel became a local celebrity known for teaching
aerobics well past her 100th birthday. She was featured on national
shows such as ``20/20'' and ``Late Night with David Letterman'' and
also rode in the pace car at the first Gwinnett Metro Senior
Race-Off at the Malibu Grand Prix amusement facility in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDaniel died of pneumonia Tuesday at Briarwood Nursing
Home in Tucker. The funeral is 11 a.m. Friday at Bill Head Funeral
Home, Duluth Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a country doctor who died in 1957, Mrs. McDaniel
was leading 20 senior citizens in a weekday aerobics class at
Shorty Howell Park in Duluth when she was 102. Only a few years
before that, she had lead a daily exercise program at a Duluth
senior citizens center.
</P>
<P>
   That vigor earned her the attention of the national media,
especially late-night talk shows. She turned down Johnny Carson,
but appeared on Letterman's show in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe she was from the last generation that had no
pesticides in their foods, the animals didn't have hormones in
them, they ate wholesome foods,'' said her daughter, Sara McDaniel
Gregory of Stone Mountain. ``Aside from that, I don't know where
her drive came from. She just would not give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Before marrying her husband and moving to Duluth, Mrs. McDaniel
_ a Walton County native _ taught briefly. Having graduated from
LaGrange Women's College as valedictorian in 1907 with a double
major in math and psychology, Mrs. McDaniel believed in education
almost as fervently as she did exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody ought to go to college. Women too,'' she said in a
1987 newspaper interview.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter said that Mrs. McDaniel never forgot poems she had
learned at college. She recited several from memory at her 111th
birthday party in August.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors other than her daughter include a son, Mack Theron
McDaniel Jr. of Atlanta; seven grandchildren; and 13
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family requests contributions be made to
the First Baptist Church of Duluth, 2908 Duluth Highway, Duluth, GA
30096.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
