<HEADER>
A9829 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUSTIN-NEWCEO-TEX     04-07 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTIN-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANDY CHIEF EXPECTED TO TAKE JUSTIN INDUSTRIES REINS
</HEADLINE>
 CEO-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a move that would involve two of Fort
Worth's signature companies, Justin Industries intends to name
Tandy Chairman John Roach to oversee its transition to a new era,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Roach, 60, would step in for retiring Chairman John Justin,
whose company has struggled with stagnating profits while waiting
to designate a successor to Justin, 82.
</P>
<P>
   The move would return Roach to an active corporate role four
months after he retired as the longtime chief executive at Tandy
Corp., the national electronics retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Directors at Justin Industries emphasized that the appointment
has not been approved formally, a move that would require an
announcement by a company whose stock is publicly traded.
Wednesday, Roach said it is ``possible'' that the board will select
someone else to lead the organization.
</P>
<P>
   But some directors, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
board supports the plan of enlisting Roach and expects to vote at a
directors meeting April 16, the day of the annual shareholders
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Justin, who also holds the title of chief executive, announced
March 15 that he will retire at the annual meeting. He led the
company for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Roach, who managed Tandy through tumultuous times, has been a
Justin Industries board member since 1982. He is one of three
directors named to the company's strategic planning committee,
established last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say, with absolute certainty, that nothing is in
concrete,'' Roach said. ``If you hear anything else, it's either a
guess or conjecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Roach said he has been approached by other boards in recent
months, including one that offered him a chairman's job. He
declined to identify the company and said he is still weighing the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Roach has said he is not interested in just sitting on boards.
He said he wants to participate only when he can have an equity
stake and make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Roach disclosed in a public filing that he had
bought 21,250 shares of Justin Industries stock, valued at about
$224,000. Previously, he owned 6,750 shares and, as a director, has
options to buy 9,000 more shares.
</P>
<P>
   Roach said he bought the additional stock in February because he
believes in the company and has been diversifying his holdings
since stepping aside at Tandy.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he recently bought shares in four energy
companies, ``and I don't expect to have a management position in
any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If he becomes chairman of Justin Industries, Roach will not
oversee daily operations, leaving that to current executives, one
director said. But he will guide a transition that will include the
naming of a new management team and the adoption of a fresh
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Another director said the board was impressed by the succession
that occurred at Tandy under Roach's watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who brought in Len Roberts?'' the director said, referring to
the current Tandy chief executive, who is credited with
revitalizing the Radio Shack chain and turning Tandy's stock into a
high-flyer this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of him (Roberts), their whole way of doing business is
changing,'' the director said. ``Let's suppose Roach did something
like that at Justin.''
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have a long history in Fort Worth. Justin's
two primary operations, Justin Boots and Acme Brick, are both more
than a century old. Its stock is listed on the Nasdaq exchange, and
it reported sales of $440 million last year. Tandy's stock is
traded on the New York Stock Exchange, and its '98 sales totaled
$4.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies and their executives have been key players in
many civic efforts, ranging from downtown revitalization and
education initiatives to the Southwestern Exposition and Livestock
Show.
</P>
<P>
   But Justin Industries has posted stagnant sales and profits for
much of the '90s, primarily because of a downturn in its boot
business. Its stock price has plunged more than 50 percent in the
past six years while the broader stock market has been booming.
</P>
<P>
   John Justin, who worked at the company founded by his
grandfather for 61 years, is the company's largest shareholder,
with 20.2 percent of the stock.
</P>
<P>
   When he announced last month that he would step down, the
company named no successor. J.T. Dickenson, the company's
president, is 69. Edward Stout Jr., the head of brick operations,
is 73, and said this year that he will retire.
</P>
<P>
   Justin said he and the board will work on ``finalizing
management roles'' by the annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot comment on the selection process now,'' Justin said
this week. ``The directors will consider this issue at the board
meeting on April 16.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Roach, Justin said he has known him
professionally and personally for years and often admired his
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got off the track once or twice at Tandy, but I think he
did a good job there,'' Justin said. ``He's very familiar with our
company, because he's been a director a long time. He knows the
people we have, and he knows corporate law and proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, in a company filing, Tandy disclosed that Roach will
retire next year as chairman and director. Previously, he had not
publicly set a date for severing ties with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would leave Tandy sooner if he took the Justin
Industries post, Roach said he has held more than one chairman's
job in the past when it didn't conflict with his Tandy duties.
</P>
<P>
   Roach's career as Tandy's chief executive began in high-flying
fashion in the early 1980s, as Tandy rode the popularity of
personal computers. But beginning in the late '80s, several company
retail initiatives stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   In his final years as CEO, Roach struggled to turn around
Tandy's money-losing Incredible Universe and Computer City chains.
Incredible Universe was closed in 1997. Many Computer City stores
were closed and the rest were sold to rival CompUSA last year. From
'92 to '98, Tandy charged off more than half a billion dollars to
cover the costs of failed ventures.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago this week, Roach announced plans to step down at
the end of '98, and Roberts took on the role as the company's most
public spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
