<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9830 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-COLUMN08-COX     04-07 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This space for rent; put your product's name here
 &HT;    By Mary Alice Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ People afflicted with vague but powerful fears
of public places are said to suffer from agoraphobia _ literally,
fear of the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But what shall we call the creeping fear that consumer life is
subsuming all life, that commercial messages are so ubiquitous and
unceasing that they drown out other ideas?
</P>
<P>
   The recent film ``EDtv'' satirizes television and its
advertising while simultaneously serving as a vehicle for a
possibly unprecedented number of advertisements. The product plugs
are big and blatant _ cheerfully undisguised. Plugs within ads
within the story line both mock the pervasiveness of consumer life
and become part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Our capacity to consider anything too holy for commercial use is
fading fast, but hasn't entirely expired. A few people were mildly
shocked when the pope's photograph was used to market Mexican
potato chips. A weak gasp of outrage greeted news that baseball
team owners might slap ads on team uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Even a devout free marketeer like columnist George Will
concludes that, although professional baseball games are already a
blur of commercial messages, putting ads on uniforms crosses some
invisible line into ``assaultive'' advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans may fail to grasp why slapping ads on players differs
appreciably from computer-magic ``virtual'' ads that make
television viewers think they're seeing ads on a ballpark fence. Or
the ads that actually are on the fence or the scoreboard. Or within
the stadium name.
</P>
<P>
   A major beer manufacturer gives money to the cash-strapped Texas
Parks and Wildlife Department, which in turn advertises the beer.
That's kicked off a controversy, but not about the propriety of
using public resources to advertise a product. The debate focuses
on the propriety of advertising a particular product _ beer _ to
hunters, fishers and recreaters who may be under-age and who may
damage themselves and other outdoorsfolk after consuming this
particular product.
</P>
<P>
   Schools, too, are brand-loyalty training centers. Channel One
provides free television sets and ``newscasts'' filled with product
advertising. Fast-food brands take over college dorm food lines and
public school cafeterias. Beverage makers vie to be the
``official'' school drink and mark their territory _ the students,
the stadiums, etc. _ with their logo.
</P>
<P>
   Are we surprised that per capita milk consumption by children
has plummeted in recent decades while soda consumption has soared,
to something like 51 gallons a year per person? Are we shocked that
so many children ``choose'' unhealthy diets?
</P>
<P>
   Hucksterism is now part of the academic curriculum.
``Information kits'' and ``curriculum units'' allow Kellogg to
teach nutrition, the coal foundation and the oil refiners to teach
environmentalism and Campbell Soup to teach science.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development is slipping product plugs into textbooks.
The Texas PTA was horrified to discover among state-approved texts
a McGraw-Hill math text packed with corporate logos and product
plugs: toys, franchise food, snack food, theme parks, television
shows, athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The PTA's legislative action director, Karen Miller, remarked
that the ``Three Rs'' of the traditional classroom are being
replaced by the ``Three Cs.'' That's commercialism, consumerism and
classism.
</P>
<P>
   A spot check indicates that about one-fourth of Texas districts
are picking the ad-packed math book, according to Debbie Graves
Ratcliffe, information officer for the Texas Education Agency.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows the agency to reject textbooks for only three
reasons, she said. These involve refusal to correct errors, failure
to meet curriculum standards and improper binding. Hucksterism
isn't mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to justify brand-name plugs, if not the clear
promotional advice. Modern American life does, after all, revolve
around brand names and marketplace choices. We're ``logo-centric.''
</P>
<P>
   Airports double as shopping malls, with commercials blaring from
waiting room televisions. The trip may be punctuated with a video
commercial for duty-free goods and a visit from flight attendants
peddling perfume and wristwatches.
</P>
<P>
   Concerts and museum exhibits promote their sponsors, public
buses are painted up as rolling commercial billboards, movie-goers
watch commercials on the big screen and public television's simple
sponsor mentions are gradually being ``enhanced'' into full-blown
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Garry Trudeau saw it all coming. In a Doonesbury strip
from months ago, Coach tries to recruit a college football player
by touting the college's ``team Nike'' and its great gear. The
young player and his mother warm to the idea. ``Well,'' he says,
``I have always wanted to kick some Reebok butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Think he learned his brand allegiances in public school?
</P>
<P>
   Mary Alice Davis is an Austin American-Statesman editorial
writer. You may contact her at mdavis(at)statesman.com or 445-3635.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
