<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW AND S&AMP;P 500 SET RECORDS; FINANCIAL SHARES RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Dow Jones industrial average and Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index set records Wednesday, led by a rally in
bank and brokerage stocks. The Nasdaq market, however, retreated
from its Tuesday high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today there was a flip-flop,'' said David Dietze, president of
Point View Financial Services in Summit, N.J. ``People seemed to
want to take profits in technology and move into some of the more
traditional Dow names.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, Citigroup, J.P. Morgan, American Express and IBM together
accounted for 70 percent of the 121.82-point gain in the Dow Jones
industrial average, which rose to 10,085.31, an increase of 1.22
percent. It was the Dow's third close above 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's index rose 9 points, to 1,326.89. The
technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 18.74 points, to 2,544.43, as
investors paused to cash in profits in some recent highfliers.
America Online, for example, slumped 9 1/2, to 158, but is still
more than nine times higher than it was in September. Yahoo fell 6
7/16, to 208 7/16, as investors awaited its earnings, which were
announced after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo said net income rose to $16.4 million, or 7 cents a share,
up from $3.3 million, or 2 cents a share, in the quarter a year
earlier. Shares of Yahoo surged as much as $8.5625, to $217, in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a rush for the tried and true names,'' said Richard
Sichel, chief investment officer at Bryn Mawr Trust Co. ``People
were saying let's step in and look at something that's not selling
at a stratospheric price-earnings ratio.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, including Thomas Galvin of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said they were cheered by the fact that relatively few
companies have warned of earnings shortfalls as the spring
reporting season starts and by new-found stability in the bond
market.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread expectations of a cut in European interest rates on
Thursday also seemed to fuel Wednesday's gains in financial stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup jumped 4 11/16, to 71 11/16; Chase Manhattan rose 5
1/8, to 84 3/8; J. P. Morgan increased 1/2, to 127 7/16; American
Express climbed 3 3/16, to 126 7/8; Charles Schwab 8 3/4, to 116,
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette rose 5 11/16, to 78, and Merrill Lynch
increased 5 3/8, to 96 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, reporting higher-than-expected profits, gained 2 15/16,
to 44, and Scott &AMP; Stringfellow reiterated its ``strong buy''
recommendation. But General Motors disappointed the market by
announcing 2 percent lower March sales and the stock skidded 4 3/8,
to 86 11/16 after having climbed 3 1/2 on Tuesday. Ford Motor rose
2 1/2, to 60 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Besides GM, the only Dow stock to lose more than a point was
Philip Morris, which fell 1 3/16, to 33 9/16, after touching a
52-week low. The stock, depressed by tobacco litigation, now sells
at just over 10 times its projected earnings for this year and
yields 5.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Major Nasdaq decliners were MCI Worldcom, 3 9/16 lower at 86;
Oracle, down 2 1/4, to 21 7/16, and Amazon.com, down 7 1/2, to 175
3/8. Microsoft eased 3/4, to 93 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   European markets were broadly higher with the London's FTSE-1000
setting a new high of 6,473.2, after rising 57.9 points, or
nine-tenths of 1 percent. Brazil's Bovespa jumped 3.26 percent, and
Hong Kong, which traded for the first time since April 1, rose 4.89
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
