u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POWS-NYT &LR;      04-07 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYPRIOT LEADER GETS NATO APPROVAL TO ESCORT U.S. SOLDIERS OUT OF
BELGRADE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The acting president of Cyprus has been given safe
passage by NATO to fly to Belgrade Thursday morning to try to bring
home the three American soldiers who were captured by Serbian
forces near the Kosovo border last week.
</P>
<P>
   Spyros Kyprianou, 66, the acting Cypriot president and speaker
of its Parliament, will fly from Athens aboard an airplane provided
by the Greek government, said Erato Kozakou-Marcoullis, the Cypriot
ambassador to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kyprianou is not going to negotiate their release but only
to pick them up on a humanitarian mission,'' Kozakou-Marcoullis
said.
</P>
<P>
   A fervent critic of the NATO air strikes, Kyprianou conceived
this plan several days ago and then worked with the Yugoslav
ambassador to Cyprus to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to accept it. On Tuesday, Kyprianou received word from
the Yugoslav Embassy in Nicosia that his plan to bring the three
servicemen out of their imprisonment in Belgrade had been approved.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan succeeds, Kyprianou will fly into Belgrade on
Thursday, pick up the three servicemen and then fly them to
Nicosia, where they would be handed over to the American
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic releases the soldiers, it would be his second peace
gesture of the week. On Tuesday he announced a cease-fire that was
rejected by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the capture of the servicemen on March 31, Serbian
television showed film of Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich., and Specialist Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas.
They were visibly bruised and battered.
</P>
<P>
   The three, part of a U.N. mission in Macedonia, were on a patrol
along the Kosovo border when they were captured.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Serb leaders said they would place the three men on
trial, but they later relented and said the Americans would be
treated as prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the White House and the Pentagon were cautious
Wednesday about the possibility that the Cypriot mission would
succeed. National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said that the
administration ``would welcome the release'' of the servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   As a country outside of NATO, Cyprus has not been part of the
allied air war and has been able to maintain its traditionally
close ties to Yugoslavia, rooted in the shared Orthodox Christian
faith.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kozakou-Marcoullis, the Cypriot leader hoped to
leave Athens Thursday between 7 and 9 a.m. He would be flying with
a member of his Cabinet but few other officials. No journalists
would be aboard, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
   Ioannis Kasoulides, foreign minister of Cyprus, said by phone
Wednesday night that he did not believe Belgrade had demanded a
cease-fire or that Kyprianou had requested one.
</P>
<P>
   He also expressed more caution than the confident Kyprianou. ``I
will wait until I see the three soldiers with the speaker of the
House here in Cyprus before being jubilant,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
