<HEADER>
A9837 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-ZHU-ART-526&AMP;ADD     04-07 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ZHU-ART-526&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITTY CHINESE PREMIER TAKES ON U.S. `SNAKE PIT' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-U.S., CHINA-ECONSCENE, CHINA-NUKE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing his biggest diplomatic challenge as China's
premier, Zhu Rongji arrived here Wednesday intent on surprising his
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders, particularly on state visits abroad, tend to be
reserved, stiff and sometimes pompous, as if having too much fun
might betray a weakness for Western pleasures. Zhu might be
expected to follow the script. He said his aides had warned him,
after all, that he faces a ``snake pit' of hostility during his
nine-day tour of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But, testing an old axiom of American politics, Zhu is trying to
fight venom with wit. The 70-year-old premier, with his poker face
and acute timing, can be funny, especially when no one in the
audience expects him to be. In the end, that pleasant surprise
might do more to soften popular American views of China than
Beijing's offer to import more American oranges.
</P>
<P>
   When Zhu combines a wry and sometimes slightly off-color sense
of humor with his fat rolodex of ``friends'' in American political
and business circles, he can sound more like a candidate for
Congress than a Communist Party cadre.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, shortly after his arrival at Los Angeles, he
detailed trade concessions China has offered as part of
negotiations to win entry into the World Trade Organization,
highlighting one that has been of particular interest to his
Californian hosts: lifting China's ban on imports of citrus fruit.
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who has known Zhu since the two were mayors
_ Zhu of Shanghai and Ms. Feinstein of San Francisco _ has
regularly complained about the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has a woman who comes each year to China,'' Zhu
said. ``Every time she raises the same old issue about citrus
fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, pausing a beat, he added, ``Thank God, from now on she
will never raise it again!''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, he tackled allegations that China had
obtained military secrets from a spy at an American nuclear
research laboratory, one of the latest irritants in U.S.-China
relations. Describing plans for China's celebration next October of
50 years of Communist rule, Zhu said China is preparing a grand
military review and exhibitions of its latest weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to explain to you in advance that these weapons
were made by China itself, not stolen from America,'' he said,
eliciting giggles from his luncheon guests. The Chinese army, he
added, will consider stenciling on the sides of its missiles the
words: ``Made in China, not in U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes, of course, are purely style. China's critics will
almost certainly view Zhu's humor as a ploy to evade addressing the
substance of their concerns, whether about human right abuses,
unfair trade practices or pilfering of American nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But at what are expected to be tough talks this week in
Washington, Zhu's relaxed demeanor could help break the tension.
The idea, suggested one senior Chinese aide traveling with the
premier, is that a few jokes can leaven the impressions of ordinary
Americans and make critics seem dogmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the people who hate China in this country are very
severe,'' the aide said. ``So we will be lighthearted.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In China, Zhu is better known for bluntness than for humor.
China's unelected leaders do not generally view politics as
entertainment. They hardly ever make fun of themselves in public, a
staple of Zhu's jokes when he addresses Western audiences.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the premier is not widely considered to be an eloquent
speaker in the Chinese context. He rarely uses the flowery couplets
and rhythmic idioms that constitute oral excellence in the
classical Chinese sense, preferring to delve into his subject
directly, to name names, to reach pointed conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   He even seems a little reckless, given China's periodic
political purges, when he speaks without notes. In reality,
although he comes across as spontaneous, aides say Zhu often
practices laboriously before important events, using
English-speaking underlings as a trial audience for rehearsals in
his own near-fluent English. He times his jokes and polishes
English phrases so he can deliver them to maximum effect, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Describing steps he is taking to fix China's troubled stock
market, Zhu told a crowd of Chinese-Americans on Tuesday evening
how he had courted Andrew Sheng, the head of Hong Kong's securities
regulatory office, to take up a similar post in Beijing. Zhu said
he had told Sheng that he could hire other overseas Chinese to
staff the office. China would guarantee them the same salaries they
make abroad.
</P>
<P>
   When Sheng pointed out that mainland China has an income-tax
rate several times higher than Hong Kong's, meaning salaries would
actually have to be much higher, Zhu said, he waved his
administrative wand to give his overseas brethren a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they could skip paying taxes,'' the premier said
in Chinese. ``But keep this to yourselves or my American friends
will be angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu also had a message for his American hosts.
</P>
<P>
   While he said that his boss, the president and Communist Party
leader, Jiang Zemin, loves Western-style opera, Zhu has other
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jiang likes it,'' Zhu said, ``but if you bring me to see any,
I'll just take a nap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
