<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-OWNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING REJECTION, MILSTEIN WITHDRAWS OFFER FOR REDSKINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Howard Milstein on Wednesday withdrew his group's
debt-laden, $803 million offer to buy the Washington Redskins from
Jack Kent Cooke's estate, after three months of occasionally
contentious wrangling with the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   When Milstein made a final plea to the league's full ownership
in the early afternoon, the New York real estate magnate knew that
he faced rejection if he did not withdraw. The league's finance
committee had already deadlocked on his group's financing package,
3-3, and it was unlikely that the 31 owners would approve the bid
if the finance committee did not.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the four and a half hour finance committee meeting,
Milstein stayed in his hotel room, occasionally wrestling with his
advisers over whether to withdraw, said one person who discussed
the situation with him. Several times, John Zuccotti, a legal
counselor to the Milstein family, was summoned to the owners'
meeting room to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   In a calm speech, Milstein reiterated why his bid should have
been approved, but conceded the owners' right to choose their
partners and agreed that if they felt he should withdraw he would.
When he left, the owners voted by 28 to 2 (with an abstention) to
accept his withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein rushed into a waiting limousine, but left behind a
group statement that said, ``In the end, we complied with all the
league's stated requirements and agreed to all of the league's
additional conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The record will show that we conducted ourselves in
an honest, forthright and courteous manner _ in short _ as
gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has never directly rejected a prospective owner, but has
persuaded candidate to drop out, if there were not enough votes for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Mara, the co-owner of the New York Giants, said, ``I
guess there was a sense of relief _ not that he withdrew _ but that
the issue is settled.'' Tom Benson, the New Orleans Saints owner
and a staunch finance committee opponent of Milstein's, said, ``It
worked out just great.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Redskins still face ownership uncertainty. The Cooke
estate will restart the sale process and John Kent Cooke, the late
owner's son, will continue to oversee the team.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke, who bid $680 million for his father's sports legacy,
could bid again, as could Daniel Snyder, a Bethesda, Md.,
businessman, who was a partner in Milstein's group.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any prospective buyer will pay as much as $803 million
is uncertain, especially after the difficult process that led to
Milstein's departure.
</P>
<P>
   The Milstein bid, the largest ever made for a United States
sports franchise, was in deep trouble Tuesday night when NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue met with several finance committee
members and Zuccotti. Tagliabue said the bid lacked the votes for
approval and an exit strategy was formed for Milstein, his brother
Edward and Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   The key element of the plan is for the league to recover a $30
million non-refundable deposit that the Milstein group paid the
Cooke estate in exchange for a vow by Milstein not to sue the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue and Robert Kraft, the chairman of the finance
committee and owner of the New England Patriots, described the
non-refundable deposit as an offensive term.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of owners felt negatively about that,'' Kraft said.
``We want to pick our own partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said, ``It was a penalty that wasn't justified.''
</P>
<P>
   The league disliked having the estate sell the team, but it had
no choice. It was rebuffed by the estate's trustees when it asked
to be presented with two prospective owners for approval. The
league wanted to be able to consider John Kent Cooke's bid, and
perhaps find a way to keep the team in the Cooke family.
</P>
<P>
   But the owners were presented only with the Milstein bid. Their
queasiness about embracing it centered on the steep level of bank
borrowing it would have required. They never accepted Milstein's
intention, at first, to borrow as much as $400 million against his
real estate assets, which were deemed not liquid, and not easy to
sell if the loan fell into default.
</P>
<P>
   A financing change made last week, in which Paul Milstein,
Howard's father, agreed to lend him $125 million, and not sue his
son if the loan was not paid, was deemed insufficient by the
owners. Paul Milstein also agreed to lend Edward $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the owners resistant to the Milstein group balked
at regarding the $150 million from the elder Milstein as equity,
and were worried that only $50 million in cash was in the deal, all
from Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of JFK, who was very well to do but always had little
cash in his pocket,'' said Kraft, who was in favor of the Milstein
financing package despite the large amount of debt. ``This group
has tremendous net worth, but most of it is illiquid or in
partnerships.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that entered into considering Milstein included
his litigious reputation, and his troubled 15-month tenure, with
Edward, as the half-owner of the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   The team's legal wars with Nassau County and SMG, the Nassau
Coliseum landlord, its slashed payroll and miserable record were
not viewed with admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue was pursued fairly or unfairly,'' said Jerry Jones,
the Dallas Cowboys owner, who supported Milstein. ``It was viewed
as a past sports involvement and negative issues were brought up.''
</P>
<P>
   Milstein was quiet yesterday about selling the 45 percent stake
in the Islanders that he and his brother own. If he had been
approved to own the Redskins, he would have been required to sell
the team. Now, he is likely to sell, but unlikely to break even.
The Milsteins and Steven Gluckstern paid $195 million last year for
the Islanders and the hockey team's cable television contract. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
