u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-2TAKE     04-07 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL DIVISIONS AT HOME REFLECT UNCERTAINTIES OVER U.S. ROLE IN
WORLD
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-POLL,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-ECON, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-POWS) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The crisis in Kosovo is causing rifts in both
political parties and changing how both parties approach military
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, who were internationalists committed to
defeating and containing the Soviet Union during the Cold War, are
now far more divided in their foreign policy views. Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, who is seeking the presidential nomination, has
been staking out the view that having entered the war, NATO must
now prevail, and be prepared to use ground troops if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   BUt a number of Republicans remain sharply critical of the NATO
operation. ``A lackluster air campaign has given the Serb dictator
Milosevic time to achieve most of his strategic goals in Kosovo,''
Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri said this week, referring to the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic. He said President Clinton
should continue to resist committing ground troops ``particularly
given the way the operation in the Balkans has been managed to this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, where the majority of Democrats opposed President
Bush's decision to wage the Gulf War eight years ago, most _ though
not all _ Democrats are rallying behind Clinton's air war against
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me the sensible thing now is what NATO is trying
to do,'' said Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader.
``Cumulatively over time this thing will have a good effect.''
</P>
<P>
   On ground troops, he said, ``I withhold judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats like Rep. Ellen Tauscher of California and Sen.
Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey have gone further than Clinton,
saying that ground troops may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But one Democratic leader is harshly critical of the president
and his foreign policy team.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outset, this operation never had more vision than the
next day,'' Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey said. He said the
acceleration of the Serbian campaign against ethnic Albanians
should have been anticipated. ``There are no questions being asked
now that were not asked in advance of this operation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think President Clinton has been very poorly served by his
foreign policy advisers,'' he said, adding that he would oppose any
commitment of ground forces to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   So far the air campaign has been waged across the congressional
recess, keeping this debate from reaching a crescendo. The
administration is preparing for three days of briefings to build
support for its Kosovo policy as soon as the House and Senate
return next week. Defense Secertary Wiliam Cohen also brought
members of Congress with him to Brussels this week.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the party positions reflect the fact that
partisanship even infects military actions. ``Depending on who's
president, people will switch position,'' said Barbara A. Bardes, a
professor of political science at the University of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   But the political divisions also reflect uncertainties over
America's role in a world no longer defined by the cold war. Both
parties are grappling to define the nation's vital interests and
responsibilities as the one remaining superpower.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century after the liberal anti-war forces behind
Geerge McGovern in 1972 called on America to come home from
Vietnam, it is by and large the Democrats right now who are most
ardently embracing intervention. In the House and Senate votes last
month, nearly all of them backed U.S. involvement in Kosovo. Some
figures traditionally on the left say it is because of the nature
of this war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil versus human beings,'' said Rep. David Bonior, the House
minority whip who opposed U.S. involvement in the Gulf War but does
not shy away from the deployment of ground forces in Kosovo. ``I
just think Milosevic is a person who is bent on extinguishing
people and I think we need to do everything we can militarily to
confront that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, D-Mo., who also opposed the Gulf war said, ``Some of
us think our vote on the Persian Gulf war maybe wasn't the right
vote. Maybe you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans, meanwhile, just a month ago were
trying to capitalize on their party's traditional edge in foreign
policy. Yet Kosovo has illustrated that the Republican
internationalism that predominated during the Cold War is no longer
a unifying Republican stand.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight of the Senate's 55 Republicans voted against the
air campaign in a nonbinding ballot on the very eve of the strikes.
And before that only 44 House Republicans voted to endorse the use
of U.S. troops as part of a NATO peacekeeping force should a peace
settlement be reached in Kosovo. An overwhelming 173 Republicans
opposed such U.S. involvement in another nonbinding vote.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republicans like McCain, Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana and Sen.
John Warner of Virginia remain interventionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a butcher loose in the backyard of NATO,'' Sen.
Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who also falls into their camp, said this
week. ``If NATO can't deal with this, are we living a charade that
there's peace and stability in Europe?''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans, some of whom saw the Gulf war as an
essential national responsibility, now make arguments about the
limits of U.S. power or say that it is time to reduce the American
role in Europe. And many conservatives are arguing to build up the
United States military but then use it only in cases where
America's vital interests are clearly at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not be in Kosovo,'' Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., said
Sunday, ``as we should not have been in Bosnia.'' He said such
deployments were stretching the military too thin. ``Our concern is
we should be able to defend America in the event something happens
where our strategic interests are at stake, such as in Iraq or in
North Korea. And this is just depleting and diluting our
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   With Congress in recess, the Republican leadership has remained
muted. House Republican leaders canceled a two-day fly around of
cities to promote their budget plan this week, with aides saying
they wanted to stay in their home districts during the time of
conflict. The cancellation also allowed them to maintain a low
profile on the Kosovo mission.
</P>
<P>
   But other House Republicans are speaking out. Rep. Tom Campbell
of California, an opponent of the Kosovo intervention, said he
plans to bring to the House floor under the 1973 War Powers
Resolution a measure disapproving of the use of U.S. forces in
combat in the Kosovo conflict, which would block ground troops and
also stop the air campaign. But neither the Clinton administration
nor any of its predecessors has recognized the act as
constitutional or binding.
</P>
<P>
   Under congressional rules such a resolution could get to the
floor for a vote by the end of April. Campbell is pressing for the
speaker, Dennis Hastert, to provide a more immediate vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of involvement in a civil war is very troubling
to me,'' Campbell said. ``I believe that is the accurate
description of the situation.'' He said he might also try to force
a House vote on a declaration of war to see what Congress really
has the stomach for in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2144EDT &QL; 
