<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVLON-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NY     04-07 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVLON-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES UP 18 PERCENT AS REVLON SAYS IT IF FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After weeks of speculation that it was about to be sold, Revlon
Inc., the cosmetics giant, said Wednesday that it was interested in
selling part or all of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon shares, which advanced more than 60 percent in two days
last month on rumors that a deal was imminent, gained nearly 18
percent Wednesday, to $23.5625, after management announced that it
was conducting a ``review of strategic alternatives'' and might
sell the beleaguered maker of Revlon, Colorstay and Almay cosmetics
and personal care products.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that if the company failed to find a bidder
willing to offer a sizable premium for the entire business, the
Almay and Ultima II brands would be the most likely to be sold.
Selling those pieces would generate some of the cash needed to stop
the bleeding on Revlon's balance sheet and enable the company,
perhaps under new management, to get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon is based in New York and is controlled by the billionaire
Ronald O. Perelman, who has an 83 percent stake in the company.
Neither he nor George Fellows, the president and chief executive,
was available for comment, according to representatives of Revlon
and of Perelman's holding company, MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon, which Perelman acquired in a leveraged buyout in 1985,
is sagging under $1.7 billion in debt. It has also faced weakening
demand as drugstore chains in this country have consolidated and
pared inventory and as international competition has grown more
intense from companies like L'Oreal SA of France, maker of
Maybelline products. Revlon has been scrambling for ways to shed
the debt and increase profitability.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement, the company said Wednesday that it had
retained Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. LLC to assist
in reviewing options for maximizing shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alternatives to be reviewed will include the possible sale of
one or more businesses of the company, in which event the company
anticipates that the proceeds would be used to pay down
indebtedness,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Shaum, a fixed-income analyst who follows the company for
SG Cowen &AMP; Co., said, ``There are a number of very large
multinational companies that I think would be interested in the
Revlon name.''
</P>
<P>
   Two widely mentioned as possible takers are the Dutch company
Unilever NV, which makes Elizabeth Arden cosmetics, and the Procter
&AMP; Gamble Co. in Cincinnati, the consumer products giant that makes
Cover Girl cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Unilever had only a small presence in drugstores
and thus would not face antitrust problems. It would also be a good
fit, they said, because it would combine Revlon's strong
international brand name with Unilever's vast international
distribution. P&AMP;G is seen as a more unlikely buyer for the entire
company because it would almost certainly run into antitrust
problems.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sales of cosmetics companies typically command prices that are
between one and a half and two times sales. Revlon would probably
get ``in the range of $30 to $50'' a share, said Tim Drake, an
analyst with the Banc One Corp., which with about 330,000 shares is
Revlon's fifth-largest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts and industry experts said, however, that although
the Revlon name was certainly worth a premium, the company might
have difficulty getting it because potential buyers would be aware
that management is eager to reduce the debt and that Perelman is
probably looking to unload some if not all of his investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look troubled now,'' said Allan G. Mottus, publisher of
The Informationalist, a trade publication. ``It's always easier to
sell a company that doesn't look troubled.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for the fourth quarter of 1998, Revlon said earnings
fell 82 percent on flat revenue. And in January, the company, whose
stock had declined by 60 percent over the last year before the
recent run-up, said it would dismiss 7 percent of its worldwide
work force, or about 1,200 people, to cut costs in the latest of a
number of reorganization attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman has had not only declines in the value of his Revlon
investment in the last year, but also huge paper losses in some of
his other holdings. He is the one of the largest shareholders of
the Sunbeam Corp., the troubled home appliance maker whose stock
collapsed last year amid management turmoil and unexpectedly large
losses. Also last year, Perelman sold his controlling interest in
Consolidated Cigar Holdings at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Perelman's favorite lieutenant, Jerry
Levin, the highly respected former chairman and chief executive of
Revlon, has been dispatched to Sunbeam, where he is now chairman
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``His best executive is at Sunbeam and he has a lot wrapped up
in that thing,'' Mottus said. ``Ron's got his hands full.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, investors have been betting that for just that
reason, Perelman was looking for ways to increase Revlon's stock
price so he could eventually cash out.
</P>
<P>
   But until Wednesday the company had declined to comment on the
unusual stock activity, even after the New York Stock Exchange
asked management to respond to possible material developments that
might be causing the market reaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
