<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9846 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      04-07 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 S.F. Web Magazine Salon Buys the WELL, an Internet Community
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
It's the feel-good Internet story of the year: Salon.com, the San
Francisco online magazine, announced yesterday that it has acquired
the WELL, a pioneering online community based in Sausalito, for an
undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   WELL members, a notoriously cantankerous bunch, were
surprisingly enthusiastic in their initial reactions. Their online
postings yesterday heaped praise on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a GOOD change, a GREAT change _ I couldn't wish for
anything better for the WELL. Absolutely a great fit. Bravo!'' one
member wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Salon bought the WELL from its owner Bruce Katz, who in the past
has felt the arrows of the WELL membership. Even Katz was heartened
by the plaudits piling up: ``This is a tough crowd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition pairs up two of the more literary-minded locales
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Salon fancies itself ``an upscale America Online,'' in the words
of President and Publisher Michael O'Donnell. It was founded in
1995 by former staffers of the San Francisco Examiner and is
unusual on the Web because of its long thoughtful commentary on a
wide range of issues, including politics, technology, books,
parenting, travel and health.
</P>
<P>
   The WELL sponsors more than 200 online ``conferences'' where
people can discuss everything from the news in Kosovo to the
Grateful Dead. The WELL, which will mark its 14th anniversary this
year, predates any other Internet chat service, but it never quite
lived up to its economic potential.
</P>
<P>
   In the lovefest that followed yesterday's announcement, Katz
called Salon ``the perfect ones to take it over,'' and WELL
Director Gail Ann Williams said members were ``dancing on the
keyboards.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the elation stems from the common ground and similar
sense of purpose, although some of it is no doubt due to the
reassurance that the WELL will continue to exist.
</P>
<P>
   WELL members nearly mutinied after Katz, the millionaire founder
of Rockport Shoes, bought half of the WELL in 1991, and then the
rest of it in 1994 for a reported total of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   As longtime WELL member Jim Warren of Woodside, a cyberrights
activist and founder of InfoWorld magazine, put it, ``The attempt
to purchase what had been an almost anarchistic collection of
loyalists and turn it into just another business did not work
well.''
</P>
<P>
   One part of the WELL, an Internet service provider, was sold to
a Canadian firm. A software company called WELL Engaged was also
carved off, although it remains in the same Sausalito office
complex, and Katz is still chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, WELL membership slipped from more than 10,000 to
about 7,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Salon execs see a profitable business with potential for
expansion, but since that sort of talk sparks alarm on the WELL,
they bent over backwards to reassure members that growth would only
happen in a controlled fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to dilute it,'' said Andrew Ross, Salon's vice
president of business development. ``The WELL is very protective of
itself, and understandably so.''
</P>
<P>
   The WELL's employees _ the equivalent of eight full-timers _
will remain in Sausalito. People pay $10 or $15 per month for
memberships, and the business runs a little better than break-even,
Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Salon isn't making any money, Katz said it has more
marketing muscle, with a national ad campaign in the works, and
deeper pockets. Its investors include Adobe Ventures, Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist, Borders Books and ASCII, a Japanese publishing concern.
</P>
<P>
   Salon is privately held and is tight-lipped about any plans to
go public. But it did make an important change, from a stock market
perspective, this week when it changed its name from Salon Magazine
to Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Salon finally obtained the domain name it's long
coveted _  &LR; www.salon.com. &LR;  Salon has wanted that Web address since
its founding, but a Texas hairdresser got it first and then played
hard to get.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Salon readers had to enter the more cumbersome
 &LR; www.salonmagazine.com &LR;  or  &LR; www.salon1999.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Salon paid an undisclosed amount of cash and stock to the hair
salon, and also turned over one of its alternate domain names,
 &LR; www.salon.net &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``It was annoying and really frustrating,'' trying to get the
domain name, said Salon President and Publisher Michael O'Donnell.
``We finally had to fly to Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the salon owner is a Salon shareholder, everyone gets
along. Salon's computers help host the salon's Web site, and they
share links.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? Maybe they could develop co-branded products. Or,
as one wag on the WELL suggested yesterday, start a new venture
that could be named Hair.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HERRING HIRING: &LR;  The Red Herring, a monthly magazine devoted to the
finances of high-tech companies, is tripling its online operations.
</P>
<P>
   That means doubling the size of its 12-person online news staff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the San Francisco magazine just hired a publisher _
Ted Gramkow, who had been advertising director at Forbes ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of what Red Herring CEO Tony Perkins sees as a boom
time for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The firm was profitable last year, magazine revenues doubled,
and publishing titan Ziff-Davis invested $3 million for what
insiders say is a 10 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Perkins says, the Herring is ready to take its brand online
_ with news, e-commerce and a host of other ambitious projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took ZDNet, Cnet and Yahoo gazillions of dollars converting
the world to use the Internet, and that was an investment I didn't
want to make,'' Perkins says. Now that the world is ready, though,
he declares: ``We want to be the technology business and investment
portal. The time is now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Herring launched an online version of the magazine about a
year ago, but it wasn't until January that it started putting
stories on its site every day.
</P>
<P>
   Now the plan is to take the site from five stories a day up to
15.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you rest, you die,'' said Rafe Needleman, the editor of Red
Herring Online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT SIGN)sfgate.com,
call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
