<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-TAXCUTS08-COX     04-07 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXCUTS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush says last-day surge put campaign tally at $7 million
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday that the
first weeks of fund raising for his presidential campaign were
about $1 million better than he initially thought.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, the final day of the fund-raising period, Bush
announced the campaign collected about $6 million in three weeks of
dialing for dollars. On Wednesday, he said the total that will be
on federal disclosure reports due next week will top $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a huge surge of money on the last day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Bush _ head and shoulders the fund-raising leader among
probable GOP contenders _ has his dad on the job. Former President
George Bush was the featured speaker Tuesday evening at a Phoenix
fund-raising event that attracted more than 200 people at a $1,000
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The event, first of the Bush presidential campaign, was a
political incursion into the hometown of two GOP rivals. Arizona
Sen. John McCain and former Vice President Dan Quayle both have
campaign bases in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron declined to comment on the
significance of Bush's ability to raise money on the former vice
president's adopted home turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Bush and former Vice President Quayle have a very
good relationship,'' said Baron. ``We are pleased the former
president was visiting the state. We expect candidates to campaign
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush had kind words for Quayle, a former Indiana
senator, last week during an Indianapolis fund-raising event for
that state's Republican Party. The ex-president said he remained
proud of his former vice president and said Quayle, ``took an
unfair pummeling from the very day I recommended him for that
job.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor plans to hit the fund-raising trail shortly after
the legislative session ends May 31, though he will have to spend
some time in Austin for the 20-day post-session period in which he
must sign or veto bills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having his father's occasional help, Bush is
working on tapping into the well-heeled and increasingly political
high-tech community. Next week's parade of visitors to Austin will
include a team of San Jose-based executives led by Floyd Kvamme, a
leading Silicon Valley venture capitalist. He was among 55
high-tech executives who ran an ad in the San Jose Mercury-News
this week urging Bush to seek the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The overall fund-raising effort _ aimed at raising the more than
$45 million it would take to be able to skip federal matching money
and spending caps it brings _ is dependant upon ``pioneers'' who
sign up to quickly bring in $100,000 each. Federal law limits
individual contributions to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 200 ``pioneers'' have signed on with Bush.
Among those involved at high levels are longtime Bush friends
Donald Evans of Midland (the campaign finance chairman), Brad
Freeman of Los Angeles and the 13 Republican governors who have
endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, where he addressed a conference of charter
school operators, Governor Bush said his fund-raising success is an
early and important indicator of the viability of his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first indication of solid support is whether or not I can
raise money,'' Bush said. ``And it appears that I'm able to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   On issues related to his current job, the governor told the
charter school officials that they are making a difference for
Texas students. Charter schools are state-funded campuses that are
free of many state regulations. There are now 88 in Texas. Next
fall, there will be 167.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charter schools are working,'' Bush told the conference. ``We
need more of them. We must not be afraid to experiment and have
social entrepreneurship flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Bush re-ignited his call for similar
experimentation with a voucher system pilot program that would
allow the use of state money for private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate committee, by a single vote, has approved such a plan.
But supporters have been unable to muster the votes to get the bill
to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is enough uncertainty that people are nervous
about it,'' said Bush. ``And that's why I think we ought to try a
limited pilot program to answer the uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
