<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SUBURBS-RACE-ART-2     04-07 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SUBURBS-RACE-ART-2TAKES(925)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTEST GROWTH FOUND IN COUNTY NEAR ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUMMING, Ga. _ Forsyth County has become the fastest-growing
county in the nation for many of the reasons that attract people to
the green edges of metropolitan areas: broad back yards for patios
and swing sets, good schools, a deep lake, all just 25 miles up the
highway from the corporate towers of Atlanta's inner suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the people moving to Forsyth County know something
else about the county that sets it apart: In a metropolitan area
where blacks are 28 percent of the population, it is almost
entirely white.
</P>
<P>
   A few new residents even know of the racial violence 87 years
ago that drove almost every black out of Forsyth County. But
officially that is considered ancient history, unrelated to the
10,000 newcomers who settled here in 1998, almost all of them
white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel that racism is an issue in Forsyth County
anymore,'' said Stevie Mills, the county administrator. ``There's
been a great deal of progress made, and all races are welcome
here.''
</P>
<P>
   There are indeed no signs of overt racism in the county. But
suburban development, like so many other aspects of life in the
South, is inextricably entangled in race, and distant moments of
brutality still affect how a city grows. Longtime residents and
planners who know Forsyth County well say it is not complete
coincidence that the county, recently designated by the Census
Bureau as the nation's fastest growing, is also, according to
census figures, the whitest among populous counties nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Most whites coming here are affluent professionals who share
little of the county's historical racial animus, and know little
about it. But for many people looking for a home on Atlanta's
pre-eminent growth corridor, Forsyth County's lack of diversity _
its homogeneity _ is an attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of an unspoken truism around here,'' said Phillip
Bettis, a prominent local lawyer who grew up here. ``No one wants
to say it, but I suspect some of it is true, though it's not
politically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas C. Bachtel, a demographer at the University of Georgia
who has done forecasting for the county's planning department, said
that many people who would consider themselves tolerant were in
effect benefiting from the county's racist past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county has become an affluent suburban bedroom
community,'' Bachtel said, ``and the people moving in have high
incomes and high educational levels. They look at the school
system, and it looks like a de facto private school. They don't
have the problems that inner-city schools have, substance abuse and
crime and that kind of thing. And in the meantime, middle-class
black families would prefer to live in neighborhoods where they
feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Many prosperous black families have moved to the south side of
the Atlanta area, while most of the people moving to Atlanta's
northern suburbs are white. And while northern Georgia has long
been predominantly white, Forsyth County is far less racially
diverse than its suburban neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent census figures, for 1997, showed that only 39
blacks lived in the entire county, which had 75,749 people. With a
white population of 99.3 percent, Forsyth was the whitest of the
country's 600 most populous counties.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since, the county grew by 10,381 people, or 13
percent, a rate that the Census Bureau says exceeds all others.
There are no figures for how many blacks moved in, but if blacks
kept pace with the overall growth, they would have added only four
people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1912, almost all of the 1,098 blacks who lived in the county
were driven out by vigilantes after three black men were accused of
raping and killing a white woman, Mae Crow. Two of the men were
convicted and hanged; the third was lynched. Black churches and
farmhouses went up in flames, and for decades after only a handful
of blacks dared to live in the county.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a group of civil rights marchers came to Cumming, the
county seat, to protest racism, and were attacked by several
hundred whites. Local people said the attackers were outsiders, but
blacks said the attackers were at least abetted by county
residents. A week later, a second march drew 20,000 demonstrators
to Cumming. The publicity gave the county a national reputation for
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, black families that have moved to the Atlanta area
in large numbers have settled in adjacent counties to the east and
south but still avoid Forsyth County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forsyth still has a negative connotation in my mind, and in
the mind of most African-Americans around here,'' said Nelson
Rivers III, the regional director of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People, who took part in the 1987 march.
``Just like Memphis will forever be the place where Dr. King was
assassinated, Cumming will always be known for that march.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take quite a while before African-Americans who know
the history will be willing to move there.''
</P>
<P>
   While blacks avoid the county, most of the people who have been
extending the metropolitan area's boundaries to the north have been
white.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, no whites said that race played a role in their
decision to move to the county, and several said they had never
heard of its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a nice place to live, and it's not far from work,''
said Stanley Travis, a computer executive who moved to a
subdivision in the south part of the county two years ago from
Memphis. ``I didn't ask anyone how many blacks live here, if that's
what you mean.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most subdivisions in the northern part of the county have no
black residents. There are about 2,000 Hispanic residents, many of
whom work at the poultry plants that are one of the county's
principal industries.
</P>
<P>
   Racial diversity has not been high on the agenda as the county
struggles to cope with its transformation from a quiet agricultural
outpost. Traffic moves more slowly every month, and the county is
running out of places to send its sewage. Mills, the county
administrator, said the county's water system, which served 700
customers outside Cumming in 1987, now has 19,000 customers. Even
developers did not object in November when county commissioners
imposed a 16-month moratorium on rezoning agriculture land for new
development.
</P>
<P>
   Swamped with the logistics of keeping the county afloat, leaders
say they do not know what, if anything, they should do to make the
county more racially diverse. There have been no recent reports of
racial incidents, and Rivers, of the NAACP, said he knew of no
complaints that blacks had been steered away from settling there.
</P>
<P>
   Bettis, the lawyer, who was co-chairman of a human rights panel
the county established after the 1987 march, said lengthy soul
searching helped cleanse the area of intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folks that were here at the time probably overcompensate
now to be fair,'' he said. ``I think people bend over backward to
avoid any possibility of being unfair or racist. We tell people, if
you move here, you will be welcome, and you will be protected. But
we haven't had many takers.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few blacks to move in was Joseph Mosley, who returned
to the Atlanta area from Ohio last year and decided to take
advantage of the amenities so many whites were enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, who works in the telecommunications industry, owns a
$350,000 house in the Deer Lake subdivision, and says he has seen
no signs of bigotry. When black friends question his wisdom of
moving to Forsyth, he says he tells them they are unfairly
stereotyping whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here to teach any lessons,'' Mosley said. ``But
if my being here teaches some people about whether an
African-American can move into a community and still uphold the
standards everyone is striving for, well, then let my presence be
an example.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
