<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     04-07 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNET HOAX ROILS SHARES OF PAIRGAIN TECHNOLOGIES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Pairgain Technologies shot up more than 30 percent
after someone using a personal Web site designed to look like an
Internet page of Bloomberg News posted a fake news report that said
the company was being taken over. The report spread to a Yahoo
message board and then to other sites frequented by stock traders.
By midday, the stock retreated as the takeover story was debunked.
</P>
<P>
   The hoax, which is being investigated by the Securities and
Exchange Commission and the Nasdaq stock market, shows the power of
Internet chat rooms and day traders, who make rapid-fire trades in
and out of stocks in which they can easily move the price.
</P>
<P>
   MARCH SALES FELL 2.2 PERCENT FOR GM
</P>
<P>
   General Motors missed out on sizzling vehicles sales in March,
reporting that its car and truck sales fell 2.2 percent from those
in the month a year earlier, largely because it could not keep up
with demand for its full-size pickup truck. Analysts had expected a
gain of 2 percent. Shares of GM fell $4.375, to $86.6875.
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO POSTS SOLID EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, whose Internet sites range from chat rooms to search
services, said that its first-quarter earnings rose fivefold and
revenue almost tripled, buoyed by growth in advertising and
commissions from online sales. Shares of Yahoo surged as much as
$8.5625, to $217, in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY ESCHEWS FILM FROM MIRAMAX
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney, the owner of Miramax Films, has termed a new
Miramax movie ``inappropriate'' because of content involving Roman
Catholics and said it should not be released under a Disney label.
The co-chairmen of Miramax said they would acquire rights to the
film and seek to sell it to another distributor.
</P>
<P>
   BANK SHARES SEND DOW TO A RECORD
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index set records, but the Nasdaq market retreated. The Dow rose
121.82 points, to 10,085.31, and the S&AMP;P 500 rose 9 points, to
1,326.89. The Nasdaq fell 18.74 points, to 2,544.43.
</P>
<P>
   APPEAL URGED IN BANANA DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   The powerful French farmers' union urged the European Union to
appeal a ruling by the World Trade Organization that the system for
importing and marketing bananas, which favors imports of bananas
from former European colonies over nations in Latin America, would
have to be changed. Sir Leon Brittan, the European Trade
commissioner, said the European Union reserved the right to appeal
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   FED TEA LEAVES POINT TO RATE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Minutes from the Federal Reserve's policy-setting meetings in
November, December and February indicate that the Fed has all but
discarded hope that the economy will slow significantly. That
increases the likelihood of a Fed rate rise. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   CONSULTANTS SPLIT OFF FROM DELOITTE
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche is expected to announce that a group of about
1,000 of its consultants, who provide companies with temporary,
experienced accountants, will leave the firm and create their own
company.
</P>
<P>
   RULING ON PENSION AGENCY REVERSED
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge reversed her opinion and ruled that the Federal
agency that takes over failed pension plans has a responsibility to
workers in such plans and can be sued for violating that duty.
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE SEEKS TO BYPASS MTV
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the joint Internet venture between Universal
Music and BMG looks like an effort to squeeze out the growing
on-line music stores. But in many ways the middlemen that the
record companies are trying to cut out are the traditional forms of
promoting music, including MTV.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT UPGRADING WINDOWS 98
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will ship an upgraded version of Windows 98 next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
