A9864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIP-MORRIS-FIRINGS     04-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIP-MORRIS-FIRINGS-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS DISMISSES THREE TOP MILLER BEER EXECUTIVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Moving to improve the sagging fortunes of its Miller
Beer unit, which has lost market share and volume in recent years,
Philip Morris dismissed three top Miller executives Wednesday,
including the chief executive and the head of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the dismissals of John MacDonough, the chief
executive, as well as Jack Rooney, the company's vice president for
marketing and Christopher Moore, the vice president for sales,
reflected Philip Morris' deep unhappiness with a series of
advertising campaigns that failed to ignite consumer interest in
the Miller brands.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them was the series of ads featuring a character
called ``Dick the creative superstar,'' which came to be seen as
tiresome and off the mark. Also unsuccessful was a subsequent
campaign for Miller Lite that tried to be edgy and appeal to
20-something beer drinkers, who are considered the best hope of the
stagnant domestic beer industry, with references to animals,
bathroom humor and offbeat characters. At the same time, the ads
did not mention the brand.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest campaigns for Miller Lite, featuring ex-sports
stars and celebrities, also missed the target. ``It's kind of like
watching paint dry,'' said Jennifer Solomon, an analyst who covers
the beer industry for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   And a recent campaign was yanked even before it made it on air,
after wholesalers were shown the ads and gave them two thumbs down.
The incident was first reported in Advertising Age last month.
</P>
<P>
   The proof was in the pitcher. Miller's volume fell last year to
41.7 million barrels, from 42.5 million barrels in 1997, and beer
distributors became enraged with the company's management after one
misstep followed another.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the advertising gaffes, Miller initiated a price war
with its archrival, Anheuser-Busch, the maker of Budweiser. Prices
fell to record low levels, and while Miller sought to take volume
and market share away from Budweiser with the costly strategy. It
was Budweiser that prevailed, by matching the pricing and coming
out with ads that were generally seen as funnier and more
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this context, with Miller not doing things right and Bud
doing things right, you see what happens,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a
global consumer products analyst for Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MacDonough, 57, came to Miller exuding promise. He had been the
brand manager for Budweiser at Anheuser who told a folksy story
about leaving the company because he was not a member of the Busch
family. According to the story, August Busch 3rd asked what he
could do to persuade MacDonough to stay. MacDonough replied,
``Adopt me.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced by John D. Bowlin, 48, who has been the
president and chief executive of Kraft Foods International, another
Philip Morris unit, since 1996. Bowlin was the president and chief
operating officer at Miller from August 1993 until December 1994.
``He was very well liked among the Miller distributors,'' said Eric
Shepard, executive editor of Beer Marketers Insights, a trade
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Bowlin has worked at Kraft's domestic unit as well as
heading up the international business. In both Kraft jobs, Bowlin
earned a reputation as a fixer who could take troubled businesses
and set them back on course, something Philip Morris seemed to be
hoping for in Miller's case as well.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mikulay, 47, and James Mortensen, 41, two executives from
Philip Morris USA, the domestic tobacco division, will head up,
respectively, Miller's marketing and sales. The appointments were
seen as a sign of Philip Morris' eagerness to correct the slump at
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a management change we are making in order to upgrade
Miller's performance,'' said Bob Minkoff, a Philip Morris
spokesman. While speculation is rife that Philip Morris intends to
sell Miller eventually, Minkoff said there was no plan to do so.
``If we wanted to sell it, why would we send a good team out
there?'' he said. ``It's a core business, and we believe we can
grow it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to shareholders printed in the company's most
recent annual report, Geoffrey C. Bible, the chief executive of
Philip Morris, indicated his displeasure with Miller, calling its
performance ``disappointing,'' although he added that the company
was ``taking encouraging steps.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 3 percent of its profits coming from Miller, on
revenues of about $500 million, Philip Morris might be better off
without its beer business, several analysts suggested. With a 21
percent market share, Miller is dwarfed by Anheuser, which has
about 45 percent. But to get the best price, certain problems need
to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing they need is a compelling marketing message for
the consumer,'' said David J. Adelman, a beer analyst for Morgan
Stanley. ``There has not been a consistent, attractive message to
the core beer consumer, and that is not something that can change
overnight.'' Although the beer industry has not grown in several
years, Miller still has an opportunity to increase its volume and
market share with the right tactics, Adelman added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cigarette industry hasn't grown since 1980,'' he said,
``and yet Philip Morris has been able to consistently grow its
share, year in and year out. Just because you have a few large
companies doesn't mean you can't have a dynamic, successful
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The management shake-up at Miller was announced after the stock
market closed. Philip Morris' shares ended trading down $1.1875, to
$33.5625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
