<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VACATIONS-AD-COLUMN-5     04-07 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATIONS-AD-COLUMN-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: DESTINATION MARKETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proving once again that nothing is sacred, not even vacation
time, companies are zeroing in on those precious moments spent in
sunny, snowy or neon-lit spots to market consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   It is all based on the theory that people on vacation experience
a temporary suspension of certain protective mechanisms and spend
more freely. Maybe the absence of bills piled on the hall table
gives rise to such a condition. At any rate, when they are away
from home, ``Consumers are likely to open up their wallets and
spend a little more rather than living on a budget, where they are
watching their dollars and living within their means,'' said Donald
Stuart, a consultant with Cannondale Associates in Wilton, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is what might be called the Proustian effect, in
which marketers believe that a product sampled on vacation becomes
a metaphor for that short, happy period of time, once vacationers
return to their everyday lives. Thus, even though a person cannot
be on vacation forever, he or she can keep buying that product
forever instead.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking has amalgamated into a concept known as
``destination marketing,'' in which companies pour promotion
dollars into places they have identified as prime vacation spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we decided to fish where the fish are,'' said Bill
Yetman, president and chief executive of Beck's North America, the
U.S. division of the German brewery. Two years ago, the company
hired extra sales representatives in seven places _ Orlando, Fla.;
New Orleans; Phoenix; Las Vegas; San Diego; southeast Florida, and
Hawaii _ and went to work promoting Beck's, one of the
higher-priced beers, in bars and hotels as well as wholesale
outlets. This year, they added the Reno-Lake Tahoe area in Nevada
to the list. San Antonio and southwest Florida are on the drawing
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are going to these destinations for vacations or
conventions,'' Yetman said, ``and the ideal situation would be that
they return from Las Vegas or wherever and go back home to Omaha or
Buffalo, and at the very least associate Beck's with the pleasant
times they had at these destinations. Or become regular consumers
of Beck's.'' The idea occurred to him, he said, while swinging a
golf club in Phoenix. ``I was looking at how beautiful it was, and
thinking: `You know, people come here a lot. I should do something
with that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is impossible to tell how many people experience a
product on vacation and end up buying it regularly. But in six of
those destination markets, Yetman said, sales of Beck's, at prices
from $2.50 to $8 a bottle, rose 20 percent or more the first year.
The seventh rose as well, though not as much.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are also in on the act. Automakers have long
placed shiny new cars inside airport arrival terminals. Godiva
chocolates, made by Campbell Soup Co., and Starbucks coffee bars
line many an airport concourse. Hotel minibars are hotly contested
display spaces for products ranging from bottled water to gourmet
potato chips, and luxury-goods makers arrange for giveaways of
their products in certain hotel rooms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Luxury marketers absolutely recognize the importance of the
travel market,'' said Lisa Henriques Hughes, publisher of Conde
Nast Traveler, where half the ad pages have nothing to do with
airlines or accommodations, but everything to do with expensive
fountain pens, Prada bags, hefty watches and imported cars.
``Travel is such a market screen for affluence.'' It is also a big
attraction for baby boomers, she added. ``Baby boomers are now in
their prime earning years. Intellectually, we want to see the
world, and we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacardi-Martini USA has a destination market, the Mandalay Bay
resort in Las Vegas, where its brands like Bacardi 8 rum and B&AMP;B
liqueur will be part of tasting seminars at the hotel. ``We are
reaching the vacationer who has disposable income, who comes away
from the tasting with information and knowledge to use at home and
experiences the product in a unique and upscale environment,'' said
a spokeswoman, Laura Baddish.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the method of steering travel to particular places
in hopes of promoting one product or another. Visa has teamed up
with cities like Baltimore and San Francisco to promote the use of
the card through books of discount coupons that can be used for
hotels and restaurants. ``It's to encourage travelers to use Visa
while they are traveling,'' said Charles Mardiks, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bacardi is trying something similar. In February, the company
held a conference for travel agents and tour-group leaders that
featured B&AMP;B made into a cocktail. At the same time, the room was
decorated with posters of the Palais Benedictine, a former palace
in Normandy that houses the distillery as well as an art gallery.
``When they are planning their clients' itineraries, this is one of
the activities they can go to,'' Ms. Baddish said.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to think about other destinations that might
work their way onto the tourist map because of consumer products
that wouldn't mind a sales boost. Could Bloomsburg, Pa., make the
cut, by virtue of the Heinz pet-food factory there? Or how about
Buena Park, Calif., which is home to a Nabisco cookie factory?
Cities could end up competing to be named ``destination markets,''
giving American companies a whole new layer of influence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
