<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC DECIDES AGAINST POINT GUARD BRUNNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No basketball players signed letters-of-intent
with USC on Wednesday, but the Trojans apparently have decided
against one player who wanted to join the team.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Brunner, a point guard from Dominguez High School, will
not be admitted to the school, although he had met with athletic
department officials recently and has worked out with some USC
players.
</P>
<P>
   Brunner played at Georgetown his freshman season and transferred
to Fresno State last year but never played for the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Brunner avoided criminal charges in two separate
cases. In December, a Fresno County judge dismissed four felony
counts of robbery and assault against Brunner. In September, Los
Angeles prosecutors dropped charges of attempted murder and robbery
of a junior college coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have three scholarships available, and are still
interested in several players.
</P>
<P>
   USC is looking at Verbum Dei point guard Marlon Parmer, who is
scheduled to make a campus visit, and Fairfax shooting guard Joe
Shipp, who is also considering California, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Another player drawing interest is Danny Brotherson, a 6-foot-3
shooting guard from Utah Valley State College in Orem, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it appears forward Shannon Swillis will remain with
the team. There had been speculation he would transfer, following
the departures last month of guard Quincy Wilder and forward Greg
Lakey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
