<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AIDS-DOCTOR-ART-1S     04-07 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIDS-DOCTOR-ART-1STLDWRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL SUES DOCTOR WHO WANTS TO LEAVE AND TAKE PATIENTS WITH
HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: subs to add fact that Dr. Wiznia and his colleagues did not
have contracts with the hospital in 11th graf; correct spelling of
Dr. Joanna Dobroszycki's name in 25th graf; minor changes
throughout) (ART ADV: Photograph is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It happens all the time in the legal and financial
worlds: Lawyers or stockbrokers jump from one firm to another,
taking their clients _ and the clients' money _ with them.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if the professional is a doctor?
</P>
<P>
   When Dr. Andrew Wiznia, a highly regarded pediatric AIDS
specialist at Bronx-Lebanon Hospital Center, announced in February
that he would move to another Bronx hospital, Jacobi Medical
Center, and that his patients and precious Medicaid and
research-grant money would follow, Bronx-Lebanon wasted no time. It
sued him and two colleagues, not only asking for millions of
dollars in damages but also seeking to bar the doctors from
treating their patients anywhere else for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Although legal maneuvering like that may be common in the
business world, Wiznia warned in court papers that such a
prohibition could have ``potentially life-threatening
consequences'' for the vulnerable patients he sees: about 180
children who are HIV positive, some with AIDS. They are not, he
adds, ``chattel belonging to any institution.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital has angrily contended in memos that ``the
patients in the pediatric AIDS center belong to the hospital'' and
has put the AIDS clinic's workers on notice that it is ``incorrect
for the staff giving patients `choices''' about where they can be
treated.
</P>
<P>
   Such high-stakes turf wars, once unheard of, are becoming more
common among hospitals around the country, health care experts say.
As managed care squeezes hospitals' budgets, hospitals are
increasingly trying to woo popular doctors, hoping they will bring
with them a rich pipeline of patients and coveted research grant
money.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the competition was mainly for doctors who treated
privately insured patients, but these days competition is fierce
even for those who care for patients covered by Medicaid, the
government-financed health insurance for the poor. Those patients
were once shunned because reimbursement for their care was so low,
but they are now considered a reasonable source of income.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest battles are over a particularly coveted set of
Medicaid patients whose bills are richly reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   This set of patients calls for many surgical specialties _
obstetrics and gynecology, neurology and orthopedic surgery. And in
New York, where Medicaid payment rates for HIV and AIDS treatment
are higher than in any other state, it includes patients like the
ones Wiznia and his colleagues have treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequence,'' said Mark Barnes, a New York health care
lawyer and former AIDS policy official with the city's Health
Department, ``is that there's acute competition among New York City
hospitals not only for AIDS patients, but for the physicians who
treat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although jilted hospitals, in general, tend to make some kind of
fuss over departing doctors, often threatening legal action or,
alternately, offering incentives for the doctors to stay, health
care experts said this case was unusual because Bronx-Lebanon had
actually gone to court to block Wiznia's move. Neither Dr. Wiznia
nor his two colleagues had contracts with the hospital. The lawsuit
keeps Wiznia and his two colleagues temporarily in place at
Bronx-Lebanon, after the sides agreed to a three-week ``cooling
off'' period, which ends Friday, when a judge is scheduled to hear
a request from the hospital to keep the doctors in place longer.
</P>
<P>
   The case has also raised complex ethical questions that doctors
and hospitals must now confront at the intersection of medicine and
big business, including questions about the rights of poor,
publicly insured patients vs. wealthier, privately insured ones.
</P>
<P>
   Would anyone, for example, try to prevent private patients from
following a doctor who switched hospitals, or describe them as
belonging to the first hospital?
</P>
<P>
   And is it unfair competition, or misuse of confidential patient
records, if a doctor tells his patients that he is leaving a
hospital and that he hopes they will follow? Or is he simply being
a conscientious doctor?
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of Wiznia's patients have indicated that they want to
follow him and his colleagues to their new home at Jacobi.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of income Bronx-Lebanon would suffer if those patients
left is compounded because Wiznia's move to Jacobi also threatens
to strip the hospital of another huge chunk of money, more than $1
million a year in research grants from the government and from drug
companies for Bronx-Lebanon's pediatric AIDS center, one of the
busiest in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because New York state's overall share of research money
from the prestigious National Institutes of Health _ the largest
contributor to Bronx-Lebanon's pediatric AIDS program _ has
declined over the last decade, such grants are as good as gold to
both private hospitals, like Bronx-Lebanon, and public hospitals,
like Jacobi.
</P>
<P>
   They are particularly important sources of income to the
hospitals in this case, both of which serve a predominantly poor
population, with many uninsured patients and few opportunities for
major philanthropic donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any major grant funding, the center will likely lose
patients and staff, thereby placing its immediate future in serious
jeopardy,'' the hospital claimed as part of the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health has written to the hospital to
say that when a principal researcher associ- ated with a grant _
such as Wiznia _ switches hospitals, generally ``the grant has
moved with that individual.'' The NIH has also called
Bronx-Lebanon, asking it to release the grant. The hospital has
refused, and it now appears the grant will remain at Bronx-Lebanon
at least while the hospital applies to have it renewed under a new
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the doctors named in the suit nor officials at
Bronx-Lebanon returned calls seeking comment for this article. But
in court documents, which include almost two months of angry
letters between the hospital and the doctors who left,
Bronx-Lebanon officials accused Wiznia of essentially arranging a
coup to steal patients and most of the AIDS center's staff.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They say that on Feb. 16, the day he resigned _ citing
longstanding disagreements with the hospital over grant spending
and the hospital's commitment to the AIDS center _ Wiznia also
handed over resignation letters for 19 of the center's 28 staff
members.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital contends that Wiznia essentially misled the other
staff members, and induced them to follow him by telling them that
the AIDS program was to be transferred to a ``windowless basement''
and that he was about to be fired, which the hospital says is
untrue. Wiznia denied that he misled anyone, and accused the
hospital of failing to support the clinic by not hiring necessary
personnel and not paying bills promptly. He said hospital officials
had told him that the clinic would be moved out of its offices near
the Grand Concourse.
</P>
<P>
   He added in court papers that he was not leaving because he
would make more money at Jacobi, which, he pointed out, is part of
the ``financially strapped municipal hospital system.'' The
incentive, he said, was that Jacobi would commit the resources he
felt he needed to run his program.
</P>
<P>
   The same day that Wiznia and two colleagues, Dr. Joanna
Dobroszycki and Dr. Michael Rosenberg, resigned, they mailed
letters to parents of their patients, reminding them that they were
legally entitled to get treatment anywhere they wanted. ``It is our
sincerest hope,'' the letter said, ``that you have been happy with
us as your medical care provider and will choose to remain our
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiznia contends that this was his moral and even legal
responsibility and, indeed, that of any doctor who moves. In his
case, his lawyers say, it was even more important because he has
treated some of the infected children continuously for as long as a
decade, has detailed knowledge of their drug regimens and medical
quirks, and has earned their trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can hardly be said that vying to care for sick children
with AIDS is analogous to stealing confidential information from an
insurance company or misappropriating cutting-edge computer
technology,'' wrote Wiznia's lawyers, referring to cases the
hospital's lawyers had cited to condemn the doctors' actions.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Ram Kairam, Bronx-Lebanon's director of pediatrics,
argues that it was exactly the hallowed doctor-patient relationship
that Wiznia and his colleagues abused. ``He confused the sanctity
of the doctor-patient relationship with the business of the
hospital,'' Kairam said. He added: ``What would IBM say if you
stole their clients and took them somewhere else?''
</P>
<P>
   Wiznia referred calls about this article to his lawyer, Richard
Nicholson. Nicholson said Wednesday that Kairam's comments betrayed
the hospital's hard focus on money.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids to them are poker chips,'' he said. ``The sanctity
of the doctor-patient relationship outweighs the business of the
hospital in every situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Thomas, 55, the grandfather of a 7-year-old HIV-positive
patient, said he would not think twice about sending his grandson
to Jacobi, even though he serves as the chairman of Bronx-Lebanon's
AIDS Community Advisory Board and feels a responsibility to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a precarious position here where I'm trying to be
neutral, but I'm going to stay loyal to the people who saved my
grandson's life,'' said Thomas, who, like many of Wiznia's
patients, speaks of him in almost reverent tones. ``Maybe there are
faults on both sides. It's like in a marriage. But you've got to
recognize the work these people have done to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   An official with one of the foster-care agencies that represents
dozens of the young patients _ about 40 percent of the hospital's
patients are in foster care _ said every foster parent associated
with that agency quickly decided to follow Wiznia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with a lot of immunologists, and he's the best one I
know,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``We didn't even have to go to the parents. We gave them the
option, but they had already made up their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the parents have already asked that their
children's medical records be transferred to Jacobi.
</P>
<P>
   But Bronx-Lebanon has let the parents know that it would love to
keep their business after Wiznia and his colleagues leave.
</P>
<P>
   The end of a March 8 letter to patients' parents was reminiscent
of an old-fashioned toaster offer from a bank: Kairam announced
that the chief executive of the hospital, Miguel Fuentes, had
authorized free parking and Metropasses for patients and their
parents, and taxis for those bringing in sick children. He promised
that the hospital would improve the elevators at the clinic and
would also start serving free lunches.
</P>
<P>
   As both sides become mired in the case, Wiznia has warned
ominously that the dispute has already begun to affect the
treatment of sick children. The National Institutes of Health has
halted enrollment of new children into their clinical drug trials
at Bronx-Lebanon because of the lawsuit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wiznia wrote, an 8-month-old baby with AIDS whose
parents consented on March 15 to enroll him in a clinical trial
``is now unable to obtain this essential treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Kairam said in an interview that Wiznia could easily enroll the
child in a similar drug trial at another hospital, and was simply
using the story of the infant to vilify Bronx Lebanon. He added
that he blamed Wiznia for the enrollment being halted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing could have been done in a peaceable manner,''
he said of Wiznia's plans to move to Jacobi. Parents of the
children who are caught in the middle of the battle say they are
just ready for it to be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that AIDS is a business,'' said Leonard Rabb, 43, an
HIV-positive man whose 10-year-old son is also infected and has
been treated by Wiznia and his colleagues for four years. ``It's
about dollars and cents. But Andy talks to my son not just as a
doctor _ as a kind of parent. When something isn't going to work,
he's honest about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing,'' he said resolutely, ``needs to get settled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
