<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANNAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOLDER ANNAN FEARS `GENOCIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-POLL,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-CONGRESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-TURKEY, KOSOVO-ECON, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES,
KOSOVO-POWS) 
(mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on
Wednesday put the United Nations firmly behind punishment for
ethnic purges, declaring that ``impunity is unacceptable'' for such
terrible violations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Annan made the statement before the U.N. Human Rights
Commission, a 53-country body that is holding its annual meeting in
Geneva to review rights violations in dozens of countries.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Annan condemned the mass expulsions from
Kosovo, but on Wednesday he went further, saying it appeared that
some aspects of the ethnic purges in the province border on
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has tried not to appear to back any one side
in the conflict over Kosovo, but the refugee tide has made
officials bolder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all gross violations, genocide knows no parallel in human
history,'' Annan said. Although the United Nations has no monitors
in the province, ``the signs are that it may be happening, once
more, in Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vicious and systematic campaign of `ethnic cleansing'
conducted by the Serbian authorities in Kosovo appears to have one
aim: to expel or kill as many ethnic Albanians in Kosovo as
possible, thereby denying a people their most basic rights to life,
liberty and security,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that violators could not hide behind the principle of
state sovereignty to avoid being held accountable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
