u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-550&AMP;ADD-N     04-07 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNER OF MASTERS MUST SHOW TOUGHNESS AND KEEP HIS HEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (See also GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
(rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The golf course has changed, but the keys to
victory have remained the same. Whoever wins the Masters, which
begins Thursday at Augusta National Golf Club, will take a familiar
path to victory.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will need a superb week of putting on Augusta's
lightning-fast greens. He will need precise approach shots, to
avoid the sure-fire trouble spots that lead to bogeys,
double-bogeys, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most important, the winner will need nerves of steel
on the weekend, the unshakable belief that he is tough enough, good
enough and composed enough to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   Many hearts have been broken on Augusta's final nine holes. So
while 96 players will tee off, far fewer have a realistic chance to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many have a chance of winning?'' said Fred Couples, who
won the Masters in 1992, and who tied for second last year.
``Fifty. But realistically, I'd say 10 or 12 guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples is on the short list of favorites, along with other
obvious choices like David Duval, Tiger Woods, Davis Love 3rd, and
last year's champion, Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike last year, when players were greeted Thursday with
winds of 30 to 35 miles an hour, the weather is not expected to be
much of a factor. Afternoon temperatures during the tournament are
expected to reach 80 degrees with little wind, and there is only a
slight chance of rain in the extended forecast. The ideal
conditions should allow more players to shoot low, which could draw
more players into contention.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no matter what happens, don't jump to conclusions on
Thursday. The first-round leader hasn't won the Masters since 1984,
when Ben Crenshaw opened with a 67.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the winner has to overcome at least one poor spell and
it usually happens early in the tournament. Even Tiger Woods
started with a 40 on the front nine in 1997, when he set the
tournament record (270) and won by a record-setting 12 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, O'Meara opened with a two-over-par 74 and he left the
18th green talking to himself before an emergency putting session
with his coach, Hank Haney, helped turn O'Meara around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable with my putter and I was putting
poorly,'' O'Meara said. ``On No. 10, I had an eight-footer for par,
and I didn't know whether I was going to pull it, push it or hit it
long. Basically, my confidence was very, very low. At that point,
I'm thinking to myself, `You can't be thinking this way if you want
to win a major championship, let alone at Augusta National.'''
</P>
<P>
   It speaks volumes about O'Meara's fortitude that he was able to
regroup and to win, never leading until the final hole, where he
sank the now famous 20-foot putt for birdie. Playing in his 15th
Masters last year, O'Meara drew on the knowledge he had acquired
over the years, while a younger player may have panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience is a big factor here,'' O'Meara said. ``On Sunday
last year, I just tried to play smart. It's not hard to be overly
aggressive here. You've got to wait and put your ball into certain
positions. You see the pin and you say, `I'm going to shoot at it.'
But if you miss, you pay a severe penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The average age for Masters winners is 32.7, not good news for
Duval, who is 27, Ernie Els who is 29, or Lee Westwood, who is 25.
Of course, Woods was 21 in 1997.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fuzzy Zoeller was the last player to win the Masters in his
first attempt, in 1979. But what do Love, O'Meara, Nick Price,
Justin Leonard, Bernhard Langer, Jack Nicklaus, Jose Maria
Olazabal, Bob Tway, Craig Stadler and Ian Woosnam have in common?
All of them missed the cut in their first Masters. Westwood, ranked
No. 7 in the world, will be trying to win the Masters in his third
attempt, something that Woods did in 1997. But Westwood admitted
Augusta nerves have hampered him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched it so many years on TV, that when I got here, I
was overwrought with the whole thing,'' Westwood said. ``A couple
of years ago, I had played nearly 72 holes by now in practice. I
wore myself out.''
</P>
<P>
   Length remains an advantage at Augusta, but average length
drivers like Nick Faldo, Olazabal and O'Meara have won this decade.
O'Meara believes what he does with the putter will be more
important than what he does with his driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has won here didn't have a mediocre putting
week,'' O'Meara said. ``Faldo, when he won, didn't have
three-putts. Tiger, when he won, putted extremely well. Putting is
as important as anything else, in my opinion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
