<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0499 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOOLHAAS-THEATER-NYT &LR;      04-07 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOOLHAAS-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE PREMIERE OF A KOOLHAAS FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This city has served itself a little slice of
architecture: the new Second Stage Theater on Eighth Avenue and
43rd Street. Designed by Rem Koolhaas, the awesomely talented Dutch
architect, in association with Richard Gluckman of New York, the
296-seat playhouse is an architectural hors d'oeuvre, really just a
piece or two of sushi on a plate.
</P>
<P>
   But it's fresh and tangy, a morsel of the sophisticated design
many New Yorkers have been craving. To paraphrase Oscar Wilde, this
latest addition to the Theater District is exquisite and leaves one
unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Founded 20 years ago by Robyn Goodman and by Carole Rothman, who
remains the group's artistic director, the Second Stage, previously
on the Upper West Side, specializes in American plays. Its new
season officially opens next week with performances of ``That
Championship Season'' by Jason Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The group's new home is an oasis in our newly upgraded Times
Square neighborhood. There is no theming, no nostalgia, plaster
nymphs or gilt rosettes. It's a light, modest arena for smart,
modern playgoers.
</P>
<P>
   This is Koolhaas' second project for New York; his design for
the Lehmann Maupin Gallery in Soho was completed in 1996. The
theater, at 307 W. 43rd St., in Clinton, occupies a four-story
former bank building that had stood empty for eight years. Built in
1927, the building has trim Art Deco lines, ornamented with
stylized polychrome foliage. The Koolhaas-Gluckman design leaves
the exterior nearly intact. It incorporates many features of the
original building, a necessity dictated by the restricted budget
and one that contributes to its esthetic effect.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance is through a plain glass door on 43rd Street. An
outer lobby, painted light gray, leads to a box office within the
bank's safe, its thick steel door plainly visible.
</P>
<P>
   The theater proper is on the second floor, a tall space, once
the main banking hall. In the upstairs lobby, walls and floor are
painted screeching orange, a vibrant color at once tropical citrus
grove and toxic defoliant. We are not in Mickey Mouseland anymore.
</P>
<P>
   There is no fixed division between the upstairs lobby and the
auditorium. Rather, a large, bleacherlike wedge of seats in the
middle of the second floor defines it into different areas in one
continuous flow: lobby, stage, backstage, seating and aisles.
</P>
<P>
   The wedge, about 12 feet tall at the rear, is asymmetrically
placed and finished with epoxy resin in a deep shade of green-gray.
An aisle leads along one side of the wedge to the front of the
house. Twelve-foot-tall windows, fitted with acoustical glass,
punctuate the wall across the aisle, framing views of 43rd Street.
The wall is draped with gold velour curtains, studded with steel
grommets. At performance time, the curtains can be drawn. When left
open, the city itself is onstage here.
</P>
<P>
   So is backstage, in part. Performers reach the stage via a
second aisle, enclosed behind a side wall of translucent corrugated
plastic on the far side of the wedge. With the house lights on
behind it, this wall glows with a cheap, industrial glamour. When
the lights are off, the plastic panels take on the glint of
satin-finish steel.
</P>
<P>
   The seats are of black wood, fitted with resilient pads made
from a gel originally developed for bicycle seats. The pads are the
color of parchment, and partly translucent; the shade darkens at
the edges, like gold velvet, an effect that echoes the plush of the
curtains. A rectangular cut in the plastic wall reveals a shallow
mezzanine furnished with a dozen or so moveable chairs.
</P>
<P>
   There is no permanent stage or proscenium. Right now the theater
has both; these are part of the set. Directors and designers are
free to construct a different staging and scenic arrangement for
each production. There is generous space from which to suspend
lights, backdrops and other items from above the stage. Tracks for
theatrical lighting extend the full length and width of the
auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The Koolhaas flair for naughtiness is restricted to two
bathrooms, set into the rear of the seating wedge and entered
through the lobby. These, too, are painted orange, with naked
fluorescent tubes glaring out from above the mirrors at eye level.
The reflection is perversely consoling: this is the worst you are
going to look all day.
</P>
<P>
   Straightforwardness filtered through a wayward imagination: this
is a Koolhaas design, all right. A theater with windows? No wall
between lobby and auditorium? These ideas may be odd to
contemplate, but they fit. They animate the intersection between
those two Vitruvian virtues, commodity and delight. So do simple
features like the gel seat pads, the strip of galvanized steel
grating used as a guardrail on one side of the wedge, the
off-center placement of a center aisle between the seats and a
quirky curve at the top of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   As readers of Koolhaas' book ``S, M, L, XL'' may recall, the
architect has periodically flirted with the idea of writing
screenplays. But he has largely sublimated this ambition into
design. City views, saturated color, translucent surfaces, the
sculptural treatment of function and the mix of cheap, costly,
space-age and traditional materials, custom-made and off-the-peg
hardware: these disparate elements are harmoniously composed in a
serpentine flow of space, as a cinematic montage is organized in
time.
</P>
<P>
   It is a performance space for spectators as well as actors, in
the sense that clothes by Prada and Jil Sander are costumes for the
urban stage. These designers dress people for a mythology of the
present. Koolhaas and Gluckman extend that mythical element into
the architectural dimension. You can show up in Gap clothes and
absorb the full effect.
</P>
<P>
   New York is poor in such spaces. Philippe Starck's interiors for
the Royalton and Paramount Hotels are holding up well for a couple
of Zeitgeist zones. John Pawson's Madison Avenue shop for Calvin
Klein and Adam Tihany's design for Jean Georges, a restaurant on
Columbus Circle, are potential classics. The new Comme des Garcons
shop in Chelsea tries too hard, but who can blame the store's
designers for overcompensation? Perhaps they're just trying to make
up for the dullness of most retail interiors.
</P>
<P>
   Among cultural institutions, we've got the galleries Gluckman
designed last year for the Whitney Museum of American Art,
Frederick Fisher's renovations at the PS 1 Contemporary Art Center,
and that's about it. There's been no esthetically alert theatrical
space since Raimund Abraham's design for the Anthology Film
Archives in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Stage is a work in progress, its completion
contingent on additional fund-raising. A small marquee has been
designed for the entrance, and there are plans to uncover and
soundproof five more of those grand windows in the auditorium,
including three behind the stage. This would make it possible to
turn the theater into a floating urban platform, hovering above the
street at dream's-eye level.
</P>
<P>
   A pity that the company's productions are limited to American
plays. Don't you want to see Beckett, Orton, Pinter, Genet and
Shakespeare staged in a house with orange bathrooms? Sure you do.
And what a gem of a showcase this theater would be for art films.
If design were a draw, the new Second Stage would become the most
sought-after screening room in town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-07 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: WHEN DEAD MEN TELL THEIR TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is often challenging and ghostly work, evaluating the wishes
of a writer who is dead, deciding whether a hidden manuscript is
worthy of display and therefore should be published.
</P>
<P>
   For authors who are important or popular, or both, there is
pressure to keep the property alive, their bodies of work available
and visible, to generate not only art but cash. To do so, there has
to be something new. Enter the literary executor, and lo and
behold, bingo, what was in the vaults is now on the bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even if that's not what the author wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The excerpt of Ralph Ellison's second novel this week in The New
Yorker reminds us that this summer there will be two major
posthumous literary events, the novel that Ellison had worked on
for 40 years and the publication of a new Ernest Hemingway novel 38
years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would have occurred without a truly resolute literary
executor, a role that is usually almost underground in its
covertness but has popped to the foreground because of the attack
on the publication of the Hemingway book by Joan Didion.
</P>
<P>
   Like only dictators or co-op boards, literary (or artistic)
executors have the absolute power to render, without restraint, the
property they superintend. They usually control only the writer's
or painter's or composer's creative work, not the remainder of the
estate as well. Thus they have the power to sift the work, edit it,
hide it away or hang it, sell it, open it only to scholars, donate
it to university libraries, have it published or performed. Or for
that matter to put a match to it.
</P>
<P>
   This spectral wedding between the executor and the dead writer
often raises the question, if an author didn't finish the novel, is
the novel publishable as the author's work? Is a de Kooning with
half the canvas left unpainted a de Kooning? Or supposing the
writer had every opportunity to finish and publish the work before
his or her death, and didn't, then can't _ shouldn't _ we assume
that the writer didn't want that work published, and aren't we then
required to honor that? Who owns the work? The artist or the
public?
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Didion's recent essay in The New Yorker, she eloquently
argued that the novel to be published by Scribner in July under
Hemingway's name, titled ``True at First Light,'' was not true
Hemingway; rather, it was cobbled out of a mountain of words he had
written but clearly had not wanted published, or he would have had
it published.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a man to whom words mattered,'' Ms. Didion wrote.
``He worked at them, he understood them, he got inside them. . . .
His wish to be survived by only the words he determined fit for
publication would have seemed clear enough.'' She described this
constructing of a Hemingway novel by the author's son Patrick, a
literary executor, with the help of Scribner as ``the systematic
creation of a marketable product, a discrete body of work different
in kind from, and in fact tending to obscure, the body of work
published by Hemingway in his lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's certainly an absolutist viewpoint. To which Patrick
Hemingway replied: ``I think it's a very valid argument. The only
trouble is he did leave the material; he didn't destroy it. Perhaps
he didn't intend to have it published, but when people are dead
it's hard to know what they want. Somebody, some day, was going to
publish these words, and I had particular insights about this
particular work.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Scribner, an editor whose great-great-grandfather
founded the publishing house, said that he had ``no doubt that
Hemingway intended the unfinished work to be published
posthumously.'' He continued: ``He knew an intelligent public would
understand the difference between books he lived to see in print
and those he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway did leave instructions not to publish his
correspondence (though they were ignored); he left instructions not
to publish the stories he wrote before he became what he considered
a good writer (though that directive was ignored, too). It would
seem he knew what he wanted published and what he didn't, which
adds muscle to Ms. Didion's essay. (The New Yorker also plans to
excerpt the Hemingway novel.)
</P>
<P>
   Ellison's second novel could also be debated. Ms. Didion said of
it, ``It's not written until it's written.'' But at least in
Elliosn's case there is evidence to believe that he would have
wanted it published. His ``Invisible Man'' (Random House) almost
immediately became acknowledged as a classic of American and even
world literature when it burst upon us in 1952. His second novel,
``Juneteenth,'' which was left unfinished when he died in 1994 and
was excerpted this week, will be published by Random House in June.
It was edited by his literary executor, John Callahan, professor of
humanities at Lewis and Clark College in Portland, Ore., who said,
``I was confronted with a real stack of manuscripts amounting to a
huge unfinished saga in which there were a number of potential
novels, one of which was `Juneteenth.'''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan contends that every word in ``Juneteenth'' was written
by Ellison and that all he did was use Ellison's notes to put the
novel's parts in the sequence that the writer wanted. ``If Ellison
had left instructions that he didn't want this unfinished work to
ever be published. I wouldn't have done it, but he didn't, and he
talked about the work, and Mrs. Ellison said she thought from their
talks that he wanted it published.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of publishing is full of what-ifs. Eugene O'Neill
asked his publisher, Random House, not to publish ``Long Day's
Journey Into Night'' for 25 years after his death, so his wife,
Carlotta O'Neill, who made being his widow a vocation, gave it to
Yale University Press, which published it within three years,
resurrecting the playwright's reputation and value.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably did it for money, but if she didn't, he might not
have been resurrected,'' said Barbara Gelb, an O'Neill biographer.
</P>
<P>
   Money certainly lurks behind the shoulder of every executor.
Sessalee Hensley, fiction buyer for Barnes &AMP; Noble, said the
Ellison book would be ``a big event both in literature in general
and African-American literature, and will be one of the two big
books of June, a good healthy best seller,'' along with Thomas
Harris' sequel to ``Silence of the Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby boomers are coming into economic power; they read
Ellison and Hemingway in their formative years, so both really
appeal to this generation,'' she said, adding: ``Every store will
have a big stack of each. They'll be floor displays in all the
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, we'd hardly know Kafka without his literary executor,
and there is this literature thing with Hemingway and Ellison. But
these new novels are also about those floor displays. The question
of whether a dead artist owns his or her work becomes a detail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
