<HEADER>
A9889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-500&AMP;AD     04-07 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: KEY TO MUSIC DEAL IS E-PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, the new joint Internet venture between
Universal Music and BMG seems to be an effort to squeeze out the
booming online music stores, like CDNow and Amazon.com. Indeed, the
two big record companies Wednesday introduced a site, Getmusic.Com,
that does compete with these sites by selling compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways, the middlemen that the record companies are
trying to cut out are the traditional media that promote music,
like Rolling Stone magazine, local radio stations and most
importantly MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of what the companies are trying to do is to use the
interactive nature of the Internet to gather the names and e-mail
addresses of their customers so they can sell more music to them by
artists they already like and to introduce them to new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promotional opportunity of the Internet, as opposed to the
commerce opportunity, is very powerful,'' said Edgar Bronfman Jr.,
chief executive of Seagram Co., which owns Universal Music.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is no better sign of the venture's lack of
enthusiasm for online retailing than that prices on Getmusic.com
are often 20 percent higher than on CDNow and Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Bronfman and BMG executives said that the most important
part of their venture is not Getmusic.com, the music store, but a
series of sites devoted to various music genres. These will start
with five sites developed by BMG, including Peeps.com, for hip-hop,
and Twangthis.Com, a country site.
</P>
<P>
   Peeps, in particular, has been effective in promoting new
artists. For example, the site started publicizing Britney Spears,
offering song samples that users could download, eight months
before her first album was released. It eventually collected the
names of 100,000 people who said they were interested in her music.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 80 percent of them bought the album,'' said Kevin
Conroy, a BMG senior vice president.
</P>
<P>
   It is this capability to gain direct access to customers that
brought Universal into the venture, said Lawrence Kenswil,
president for electronic commerce at Universal Music. ``People
aren't our customers directly,'' he said. ``They are radio station
listeners, record store customers or MTV viewers. At the end of the
day, we need information about that that is not filtered by third
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to lure people to the genre sites with inside
information and music samples that other sites do not have. Of
course, such content is the stuff of other media outlets, notably
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   And Viacom Inc., MTV's parent, is readying a big new music site.
Fred Sieber, president of MTV Networks Online, said that it would
not be cut out of the information flow because of its longstanding
reputation with both musicians and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists will talk to us, like they have for 20 years,'' he
said. ``Nobody doesn't want their music exposed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to its promotional goals, the BMG-Universal venture
is meant to position the record companies for the day when their
customers will be able to download digital versions of records
directly to their computers or to small portable devices, though
Getmusic does not offer such downloads today.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal copies of music, using the MP3 format, are the staple of
many college dorm rooms already. But the record companies want to
impose a system that keeps the royalties flowing their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to control the gatekeeper,'' said Thomas Middelhoff,
chairman of Bertelsmann A.G., which owns BMG. ``In the music
business of the future, it is crucial to have direct control over
the customer downloads,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, by contrast, offers an expanded vision of how music
will be sold on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will buy digital music across retail channels,'' he
said. They will use kiosks in stores, push a `buy now' button on
their Internet radio stations, and they will buy using new
devices'' like portable digital players that let people listen to
downloaded music.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly clear whether the record companies, in fact, have
the upper hand in the game going forward. Many music industry
executives envision the day when popular musicians themselves will
sell songs directly to their fans from their Web sites. Record
retailers, by contrast, argue that since they have the
relationships with customers, they are in the best position to be
the center of music buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the retailers who are imperiled, it's the labels,''
said Russell I. Pillar, chief executive of the Virgin Entertainment
Group, the Virgin Group unit that owns a chain of record stores and
will soon open an online music store. ``People buy artists, they
don't buy labels. So you will buy your Cher disk from
Virginmega.com or from Cher.com. You won't buy it from the label
because you don't know who the label is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
