r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-BOATING1STLD-WRIT     04-07 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-BOATING1STLD-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURTURE YOUR OUTBOARD BEFORE TROUT OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, inserts word ``older'' in 8th graf) 
By JEREMY BAGOTT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Meet Bob Brown, who has owned The Anchor, a marine
hardware and small-boat retailer in Reseda, since 1956. The man
knows outboard motors. His employees are convinced his heart beats
in two-stroke cycles and that a carbureted mixture of fuel and oil
flows through his veins.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is considered the Mark McGwire of Merc, the Michael Jordan
of Johnson, the Evander Holyfield of Evinrude.
</P>
<P>
   While he knows outboards, he also knows that maintenance of the
family motor ranks right up there with worming Fido, flushing the
hot-water heater and flossing: It's mostly put off until signs of
trouble arise.
</P>
<P>
   And as the days, hours and seconds tick down to Crowley Lake's 5
a.m. flare that kicks off the Eastern Sierra trout opener April 24,
Brown implores anglers to be good to that motor. Because for some
boaters who back their trailers down the ramps at roadside venues
like Crowley, Convict and June lakes, the day will be more bane
than blessing.
</P>
<P>
   The good news? There's more than two weeks left to inspect your
boat and trailer, lay in the right supplies and get the outboard
back in commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Californians don't decommission their boats at the end of the
season. That's more a `back East' thing,'' said Brown. ``It's
because there's no real offseason here.''
</P>
<P>
   But storing an engine properly over periods of inactivity, he
assures, is !ital!not!off! the exclusive domain of Upstate New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Had you done things right, you might have carefully drained the
fuel from your older outboard's tank. And mounted the engine in a
trash can filled with water, then let it run in neutral until it
died of fuel starvation and the float bowl emptied.
</P>
<P>
   You took an aerosol can of fogging oil _ available at any marine
store _ and sprayed the carburetor throat and pulled the starter
cord a few times. And you removed the plugs and sent a spritz of
oil into each cylinder and pulled the starter cord a few more times
to distribute it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you drained and refilled the lower-unit gear lubricant.
</P>
<P>
   You !ital!did!off! do all of that, right?
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is no, and your older two-stroke has been sitting
for three months or your four-popper for more than eight months,
there could be trouble afoot.
</P>
<P>
   More on that later, but listen to those who have made boating on
the first day of trout season a tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing buddies Ron Herschberger of Mar Vista and Mas Nobunaga
of West Los Angeles have done the opener for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Nobunaga, who takes his 21-foot Boston Whaler up Highway 395
every year, is big on safety, while Herschberger, whose most recent
boat was a wood-and-glass outboard with a Johnson 35, is the
Johnny-on-the-spot parts guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice,'' said Herschberger, ``is to take extra shear pins
for the prop (shear pins hold the propeller in place and are
designed to shear off in the event it hits an obstruction) and
extra spark plugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the people up there have fouled plugs because their
carburetors aren't adjusted for high altitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobunaga focuses on issues of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``June Lake can be dangerous if it's windy,'' he said. ``It can
be just as bad as the ocean. Stay close to shore in boats with
smaller motors. Also have life jackets, a fire extinguisher and at
least one oar, preferably two,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now back to the specifics on what happens if you didn't properly
prep your engine for storage, and how to rectify problems that may
have developed.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel in your carburetor float bowl may have gone bad and the
carb jets could be gunked up. If you suspect this has happened,
it's best to have it checked out, said Brown, who also recommends
spending the money to replace the in-line fuel filter and
water-fuel separator.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Brown's short lecture on plugs if they haven't been
replaced in a year: Get new ones.
</P>
<P>
   If the old plugs come out oil-fouled, pitted, carbon-fouled or
otherwise look like a caddis fly hatch occurred on the electrodes,
consult a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Brown recommends attending to the grease fittings and
aggressively cleaning the motor.
</P>
<P>
   Refer to the owner's manual for the lube points and how often
they should be tended to, as well as for recommendations on
changing the lower-unit oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these engines are 20 and 30 years old, and the
lower-unit oil is critical,'' Brown said. ``Make sure the lubricant
is clean when you take it out. If it's not, you have to find out if
water is getting in and where it's coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   On the outboard's water pump, Brown is a stickler: ``Replace it
every year for saltwater use, every two years for freshwater.''
Most engine manufacturers agree.
</P>
<P>
   After the engine has been checked and you've pulled your boat to
the Eastern Sierra, keep in mind that some of the lakes have speed
limits. All the lakes along the June Lake Loop have a 10-mph speed
limit, except Grant Lake. Upper Twin Lake out of Bridgeport has no
speed limit, while at neighboring Lower Twin it's 5 mph. Check with
the marina at the lake in question. Most have ramp fees. As far as
boat-size restrictions, ``If you can get it into the lake,'' said
Ken Blaisdell of June Lake's Big Rock Landing, ``you can run it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
