<HEADER>
A9900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES08-CO     04-07 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schuerholz holds course on bullpen
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite Mark Wohlers' first-outing shakiness and Mike
Remlinger's pulled back muscle, which has him on the 15-day
disabled list, Braves general manager John Schuerholz hasn't pushed
any panic buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're OK,'' Schuerholz said when asked if he was
looking around for any bullpen help. ``If Remlinger had a serious
injury, then I would give you another answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger is expected to heal relatively quickly from a pulled
back muscle. As for Wohlers, Schuerholz wasn't ready to close the
book on him after watching his four walks and two runs allowed in
the ninth inning of the Braves' opening day loss to the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first outing at Turner Field had to take place sooner or
later I'm sure he was a little anxious and uptight,'' Schuerholz
said. ``It's out of the way now. Let's see how he does the next
times out. I think he'll be fine. He threw the ball hard. He threw
the ball with some quality, he just didn't have his command. I'm of
the opinion that he can get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Schuerholz's optimism otherwise comes from the way John
Rocker and Kevin McGlinchy are going about their business. They
both recorded outs against the single hitters they faced in
Monday's loss to the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker pitched the entire spring without giving up a run. The
only number that could have caused concern was his 10 walks in 12
innings pitched, but Rocker thinks he's found the root of that
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to do too much too soon,'' Rocker said. ``I was
really wanting my velocity to be there and I was overthrowing at
times. I was trying to do in my fourth inning what I throw after
five months, trying to spot a 95 mile-an-hour fastball. But the
last three outings I've felt real strong, real comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer throws
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Russ Springer threw off the bullpen mound for 15
minutes Wednesday and all went well, he said afterward. It was 12
weeks to the day since he had had surgery for a herniated disc in
his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was as close to 100 percent as I can remember,'' Springer
said. ``Felt good. . . . I didn't hold anything back.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer plans to throw again on Friday and Sunday and, if all
goes well, leave for a rehabilitation assignment as the Braves
leave for their first road trip. The Braves should finalize those
plans in the next day or so
</P>
<P>
   Boone's luck
</P>
<P>
   It took a head-first slide into first base for an infield hit to
end Bret Boone's 0-for-7 start as a Brave. He grounded out three
times and either lined or flied out the other four. Otherwise, he
was drawing walks _ he took three of them on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it happens,'' Boone said with a shrug Wednesday
afternoon. ``I feel good though. Best I've felt to open a season,
maybe ever, as far as seeing the ball. I feel good. No hits. It's
weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon's start
</P>
<P>
   In his first pinch hit appearance of the season, rookie Randall
Simon came through with a base hit on Tuesday night on a line drive
to left field. It got lost in the hit barrage of the Braves' 11-3
win but it was significant for Simon, who made this team for his
left-handed bat off the bench. Also of note was that it came on an
3-1 pitch for the young hitter not known for having much patience
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spring I've been doing a lot of coming off the bench,''
Simon said. ``I feel like I'm getting used to it. . . . I just go
to the plate and don't try to change anything, keep swinging like
always.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
