<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILLIES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz in command as Phillies are shut down
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After getting blasted for 17 hits by the Braves on
Tuesday night, the Phillies came back to Turner Field on Wednesday
for a pounding of a different sort. This from the right arm of John
Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' No. 3 starter extended the Phillies' misery for
another day by surrendering four singles in the first three innings
and nothing for the next four, commanding Atlanta to a 4-0 win.
Lucky for Philadelphia, Smoltz had to take a seat after the seventh
because of early-season pitch-count restriction.
</P>
<P>
   After dropping the season opener on Monday, the Braves have won
two in a row and 20 of the last 27 games against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-6 Phillies right-hander Carlton Loewer foiled the
Braves for much of the game, but he was no match for Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz teased the Phillies early on, giving up only a pair of
infield hits, a flare to right and one hard-hit liner up the middle
by Desi Relaford in the first three innings. But after Scott
Rolen's soft single to right in the third inning, Smoltz recorded
13 consecutive outs. He struck out eight in his seven innings of
work, throwing 63 of his 93 pitches for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz also managed to give Greg Maddux a little run for his
money, trying to follow up Maddux's Tuesday night home run with one
of his own. Smoltz gave a ball a nice ride off his bat in the fifth
inning, but to the deepest part of the ballpark for an out in
center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who hit Loewer hard both times they saw him last
year, combining for 12 earned runs in 6 2/3 innings pitched, got
only two runs off him in the first six innings on Wednesday night
before adding a pair in the seventh. And with Smoltz pitching as
effectively as he did this spring (2.63 ERA), not to mention last
season (17-3, 2.90 ERA), that was more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone started the rally with his first hits of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming the frustration of an 0-for-7 start, Boone came
through with a pair of hits in his first two at-bats on an infield
hit in the first inning and a solid liner to left in the fourth
inning. He was rewarded for the second one with a gift from Marlon
Anderson. The Phillies second baseman let a Chipper Jones grounder
roll right under his glove, so Boone, who had stolen second, scored
instead of stopping at third for a 1-0 Braves lead in the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   A batter later, Jordan reached on a fielder's choice. He scored
from first on a Javy Lopez double to left field, blowing right past
and Ned Yost stop sign and safely into home for a 2-0 Braves lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
