<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HANK-HAMMER08-COX     04-07 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HANK-HAMMER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aaron's return to glory
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everyone knew Ben Selig's Ford dealership in Milwaukee
in the mid-1950s, and no one knew the place better than the Braves.
Many of them drove Selig loaner cars that were proudly provided for
the mighty heroes in a baseball-mad town.
</P>
<P>
   That provided Allan Selig, Ben's son, his first entree into the
Braves' clubhouse and, more specifically, began his relationship
with Hank Aaron. In 1954, two months after his 20th birthday, Aaron
earned the left fielder's job after starter Bobby Thomson broke a
leg. Selig, called Bud by everyone and just three months away from
his 20th birthday, spent plenty of time around that team
trouble-shooting car matters for his father.
</P>
<P>
   Selig was in the stands for Aaron's debut that Opening Day, and
Aaron quickly befriended him, beginning a close relationship that
exists to this day. Neither could have expected that both would
become giants of the game. Or that both could be so stigmatized by
their ascents to power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bud sympathized with me and knew what I had gone
through,'' Aaron said. ``I have to give credit to him. He helped
tone me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight at Turner Field, Selig, now commissioner of baseball,
will unveil the Hank Aaron Award, which will honor the best hitter
in each league each year. The goals are varied: Selig, striving to
revitalize fan interest in a game still marked by the players
strike of 1994-95, hopes the award stimulates new public awareness;
it also salutes Aaron for breaking Babe Ruth's career home run
record 25 years ago tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But down deep, it is the commissioner's extended hand to Aaron,
an attempt to welcome the home run king back to the game he became
estranged from during the intervening decades. The Aaron Award is,
at its root, about a relationship between a poor Alabama black kid
and a Jewish Wisconsin car dealer and about a friendship nearly a
half-century old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anguished about Hank and worried about him,'' Selig said.
``I do think Hank was greatly unappreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the country's infatuation with the Mark McGwire-Sammy
Sosa home run chase last summer to contrast what Aaron went through
in 1974. The racial hate mail was ugly enough. But breaking a
record held by Ruth, a god even 26 years after his death, depressed
a large segment of baseball's following. Aaron suggests that Mickey
Mantle would have been the people's choice to hit No. 715.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only real disappointment,'' Aaron said. ``I just
wish I could have enjoyed it as much as Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
enjoyed the home run race last season. ... I can enjoy it now.
Twenty-five years ago, I was a bitter person.''
</P>
<P>
   That bitterness was readily apparent to fans. After his
retirement, Aaron rarely appeared at the ballpark. Although he
spent 13 seasons as the Braves vice president for player
development, after stepping down in 1989, he all but vanished from
the baseball landscape. Aaron's admission that he occasionally
re-read some of the hate letters he kept in a box in his attic was,
for many people, a sad, troubling image.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron long maintained that baseball never truly recognized his
achievement, and to watch how Major League Baseball promoted the
McGwire-Sosa saga, his point is well taken. As he took on political
causes, Aaron became more insistent that baseball improve its poor
record of minority hiring. The more outspoken he became, the more
he distanced himself from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he wrote and spoke and campaigned to meet this
responsibility, a curious thing happened,'' Lonnie Wheeler, author
of ``I Had A Hammer,'' wrote in Aaron's new release, ``Home Run.''
``Critics began complaining that Henry Aaron _ the man who had
nothing to say _ had more to say than they wanted to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Several developments have influenced Aaron's life since then.
For one, baseball's minority-hiring practices have improved, for
which he can take some credit. The passing of time might have
softened some of his edges, too. But the Hank Aaron Chasing The
Dream Foundation, an offshoot of Aaron's Youth Leadership
Foundation, has become his proudest achievement. The foundation
benefits underprivileged youths ages 9-12.
</P>
<P>
   But the game also seems to be seeking Aaron out. MLB helped
stage his gala 65th birthday party on Feb. 5, complete with
President Bill Clinton on the dais. If the McGwire-Sosa epic served
to return the spotlight to Aaron, it found a happier man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tribute Feb. 5 speaks for itself,'' said Bill
Bartholomay, the Braves chairman of the board. ``I think what's
happening is, there is a little bit more of the history out there
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think baseball is different,'' Bartholomay said. ``Five
years after the labor stoppage, I think we're recognizing our
history a little bit better. People are doing things with their
baseball afterlife, and the kids are picking up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig has made Aaron a personal initiative. He has done
extensive fund-raising work with the Milwaukee chapter of the
Chasing The Dream Foundation. The birthday bash, a virtual
coming-out party, bore the commissioner's fingerprints. He helped
deliver the host of baseball stars that attended.
</P>
<P>
   It all is in a stark contrast to previous baseball leadership.
Then-commissioner Bowie Kuhn was conspicuously absent the night
Aaron hit No. 715. He had made a commitment to address a Cleveland
Indians fans banquet that night, which sounds as hollow now as it
did then.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (Aaron) went through back then was so heart-breaking,''
Selig said. ``I'm so happy that, while he's alive and healthy, he
can enjoy the fruits and benefits of his great career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aaron Award is a significant salute, for baseball has not
minted a new award since 1967. Aaron, making appearances around
major-league parks all season to help celebrate the 25th
anniversary of the home run record, also promotes the award by his
presence.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing out the first pitch in Seattle on Monday night,
he hugged Ken Griffey Jr., the current player Aaron believes to
have the best shot at 755, and the moment suggested nothing of an
aging star once angry with the world. Griffey, who turns 30 on Nov.
11, stands at 351 homers after just over 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Where previous MLB administrations saw nothing, Selig sees a way
to lock two baseball generations and help Aaron's legacy
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting things done in a little more rational
manner now,'' Batholomay said. ``Let's put it that way. The
important thing is, it's being done.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron admits to being ``a little more proud'' of his record now
than he once was. If he wasn't quite the hero Mantle or Mays or
even Ruth was, as some critics charged when he hit No. 715, he will
walk the field tonight with his star re-cast. Hank Aaron comes home
and his old friend Bud Selig will be there too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the greatest ride,'' Aaron said. ``I can say to
the fans, especially in the last 10 years, things have been just
wonderful for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
