<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teams' mantra on offensive line: Bigger is better
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not until he arrived at Indianapolis for the NFL
scouting combine two months ago did San Jose State guard David
Loverne ever think of himself as anything but a big man on campus.
But as Loverne checked the other offensive linemen shoehorned into
a shuttle bus, he realized that he was the only one occupying just
one seat.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the 6-foot-3, 292-pound Loverne said, he felt
more like a graduate of Lilliput State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys were absolute monsters,'' said Loverne, one of just
six offensive-line prospects under 300 pounds at the combine.
``They were some of the largest human beings I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The pool of offensive linemen in this year's draft is both
gargantuan and good. In the eyes of scouts, bigger is better, and
this year, a prospect had better be bigger to gain attention.
</P>
<P>
   Retired New York Giants general manager George Young and Jets
coach Bill Parcells share what they call ``The Planet Theory'' _
there are a finite number of 300-pounders on Earth, and woe to the
team that ignores them in the draft. In the 1999 draft, however, it
might be difficult for a team to complete the proceedings without
landing at least one 300-pound blocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely are enough of them to go around,''
Philadelphia Eagles offensive line coach Keith Rowen said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ The average weight of the 54 offensive linemen at the combine
was 317.5 pounds. The lightest of the prospects was 290 pounds and
there were 14 players 325 pounds or more and five 340 pounds or
more.
</P>
<P>
   _ The group had an average height of 6 feet 4 1/2, and just one
player was under 6-2. There were 13 players 6-6 or taller.
</P>
<P>
   _ UCLA tackle Kris Farris actually looked skinny at 6-7 7/8 and
313 pounds. Several scouts told John Tait of Brigham Young (6-6
1/8, 310), the consensus No. 1 prospect at tackle, that he should
add some upper-body bulk. Even though Aaron Gibson of Wisconsin was
a whopping 386 pounds, no one suggested he head for a sauna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size matters,'' St. Louis offensive line coach Jim Hanifan
said. ``But it doesn't mean a thing if you can't play. These guys
are big and they can play. The quantity is there this year. It's
probably the deepest position in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams have selected 45 offensive linemen in the opening
round during the 1990s, second only to defensive linemen, 56. Not
since 1994 have fewer than five blockers gone off the board in
Round 1. Five or six probably will go in the opening round this
year,and even more in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
