<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-DUVAL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval comes to Augusta on verge of greatness
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Staring into a TV camera at the TPC at Sugarloaf
on Sunday night after an 11th win in 34 attempts, David Duval
seemed as perplexed as everyone else. Fess up, Double D. How does a
guy go from ``can't win'' to ``can't lose'' in 18 months?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on,'' said Duval, Oakleys stowed on
his cap brim. ``I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the 63rd Masters, his colleagues were asking Duval
questions like, ``When are you going to take some more time off?''
and, ``What's your schedule for the rest of the year?''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, David, if you're skipping the Texas swing, point
me to the DFW Airport. Around putting greens and practice ranges
lately, they spare no hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably having a better run than anybody I've seen on
Tour,'' Lee Janzen said. ``Not since Watson in the early '80s.
Maybe the mid-70s. It's just incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read all those quotes last week about him coming to Atlanta
to warm up,'' Brad Faxon said. ``Now he's winning his warm-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Calcavecchia said, ``I hate to compare him to Nicklaus, but
I really think he has the greatest mind since Nicklaus.''
</P>
<P>
   People who watch Duval on television and declare him robotic
should have been in the interview room Tuesday at Augusta National.
People remembering him from less mature days at Georgia Tech, once
holding the 54-hole lead of the BellSouth Classic, should have been
there, too. The new David Duval _ golf's No. 1 player on the
greatest run in two decades _ is joking and laughing as he lugs all
the loot to his Jacksonville Beach branch. He is confident, yet
modest. He will deflect any comparisons with Nicklaus or Palmer or
Miller. Nope, he hasn't done enough yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won 11 out of probably 120,'' Duval said, drawing
reference to those now-ancient times, when he went winless for 92
events before October 1997. ``I might be in the process of being a
star or whatever, but not like Tiger (Woods),'' the 27-year-old
Duval said. ``Tiger is a star. Tiger is outside the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That could change today, as Duval, clearly installed as the
favorite, stalks his third tournament win in a row and a green
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's beating us every week, which is a negative for us,''
Janzen said, ``but the positive part is that he is showing us that
the sky's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Atlanta win, Duval hit only the range and the
short-game area Tuesday. He played 18 holes Wednesday morning and
then the par-3 tournament. The serious research came three weeks
ago during two rounds at Augusta National. On his first attempt at
the four altered holes and new rough, he shot a 5-under-par 67. The
second day he bogeyed the first five holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped keeping score,'' Duval said, laughing. ``I beat one
of the assistant (pros) and got beat by two of the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready to get started today, Duval also wants to build on last
year's Masters. Draining and disappointing as it was to finish a
stroke behind Mark O'Meara, Duval emerged without a need for
psychotherapy. The guy who won birdied three of the last four
holes; a bogey on 16 and two pars doesn't quite qualify as a
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would I do differently? Seriously?'' Duval said. ``Have
him not make a 20-footer and I get in a playoff? Am I satisfied I
did everything I could? Absolutely. ... What it does is tell me
that I can win that golf tournament. I mean, there is no question
in my mind that I can win that golf tournament. Doesn't mean I'm
going to, but I have the ability to.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody seems to agree. Paul Stankowski suggested last week
that Duval ``is our only shot for a Grand Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval has done everything but win a major. He has shot a Sunday
59 to win. He has won four times in eight 1999 events. He has won
enough money to purchase the TV rights to the Masters, if not the
title itself. Interestingly, if Duval could have one shot to reload
last year, it would not be the ball at the 16th that remained on
the right slope, almost guaranteeing the final-round three-putt.
Worse was the birdie that got away at the par-3 fourth on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just brutal,'' he said. ``Front pin, right over the bunker. I
had it 3 feet straight up the hill, and I didn't even hit the
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   From a technical standpoint, he has improved his chipping and
putting greatly, combining them with a murderous long game. He is
leading the PGA Tour in seven categories _ money, scoring, birdies,
greens in regulation, putting, total driving and all-around. Beyond
that, Duval has learned not to force a shot when in contention or
fret over a bad one. When asked Tuesday why he is such a
``dullard,'' Duval laughed it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other players might get fired up by getting upset,'' he said.
``That doesn't do me right. It doesn't serve me well. ... I can't
rehit a shot. I can only move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   When the final numbers are totaled, one-putts will mean more
than one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a fan before I got on tour, and Tom Watson was my
favorite player,'' Janzen said. ``Watching him on TV, I thought he
was very quiet. Now that I know him, I don't think he's quiet at
all. ... I guess when David decides, everybody will get to know
him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
