</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LICKLITER08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lickliter's hard, long work results in him `living an absolute
dream'
 &HT;    By Ron Jackson and Lawrence Budd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Franklin native Frank Lickliter Jr. tees off this
morning in his first Masters tournament nine years after a guard
refused to let him and his Wright State University golf teammates
onto the historic Augusta National golf course.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Raiders tried to visit the Masters course in
Georgia between rounds at a nearby college tournament. Augusta's
fabled fairways, lined with flowering azaleas, dogwoods and
magnolias, are an exclusive sight few golfers get to enjoy. All
Masters players have to be invited and tickets _ even to practice
rounds _ are just as hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guard house was the closest we got. They didn't buy our
line that we wanted buy some things at pro shop,'' recalled coach
Fred Jefferson. ``The guard said, `We'll bring it out.' Frank and
the rest of the golfers were disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lickliter, 29, matching strokes with the world's greatest
golfers at the first major tournament of the year represents the
latest _ and greatest _ proof that his years of practice are paying
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another step,'' said his dad, Frank Lickliter Sr.
``Actually he's treating the Masters like it's another tournament.
He thinks he belongs out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter began the journey to Augusta in earnest at 13, when he
resolved to become a professional golfer. During high school, he
spent endless hours driving golf balls into a makeshift driving
range his father built in the basement of their Main Street home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a lot of sacrifices. He didn't worry about the prom,
or homecoming or any dances. He didn't have a lot of dates in high
school. He was focused on golf. That was his passion,'' said his
mother, Maryann.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Frankie'' walks to the first tee at Augusta and hears the
roar of the crowd today, his parents will be there behind the
yellow ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always a special thrill when they introduce him on the
first tee and announce he's from Franklin, Ohio. We're very proud
of that,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than risk disturbing his son's concentration, the elder
Lickliters will weave through the gallery at Augusta National,
picking unobtrusive vantage points, usually half a hole ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to have anything to do with him during the
tournament. It's not good for him. Rarely do we speak during the
tournament,'' his dad said.
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter's father, a retired computer repairman at AK Steel,
could hardly afford a country-club membership. Father and son would
walk to nearby Anthony Wayne Elementary School for practice
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I taught him anything, it was the value of practice and the
need to work on his game everyday. I taught him the work ethic,''
his father said.
</P>
<P>
   After Lickliter resolved to become a pro, his father bought him
a membership at the Shaker Run Golf Club in Turtlecreek Twp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I would subsidize his golf if he played every
day,'' Lickliter said. ``He didn't have to worry about a summer
job. I still remember going to pick him up at Shaker and seeing a
solitary figure in the twilight on the driving range. It was always
Frankie working on his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter still holds the Shaker Run course record, which he set
in 1994, needing only 65 strokes for 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman at Franklin High School, he earned the No. 1 spot
on the golf team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked harder than any athlete I coached in any other
sport. He was just relentless, even as freshman. He had a musty
basement and he and his father built a small driving range down
there where he would hit golf balls into the net year round,'' said
coach Kevin Hollon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other coaches and players were in awe of his hand and wrist
movement, even at that young age. What was surprising, he didn't
have the country-club upbringing,'' Hollon said.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior, Lickliter placed fourth in the state and led the
team to a sixth-place finish. In his senior year, he claimed the
district and regional individual titles and led the Wildcats to a
seventh-place state finish. He also placed seventh individually in
the state tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Williams grew up with the Lickliter children.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled a statement a teen-age Lickliter scrawled on a
bedroom mirror in permanent ink: ``I can sink any putt.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wright State, Lickliter won seven Division I tournaments. He
was the first Wright State golfer to appear in the NCAA Division I
tournament (1989) and helped the Raiders become the university's
first team to participate in an NCAA Division I tournament (1990).
In 1996 he was inducted into the Wright State University Athletic
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked harder than any golfer we've had here. He was always
seeking out tougher competition and always learning. Some of the
drills I use for my golfers now I learned from Frank,'' the coach
said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 to 1995, Lickliter played the Nike Tour, the minor
league of pro golf. Occasionally he would turn to his parents for
help in making ends meet between paydays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankie had some hard times, living on a shoestring budget,''
his father said. ``There were times Maryann and I scraped up $1,000
for him to go to Florida and play. He'd call and say, `I'm down to
$200 and I would tell him to come home. It took him a little bit
longer than everybody else to reach the tour,'' said his father.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Lickliter won the Boise Open, a breakthrough victory
with a $45,000 purse, then graduated from the PGA's qualifying
school. In 1996, he joined the PGA Tour and last year he finished
45th on the money list.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lickliter lives in an exclusive Gulf Coast golf community
in Florida, north of St. Petersburg, and enjoys a life of luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is living an absolute dream,'' his father said. ``He's
living in a half-million dollar house in Sawgrass and drives a
$100,000 Hummer.''
</P>
<P>
   He is engaged to his secretary, Diane Owen.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Lickliter finished second, winning $302,400, at
1999 AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   ``He signed over 500 autographs during that tournament,'' his
mother said with a proud smile. Family friend Norma Kennard said
she's hardly a golf fan, but plans to watch the Masters on TV
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud of him. He's spoken well for our small town,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
