<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family feel pervades par-3 tournament
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Golf's most famous caddie has a new bag, but he didn't
carry it Wednesday. Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, the mustachioed former
worker bee fired by Tiger Woods and hired by Jim Furyk, took the
afternoon off. In his place was the pro's freckled 15-year-old
cousin, Dave Furyk of South Park, Pa., shouldering the five clubs
needed in the Masters par-3 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a great experience, just being with my cousin _
and getting to putt on No. 9,'' said Dave, who got to roll a
10-footer. Not many people can say they did that at Augusta
National.
</P>
<P>
   The casual competition afforded players the chance to allow
their families and friends a walk inside the ropes. Stewart Cink's
father, Rob, from Alabama, tended the flag for him. Stefan Langer
caddied for dad Bernhard. Corey Pavin and Fred Funk walked up the
fairway with their little boys. Mark Calcavecchia's 9-year-old
daughter, Britney Jo, donned a small white jumpsuit, her blond hair
in a ponytail _ just like some of the regular caddies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a little bit of Fluff rubbed off on the whippersnappers.
Six-year-old Andrew Perry, who toted four clubs for his dad, Chris,
knew just how to spin his newfound fame. ``Do you want my
autograph?'' he piped up.
</P>
<P>
   Durant par-3 champ
</P>
<P>
   If the Masters jinx holds, Joe Durant will not win Sunday. He
won the par-3 tournament with a 5-under 22, and no player who has
won it has gone on to take the Masters. Gary Player, Scott Verplank
and Mark Brooks finished a stroke behind. Georgia Tech star Matt
Kuchar recovered enough from a stomach bug to ace the 55-yard
second hole. Fuzzy Zoeller holed out his tee shot on the ninth
hole. Tournament favorite David Duval, on the other hand, made sure
he was nowhere near the lead. He turned in a 14-over 41.
</P>
<P>
   Slower play expected
</P>
<P>
   Expect Thursday's threesomes to take as long as an hour longer
to complete the round than the traditional twosomes. The ``time
par'' for a threesome is 4 hours, 45 minutes, Masters competition
chairman Will F. Nicholson Jr. said. ``I don't think it's going to
be a five-hour round,'' Nicholson predicted. The move to threesomes
was made to accommodate the large 96-player field. Those groupings
remain the same Friday, with start times in reverse order, because
some pros requested a chance to play in the morning at least one
day so they could avoid spike marks on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Tee times of note
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sarazen, 97, Byron Nelson, 87, and Sam Snead, 86, tee off
at 8 a.m. today as honorary starters. Here's when the golfers with
Georgia ties go off: Davis Love III of Sea Island, 9:32 a.m.; Matt
Kuchar of Georgia Tech, 10:16 a.m.; Larry Mize of Columbus, 10:49
a.m.; Tommy Aaron of Gainesville, 11 a.m.; Billy Andrade of
Atlanta, 1:01 p.m.; and Stewart Cink of Smyrna, 1:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Streaks alive
</P>
<P>
   Doug Ford adds to his record of most starts at the Masters _ 47
this week, while Arnold Palmer is only one behind. Billy Casper and
Gary Player will be playing their 42nd. All past winners attended
the Champions Dinner on Tuesday night, with no adverse reactions to
the sushi and sashimi appetizers ordered by defending champ Mark
O'Meara _ not even Sam Snead, who is more comfortable fishing with
bait, not eating it.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to this report: Tim Ellerbee
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
