A9907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN08-CO     04-07 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lickliter a long way from Franklin, Ohio
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ For golfers, this is the place you must be in
early-mid April to justify your existence. This is where
immortality awaits, here at Augusta National Golf Club, here among
the pines and the flowers and the ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   And thus did Frank Lickliter, having missed the cut last week at
the BellSouth Classic, drive down Magnolia Lane on Saturday in his
Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Might be the first Hummer that's ever been on the grounds,''
said Steve Jones.
</P>
<P>
   And how did that drive feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Another good day,'' Frank Lickliter said, ``in a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   A very good year. Three months into the season, the kid who grew
up in Franklin is 21st on the PGA Tour money list at $506,806.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching the Masters with my dad when I was a
kid,'' Lickliter said. ``It was even before I played golf. I
remember Fuzzy winning it. And Ballesteros.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be 1979 and 1980 when Lickliter was 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   He started playing when he was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was Wednesday, a day before the 63rd Masters, and
Lickliter, 29, was standing in the Augusta National locker room,
hunched over his new putter with the sterling silver face that
famous craftsman Scotty Cameron spent a month making.
</P>
<P>
   Baby, won't you look at me now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' he said to Rocco Mediate, ``it's got my initials on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there they were, on the putter head: ``F.L.''
</P>
<P>
   So I said, here's this kid from little Franklin, who grew up to
become Cinderella at the Masters, and he went into the Bill Murray
monologue from ``Caddyshack,'' complete with the faux-Scottish
accent.
</P>
<P>
   Lickliter qualified for his first Masters by finishing fourth at
last year's PGA. Mark O'Meara saw him in the locker room and said,
``Congratulations on making the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought about it until then,'' Lickliter said. ``And
even after he said it, it didn't really sink in.''
</P>
<P>
   It sank in Saturday when he drove in off Washington Road and
down through the Magnolias and those huge above-ground roots that
stretch forever, just like the roots of this game.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed? Apparently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've driven in since then,'' Lickliter said, ``I've
come through Magnolia Lane. I haven't taken the back way to the
players' parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows Masters tradition, and as he has tapped into it during
his practice rounds.
</P>
<P>
   On No. 9, he studied where Greg Norman's ball hit next to the
cup in 1996, then spun 90 feet back off the green. ``Three feet
from being perfect,'' Lickliter said. ``A little greed out here can
be a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10, he recalled the 60-foot sidewinding putt Ben Crenshaw
made in 1984 en route to victory. ``I looked at that line,''
Lickliter said, ``and I just thought, `Unbelievable.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the 12th, in the middle of Amen Corner, he paused on the bank
in front of the green where Fred Couples' ball fell short, but
somehow stayed out of Rae's Creek in 1992 on his way to the
championship. ``I dropped a couple of balls right in that spot and
every one rolled into the creek,'' Lickliter said. ``I'll tell you
what: Freddie got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   On 16, he walked in Jack Nicklaus' bear tracks from the
45-footer uphill that won it in 1975. ``I've seen that putt on Golf
Channel,'' Lickliter said. ``I love those old tournaments on Golf
Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years out of Wright State; Hummer in the parking lot;
Cinderella at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream,'' Frank Lickliter said, 25 hours from his
12:50 p.m. Thursday tee time. ``I'm lucky enough to be living a
dream.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
