<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EISENHOWER TREE RE-EMERGES AS FACTOR IN THE MASTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also GLF-MASTERS) 
(rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA , Ga. _ Of the thousands of trees that decorate the
Masters at Augusta National, it's the only one with a name: the
Eisenhower Tree, or Ike's Tree.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big, wide loblolly pine with sprawling boughs that, from
the 17th tee, blocks the left side of the fairway the way Shaquille
O'Neal blocks the lane. And when Dwight D. Eisenhower was president
of the United States and an Augusta National member, his tee shot
there invariably plunked into that tree.
</P>
<P>
   At a 1956 board meeting, the president even stood up and
demanded that the tree be chopped down. Hearing that, Clifford
Roberts, then the club's crusty chairman, quickly adjourned the
meeting. ``To protect the club's property,'' Roberts explained.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the power of the presidency at Augusta National, but
the president's name was instantly attached to that tree. And now,
with the tee moved back 25 yards this year on what is now the
425-yard 17th hole, the Eisenhower Tree is suddenly as intimidating
to the Masters golfers as it was to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before,'' Tiger Woods was saying on Tuesday, ``I never thought
about that tree.'
</P>
<P>
   Precisely the point. Until this year, Woods, John Daly, David
Duval and golf's other long hitters would bomb their tee shots
above and beyond the Eisenhower Tree as if it weren't even there.
</P>
<P>
   Now the long hitters must think about making sure their tee
shots soar above it. And the shorter hitters must make sure to keep
their tee shots out where the fairway curls around it. ``I probably
can't hit it over the Eisenhower Tree now,'' said Mark O'Meara, who
birdied the 17th and 18th holes to win last year. ``I probably have
to work around it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Masters' most significant hole alterations in one year,
the golfers now must stop and think and maybe think again on No. 2,
No. 11, No. 15 and No. 17 instead of just swinging away.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time, Augusta National has grown some rough to
make the golfers think even more.
</P>
<P>
   Cut at a neat one and three-eighths inches, it's hardly the four
to five inches of thick, tangled rough at a United States Open, but
it's enough to both hurt and help _ to make the golfers stop and
think, especially on their shots out of the rough to the green, and
to keep a wandering tee shot from bounding too far into the
slippery pine straw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball's not going to go as far,'' Fred Couples said, ``but
it'll be tough judging your second shots.''
</P>
<P>
   With a new tee adding 25 yards, No. 2 is now 575 yards, but only
Woods, Daly, Duval and the other long hitters are likely to risk
drawing their tee shots beyond the gaping bunker 325 yards away at
the right corner of the par-5 dogleg left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can hit a perfect drive down the hill on the left
side, more power to them,'' said Tom Fazio, the Masters' consulting
architect. ``If not, they're either in trouble or it's now a much
longer second shot.''
</P>
<P>
   At No. 11, still a 455-yard downhill par-4, the green has been
raised 2 feet to avert a repeat of the flood that washed out the
green in 1990 when Rae's Creek overflowed. The green was also
extended to create a treacherous back-left pin position.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 15, the par-5 of 485 yards where Gene Sarazen's
double-eagle two in 1935 soared over the pond in front of the
green, 20 loblolly pines averaging 35 feet in height were installed
to the right of the fairway, out where most tee shots land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mounds on the right side of that fairway are gone,'' Fazio
said. ``The big hitters used to slingshot their tee shots off those
mounds. And if they're in or behind those trees on the right, they
probably won't have a shot to the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Those trees should be a new factor, especially Sunday when the
Masters boils down to the closing holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was not only to make 15 play a little longer,'' Fazio
said, ``but also to narrow the width of the ideal landing area, at
least in the minds of the golfers.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the leaders get to the 17th tee on Sunday, they will be
staring at the Eisenhower Tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 17th hole has needed something,'' said Jack Nicklaus, the
six-time Masters winner who will not be playing this week while he
recuperates from hip surgery. ``The 17th has been playing too short
and too easy for a 17th hole for quite a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, President Eisenhower must be chuckling.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
