A9912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-REFO     04-07 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-REFORM08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Limit on contributions pending in House
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Undaunted by constitutional restrictions and a
skeptical House speaker, supporters of campaign contribution lmits
testified Wednesday that caps are the only way to dissipate a cloud
of corruption hovering over Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point you have to ask: Are these sums of money so
obscene that there's an appearance of corruption in the entire
system?'' said Frank Newton, dean of the Texas Tech School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Newton and a parade of activists from government watchdog groups
urged the House Elections Committee to endorse a bill filed by Rep.
Tom Uher (D-Bay City), which would limit contributions in races for
the Texas House and Senate. The House Committee on Elections left
the bill pending.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe that large contributors have too much influence on
the political process in Texas. Some suggest that even if there
isn't a direct link between contributions and public policy, the
appearance of corruption dampens political participation.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that limiting contributions is akin to
restricting free speech, and that limits would benefit wealthy
candidates willing to pump their own money into a campaign. Efforts
to enact contribution limits in Texas _ one of a handful of states
without them _ have foundered in recent legislative sessions, and
the Uher bill faces long odds.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Pete Laney pointed to campaign finance reform as
one of his top priorities at the beginning of the session, but he
said last month that ``there's probably not enough folks in either
house'' to pass a contribution limit. Instead, Laney said, the
Legislature should concentrate on improving disclosure laws.
</P>
<P>
   Uher's bill also has to pass constitutional muster: The U.S.
Supreme Court has ruled that contribution limits can be
unconstitutional if set too low. The Uher measure debated Wednesday
would put a $1,000 cap per election on individual House
contributions to House candidates or political action committees.
The limit for Senate candidates would be $2,000. Newton and other
supporters said the limits in the Uher bill are in line with caps
in other states that have withstood legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But one member of the committee, Rep. Jerry Madden
(R-Richardson), said he believes that any contribution limits
``break into someone's right to participate in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe that disclosure is the best way,'' Madden
said.
</P>
<P>
   At an early morning news conference, Madden joined
representatives and senators of both parties to endorse bills that
would require electronic filing of campaign finance records, which
would then be posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
