<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0516 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-A'S-NYT &LR;      04-07 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-A'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDOZA STARTS THINGS ROLLING AND IRABU WRAPS IT UP AS YANKEES TOP
A'S
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Ramiro Mendoza will return to the Yankees'
bullpen once Hideki Irabu's probation expires and Andy Pettitte
recovers from his various injuries. The Yankees are undoubtedly a
better team with the versatile and durable Mendoza available in
relief, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But they are pretty good when Mendoza starts, too. He pitched
eight scoreless innings, allowing only five singles and a walk in
the Yankees' 4-0 shutout of the Oakland Athletics Wednesday. And,
Mendoza justified manager Don Zimmer's decision to start him
instead of Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu had a small share of satisfaction, as well, pitching
the final inning and twice moving to cover first base on ground
balls to the right side, with a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' starting pitching is a potential weakness: Pettitte
is on the disabled list; Irabu is effectively imprisoned in the
bullpen because of his recent misdeeds, and the 30-something aces,
Roger Clemens and David Cone, are holding up the staff.
</P>
<P>
   But the starting pitching, which anchored the 125-victory season
in 1998, was spectacular in the first three days here: Clemens,
Orlando Hernandez and Mendoza permitted only 12 hits and six runs
in 212/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   After Irabu pitched the ninth inning, the Yankees gulped down
ribs and beans on plastic plates and headed home. They will play
their home opener Friday against the Detroit Tigers, with David
Cone pitching against Beiker Graterol, a 24-year-old player who has
spent six seasons in the minor leagues and has never seen Yankee
Stadium in person.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza's turn in the rotation does not come up again until
April 13, but Irabu might pitch then, and barring injury, Mendoza
could be back in the bullpen by month's end.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he deserves such a fate. Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager, argued last June that Mendoza did nothing to lose his spot
in the rotation, but Hernandez supplanted him anyway through an
executive order, and the Yankees were a better team as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza has grumbled privately about his fate, but never
outwardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say this: With the game he pitched today, he's liable
to have something to say,'' Zimmer said. ``He hasn't done much of
anything wrong since he's been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter said: ``Mendoza can pitch. He knows he can pitch.
Everybody knows he can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees love to play behind him, because of his
machine-gun style of pitching, firing strikes one after another,
working fast and forcing opposing hitters to swing. Mendoza threw
only 104 pitches in his eight innings, 13 pitches an inning. The
American League average last year was 16 pitches an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in this way, second baseman Chuck Knoblauch said,
``keeps your defense in the game,'' makes them concentrate and
anticipate with each pitch knowing there is a very good chance the
ball will be hit to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you saw some plays being made that were
extraordinary,'' Knoblauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who made three great plays in Tuesday's 7-4 victory,
took a hit away from Ben Grieve in the fifth inning Wednesday.
Jeter ranged far to his left to rob Tony Phillips in the sixth.
Oakland had a runner at first and one out in the fifth, with the
Yankees leading 3-0, when A.J. Hinch slugged a long drive to deep
center.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams got a good jump on the ball, but it still
appeared as if the ball had gone over his head _ until he reached
up with his glove hand, on a dead run, and speared the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza said he was a little tired in the eighth, with his pitch
count nearing 100, and with two outs and a runner at first,
Phillips smashed a high drive toward the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   But Chad Curtis tracked the ball, sprinting, glancing at the
wall he was charging and then at Phillips' liner, back and forth,
until he caught the ball a step in front of the fence, banging into
the wall. The defense, Mendoza suggested later, was the difference
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu started warming up during the eighth inning, and the way
Zimmer figured it, if Irabu could pitch an inning with a
respectable lead, maybe he would have a chance to get his
confidence back and regain some confidence in the eyes of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza got through the eighth with a 4-0 edge, and Irabu was
waved into the game for the bottom of the ninth. He threw hard and
pitched well. It was his first step out of purgatory. And the first
step toward the return of Mendoza to the bullpen, in spite of his
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very good today,'' Irabu said. ``He was great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
