<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL SETS STANDARD AT THE MASTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Augusta National Golf Course has two sides.
There's the one the public sees, and the one you have to get close
to if you are to appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes Augusta National the perfect analogy for the two
golfers most likely to subdue her this week.
</P>
<P>
   The back nine (second nine in Masters-speak) you've surely seen.
Only Tiger Woods' smile is more photogenic. It is Amen Corner and
Gene Sarazen's double eagle 2.
</P>
<P>
   The first nine is inscrutable. It is an elevated tee and tilted
greens and Bruce Devlin's double eagle 2.
</P>
<P>
   When you think of the Masters, you think of Augusta National's
back nine because the tournament committee _ which contours the
television coverage _ deigns it so. Likewise, when you think of
golf superstars you think of Woods because a mighty marketing
machine has dictated that you do.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? The front nine deserves your attention and so does
David Duval, who is playing so well you wouldn't be at all
surprised to see him eschew the Hogan Bridge at the 12th green and
walk across Rae's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Duval has played in eight tournaments in 1999 and prevailed in
four, his .500 winning percentage unsurpassed by either Woods, the
Washington Capitals, the Phoenix Suns, the Cincinnati Reds, Silver
Charm, NATO forces in Kosovo or FOX network programmers.
</P>
<P>
   No one who drives for dough, with the possible exception of Jeff
Gordon, has kept pace with Duval, who has finished first in 11 of
his past 34 starts. He is one of only three players over the past
30 years to win at least three PGA Tournaments in three consecutive
years, joining Jack Nicklaus and Tom Watson, both future Hall of
Famers.
</P>
<P>
   And yet when it comes to owning Madison Avenue, Duval is a few
signatures shy of a deed. When Woods turned professional after his
sophomore year at Stanford he enlisted the services of agent Hughes
Norton who, in turn, removed Duval from his client Rolodex, the
better to concentrate on making Woods rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   He succeeded so well that Woods last year deemed him expendable,
removing Norton from his Rolodex. Woods can _ and does _ turn his
charisma on and off like a television camera, smiling when it suits
him and scowling when it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is different. He learned at a painfully early age that
life itself is the richest reward.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 9, his 12-year-old brother Brent was diagnosed with
a blood disorder. Duval donated bone marrow in an effort to save
his brother's life but Brent's body rejected it and five months
later he died, in May of 1981.
</P>
<P>
   If smiles for the longest time were hard for Duval to
manufacture, can you blame him?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Woods, who wears his emotions like endorsements, Duval
continues to keep his feelings largely under wraps. That doesn't
mean he's unapproachable and it shouldn't make him unmarketable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in his next life Duval will be an air traffic controller.
He certainly was unflappable the other day when he sat down in the
interview room and the first question posed to him was not really a
question at all:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's kind of a perception out there that you're somewhat of
a dullard.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been the end of the interview session for a lot
of athletes. Not Duval. After a long pause, the man who oozes so
little emotion exuded a lot of character.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the perception, that's fine,'' he said evenly.
``That's how I try to play. I try not to make mistakes ... I try to
keep the stress level as minimal as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Woods won his first (and only) major here in startling
fashion. His 12-stroke victory sent his marketing machine into
overdrive and sent Masters officials scurrying to the drawing board
to ``Tiger-proof'' the course.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has four PGA victories since then. Duval has posted that
many victories in the past three months. The way he has been
playing, the only way to Duval-proof any course, including Augusta
National, might be to plant more flowers and pray the pollen rouses
the allergies that prompted Duval to don the wraparound sunglasses
that have become his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be in the process of becoming a golf star or whatever
you want to call it,'' Duval said. ``But I'm not like Tiger in the
sense that Tiger is a star. He (transcends) the game. I don't see
myself that way and I don't think I ever will.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I might seem uncomfortable (with the concept).''
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows you can find, without too much fuss, professional
athletes with far worse failings than that. That Duval is the No. 1
golfer on the planet and feels undeserving of a pedestal may be all
the more reason he belongs there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
