A9924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPREADING-CRIME-BILL0     04-07 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPREADING-CRIME-BILL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anti-gang bills approved in Texas
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Six bills designed to curb Texas' growing crime
wave from prison and street gangs were approved Wednesday, even as
a legislative fight surfaced over a key element of the crackdown _
the creation of a statewide computer network to track gang members.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-hour hearing at the Capitol, a standing-room-only
crowd of law enforcement officials from across Texas argued against
giving locally elected officials such as city councils a say in
whether to participate in the network.
</P>
<P>
   And the Senate Criminal Justice Committee obliged, deleting a
provision that would have allowed for local public hearings on the
issue. But state Sen. Royce West, author of the anti-gang bills,
said he intends to raise the issue again when the bills are debated
by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important issue _ what kind of information
would be kept, whether it should be kept at all _ and I think that
should be the subject of lively and spirited debate on the local
level,'' said West (D-Dallas). ``I think this database is a key
part of dealing with these gangs. But there are issues of privacy
and of checks and balances that we must also address.''
</P>
<P>
   Under West's original bill, city councils and county
commissioners' courts could have opted not to join the computer
network. And once they were part of it, they could not have pulled
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meat and potatoes of gang enforcement in Texas is gang
intelligence . . . the database, the files, the photos, the
information that allows officers to track and investigate cases,''
said Kim Ogg, head of the Houston mayor's anti-gang office.
``There's much more at stake here than just a gang database.''
</P>
<P>
   Explained Chuck Brawner, president of the Texas Municipal Police
Association: ``If we allow local governments the option of opting
out . . . we will not have a statewide database.''
</P>
<P>
   Much the same sentiment was echoed by Sgt. Wes McBride, head of
gang enforcement for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department,
whose computer network is one of several prototypes for what Texas
wants to create.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other group in this country that kills and maims
as much as criminal street gangs,'' he said. ``Cities and towns
that opt out (in California) . . . become sanctuaries for gang
members.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current Texas law, local police departments and sheriff's
offices are allowed to keep their own files on gang members but
there is no statewide network of that information. But because that
law expires in September, a new law allowing those files must be
passed _ or they will all have to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   While most police officials opposed the computer database bill
at Wednesday's hearing _ they disliked provisions that would have
allowed adults listed in the database as gang members to challenge
that in court, and cautioned against letting privacy concerns
outweigh police needs _ they overwhelmingly supported the other
five elements of the anti-gang plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmen from Austin to Dallas to Houston to Corpus Christi
attended the lengthy Wednesday hearing, underscoring the importance
of the gang issue _ and the bills _ in the legislative session. A
key program of the current legislative session, the anti-gang plan
was prompted by a two-year study by a Senate panel headed by West
of Texas' growing problem with gangs _ criminal street groups and
prison gangs that police say now include more than 84,000 members
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Unanimously approved by the committee were bills that would
require prison officials to notify local lawmen when prison gang
members are released from prison, would bolster training so parole
officers can more closely supervise prison gang members once they
are freed from behind bars, create a statewide police task force to
track gangs and would create a restricted Internet site to allow
police to better exchange investigative tips about gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Also approved was a bill that would make it a crime for the
first time to solicit membership in a criminal street gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas needs to be proactive against gangs, certainly, but I am
also aware of abuses by a minority of law enforcement agencies who
_ how shall I say it _ have invaded the privacy rights of
individuals and we need to have a system of checks and balances to
prevent that,'' West said. ``Inclusion in this database should be
based on conduct, not on characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
