<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON ZIMMER IS NO MERE CARETAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio, Mass.)  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Yankees return for their home opener with
two victories and one loss. And by the way, who gets credit for the
Yankee record until Joe Torre comes back?
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer gave his opinion Wednesday with the wisdom of Solomon
_ and not Solomon Hemus, the former manager of the Cardinals,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe gets the wins; I get the losses,'' Zimmer decided.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it is not up to Zimmer to cede the good side of the
record to his buddy, who is recuperating from cancer surgery. The
Elias Sports Bureau, record-keeper to the world, will have the
final say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every case is different,'' said Steve Hirdt of Elias
Wednesday. ``It's not just a matter of who calls the hit-and-run
play. If somebody doesn't manage for a day because his daughter is
graduating from school, he's still the manager. We'll wait until
the situation resolves itself to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre will be back in a couple of weeks, and Zim portrays
himself as a mere seat-warmer, but the old passion has kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   He is so intense about managing that his body quivered at the
end of Tuesday night's game, his breathing shallow, his voice
husky. He has called for daring plays on the bases, he has made
hunch decisions about his left fielder, and he stuck with Ramiro
Mendoza Wednesday, even when The Boss of All Bosses seemed to be
pushing for his new best friend, Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer's instincts were perfect. Mendoza pitched eight scoreless
innings and then Zimmer used Irabu in the ninth inning and received
three straight outs to wrap up a 4-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like it was 10-0,'' Zimmer said later, of his trust
for Irabu. ``It was 4-0. Things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened, and Zimmer did not gloat about winning a game
with the more prepared pitcher while rehabilitating the psyche of
another pitcher. In his mind, he merely supervised another victory
for Torre's record.
</P>
<P>
   But underneath? You could hear the old boy's heart thumping.
After trying to hold back his emotions, Zimmer has allowed himself
to be what he is, a throwback to the old days when managers
actually sat around and talked baseball rather than give tight,
little press availabilities.
</P>
<P>
   With his garrulous streak and his slight limp from an arthritic
knee, Zimmer is starting to blur with Casey Stengel, for whom he
played one historic month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make a living telling the truth,'' Casey used to say.
</P>
<P>
   When told he is sounding more and more like Casey, Zimmer said,
``That's a compliment,'' and indeed it is. He played for Casey in
the spring of 1962, for the Worst Team in the History of Baseball _
Casey won 40 but the Mets lost 120.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the dog out of the ball in spring training and Casey
kept smiling at me like I was gonna hit .400,'' Zimmer recalled.
``I got one hit on opening day and we lost. I got one hit the next
day and we lost. Then I went 0 for 30 and we still lost.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, Zimmer recalled, he was in the shower, and Casey showed
up and gave an elaborate wink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey said something like, `You're gonna like it, short-center
field, it's good for you,'' and I said, `Casey, I don't know what
in the world you're talking about,' and he said, `Oops, I forgot to
tell you, we just traded you to Cincinnati.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was good for Zimmer. Nobody knew it, but his father was ill,
and he got to play at home for the rest of the season. He said he
has been lucky like that all his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed at Fenway Park; I managed at Wrigley Field'' _ and
tomorrow he manages in Yankee Stadium, 51 years after his first
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't remember his first game at Cambridge, Md., in the old
Eastern Shore League, ``but I sure as heck remember the third game.
I couldn't hold onto a ball, and finally I snagged one and I threw
it clear up against the outhouse behind first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sending the local paper to my father back home in
Cincinnati and he called me and said, `Your third game in pro ball,
and you've already set a league record _ six errors in one game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now it is 51 years later, and Zimmer is opening another season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how ballplayers are out day by day?'' Zimmer said.
``That's the way it is with me. I just want to make it to May 1.''
</P>
<P>
   He will turn the team over to Torre, but he will privately
relish these precious days, when he got to do something he still
loves so much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
