<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIGUA-LAUNDERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARNS ON ANTIGUA MONEY LAUNDERING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Treasury Department warned banks Wednesday to
be especially careful of financial transactions routed through
Antigua and Barbuda, saying that changes in the Caribbean nation's
law ``threaten to create a haven for money laundering.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the changes, the operations of about 50 offshore
banks in the Caribbean islands had been watched with suspicion by
U.S. officials, James E. Johnson, the undersecretary for
enforcement, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, the islands weakened their anti-money-laundering
law, to the dismay of American officials. Amendments heightened
bank secrecy, hobbled investigators and put up obstacles to
international cooperation, Johnson said. Supervision of the
offshore banks was entrusted to a new agency, the International
Financial Sector Authority, whose six-member board includes four
executives from the offshore banks being regulated _ a conflict of
interest that invites abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Embassy of Antigua and Barbuda issued a
statement acknowledging the Treasury Department's concerns. Prime
Minister Lester Bird said his government had set up a committee to
propose changes in the law to satisfy American concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the status of money-laundering enforcement is
watched by big narcotics traffickers. ``If you're a narcotics
trafficker, you can move your drugs and never get any powder on
your fingers and profit tremendously,'' he said. ``But money tends
to stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he said, banking laws that make it easier for a
trafficker to do business with hard-to-trace money are the bane of
law enforcement, adding that lax banking laws also increase the
danger of bank frauds involving millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Treasury officials hoped that Antigua and Barbuda,
a former British colony of about 64,000 people situated southeast
of Puerto Rico, would reverse course and toughen its law.
</P>
<P>
   In the embassy statement, Bird said his government did not want
to antagonize the United States, ``but at the same time we would
like the offshore financial sector to serve our economic
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would welcome the help of the United States in achieving
this objective,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0522 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENSION-GUARANTOR-460     04-07 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENSION-GUARANTOR-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES U.S. PENSION GUARANTOR CAN BE SUED BY WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After reading a memo leaked by a whistle-blower, a federal judge
reversed her opinion Wednesday and ruled that the federal agency
that takes over failed pension plans has a responsibility of
loyalty to workers in such plans and can be sued for violating that
duty.
</P>
<P>
   The memo showed that the agency, the Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corp., organizes its budget and regards its activities differently
from the way it had presented itself in court while defending
against a lawsuit brought by the Association of Former Pan Am
Employees.
</P>
<P>
   The association contends that the agency has delayed determining
how much its members are due and has shortchanged them hundreds of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important victory for people in failed pension
plans who can now sue to remove'' the pension agency if it does not
fulfill its duty of loyalty, said Harvey M. Katz of New York, the
lawyer for the association.
</P>
<P>
   The pension agency has repeatedly sought to dismiss the
class-action lawsuit on the ground that it operates as a government
agency and is not subject to the duty of loyalty imposed on private
companies as pension plan trustees.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Judge Loretta A. Preska of U.S. District Court
in Manhattan threw out all but one of the claims that the pension
agency stands in the same shoes as any other pension-plan trustee
and is therefore subject to the Employee Income Retirement Security
Act, the 1974 law that regulates pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   In all but one area she accepted the agency's argument that it
operates as an arm of the government in most activities and ruled
that it was largely immune from such litigation.
</P>
<P>
   But in a five-page opinion issued Wednesday, Preska said she was
reversing herself after reading the leaked memo. The memo, the
judge wrote, suggested that the pension agency ``itself views
benefit calculation as a trustee function'' that is separate from
its government functions.
</P>
<P>
   The memo was leaked by an employee of the pension agency who is
known only as Jim Dough. The employee, together with the Pan Am
employees association, is pressing a separate federal suit in
Baltimore on behalf of the pension agency against one of its
biggest contractors after accusations of overbilling.
</P>
<P>
   Preska's ruling is the latest blow to the agency, which was
harshly criticized last month by its inspector general and which
will be the subject this summer of Senate hearings into delays in
determining the benefits due the 450,000 workers in the failed
pensions plans it administers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan Am employees association is suing the pension agency,
saying that eight years after the airline filed for bankruptcy is
too long for many of its 45,000 members to be told how much they
are due so they can begin appealing the benefit determinations..
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agency's executive director, David M. Strauss, traveled to
Las Vegas, Nev., and New York a year ago to lobby with labor
leaders to cut off financing for the lawsuit, which he said lacked
merit.
</P>
<P>
   James Keightley, the pension agency's general counsel, said
Wednesday that it ``has fulfilled all of its obligations under the
law to Pan Am participants'' and that ``we are confident that,
after further review, the court will find that claims of fiduciary
breach are without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that by the end of this month, the last benefit
determinations should be issued to participants in the largest Pan
Am plan, and he noted that the pension agency was paying $100
million a year in benefits to 16,000 former Pan Am workers.
</P>
<P>
   The agency says that most of the problems addressed in the
lawsuit and the inspector general reports were inherited from
President George Bush's administration and that they are being
aggressively resolved under the Clinton administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
