<SLUG> BC-RELIEF-SEATTLE-KOSOVO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON RELIEF AGENCIES SEE SUFFERING UP CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ During the day, John Schenk says his new surroundings
look positively inviting: sun-splashed sidewalk cafes at which to
lounge and Mediterranean temperatures with which to warm his
Northwest-chilled bones.
</P>
<P>
   But distance or darkness shatters that image of Podgorica,
Montenegro. A few hours away in the mountains, refugees from Kosovo
huddle on the concrete floors of factories and crowd into mosques
for shelter, driven out of their homeland by Serb forces. At night,
war comes to Podgorica _ NATO bombs exploded Tuesday in the middle
of the Montenegrin capital and set hillsides aflame outside the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit of a tinderbox,'' Schenk, a Tacoma resident, said
Wednesday by telephone from Podgorica. But a tinderbox in need of
relief. That's where Schenk comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Schenk works for World Vision, a charity based in Federal Way,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the response to support Schenk's work and that of other
World Vision workers has been strong, said spokesman Dean Owen.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been much the same at World Concern, a charity
based in North Seattle. ``My phones have been ringing off the hook
here,'' said Rick Dennler, who was answering calls Wednesday. ``The
response has been tremendous as far as the outpouring of people who
want to contribute. From my perspective, it seems to be every bit
as a good as the response to Hurricane Mitch.''
</P>
<P>
   People have been donating blankets, clothing and other items,
supplies that will be packed and sent to a network of churches in
Albania and Macedonia for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   What's spurring the giving is simple, Kelly Miller said from the
World Concern warehouse. Images of human suffering on newspaper
front pages and the nightly television news have touched people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell a story,'' Miller said, ``and people respond.''
</P>
<P>
   For John Schenk, 50, the images only begin to tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are exhausted and traumatized when they arrive here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He met one group of nine people who traveled for 30 hours in
winter weather, over mountains and without sleep, to escape Serb
forces in Kosovo. The oldest member of the group was a 64-year-old
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you can imagine the state the people are in when they
arrive,'' Schenk, 50, said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Montenegro have opened their homes, businesses and
churches to refugees, Schenk said.
</P>
<P>
   World Vision is trying to supply people with food, blankets and
the basics of human sanitation. Making the job harder is that
relief flights from the West aren't getting into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get supplies in country, but it's getting scarcer
and scarcer,'' he said. ``Prices in the stores have doubled in the
last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   One plan is to buy enough flour and yeast to provide bread to
2,500 people for two weeks. Tuesday, World Vision had found a
seller for 20 tons of flour.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, someone ``bought it out from under us,'' Schenk
said.
</P>
<P>
   World Vision is putting together family packs of food to feed
seven people for a week and trying to line up woodstoves, pots and
cooking utensils.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers like Schenk also watch their backs. ``We're
maintaining a very low profile.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S government has urged Americans to get out of Montenegro,
and the Montenegrin government has suggested the same thing, saying
it can't guarantee their safety.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Yugoslav troops loyal to President Slobodan Milosevic
have moved into residential neighborhoods in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Schenk is a Canadian, but, he says, that may not make much
difference. ``People don't ask you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel vulnerable. If we start feeling profoundly unsafe, then
we will be leaving. Right now it just requires somes wisdom and
prudence.''
</P>
<P>
   World Vision is well on its way to raising the $2 million it
needs for Kosovo relief, Owen said. In addition to Montenegro, the
relief agency hopes to be up and running with an operation in
Albania by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   World Vision is only accepting donations of money. Wednesday, it
was getting 40 to 50 calls an hour from contributors. In the past
week, callers and those using its Internet site have contributed
$300,000 in the United States and $140,000 in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   World Vision can be reached at 888-511-6565 or at
www.worldvision.org.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, World Concern is using contributions of money to buy
items like infant formula. But it is also accepting goods. The
charity especially needs new baby bottles and nipples and
disposable diapers. It also needs blankets and clothing, especially
shoes, socks and underwear.
</P>
<P>
   World Concern's cash donation number is 800-739-9800. Its Web
site is www.worldconcern.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
