<SLUG> BC-NY-RAPIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY MAN IN CUSTODY MAY HAVE COMMITTED 51 RAPES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 38-year-old man who the police say may be
responsible for the largest series of rapes in recent years was
arrested and charged in four of those attacks Wednesday, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Issaac Jones, who investigators say may have attacked
as many as 51 women in the Bronx, upper Manhattan and Mount Vernon
in Westchester County since 1993, was captured Tuesday afternoon as
he tried to sell a Bronx pawnbroker several pieces of jewelry he
had stolen from one victim, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   It was during the search for a suspect in the rapes that four
officers from the Police Department's Street Crime Unit shot and
killed Amadou Diallo on Feb. 4 as he entered his home in the
Soundview section.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones was caught, he was with a woman whom Police
Commissioner Howard Safir described as an associate. Jones, who has
been charged with four counts of rape and eight counts of robbery,
violently assaulted and robbed many of his victims, who ranged from
age 13 to 53, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has confessed to the crimes that he has been charged
with,'' Safir said at a news conference. ``Debriefing is
continuing.'' Jones voluntarily gave investigators a blood sample,
and Safir said that results of a DNA analysis would probably link
him to the other attacks, which were marked in part by the
distinctive method of the crimes. He said 17 of the unsolved rapes
had already been linked by DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that Jones was previously convicted of sodomy
in 1983 and robbery in 1989. He was released from prison in 1993,
and remained on parole until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the first of the series of rapes occurred in
August 1993 and that the most recent one was this Valentine's Day,
when two women were sexually assaulted and robbed in the elevator
of their building in the Washington Heights section of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
