<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HABIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD F. HABIG, 91, BUILDER OF A BILLION-DOLLAR COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind. Ky.)   (rk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arnold Francis Habig, who built a small Indiana woodworking shop
into Kimball International Inc., died on March 29 at Memorial
Hospital in Jasper, Ind., his birthplace and seat of the
diversified billion-dollar company. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Jasper as the third oldest of 10 children, he held
a variety of odd jobs in his youth, delivering newspapers and baked
goods, cleaning offices, running a movie-theater projector and
working in a Coca-Cola bottling plant. In 1926 he graduated from
Spencerian Business College in Louisville, Ky., and worked briefly
as an accountant there.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home, he went to work at Jasper Machine Works. Then in
1928 he joined the Jasper Wood Products Co. as an accountant and
rose to become plant manager and a director. He stayed until 1950,
when he was elected a director and president of the Midwest
Manufacturing Co.
</P>
<P>
   He also took over as plant manager of that company, which had
some two dozen employees and a 25,000-square-foot production plant.
The company, which changed its name to the Jasper Corp., quickly
grew under his guidance into a leading maker of wood cabinets for
America's top manufacturers of television sets and phonographs.
</P>
<P>
   Sales more than quadrupled to $748,000 in 1950, and it had
profit of $39,000. By comparison, Kimball International _ the name
adopted in 1974 _ posted $1.03 billion in sales and reported net
earnings of $55 million for 1998, with Habig's sons holding top
positions in the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, the Jasper Corp. bought the W.W. Kimball Co. of
Chicago, a venerable but ailing maker of pianos and organs founded
in 1857. As a division of Jasper and then Kimball International it
regained its position as a leading manufacturer of keyboard
instruments, and in 1966 acquired Boesendorfer of Vienna, often
called the Rolls-Royce of concert grands.
</P>
<P>
   At plants in eight states and four more abroad, Kimball's more
than 9,000 employees manufactured a wide variety of consumer
durables under its family of brand names, including furniture and
audio speaker systems, as well as veneer, plywood and wood
components.
</P>
<P>
   Habig introduced a profit-sharing system to provide nest eggs
for company employees and scholarship programs for their children.
He was active in community affairs and supported various charities,
particularly in the arts and education.
</P>
<P>
   He led the company as president and then chairman from 1950
until 1990, when he formally retired from Kimball's board. But he
remained active in the company, most recently in a consulting role
with the title of assistant to the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Habig's first wife, Mary Ann Jahn Habig, died in 1972. They had
been married for 44 years. That year he married Barbara T.
Cukierski, who survives. Other survivors are three sons and three
daughters from his first marriage: Thomas L., Douglas A., and John
B., all of Jasper, and the vice chairman, chairman and chief
executive, and senior vice president for electronics operations,
respectively; Nancy Habig, also of Jasper; Barbara Jane Habig of
Bloomington, Ind., and Marilyn Schultheis of Evansville, Ind.;
three brothers, Anthony and Jerome, of Jasper, and Francis, of High
Point, N.C.; 12 grandchildren, and 17 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0528 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEAPONS-VOTE-KAN &LR;      04-07 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEAPONS-VOTE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Concealed-weapons issue ran into impenetrable opposition in urban
areas  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Supporters of concealed handguns in Missouri
can blame their loss in Tuesday's election on surprisingly vigorous
opposition from urban voters and weaker-than-expected support in
several key rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri voters defeated Proposition B by about 44,000 votes, or
52 percent to 48 percent, thanks largely to an outpouring of
anti-gun votes in St. Louis County. Proposition B would have
allowed Missouri residents to carry concealed firearms for the
first time since Jesse James terrorized the state. And, like James,
the proposition was more popular in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposition's rural support wasn't strong enough to
offset anti-gun sentiment in the state's two largest metropolitan
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Rural areas make up about 62 percent of Missouri's population.
Voters there favored concealed guns 60 percent to 40 percent. But
voters in Kansas City and St. Louis opposed the measure by an even
larger margin: 65 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Weaker-than-expected support in the Springfield area and
northwestern Missouri also played important roles in the measure's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Gun advocates had hoped for low voter turnout, in the belief
that concealed-weapons supporters would dominate the polls during
an April election with no other major statewide issue on the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   However, the emotions generated by the gun-rights debate sparked
a record April turnout of 1.3 million voters. Secretary of State
Rebecca Cook had predicted a turnout of 900,000, or about 25
percent of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis County, where 70 percent of voters opposed concealed
guns, provided two of every nine votes cast in the election and
nearly one of every three votes against Proposition B. Within the
St. Louis city limits, 74 percent voted no.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Kansas City limits, 72 percent opposed the
proposition. Jackson County, overall, voted concealed weapons down
61 to 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Myers, campaign manager for Missourians Against Crime, said
Tuesday he expected the rural vote to make up for a poor showing in
the cities.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Hodgdon, a board member of the National Rifle
Association from Overland Park, Kan., said he was surprised by how
badly the vote turned out in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know headquarters was worried about St. Louis from the
start,'' Hodgdon said. ``I thought it would lose by much less.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in some rural areas, support was mixed. In the 19
counties of northwestern Missouri, 48.2 percent of the voters
opposed concealed handguns. In Buchanan County, where St. Joseph is
the biggest city, 57 percent voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgdon attributed the weak showing in northwestern Missouri to
the influence of the Kansas City media, which editorialized against
concealed guns.
</P>
<P>
   In Greene County, dominated by Springfield, gun advocates had
hoped for a big win. Even pro-gun radio ads by John Ashcroft, the
Republican U.S. senator from Springfield, didn't generate
widespread support.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal passed by fewer than 3,000 votes in Greene County,
with 47 percent voting against it.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates couldn't keep from gloating over Missouri
voters' rejection of concealed weapons, despite the NRA's spending
nearly $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to be a good day when you win after being outspent
5-1,'' said Brian Morton, a spokesman for Handgun Control Inc. in
Washington. ``No matter how much money they spent, Missouri voters
could see through the extremist positions of the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, which had earlier called the election a showdown over
Second Amendment rights, on Wednesday downplayed the significance
of the vote. The group blamed Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan for the
outcome and criticized him for meddling in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did everything he could do to defeat this measure,'' NRA
spokesman Bill Powers said. ``This crosses the line to where it
becomes a mistrust of the people of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment perplexed many anti-gun workers, some of whom had
privately criticized Carnahan for not having actively opposed
concealed weapons. Carnahan, who had threatened to veto
concealed-weapons legislation for years, kept a low profile on the
issue after the legislature passed a bill submitting it to a public
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers thought he was trying to downplay his opposition,
to avoid offending rural voters in next year's campaign for U.S.
Senate against Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan spokesman Chris Sifford found the NRA criticism
somewhat confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It obviously doesn't make a lot of sense for an organization
in Fairfax, Va., to criticize the governor for being involved in a
public policy issue in Missouri,'' he said. ``This is a group that
pumped millions of dollars into a Missouri campaign from out of
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodgdon said the NRA originally planned to spend $3.5 million on
the Missouri election. The group pumped in at least another
$250,000 as the campaign went down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgdon tried to put a good face on the outcome. He said the
campaign provided an opportunity to publicize the arguments for
legalizing concealed handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well over 600,000 Missourians supported concealed-carry,''
Hodgdon said. ``We came so close to being a majority, and the
people learned so much about it. Before the process started, I
think the public would have been overwhelmingly against us.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of the measure to legalize concealed firearms in
Missouri resounded across the state line in Kansas. State Rep.
Candy Ruff of Leavenworth said Wednesday that her bill to allow
concealed weapons in Kansas also will die.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of work to do educating people,'' said Ruff, a
Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-07-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
