u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAP-NYT &LR;      04-07 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-CAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS MAY HAVE BROKEN SALARY CAP RULES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League is investigating accusations that
the Dallas Cowboys violated the league's salary cap rules. The team
could face multimillion-dollar fines and even the temporary loss of
services of the players in question.
</P>
<P>
   The salary cap is considered a vital element that helps maintain
the integrity of the game. Some league executives believe salary
cap violations are almost as damaging to the competitive nature of
pro football as drug use by its players. That is why the league
offers a $1 million reward to anyone with proof that a team is
violating salary cap rules.
</P>
<P>
   Last month it was reported that the Cowboys had reached
multiyear contract agreements, but did not sign center Mark
Stepnoski, wide receiver Raghib Ismail or linebacker Quentin
Coryatt. The Cowboys did not deny the deals had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Once an agreement has been consummated between a player's agent
and a team, the league urges the team to sign the player to a
contract as soon as possible. After the contract is signed, league
rules stipulate that it must be submitted to the league office
within 24 hours and, subsequently, every team in the league is made
aware of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Several teams said they recently contacted the agents for
Stepnoski, Ismail and Coryatt and were told that each player was no
longer interested in their teams. The teams said they conducted
their own investigation and determined that some sort of
arrangement had been reached between the Cowboys and three players.
</P>
<P>
   At that point at least several teams complained to the league
office. Those teams told the NFL they believed the Cowboys had
reached a verbal or written agreement with the three players, but
had not signed them to a contract to circumvent cap rules.
</P>
<P>
   At least two teams believe the Cowboys, about $255,000 under the
$59 million salary cap, may have hidden a deal with the three
players because they did not have the room to sign them, but wanted
to make sure other teams did not sign them.
</P>
<P>
   The league, prompted by the complaints, began to explore the
situation themselves, according to team executives, union officials
and agents.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL confirmed they are looking into the matter but had no
further comment.
</P>
<P>
   The league is examining whether the Cowboys made two separate
violations, officials said. First, not reporting a contractual
agreement within 24 hours and second, circumventing the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Initial offenses for either violation usually incur a warning
from the league. It is not known if Dallas has previously been
warned. Or, if the league feels the violations are serious enough,
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue could fine the Cowboys as much as $2
million or even temporarily revoke any contract Ismail, Stepnoski
and Coryatt may have agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   There is currently no proof the Cowboys have broken any rules. A
team spokesman said the Cowboys have been contacted by league
officials regarding Coryatt, but the league was satisfied with the
teams' explanation about his presence at the Cowboys training
facility even though he was not signed. (Coryatt was visiting a
friend on the team.) They have not been contacted about the other
two players, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The players have not agreed to terms or signed any contracts
and, therefore, could not have violated any rules, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Cowboys are guilty, it is almost impossible to
police many of the salary cap rules. It is too easy to cheat and
too hard to prove.
</P>
<P>
   Still, team and league executives said they believe there is
anecdotal evidence the Cowboys do have an agreement and are indeed
breaking the rules. They point to the fact Ismail and Coryatt have
recently been house-hunting in Dallas and that all three players
stopped listening to inquiries from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   What also caused the ire of at least two teams was that they
were interested in a Dallas restricted free agent they would not
identify. The Cowboys have the right of first refusal and can match
any offer made to one of their restricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams believe the Cowboys would be near or over the
salary cap if the three contracts were signed, thus, Dallas would
not be able to match an offer made to the restricted player.
</P>
<P>
   The three players could be important for Dallas this coming
season. Stepnoski is a former Pro Bowl player, Ismail would add
speed to the team's receiving corps and Coryatt is a former
first-round pick with the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
