<HEADLINE>
OUT OF BOUNDS: WHAT THE BLOCKERS BLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CIR-FILTERS-WORDS) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web filters use lists of objectionable words. Of course, for the
same reasons these words are put on the lists, they're often
unprintable. Most screen out obvious words like ``naked'' or
``sex.'' Here are examples of what's filtered: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NET NANNY
</P>
<P>
   bomb
</P>
<P>
   bondage
</P>
<P>
   fetish
</P>
<P>
   spunk
</P>
<P>
   voyeurism
</P>
<P>
   www.underground.net
</P>
<P>
   Net Nanny filters all information that a person types while on
the computer as well as all information sent to the computer.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSITTER
</P>
<P>
   babe
</P>
<P>
   erotica
</P>
<P>
   gay rights
</P>
<P>
   Nazi
</P>
<P>
   pot
</P>
<P>
   Cybersitter users who type these words into an Internet search
engine will receive either an ``object not found'' message or zero
search results. Cybersitter also blocks obvious pornography sites
and sites like these, some of which relate to political groups,
like the National Organization for Women:
</P>
<P>
   www.now.org
</P>
<P>
   www.glaad.org
</P>
<P>
   SURF WATCH
</P>
<P>
   White power
</P>
<P>
   Erotica
</P>
<P>
   Girlz
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core pornography
</P>
<P>
   Surf Watch users who type these words into an Internet search
engine will receive zero search results. Surf Watch also blocks
Internet sites like these:
</P>
<P>
   www.gambling.com
</P>
<P>
   www.peacefire.org/bypass/SurfWatch
</P>
<P>
   www.tasdistillery.com.au
</P>
