<HEADER>
A0076 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDER-PLEA-KAN &LR;      04-07 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-PLEA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEA OF NOT GUILTY ENTERED TO CHARGES IN ONE OF 5 HOMICIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL and LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The man suspected in the killings of five men
pleaded not guilty Wednesday in one of the homicides amid tight
security after police received several death threats against him.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged Gary Beach this week with first-degree
murder and armed criminal action in the death of Kenneth Gulley,
45, of Independence. Gulley's body was one of five found Monday in
Beach's rental house at 4275 Jefferson St. Police released the
identity of the fifth victim Wednesday: Jeral B. Nickerson, 61, of
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said Beach, 56, is the only person suspected in
the homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Beach was arrested Tuesday morning a few blocks from his house.
He was questioned by police and placed in the city jail to await
arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives escorted Beach from the jail to the Jackson County
Courthouse on Wednesday morning, but deviated from the usual
routine because of the threats. Police said several persons called
a tips hotline overnight, claiming they planned to kill Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives escorted Beach to an unmarked police vehicle with
darkened windows and loaded him into the vehicle in an area not
readily accessible to the public. They left police headquarters
earlier than normal and drove Beach past waiting reporters and
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners are usually escorted past photographers in an open
garage area and loaded into a van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the multiple threats, we didn't want to take any
chances,'' said Detective Al DeValkenaere, who drove Beach to his
court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   DeValkenaere said Beach said nothing during the brief trip.
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouse, a hostile spectator whispered an expletive to
Beach as he walked by.
</P>
<P>
   Beach entered his plea of not guilty and was taken to the
Jackson County Jail, where he is being held without bond.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they were still trying to determine whether each
victim had been shot with the same weapon. Court records showed
Gulley died from a gunshot wound to the face and police initially
said it appeared each victim died from gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   A gun was recovered from Beach's car when he was arrested, but
police have not said whether it is thought to be the murder weapon.
Relatives said Beach traded two handguns to his brother for a 9mm
pistol two weeks ago. Police searching Beach's house found 9mm
cartridge casings near the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities don't think all five victims were killed at the same
time, but they declined to reveal when each victim died or in what
order. Besides Gulley and Nickerson, the other victims were
Christopher Conrad, 27, of Overland Park; Mark Nelson, 28, of
Kansas City; and Mike L. Davis, 32, of Kansas City. Nelson and
Davis lived with Beach and Nickerson had lived with Beach in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Police met with the victims' family members Wednesday night to
brief them on the progress of the homicide investigation. Family
members declined to comment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and neighbors said Nickerson, the last victim
identified, was a quiet, private man who caused no one harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was strait-laced,'' said Ken Ruhnke, who lived across the
street from Nickerson in the 3600 block of Jefferson Street. ``He
went to work every day. He was like clockwork. Very routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson drove for a limo service for years, working closely
with fellow limo driver Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson was a close friend of Beach. For years, waitresses
served them meals almost every day at Nichols Lunch, a 24-hour
restaurant at 39th Street and Southwest Trafficway. Waitresses said
they usually ate with Davis, who was Beach's stepson and who lived
with Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Nickerson had moved a couple of weeks ago from his rental home
to an apartment at Roanoke Parkway and Jarboe Street, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   New owners had bought the well-kept two-story house on Jefferson
he had rented for more than a decade, and didn't want to rent it
out.
</P>
<P>
   So he was forced to move, which he was upset about, neighbors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said Nickerson was diabetic and had a regular lunch he
loved _ ``cheeseburger, hold the fries, salad with diet dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   He was always nicely dressed and treated people kindly.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhnke said Nickerson had few visitors to his home.
</P>
<P>
   In another development Wednesday, police determined a stolen car
that was left with its engine running on the street next to Beach's
house last week was not related to the homicides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
