<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELOITTE-CONSULTANTS-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,000 DELOITTE CONSULTANTS LEAVE FIRM TO FORM COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big Five accounting firms may be too successful at what was
once a secondary business: consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche, a unit of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, is
expected to announce Thursday that a group of about 1,000 of its
consultants, who provide companies with temporary, experienced
accountants, will leave the firm and create their own company.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants said they have had to turn down an increasing
number of proposals because they involved providing accountants and
financial managers to companies that Deloitte &AMP; Touche audited.
</P>
<P>
   Federal securities regulators have raised concerns about similar
arrangements in the past because they could be creating conflicts
of interest for auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors must be independent because their job is to review the
financial statements companies have prepared. Conflicts can arise
when an accounting firm's consultants are helping to prepare those
financial statements since the auditors could be seen as reviewing
their own work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting more and more requests from Deloitte &AMP; Touche
audit clients that we could not do because of independence
concerns,'' said Donald B. Murray, who helped create what has
quickly grown into a $100 million consulting business for Deloitte.
``It was becoming more and more of an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The consultants would not disclose how much they paid Deloitte &AMP;
Touche to leave. Their new company, Resources Connection, is based
in Santa Ana, Calif. The private transaction closed on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   All of the nation's five largest accounting firms have
consulting practices where they supply accountants to companies on
a contract basis. In some cases, the accounting firms agree to take
over the company's entire accounting and finance department in what
is referred to as outsourcing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, companies worldwide spent more than $7 billion to
outsource their accounting and finance departments, said Eric
Blantz, an analyst at Dataquest, a consulting firm in Lowell, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Five accounting firms, he said, are among the top 10
providers of the outsourcing of accounting work, which includes
activities such as billing customers and providing internal
auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young, for example, has a joint venture with Shell
International, a unit of the Royal Dutch/Shell Group. The venture,
called Tasco Europe, performs the accounting work for Shell's
businesses and also offers its services to companies across Europe.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Murray said many of the accountants who work for Re:sources
Connection were once auditors at Deloitte or at other Big Five
firms. Many of the accountants also have held top accounting and
finance jobs at companies.
</P>
<P>
   At Deloitte, and now at Re:sources Connection, the
accountants-turned-consultants are hired by companies that need
accounting experts to manage a complicated job like combining the
company's accounting records with those of another company that has
just been acquired.
</P>
<P>
   In December, another group of consultants left Deloitte &AMP;
Touche. Those consultants, who helped form a new company called EPS
Solutions, also offer outsourcing services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the things they had wanted to do at Deloitte,
they couldn't do because of independence concerns,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu said its global consulting revenues had
grown at a rate of 40 percent last year to $3.24 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
