<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES DROPPED FOR DEMONSTRATORS WHO PROTESTED DIALLO SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan Criminal Court judge dismissed disorderly
conduct and other charges Wednesday against the 1,166 demonstrators
arrested during last month's wave of daily protests over the police
shooting of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   After the court session, defense lawyers welcomed the
dismissals, which came as no surprise, because the Manhattan
district attorney, Robert M. Morgenthau, announced last week that
he was likely to ask a judge to throw out the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demonstrations at Police Plaza have set a new national
standard as a way of making people take notice of a critical issue
that confronts us,'' said Michael A. Hardy, one of four lawyers who
addressed a bank of television cameras and reporters on a sidewalk
outside the court building Wednesday. ``That is the issue of the
relationship between law enforcement and the minority communities
all across this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that he was
against automatic dismissal of the charges, a view he reiterated
Wednesday. ``The courts should have adjudicated this,'' Safir said.
``I have a lot of respect for District Attorney Morgenthau. He and
I usually agree. This time we disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said on Saturday that he could see both
sides of the disagreement, but a spokeswoman said Wednesday that
Giuliani supported the judge's decision. ``The protesters'
detention, which in some instances was for up to 10 hours, is
equivalent to a form of punishment,'' said the spokeswoman, Sunny
Mindel.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 1,166 people, including a handful of politicians and
celebrities, blocked the entrance to 1 Police Plaza and certain
Wall Street buildings during three weeks of peaceful but systematic
protests last month. The demonstrations ended March 29, two days
before the four white police officers who fatally shot Diallo, an
immigrant peddler, on Feb. 4 were arraigned on second-degree murder
charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
