<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0083 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS &LR;      04-07 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Big hitters still own Masters edge
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUGUSTA, Ga. _ There have been so many changes at Augusta National
Golf Club this year, such as the inch-long fuzzy rough that can
play havoc with shots aimed from it to those treacherous greens.
</P>
<P>
   Also new is the added length on two par-5s and pine trees
between Nos. 15 and 17 that popped up like a Chia forest to provide
previously forgiving spaces a bit more bite.
</P>
<P>
   Threesomes teeing off this morning for only the second time in
Masters history. No Jack Nicklaus. Both rare oddities.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you know, there's going to be a windmill on the
11th green that will gobble up golf balls and spit them back out up
the fairway. Or, at the very least, tennis courts.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the alterations at one of golf's most
history-conscious sites, some things never change.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a segment of an interview with Masters tournament
chairman Hootie Johnson on Wednesday yielded this exchange:
</P>
<P>
   Question: Would you mind telling us how many African-American
and how many female members there are at Augusta National?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson: ``Well, that's a club matter, ma'am, and all club
matters are private.''
</P>
<P>
   Question: Are there female members?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson: ``That's a club matter and all club matters are
private, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, we'll take that as a ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Some traditions stand tall amid the dogwoods and azaleas.
</P>
<P>
   Another one that survives the attempts to bring it down is the
fact that the big-knockers still have the best chance of winning
the Masters when tournament play opens this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Taking out bunkers along the par-5 15th means shorter, more
accurate drivers can't use the mounds to get extra distance.
Similarly, the additional 20 yards on No. 2 means only the longest
hitters will be able to get on or handy to the green in two shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the changes are beneficial to all the long hitters, no
doubt about it,'' Tiger Woods said. ``Some of the short hitters
could use the mounds on No. 15 and they aren't there now. They'll
be hitting 3-woods or long irons into that green. No. 17 is a huge
advantage for a long hitter. I don't even think about that
Eisenhower Tree, and the shorter hitters have to go around it.
That's a tough shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods joins David Duval as the heavy favorites to win the 63rd
Masters. Whether their rivalry blossoms this week like the redbuds
surrounding the 16th hole depends much on whether either or both of
them can make a run at the green jacket come Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And the new Augusta plays right into the hands of both players,
along with Ernie Els, John Huston, Greg Norman and others who can
put the ball into orbit _ or at least beyond Ike's Tree on the
newly conformed 17th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here, having length is a good deal,'' Fred Couples
said. ``I've done well and finished seventh or 10th or whatever
here just because I hit the ball a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   While nobody's certain what to expect out of the new Augusta,
the guess is that scores will rise slightly, mainly because the
changes won't really change the course for long hitters, but will
penalize short-knockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they hadn't had to make the changes simply because of
(the evolution) of equipment,'' said Nicklaus, who will be missing
his first Masters in 41 years because he has not fully recovered
from hip-replacement surgery. ``But I think that the changes that
have been made are quite good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes are going to add a stroke, probably two strokes to
the field. I think No. 2 will play half a stroke harder per round
and I think No. 17 will play half a stroke harder per round. So I
think the course is probably one stroke tougher per round.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as good as these guys are, if they get the right
conditions, they'll still shoot low scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Couples: ``In my opinion, I think scores will go up. But I
would say there are only so many guys who have a real chance at
winning. My four or five would start with David Duval. I think
Vijay Singh is going to be up there. I'll go with Tiger Woods and
Ernie Els.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked where he would fit in the ratings, Couples said: ``I'm No.
1. I never predict myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, of course, is going for his third victory in a row,
having already collected winner's checks at the Players
Championship and BellSouth Classic over the past two weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Duval has no real worries coming into the the tournament. He
dismissed any speculation that, after winning the last two events
on Tour, he might be lacking enough fuel in the tank to stay
mentally in gear for the year's first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't have to rely on adrenalin here,'' Duval said. ``If you
can't get worked up and ready to play here, you need to do
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who isn't worked up is defending champion Mark
O'Meara. He could spend the rest of his career basking in the
memory of sinking that 20-foot putt on No. 18 to win last year's
Masters and nobody would blame him. His birdie-par-birdie-birdie
finish last year catapulted him to a dream year. He won the British
Open in addition to the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to enjoy this week,'' O'Meara said, but
quickly added he didn't want people to get the wrong impression
about his focus. ``I'm prepared. I feel like I'm playing better now
than I was last year coming in. With golf, anything can happen. But
I definitely want to enjoy the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether everybody enjoys all the newness at venerable Augusta is
another subject. But regardless of whether the changes favor long
hitters, the movers and shakers at Augusta are pleased with the
results of the face lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we hope to do is keep up with golf and the game of
today,'' Johnson said. ``The guys are hitting it longer and they're
in better condition and the equipment is better. We're attempting
to strengthen the golf course to stay in tune with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, Augusta is trying to keep up with progress in
the game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about those female members
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
