<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-COLUMN-HN     04-07 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Duval is latest in can't-miss line
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Along with all of the other changes at Augusta
National this year _ the new trees planted along the right side of
the No. 15 fairway, the extra yardage added to the tee shots on
Nos. 2 and 17, the 1]-inch rough around the course _ you stroll
down Magnolia Lane and almost expect to see David Duval's profile
painted on the roof of the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is the Duval Open. Or so we are led to believe
by the covers of all the hype machines.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated: ``David Duval is on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf World: ``Can David slay Goliath?''
</P>
<P>
   Golfweek: ``Duval! Four!''
</P>
<P>
   And the numbers shout just as loud. The ones that tell us that
while spring is barely two weeks old, Duval has already won four
tournaments on the PGA Tour this year and is ranked No. 1 on both
the money list and in the computer rankings of the world's best
players.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to form this weekend, Duval will blitz
straight down the middle of the fairways with his laser-straight
drives, have them singing hosannas in Amen Corner with his feathery
putting touch, slip into the green jacket early Sunday evening and
then hop aboard a military transport plane that will carry him to
Kosovo, where he'll take care of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe another golfer will step into Duval's path and
detour the victory parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Duval is playing better,'' Tiger Woods said. ``We'll
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, premature coronations have a way of making the would-be
kings left to feel like jokers. What Duval is right now is Duke on
the eve of the NCAA basketball tournament. All that's left to do is
actually win the thing. The Blue Devils were the hottest things
since the invention of the wheel until Connecticut came along to
play the role of the nail that punctured their tire.
</P>
<P>
   It is the nature of this sports business. There is always going
to be another version of the biggest and baddest on the block, the
unbeatable monster. That is, until somebody comes along to beat it.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, Woods strode onto Augusta National and
brought the hallowed course to its knees, shooting a Masters'
record 270 and winning by another record 12 shots over Tom Kite.
That performance, to hear all of the descriptions and read the
analyses, effectively ended competitive golf as we know it straight
through the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath brought word that golf courses would have to be
``Tiger-proofed'' in order to maintain a competitive balance in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The afternmath from April of 1997 also brought this: four tour
wins by Woods and 11 by Duval, who is now either the next great
thing or the latest flavor of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be a disappointment if I didn't win,''
Duval said. ``I'd consider it a disappointment if I didn't
contend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' said Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Duval had a chance a year ago until Mark O'Meara sank a 20-foot
putt on the last hole to win by a stroke. Now he returns as the
smokingest gun to draw on Augusta National since Arnold Palmer in
1960 and Johnny Miller in 1974 both entered the Masters with four
tour victories already in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Not that golf needs much more to make it a sizzling sport
entering the 21st century. But a Woods-Duval rivalry could send it
into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, it could be the first of its kind. For while Sam
Snead, Ben Hogan and Byron Nelson were all born in the same year,
1912, there were real-life intrusions _ World War II, a devastating
injury to Hogan and the early retirement of Nelson _ that cut down
what could have been a glorious rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was 10 years older than Jack Nicklaus when the Golden
Bear began to roar, Nicklaus had a decade on Tom Watson and, by the
time Nick Faldo and Greg Norman started warring, both golfers were
already in their mid-to-late 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have Duval, 27, and Woods, 23, sitting in the top two
positions in the computer rankings, a pair of aces from the same
generation, familiar with the same slang and the same popular
music, maybe ready to square off for years and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger is the flamboyant one, known for wearing red and showing
his emotions on the course. Duval is the controlled one, never
changing his expression and his favorite Sunday outfit is a cool
blue.
</P>
<P>
   Duval wears his trademark Oakley sunglasses. Woods wears his
trademark megawatt smile. Duval has those 11 wins overall. But
Woods has a win in a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the two of them and it really is what it's all
about,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   That and living up to the hype.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
