<P>
   NY-AIDS-DOCTOR (New York) _ It happens all the time in the legal
and financial world: Lawyers or stockbrokers jump from one firm to
another, taking their clients _ and the clients' money _ with them.
But what happens if the professional is a doctor? That is the issue
in a Bronx lawsuit involving a leading pediatric AIDS doctor. By
Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ELDERLY-VOTERS (Deerfield Beach, Fla.) _ When the wave of
retirees moved to South Florida during the condominium booms of the
1960s and 1970s, they brought their machine politics with them.
Their condo associations and social clubs were just like the
meeting halls and church basements back home, and they became a
steady, swelling political force, and they voted for Democrats. But
now the New Deal Democrats are being replaced by immigrants from
Latin America, the Caribbean, Canada, Europe, as well as American
blacks and younger, working people. ``Between now and 2010, the
Democratic Party will be losing its most stable and loyal core,''
said a political scientist. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-KIDS (Undated) _ The first national survey of drug use by
children in the 4th and 6th grades shows that use shoots up as kids
enter middle school, but that levels are not high and are not
rising. The most commonly used drugs by far: beer and cigarettes.
By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BIRTH-DEFECTS (Undated) _ A study from Norway being
published on Wednesday in the New England Journal of Medicine is
the first to provide information about women with birth defects:
they are less likely than others to have children, and those who do
give birth have an increased risk of having a child with the same
birth defect as the mother. However, most give birth to healthy
children, and their children are not at increased risk for any type
of defect except the mother's. The study, based on birth
certificates in Norway, is the first to provide this kind of data,
and researchers say it could not have been done in the U.S. because
of the way records are kept here. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PAIRGAIN-WEB-FRAUD (New York) _ One of the oldest frauds on Wall
Street has been updated for the Internet age. Using a personal web
site designed to look like the Internet page of Bloomberg Business
News, someone posted a fake news story that said an American
technology company called PairGain Technologies Inc. was being
taken over by an Israeli rival. The report spread to a Yahoo
message board and then to other sites frequented by stock traders,
who quickly bid up PairGain's stock by more than 30 percent. By
midday, the stock had retreated as the takeover story was debunked.
By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOX (Undated) _ In a move that could radically alter the
relationship between broadcast networks and their affiliated
stations, the Fox network is unilaterally reclaiming for itself
more than 20 percent of the commercial time now sold by its local
affiliated stations. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Trade officials from the United
States and China are scrounging for a deal that would allow
President Clinton and Prime Minister Zhu Ronghi to announce that
the two countries have come to agreement on China's application to
join the World Trade Organization. If the issue were narrowly about
trade and economics, the two sides would probably have little
trouble shaking hands. By Michael M. Weinstein.
