<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HYMNS-NYT &LR;      04-07 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HYMNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTIONS OF OF MUSIC FOR THE SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first piece of music some children are likely to hear is not
a popular tune or even a lullaby, but a hymn. A mother's favorite,
or the choir's rendition at a family christening or wedding or
funeral, can conquer time and elevate the soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Onward, Christian Soldiers'' is a common favorite, especially
for people who grew up before some denominations decided that it
sounded hostile and pulled it from their hymnals. Perhaps a fan
would like to hear it again or know more about it _ author, date,
background. That presents a problem. No matter that many people
find hymns to be the most moving form of music; they're not going
to encounter them on the top 40 during drive time. Religious radio
stations do their part, but their air time is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's a tip: the Cyber Hymnal, at tch.simplenet.com.
``Are you choosing hymns for a worship service, but don't know what
they sound like? Now you can find out,'' it announces with a
revival preacher's enthusiasm. The free site has more than 1,600
Christian hymns and gospel songs from many denominations. It
includes lyrics, background information, photos, links, MIDI sound
files and scores for downloading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Onward, Christian Soldiers'' is listed by title, with the
following information. ``Words: Sabine Baring-Gould, 1864.
Baring-Gould wrote this hymn for a procession of children marching
between two villages in his parish on Whitsunday (he later said he
dashed off the lyrics in under 10 minutes).'' The composer was Sir
Arthur Sullivan (1871), and the music is ``St. Gertrude.'' There
are pictures of both men and a MIDI file for the tune. There are
indexes by title, author or composer (20 hymns by Sullivan are
provided) and tune (two other hymns also use ``St. Gertrude).''
</P>
<P>
   Don't have a favorite hymn? The Cyber Hymnal will surf for you,
playing one after another at random. Perhaps its most entertaining
page is Hymn Trivia. By far the most popular hymn, based on Web
traffic, is ``Amazing Grace.'' The tune most often used in hymns is
``Duke Street.'' The most prolific author is probably Frances Jane
(Fanny) Crosby (1820-1915), who the site says wrote more than 8,000
hymns, the last one the day before she died at age 95. The site
also lists 10 hymns (including ``Onward, Christian Soldiers'') that
were heard in movies that won or were nominated for Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other hymn sites on line. A beautiful one is
Traditional Catholic MIDI files
(www.homestead.com/midicatholic/Catholicinformation.html), by Don
Wyckoff. The Eastern Catholic Liturgical Music site
(www.homestead.com/Easterncatholichymns/SpasiHospodi.html) offers
hymns and other music from the Byzantine, Ukrainian, Armenian,
Maronite and other Eastern rites. The Christian Classics Ethereal
Library at Wheaton College (ccel.wheaton.edu/(NU)Hymns) has the
words to the Protestant Episcopal Hymnal of 1916, John Wesley's
``Collection of Hymns, for the Use of the People Called
Methodists,'' other collections and 200 sound files.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasm is everything in a hymn. Hymn sites are as apt to be
created by devout individuals as by religious organizations or
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to hear the old hymns I sang as a child,'' Brian M.
Ames wrote by e-mail about the Ames Hymn Collection
(junior.apk.net/bmames/hymnsjs.htm). Ames' site begins with ``The
Woods,'' which he wrote in memory of his father, Jay Walter Ames,
who died Feb. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I enjoy most about my hymn site is when I see it bring
comfort to the suffering,'' Ames wrote via e-mail. ``I have made a
point to overlook differences, welcoming the use of my hymns by
those of various views and life styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One site, operated by a Baptist fundamentalist, has a link to
my site not too far from links to pages describing the evils of the
Roman Catholic Church, of which I am an adherent. Another site,
operated as a ministry to gays and lesbians, was so expectant of
rejection in their request to use my music that it nearly broke my
heart. At yet another site, several of my hymns have been used to
create a touching memorial to a deceased mother. To me, this is
what hymns on the Web should do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
