A0089 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-Rockets-Spurs-HNS     04-07 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-Rockets-Spurs-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets remember Spurs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Leave it to Charles Barkley to take the first verbal swing in the
ongoing feud between the Rockets and San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs return to Compaq Center tonight for the first time
since they beat the Rockets by 17 points March 2, and Barkley
believes there is a score to settle between the Midwest Division
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spurs have a good team, but we owe them a game,
actually,'' Barkley said. ``They came here and spanked us pretty
good. That was actually pretty much our wakeup call for the season.
They humiliated us last time here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their goals are a little bit different than ours. They just
want to play well _ we want to win championships. Yeah, their goals
are different than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs might argue that point _ they are the league's hottest
team, winning 17 of their last 19 games. The streak has moved the
Spurs up to the No. 3 seed in the Western Conference playoff
picture, just ahead of you know who.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets are itching for a chance to exact a little
revenge, especially when they look back on that 99-82 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' said Hakeem Olajuwon. ``We lost to them in that
last game here and I don't think we want to form that kind of
habit, for them to think that they can come in here and win. We
have to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially considering the schedule over the next couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets play San Antonio tonight at Compaq Center and then
hit the road for Sunday's game at Utah. Then it's on to Minnesota
to play the Timberwolves on Monday, then home games against
Vancouver (April 14) and Portland (April 15).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to play much better teams right now,'' Scottie
Pippen said. ``We're looking at San Antonio, then we have to go
into Utah and then we have Minnesota (on the road). It's going to
get a little hectic for us, but it's that time of the season when
we have to start playing against some stiffer competition so we can
start to figure out where we are as a team and if we're really
getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs will be a pretty good measuring stick.
</P>
<P>
   With 7-0 Tim Duncan and 7-1 David Robinson up front, the Spurs
have enough size to bother an inside-oriented team like the
Rockets. Add the fact that the teams are fierce rivals, a facet
that got a bit spicier when the Spurs picked up former Rocket Mario
Elie during the offseason, and you have the necessary ingredients
for a big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a rivalry because of the matchups,'' Olajuwon
said. ``It's balanced because you have great big men on that team
and we play the same style of basketball. Our strengths are their
strengths, so it's always a battle against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich expects.
With the playoffs less than a month away, Tomjanovich is looking
for a little playoff-type intensity when the teams hit the floor
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, and they were struggling when we played
them earlier in the season,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But they've got a
tremendous run going here. They have two of the best big men in the
game and they have a lot of competitors on that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a playoff-intensity type (of game).
And we need that. We have only 16 games left so it's going to be
good for not only our rookies but even our veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   A big plus with the season winding down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 10 (games) at home and six on the road,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``We do have some tough opponents, but that should also be a
positive to get us in a playoff-type mentality going down the
stretch. And there are going to be some big challenges, because
we're going to go against teams we're in the (playoff) race with.''
</P>
<P>
   Which has been one of the knocks against the Rockets this season
_ their record against upper-echelon teams.
</P>
<P>
   Against the other top seven teams in the West (Utah, Portland,
San Antonio, Minnesota, Phoenix, Seattle and the Los Angeles
Lakers), the Rockets are 4-8 overall and 0-6 on the road. And the
Rockets lost to three of the top three teams in the East _ at
Miami, at Orlando and at home to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   So getting a good win against a tough opponent like San Antonio
could get the Rockets started off on the right foot in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to beat good teams,'' Tomjanovich said. ``To
get anywhere, you're going to have to do it. To get anywhere in the
playoffs, you're going to have to beat somebody. Hopefully, we'll
have the home-court advantage in the first round, but we don't know
that yet because it's one hell of a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had great races at the top, in the middle and down at
the bottom of the playoff seedings, so this is going to be an
exciting last month of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
