<DOCNO> NYT19990407.0543 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-AARON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-07 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-AARON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Aaron's glorious legacy ages well
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time passes _ of course, one is prompted to ask, what else is
time to do? Time blurs. Time enhances. Time tricks us. But it
doesn't really stand still, no matter what we read or hear or feel.
</P>
<P>
   Time has elevated Henry Aaron, at long last, to his rightful
place as one of baseball's deities. Twenty-five years after he
broke Babe Ruth's career home run record, on April 8, 1974, the
recognition that was oddly denied him at the moment has come to
this most unassuming of players. Undiluted, unquestioned,
uncluttered by trivia, Aaron is honored now as the greatest
performer of his era.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates, Warren Spahn and Eddie Mathews, said so. The
revered Ted Williams, the precise Stan Musial and the adored Mickey
Mantle said so. The two most dominant pitchers of his generation,
Sandy Koufax and Bob Gibson, said so. More important, time says so.
</P>
<P>
   The past has become an ally, not his enemy. No longer does he
chase Babe Ruth's ghost through a long, winding, fog-shrouded
alley. The comparisons to Mantle and Willie Mays are still there,
but the numbers are in and they all shout the same name: Hank
Aaron. He was a power hitter who could steal bases, an outfielder
who made hard catches look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Mantle, among others, observed that if Henry had spent his
career in such media centers as New York or Los Angeles, instead of
such outposts as Milwaukee and Atlanta, there would have been no
debate about his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   The longest countdown the game had known began in earnest in
April 1971, when Aaron drilled his 600th homer off Gaylord Perry of
the Giants. At age 37, he would clear the fence 47 times, a
personal best, and bat .327. For the better part of four years, or
roughly the time it took Michelangelo to paint the ceiling of the
Sistine Chapel, the media and the public would track his progress.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to plod away, placing one stone atop the other,
while millions kept score. It was to be the lengthiest chase scene
in sports. He conducted himself handsomely, seldom if ever rude, if
not always accommodating. The pressures that surrounded him were
unknown to Ruth, for two reasons. Unlike the Babe, Hank had a goal
to pursue, creating enormous suspense in the process.
</P>
<P>
   And communications on the planet had undergone a radical change
in 40 years. Radio and television carried the news instantly to
every corner of the globe, and the computer had invaded even that
holy sanctuary, the baseball press box.
</P>
<P>
   An army of journalists tested his capacity to cope. Despite all
the new notoriety, Henry continued to drive a Chevrolet. His
wardrobe was still modest and his lifestyle anything but lavish. He
was sensitive about giving anyone the impression that he was a big
shot. He had the normal vanity of one who excelled at his work, but
high-rolling was a tender subject.
</P>
<P>
   He went to lengths to avoid the appearance of immodesty,
recalling vividly the thin days of his childhood in Mobile, Ala.,
where his father was a laborer on the dry docks, supporting a wife
and eight kids.
</P>
<P>
   Adrift at 17 with the Indianapolis Clowns of the Negro League,
Henry caught the eye of scouts for the Boston Braves and the New
York Giants, and the teams competed for him. The Giants offered
$150 a month. The Braves went to $350. So, for $200 a month, the
Giants walked away from the man who would one day smash more home
runs than Ruth. In the process, they lost the chance to present an
outfield that would have included Mays and Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Up until the time he signed with the Braves and was shipped to a
farm club, Henry had never ridden in an airplane. His meal
allowance was $2 a day. The players ate mostly out of grocery
stores.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was hunting down the Babe, Aaron was among the
highest salaried stars at $200,000 a year, but still underpaid. His
mail reflected the fierce resistance of the same purists who
rejected Roger Maris. But the hate mail and death threats poured in
as well, from the bigots who were inflamed by the idea of a black
Alabaman eclipsing the Babe. They were a flyspeck _ it was hoped _
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   When Hank finished the 1973 season with 713 home runs, the sport
was left dangling by its thumbs. You half expected the Braves to
transfer him to the Manned Space Center in Houston, where he would
be kept in quarantine, shielded from anyone bearing germs. On
visiting day, his family would talk to him through a glass
partition.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a mild storm developed when the Braves announced Henry
would be held out of the opening series of the 1974 season at
Cincinnati, thus assuring a sellout in Atlanta for the home opener,
and beyond. The commissioner, Bowie Kuhn, responded by ordering
Aaron to play all three games against the Reds, or face a severe,
if unidentified, penatly.
</P>
<P>
   Henry not only played, but predictably hit his 714th homer off
Jack Billingham on opening day to tie the record.
</P>
<P>
   Now the scene shifted to Fulton County Stadium, on the night of
April 8, with a full house that did not include the commissioner.
In the fourth inning, Aaron stepped in to face lefty Al Downing of
the Dodgers. Milo Hamilton, now the familiar voice of the Houston
Astros, was calling the game on radio for Atlanta. The home plate
umpire was Satch Davidson, a Houston resident since his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the batter's box, Aaron said to Dusty Baker, who
followed him in the batting order: ``I'm tired of all this. I'm
ready to get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   And, now, here's Milo:
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd is up all around. The pitch to him bounced it up
there, ball one (loud boos). Henry Aaron in the second inning
walked and scored. He's sitting on 714. Here's the pitch by Downing
swinging there's a drive into left-center field. That ball is gonna
beee OUTA HERE! IT'S GONE! IT'S 715! THERE'S A NEW HOME RUN
CHAMPION OF ALL TIME, AND IT'S HENRY AARON ''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 53,775 exploded in rapture. Among the enduring sights
of that evening was a young Atlanta relief pitcher, Tom House,
catching the ball in the bullpen and racing down the foul line to
home plate to hand the priceless souvenir to Aaron, who was being
embraced by his mother and swarmed by his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And so the deed was done by the player his fans called The
Hammer.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he prizes the most extended of all power records, as
much as he enjoys being called The Home Run King, he points out
softly that it is only a part of his story. He ranks first on the
all-time list for runs batted in, extra base hits and total bases,
second in runs scored, third in hits (behind Pete Rose and Ty
Cobb.)
</P>
<P>
   He was not exactly shortchanged in the glory department. He was,
after all, admired by millions and swept into the Hall of Fame on
the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not larger than life, as Ruth was. He lacked the
showmanship of Mays or the boyish charm of Mantle or the temper of
Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He was understated and effortless in the style of Joe DiMaggio.
He played the game as if it was an art, not a competition. He was
grace in a gray flannel suit. Mays was a bit of a ham. Aaron was as
smooth as a swan gliding along a lake. Williams attacked the ball.
Aaron got it to cooperate with him.
</P>
<P>
   He hit 755 home runs in 23 years, without ever producing 50 in a
season. His homers were usually line drives, not the high, soaring
swats of Ruth or the orbital explosions of a Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his first home run off Vic Raschi of the Yankees on April
23, 1954, and his last off Dick Drago of the Angels on July 20,
1976. In the years since he retired, his poise and skills as a
speaker have grown dramatically. He moved into the executive
offices of the Braves, and has spoken out frequently on baseball's
failure to address minority hirings. He feels secure about his
place in baseball lore.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron was a tough out because he had a classic stroke and was
rarely out of control. He weighed 180 and his home runs were the
results of quick wrists, not strength. He had patience and sharp
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Hank once fouled off a dozen pitches against Sandy Koufax, who
finally stepped off the mound, rubbed up the ball and called down
to him: ``Hank, it's me and you now. I'm going to throw my best
fastball right down the middle, and you're either going to hit it
out of the park or not out of the park. But there will be no more
foul balls.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next pitch, Aaron popped up.
</P>
<P>
   Then and now, the essence of the sport was the great hitter
against a great pitcher. This element, and more, is captured in a
superb coffee-table book called Home Run, My Life in Pictures,
celebrating the 25th anniversary of Aaron's record.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gibson provides a rare, lovely, funny insight: ``Aaron had
reached base somehow. He was going to steal second on me, and I
went into my stretch. A lot of guys tried to time me. Well, I went
into my stretch and I looked over my shoulder, and he started
running. I turned around and chased him. I got within about four
feet from him, and he was standing there facing me
</P>
<P>
   ``We both were standing still. He would fake to the left and I'd
fake to the left. He'd fake to the right and I'd fake to the right.
I started grinning and I said, ``I got you now.' And he started
laughing, then he just fell on the ground and I touched him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not often, in his illustrious 23-year career, that anyone
caught Henry Aaron off base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
